// Question banks for Group Study (Kahoot-style live sessions). Kept separate
// from theme.js/group-study.js since this is pure data, not logic.
//
// Each entry is keyed by a stable quiz id (used in the host UI's quiz
// picker and stored on the room doc) and shaped as:
//   { title: string, questions: [ { q: string, choices: string[4], answer: 0-3, exp: string } ] }
// This is a DIFFERENT, deliberately simpler shape than any individual
// quiz file's own in-page question format (which varies across the site's
// 6 quiz-engine families -- see feedback_exam_mode memory) -- ported by
// hand per quiz rather than trying to read each file's bespoke format
// live. To add another quiz to Group Study: extract its question array
// (e.g. via a quick headless-Chrome eval of `JSON.stringify(questions)`
// on the real page, which sidesteps hand-transcribing 30-70 questions)
// into this same {q, choices, answer, exp} shape and add a new key below.
// See feedback_group_study memory for the full design.
window.GROUP_QUIZZES = {"gi-physiology":{"title":"GI Physiology","questions":[{"q":"Peristalsis (the propulsive movement of the gut) fundamentally requires...","choices":["The sympathetic nervous system to initiate the contraction","The sphincter of Oddi to open first","The myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus, and can occur without the autonomic nervous system","Complete removal of the enteric nervous system"],"answer":2,"exp":"Peristalsis is coordinated by the enteric (myenteric) plexus and proceeds even without autonomic input, though the parasympathetics modulate it. It does not require the sympathetic system to start, the sphincter of Oddi, or removal of the ENS — destroying the ENS actually abolishes it.","cite":"Slide 39"},{"q":"According to the “law of the gut,” a bolus that distends the intestine causes...","choices":["Contraction on the orad (upstream) side and relaxation on the downstream (aboral) side","Relaxation on both sides at the same time","Contraction ahead of the bolus, pushing it backward","No coordinated response unless the sympathetic nerves fire"],"answer":0,"exp":"Distension makes the segment behind the bolus contract while the segment ahead relaxes, propelling contents aborally. Simultaneous relaxation, contraction ahead of the bolus, or dependence on sympathetic input all misdescribe this reflex.","cite":"Slide 39"},{"q":"Segmentation contractions serve mainly to...","choices":["Rapidly propel chyme toward the colon","Mix chyme with digestive secretions rather than propel it","Keep the sphincters tonically closed","Trigger the defecation reflex"],"answer":1,"exp":"Segmentation is a mixing movement that churns chyme with secretions and improves mucosal contact, with little net propulsion. Propulsion is peristalsis, tonic closure is a sphincter role, and the defecation reflex is a separate event.","cite":"Slide 39"},{"q":"In GI smooth muscle, what is the role of “slow waves”?","choices":["They directly cause every contraction by themselves","They are action potentials that always produce contraction","They inhibit all smooth-muscle activity","They are rhythmic membrane oscillations that set the timing; contraction occurs only when they reach threshold and trigger spike potentials"],"answer":3,"exp":"Slow waves are subthreshold oscillations (the basic electrical rhythm); a contraction results only when a slow wave is driven to threshold and fires spike potentials. They do not by themselves cause every contraction, are not always action potentials, and are not purely inhibitory.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"GI smooth muscle behaves as a functional syncytium because...","choices":["Each cell is individually innervated by its own motor neuron","Gap junctions electrically couple the cells, letting action potentials spread from cell to cell","The cells physically fuse into one giant multinucleated fiber","It has no electrical connections between cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Gap junctions provide low-resistance electrical connections, so a signal spreads through the muscle as a unit. The cells are not each individually innervated, do not truly fuse into one fiber, and are certainly electrically connected.","cite":"Slide 36"},{"q":"How does autonomic input generally affect GI activity?","choices":["Both divisions stimulate the gut equally","Parasympathetic inhibits and sympathetic stimulates","Parasympathetic input mainly stimulates, and sympathetic input mainly inhibits","Neither division affects gut motility"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parasympathetic (vagal/pelvic, ACh) activity generally stimulates motility and secretion, while sympathetic (NE) activity generally inhibits. The other options reverse or deny these effects.","cite":"Slide 25"},{"q":"The migrating motor complex (MMC) functions to...","choices":["Sweep undigested residue toward the colon between meals, keeping upper-gut bacterial counts low","Mix chyme with enzymes right after a meal","Trigger mass movements in the colon","Neutralize gastric acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"The MMC is the interdigestive “housekeeping” pattern that clears residue and bacteria from the upper gut between meals, mediated by motilin. It is not a postprandial mixing pattern, does not drive colonic mass movements, and has no role in neutralizing acid.","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Which gastric cell secretes both hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor?","choices":["Chief (peptic) cells","G-cells","Mucous neck cells","Parietal (oxyntic) cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Parietal (oxyntic) cells secrete both HCl and intrinsic factor. Chief cells make pepsinogen, G-cells make gastrin, and mucous neck cells make mucus.","cite":"Slide 79"},{"q":"Pepsinogen is secreted primarily by which cells?","choices":["Chief (peptic) cells","Parietal cells","G-cells","ECL cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Chief (peptic) cells secrete pepsinogen. Parietal cells make acid and intrinsic factor, G-cells make gastrin, and ECL cells release histamine.","cite":"Slide 79"},{"q":"How is inactive pepsinogen converted to active pepsin?","choices":["Bile salts activate it in the duodenum","Enterokinase cleaves it at the brush border","It is secreted already active","Gastric acid converts it to pepsin, which then activates more pepsinogen (autocatalysis)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Acid converts pepsinogen to pepsin, and the pepsin formed activates still more pepsinogen — an autocatalytic loop. Bile salts and enterokinase act on other substances, and pepsinogen is secreted inactive.","cite":"Slide 83"},{"q":"Why is intrinsic factor considered the only indispensable component of gastric juice?","choices":["It is required to activate pepsinogen","It neutralizes duodenal acid","It is required for vitamin B12 absorption in the ileum","It emulsifies dietary fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"Intrinsic factor binds vitamin B12 so the complex can be absorbed in the ileum, and its loss causes B12 deficiency — which is why it is the one indispensable gastric secretion. It does not activate pepsinogen, neutralize acid, or emulsify fat.","cite":"Slide 87"},{"q":"Which is a physiological function of gastric acid (HCl)?","choices":["Emulsifying fats for absorption","Converting pepsinogen to pepsin and providing a bacteriostatic environment","Directly absorbing amino acids","Neutralizing chyme entering the duodenum"],"answer":1,"exp":"Gastric acid activates pepsinogen to pepsin, begins protein digestion, and limits ingested microbes (bacteriostatic). It does not emulsify fat, absorb amino acids, or neutralize duodenal chyme — that is bicarbonate's role.","cite":"Slide 82"},{"q":"Gastrin and acetylcholine strongly stimulate acid secretion partly by triggering release of which paracrine agent from ECL cells?","choices":["Somatostatin","Secretin","Motilin","Histamine"],"answer":3,"exp":"Gastrin and ACh stimulate ECL cells to release histamine, which powerfully drives parietal-cell acid secretion. Somatostatin and secretin inhibit acid, and motilin governs interdigestive motility.","cite":"Slide 91"},{"q":"When the antral pH becomes very low, gastrin release is inhibited largely because acid...","choices":["Directly destroys the G-cells","Stimulates somatostatin release, which suppresses gastrin (negative feedback)","Converts gastrin into secretin","Increases histamine release"],"answer":1,"exp":"A low antral pH stimulates somatostatin, which inhibits gastrin release — a negative-feedback brake on acid secretion. Acid does not destroy G-cells, convert gastrin to secretin, or raise histamine.","cite":"Slide 94"},{"q":"Besides stimulating gastric acid secretion, gastrin has what other notable action?","choices":["A trophic effect promoting growth of the oxyntic (gastric) mucosa","Emptying the gallbladder","Stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion","Inhibiting all gastric secretion"],"answer":0,"exp":"Beyond stimulating acid, gastrin is trophic to the oxyntic mucosa, promoting its growth. Gallbladder emptying and pancreatic enzyme secretion are CCK's actions, and gastrin stimulates rather than inhibits gastric secretion.","cite":"Slide 12"},{"q":"Which luminal stimulus most strongly triggers CCK release from duodenal I-cells?","choices":["Intact triglycerides","Glucose alone","Fatty acids and monoglycerides (products of fat digestion), plus peptides and amino acids","Water"],"answer":2,"exp":"CCK release is triggered by fat-digestion products (fatty acids, monoglycerides) and by peptides/amino acids — not by intact triglycerides, glucose alone, or water.","cite":"Slide 13"},{"q":"A major action of CCK is to...","choices":["Contract the gallbladder and relax the sphincter of Oddi, delivering bile to the intestine","Stimulate gastric acid secretion","Relax the gallbladder so it stores more bile","Neutralize acid by directly secreting bicarbonate"],"answer":0,"exp":"CCK contracts the gallbladder and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi, sending bile and pancreatic enzymes into the duodenum. It does not stimulate acid, promote bile storage, or directly secrete bicarbonate.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"Secretin is called “nature's antacid” because, in response to duodenal acid, it...","choices":["Directly buffers acid within the stomach","Stimulates more gastrin release","Stimulates pancreatic and biliary bicarbonate secretion and inhibits gastric acid","Increases gastric emptying of acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Secretin, released by duodenal acid, drives bicarbonate secretion from pancreas and bile ducts and inhibits gastric acid and gastrin. It does not buffer acid directly in the stomach, raise gastrin, or speed acid emptying.","cite":"Slide 16"},{"q":"Glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide (GIP) is notable because it...","choices":["Is the main stimulus for gallbladder contraction","Activates pancreatic proteolytic enzymes","Is released only during fasting","Stimulates insulin release in response to oral nutrients (an incretin effect)"],"answer":3,"exp":"GIP is an incretin: oral nutrients trigger it to enhance insulin release (and it inhibits gastric acid). Gallbladder contraction is CCK's role, zymogen activation is enterokinase/trypsin, and GIP is released after eating, not during fasting.","cite":"Slide 17"},{"q":"Which hormone is released cyclically during fasting to drive the migrating motor complexes?","choices":["Cholecystokinin","Motilin","Secretin","Gastrin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Motilin is released cyclically during fasting and drives the migrating motor complexes. CCK, secretin, and gastrin are released in response to a meal and serve digestive rather than interdigestive roles.","cite":"Slide 18"},{"q":"Which enzyme in saliva begins the digestion of starch in the mouth?","choices":["Pepsin","Trypsin","α-amylase (ptyalin)","Lingual lipase"],"answer":2,"exp":"Salivary α-amylase (ptyalin) starts starch digestion in the mouth. Pepsin digests protein in the stomach, trypsin is a pancreatic protease, and lingual lipase acts on fat, not starch.","cite":"Slide 72"},{"q":"Pepsin works best under what conditions, and what happens as pH rises?","choices":["It works best at alkaline pH and is inactivated by acid","It is optimally active at acidic pH (~1.8–3.5) and is inactivated as pH rises toward neutral","It is equally active across all pH values","It requires bile salts to function"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pepsin is optimally active in the acidic stomach (pH ~1.8–3.5) and loses activity as pH climbs toward neutral (irreversibly above pH 7–8). It is not alkaline-optimal, pH-independent, or bile-dependent.","cite":"Slide 83"},{"q":"After pancreatic amylase acts, where is carbohydrate digestion completed?","choices":["In the stomach by pepsin","Inside the liver","In the colon by bacteria only","At the brush border, by membrane-bound disaccharidases"],"answer":3,"exp":"Luminal amylase yields disaccharides and oligosaccharides, and final carbohydrate digestion is completed by brush-border disaccharidases (maltase, sucrase, lactase). It is not finished by gastric pepsin, in the liver, or solely by colonic bacteria.","cite":"Slide 123"},{"q":"Enterokinase (enteropeptidase) on the intestinal brush border is essential because it...","choices":["Activates trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the other pancreatic zymogens","Directly digests triglycerides","Neutralizes gastric acid","Absorbs amino acids"],"answer":0,"exp":"Enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and more trypsinogen. It does not digest fat, neutralize acid, or absorb amino acids.","cite":"Slide 104"},{"q":"The final steps of protein digestion (di- and tripeptides to amino acids) occur...","choices":["Only in the stomach lumen","At the brush border and within the cytoplasm of the mucosal cells","Only in the mouth","In the colon"],"answer":1,"exp":"Protein digestion finishes at the brush border (oligopeptidases, dipeptidases) and in the enterocyte cytoplasm (di-/tripeptidases). It is not completed in the stomach, mouth, or colon.","cite":"Slide 127"},{"q":"What is the role of bile salts in fat digestion?","choices":["They emulsify large fat droplets into smaller ones, increasing the surface area for lipase","They chemically break triglycerides into fatty acids","They transport fat directly into the blood","They neutralize stomach acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Bile salts are emulsifiers: they disperse large fat globules into fine droplets, expanding the surface on which pancreatic lipase acts. The chemical breakdown of triglycerides is lipase's job, and bile salts neither carry fat into blood nor neutralize acid.","cite":"Slide 137"},{"q":"How do the products of fat digestion (monoglycerides and fatty acids) reach the enterocyte surface for absorption?","choices":["Dissolved freely in water and diffusing on their own","Bound to intrinsic factor","Packaged into micelles with bile salts, which ferry them to the brush border","Inside chylomicrons formed in the lumen"],"answer":2,"exp":"Because they are poorly water-soluble, monoglycerides and fatty acids are carried in micelles with bile salts to the enterocyte brush border. They do not simply diffuse, bind intrinsic factor, or ride in lumen-formed chylomicrons — chylomicrons form inside the enterocyte.","cite":"Slide 133"},{"q":"Where are bile salts reabsorbed to be recycled back to the liver?","choices":["In the stomach","In the duodenum","In the colon","In the ileum"],"answer":3,"exp":"Bile salts are actively reabsorbed in the ileum and returned to the liver (the enterohepatic circulation). They are not reclaimed in the stomach, duodenum, or colon.","cite":"Slide 121"},{"q":"The delivery of stored bile into the small intestine after a fatty meal is triggered mainly by...","choices":["Secretin, which contracts the gallbladder","Gastrin, which relaxes the sphincter of Oddi","Motilin, during fasting","CCK, which contracts the gallbladder"],"answer":3,"exp":"A fatty or protein-rich meal releases CCK, which contracts the gallbladder and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi to deliver bile. Secretin drives bicarbonate, gastrin governs acid, and motilin acts during fasting.","cite":"Slide 15"},{"q":"In addition to acting on the pancreas, secretin stimulates the liver/biliary system to secrete...","choices":["Digestive enzymes","Intrinsic factor","Bicarbonate-rich fluid","Larger amounts of bile salts"],"answer":2,"exp":"Secretin stimulates the liver and bile ducts (and pancreas) to add bicarbonate-rich fluid that helps neutralize acid. It does not stimulate enzyme, intrinsic-factor, or bile-salt output.","cite":"Slide 16"},{"q":"The exocrine pancreas serves two key roles as chyme enters the small intestine:","choices":["Absorbing nutrients and storing bile","Supplying digestive enzymes for all nutrient types and bicarbonate to neutralize acid chyme","Producing intrinsic factor and gastrin","Emulsifying fat and reabsorbing bile salts"],"answer":1,"exp":"The exocrine pancreas secretes enzymes for carbohydrate, protein, and fat digestion plus bicarbonate to neutralize acidic chyme. It does not absorb nutrients or store bile, make intrinsic factor/gastrin, or emulsify fat (a bile-salt role).","cite":"Slide 99"},{"q":"Why are pancreatic proteolytic enzymes secreted as inactive precursors (zymogens)?","choices":["To prevent the pancreas from digesting itself","Because they are only active in the stomach","Because acid is required to synthesize them","To allow them to be absorbed before activation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Proteolytic enzymes are stored and secreted as inactive zymogens (with a trypsin inhibitor present) so they cannot digest the pancreas that makes them. They are not stomach-specific, do not require acid for synthesis, and are not absorbed.","cite":"Slide 103"},{"q":"Once formed, trypsin plays a central role in the intestine by...","choices":["Activating chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and more trypsinogen","Neutralizing acid chyme","Emulsifying fats","Absorbing peptides"],"answer":0,"exp":"Trypsin is the master activator: it converts chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and additional trypsinogen to their active forms. Neutralizing acid is bicarbonate's role, emulsifying fat is bile's, and absorption is the mucosa's.","cite":"Slide 104"},{"q":"Pancreatic acinar cells store a trypsin inhibitor in order to...","choices":["Speed up enzyme activation within the pancreas","Block any trypsin that forms prematurely inside the acinar cells and ducts","Neutralize bicarbonate","Activate chymotrypsin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Trypsin inhibitor neutralizes small amounts of trypsin that activate prematurely within acini and ducts, preventing autodigestion; overwhelming it contributes to pancreatitis. It does not accelerate activation, neutralize bicarbonate, or activate chymotrypsin.","cite":"Slide 105"},{"q":"Pancreatic bicarbonate secretion is important because it...","choices":["Activates trypsinogen directly","Emulsifies dietary fat","Stimulates gastric acid secretion","Neutralizes acidic chyme, creating the pH (~7–8) needed for pancreatic enzymes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Pancreatic bicarbonate neutralizes acid entering the duodenum, establishing the near-neutral pH at which pancreatic enzymes work best. It does not activate trypsinogen (enterokinase does), emulsify fat (bile does), or stimulate gastric acid.","cite":"Slide 106"},{"q":"Pancreatic enzyme secretion versus bicarbonate/fluid secretion are controlled mainly by:","choices":["Both entirely by gastrin","Enzyme output by acid; bicarbonate output by fat","Enzyme secretion by fat and protein (via CCK); bicarbonate/fluid secretion by acid (via secretin)","Both by intrinsic factor"],"answer":2,"exp":"Pancreatic enzyme secretion tracks duodenal fat and protein (through CCK), while bicarbonate/fluid secretion tracks duodenal acid (through secretin). Gastrin and intrinsic factor are not the main controllers, and the acid/fat pairing is reversed in the other option.","cite":"Slide 107"},{"q":"After chylomicrons deliver most of their triglyceride to tissues, the remnants are...","choices":["Excreted in bile unchanged","Reabsorbed in the ileum","Taken up (cleared) by the liver","Converted back into bile salts in the gut"],"answer":2,"exp":"After lipoprotein lipase strips triglyceride from chylomicrons in the tissues, the cholesterol-rich remnants are cleared by the liver. They are not excreted intact in bile, reabsorbed in the ileum, or turned into bile salts in the gut.","cite":"Slide 138"},{"q":"Which lipoprotein returns excess cholesterol from the tissues back to the liver?","choices":["LDL","VLDL","Chylomicrons","HDL"],"answer":3,"exp":"HDL performs reverse cholesterol transport, returning excess cholesterol from tissues to the liver. LDL delivers cholesterol to cells, VLDL carries liver-made triglyceride to tissues, and chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the gut.","cite":"Slide 139"},{"q":"Bile, which is essential for fat emulsification, is produced by which organ?","choices":["The liver","The gallbladder","The pancreas","The duodenal mucosa"],"answer":0,"exp":"The liver produces bile continuously; the gallbladder only stores and concentrates it between meals. The pancreas and duodenal mucosa secrete other digestive fluids, not bile.","cite":"Slide 113"},{"q":"The villi and microvilli of the small intestine are important because they...","choices":["Secrete the pancreatic enzymes","Vastly increase the surface area available for absorption","Neutralize gastric acid","Store bile salts"],"answer":1,"exp":"Villi (~10-fold) and microvilli/brush border (~20-fold) hugely amplify the absorptive surface area of the small intestine. They do not secrete pancreatic enzymes, neutralize acid, or store bile salts.","cite":"Slide 118"},{"q":"Glucose and galactose are absorbed across the intestinal brush border by...","choices":["Simple diffusion down their concentration gradient","Facilitated diffusion that does not use sodium","Endocytosis","Secondary active transport coupled to sodium (SGLT-1)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Glucose and galactose share the Na⁺-coupled SGLT-1 carrier, using the sodium gradient (maintained by the Na⁺–K⁺ ATPase) for secondary active transport. They are not absorbed by simple diffusion, sodium-independent facilitated diffusion, or endocytosis.","cite":"Slide 126"},{"q":"How is fructose absorbed, in contrast to glucose?","choices":["By secondary active transport with sodium","By primary active transport using ATP directly","By facilitated diffusion (GLUT-5), needing no energy or sodium","By endocytosis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Fructose crosses via GLUT-5 facilitated diffusion, moving down its gradient without energy or sodium coupling — unlike glucose and galactose. It is not actively transported or taken up by endocytosis.","cite":"Slide 126"},{"q":"The final products of carbohydrate digestion that are actually absorbed are...","choices":["Monosaccharides, mostly glucose","Disaccharides such as maltose and lactose","Short glucose polymers","Starch fragments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Carbohydrates must be reduced to monosaccharides (about 80% glucose, plus fructose and galactose) before absorption. Disaccharides, oligosaccharides, and starch fragments must first be split at the brush border.","cite":"Slide 125"},{"q":"Which statement about protein absorption is correct?","choices":["Di- and tripeptides use a different carrier than free amino acids and are absorbed faster","Only free amino acids can be absorbed","Whole proteins are absorbed intact in adults","Peptides are absorbed only in the stomach"],"answer":0,"exp":"Small di- and tripeptides are taken up by a separate carrier (and hydrolyzed inside the cell), and are actually absorbed faster than free amino acids. Whole proteins are not absorbed intact in adults, and peptide absorption occurs in the small intestine, not the stomach.","cite":"Slide 129"},{"q":"After fats are reassembled into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons, they enter the...","choices":["Portal blood directly","Bile ducts","Lymphatic system (lacteals), because chylomicrons are too large for blood capillaries","Gastric veins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chylomicrons are too large to enter blood capillaries, so they pass into the lacteals and travel via lymph to the thoracic duct before reaching the blood. They do not enter portal blood, bile ducts, or gastric veins directly.","cite":"Slide 135"},{"q":"Once inside the enterocyte, absorbed monoglycerides and fatty acids are...","choices":["Broken down further into glycerol and carbon dioxide","Reassembled into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons","Absorbed directly into the portal vein as free fat","Returned to the lumen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Inside the enterocyte, absorbed monoglycerides and fatty acids are re-esterified into triglycerides and packaged (with apoproteins) into chylomicrons. They are not oxidized to CO₂ there, sent into portal blood as free fat, or returned to the lumen.","cite":"Slide 132"},{"q":"Vitamin B12 (bound to intrinsic factor) is absorbed at which site?","choices":["The stomach","The duodenum","The colon","The ileum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The intrinsic-factor–B12 complex is absorbed in the ileum (as are bile salts). The stomach and colon absorb little B12, and the duodenum mainly absorbs other nutrients, iron, and calcium.","cite":"Slide 121"},{"q":"The intrinsic defecation reflex is initiated when...","choices":["Feces enter and distend the rectum, triggering myenteric-plexus signals","The stomach empties completely","The internal anal sphincter contracts","Bile enters the colon"],"answer":0,"exp":"Rectal distension by feces triggers the intrinsic (ENS-mediated) reflex, which contracts the colon/rectum and relaxes the internal anal sphincter. Gastric emptying, sphincter contraction, and bile entering the colon do not initiate it.","cite":"Slide 66"},{"q":"For defecation to occur, the internal anal sphincter relaxes and then...","choices":["The internal sphincter must contract again","The external anal sphincter must be voluntarily relaxed","The pyloric sphincter must open","Mass movements must stop"],"answer":1,"exp":"The internal anal sphincter (smooth muscle) relaxes reflexively, but defecation proceeds only if the external anal sphincter (striated, voluntary) is consciously relaxed. Re-contracting the internal sphincter, opening the pylorus, or stopping mass movements would not allow it.","cite":"Slide 66"},{"q":"How does the spinal-cord (parasympathetic) defecation reflex relate to the intrinsic reflex?","choices":["It replaces the intrinsic reflex entirely","It is qualitatively different and unrelated","It inhibits defecation","It greatly intensifies the intrinsic reflex via pelvic-nerve parasympathetic fibers"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spinal (parasympathetic, S2–S4) reflex reinforces — not replaces — the intrinsic reflex, greatly strengthening colonic and rectal contractions through pelvic-nerve fibers. It is not qualitatively different, unrelated, or inhibitory.","cite":"Slide 67"}]},"gi-physiology-v2":{"title":"GI Physiology (v2)","questions":[{"q":"Peristalsis differs from segmentation in that peristalsis...","choices":["propels contents forward along the tract, while segmentation mainly mixes them","occurs only in the esophagus and nowhere else in the gut during this particular process","only mixes contents, while segmentation moves them forward","is a voluntary movement, while segmentation is involuntary"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Peristalsis is a progressive wave of contraction behind the bolus that moves contents onward, whereas segmentation is alternating localized contractions that chop and mix contents with digestive juices without net forward movement.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-46"},{"q":"During swallowing, the pharyngeal phase is an involuntary reflex that protects the airway by...","choices":["releasing bile to help move the bolus along under most conditions in the body","relaxing the diaphragm to pull the bolus downward","opening the airway wide so the bolus can pass through it","elevating the larynx and covering it with the epiglottis as the bolus passes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Once swallowing is initiated, the pharyngeal phase is a rapid involuntary reflex: the soft palate closes the nasopharynx, breathing is briefly inhibited, and the larynx rises so the epiglottis covers the airway, directing the bolus into the esophagus and preventing aspiration.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-45"},{"q":"Between meals, the migrating motor complex serves to...","choices":["absorb the bulk of dietary nutrients into the blood","sweep residual contents and bacteria along the gut during fasting","trigger the release of bile in response to fat during this process","mix a large meal thoroughly with digestive enzymes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The migrating motor complex is a cyclic pattern of contractions during fasting (associated with motilin) that sweeps leftover food particles, secretions, and bacteria toward the colon — a 'housekeeping' function that keeps the small intestine clear between meals.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-46"},{"q":"The basic rhythm of gastrointestinal smooth-muscle contractions is set by...","choices":["hormones released only during the intestinal phase","conscious signals sent from the cerebral cortex","slow waves of electrical activity generated by pacemaker cells in the gut wall","the rate at which the stomach secretes acid under most conditions throughout the body"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Pacemaker cells (the interstitial cells of Cajal) generate rhythmic slow waves of membrane potential that spread through the smooth muscle; these waves set the maximum frequency of contractions, though a contraction occurs only when a slow wave reaches threshold and fires action potentials.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 24-33, 40-46"},{"q":"During swallowing, the lower esophageal sphincter must relax to...","choices":["allow the bolus to pass from the esophagus into the stomach","release bile into the esophagus to begin digestion","push stomach acid up into the mouth for buffering","prevent any food from entering the stomach at all during this process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. As a peristaltic wave carries the bolus down the esophagus, the lower esophageal sphincter relaxes to let it enter the stomach, then closes again to help prevent reflux of acidic gastric contents back into the esophagus.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-45"},{"q":"Which hormone-action pairing is correct for the digestive response to a meal?","choices":["CCK — is the principal stimulus for gastric acid from parietal cells","Secretin — stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate to neutralize duodenal acid","Gastrin — relaxes the gallbladder and constricts the sphincter of Oddi","Motilin — is released after meals to speed nutrient absorption"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: secretin, released by duodenal acid, stimulates pancreatic and biliary bicarbonate, acting as 'nature's antacid'.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 14-16"},{"q":"Gastrin promotes digestion primarily by...","choices":["inhibiting all secretion during the intestinal phase","contracting the gallbladder to release stored bile","neutralizing stomach acid to protect the duodenum","stimulating gastric acid secretion and gastric motility"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Gastrin, released by antral G-cells in response to protein and stomach distension, stimulates parietal-cell acid secretion (largely via histamine release) and increases gastric motility, preparing the stomach to process a meal.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 96"},{"q":"Cholecystokinin (CCK), released when fat and protein reach the small intestine, promotes fat digestion by...","choices":["contracting the gallbladder and stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion","converting the fat directly into glucose","increasing gastric acid output to break down the fat","stimulating the stomach to empty faster during this process in the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. CCK causes the gallbladder to contract and release stored bile while stimulating the pancreas to secrete digestive enzymes; together these deliver bile salts and lipase to the duodenum, and CCK also slows gastric emptying to match the intestine's capacity.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 130-133"},{"q":"Vagal (parasympathetic) stimulation of the stomach generally...","choices":["increases both gastric motility and acid secretion","decreases motility while raising acid secretion","shuts down all secretion during a meal","acts only on the pancreas, not the stomach"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Parasympathetic (vagal) input, acting largely through acetylcholine, stimulates gastric smooth muscle contraction and enhances secretion, including acid from parietal cells and gastrin release; this underlies the cephalic phase of gastric secretion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 88-90"},{"q":"How does gastrin most powerfully stimulate gastric acid secretion?","choices":["By directly neutralizing somatostatin's inhibition of the chief cells","By stimulating duodenal S-cells to release secretin into the circulating bloodstream","By converting pepsinogen into active pepsin within the acidic gastric lumen itself","Largely by driving ECL cells to release histamine, which acts on parietal cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: much of gastrin's potent acid effect is indirect, through histamine released from ECL cells acting on parietal cells.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 88-91"},{"q":"The cephalic phase of gastric secretion is triggered by...","choices":["fat and protein reaching the small intestine","the sight, smell, or thought of food acting through the vagus nerve","stretch of the stomach wall as food enters","acidic chyme arriving in the duodenum after the stomach has emptied its load"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The cephalic phase begins before food reaches the stomach: sensory and cognitive cues (sight, smell, taste, thought of food) drive vagal output that stimulates gastric secretion in anticipation of the meal, accounting for roughly a third of the acid response.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 92-95"},{"q":"Secreting pancreatic proteases as inactive zymogens is important because it...","choices":["makes the enzymes work better in the acidic stomach","lets the pancreas store the enzymes for years at a time","allows the enzymes to digest carbohydrates instead of protein","prevents the enzymes from digesting the pancreas that makes them"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. If active proteases were produced within the pancreas, they would digest the organ's own tissue; secreting them as inactive zymogens (activated only in the intestine) protects the pancreas from self-digestion, a safeguard whose failure underlies pancreatitis.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101-105"},{"q":"Pancreatic amylase continues carbohydrate digestion by...","choices":["converting absorbed glucose directly into stored glycogen in the gut wall","splitting proteins into individual amino acids","emulsifying dietary fat into small droplets","breaking starch down into disaccharides within the small intestine"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Pancreatic amylase, secreted into the duodenum, hydrolyzes starch and glycogen into disaccharides and short oligosaccharides; brush-border enzymes then complete the job by splitting these into absorbable monosaccharides. It is the main luminal enzyme for carbohydrate digestion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101, 123-124"},{"q":"Disaccharides such as lactose, sucrose, and maltose are digested by...","choices":["gastric acid in the stomach during this particular process in the tissues","brush-border enzymes on the intestinal surface just before absorption","salivary amylase acting in the mouth","bile salts secreted from the gallbladder"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Enzymes anchored on the microvilli of the intestinal brush border — lactase, sucrase, and maltase — split disaccharides into monosaccharides right at the absorptive surface, so the resulting glucose, fructose, and galactose can be taken up immediately.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 123-127"},{"q":"Final digestion of disaccharides such as lactose occurs...","choices":["at the brush border, where membrane-bound enzymes split them into monosaccharides","within the pancreatic duct before the sugars reach the intestine","in the stomach, where gastric acid hydrolyzes them completely into free glucose units","in the mouth, where salivary amylase completes their breakdown"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Disaccharidases such as lactase, sucrase, and maltase are fixed on the intestinal brush border; they perform the final step of carbohydrate digestion, splitting disaccharides into absorbable monosaccharides right at the absorptive surface.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 123-125"},{"q":"The stomach lining is protected from its own acid and pepsin mainly by...","choices":["a layer of mucus and bicarbonate secreted over the epithelium","the complete absence of acid in contact with the wall","rapid peristalsis that keeps acid away from the lining","a continuous flow of bile that neutralizes the acid in the body"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Surface mucous cells secrete a thick, bicarbonate-rich mucus layer that coats the gastric epithelium; this barrier neutralizes acid at the cell surface and shields the lining from pepsin, so the stomach can hold strong acid without digesting itself.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-90"},{"q":"Salivary amylase begins the digestion of...","choices":["fat, by emulsifying it into small droplets","nucleic acids, releasing their component nucleotides","starch, though its action is soon halted by stomach acid","protein, which it splits into individual amino acids"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Salivary amylase (ptyalin) starts breaking down starch in the mouth; when the bolus reaches the acidic stomach, the low pH inactivates the enzyme, and starch digestion resumes in the small intestine with pancreatic amylase.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 76-79, 123"},{"q":"Protein digestion is completed at the intestinal brush border, where...","choices":["bile salts emulsify the peptides into droplets in most cases","stomach acid dissolves the peptides into amino acids","peptidases split small peptides into absorbable amino acids","salivary amylase finishes breaking down the protein"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. After stomach and pancreatic proteases break protein into small peptides, brush-border peptidases (and enzymes inside the enterocyte) complete digestion by splitting these into free amino acids and di- and tripeptides that can be absorbed.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 123-129"},{"q":"Between meals, the gallbladder...","choices":["stores and concentrates bile by absorbing water and electrolytes","actively secretes new bile salts into the duodenum","empties continuously to keep the duodenum supplied in the body under most conditions","manufactures new bile from cholesterol entirely on its own"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. During fasting the sphincter of Oddi is closed and bile is diverted into the gallbladder, whose mucosa absorbs water and electrolytes to concentrate the bile several-fold; it is then released when a fatty meal triggers CCK.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 17"},{"q":"Bile salts are used efficiently because most are...","choices":["broken down for energy once fat absorption is complete","reabsorbed in the ileum and returned to the liver for reuse (enterohepatic circulation)","excreted entirely in the feces after a single use under most conditions throughout the body","converted into pancreatic enzymes in the duodenum"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. After aiding fat absorption, the great majority of bile salts are reabsorbed in the terminal ileum and carried back to the liver in the portal blood to be secreted again; this enterohepatic circulation recycles the limited bile-salt pool many times per meal.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-17"},{"q":"Bile contains both bile salts and bile pigments; the bile pigments (mainly bilirubin) are...","choices":["hormones that stimulate pancreatic secretion during this process","the active agents that emulsify fat in the intestine","waste products of hemoglobin breakdown excreted in the bile","enzymes that digest carbohydrates in the duodenum"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Bile pigments such as bilirubin are waste from the breakdown of heme (from old red cells); the liver conjugates and excretes them in bile. In contrast, bile salts are the functional emulsifiers derived from cholesterol.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-17"},{"q":"Glucose and fructose are absorbed by the enterocyte through different routes because...","choices":["glucose diffuses freely through the membrane while fructose requires ATP directly","glucose requires bile-salt micelles while fructose crosses as a free monosaccharide","glucose uses Na+-coupled secondary active transport; fructose uses facilitated diffusion","glucose enters by endocytosis while fructose is co-transported inward with sodium ions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: glucose (and galactose) enter by Na+-dependent SGLT1, whereas fructose enters by facilitated diffusion via GLUT5.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 126"},{"q":"By the time colonic contents approach the rectum, the large intestine has primarily...","choices":["absorbed most of the remaining water and electrolytes to form solid feces","absorbed the bulk of dietary glucose and amino acids","added large volumes of bile to emulsify the residual dietary fat still present","secreted digestive enzymes to complete nutrient breakdown"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The main function of the colon is to reabsorb water and electrolytes from the residual chyme, progressively concentrating it into formed feces before it reaches the rectum to trigger the defecation reflex.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"Rectal distension triggers defecation through which combined mechanism?","choices":["A sympathetic reflex that contracts the rectum and relaxes both sphincters","A purely voluntary process controlled entirely by the external sphincter","A hormonal signal from the colon that stimulates mass movements only","An intrinsic ENS reflex reinforced by a sacral parasympathetic cord reflex"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: an intrinsic myenteric reflex is strengthened by a sacral (parasympathetic) spinal cord reflex, with voluntary external sphincter control.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 65-67"},{"q":"Defecation can be voluntarily postponed because...","choices":["the rectum can absorb the feces if defecation is delayed","the external anal sphincter is skeletal muscle under conscious control","individual mass movements can be consciously stopped anywhere in the colon","the internal anal sphincter is under full voluntary command"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Although rectal filling relaxes the internal anal sphincter reflexly, the external anal sphincter is striated (skeletal) muscle innervated by the somatic pudendal nerves and under voluntary control, so a person can consciously delay defecation.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 61-68"},{"q":"Because portal blood passes through the liver before reaching the body, the liver can...","choices":["return undigested food directly to the stomach","store the absorbed material permanently as bile","metabolize and detoxify many absorbed substances before they circulate","add dissolved oxygen to the blood returning from the gut before it circulates"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Nutrients and other absorbed substances from the gut drain first through the portal vein into the liver, allowing it to process nutrients, store or release glucose, and detoxify drugs and toxins (first-pass metabolism) before the blood reaches the systemic circulation.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 3, 8"},{"q":"Kupffer cells within the liver contribute to defense by...","choices":["producing bile pigments for excretion into the intestine","phagocytizing bacteria and debris carried in from the gut via portal blood","secreting insulin to regulate the blood glucose level","storing iron recovered from the diet for later use under most normal conditions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Kupffer cells are resident macrophages lining the liver sinusoids; because portal blood from the intestine passes through the liver, they are positioned to engulf bacteria and debris before that blood enters the general circulation.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 6-8"},{"q":"Which statement about protein absorption is correct?","choices":["Protein absorption occurs mainly in the stomach alongside pepsin action","Peptides are absorbed intact into blood without any further breakdown","Only free amino acids can be absorbed, since peptides are never taken up at all","Di- and tripeptides are absorbed by their own carrier, then split inside the cell"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. In addition to amino-acid transporters, the enterocyte has a distinct carrier for di- and tripeptides (which is actually faster); once inside, cytoplasmic peptidases hydrolyze these small peptides to free amino acids before they enter the blood.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 127-129"},{"q":"Much of the absorption of nutrients like glucose and amino acids is coupled to...","choices":["the digestion of water into hydrogen and oxygen","the breakdown of the nutrients by stomach acid in most cases","the transport of sodium, whose gradient powers their uptake","the emulsifying action of bile salts on the nutrients"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Glucose and amino acids are absorbed by sodium-coupled cotransporters: the inward sodium gradient (maintained by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase) drives these nutrients into the enterocyte against their own gradients, an example of secondary active transport.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 126-129"},{"q":"Absorbed dietary fat reaches the systemic circulation by...","choices":["being stored within the liver for a time before any of it is finally released","traveling as chylomicrons through lymph and entering blood at the thoracic duct","binding tightly to hemoglobin so as to be carried for transport inside the red blood cells","diffusing straight into the portal vein like glucose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Reassembled triglycerides are packaged into chylomicrons, which are too large to enter blood capillaries; they enter the lacteals of the villi, travel through the lymphatic system, and join the bloodstream where the thoracic duct empties into the venous system.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 135-138"}]},"gi-physiology-v3":{"title":"GI Physiology (v3)","questions":[{"q":"Slow waves in gastrointestinal smooth muscle determine the...","choices":["the rate of gastric acid secretion coming from the stomach's parietal cells during a meal","maximum frequency and timing of contractions, though not every wave triggers one","rate at which the exocrine pancreas releases its digestive enzymes into the gut","absolute strength of every contraction regardless of neural input"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Slow waves are rhythmic oscillations in membrane potential set by the interstitial cells of Cajal; they set when contractions can occur, but an actual contraction happens only if the wave reaches threshold with spike potentials, so they pace but do not force every contraction.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 35-39"},{"q":"The enteric nervous system is notable because it...","choices":["can coordinate motility and secretion largely on its own, independent of the CNS","operates solely through circulating hormones in the blood rather than through any neurons","controls only the secretion of gastric acid and nothing else along the gut wall","requires constant input from the brain to function at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The enteric nervous system, with its myenteric and submucosal plexuses, contains enough neurons to integrate reflexes and control motility and secretion by itself; the autonomic nervous system modulates it, but the gut can function even without central input.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 24-33"},{"q":"As a meal enters the stomach, receptive relaxation allows it to...","choices":["secrete bile to begin the early emulsification of dietary fat","immediately propel all contents into the duodenum at once","accommodate a large volume with little rise in internal pressure","absorb most nutrients before they reach the small intestine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. A vagovagal reflex relaxes the orad stomach (mediated by NO and VIP) so it can expand to hold a meal without a large pressure increase, storing food for gradual processing and controlled emptying.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 44, 46"},{"q":"The peristaltic reflex ('law of the gut') moves contents aborally by...","choices":["contracting the entire intestine at once to squeeze contents forward","relying on sympathetic input to drive rhythmic forward propulsion","contracting the segment behind the bolus while relaxing the segment ahead","alternating haustral pouches that slowly knead contents toward the anus"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: distension causes contraction orad (behind) with receptive relaxation downstream, propelling contents forward.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 39"},{"q":"When acidic, fatty chyme enters the duodenum, hormonal signals act to...","choices":["stop all pancreatic secretion until the stomach empties in most cases","accelerate gastric emptying to clear the stomach quickly","trigger immediate defecation of the intestinal contents","slow gastric emptying so the small intestine is not overwhelmed"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Fat and acid in the duodenum trigger enterogastric signals (including CCK and secretin) that slow gastric emptying; this ensures the duodenum has time to neutralize acid and digest fat before receiving more chyme.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 46"},{"q":"Cholecystokinin, released in response to fat and protein in the duodenum, acts to...","choices":["stimulate parietal cells to secrete their maximal load of acid","contract the gallbladder and stimulate pancreatic enzyme secretion","trigger mass movements that empty the distal colon in the body under most conditions","relax the gallbladder while inhibiting all pancreatic secretion"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. CCK from duodenal I-cells is the principal signal that contracts the gallbladder (and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi) while strongly stimulating pancreatic enzyme release, delivering bile and enzymes to digest fat and protein.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15"},{"q":"When acidic chyme enters the duodenum, the hormone secretin is released and acts to...","choices":["speed gastric emptying so more chyme enters quickly","stimulate the pancreas to secrete bicarbonate that neutralizes the acid","increase gastric acid secretion to aid digestion","contract the gallbladder to release bile as it is usually described here"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Secretin, released from duodenal cells in response to acid, signals the pancreas (and liver) to secrete a bicarbonate-rich fluid; this neutralizes the acidic chyme, protecting the intestinal lining and creating the alkaline pH that pancreatic enzymes require.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 100-105"},{"q":"Late in a meal, as gastric contents become very acidic, acid secretion declines because...","choices":["low pH triggers somatostatin, which suppresses gastrin release","secretin from the stomach directly stimulates further gastrin output","histamine is depleted faster than ECL cells can regenerate it","parietal cells run out of the carbonic anhydrase needed to make acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: falling pH stimulates somatostatin and directly inhibits gastrin, providing negative feedback that reduces acid output.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 90, 94-95"},{"q":"The gastric phase of secretion, which occurs once food reaches the stomach, is triggered mainly by...","choices":["the sight and smell of food before it is eaten","acidic chyme arriving in the duodenum as it is usually described here","distension of the stomach wall and the presence of protein products","a fall in blood glucose between meals"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. When food enters the stomach, distension of the wall and peptides from partially digested protein stimulate local reflexes, vagovagal reflexes, and gastrin release, driving a large portion of the acid and enzyme secretion during the meal.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 92-96"},{"q":"The pancreatic bicarbonate response to a meal is driven mainly by...","choices":["gastrin, released as protein stretches the stomach wall","insulin, released as blood glucose rises after eating","motilin, released cyclically during the fasting state","secretin, released when acidic chyme lowers the duodenal pH"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. When acidic chyme enters the duodenum and pH falls below about 4.5, S-cells release secretin, which stimulates the pancreatic ducts to secrete a bicarbonate-rich fluid that neutralizes the acid and protects the mucosa.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 106-109"},{"q":"The pancreas avoids digesting itself largely because...","choices":["enzymes are secreted so slowly that ongoing tissue repair always manages to keep pace","pancreatic tissue simply lacks any receptors for its own digestive enzymes entirely","proteases are stored and secreted as inactive zymogens activated only in the gut","bicarbonate keeps the acinar pH too high for any enzyme to function"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: enzymes like trypsinogen are stored inactive (with a trypsin inhibitor) and activated only in the intestine.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 103-105"},{"q":"Pancreatic proteases such as trypsin are secreted as inactive precursors that are then activated...","choices":["in the intestinal lumen, so the pancreas is not digested by its own enzymes","only after the food has entered the large intestine as it typically occurs here","by stomach acid before they reach the small intestine","within the pancreatic cells immediately after synthesis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Proteases are released as zymogens (e.g., trypsinogen) and activated only after reaching the small intestine — enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the others. This delay protects the pancreas from self-digestion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101-105"},{"q":"Saliva aids the earliest stage of digestion by...","choices":["lubricating food and beginning starch breakdown with salivary amylase","neutralizing stomach acid before food is swallowed","emulsifying dietary fat into small droplets during this process in the tissues","completing the digestion of protein into amino acids"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Saliva moistens and lubricates food to ease swallowing, dissolves substances for taste, begins carbohydrate digestion with salivary amylase, and contains lysozyme with mild antibacterial action — launching digestion in the mouth.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 76-81"},{"q":"Within the gastric glands, the division of labor is such that...","choices":["both cell types secrete only mucus to protect the lining during this particular process","parietal cells secrete pepsinogen while chief cells secrete acid","chief cells secrete bile and parietal cells secrete enzymes","chief cells secrete pepsinogen while parietal cells secrete acid and intrinsic factor"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Chief cells release pepsinogen (activated to pepsin by acid), while parietal cells secrete hydrochloric acid (which also activates pepsinogen and kills microbes) and intrinsic factor needed for vitamin B12 absorption. Each cell type has a distinct secretory role.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-90"},{"q":"Enterokinase (enteropeptidase) on the intestinal brush border initiates protein digestion by...","choices":["emulsifying protein aggregates so that pepsin can reach them","converting trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the other proteases","activating pancreatic amylase so that it can begin breaking down starch","cleaving dietary protein directly into individual absorbable free amino acids"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which autocatalytically activates chymotrypsinogen and procarboxypeptidase.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 104"},{"q":"Pepsin works best in the stomach because it...","choices":["digests dietary carbohydrates rather than protein in the stomach","requires the alkaline environment created by bile","functions only after being neutralized in the duodenum","is a protease with an acidic optimal pH provided by gastric HCl"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Pepsin is a protein-digesting enzyme with an acidic pH optimum (roughly 1.8–3.5); gastric HCl both activates pepsinogen to pepsin and provides the low pH environment in which pepsin is most active, so it functions well in the stomach and is inactivated in the alkaline duodenum.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-85"},{"q":"Bile salts emulsify fat effectively because each molecule...","choices":["is entirely water-soluble and dissolves the fat outright","has both a water-soluble and a fat-soluble end (it is amphipathic)","binds oxygen to help oxidize the fat for energy in the body's tissues","chemically digests the triglyceride into fatty acids itself"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Bile salts are amphipathic: one part associates with water and the other with lipid. This lets them coat fat droplets and break them into many tiny droplets, greatly increasing the surface area available for lipase to act on.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 130-133"},{"q":"Bile salts aid fat absorption because their amphipathic structure lets them...","choices":["emulsify fat and ferry lipid digestion products to the mucosa as micelles","actively pump fatty acids across the enterocyte membrane using ATP","convert dietary cholesterol into water-soluble bile pigments for excretion","chemically hydrolyze triglycerides into fatty acids and glycerol"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: being amphipathic, bile salts emulsify fat and form micelles that carry monoglycerides and fatty acids to the mucosa.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 20"},{"q":"Enterohepatic circulation conserves bile salts by...","choices":["converting them into cholesterol for storage in the gallbladder","excreting nearly all of them in the feces after a single use","secreting them into the urine for later reabsorption by the kidney","reabsorbing most of them in the ileum and returning them to the liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. About 95% of secreted bile salts are actively reabsorbed in the terminal ileum, enter the portal blood, and are taken back up by hepatocytes for re-secretion, so the same pool is reused several times per meal and only a small fraction is lost in feces.","cite":"GI Physiology (bile), Ch 71 Liver, slide 25"},{"q":"After fatty acids are reassembled into triglycerides inside the enterocyte, they...","choices":["bind intrinsic factor and are carried to the ileum for their later active uptake","are packaged into chylomicrons that enter lymph rather than blood capillaries","diffuse directly into portal blood for immediate transport to the liver","are stored in the brush border until bile salts release them to plasma"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: triglycerides are packaged into chylomicrons, which are too large for capillaries and enter lacteals/lymph, reaching blood via the thoracic duct.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 135-137"},{"q":"The gastrocolic reflex helps explain why...","choices":["eating a meal often stimulates the urge to defecate","the stomach empties immediately when the colon fills","bile is released the moment food enters the mouth","nutrients are absorbed faster in the large intestine"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The gastrocolic reflex links stomach filling to increased colonic motility: distension of the stomach triggers mass movements in the colon that propel contents toward the rectum, which is why a meal frequently prompts the urge to defecate.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"Bacteria residing in the colon contribute usefully to the host by...","choices":["digesting and absorbing dietary fat for the body under most normal conditions","producing hydrochloric acid to sterilize the stool","synthesizing certain vitamins, including vitamin K, that can be absorbed","secreting insulin to regulate the body's glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The large intestine's resident bacteria ferment undigested material and synthesize several vitamins — notably vitamin K and some B vitamins — a portion of which the colon absorbs, supplementing the dietary supply.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"The colon's pouch-like haustra are formed and their contractions serve to...","choices":["secrete digestive enzymes to finish breaking down food","absorb the bulk of dietary fat and protein","mix and slowly move contents while water is absorbed","rapidly propel contents straight to the rectum"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The haustra are sacculations produced by the colon's muscle arrangement; their slow, segmenting contractions (haustration) knead the contents and expose them to the mucosa for water and electrolyte absorption, gradually moving material along toward the rectum.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"The liver prepares bilirubin for excretion by...","choices":["binding it tightly to intrinsic factor for its absorption in the ileum","conjugating it with glucuronic acid to make it water-soluble for bile","converting it into a bile salt that emulsifies dietary fat","oxidizing it into iron that is then returned to the bone marrow"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Hepatocytes conjugate lipid-soluble (unconjugated) bilirubin with glucuronic acid, converting it to a water-soluble (conjugated) form that can be excreted into bile; impaired conjugation or excretion causes jaundice.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-16"},{"q":"During fasting, the liver helps maintain blood glucose by gluconeogenesis, which is the...","choices":["absorption of glucose directly from the digested food","breakdown of stored glycogen into glucose molecules during this process in the tissues","conversion of glucose into fat for long-term storage","synthesis of new glucose from noncarbohydrate sources such as amino acids and lactate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Gluconeogenesis is the liver's production of glucose from noncarbohydrate precursors — amino acids (from protein), lactate, and glycerol — sustaining blood glucose once glycogen stores are exhausted during fasting, which is vital for glucose-dependent tissues like the brain.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9; Ch 68, slides 25-27"},{"q":"The small intestine's absorptive surface is vastly increased by...","choices":["thick muscular walls that grind the food finely under most normal conditions","a single large chamber that holds food for a long time","circular folds, villi, and microvilli that multiply the surface area","a smooth, flat lining that speeds the passage of food"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Three levels of folding — the circular folds of the wall, the finger-like villi, and the microvilli of the brush border — together increase the absorptive surface area enormously, maximizing contact between nutrients and the absorptive cells.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 120-122, 140"},{"q":"Adequate absorption of the fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K depends on...","choices":["an acidic intestinal pH created by gastric secretions","the presence of bile salts to incorporate them into micelles","a specialized active pump unique to each vitamin in this scenario","conversion into water-soluble forms before uptake"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Fat-soluble vitamins are absorbed along with dietary fat; bile salts are needed to form the micelles that ferry them to the enterocyte surface. Impaired bile flow therefore reduces uptake of these vitamins.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 132-133, 144"},{"q":"Micelles improve fat absorption by...","choices":["ferrying poorly soluble fatty acids and monoglycerides to the enterocyte surface","actively transporting whole fat droplets across the cell membrane","chemically converting the triglycerides into small water-soluble sugars for uptake","carrying absorbed fat directly into the portal blood as chylomicrons"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Bile-salt micelles solubilize the products of fat digestion (fatty acids, monoglycerides, cholesterol) and shuttle them across the unstirred water layer to the brush border, where they are released to diffuse into the enterocyte.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 132-133"},{"q":"Glucose absorption against its gradient is powered indirectly by...","choices":["the sodium gradient maintained by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase","the concentration gradient of fructose in the lumen","bile-salt micelles physically pulling the glucose into the cell","direct hydrolysis of ATP by the glucose carrier itself"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Glucose enters the enterocyte on the SGLT1 cotransporter, riding the inward sodium gradient; that gradient is set up by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase, so glucose uptake is secondary active transport ultimately powered by ATP used to pump sodium.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 126"},{"q":"Water is absorbed across the intestinal wall mainly by...","choices":["active transport pumps that move water directly against gradients","binding to bile salts that carry it into the enterocyte","digestion of water molecules by brush-border enzymes during this process","osmosis, following the absorption of solutes such as sodium and glucose"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Water absorption is passive: as sodium, glucose, amino acids, and other solutes are absorbed, they raise the osmotic pull on the blood side, and water follows by osmosis. This is why efficient solute uptake drives water uptake.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 140-143"}]},"hemostasis":{"title":"Hemostasis","questions":[{"q":"Red blood cells are rich in carbonic anhydrase. Why is this enzyme important for gas transport?","choices":["It keeps hemoglobin's iron in the ferric state so it can bind oxygen","It lets most CO₂ be carried in the blood as bicarbonate","It allows the red cell to generate ATP without mitochondria","It buffers the plasma directly by producing lactic acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Carbonic anhydrase catalyzes CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃, which dissociates so most CO₂ travels as bicarbonate (also the body's major extracellular buffer). (A) is wrong — oxygen-binding iron must stay ferrous, and the enzyme doesn't set iron's state. (C) is wrong — RBC ATP comes from glycolytic enzymes. (D) is wrong — the enzyme handles CO₂/bicarbonate, not lactic acid.","cite":"Slide 3"},{"q":"How does the biconcave disc shape of a red blood cell aid its function?","choices":["It maximizes mitochondrial packing for ATP production","It increases the number of heme groups the cell can hold","Its redundant membrane lets the cell deform to pass through capillaries","It stops the cell from ever being trapped and destroyed in the spleen"],"answer":2,"exp":"The biconcave shape provides excess ('redundant') membrane relative to volume, so the cell can bend and squeeze through capillaries narrower than itself. (A) is wrong — mature RBCs have no mitochondria. (B) is wrong — heme number tracks hemoglobin content, not shape. (D) is wrong — aged, stiffened cells are in fact removed in the spleen.","cite":"Slide 4"},{"q":"Aside from carrying oxygen, what is another major role of hemoglobin?","choices":["It acts as an excellent acid-base buffer","It is the main storage form of iron in plasma","It carries the majority of CO₂ as carbaminohemoglobin","It converts bilirubin into excretable bile pigments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hemoglobin is a very effective acid-base buffer in addition to transporting oxygen. (B) is wrong — iron is stored as ferritin/hemosiderin. (C) is wrong — most CO₂ travels as bicarbonate, not bound to hemoglobin. (D) is wrong — bilirubin is made by macrophages from the porphyrin ring, not by hemoglobin.","cite":"Slide 3"},{"q":"Platelets have no nucleus. What is the direct consequence of this?","choices":["They are unable to store calcium for clotting","They cannot adhere to exposed collagen","They cannot contract during clot retraction","They cannot reproduce"],"answer":3,"exp":"Without a nucleus, platelets cannot reproduce. (A) is wrong — platelets do store Ca²⁺. (B) is wrong — they adhere to collagen, aided by von Willebrand factor. (C) is wrong — they contract using actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin.","cite":"Slide 32"},{"q":"What gives platelets their contractile ability, used later in clot retraction?","choices":["Actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin","Osmotic swelling followed by collapse","Beating of surface cilia","ATP-powered flagellar movement"],"answer":0,"exp":"Platelets contain actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin (actomyosin), giving them true contractile capability. (B), (C), and (D) describe mechanisms platelets do not use — there is no ciliary, flagellar, or purely osmotic contraction.","cite":"Slide 32"},{"q":"Platelets enter the circulation through which process?","choices":["Budding directly from vascular endothelial cells","Fragmentation of megakaryocytes","Division of circulating monocytes","Final maturation of reticulocytes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Platelets are cell fragments released by megakaryocytes in the bone marrow. (A), (C), and (D) name unrelated cells — endothelium, monocytes, and reticulocytes (which mature into red cells) do not produce platelets.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"The hematocrit ('packed cell volume') measures which of the following?","choices":["Grams of hemoglobin per 100 mL of blood","The number of red cells per cubic millimeter","The oxygen carried per gram of hemoglobin","The percentage of blood volume made up of packed red cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Hematocrit is the fraction of blood volume occupied by packed red cells (normally ~40–45%). (A) describes hemoglobin concentration, (B) the RBC count, and (C) oxygen-carrying capacity — all distinct measurements.","cite":"Slide 6"},{"q":"How many oxygen molecules can a single hemoglobin molecule carry, and why?","choices":["Two — one for each beta chain","Sixteen — four for each of the four chains","Four — one for each iron atom","Eight — one for each globin chain"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each hemoglobin has four heme groups, each with one iron atom that binds one O₂ molecule — four O₂ molecules (eight oxygen atoms) per hemoglobin. (D) confuses the four chains with eight molecules; (A) and (B) miscount the heme/iron units.","cite":"Slide 21"},{"q":"In which oxidation state must hemoglobin's iron remain to transport oxygen?","choices":["Ferrous (Fe²⁺); ferric iron cannot carry oxygen","Ferric (Fe³⁺); ferrous iron cannot carry oxygen","Either state carries oxygen equally well","Iron is not directly involved in oxygen binding"],"answer":0,"exp":"Oxygen is carried only when iron is ferrous (Fe²⁺); oxidation to ferric (Fe³⁺) yields methemoglobin, which cannot carry oxygen. (B) reverses the states, (C) is false, and (D) is wrong because iron is the oxygen-binding site.","cite":"Slide 27"},{"q":"Why is methemoglobin unable to support oxygen transport?","choices":["It binds oxygen so tightly it never releases it","Its iron is in the ferric state and cannot carry oxygen","It has lost the globin chains needed for cooperativity","It precipitates and ruptures the red cell membrane"],"answer":1,"exp":"Methemoglobin contains ferric (Fe³⁺) iron, which cannot bind and transport oxygen. (A) is wrong — the problem is failure to carry O₂, not to release it. (C) is wrong — globin chains are intact. (D) describes a different process.","cite":"Slide 27"},{"q":"What is the chain composition of the predominant adult hemoglobin (hemoglobin A)?","choices":["Four alpha chains","Two alpha and two gamma chains","Two alpha and two beta chains","Two beta and two delta chains"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hemoglobin A, the main adult form, has two alpha and two beta chains. (B) describes fetal-type pairing, and (A) and (D) are combinations not found in normal adult hemoglobin A.","cite":"Slide 21"},{"q":"Why do differences among globin chain types matter functionally?","choices":["They change how many iron atoms each molecule contains","They determine the red cell's lifespan","They set the activity of carbonic anhydrase","They alter the oxygen-binding affinity of hemoglobin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Different globin chains give hemoglobin variants different oxygen-binding affinities. (A) is wrong — each chain still carries one heme/iron. (B) and (C) are unrelated to globin chain identity.","cite":"Slide 22"},{"q":"How is oxygen bound to hemoglobin's iron?","choices":["By an irreversible covalent bond to the globin chain","By a loose, reversible bond at a coordination site of iron","By an ionic bond, so it is carried as ionic oxygen","By binding to the porphyrin ring, independent of iron"],"answer":1,"exp":"Oxygen binds loosely and reversibly to one of iron's coordination bonds and is carried as molecular (not ionic) oxygen, allowing loading in the lungs and unloading in tissues. (A) is wrong — binding is reversible; (C) is wrong — oxygen stays molecular; (D) is wrong — iron is the binding site.","cite":"Slide 23"},{"q":"In what form is iron transported through the blood plasma?","choices":["Bound to transferrin","Enclosed within ferritin","As free ionic iron","Within hemosiderin granules"],"answer":0,"exp":"Plasma iron is carried loosely bound to transferrin, which can release it to any tissue cell. (B) and (D) are intracellular storage forms, and (C) is wrong — free ionic iron is not the normal transport form.","cite":"Slide 25"},{"q":"What is the main intracellular storage form of iron?","choices":["Transferrin","Ceruloplasmin","Ferritin, formed when iron combines with apoferritin","Apotransferrin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inside cells, iron combines with apoferritin to form ferritin, the principal storage form. (A) and (D) are transport-related proteins, and (B) is a copper-carrying protein, not an iron store.","cite":"Slide 25"},{"q":"Where is the largest share of the body's iron located?","choices":["Stored as ferritin in the liver","Within hemoglobin","Within myoglobin","Bound to circulating transferrin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Most body iron (~65%) is in hemoglobin. Liver ferritin stores, myoglobin, and transferrin-bound iron each hold much smaller fractions.","cite":"Slide 24"},{"q":"A low plasma transferrin level (poor iron transport) tends to produce which result?","choices":["Enlarged, macrocytic red cells","Iron overload deposited in tissues","Increased oxygen affinity of hemoglobin","Hypochromic red cells containing too little hemoglobin"],"answer":3,"exp":"With too little transferrin to deliver iron, red cells are made with less hemoglobin than normal — hypochromic anemia. (A) reflects B12/folate problems; (B) is the opposite of poor transport; (C) is unrelated.","cite":"Slide 25"},{"q":"After hemoglobin is broken down, what happens to its porphyrin ring?","choices":["It is recycled directly into new hemoglobin","It is stored as hemosiderin in macrophages","It is converted, step by step, into bilirubin","It is excreted unchanged by the kidneys"],"answer":2,"exp":"Macrophages convert the porphyrin ring stepwise into bilirubin, which is released to the blood and secreted in bile. (A) and (B) apply to the iron portion (reused or stored); (D) is wrong — the ring is chemically processed first.","cite":"Slide 28"},{"q":"What does it mean that hematopoietic stem cells are 'pluripotent'?","choices":["They can produce only red blood cells","They can give rise to several different cell types","They have already committed to a single lineage","They are mature cells already circulating in blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pluripotent means capable of giving rise to several different cell types — here, all blood cell lines. (A) and (C) describe committed/limited cells, and (D) is wrong — stem cells are not mature circulating cells.","cite":"Slide 9"},{"q":"Hematopoiesis is driven by which two general classes of signals?","choices":["Erythropoietin and thrombopoietin only","Oxygen and carbon dioxide gradients","Vitamin B12 and folate","Growth inducers and differentiation inducers"],"answer":3,"exp":"Hematopoiesis is driven by growth inducers (e.g., interleukin-3) and differentiation inducers. (A) names specific hormones, not the general categories; (B) and (C) are conditions/nutrients, not inducer classes.","cite":"Slide 9"},{"q":"How does hematopoiesis shift in response to hypoxia versus infection?","choices":["Hypoxia drives white-cell output; infection drives red-cell output","Both conditions drive red-cell production equally","Hypoxia drives red-cell production; infection drives white-cell production","Neither condition changes hematopoiesis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hematopoiesis adapts: hypoxia stimulates erythropoiesis (more red cells for oxygen delivery), while infection/inflammation stimulates white-cell production. (A) reverses these; (B) and (D) ignore the selective response.","cite":"Slide 9"},{"q":"From the last month of gestation through adulthood, where does blood cell production mainly occur?","choices":["Bone marrow","The yolk sac","The liver and spleen","The lymph nodes"],"answer":0,"exp":"By late gestation and throughout adult life, the bone marrow is the primary site of hematopoiesis. The yolk sac (earliest weeks) and liver/spleen (mid-gestation) are earlier sites, and lymph nodes are not the main producers.","cite":"Slide 7"},{"q":"Where is the majority of erythropoietin produced?","choices":["The bone marrow","The liver","The spleen","The kidney"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 90% of erythropoietin is made in the kidney (roughly 10% in the liver). The bone marrow is EPO's target, not its main source, and the spleen is not a major producer.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"What is the primary physiological stimulus for erythropoietin release?","choices":["Hypoxia","A rise in blood pH","High iron stores","Increased blood viscosity"],"answer":0,"exp":"Low tissue oxygen (hypoxia) is the key trigger for EPO release. (B), (C), and (D) do not drive EPO; excessive viscosity is a consequence the system tries to avoid, not a stimulus.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"Which molecule links low oxygen to increased erythropoietin gene transcription?","choices":["Thrombomodulin","Hypoxia-inducible factor-1 (HIF-1)","Carbonic anhydrase","Antithrombin III"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hypoxia raises HIF-1, which binds hypoxia-response elements in the EPO promoter to increase EPO transcription. (A) and (D) are coagulation regulators, and (C) is a CO₂-handling enzyme — none control EPO transcription.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"The relationship between tissue oxygenation, EPO, and red cell mass is an example of what kind of control?","choices":["A positive feedback loop","Feed-forward amplification","An open-loop system","A negative feedback loop"],"answer":3,"exp":"More red cells improve oxygenation, which then reduces the hypoxic drive for EPO — classic negative feedback. (A) would be self-amplifying (the opposite), and (B)/(C) do not describe this self-correcting system.","cite":"Slide 13"},{"q":"Why do individuals without functioning kidneys typically become anemic?","choices":["The liver overproduces EPO and suppresses the marrow","Residual EPO (mostly hepatic) is too little for normal red-cell production","The bone marrow is destroyed without a renal signal","Iron can no longer be absorbed without a kidney hormone"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney makes ~90% of EPO; the ~10% residual (mainly liver) is insufficient, so hematocrit falls toward 23–25%. (A) is wrong — hepatic EPO is too low, not excessive; (C) is wrong — the marrow isn't destroyed; (D) misstates iron absorption.","cite":"Slide 15"},{"q":"Why are vitamin B12 and folate essential for red blood cell production?","choices":["They form the heme ring of hemoglobin","They carry iron into the mitochondria","They are required for DNA synthesis during rapid cell proliferation","They directly stimulate erythropoietin release"],"answer":2,"exp":"Both vitamins are needed to make thymidine triphosphate and therefore DNA, which rapidly dividing red-cell precursors require. (A) is wrong — heme synthesis is a separate pathway; (B) describes transferrin's role; (D) is wrong — they don't trigger EPO.","cite":"Slide 17"},{"q":"Why can reticulocytes still synthesize hemoglobin even though they are nearly mature?","choices":["They still contain a functional nucleus","They retain mitochondria and centrioles","They retain some endoplasmic reticulum and mRNA","They store erythropoietin internally"],"answer":2,"exp":"Reticulocytes keep a small amount of endoplasmic reticulum and mRNA, allowing continued hemoglobin synthesis. (A) is wrong — they have no nucleus; (B) and (D) name structures/substances not responsible for this synthesis.","cite":"Slide 18"},{"q":"What is the correct sequence of events in hemostasis?","choices":["Platelet plug → vascular constriction → blood clot → healing","Vascular constriction → platelet plug → blood clot → healing and recanalization","Blood clot → platelet plug → vascular constriction → healing","Vascular constriction → blood clot → platelet plug → healing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hemostasis proceeds as vascular constriction, then a platelet plug, then a blood clot, then healing/recanalization. The other orders misplace one or more steps — constriction comes first and the clot forms after the platelet plug.","cite":"Slide 29"},{"q":"Which mechanism is most important for constricting large blood vessels after injury?","choices":["Myogenic contraction from direct damage to the vessel wall","Thromboxane A2 released by platelets","Sympathetic nervous reflexes from pain fibers","Local autacoids from traumatized tissue"],"answer":0,"exp":"For large vessels, direct injury triggers myogenic contraction, the most important constriction mechanism. Thromboxane A2 (B) matters most for small vessels, while nervous reflexes (C) and autacoids (D) contribute but aren't dominant for large vessels.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Thromboxane A2 released from platelets is especially important for which action?","choices":["Dissolving the fibrin clot once healing begins","Directly activating the intrinsic pathway","Inhibiting platelet aggregation to limit the clot","Constricting smaller blood vessels"],"answer":3,"exp":"Thromboxane A2 from platelets is particularly important for constricting smaller vessels. (A) describes fibrinolysis, (B) is unrelated to TXA2, and (C) is the opposite — TXA2 promotes, not inhibits, platelet activation.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Why do platelets stick to injured vessel areas but not to normal, intact endothelium?","choices":["Intact endothelium constantly releases thromboxane A2","Platelets can bind only to nucleated cells","Their surface glycoproteins repel intact endothelium but adhere to exposed collagen","Intact endothelium lacks tissue factor"],"answer":2,"exp":"Platelet surface glycoproteins repel normal intact endothelium yet adhere to injured endothelium and exposed collagen. (A) and (D) misattribute the selectivity, and (B) is false — platelets bind collagen and matrix, not nucleated cells specifically.","cite":"Slide 33"},{"q":"What is the role of von Willebrand factor in forming the platelet plug?","choices":["It converts prothrombin into thrombin","It helps platelets adhere to exposed collagen","It cross-links fibrin monomers into a mesh","It inhibits platelets to keep the plug small"],"answer":1,"exp":"Von Willebrand factor bridges platelets to collagen, facilitating adhesion. (A) is the job of prothrombin activator, (C) is factor XIII's role, and (D) is the opposite of vWF's pro-adhesive function.","cite":"Slide 34"},{"q":"Activated platelets secrete ADP and thromboxane A2. What do these substances accomplish?","choices":["They activate additional platelets through positive feedback","They dissolve the forming platelet plug","They convert fibrinogen into fibrin","They inhibit vascular constriction"],"answer":0,"exp":"ADP and thromboxane A2 recruit and activate more platelets, a positive-feedback loop that builds the plug. (B) is the opposite effect, (C) is thrombin's action, and (D) is wrong — these promote hemostasis.","cite":"Slide 34"},{"q":"Which step is the rate-limiting step of blood coagulation?","choices":["Conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin","Cross-linking of fibrin by factor XIII","Activation of plasminogen to plasmin","Formation of prothrombin activator"],"answer":3,"exp":"Forming prothrombin activator is the rate-limiting step; once formed, it rapidly converts prothrombin to thrombin. (A) and (B) occur downstream, and (C) is part of clot breakdown, not formation.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"What does prothrombin activator do?","choices":["It converts fibrinogen directly into fibrin","It converts prothrombin to thrombin in the presence of calcium","It cross-links adjacent fibrin fibers","It activates plasminogen to plasmin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Prothrombin activator, with Ca²⁺, converts prothrombin to thrombin. (A) is thrombin's downstream action, (C) is factor XIII's role, and (D) belongs to tissue plasminogen activator in fibrinolysis.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"How does thrombin act on fibrinogen?","choices":["It cleaves small peptides from fibrinogen, forming fibrin monomers that polymerize","It directly cross-links fibrinogen into a stable mesh","It converts fibrinogen back into prothrombin","It degrades fibrinogen into soluble fragments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Thrombin removes small peptides from fibrinogen to create fibrin monomers, which polymerize into fibrin fibers. (B) is factor XIII's cross-linking step, (C) reverses the pathway, and (D) describes plasmin's degradative action.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"What is the function of factor XIII (fibrin-stabilizing factor)?","choices":["It converts prothrombin to thrombin","It initiates the extrinsic pathway","It covalently cross-links fibrin, strengthening the clot","It dissolves the clot after healing"],"answer":2,"exp":"Factor XIII, activated by thrombin, covalently cross-links fibrin monomers and fibers, so the clot is weak without it. (A) is prothrombin activator's role, (B) is tissue factor's role, and (D) describes plasmin.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"How does thrombin promote clot extension through positive feedback?","choices":["By inactivating factor V to slow the reaction","By acting on prothrombin and other factors to generate still more thrombin","By dissolving fibrin at the clot's edge","By blocking recruitment of additional platelets"],"answer":1,"exp":"Thrombin feeds back to produce more thrombin and more prothrombin activator, extending the clot. (A) is the opposite — thrombin activates factor V; (C) and (D) would limit the clot, not extend it.","cite":"Slide 42"},{"q":"Clot retraction depends on which cells, acting through what mechanism?","choices":["Platelets contracting via actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin","Red cells contracting by osmotic shrinkage","No cells — retraction is purely spontaneous","White cells engulfing and compacting fibrin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Platelets bound to fibrin contract using actin/myosin/thrombosthenin, tightening the clot; retraction will not occur without platelets. (B), (C), and (D) are incorrect — red cells, spontaneous action, and white cells do not drive retraction.","cite":"Slide 43"},{"q":"What initiates the extrinsic pathway of coagulation?","choices":["Blood contacting collagen or a glass surface","Activation of factor XII","Thrombin cleaving fibrinogen","Release of tissue factor from traumatized tissue"],"answer":3,"exp":"The extrinsic pathway begins when injured tissue releases tissue factor (factor III). (A) and (B) start the intrinsic pathway, and (C) is a later, common-pathway event.","cite":"Slide 45"},{"q":"In the extrinsic pathway, tissue factor forms a complex that activates which clotting factor?","choices":["Factor XII","Factor VII (converting it to VIIa)","Factor IX","Factor XIII"],"answer":1,"exp":"Tissue factor acts as a high-affinity receptor for factor VII, activating it to VIIa; the TF–VIIa complex then activates factor X. (A) and (C) belong to the intrinsic pathway, and (D) is the fibrin-stabilizing factor.","cite":"Slide 45"},{"q":"What triggers the intrinsic pathway of coagulation?","choices":["Release of tissue factor from injured tissue","Thrombin cleaving fibrinogen","Contact of blood and factor XII with collagen or a wettable surface","Binding of von Willebrand factor to platelets"],"answer":2,"exp":"The intrinsic pathway starts when blood/factor XII contacts collagen or a wettable surface (e.g., glass), activating factor XII. (A) initiates the extrinsic pathway, (B) is a common-pathway step, and (D) relates to platelet adhesion.","cite":"Slide 46"},{"q":"Where do the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways converge?","choices":["At the activation of factor X (the common pathway)","At the activation of factor XII","At the release of tissue factor","At the cross-linking of fibrin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Both pathways meet at the activation of factor X, entering the common pathway toward thrombin and fibrin. (B) and (C) are pathway-specific starting points, and (D) is a later step after thrombin has acted.","cite":"Slide 47"},{"q":"Why is the extrinsic pathway able to produce a clot faster than the intrinsic pathway?","choices":["It requires many more sequential steps","It does not require calcium","It has fewer steps and can clot in under about 15 seconds","It bypasses factor X entirely"],"answer":2,"exp":"The extrinsic pathway is 'explosive,' clotting in as little as ~15 seconds because it has fewer steps; the intrinsic pathway is slower (1–6 minutes). (A) is the opposite, (B) is false (Ca²⁺ is still needed), and (D) is wrong — both pathways activate factor X.","cite":"Slide 47"},{"q":"How does thrombomodulin help limit clotting?","choices":["It directly digests fibrin fibers","It binds thrombin and activates protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa","It potentiates antithrombin III","It blocks the release of tissue factor"],"answer":1,"exp":"Thrombomodulin binds thrombin; the complex activates protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa, slowing coagulation. (A) describes plasmin, (C) describes heparin's mechanism, and (D) is not thrombomodulin's action.","cite":"Slide 48"},{"q":"What is the role of antithrombin III in controlling coagulation?","choices":["It combines with and inactivates thrombin not bound to fibrin","It converts prothrombin into thrombin","It cross-links fibrin fibers","It activates the extrinsic pathway"],"answer":0,"exp":"Antithrombin III binds and inactivates the thrombin not already trapped on fibrin, limiting clot spread. (B), (C), and (D) describe pro-coagulant steps — the opposite of antithrombin III's inhibitory role.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"What is vitamin K's essential role in coagulation?","choices":["It cross-links fibrin monomers into a stable clot","It converts plasminogen into plasmin","It directly activates platelets at the injury site","It is needed to carboxylate glutamic acid in prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X"],"answer":3,"exp":"Vitamin K is required to carboxylate glutamic acid residues on prothrombin and factors VII, IX, X (and protein C), making them functional. (A) is factor XIII's role, (B) is tPA's role, and (C) is unrelated to vitamin K.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"How is a clot eventually broken down during healing?","choices":["Thrombin is converted to plasmin, which cross-links fibrin","Fibrinogen is converted to plasmin, which builds new clot","Plasminogen is activated to plasmin, which digests fibrin fibers","Antithrombin is converted to plasmin, which stores iron"],"answer":2,"exp":"Tissue plasminogen activator converts plasminogen (trapped in the clot) to plasmin, which digests fibrin and reopens the vessel. (A), (B), and (D) misidentify plasmin's precursor and function — plasmin comes from plasminogen and degrades, rather than builds, the clot.","cite":"Slide 51"}]},"hemostasis-v2":{"title":"Hemostasis (v2)","questions":[{"q":"Red blood cells contain abundant carbonic anhydrase. How does this enzyme support the blood's role in gas transport?","choices":["It loads oxygen onto the heme groups so that each red cell carries more O2 per pass","It speeds hydration of CO2 to carbonic acid, letting most CO2 travel as bicarbonate","It buffers lactic acid from the red cell's own anaerobic glucose metabolism","It binds free iron and keeps hemoglobin locked in its oxygen-carrying ferrous state"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: carbonic anhydrase catalyzes CO2 + H2O to H2CO3, so most CO2 is carried as HCO3-, the major extracellular buffer.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 3"},{"q":"The biconcave disc shape of the red blood cell chiefly benefits its function by...","choices":["maximizing surface area for gas exchange and allowing deformation through narrow capillaries","increasing its internal volume so that it can store a large amount of extra dissolved oxygen","providing rigidity so the cell resists rupture in high-pressure arteries","creating a nucleus-rich center that supports rapid ongoing cell division"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The biconcave geometry gives a high surface-area-to-volume ratio (short diffusion distances for O2 and CO2) and lets the cell fold to squeeze through capillaries narrower than its own diameter, both of which optimize gas transport.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Blood makes up roughly what fraction of total body weight, and what is its largest component by volume?","choices":["about 25% of body weight, with red cells being the largest fraction","about 40% of body weight, split evenly between cells and plasma","about 7–8% of body weight, with plasma being the largest fraction by volume","under 1% of body weight, made up almost entirely of platelets in this scenario"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Blood accounts for roughly 7–8% of body weight (about 5 liters in an adult), and plasma — mostly water with dissolved proteins, electrolytes, and nutrients — makes up a little over half of blood volume, the single largest component.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"A reticulocyte count is useful clinically because reticulocytes are...","choices":["platelets that have just been released from megakaryocytes","old red cells about to be removed by the spleen as it typically occurs here","a type of white cell that increases during infection","immature red cells whose number reflects the marrow's production rate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Reticulocytes are newly released, not-yet-mature red cells; a rising count signals that the marrow is actively producing red cells (for example, in response to blood loss), while a low count suggests impaired production.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Platelets (thrombocytes) are best described as...","choices":["mature nucleated cells that divide within the bloodstream","a specialized type of white blood cell that fights infection","cell fragments pinched off from large megakaryocytes in the marrow","oxygen-carrying cells closely related to red blood cells in most cases"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Platelets are not whole cells but membrane-bound fragments shed from megakaryocytes in the bone marrow; despite lacking a nucleus, they carry granules and machinery essential for hemostasis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 6, 30-33"},{"q":"Each hemoglobin molecule can carry up to four oxygen molecules because it contains...","choices":["four globin chains but only a single oxygen-binding site","four heme groups, each with an iron atom that binds one oxygen","a single large heme unit that binds all four oxygens at once","four copies of the iron-free protein globin without any heme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin is a tetramer with four polypeptide (globin) chains, each holding a heme group with a central iron (Fe2+) atom; each iron can reversibly bind one oxygen molecule, so one hemoglobin carries up to four.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 20-21"},{"q":"The sigmoid (S-shaped) oxygen-hemoglobin curve reflects that...","choices":["binding of one oxygen molecule increases hemoglobin's affinity for the next","oxygen binding is entirely independent at each of the four sites","each hemoglobin molecule can bind only a single oxygen at any given time","hemoglobin binds oxygen and carbon dioxide at the identical site"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin binds oxygen cooperatively: attachment of one O2 changes the molecule's conformation and raises its affinity for subsequent O2, producing the characteristic S-shaped curve that favors loading in the lungs and unloading at tissues.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"Hemoglobin concentration is normally reported around 15 g/dL. This value reflects...","choices":["the number of white cells circulating per microliter","the fraction of hemoglobin currently bound to oxygen","the amount of oxygen-binding protein per volume of blood","the percentage of blood volume made up of red cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin concentration measures how much oxygen-carrying protein is present per unit volume of blood; since each gram binds about 1.34 mL of O2, this value largely determines the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"A markedly elevated hematocrit (as in polycythemia) tends to...","choices":["reduce oxygen-carrying capacity by crowding out the plasma proteins","raise blood viscosity, increasing the resistance the heart must pump against","have no effect on flow because viscosity depends only on the plasma","lower blood viscosity markedly, easing the overall workload placed on the heart"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Viscosity rises steeply as hematocrit climbs; thicker blood increases vascular resistance, so the heart must generate more pressure to maintain flow. This is why very high hematocrits strain the circulation.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Each gram of hemoglobin can bind a fixed amount of oxygen, which is why hemoglobin concentration largely determines...","choices":["the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood","the number of white cells available to fight infection","the speed at which blood clots after an injury","the plasma colloid osmotic pressure of the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Because each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 mL of oxygen when fully saturated, the total hemoglobin concentration sets the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity; this is why anemia, with low hemoglobin, reduces oxygen delivery even when the lungs work normally.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 20-21"},{"q":"Iron absorbed from the diet is carried in the blood bound to...","choices":["bile salts, which shuttle it back to the liver in the body's tissues","hemoglobin, which ferries it through the plasma","albumin, the general carrier for all trace metals","transferrin, which delivers it to the marrow and storage sites"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Absorbed iron is transported in plasma bound to transferrin, which delivers it to the bone marrow for hemoglobin synthesis and to the liver and other tissues for storage as ferritin; free iron is toxic, so it is kept protein-bound.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"The normal circulating lifespan of a red blood cell is about...","choices":["several years, being among the longest-lived cells","120 days, after which macrophages remove the aged cell","30 days, limited by the loss of their mitochondria","a few hours, similar to the lifespan of a neutrophil"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Red cells survive roughly 120 days; lacking a nucleus and organelles, they cannot repair themselves and become fragile, so macrophages (mainly in the spleen and liver) phagocytize the senescent cells and recycle their components.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Most of the erythropoietin that drives red cell production is released from the...","choices":["bone marrow, whenever iron stores in the body run low","liver, in direct response to a rising red blood cell count","kidneys, in response to reduced oxygen delivery to renal tissue","spleen, as it continually breaks down senescent red blood cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The kidneys are the principal source of erythropoietin; specialized cells sense reduced oxygen delivery and secrete EPO, which stimulates marrow erythropoiesis to restore oxygen-carrying capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"Deficiency of vitamin B12 or folate produces abnormally large red cells because these vitamins are required for...","choices":["DNA synthesis, so nuclear maturation lags while the cytoplasm keeps growing","hemoglobin assembly, so cells swell to hold the excess unbound globin","iron incorporation, so cells enlarge to compensate for low oxygen content","membrane repair, so cells round up and expand as they lose deformability"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: without B12/folate, thymidine and thus DNA cannot be made, so the cell grows without dividing, forming large macrocytes.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"When an old red blood cell is broken down, the heme portion is processed so that...","choices":["the iron is discarded in the urine and the heme exhaled as a general rule","it is converted directly into new hemoglobin without change","its iron is recycled while the rest becomes bilirubin excreted in bile","the entire heme molecule is stored intact for later reuse"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. As senescent red cells are destroyed, the globin is recycled to amino acids and the heme iron is salvaged for reuse, while the remaining porphyrin ring is converted to bilirubin, which the liver conjugates and excretes in bile.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Vitamin B12 and folate are needed for red cell production chiefly because they...","choices":["stimulate the kidney to release more erythropoietin under most normal conditions","form the globin chains that make up the hemoglobin molecule","provide the iron atom that sits at the center of each heme","support DNA synthesis required for the rapid division of precursor cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Erythropoiesis involves rapid cell division, which demands DNA synthesis; B12 and folate are cofactors for that process. Their deficiency impairs nuclear maturation, producing large, poorly functional cells (megaloblastic anemia).","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"Vitamin K is essential for coagulation because it...","choices":["binds calcium so it cannot participate in the cascade","directly dissolves clots once a wound has healed during this particular process in the tissues","is required by the liver to synthesize several clotting factors, including prothrombin","is the enzyme that converts fibrinogen into fibrin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Vitamin K is a cofactor the liver uses to produce functional prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X; without it, these factors are made in an inactive form, and clotting is impaired — the basis of warfarin's action.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 46-47"},{"q":"Days after a clot forms, it is dissolved when plasminogen is converted to...","choices":["plasmin, which digests the fibrin meshwork of the clot","fibrinogen, which is redeposited to enlarge the clot","thrombin, which reinforces the fibrin meshwork further","prothrombin activator, which restarts the clotting cascade"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Plasminogen incorporated into the clot is activated to plasmin, a protease that breaks down fibrin (fibrinolysis), clearing the clot once the vessel has healed.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-48"},{"q":"Thrombin does more than convert fibrinogen to fibrin; it also...","choices":["carries oxygen to the healing tissue under most conditions in the body","feeds back to accelerate earlier steps, amplifying its own generation","blocks all further clotting to prevent an excessive clot","immediately dissolves the clot it has just created"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Thrombin exerts positive feedback on the cascade — activating factors and platelets that promote further prothrombin activator formation — so that once enough thrombin appears, the reaction accelerates explosively to seal the wound quickly.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Which event is considered the rate-limiting step of blood coagulation?","choices":["Cleavage of fibrinogen by thrombin into circulating fibrin monomers","Aggregation of platelets into the initial soft plug that forms over the wounded vessel","Cross-linking of fibrin strands by activated fibrin-stabilizing factor","Formation of prothrombin activator, which then converts prothrombin to thrombin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: generating prothrombin activator is the rate-limiting step; it converts prothrombin to thrombin in the presence of calcium.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 40"},{"q":"Thrombin is central to coagulation because it...","choices":["acts only on platelets and has no effect on plasma clotting proteins","converts fibrinogen to fibrin and also activates factors that accelerate its own formation","binds circulating vitamin K directly so that new clotting factors can then be manufactured","directly digests fibrin strands to keep the growing clot from spreading"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Thrombin cleaves fibrinogen into fibrin and additionally activates factors (and platelets) upstream, creating positive feedback that accelerates further thrombin generation and rapidly amplifies the clot.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Immediately after a vessel is cut, the first hemostatic response is...","choices":["conversion of prothrombin to thrombin throughout the plasma","fibrin cross-linking that seals the wound within seconds","release of erythropoietin to replace the lost red cells","vascular spasm that constricts the vessel and limits blood loss"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The earliest response is immediate vascular spasm (myogenic, neural, and local factors), which narrows the vessel and reduces blood loss even before the platelet plug and coagulation cascade take over.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34-40"},{"q":"Place the phases of hemostasis in their correct order.","choices":["Vascular spasm, then platelet plug, then coagulation and clot formation","Clot retraction, then platelet plug, then vascular spasm","Coagulation first, then vascular spasm, and finally the platelet plug","Platelet plug, then fibrinolysis, then vascular spasm during this particular process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Hemostasis proceeds as immediate vascular spasm, followed by formation of the platelet plug (primary hemostasis), and then the coagulation cascade producing a fibrin clot (secondary hemostasis), which is later remodeled and dissolved.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34-48"},{"q":"The intrinsic and extrinsic pathways converge at a common pathway that begins with the activation of...","choices":["fibrinogen, which is the first factor of the cascade","tissue factor, which is unique to the intrinsic pathway","plasminogen, which initiates clot formation","factor X, leading to prothrombin activator formation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Both initiating pathways lead to activation of factor X; activated factor X (with factor V, calcium, and phospholipid) forms prothrombin activator, which converts prothrombin to thrombin. This shared final sequence is the common pathway.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"The extrinsic pathway of coagulation is triggered when...","choices":["tissue factor from damaged cells outside the vessel contacts the blood","platelets release erythropoietin at the site of injury","plasmin begins to break down an existing fibrin clot during this process","blood contacts negatively charged collagen within the vessel"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The extrinsic (tissue factor) pathway begins when trauma exposes blood to tissue factor released by damaged extravascular cells; this rapidly activates the cascade toward prothrombin activator, and it is the faster of the two initiating pathways.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-46"},{"q":"Calcium ions are required at multiple steps of coagulation because they...","choices":["dissolve the clot completely once the healing process is fully complete","are needed for clotting factors to assemble on phospholipid surfaces","directly cleave fibrinogen into fibrin strands","are the enzyme that converts prothrombin to thrombin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Calcium (factor IV) bridges vitamin K-dependent clotting factors to the negatively charged phospholipid surfaces of platelets, allowing the reaction complexes to assemble; without calcium, the cascade cannot proceed, which is why calcium chelation prevents clotting in a blood tube.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Intact, undamaged endothelium helps prevent unwanted clotting by...","choices":["actively cross-linking any fibrin that forms nearby during this process in the tissues","absorbing all calcium out of the surrounding plasma","continuously releasing thrombin into the passing blood","presenting a smooth, negatively charged surface that repels platelets and factors"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Healthy endothelium is smooth and carries a negative surface charge that repels platelets and clotting factors, and it secretes antithrombotic substances; this keeps blood fluid until injury exposes the underlying tissue and triggers hemostasis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34, 48"},{"q":"The intrinsic pathway of coagulation is initiated when blood contacts...","choices":["erythropoietin that is secreted by the injured kidney into the blood","bile salts entering the bloodstream from the gut","a negatively charged surface such as exposed subendothelial collagen","tissue factor released from damaged extravascular cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The intrinsic (contact) pathway is triggered when blood is exposed to negatively charged surfaces like subendothelial collagen, which activates factor XII and begins the cascade using components already present in the blood.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"The extrinsic pathway is triggered when tissue factor is exposed. The extrinsic and intrinsic pathways then converge by...","choices":["releasing thromboxane A2 to recruit additional nearby platelets","activating factor X, which assembles prothrombin activator","activating factor XII on contact with subendothelial collagen","cleaving fibrinogen directly without first forming thrombin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: both pathways activate factor X, forming prothrombin activator in the common pathway.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"Von Willebrand factor contributes to hemostasis mainly by...","choices":["helping platelets adhere to the exposed vessel wall at the injury site","dissolving the fibrin meshwork after the wound heals","stimulating the marrow to produce more platelets under most normal conditions","converting prothrombin directly into active thrombin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Von Willebrand factor bridges platelet surface receptors to exposed subendothelial collagen, anchoring platelets at the site of injury; it also stabilizes factor VIII in the circulation, so its deficiency causes a bleeding tendency.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 33-34"}]},"hemostasis-v3":{"title":"Hemostasis (v3)","questions":[{"q":"Albumin, the most abundant plasma protein, is important because it...","choices":["forms the fibrin meshwork that seals a damaged vessel as it is usually described here","carries oxygen from the lungs to the peripheral tissues","generates most of the plasma colloid osmotic pressure and transports many substances","acts as an antibody that neutralizes invading microbes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Albumin is the chief contributor to plasma colloid (oncotic) osmotic pressure, keeping fluid within the vasculature, and it serves as a carrier for hormones, fatty acids, drugs, and other poorly soluble substances. Low albumin therefore causes edema.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-5"},{"q":"Blood serves three broad roles — transport, regulation, and protection. Which pairing correctly matches a component to one of these roles?","choices":["Platelets transport dietary nutrients, while the red cells are what defend against infection","White cells regulate body temperature, while plasma proteins carry oxygen","Plasma dissolves most oxygen for transport, while the red cells are what actually clot the blood","Red cells carry out transport of oxygen, while platelets and clotting proteins provide protection"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Red cells (via hemoglobin) exemplify the transport role by carrying oxygen, while platelets and plasma clotting proteins serve the protective role by sealing damaged vessels; each component maps to a distinct one of blood's broad functions.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"Plasma differs from serum in that plasma still contains...","choices":["the clotting proteins such as fibrinogen that serum has lost","antibodies that are absent from serum as it typically occurs here","dissolved oxygen that serum cannot hold","far more red blood cells than serum does"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Plasma is the fluid obtained when clotting is prevented, so it retains fibrinogen and the other clotting factors; serum is the fluid left after blood has clotted, meaning those clotting proteins have been consumed and removed. That is the defining difference between the two.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-5"},{"q":"When a blood sample is centrifuged, the thin 'buffy coat' between the packed red cells and the plasma consists of...","choices":["white blood cells and platelets","clotting factors that have precipitated out","concentrated plasma proteins only","immature red blood cells released early"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Centrifuged blood separates into dense red cells at the bottom, plasma on top, and a thin intermediate buffy coat containing the white blood cells and platelets, which are intermediate in density between red cells and plasma.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"Which best describes a functional distinction between plasma proteins and the formed elements of blood?","choices":["Plasma proteins buffer carbon dioxide, while the formed elements dissolve dietary lipids","Plasma proteins carry oxygen, while the formed elements maintain colloid osmotic pressure","Plasma proteins clot the blood on their own, while the formed elements neutralize all invading toxins","Plasma proteins such as albumin generate colloid osmotic pressure, while red cells transport oxygen"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Albumin and the other plasma proteins are too large to cross the capillary wall freely, so they hold water in the vasculature and create colloid (oncotic) osmotic pressure; the formed element responsible for oxygen carriage is the red cell, via hemoglobin. The two therefore serve genuinely different roles.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"Each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 mL of O2. Why does anemia lower oxygen delivery even when arterial PO2 is normal?","choices":["Less hemoglobin is available to bind oxygen, so the oxygen content per volume of blood falls","Fewer red cells increase plasma viscosity, which physically traps the oxygen under these conditions","Anemia saturates the remaining hemoglobin so tightly that it cannot release oxygen","Low hemoglobin somehow raises arterial PO2 but then blocks oxygen from leaving the plasma"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Oxygen content depends on how much hemoglobin is present, not just on PO2. With fewer grams of hemoglobin, each unit of blood carries fewer milliliters of O2 even though PO2 (and therefore saturation) is normal, so delivery drops.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"Each hemoglobin molecule can transport four O2 molecules. Which structural feature accounts for this?","choices":["Four carbonic anhydrase sites that each convert one O2 for transport","Four globin chains that each dissolve one O2 into the red-cell cytoplasm","Four disulfide bonds that each trap a single dissolved oxygen molecule","Four heme groups, each with one iron atom that reversibly binds one O2"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: adult hemoglobin has four globin chains, each with a heme/iron that reversibly binds one O2, so four O2 per molecule.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"Anemia is fundamentally a state in which...","choices":["the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity is reduced below normal","the white blood cell count falls below the normal range","arterial oxygen partial pressure is always markedly low","the blood carries too much oxygen for the tissues to use"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Anemia means a deficiency of functional hemoglobin (from too few red cells or too little hemoglobin per cell), which lowers the amount of oxygen the blood can carry and deliver to tissues, regardless of the specific cause.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 20-21"},{"q":"A hematocrit of 42% tells you which of the following about a whole-blood sample?","choices":["Red cells occupy about 42% of whole-blood volume, the remainder being plasma","Plasma proteins account for close to 42% of the blood's osmotic pressure","About 42% of circulating hemoglobin is currently saturated with oxygen","Hemoglobin makes up roughly 42% of the mass of each individual red cell"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: hematocrit is the packed cell (mostly RBC) volume as a percent of whole blood, normally ~40-45%.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"In polycythemia the oxygen-carrying capacity rises, yet the condition can impair circulation because...","choices":["the plasma volume expands and dilutes the hemoglobin","the kidneys stop producing erythropoietin entirely","the extra red cells cannot bind any oxygen at all as it typically occurs here","the accompanying rise in blood viscosity increases resistance to flow"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Although more red cells raise oxygen-carrying capacity, the higher hematocrit sharply increases blood viscosity; the thicker blood resists flow and raises the load on the heart, which can offset or outweigh the benefit of extra oxygen capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Erythropoietin secretion is governed by a negative feedback loop in which...","choices":["the liver senses red cell count and sets erythropoietin directly","erythropoietin rises steadily regardless of oxygen levels under most normal conditions","high tissue oxygen raises erythropoietin to make more red cells","low tissue oxygen raises erythropoietin, and restored oxygen delivery lowers it"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. When tissue oxygen delivery falls, the kidneys secrete more erythropoietin, stimulating red cell production; as the added red cells restore oxygen delivery, the stimulus subsides and erythropoietin falls, closing the loop and keeping red cell mass appropriate.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"All blood cell lines ultimately arise from...","choices":["endothelial cells lining the marrow sinusoids","pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow","mature lymphocytes that dedifferentiate in the spleen","circulating monocytes that divide within the blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Every blood cell lineage — red cells, all white cells, and platelets — derives from pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells in the marrow, which give rise to committed progenitors under the influence of specific growth factors.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"When senescent red cells are broken down, most of their iron is...","choices":["converted into bilirubin so it can be stored in the liver","excreted unchanged in the bile as the body's main iron-removal route","recycled by macrophages and returned to the marrow for new hemoglobin","lost through the kidneys and must be fully replaced by diet each day"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages of the reticuloendothelial system phagocytize old red cells, salvage the iron, and return it (via transferrin) to the marrow, so the body reuses iron efficiently rather than relying on daily intake.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Adequate red cell production depends on vitamin B12, whose absorption in turn requires...","choices":["erythropoietin that is produced mainly by the kidneys","intrinsic factor secreted by the gastric parietal cells","pancreatic amylase acting in the duodenum","bile salts released from the gallbladder under these conditions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vitamin B12 must bind intrinsic factor, made by gastric parietal cells, to be absorbed in the terminal ileum; loss of intrinsic factor (as in atrophic gastritis) causes B12 deficiency and the impaired red-cell maturation of pernicious anemia.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17; GI B12 slides"},{"q":"Chronic hypoxia raises red-cell production largely through which mechanism?","choices":["Stabilized HIF-1 drives kidney erythropoietin output, boosting marrow erythropoiesis","Direct hypoxic stimulation of the marrow stem cells acting independently of any hormone","Increased hepatic transferrin release that accelerates hemoglobin assembly","Sympathetic signaling to the spleen that releases stored mature red cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: hypoxia stabilizes HIF-1, which increases renal erythropoietin, stimulating marrow production of red cells.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"Formation of the platelet plug follows the sequence of...","choices":["aggregation first, then adhesion, and finally activation under these conditions","adhesion to the injured wall, activation, then aggregation into a plug","conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin before any platelets act","dissolution of the vessel wall to release clotting factors"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Platelets first adhere to exposed collagen at the injury (aided by von Willebrand factor), then become activated and release mediators such as ADP and thromboxane A2, which recruit and cause more platelets to aggregate, building the primary hemostatic plug.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-34"},{"q":"The immediate vascular spasm after a vessel is cut is produced by a combination of...","choices":["local myogenic contraction, nervous reflexes, and platelet-released factors","a rise in blood pressure that forces the vessel closed","erythropoietin acting on the vessel wall during this particular process in the tissues","the fibrin meshwork physically squeezing the vessel shut"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vascular spasm arises from several sources: direct myogenic contraction of the injured vessel, local and nervous reflexes triggered by pain and injury, and vasoconstrictor substances (like thromboxane A2 and serotonin) released by platelets; more severe trauma produces stronger spasm.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34-37"},{"q":"During the platelet response to injury, dense-granule contents such as serotonin contribute by...","choices":["dissolving the forming clot to keep the vessel open","converting fibrinogen into fibrin at the wound","promoting vasoconstriction that reinforces the initial vascular spasm","carrying oxygen to the injured tissue under most conditions in the body"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Activated platelets release serotonin and thromboxane A2 from their granules; these promote vasoconstriction, reinforcing the vascular spasm that reduces blood flow through the injured vessel while the plug and clot form.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-37"},{"q":"On healthy, intact endothelium, what normally limits inappropriate clot formation?","choices":["Rapid platelet turnover that clears activated factors before they can act","Continuous low-level plasmin release that digests any fibrin as it forms","High local calcium that keeps the clotting factors in their inactive states","A smooth glycocalyx plus thrombomodulin that diverts thrombin toward protein C"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the smooth glycocalyx repels platelets/factors, and thrombomodulin binds thrombin to activate protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 48"},{"q":"When platelets contact exposed collagen, they become activated and...","choices":["absorb calcium so it cannot participate in the clotting cascade during this particular process","release plasmin that immediately begins dissolving the clot as it forms","secrete erythropoietin that stimulates the marrow to replace them","release ADP and thromboxane A2 that recruit and activate additional platelets"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Activated platelets undergo the release reaction, secreting ADP and thromboxane A2; these recruit and activate more platelets, creating positive feedback that builds the platelet plug at the injury site.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 34"},{"q":"Antithrombin III limits clotting by...","choices":["supplying vitamin K for new factor synthesis","inactivating thrombin and other activated clotting factors","stimulating the platelets to aggregate together much faster","cross-linking fibrin to strengthen the clot"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Antithrombin III is a natural anticoagulant that binds and neutralizes thrombin and several other activated serine-protease factors, restraining the cascade and helping confine clot formation to the site of injury (its action is greatly accelerated by heparin).","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 48"},{"q":"Once fibrin strands form, factor XIII strengthens the clot by...","choices":["activating platelets to release more thromboxane","dissolving excess fibrin to limit the clot's size","cross-linking adjacent fibrin strands into a stable meshwork","converting still more fibrinogen into new fibrin strands"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Activated fibrin-stabilizing factor (factor XIII) forms covalent cross-links between fibrin strands, converting the initially loose fibrin into a strong, stable three-dimensional meshwork that resists breakdown.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Von Willebrand factor contributes to primary hemostasis mainly by...","choices":["cleaving fibrinogen into the fibrin strands that anchor the platelet mass","bridging platelets to exposed collagen so they adhere at the injury site","converting prothrombin to thrombin on the surface of activated platelets","triggering vascular smooth muscle spasm to narrow the damaged vessel"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: von Willebrand factor binds platelets to exposed subendothelial collagen, promoting adhesion of the plug.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 34"},{"q":"Vitamin K is required for the liver to make functional prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X because it...","choices":["cleaves the inactive factor precursors into their active protease forms","enables carboxylation of glutamate residues needed for calcium binding","supplies the phospholipid surface where these clotting factors are assembled","transports the finished factors from hepatocytes into the circulating plasma"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: vitamin K is the cofactor for carboxylating glutamate residues, allowing these factors to bind calcium and function.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 54"},{"q":"After a clot forms, clot retraction occurs as platelets...","choices":["release erythropoietin to replace lost red cells","convert fibrin back into soluble fibrinogen during this particular process","contract and pull the fibrin strands together, drawing wound edges closer","dissolve the fibrin to reopen the vessel immediately"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Platelets trapped in the clot contract, pulling on the fibrin meshwork; this retracts the clot, squeezes out serum, and draws the edges of the damaged vessel closer together, aiding healing.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-43"},{"q":"A very low platelet count tends to cause bleeding because platelets are needed to...","choices":["carry the oxygen required for wound healing during this particular process","form the initial plug and support the reactions of the clotting cascade","dissolve clots so blood can keep flowing freely","produce the antibodies that fight wound infection"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Platelets form the primary hemostatic plug at sites of injury and provide the phospholipid surface on which clotting reactions assemble; when their number is too low, both plug formation and clot generation are impaired, producing a bleeding tendency.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-34"},{"q":"Heparin acts as an anticoagulant chiefly by...","choices":["supplying the vitamin K needed to make clotting factors","directly cross-linking fibrin to trap the clotting factors","greatly enhancing the activity of antithrombin against thrombin","stimulating platelets to form a stronger plug during this process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Heparin binds antithrombin III and dramatically accelerates its ability to inactivate thrombin and other activated clotting factors; this potentiation is why heparin rapidly reduces clotting, and it is normally released in small amounts by mast cells and basophils.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 48"},{"q":"To keep a donated blood sample from clotting during storage, an agent is added that removes or binds calcium; this works because calcium is...","choices":["the trigger that begins the intrinsic pathway","the enzyme that directly cleaves fibrinogen into fibrin","required at several steps of the clotting cascade","needed only to dissolve clots after they form"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Calcium ions (factor IV) are needed for multiple reactions of the coagulation cascade, so binding or removing calcium (for example, with citrate) prevents the cascade from proceeding and keeps stored blood from clotting.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Fibrinolysis is triggered when plasminogen activators such as tPA...","choices":["convert plasminogen trapped in the clot into active plasmin","stimulate platelets to build a larger clot during this process","convert plasmin back into inactive plasminogen","cross-link fibrin strands to strengthen the clot"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) and similar activators convert clot-bound plasminogen into plasmin, the enzyme that digests fibrin; this gradually dissolves the clot once the vessel has healed and restores normal flow.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-48"},{"q":"Platelets and healthy endothelium exert opposing influences on clotting because platelets release thromboxane A2 while intact endothelium releases...","choices":["additional thromboxane A2 to reinforce aggregation","prostacyclin, which inhibits platelet aggregation and dilates the vessel","fibrinogen to accelerate clot formation on its surface","erythropoietin to stimulate red cell production during this particular process"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Thromboxane A2 from activated platelets promotes aggregation and vasoconstriction, whereas intact endothelium releases prostacyclin, which inhibits platelet aggregation and dilates the vessel; the balance keeps clotting localized to injury sites.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-34, 48"}]},"immunology":{"title":"Immunology","questions":[{"q":"White blood cells defend against infection through which two broad strategies?","choices":["Phagocytosis of invaders and forming antibodies/sensitized lymphocytes","Delivering oxygen and removing carbon dioxide","Clotting blood and repairing damaged vessels","Buffering pH and transporting hormones"],"answer":0,"exp":"WBCs both directly ingest invaders by phagocytosis and generate antibodies/sensitized lymphocytes that neutralize specific invaders. (B) and (D) describe red-cell and plasma roles, and (C) is the job of platelets and clotting factors, not the defensive strategies of WBCs.","cite":"Slide 3"},{"q":"Among the white blood cell types listed in the deck, which functions specifically to activate blood clotting?","choices":["Neutrophils","Eosinophils","Platelets","Lymphocytes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Platelets (from megakaryocytes) are grouped with the WBCs here and function specifically to trigger blood clotting. Neutrophils and eosinophils are phagocytic/effector granulocytes, and lymphocytes serve the immune system — none of these initiate clotting.","cite":"Slide 4"},{"q":"How does the number of white blood cells compare with red blood cells in the blood?","choices":["WBCs are roughly equal in number to RBCs","WBCs are about 700-fold fewer than RBCs","WBCs outnumber RBCs about 10-fold","WBCs are about 10-fold fewer than RBCs"],"answer":1,"exp":"With ~7,000 WBC/µL versus ~5,000,000 RBC/µL, WBCs are roughly 700-fold fewer than red cells. The other options misstate this large disparity.","cite":"Slide 5"},{"q":"Where do granulocytes and monocytes primarily develop, and what happens to most of them before they are needed?","choices":["In lymph nodes; they circulate in blood immediately","In the thymus; they are stored in the spleen","In bone marrow; most are stored there until needed peripherally","In the liver; they mature within peripheral tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Granulocytes and monocytes develop in the bone marrow, where about three times as many are stored as circulate, ready for release. (A), (B), and (D) misplace both the developmental site and the storage pool.","cite":"Slide 11"},{"q":"Where do most lymphocytes develop?","choices":["Peripheral lymphoid organs such as the thymus, spleen, and lymph nodes","Exclusively within the red bone marrow","In the liver sinusoids throughout adult life","Within the circulating blood plasma"],"answer":0,"exp":"Lymphocytes develop mostly in peripheral lymphoid organs (thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymph nodes, Peyer's patches). (B) describes granulocyte/monocyte development, and (C) and (D) are not sites of lymphocyte development.","cite":"Slide 11"},{"q":"How do neutrophils and monocytes differ in their readiness to fight infection?","choices":["Neutrophils are immature; monocytes act immediately","Both remain immature until activated in the marrow","Neither can act until it reaches a lymph node","Neutrophils are mature and act immediately; monocytes mature into macrophages in the tissues"],"answer":3,"exp":"Neutrophils are mature cells that respond at once, whereas monocytes are relatively immature and become effective only after maturing into tissue macrophages. (A) reverses this, and (B) and (C) are incorrect.","cite":"Slide 13"},{"q":"After entering the tissues, monocytes become macrophages that typically...","choices":["Die within a few hours","Can survive and function for months or longer","Return to the blood as neutrophils","Convert into lymphocytes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Tissue macrophages are long-lived, surviving months or longer. (A) understates their lifespan, and (C) and (D) describe conversions that do not occur — macrophages do not revert to neutrophils or become lymphocytes.","cite":"Slide 12"},{"q":"Which trio of properties allows neutrophils and macrophages to reach a site of infection?","choices":["Diapedesis, ameboid motion, and chemotaxis","Agglutination, precipitation, and lysis","Opsonization, margination, and apoptosis","Phagocytosis, degranulation, and mitosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"These cells cross vessel walls (diapedesis), crawl through tissue (ameboid motion), and steer toward chemical signals (chemotaxis). (B) lists antibody actions, (C) mixes unrelated processes, and (D) lists effector/reproductive functions, not modes of locomotion.","cite":"Slide 13"},{"q":"Compared with a neutrophil, an activated tissue macrophage can...","choices":["Ingest only a single bacterium before dying","No longer perform phagocytosis at all","Phagocytize far more particles — up to about 100 bacteria","Only ingest viruses, never bacteria"],"answer":2,"exp":"Activated macrophages are highly effective phagocytes, able to engulf up to ~100 bacteria and even large particles like damaged red cells. (A), (C), and (D) all understate or misstate their phagocytic capacity.","cite":"Slide 17"},{"q":"What is chemotaxis, as it applies to neutrophils and macrophages?","choices":["Random drifting along with the bloodstream","Attachment of the cell to the vessel wall","Directed movement toward the source of a chemical signal","Ingestion of a foreign particle"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chemotaxis is directed movement toward (or away from) a chemical gradient — e.g., toward bacterial toxins or complement products. (A) is undirected, (B) describes margination, and (D) describes phagocytosis.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"How do lymph nodes help contain an infection?","choices":["They produce red blood cells to replace losses","Macrophages lining the sinuses phagocytize particles, preventing spread","They store neutrophils until an infection resolves","They filter oxygen out of the lymph"],"answer":1,"exp":"Macrophages lining the nodal sinuses phagocytize foreign particles carried in the lymph, keeping them from disseminating through the body. (A), (C), and (D) are not lymph-node functions.","cite":"Slide 22"},{"q":"What is the correct path of lymph through a lymph node?","choices":["Efferent lymphatics → sinuses → afferent lymphatics","Blood capillaries → node → arterial blood","Afferent lymphatics → nodal sinuses → hilus → efferent lymphatics","Hilus → afferent lymphatics → venous blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lymph enters through afferent lymphatics, flows through the medullary sinuses, and exits at the hilus via efferent lymphatics toward venous blood. (A) reverses the flow, and (B) and (D) misroute it.","cite":"Slide 22"},{"q":"What is the role of Kupffer cells in the liver sinusoids?","choices":["They synthesize clotting factors","They store iron released from red cells","They produce bile for digestion","They remove nearly all bacteria from portal blood in a single pass"],"answer":3,"exp":"Kupffer cells are fixed macrophages that clear ~99% of bacteria from portal blood on a single pass. (A) and (C) are hepatocyte functions, and (B) is not the Kupffer cell's defensive role.","cite":"Slide 23"},{"q":"Which specialized macrophages handle inhaled particles and microorganisms?","choices":["Kupffer cells","Histiocytes","Alveolar macrophages","Splenic macrophages"],"answer":2,"exp":"Alveolar macrophages digest or entrap particles and microbes reaching the lungs. Kupffer cells guard portal blood in the liver, histiocytes are skin/subcutaneous macrophages, and splenic macrophages screen circulating blood.","cite":"Slide 21"},{"q":"The monocyte-macrophage (reticuloendothelial) system mainly functions to...","choices":["Remove dead or abnormal cells, tissues, and foreign substances","Transport oxygen to peripheral tissues","Produce circulating antibodies","Generate clotting factors in the liver"],"answer":0,"exp":"This distributed system of macrophages clears dead/abnormal cells and foreign material throughout the body. (B) is a red-cell role, (C) is a B-cell/plasma-cell role, and (D) is a hepatocyte role.","cite":"Slide 20"},{"q":"Macrophages in the red pulp of the spleen are important for...","choices":["Producing erythropoietin","Storing lymph before it enters the blood","Removing invading organisms, debris, and aged blood cells","Presenting antigens exclusively to B-cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Splenic red-pulp macrophages are richly exposed to circulating blood and remove organisms, debris, and senescent cells and platelets. (A), (C), and (D) misattribute their role.","cite":"Slide 24"},{"q":"A distinctive feature of lymphocytes, compared with granulocytes, is that they...","choices":["Live only a few hours in the circulation","Cannot leave the bloodstream","Are unable to enter lymph nodes","Continuously recirculate between blood and lymph and are long-lived"],"answer":3,"exp":"Lymphocytes continuously recirculate blood → lymph → nodes → blood and can live for weeks, months, or longer. (A) describes granulocytes, and (B) and (C) contradict lymphocyte recirculation.","cite":"Slide 12"},{"q":"Why are the tonsils and adenoids positioned in the throat and pharynx?","choices":["To filter aged red cells from the blood","To intercept antigens entering from the upper respiratory tract","To store mature T-cells before release","To produce lymph fluid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Lymphoid tissue is placed strategically; tonsils and adenoids intercept antigens from the upper respiratory tract. (A), (C), and (D) are not their function.","cite":"Slide 39"},{"q":"Compared with blood capillaries, lymph capillaries are...","choices":["Much less permeable to particles","Impermeable to all proteins","Highly permeable, allowing particles to enter the lymph","Identical in permeability"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lymph capillaries are highly permeable relative to blood capillaries, so particles readily enter the lymph (where nodal macrophages can screen them). (A), (B), and (D) misstate this permeability.","cite":"Slide 21"},{"q":"During inflammation, neutrophils first stick to the vessel wall (margination). What mediates this sticking step?","choices":["Perforins binding to the endothelium","Adhesion molecules on the endothelium binding integrins on the neutrophil","Antibodies cross-linking the neutrophil","Complement lysing the endothelial cell"],"answer":1,"exp":"Inflammatory cytokines induce endothelial adhesion molecules (selectins, ICAM-1) that bind complementary integrins on neutrophils, causing margination before diapedesis. (A), (C), and (D) describe unrelated processes.","cite":"Slide 28"},{"q":"Which feature makes a particle MORE likely to be phagocytized?","choices":["A smooth surface","An intact protective protein coat","A negative charge that repels phagocytes","A rough surface"],"answer":3,"exp":"Rough surfaces favor phagocytosis, whereas the body's own smooth-surfaced, protein-coated structures resist it. So (A) and (B) describe features that resist phagocytosis, and (C) is not one of the three selective cues described.","cite":"Slide 15"},{"q":"What does opsonization accomplish?","choices":["It marks a pathogen (with antibody and complement C3) for easier phagocytosis","It directly lyses the pathogen's membrane","It prevents antibodies from binding the pathogen","It neutralizes a toxin's active site"],"answer":0,"exp":"Opsonization tags a pathogen with antibody plus complement C3, attracting phagocytes and making ingestion far easier. (B) is complement-mediated lysis, (C) is the opposite of what happens, and (D) describes neutralization.","cite":"Slide 15"},{"q":"How is an ingested microbe digested inside a phagocyte?","choices":["The phagosome fuses with a lysosome, exposing the microbe to digestive enzymes","The microbe is expelled and lysed outside the cell","Antibodies inside the cell dissolve the microbe","The nucleus engulfs and degrades the microbe"],"answer":0,"exp":"The phagosome fuses with a lysosome to form a phagolysosome, where proteolytic enzymes (and lipases in macrophages) digest the microbe. (B), (C), and (D) do not describe intracellular digestion.","cite":"Slide 16"},{"q":"Which set of changes characterizes acute inflammation?","choices":["Vasoconstriction and decreased capillary permeability","Reduced blood flow and suppressed immunity","Vasodilation, increased capillary permeability, and leukocyte accumulation","Increased red-cell production and a fall in white-cell count"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inflammation features vasodilation with increased blood flow, greater capillary permeability, and accumulation of granulocytes and monocytes. (A) is the opposite, and (C) and (D) misdescribe the response.","cite":"Slide 25"},{"q":"How does fibrinogen leaking from damaged capillaries help contain an infection?","choices":["It clots in the tissue, walling off the area and limiting bacterial spread","It directly kills bacteria by phagocytosis","It dissolves bacterial cell walls","It attracts red cells to the injury"],"answer":0,"exp":"Leaked fibrinogen clots in the interstitium, minimizing fluid exchange and 'walling off' the area so bacteria spread less. (B), (C), and (D) are not fibrinogen's role.","cite":"Slide 26"},{"q":"What provides the FIRST line of cellular defense at a new site of infection?","choices":["Neutrophils migrating from the blood","Increased bone marrow production of white cells","Circulating antibodies","Tissue macrophages already present, which enlarge and mobilize"],"answer":3,"exp":"Resident tissue macrophages act first, enlarging and becoming mobile. Neutrophils are the second line (within ~1 hour), a second macrophage wave is third, and increased marrow output is fourth.","cite":"Slide 27"},{"q":"As a later line of defense, how does the bone marrow respond to a sustained infection?","choices":["It shuts down white-cell production to conserve resources","It increases granulocyte and monocyte production many-fold","It releases mature lymphocytes within minutes","It converts red cells into white cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The marrow can raise neutrophil and monocyte output 20–50-fold and sustain it for months, with the first new cells released in 3–4 days. (A) is the opposite, and (C) and (D) are physiologically wrong.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Eosinophils are especially important in defense against...","choices":["Intracellular viruses","Encapsulated bacteria","Parasites such as helminths (worms)","Fungal spores circulating in the blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Eosinophils attach to parasites and release toxic substances (including major basic protein) that kill them. They are weak phagocytes, so (A), (B), and (D) are not their specialty.","cite":"Slide 33"},{"q":"What triggers mast cells and basophils to degranulate?","choices":["Direct phagocytosis of a bacterium","Binding of complement C3 to the cell","Contact with a rough particle surface","Cross-linking of surface-bound IgE by its specific antigen"],"answer":3,"exp":"When antigen cross-links IgE already bound to their surface receptors, mast cells and basophils degranulate, releasing histamine, heparin, and other mediators. (A), (B), and (C) do not trigger this release.","cite":"Slide 34"},{"q":"When an antibody covers the toxic site of a toxin so it can no longer act, this is called...","choices":["Agglutination","Precipitation","Neutralization","Opsonization"],"answer":2,"exp":"Neutralization is the antibody covering the harmful sites of an antigen/toxin. Agglutination clumps particles, precipitation makes a soluble complex insoluble, and opsonization tags a pathogen for phagocytosis.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Antibodies binding many bacteria together into a clump is an example of...","choices":["Agglutination","Neutralization","Lysis","Precipitation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Agglutination binds multiple particles bearing surface antigens into a clump. Neutralization masks toxic sites, lysis ruptures the target membrane, and precipitation drives a soluble antigen-antibody complex out of solution.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"What is the main role of the complement system?","choices":["To produce antibodies specific to each antigen","To enhance antibody and phagocyte actions and attack pathogen membranes","To present antigens to helper T-cells","To generate memory cells for future exposures"],"answer":1,"exp":"Complement 'complements' antibodies and phagocytes — promoting clearance, driving inflammation, and attacking pathogen membranes. (A) is a B-cell role, (C) is antigen presentation, and (D) is a memory-cell function.","cite":"Slide 53"},{"q":"Which part of an antibody molecule binds to its specific antigen?","choices":["The constant portion of the heavy chains","The disulfide bonds linking the chains","The complement-binding region","The variable portion"],"answer":3,"exp":"The variable portion differs for each antibody and forms the antigen-binding site. The constant portion governs properties like diffusivity and complement binding, disulfide bonds hold the chains together, and the complement region is separate from antigen binding.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"How do cytotoxic (killer) T-cells destroy their targets?","choices":["By engulfing and digesting them through phagocytosis","By walling the cell off with fibrin","By producing large amounts of circulating antibody","By secreting perforins that punch holes and delivering cytotoxic substances"],"answer":3,"exp":"Killer T-cells bind a target bearing its antigen, secrete pore-forming perforins, and release cytotoxic substances directly into the cell. (A) is a phagocyte's method, (C) is humoral immunity, and (D) is inflammation's walling-off.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"Why are helper T-cells described as central to the immune response?","choices":["They directly lyse infected cells with perforins","Their cytokines regulate B-cells, cytotoxic T-cells, and macrophages","They are the only cells that phagocytize bacteria","They form the antibodies of humoral immunity"],"answer":1,"exp":"Helper T-cells secrete cytokines/lymphokines that coordinate B-cells, cytotoxic T-cells, and macrophages — the immune system is nearly paralyzed without them. (A) is the cytotoxic T-cell's job, (C) is a phagocyte role, and (D) is the plasma cell's job.","cite":"Slide 57"},{"q":"How do T-cells recognize antigen, unlike B-cells?","choices":["They recognize antigen fragments presented on MHC molecules","They bind intact free antigen directly","They detect antigen only after it is agglutinated","They require complement in order to bind antigen"],"answer":0,"exp":"T-cells respond only to processed antigen fragments displayed on MHC molecules of antigen-presenting cells, whereas B-cells (and antibodies) recognize intact antigen. (C) and (D) are not requirements for T-cell recognition.","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Which statement best describes innate immunity?","choices":["It targets one specific antigen with tailored antibodies","It develops only after weeks of exposure to a pathogen","It relies on memory cells from a prior infection","It resists organisms and toxins using non-specific, general defenses"],"answer":3,"exp":"Innate immunity uses non-specific, ready-made defenses (skin, gastric acid, neutrophils/macrophages, complement, NK cells). (A), (B), and (C) all describe acquired immunity, which is specific, slower to develop, and memory-based.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"A key contrast between acquired and innate immunity is that acquired immunity...","choices":["Is present and fully active from birth","Does not develop until the body is attacked and can take weeks to months","Provides no protection against toxins","Cannot distinguish one antigen from another"],"answer":1,"exp":"Acquired immunity develops only after exposure, requiring weeks to months to mount a specific response. (A) describes innate defenses, and (C) and (D) contradict acquired immunity's specificity and potency.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"The two branches of acquired immunity are...","choices":["Humoral (B-cell/antibody) immunity and cell-mediated (T-cell) immunity","Phagocytosis and complement activation","Inflammation and fever","Skin barriers and gastric acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Acquired immunity comprises humoral immunity (circulating antibodies from B-cells) and cell-mediated immunity (activated T-cells). (B) and (D) are innate mechanisms, and (C) lists non-specific responses.","cite":"Slide 37"},{"q":"Which cells provide humoral immunity, and how?","choices":["Cytotoxic T-cells, by lysing infected cells","Macrophages, by phagocytizing antigens","Natural killer cells, by non-specific killing","B-lymphocytes, by forming antibodies"],"answer":3,"exp":"Humoral ('circulating') immunity comes from B-lymphocytes that produce antibodies, while T-cells provide cell-mediated immunity. (A) is cell-mediated, and (B) and (C) are effector mechanisms not classed as humoral immunity.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"What is an antigen, and which part of it does the immune system specifically recognize?","choices":["A carbohydrate on red cells; recognized by its charge","A protein or large polysaccharide; recognized at specific sites called epitopes","A small lipid; recognized by its solubility","A metal ion; recognized by complement"],"answer":1,"exp":"Antigens are typically proteins or large polysaccharides (MW > 8,000) with recurring surface groups; the specific sites recognized are epitopes. The other options misidentify both the molecule and the recognized region.","cite":"Slide 38"},{"q":"Where are future T-lymphocytes and B-lymphocytes 'preprocessed'?","choices":["T-cells in the thymus; B-cells in the bone marrow (and fetal liver)","Both in the thymus","Both in the spleen","T-cells in the marrow; B-cells in the thymus"],"answer":0,"exp":"T-cells are preprocessed in the thymus, while B-cells are preprocessed in the fetal liver and then the bone marrow. (B), (C), and (D) misassign one or both lineages.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"According to clonal selection, what happens when an antigen enters the body?","choices":["Every lymphocyte in the body responds to it equally","All lymphocytes change their receptors to match it","It activates the pre-existing clone whose receptors are complementary, which then proliferates","It suppresses lymphocyte division to conserve energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"An antigen selects the pre-existing clone bearing complementary receptors, which then multiplies and secretes matching antibodies. (A) and (B) contradict clonal specificity, and (D) is the opposite of what occurs.","cite":"Slide 43"},{"q":"How can the body generate millions of distinct antibodies from only a few thousand relevant genes?","choices":["Each antibody is coded by its own dedicated gene","Antibodies mutate randomly after every infection","Complement rearranges the antibodies in plasma","Hundreds of gene 'cassettes' (segments) recombine in many permutations"],"answer":3,"exp":"Diversity arises because hundreds of gene segments (cassettes) combine in vast numbers of permutations, yielding millions of specificities. (A) contradicts the segment model, and (B) and (C) are not the mechanism described.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"How does the body mainly avoid attacking its own tissues (immunologic tolerance)?","choices":["Self-reactive T- and B-cell clones are induced to undergo apoptosis and are deleted","Self-antigens are permanently hidden from all immune cells","Antibodies against self are neutralized by complement","Helper T-cells ignore every antigen they meet"],"answer":0,"exp":"Tolerance is achieved largely by clonal deletion: clones that bind self-antigens with high affinity are driven into apoptosis (T-cells in the thymus, B-cells in the marrow). (B), (C), and (D) are not the primary mechanism.","cite":"Slide 61"},{"q":"What is the proposed role of suppressor (regulatory) T-cells?","choices":["To amplify the response to every antigen encountered","To secrete antibodies during humoral immunity","To present antigen on MHC molecules","To help maintain tolerance to self-antigens and limit autoimmunity"],"answer":3,"exp":"Suppressor/regulatory T-cells are thought to restrain helper and cytotoxic T-cells, maintaining self-tolerance and preventing autoimmunity. (A) is the opposite effect, (C) is an APC role, and (D) is a plasma-cell function.","cite":"Slide 60"},{"q":"Active immunity is produced by...","choices":["Infusing preformed antibodies from an immune donor","Exposure to killed organisms, their products, or attenuated organisms","Blocking complement activation","Removing the thymus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Active immunity develops when the body is exposed to killed organisms/toxoids or attenuated organisms and mounts its own response. (A) describes passive immunity, and (C) and (D) would impair, not create, immunity.","cite":"Slide 63"},{"q":"How does passive immunity differ from active immunity?","choices":["It is generated by the person's own lymphocytes after infection","It produces lifelong protection through memory cells","It involves transferring preformed antibodies and is relatively short-lived","It relies on innate barriers such as skin and acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Passive immunity comes from infused preformed antibodies (or activated cells) from an immune individual and lasts only ~2–3 weeks. (A) and (B) describe active immunity, and (D) describes innate immunity.","cite":"Slide 63"},{"q":"Why is a second exposure to the same antigen met with a stronger, faster response?","choices":["The first exposure eliminated all lymphocytes, so replacements react faster","Memory B- and T-cells from the first exposure persist and respond rapidly","Complement permanently coats the antigen after the first exposure","The antigen becomes weaker over time"],"answer":1,"exp":"Memory B- and T-cells generated during the first exposure remain and mount a rapid, amplified secondary response — the basis for booster immunizations. (A), (C), and (D) do not explain the secondary response.","cite":"Slide 48"},{"q":"Which statement about the complement system best captures how it bridges innate and acquired immunity?","choices":["It is part of innate immunity, yet its classical pathway can be activated by antibodies from the adaptive system","It is part of acquired immunity and produces memory cells","It is adaptable and changes over a person's lifetime","It presents antigen fragments to T-cells on MHC"],"answer":0,"exp":"Complement is a fixed, non-adaptive (innate) set of proteins, but antibodies from the adaptive system can trigger its cascade — linking the two arms. (B) and (C) wrongly call it adaptive/changeable, and (D) describes antigen presentation, not complement.","cite":"Slide 53"}]},"immunology-v2":{"title":"Immunology (v2)","questions":[{"q":"Neutrophils are the body's first cellular responders to bacterial infection because they...","choices":["are numerous, circulate ready to act, and rapidly phagocytize bacteria","secrete antibodies that specifically neutralize the invading bacteria","mature slowly in the tissue before they can begin any phagocytosis","live for months in tissues, waiting to present antigen to lymphocytes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Neutrophils are the most abundant circulating white cell and are already mature, so they marginate, undergo diapedesis, and phagocytize bacteria within about an hour of infection, making them the earliest cellular defense.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 3-13, 28-30"},{"q":"Eosinophils are especially important in defending against...","choices":["intracellular viruses, which they lyse using secreted perforins","extracellular bacteria, which they clear mainly by opsonization","parasitic worms, which they attack by releasing toxic granule proteins","fungal spores, which they engulf through receptor-mediated endocytosis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Eosinophils specialize against large parasites such as helminths; they attach to the worm and release toxic granule contents (including major basic protein) that damage it, since the parasite is too big to phagocytize.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 33"},{"q":"Eosinophils are especially important in defense against...","choices":["producing the majority of the body's antibodies","clotting, by helping platelets form a plug during this particular process","oxygen transport to actively infected tissue","parasitic worm infections, and they also modulate allergic responses"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Eosinophils specialize in attacking large parasites such as helminths, releasing toxic granule contents onto them, and they also participate in modulating allergic and inflammatory reactions, which is why their numbers rise in parasitic infections and allergies.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 13-17, 34"},{"q":"The pus that can form at a site of bacterial infection consists largely of...","choices":["excess plasma proteins that have precipitated during this process","dead neutrophils, tissue debris, and destroyed bacteria","red blood cells that have leaked from the vessels","newly formed antibodies concentrated at the site"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Pus is an accumulation of neutrophils that have died after phagocytizing bacteria, together with liquefied tissue debris and destroyed microbes; its formation reflects the intense but self-limited action of these first-responder phagocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-31"},{"q":"Compared with neutrophils, macrophages are able to...","choices":["phagocytize many more particles and survive to keep functioning","divide rapidly within the blood to expand their numbers","carry oxygen to the site to support the inflammatory response","produce specific antibodies against the ingested organism"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages are larger, longer-lived, and far more powerful phagocytes than neutrophils; they can engulf many organisms and large debris and continue functioning, whereas neutrophils typically ingest a limited number and then die.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 29-31"},{"q":"Among the circulating white blood cells, the most numerous under normal conditions are the...","choices":["basophils, which release histamine during allergy","monocytes, which mature into tissue macrophages","eosinophils, which target parasitic worms during this particular process","neutrophils, the first-responding phagocytes of acute infection"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Neutrophils are normally the most abundant circulating white cells and are the first phagocytes to arrive at sites of acute bacterial infection, engulfing and destroying invaders before dying and contributing to pus.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 12-17, 26-30"},{"q":"Lymph nodes contribute to immunity mainly by...","choices":["storing mature neutrophils until an infection calls them out","filtering lymph and exposing trapped antigens to resident lymphocytes","secreting digestive enzymes that break down circulating pathogens","manufacturing red blood cells that carry antigen to the spleen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As lymph percolates through the node, macrophages lining the sinuses trap antigens and present them, while resident B- and T-lymphocytes are positioned to encounter and respond to those antigens, mounting an adaptive response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22, 39"},{"q":"T-lymphocytes are so named because they mature in the...","choices":["thymus, where they are selected for function and self-tolerance","tibial marrow, a specialized region of long bones under these conditions","thyroid, under the direct control of thyroid hormone","tonsils, which serve as their primary maturation site"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. T-cells complete their maturation in the thymus, where they undergo selection that keeps useful, self-tolerant clones and deletes strongly self-reactive ones; the 'T' reflects this thymic education.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 40-42"},{"q":"Kupffer cells lining the liver sinusoids illustrate which principle of the monocyte-macrophage system?","choices":["Circulating platelets become tissue phagocytes at sites of slow blood flow","Monocytes settle in tissue as fixed macrophages that filter passing blood","Neutrophils mature in the liver before entering the general circulation","Lymphocytes convert into macrophages once they reach the portal vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: fixed tissue macrophages such as Kupffer cells strip bacteria from portal blood, filtering the circulation.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 20-23"},{"q":"One way the lymphatic system supports immune surveillance is by...","choices":["absorbing dietary glucose and delivering it straight to lymphocytes","producing antibodies within the lymphatic vessels themselves before lymph returns to blood","pumping freshly oxygenated blood directly to the sites of active infection in the tissues","returning interstitial fluid and any captured antigens through nodes before reaching the blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Lymphatics collect interstitial fluid (and antigens or microbes within it) and route it through lymph nodes for immune screening before returning it to the bloodstream, so pathogens are intercepted en route.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22, 39"},{"q":"Opsonization increases phagocytosis of a bacterium by...","choices":["attracting neutrophils along a chemical gradient toward the microbe","coating it with antibody and complement C3b that phagocytes recognize","fusing lysosomes with the phagosome to form a digestive vesicle","digesting its protective capsule so the cell surface becomes rough"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: opsonins such as antibody and C3b bind the microbe and mark it for recognition and ingestion by phagocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 15-16"},{"q":"Cytotoxic (CD8) T-cells destroy virus-infected cells by...","choices":["releasing perforins and enzymes that trigger the target cell's death","engulfing the entire infected cell by phagocytosis","coating the infected cell with antibody so it can be removed much later","secreting histamine that lyses the infected cell"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Cytotoxic T-cells recognize antigen presented on MHC I of an infected cell, then release perforins that form pores and enzymes that enter and induce the target cell's death, eliminating the reservoir of viral replication.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 59"},{"q":"Dendritic cells are considered the most potent antigen-presenting cells because they...","choices":["form the pores that lyse virus-infected host cells directly","store iron recovered from red cells for later hemoglobin synthesis","secrete the antibodies that tag pathogens throughout the body for destruction","specialize in capturing antigen and displaying it to activate naive T-cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Dendritic cells are distributed throughout tissues, and their principal job is to capture antigen and present it on MHC to naive T-cells, making them the most effective initiators of adaptive responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 55"},{"q":"One direct action of the complement cascade is to...","choices":["present antigen fragments to helper T-cells","form membrane pores that lyse the targeted microbe","generate memory cells for a faster second response","synthesize antibodies specific to the pathogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Beyond opsonizing microbes and promoting inflammation, the complement cascade assembles a membrane attack complex that punches pores in the target's membrane, causing lysis — a direct killing mechanism of this innate system.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 53"},{"q":"The complement system aids defense in several ways, including...","choices":["opsonizing microbes, attracting phagocytes, and lysing target cells","storing iron released from broken-down red cells","carrying oxygen to the site of an infection under most conditions in the body","producing the specific antibodies against a pathogen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Complement enhances immunity in multiple ways: it opsonizes microbes to promote phagocytosis, its fragments attract phagocytes (chemotaxis) and drive inflammation, and its terminal components form a membrane attack complex that lyses target cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 52-53"},{"q":"Why does loss of helper T-cells (as in advanced HIV) cripple the whole immune response?","choices":["Helper T-cells manufacture essentially all of the body's circulating complement proteins","Helper T-cells physically block viruses from entering any host cells in the body","Helper T-cells are the only cells able to directly phagocytize bacteria","Helper T-cells release cytokines that coordinate both antibody and cytotoxic responses"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Helper (CD4) T-cells secrete cytokines/lymphokines that stimulate B-cell antibody production, cytotoxic T-cell activity, and macrophage function; without them, the coordinated adaptive response collapses, which is why CD4 loss is so devastating.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 57-58"},{"q":"Helper T-cells (CD4 cells) are central to adaptive immunity because they...","choices":["directly engulf and digest invading bacteria under most conditions in the body","release cytokines that activate and coordinate B-cells and cytotoxic T-cells","carry oxygen to lymphoid tissues during infection","form the physical barrier that keeps microbes out"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Helper T-cells act as coordinators: after recognizing antigen presented on MHC, they secrete cytokines that stimulate B-cells to make antibody and help activate cytotoxic T-cells and macrophages, so their loss severely cripples the whole adaptive response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 55-59"},{"q":"Opsonization enhances phagocytosis by...","choices":["dissolving the microbe's cell wall before it is engulfed","forming memory cells for a faster response next time during this process in the tissues","coating a microbe with antibody or complement so phagocytes grip it more easily","attracting white cells toward the infection along a gradient"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Opsonization tags a pathogen with antibody or complement fragments that phagocyte receptors recognize; this greatly increases the efficiency with which neutrophils and macrophages attach to and engulf the organism.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 30, 53"},{"q":"Primary lymphoid organs differ from secondary lymphoid organs in that primary organs are where lymphocytes...","choices":["are destroyed, whereas secondary organs store them as it is usually described here","produce antibodies, whereas secondary organs make red cells","are formed and mature, whereas secondary organs are where they meet antigen","encounter antigen, whereas secondary organs form them"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Primary lymphoid organs (bone marrow and thymus) are where lymphocytes originate and mature; secondary lymphoid organs (lymph nodes, spleen, tonsils) are where mature lymphocytes encounter antigen and mount responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22-24, 40-44"},{"q":"Which statement about antibody isotypes is correct?","choices":["IgG appears first, while IgM is the antibody of allergic reactions","IgM appears first in a response, while IgG is the most abundant in plasma","IgE is the most abundant plasma antibody and mainly drives agglutination","IgA is produced only after IgG and functions inside infected cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. IgM is the earliest antibody produced in a primary response (and is a large pentamer with many binding sites), whereas IgG makes up roughly three-quarters of plasma immunoglobulin and dominates the later and secondary responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 51"},{"q":"Why is the secondary response to a repeated antigen faster and stronger than the first?","choices":["Complement proteins are consumed the first time and later regenerate larger","Plasma cells from the first exposure never die and keep secreting antibody","The innate system is permanently reprogrammed to recognize that antigen","Memory B- and T-cells from the first exposure persist and react quickly"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: memory lymphocytes generated on first exposure remain and mount a rapid, amplified secondary response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 48"},{"q":"Vaccination with a killed or attenuated organism works by...","choices":["exposing the immune system to antigen so memory cells form without disease","supplying preformed antibodies that act for a few weeks","boosting the nonspecific innate barriers such as the skin and gastric acid","permanently deleting lymphocytes that react to the pathogen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A vaccine presents the antigens of a pathogen (as killed or attenuated forms) so the adaptive system mounts a response and generates memory cells, conferring active immunity and rapid protection on later exposure — without causing the disease itself.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"Self-tolerance is maintained largely because lymphocyte clones that strongly react to self are...","choices":["stored in lymph nodes and activated only during infection","coated with antibody so that they cannot reach any host tissue","deleted by apoptosis during development in the thymus or marrow","converted into memory cells that ignore the self-antigen"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Developing T-cells in the thymus and B-cells in the marrow that bind self-antigens with high affinity are induced to undergo apoptosis (clonal deletion), removing most self-reactive clones and preventing autoimmunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 41, 61"},{"q":"In the sequence of an acute inflammatory response, which cells typically arrive first, followed by which?","choices":["neutrophils arrive first, followed later by monocytes that become macrophages","red blood cells arrive first to wall off the infection","lymphocytes arrive first, before any phagocytes appear under most normal conditions","macrophages arrive first, followed by neutrophils days later"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Neutrophils are the earliest cellular responders, arriving within about an hour; over the following hours to days, monocytes migrate in and mature into macrophages that continue phagocytosis and clean-up, giving the characteristic two-wave cellular response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-31"},{"q":"Compared with the primary response, the secondary antibody response is...","choices":["identical in speed and magnitude to the first","limited to IgM with no IgG produced at all","faster, larger, and dominated by higher-affinity IgG","slower and weaker because memory cells have died off"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Because memory B- and T-cells persist from the first exposure, a repeat encounter produces a response that is quicker, of greater magnitude, and dominated by high-affinity IgG rather than the IgM that led the primary response; this is the basis of booster immunizations.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 48"},{"q":"Which is an example of an innate (nonspecific) defense?","choices":["high-affinity IgG antibodies tailored to one pathogen","clonal selection of a lymphocyte matching one antigen","intact skin and acidic gastric secretions that block or kill microbes","memory B-cells produced after a specific vaccination during this process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Innate defenses are present from birth and act nonspecifically; physical and chemical barriers such as intact skin, mucus, cilia, and acidic stomach secretions prevent entry or destroy many microbes without needing prior exposure.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 18-20, 60"},{"q":"In an immediate allergic reaction, symptoms arise when an allergen...","choices":["neutralizes complement so inflammation cannot occur","cross-links IgE on mast cells, triggering release of histamine","stimulates the marrow to overproduce red blood cells","is engulfed by cytotoxic T-cells that then release perforin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. In allergy, IgE bound to mast cells and basophils is cross-linked by the allergen, causing these cells to degranulate and release histamine and other mediators; the resulting vasodilation, increased permeability, and smooth-muscle effects produce allergic symptoms.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 64-65"},{"q":"Receiving preformed antibodies (for example, across the placenta) provides...","choices":["active immunity that is delayed but long-lasting","innate immunity that never involves any antibodies","permanent immunity through the recipient's own memory cells","passive immunity that is immediate but temporary"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Preformed antibodies protect right away because no immune response has to develop, but they are gradually degraded and no memory cells are formed, so the protection is short-lived (weeks).","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"Which pairing correctly matches a defense with its immune category?","choices":["Antigen-specific plasma cells — innate; lysozyme in tears — acquired","Complement proteins — acquired; helper T-cell clones — innate immunity","Gastric acid and intact skin — innate; circulating antibodies — acquired","Memory B-cells — innate; natural killer cells — acquired immunity"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: skin and gastric acid are nonspecific innate barriers, while antigen-specific antibodies are acquired immunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 35-37"},{"q":"In an immediate (type I) allergic reaction, symptoms arise when...","choices":["antigen cross-links IgE bound to mast cells, triggering histamine release","cytotoxic cells lyse host cells that display the offending antigen","antibodies precipitate with soluble antigen and deposit in tissues","T-cells slowly infiltrate the skin over one to two days after contact"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: in immediate hypersensitivity, antigen cross-links IgE on mast cells/basophils, causing degranulation and histamine release.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 64-65"}]},"immunology-v3":{"title":"Immunology (v3)","questions":[{"q":"During acute infection, why do neutrophils dominate the earliest response while macrophages dominate later?","choices":["Neutrophils recirculate for weeks, so they reach tissue before slower monocytes","Macrophages act only after antibodies have coated the pathogen for ingestion","Macrophages must first divide within the tissue before they can phagocytize","Neutrophils are mature and arrive within an hour; macrophages take days to build up"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: mature neutrophils respond immediately, whereas monocytes must accumulate and mature into macrophages over days.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 28-30"},{"q":"To reach an infected tissue, white blood cells first leave the capillary by...","choices":["being carried passively into the tissue by bulk fluid flow in the body","squeezing between endothelial cells in a process called diapedesis","converting into red blood cells that diffuse across the wall","dissolving the entire capillary wall with digestive enzymes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Leukocytes exit the bloodstream by diapedesis — deforming and slipping between the endothelial cells of the capillary or venule wall — and then move toward the infection by chemotaxis, following chemical gradients released at the site.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-28"},{"q":"Circulating monocytes contribute to defense by...","choices":["producing antibodies against specific bacterial antigens","forming the fibrin meshwork that walls off infection","carrying dissolved oxygen to the sites of active infection in the tissues","entering tissues and maturing into long-lived phagocytic macrophages"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Monocytes circulate briefly, then migrate into tissues where they enlarge and mature into macrophages — powerful, long-lived phagocytes that can ingest many organisms, clear debris, and present antigen to lymphocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 13, 17, 30"},{"q":"Basophils and mast cells release histamine and heparin, which contribute to...","choices":["the direct killing of virus-infected cells","the transport of oxygen within the blood","the synthesis of new antibodies in lymph nodes","the inflammatory and allergic response"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Basophils and their tissue counterparts, mast cells, store histamine, heparin, and other mediators; when triggered (for example, by IgE cross-linking), they degranulate, driving the vasodilation, increased permeability, and other features of inflammation and immediate allergy.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 34, 64-65"},{"q":"A rise in the circulating white blood cell count (leukocytosis) commonly indicates...","choices":["an active infection or inflammatory process in the body","a fall in the number of red blood cells present as a rule","an excess of platelets circulating in the blood","a reduced ability of the body to fight infection"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Leukocytosis, an increase in circulating white cells, is a typical response to infection or inflammation, as the marrow releases and produces more leukocytes to meet the demand; the pattern of which cells rise can hint at the cause.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-30"},{"q":"Macrophages play a dual role in immunity because they both...","choices":["form blood clots and also filter lymph in the nodes","phagocytize pathogens and present their antigens to activate lymphocytes","secrete acid and also cross-link fibrin strands during this particular process","produce antibodies and also carry oxygen to tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages are powerful phagocytes that engulf and destroy pathogens, and they also display fragments of the ingested antigen on MHC to helper T-cells, bridging the innate and adaptive responses — a key dual function.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 29-31, 55"},{"q":"A lymph node contributes to immunity by...","choices":["filtering lymph and trapping antigens for presentation to lymphocytes","manufacturing red blood cells for the circulation","producing digestive enzymes for the intestine","storing bile between meals for fat digestion during this particular process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. As lymph percolates through a node, macrophages and dendritic cells trap and present antigens to the resident lymphocytes; this filtering role brings antigen and responding cells together, which is why nodes enlarge during nearby infections.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Because lymphatics return interstitial fluid to the blood, blockage of lymphatic drainage typically causes...","choices":["an immediate rise in the arterial blood pressure","a rapid fall in the volume of interstitial fluid","accumulation of fluid in the tissues, producing edema","complete loss of the body's ability to make antibodies"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The lymphatic system continuously returns filtered interstitial fluid (and protein) to the bloodstream; if drainage is blocked, that fluid accumulates in the tissue, causing swelling (edema). This links lymphatic function to fluid balance as well as immunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Lymphocytes are unusual among leukocytes because they...","choices":["survive only a few hours in the blood before being routinely replaced","remain fixed in one tissue for their entire lifespan","recirculate continuously between blood, lymph, and lymphoid tissue","are unable to leave the bloodstream at any time"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Unlike short-lived neutrophils, lymphocytes are long-lived and recirculate endlessly — from blood into lymphoid tissue, into lymph, and back to blood — which maximizes their chance of encountering the specific antigen they recognize.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 12"},{"q":"B-lymphocytes complete their maturation in the...","choices":["spleen, which is their only site of origin","thymus, alongside developing T-lymphocytes","liver, throughout the whole of adult life in the body","bone marrow, before circulating to lymphoid tissues"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. In mammals, B-cells mature in the bone marrow (the 'B' is often associated with the bursa in birds, but marrow in humans); once mature, they seed lymph nodes, spleen, and other lymphoid tissue where they can respond to antigen.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 40-44"},{"q":"The spleen supports immunity mainly by...","choices":["filtering blood and removing pathogens and worn-out cells","producing digestive bile that destroys the ingested bacteria","secreting digestive enzymes into the bloodstream","manufacturing intrinsic factor needed for B12 uptake"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The spleen filters the blood: macrophages in its red pulp and sinuses remove circulating microbes, debris, and senescent red cells and platelets, while its white pulp houses lymphocytes that mount adaptive responses to blood-borne antigens.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 24"},{"q":"Which describes a direct way antibodies neutralize a bacterial toxin?","choices":["Inserting pore-forming perforins directly into the toxin molecule","Binding and covering the toxic site so it cannot act on host cells","Secreting interleukins that suppress further toxin production","Phagocytizing the toxin and digesting it within a phagolysosome"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: neutralization occurs when antibodies cover the toxic/active site of the antigen so it cannot bind host tissue.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 52"},{"q":"The complement system enhances immunity primarily by...","choices":["opsonizing microbes, driving inflammation, and lysing target membranes","generating antigen-specific antibodies tailored to each pathogen","producing the memory cells responsible for a faster secondary response","presenting antigen fragments to helper T-cells on MHC molecules"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: complement complements antibody and phagocyte action through opsonization, inflammation, and membrane lysis.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 53"},{"q":"Interferons contribute to innate defense against viruses by...","choices":["signaling neighboring cells to resist viral replication","directly binding and neutralizing circulating antibodies","forming the membrane attack complex that lyses cells","carrying oxygen to virus-infected tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Virus-infected cells release interferons, which act on nearby cells to induce an antiviral state — producing proteins that interfere with viral replication — thereby limiting the spread of the virus before the adaptive response is fully mobilized.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 52-53, 60"},{"q":"A typical antibody molecule is Y-shaped, and its two identical tips are important because they...","choices":["digest the antigen the way an enzyme would","anchor the antibody permanently to the plasma cell","bind the specific antigen, giving each antibody two antigen-binding sites","carry oxygen to the site of the infection during this process in the tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The variable regions at the two tips of the Y form the antigen-binding sites, both specific for the same antigen; having two sites lets a single antibody link antigens together (aiding agglutination) while the stem region interacts with other immune components.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 50-53"},{"q":"Long-lasting immunity after an infection depends on...","choices":["antibodies from the first infection remaining in the blood forever","a permanent rise in body temperature that deters the pathogen","memory lymphocytes that persist and respond rapidly on re-exposure","neutrophils that stay elevated permanently after the infection"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. During a response, some activated B- and T-cells become long-lived memory cells; on later exposure to the same antigen they mount a faster, stronger secondary response, which is the basis of durable immunity and of vaccination.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 45-48"},{"q":"Antibodies help neutralize threats directly by...","choices":["engulfing and digesting bacteria the way phagocytes do","synthesizing new complement proteins at the infection site","forming pores that lyse the host's own infected cells in the body's tissues","binding and inactivating toxins or blocking a microbe's ability to attach"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Beyond tagging pathogens for other defenses, antibodies can directly neutralize by binding toxins to render them harmless and by coating microbes to block the sites they use to attach to and enter host cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 50-53"},{"q":"The redness and warmth of acute inflammation result largely from...","choices":["loss of all blood flow to the damaged region","vasoconstriction that traps blood in the tissue","vasodilation and increased blood flow to the injured area","antibody deposition occurring within the vessel walls"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Inflammatory mediators such as histamine cause local vasodilation and increased blood flow, which produce the redness and warmth; increased capillary permeability then adds the swelling characteristic of inflammation.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 25"},{"q":"In immunology, an antigen is best defined as...","choices":["an antibody produced by an activated plasma cell","a signaling chemical that raises the body's temperature","a molecule the immune system recognizes as foreign and responds to","a phagocytic white cell that engulfs bacteria under most normal conditions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. An antigen is any molecule (often a protein or polysaccharide) that the immune system can recognize as foreign and mount a response against; the specific portion actually bound by an antibody or receptor is called the epitope.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 45-53"},{"q":"Why can a cytotoxic T-cell not respond to free, intact antigen the way a B-cell can?","choices":["T-cells must first be opsonized by complement before they can bind antigen","T-cells recognize only antigen fragments displayed on MHC molecules","T-cells lack surface receptors and rely entirely on secreted antibody","T-cells respond only to polysaccharide antigens, never to proteins"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: unlike B-cells, T-cells recognize processed antigen fragments presented by MHC, not free intact antigen.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 55"},{"q":"The swelling of acutely inflamed tissue is caused largely by histamine, which...","choices":["dilates local vessels and increases their permeability, letting fluid leak into tissue","forms fibrin that physically enlarges the tissue","carries extra oxygen that expands the tissue during this particular process in the tissues","constricts vessels and drives fluid back into the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Histamine released by mast cells and basophils dilates nearby vessels and increases capillary permeability; plasma fluid then leaks into the tissue, producing the swelling (edema) of acute inflammation along with redness and warmth.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 25, 64-65"},{"q":"When activated by their specific antigen, B-lymphocytes proliferate and differentiate into...","choices":["phagocytes that engulf and digest the antigen","cytotoxic cells that directly lyse infected host cells","plasma cells that secrete large amounts of antibody","red blood cells that transport the antibody in plasma"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Antigen-activated B-cells (with helper T-cell support) proliferate and differentiate into plasma cells, which are antibody factories secreting large quantities of the specific antibody, while some become memory B-cells for future responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 44-50"},{"q":"The primary (first) response to a new antigen is relatively slow because...","choices":["the few matching lymphocytes must be selected and expanded before antibody rises","the innate barriers must fail completely first","memory cells from a prior exposure block the response","antibodies from birth must first be used up during this particular process in the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. On first exposure, only a small number of lymphocytes recognize the antigen; they must be activated and proliferate into a large clone (and differentiate into plasma cells) before substantial antibody appears, producing a lag of several days in the primary response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 45-48"},{"q":"Humoral immunity and cell-mediated immunity differ chiefly in that humoral immunity...","choices":["uses T-cells directly, while cell-mediated immunity uses antibodies","works through antibodies in body fluids, while cell-mediated immunity uses T-cells directly","provides only immediate barriers such as skin and mucus during this particular process in the tissues","is part of the innate system, while cell-mediated is acquired"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Humoral (antibody-mediated) immunity relies on antibodies secreted by plasma cells that circulate in body fluids to target extracellular threats, whereas cell-mediated immunity uses T-cells (especially cytotoxic T-cells) to act against intracellular pathogens and abnormal cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 44-59"},{"q":"The enormous variety of antibody specificities is generated by...","choices":["random recombination of gene segments, producing many distinct lymphocyte clones","the antigen itself instructing the lymphocyte how to fold its antibody","the thymus copying antibodies from previously infected individuals","a single gene that mutates anew during each and every separate infection encountered"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A limited set of gene segments (cassettes) recombine in many permutations during lymphocyte development, so millions of clones each bearing a unique specificity arise from a modest number of genes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 44"},{"q":"Humoral and cell-mediated immunity differ in that humoral immunity...","choices":["provides no memory, while cell-mediated generates lasting protection","acts only inside infected cells, while cell-mediated acts in the blood","requires no prior antigen exposure, while cell-mediated must be triggered","uses B-cell-derived antibodies, while cell-mediated uses activated T-cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: humoral immunity works through B-cell antibodies; cell-mediated immunity works through activated T-lymphocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 37"},{"q":"Natural killer (NK) cells are considered part of innate immunity because they...","choices":["can only act after memory cells have formed during this process in the tissues","destroy virus-infected and abnormal cells without needing prior sensitization","mature in the thymus and require MHC-matched antigen","produce highly specific antibodies after being primed"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. NK cells recognize and kill virus-infected and tumor cells based on general 'danger' signals and altered surface markers, acting quickly without the antigen-specific priming that adaptive lymphocytes require — which places them in the innate arm.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 33, 59-60"},{"q":"Passive immunity, such as antibodies passed in breast milk, is limited because...","choices":["it triggers lifelong immunity through the recipient's own T-cells","it works only against the recipient's own tissues rather than against pathogens","it strengthens over time as the antibodies multiply","the recipient makes no memory cells, so protection fades as antibodies degrade"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. In passive immunity the recipient receives ready-made antibodies but mounts no response of their own, so no memory cells form; as the transferred antibodies are gradually degraded, protection wanes within weeks.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"Self versus non-self recognition by T-cells relies on...","choices":["antibodies coating every one of the body's own cells","MHC molecules that display cell peptides for T-cell inspection","the color of the surface pigments on each host cell","histamine tags that mark self cells as friendly under these conditions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules on cell surfaces present peptide fragments; T-cells inspect these displays and react to foreign peptides while tolerating self, which is how the adaptive system distinguishes self from non-self.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 55-58"},{"q":"Immunoglobulin A (IgA) is particularly important because it...","choices":["is the first antibody produced during a new infection during this particular process","protects mucosal surfaces and is secreted in fluids such as saliva and breast milk","forms the membrane attack complex that lyses microbes","is the antibody chiefly responsible for allergic reactions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. IgA is the main antibody found in secretions — saliva, tears, respiratory and intestinal mucus, and breast milk — where it guards the mucosal surfaces that are common entry points for pathogens and provides passive protection to breastfeeding infants.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 50-53"}]},"metabolism":{"title":"Metabolism","questions":[{"q":"Glucose enters most cells of the body by...","choices":["Facilitated diffusion — a carrier is needed but energy is not","Primary active transport that directly uses ATP","Simple diffusion straight through the lipid bilayer","Receptor-mediated endocytosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Glucose crosses most cell membranes by facilitated diffusion: a carrier protein (GLUT) moves it down its concentration gradient without using ATP. It is not pumped by primary active transport, does not dissolve through the bilayer, and is not taken up by endocytosis.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 4"},{"q":"Which statement about insulin and cellular glucose uptake is correct?","choices":["All cellular glucose uptake requires insulin","Most glucose uptake uses insulin-independent carriers (e.g., GLUT-1); GLUT-4 in muscle and fat is insulin-dependent","No glucose transporter responds to insulin at all","Insulin is required for glucose uptake only in the liver"],"answer":1,"exp":"Most post-absorptive glucose uptake uses insulin-independent transporters like GLUT-1, while GLUT-4 in muscle and adipose is the insulin-dependent carrier. So not all uptake needs insulin, some transporters clearly respond to it, and the liver is not the special case.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 4"},{"q":"Why does phosphorylating glucose to glucose-6-phosphate “trap” it inside a cell?","choices":["It makes the glucose molecule much smaller","It binds the glucose to the cell's DNA","The charged phosphate group prevents it from crossing the membrane back out","It immediately converts the glucose into fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"Adding a phosphate gives glucose-6-phosphate a charge that keeps it from recrossing the membrane, trapping it for use; tissues that export glucose need glucose-6-phosphatase to remove it. Phosphorylation does not shrink glucose, bind it to DNA, or turn it into fat.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 7"},{"q":"The net product of glycolysis (per glucose) is...","choices":["2 lactate, 4 ATP, and 4 NADH","1 pyruvate, 2 ATP, and no NADH","2 acetyl-CoA and 6 ATP","2 pyruvate, 2 ATP, and 2 NADH"],"answer":3,"exp":"Glycolysis nets 2 pyruvate, 2 ATP (4 produced minus 2 invested), and 2 NADH per glucose. Lactate forms only when NAD⁺ must be regenerated, acetyl-CoA is a later product, and the other counts are wrong.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 14"},{"q":"The complete aerobic oxidation of one glucose molecule yields approximately how many ATP?","choices":["About 38 ATP","About 2 ATP","About 100 ATP","About 12 ATP"],"answer":0,"exp":"Full aerobic oxidation of one glucose yields roughly 38 ATP (glycolysis, pyruvate→acetyl-CoA, the TCA cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation). About 2 ATP is the anaerobic, glycolysis-only yield; 100 and 12 are incorrect.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 23"},{"q":"In the electron transport chain, each NADH and each FADH₂ yield approximately...","choices":["1 ATP from each","3 ATP from each","3 ATP per NADH and 2 ATP per FADH₂","2 ATP per NADH and 3 ATP per FADH₂"],"answer":2,"exp":"NADH delivers electrons entering high in the chain (~3 ATP), while FADH₂ enters lower (~2 ATP). They do not yield equal amounts, and the last option reverses the two.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 22"},{"q":"During intense exercise, the main reason muscle converts pyruvate to lactate is to...","choices":["produce extra ATP directly from the lactate","regenerate NAD⁺ so glycolysis can continue producing ATP","store oxygen for later use","make new glucose from pyruvate in the muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"Converting pyruvate to lactate reoxidizes NADH to NAD⁺, which glycolysis needs to keep running when oxygen or mitochondrial capacity is limiting. Lactate formation makes no extra ATP itself, stores no oxygen, and gluconeogenesis happens later in the liver, not the muscle.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 25"},{"q":"The pentose phosphate (hexose monophosphate) shunt is important because it produces...","choices":["large amounts of ATP","lactate to send to the liver","ketone bodies for energy","NADPH and ribose-5-phosphate for biosynthesis and nucleic acids"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pentose phosphate shunt generates NADPH (for reductive biosynthesis) and ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleic acids), not ATP. It does not make lactate or ketone bodies.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 29"},{"q":"Which condition favors gluconeogenesis?","choices":["A high glucagon-to-insulin ratio (as in fasting)","A high insulin-to-glucagon ratio","High blood glucose right after a meal","Low cortisol levels"],"answer":0,"exp":"Gluconeogenesis (mainly hepatic) is favored by a high glucagon:insulin ratio, high mitochondrial NADH and acetyl-CoA, and high cortisol — the fasting state. A high insulin ratio, post-meal hyperglycemia, and low cortisol all suppress it.","cite":"Ch. 68, Slide 30"},{"q":"Chylomicrons and VLDL differ in that...","choices":["both are made only in the liver","chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the intestine, while VLDL is made in the liver","chylomicrons are made in the liver and VLDL in the gut","neither particle carries triglyceride"],"answer":1,"exp":"Chylomicrons are assembled in intestinal mucosa to carry absorbed dietary fat, while VLDL is synthesized in the liver (its triglyceride made largely from carbohydrate). The other options misplace their origins or deny that they carry triglyceride.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 6"},{"q":"Lipoprotein lipase, attached to capillary endothelium, functions to...","choices":["synthesize triglycerides inside adipocytes","package cholesterol into HDL","hydrolyze triglycerides in chylomicrons and VLDL, releasing fatty acids to tissues","make ketone bodies in the liver"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lipoprotein lipase hydrolyzes the triglycerides carried in chylomicrons and VLDL, freeing fatty acids for uptake by tissues (adipose, muscle, heart). It does not synthesize triglycerides, build HDL, or make ketones.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 13"},{"q":"Beta-oxidation of fatty acids breaks them down into...","choices":["glucose molecules","amino acids","pyruvate directly","acetyl-CoA units that can enter the TCA cycle"],"answer":3,"exp":"Beta-oxidation sequentially cleaves fatty acids into acetyl-CoA units that feed the TCA cycle (and ketone-body synthesis). It does not yield glucose, amino acids, or pyruvate directly.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 17"},{"q":"Ketone bodies are produced by the liver mainly...","choices":["from glucose during a carbohydrate-rich meal","from fatty acids, to serve as an energy source for other tissues","to store excess dietary protein","only during the well-fed state"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver makes ketone bodies from fatty acid–derived acetyl-CoA (especially when fat oxidation is high, as in fasting) and exports them as fuel for other tissues. They are not made from glucose in the fed state or used to store protein.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 15"},{"q":"Which is a normal function of cholesterol?","choices":["Serving as a precursor for bile acids and steroid hormones","Acting as the body's main energy currency","Carrying oxygen in the blood","Functioning as a digestive enzyme"],"answer":0,"exp":"Cholesterol is a membrane component and the precursor for bile acids and steroid hormones. ATP is the energy currency, hemoglobin carries oxygen, and cholesterol is not an enzyme.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 2"},{"q":"How does increasing bile acid excretion (e.g., by fiber that traps bile salts) affect plasma cholesterol?","choices":["It raises plasma cholesterol","It has no effect on plasma cholesterol","It converts cholesterol directly into glucose","It lowers plasma cholesterol, because bile acids are made from cholesterol"],"answer":3,"exp":"Excreting bile acids forces the liver to consume cholesterol to make more, lowering plasma cholesterol; fecal loss is the only route of cholesterol removal. So it does not raise cholesterol, have no effect, or make glucose.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 36"},{"q":"Insulin promotes fat storage by...","choices":["stimulating hormone-sensitive lipase","blocking glucose uptake into cells","stimulating lipoprotein lipase and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase","promoting beta-oxidation of fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"Insulin stores fat by activating lipoprotein lipase (loading fatty acids into adipocytes) and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase (blocking breakdown of stored triglyceride). It promotes glucose uptake and opposes fat mobilization and beta-oxidation.","cite":"Ch. 69, Slide 22"},{"q":"To synthesize a non-essential amino acid, a cell needs a carbon skeleton (α-keto acid), an amino group, and...","choices":["an aminotransferase enzyme (a vitamin B6 derivative)","intrinsic factor","bile salts","a fatty acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Making a non-essential amino acid requires a carbon skeleton (α-keto acid), an amino group (from glutamate/glutamine), and an aminotransferase, which is a vitamin B6–derived enzyme. Intrinsic factor, bile salts, and fatty acids play no role in transamination.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 7"},{"q":"Transamination is the process of...","choices":["removing a phosphate from glucose","transferring an amino group from one molecule (e.g., glutamate) to an α-keto acid","breaking a peptide bond by adding water","oxidizing fatty acids to acetyl-CoA"],"answer":1,"exp":"Transamination moves an amino group from a donor (often glutamate) onto an α-keto acid, forming a new amino acid — the core reaction for making non-essential amino acids. Dephosphorylation, peptide-bond hydrolysis, and beta-oxidation are unrelated.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 13"},{"q":"Oxidative deamination of an amino acid removes the amino group, generating...","choices":["glucose","a fatty acid","a ketone body","ammonia, which must be detoxified"],"answer":3,"exp":"Deamination strips the amino group off an amino acid, releasing ammonia (which the liver converts to urea). It does not directly yield glucose, a fatty acid, or a ketone body — those may come from the remaining carbon skeleton.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 16"},{"q":"The urea cycle, which occurs essentially only in the liver, serves to...","choices":["synthesize new proteins","produce ATP directly","convert toxic ammonia into urea for excretion","store nitrogen as glycogen"],"answer":2,"exp":"The urea cycle (ornithine–citrulline–arginine) packages toxic ammonia into urea for renal excretion; excess ammonia is dangerous partly because it depletes α-ketoglutarate and stalls the TCA cycle. It does not build proteins, make ATP directly, or store nitrogen as glycogen.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 16"},{"q":"Amino acids that are broken down to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are called...","choices":["ketogenic, because they give rise to ketone bodies","glucogenic, because they form glucose","essential, because they cannot be made","non-essential, because they are synthesized"],"answer":0,"exp":"Amino acids degraded to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are ketogenic (they can form ketone bodies), whereas those forming glucose or TCA intermediates are glucogenic. 'Essential' vs 'non-essential' refers to whether the body can synthesize them — a different classification.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 18"},{"q":"Which hormone causes breakdown of tissue protein, providing amino acids for gluconeogenesis?","choices":["Insulin","Growth hormone","Testosterone","Cortisol (glucocorticoids)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cortisol promotes breakdown of extrahepatic tissue protein, raising plasma amino acids for gluconeogenesis. Insulin, growth hormone, and testosterone all promote protein synthesis instead.","cite":"Ch. 70, Slide 19"},{"q":"Regarding the liver's blood supply...","choices":["It is supplied almost entirely by the hepatic artery","It receives about 30% of cardiac output, most of it from the portal vein","It receives less than 5% of cardiac output","It has no venous inflow"],"answer":1,"exp":"About 30% of cardiac output flows through the liver, roughly 75% via the portal vein and 25% via the hepatic artery, at low pressure and resistance. It is not chiefly arterial, is far more than 5% of output, and has major portal venous inflow.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 3"},{"q":"The liver acts as a blood reservoir, normally holding about...","choices":["50% of total blood volume","less than 1% of blood volume","10% of total blood volume (~450 mL), expandable in heart failure","no blood between meals"],"answer":2,"exp":"The liver normally holds about 10% of blood volume (~450 mL) and can expand by up to a liter in heart failure or release blood during hemorrhage/exercise. The other figures are far off.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 5"},{"q":"Kupffer cells in the liver sinusoids function to...","choices":["remove bacteria and particulate matter (about 99% of gut bacteria) from portal blood","synthesize bile salts","store vitamin B12","produce erythropoietin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Kupffer cells are sinusoidal macrophages that clear ~99% of bacteria arriving from the gut via the portal blood. Bile-salt synthesis is a hepatocyte function, B12 storage is separate, and erythropoietin is chiefly renal.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 7"},{"q":"The liver's “glucose buffer” function means it...","choices":["prevents any glucose from entering the blood","only stores glucose and never releases it","converts all absorbed glucose immediately to fat","stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose between meals"],"answer":3,"exp":"As a glucose buffer, the liver stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose (via glycogenolysis, then gluconeogenesis) between meals, stabilizing blood glucose. The other options describe one-way or nonexistent handling.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 9"},{"q":"The liver requires which vitamin to manufacture prothrombin and several clotting factors?","choices":["Vitamin C","Vitamin K","Vitamin B12","Vitamin A"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver needs vitamin K to make prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X, so liver disease or vitamin K deficiency causes bleeding. Vitamins C, B12, and A serve other roles.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 11"},{"q":"In hepatic bilirubin handling, which step is rate-limiting?","choices":["Uptake of free bilirubin into the hepatocyte","Conjugation with glucuronic acid","Excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile","Binding of bilirubin to albumin in the blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Of the hepatic steps — uptake, conjugation with glucuronic acid, and excretion — excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile is rate-limiting. Albumin binding happens in the blood before uptake, not within the hepatocyte.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 14"},{"q":"The amphipathic nature of bile salts allows them to...","choices":["emulsify fats and carry lipids to the intestinal wall in micelles","chemically digest triglycerides into fatty acids","neutralize stomach acid","absorb water in the colon"],"answer":0,"exp":"Being amphipathic, bile salts act as detergents that emulsify fat and ferry lipids to the mucosa in micelles. Chemical digestion of triglyceride is lipase's role, and bile salts neither neutralize acid nor absorb colonic water.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 20"},{"q":"In the enterohepatic circulation, about 95% of secreted bile salts are...","choices":["excreted in the feces","destroyed by pancreatic enzymes","converted to cholesterol in the gut","reabsorbed (mostly in the ileum) and returned to the liver for reuse"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 95% of secreted bile salts are reabsorbed, chiefly in the ileum, and returned via portal blood to the liver; only the small fraction lost in feces is replaced by new synthesis. They are not mostly excreted, digested, or turned back into cholesterol in the gut.","cite":"Ch. 71, Slide 25"},{"q":"Which macronutrient provides the most energy per gram?","choices":["Carbohydrate (~4 kcal/g)","Fat (~9 kcal/g)","Protein (~4 kcal/g)","All provide equal energy per gram"],"answer":1,"exp":"Fat yields about 9 kcal/g, more than double carbohydrate or protein (~4 kcal/g each). They are not equal per gram.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 4"},{"q":"The body's largest energy reserve is stored as...","choices":["triglyceride in adipose tissue","glycogen in the liver","glucose in the blood","protein in muscle"],"answer":0,"exp":"Adipose triglyceride is by far the largest energy reserve (~120,000 kcal in a lean adult). Liver glycogen and blood glucose hold only small amounts, and although protein is abundant, little is used as an energy store.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 3"},{"q":"A respiratory quotient (RQ) of about 1.0 indicates the body is burning mainly...","choices":["fat","protein","carbohydrate","a mix favoring fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"An RQ (CO₂ produced ÷ O₂ consumed) near 1.0 indicates carbohydrate oxidation; pure fat gives ~0.7 and protein ~0.8, with a mixed diet averaging ~0.8.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 6"},{"q":"Which hypothalamic region serves as the satiety center, whose destruction causes overeating?","choices":["The lateral nuclei","The ventromedial nuclei","The preoptic area","The posterior hypothalamus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ventromedial nuclei form the satiety center; their destruction causes hyperphagia and obesity. The lateral nuclei are the feeding center (lesions cause inanition), and the preoptic/posterior areas handle temperature.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 9"},{"q":"Leptin, released from adipose tissue, acts on the hypothalamus to...","choices":["strongly stimulate hunger","raise blood glucose directly","slow the heart rate","reduce appetite and food intake"],"answer":3,"exp":"Leptin signals the hypothalamus to suppress appetite and raise energy expenditure as fat stores grow. It does not stimulate hunger (that is ghrelin), raise glucose, or slow the heart.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 13"},{"q":"Which hormone, released mainly from the stomach, stimulates feeding?","choices":["Ghrelin","Leptin","CCK","Peptide YY"],"answer":0,"exp":"Ghrelin, released mainly from the stomach's oxyntic cells, stimulates feeding. Leptin, CCK, and peptide YY all inhibit feeding.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 11"},{"q":"Which vitamins are stored in the body to a significant extent?","choices":["Water-soluble vitamins such as C and the B group","No vitamins are stored at all","Fat-soluble vitamins such as A and D","Only vitamin C is stored"],"answer":2,"exp":"Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) can be stored, notably A and D in the liver, whereas water-soluble vitamins (C and most Bs) are not stored significantly and must be supplied regularly.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 17"},{"q":"Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is essential for...","choices":["blood clotting factor synthesis","collagen formation and normal connective tissue","calcium absorption","visual pigment formation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Vitamin C is required for collagen synthesis, so its deficiency (scurvy) causes connective-tissue breakdown and poor wound healing. Clotting-factor synthesis needs vitamin K, calcium handling needs vitamin D, and visual pigments need vitamin A.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 27"},{"q":"Vitamin D is essential for...","choices":["collagen synthesis","oxygen transport","amino acid transamination","calcium and phosphate balance"],"answer":3,"exp":"Vitamin D (activated via skin UV, then the liver and kidney) is essential for calcium and phosphate balance; deficiency causes rickets. Collagen needs vitamin C, oxygen transport needs hemoglobin, and transamination needs vitamin B6.","cite":"Ch. 72, Slide 28"},{"q":"Phosphocreatine in muscle functions as...","choices":["a rapid reserve to regenerate ATP during short bursts of activity","the body's main long-term energy store","a direct source of glucose","a heat-producing hormone"],"answer":0,"exp":"Phosphocreatine acts as an immediate high-energy buffer, rephosphorylating ADP to ATP during brief, intense activity. It is not a long-term store, a glucose source, or a hormone.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 2"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate (BMR) is measured under which conditions?","choices":["Immediately after exercise","During digestion of a large meal","After a 12-hour fast, at rest, in a comfortable temperature, without excitement","In a cold environment while shivering"],"answer":2,"exp":"BMR is measured under standardized resting conditions — a 12-hour fast, physical and mental rest, and a neutral temperature — so exercise, digestion, and shivering do not inflate it. The other conditions all raise metabolic rate.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 8"},{"q":"Which nutrient produces the greatest thermic effect (rise in metabolic rate during digestion)?","choices":["Fat (~4%)","Protein (up to ~30%)","Carbohydrate (~4%)","All are equal"],"answer":1,"exp":"Protein has by far the largest thermic effect of food, raising metabolic rate up to ~30%, versus about 4% for carbohydrate and fat.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 10"},{"q":"Which factor increases the metabolic rate?","choices":["Sleep","Decreased muscle mass","A warm, resting state after fasting","Increased thyroid hormone"],"answer":3,"exp":"Thyroid hormone — like exercise, greater lean mass, sympathetic activity, fever, and cold — raises metabolic rate. Sleep, less muscle, and a warm resting fasted state lower it.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 9"},{"q":"The “oxygen debt” repaid after strenuous exercise is used to...","choices":["convert lactate back to glucose and restore ATP, phosphocreatine, and oxygen stores","digest the next meal","produce more lactate","lower body temperature"],"answer":0,"exp":"The oxygen debt is the extra O₂ consumed afterward to reconvert lactate to glucose, rebuild ATP and phosphocreatine, and reload hemoglobin/myoglobin and lung oxygen. It is not for digestion, making lactate, or cooling.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 6"},{"q":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate by measuring...","choices":["body weight loss","urine volume","oxygen consumption","heart rate alone"],"answer":2,"exp":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate from oxygen consumption (~250 mL/min at rest), since about 95% of energy expenditure comes from reactions of oxygen with foods. Weight loss, urine volume, and heart rate alone are not used.","cite":"Ch. 73, Slide 7"},{"q":"How do core and skin temperature differ?","choices":["Both vary widely with the environment","Core temperature stays nearly constant, while skin temperature varies with the environment","Skin temperature is the most tightly regulated value","Core temperature swings more than skin temperature"],"answer":1,"exp":"Deep (core) temperature is held nearly constant (varying <1°F normally), whereas skin temperature rises and falls with the surroundings. The other options misstate which is regulated.","cite":"Ch. 74, Slide 2"},{"q":"The body's main temperature-control center is located in the...","choices":["cerebellum","medulla's respiratory center","spinal cord alone","hypothalamus (preoptic/anterior area)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The hypothalamus, especially the preoptic/anterior area with its heat- and cold-sensitive neurons, is the body's thermostat. The cerebellum, medullary respiratory center, and spinal cord are not the control center.","cite":"Ch. 74, Slide 5"},{"q":"Which is a mechanism of heat LOSS from the body?","choices":["Evaporation of sweat","Shivering","Vasoconstriction of skin vessels","Piloerection"],"answer":0,"exp":"Evaporation (of sweat and insensible water) loses heat, along with radiation and conduction/convection. Shivering and piloerection generate or conserve heat, and skin vasoconstriction reduces heat loss.","cite":"Ch. 74, Slide 6"},{"q":"Sweat glands are stimulated to secrete by...","choices":["parasympathetic fibers releasing norepinephrine","the somatic motor system","sympathetic cholinergic fibers releasing acetylcholine","circulating insulin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Sweating is driven by the anterior hypothalamus via sympathetic fibers that are cholinergic — they release acetylcholine even though they travel in sympathetic nerves. It is not parasympathetic, somatic, or insulin-mediated.","cite":"Ch. 74, Slide 8"},{"q":"When the body is cold, which response increases heat production?","choices":["Cutaneous vasodilation","Sweating","Inhibition of the sympathetic nervous system","Shivering, which can raise heat production several-fold"],"answer":3,"exp":"In the cold, shivering (plus vasoconstriction, sympathetic excitation, and thyroxine) raises heat production up to 4–5-fold. Vasodilation, sweating, and sympathetic inhibition all promote heat loss, not gain.","cite":"Ch. 74, Slide 14"}]},"metabolism-v2":{"title":"Metabolism (v2)","questions":[{"q":"The liver's contribution to fat digestion is its production of...","choices":["bile, which emulsifies fat to aid its digestion and absorption","hydrochloric acid, which breaks fat into fatty acids","lipase, the main enzyme that digests dietary fat","insulin, which drives fat storage after a meal as a general rule"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The liver continuously produces bile, whose bile salts emulsify dietary fat into small droplets; this greatly increases the surface area for pancreatic lipase to act and helps form the micelles that carry fat products to the absorptive surface.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-17"},{"q":"During fasting, the liver supports other tissues by...","choices":["converting circulating ketones back into stored dietary fat","producing ketone bodies from fatty acids for use as fuel","storing all fatty acids so they cannot be used","releasing oxygen bound to stored hemoglobin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. In fasting, the liver oxidizes fatty acids and converts the surplus acetyl-CoA into ketone bodies, which it exports as an alternative fuel for tissues such as the brain, sparing glucose during prolonged energy shortage.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 15-19; Ch 71, slide 12"},{"q":"The liver disposes of the nitrogen from amino-acid breakdown by...","choices":["converting toxic ammonia into urea for excretion by the kidneys","storing the ammonia in hepatocytes until it is needed","exhaling the ammonia directly through the lungs","converting the ammonia into glucose for energy under these conditions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Deamination of amino acids releases ammonia, which is highly toxic; the liver's urea cycle converts it into urea, a far less toxic compound that the kidneys excrete. Liver failure allows ammonia to accumulate.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 16-17; Ch 71, slide 10"},{"q":"The liver's role as a blood-glucose buffer means it...","choices":["converts all absorbed glucose immediately into triglyceride for storage","secretes insulin whenever plasma glucose rises above the normal range","prevents any glucose from reaching the systemic circulation directly","stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose between meals"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the liver takes up and stores glucose as glycogen postprandially and releases glucose during fasting, buffering blood levels.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9"},{"q":"Glycolysis in the cytoplasm yields, per glucose molecule, a net of...","choices":["2 ATP and lactate, which can occur only with oxygen present","no ATP at all, serving only to store glucose as glycogen","2 ATP and 2 pyruvate, even in the absence of oxygen","36 ATP and carbon dioxide, requiring oxygen throughout"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Glycolysis produces a net of 2 ATP (and 2 NADH) and 2 pyruvate molecules per glucose, and it proceeds without oxygen; this modest yield is why anaerobic tissues rely on it but generate far less ATP than aerobic metabolism.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 10-16"},{"q":"Glucagon and insulin have opposing effects on blood glucose in that glucagon...","choices":["lowers blood glucose while insulin raises it","has no effect on blood glucose, unlike insulin","raises blood glucose while insulin lowers it","and insulin both raise blood glucose together"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Glucagon (from pancreatic alpha cells) raises blood glucose by promoting hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis, whereas insulin (from beta cells) lowers it by promoting cellular uptake and storage; together they keep glucose within a narrow range.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 4, 30; Ch 71, slide 9"},{"q":"The pentose phosphate pathway is important mainly because it produces...","choices":["NADPH for biosynthesis and ribose for nucleic acids","large amounts of ATP for muscle contraction","urea, used to dispose of the body's excess nitrogen","lactate to regenerate NAD+ during exercise"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The pentose phosphate (hexose monophosphate) shunt diverts glucose-6-phosphate to generate NADPH — the reducing power for fatty-acid and other biosynthesis and for antioxidant defense — and ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide and nucleic-acid synthesis, rather than making ATP.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 28-29"},{"q":"During a sudden fight-or-flight response, epinephrine helps supply energy by...","choices":["blocking the release of glucose into the blood","stimulating rapid glycogen breakdown to raise blood glucose","promoting glycogen storage to conserve glucose","converting glucose into structural protein in the body's tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Epinephrine promotes glycogenolysis in the liver (and muscle), quickly liberating glucose to fuel a stress response; it also mobilizes fatty acids, providing a rapid surge of available energy substrates.","cite":"Ch 68, slide 30; Ch 71, slide 9"},{"q":"Fat is the body's most efficient long-term energy store largely because it...","choices":["yields more energy per gram and is stored with little associated water","provides the least energy per gram of any fuel under most normal conditions","is stored with large amounts of water for quick access","can be used only by the liver and not by other tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fat provides about 9 kcal per gram (versus ~4 for carbohydrate or protein) and is stored in a nearly anhydrous form, so it packs far more energy per unit weight than glycogen, which is stored with substantial water — making fat the ideal compact reserve.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 4-5; Ch 73, slide 12"},{"q":"Cells take up cholesterol-rich LDL particles by...","choices":["binding them to LDL receptors and internalizing them","allowing LDL to diffuse freely across the membrane","converting LDL into HDL at the cell surface","digesting LDL with pancreatic lipase in the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Cells express LDL receptors that bind circulating LDL and bring it in by receptor-mediated endocytosis, delivering cholesterol for membrane and steroid synthesis; too few functional receptors leave LDL in the blood and raise plasma cholesterol.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 36"},{"q":"Insulin promotes fat storage in part by...","choices":["blocking lipoprotein lipase so tissues cannot take up fat","inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase so stored triglyceride is not broken down","stimulating ketone body production from the mobilized fatty acids in the liver","activating hormone-sensitive lipase to release fatty acids"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Insulin suppresses hormone-sensitive lipase in adipocytes, preventing breakdown of stored triglyceride, while it also stimulates lipoprotein lipase and fatty-acid synthesis, together favoring net fat storage in the fed state.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 22; Ch 73, slide 15"},{"q":"High-density lipoprotein (HDL) is often called 'good' cholesterol because it...","choices":["delivers cholesterol from the liver to the artery walls","carries excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver for disposal","prevents the liver from making any cholesterol at all in the body's tissues","is the main particle that carries dietary fat from the gut"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. HDL performs reverse cholesterol transport, picking up excess cholesterol from peripheral tissues and returning it to the liver for excretion in bile; this helps clear cholesterol from vessel walls, in contrast to LDL, which delivers cholesterol to tissues.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 6, 36"},{"q":"The urea cycle is the body's solution to the problem that...","choices":["amino acids contain too little nitrogen to be useful","the body cannot break down amino acids at all during this particular process in the tissues","glucose must be converted into protein for storage","ammonia from amino-acid breakdown is toxic and must be converted for safe excretion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Deamination of amino acids releases ammonia, which is toxic even at low levels; the liver's urea cycle converts ammonia into urea, a far safer compound that the kidneys excrete, allowing the body to dispose of nitrogen without ammonia toxicity.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 16-17"},{"q":"The body maintains an amino-acid pool that is best described as...","choices":["a reserve used only for energy and never for building protein","a set of amino acids that cannot be exchanged or replaced","a dynamic supply drawn on for protein synthesis and replenished by turnover and diet","a fixed, permanent store of protein that is never used under most conditions in the body"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Free amino acids form a pool that is continuously used to build new proteins and replenished by dietary intake and by the breakdown (turnover) of existing body proteins; this balance lets the body remodel and repair proteins constantly.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 3-6"},{"q":"Growth hormone promotes a positive nitrogen balance by...","choices":["stimulating amino-acid uptake and protein synthesis in tissues","accelerating the breakdown of tissue protein for fuel","blocking all amino acids from entering the cells in the body's tissues","converting body protein directly into stored fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Growth hormone enhances the transport of amino acids into cells and stimulates protein synthesis while sparing protein from breakdown; the net anabolic effect builds tissue protein, producing a positive nitrogen balance during growth.","cite":"Ch 70, slide 19"},{"q":"Short-term meal termination is promoted by signals such as...","choices":["leptin secreted by fat cells over days to weeks","a steady fall in blood glucose occurring throughout the course of the meal","gastric distension and CCK release acting through vagal afferents","ghrelin rising steadily throughout the meal"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. As the stomach fills, stretch is signaled by vagal afferents, and fat/protein in the duodenum releases CCK; together these short-term signals promote satiety and help end the meal, acting over minutes rather than days.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 11"},{"q":"During prolonged starvation, ketone bodies become important because they...","choices":["are stored in large amounts before starvation begins","provide an alternative fuel for the brain, sparing body protein","are the only fuel the body can produce from glucose","prevent the body from using any fat for energy in the body's tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As fasting continues, the brain adapts to use ketone bodies produced by the liver from fat; this reduces the brain's demand for glucose and therefore lessens the breakdown of body protein for gluconeogenesis, prolonging survival.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 17-19; Ch 69, slides 15-19"},{"q":"Destruction of the lateral hypothalamic nuclei tends to cause...","choices":["excessive eating, since this is the satiety center","essentially no change in appetite or feeding behavior whatsoever","an inability to regulate body temperature only","reduced eating and weight loss, since this is the feeding center"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The lateral hypothalamus acts as the feeding (hunger) center; lesions here remove the drive to eat, producing reduced intake and weight loss (inanition). This complements the ventromedial nuclei, which serve as the satiety center.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 9"},{"q":"In a sedentary person, the largest component of daily energy expenditure is...","choices":["the energy cost of occasional vigorous physical exercise sessions","shivering to maintain body temperature","the basal metabolic rate needed to sustain resting functions","the thermic effect of digesting food"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. In most sedentary people the basal metabolic rate — the energy to run vital resting processes — accounts for the majority (roughly 50–70%) of daily expenditure, far exceeding the smaller contributions of activity and the thermic effect of food.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 2; Ch 73, slide 10"},{"q":"Leptin is best described as a signal that...","choices":["reports the size of fat stores and reduces appetite over the long term","directly digests dietary fat within the lumen of the small intestine","triggers hunger within minutes of the stomach emptying","is released mainly by the stomach in order to help initiate each separate meal"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Leptin is secreted by adipocytes in proportion to fat mass; higher stores mean more leptin, which acts on the hypothalamus to reduce appetite and increase expenditure, providing long-term regulation of body weight.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 13-15"},{"q":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate by measuring...","choices":["the carbon dioxide dissolved in the arterial blood under these conditions","the total nitrogen excreted in the urine over a day","the heat radiated directly from the whole body surface over time","oxygen consumption, since most energy release depends on oxygen use"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Because about 95% of the body's energy release comes from reactions consuming oxygen, oxygen consumption is a reliable proxy for metabolic rate; indirect calorimetry measures O2 use rather than heat directly.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 7"},{"q":"Sympathetic activation can raise metabolic rate in part by...","choices":["blocking thyroid hormone from acting on tissues","lowering the core body temperature in order to reduce metabolic demand","stimulating heat production, including thermogenesis in brown fat","shutting down all cellular metabolism to save energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Sympathetic activity increases cellular metabolism and can drive thermogenesis, notably in brown adipose tissue, raising heat production and metabolic rate; this contributes to the metabolic response to cold and stress.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 9"},{"q":"Larger individuals tend to have a higher total basal metabolic rate partly because...","choices":["a bigger body always has a much lower body temperature","surface area has no relationship to heat loss or metabolism","larger bodies have proportionally less active tissue during this process","a greater body mass and surface area require more energy to maintain"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Basal metabolic rate scales with body size: more metabolically active tissue and a larger surface area (over which heat is lost) mean more total energy is needed to maintain the resting body, which is why BMR is often expressed relative to body size.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 8-11"},{"q":"One reason men tend to have a higher basal metabolic rate than women is...","choices":["a smaller total body surface area losing less heat","a higher ratio of metabolically active lean muscle to fat","the absence of any thermic effect from their food","a somewhat lower body temperature that tends to speed up reactions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Lean muscle is more metabolically active than fat, and men on average carry a higher muscle-to-fat ratio (linked to testosterone), which raises their resting energy expenditure relative to women.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 9, 11"},{"q":"Physical activity raises total energy expenditure primarily because...","choices":["the basal metabolic rate itself falls during exercise","body temperature drops, forcing more heat production during this process in the tissues","digestion of food stops so all energy goes to movement","contracting muscles greatly increase their consumption of energy substrates"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Exercise is the most variable component of energy expenditure: working muscles sharply increase their use of glucose and fatty acids to fuel contraction, raising oxygen consumption and total metabolic rate well above the resting level.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 10-12"},{"q":"On exposure to cold, the posterior hypothalamus conserves and generates heat by...","choices":["driving cutaneous vasoconstriction and shivering to raise heat production","lowering the overall metabolic rate in order to reduce the body's oxygen demand","inhibiting thyroxine release to slow chemical thermogenesis","stimulating sweating and cutaneous vasodilation to trap and hold body warmth"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: cold responses include sympathetic cutaneous vasoconstriction and shivering, which conserve and generate heat.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 14-15"},{"q":"Heat loss by conduction and convection differ in that convection...","choices":["requires evaporation of sweat to remove any heat","carries heat away by the movement of air or fluid over the skin","emits heat as infrared waves without any medium in this scenario","transfers heat only to objects touching the skin directly"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Conduction transfers heat to objects or air in direct contact, while convection removes heat as moving air or water carries the warmed layer away and replaces it with cooler medium; a breeze increases convective loss.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6-9"},{"q":"With repeated exposure to a hot environment, acclimatization improves heat tolerance largely by...","choices":["shutting down cutaneous blood flow to the skin as a general rule","reducing the sweating rate to conserve body water","lowering the hypothalamic set point permanently","increasing the sweating rate and conserving salt in the sweat"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Heat acclimatization enhances the capacity to sweat earlier and more profusely (improving evaporative cooling) and, via aldosterone, conserves sodium in the sweat, protecting the body's salt balance during heavy sweating.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 8-10"},{"q":"Which is a genuine mechanism of body heat loss?","choices":["Vasoconstriction, the narrowing of skin vessels","Radiation, the emission of infrared heat waves to cooler surroundings","Shivering, the production of heat by muscle contraction","Piloerection, the raising of the body hairs to shed heat to the surroundings"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Radiation transfers heat as infrared waves from the warm body to cooler surrounding objects and is a major route of heat loss at rest; the other options listed are heat-conserving or heat-generating responses, not means of losing heat.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6, 13-14"},{"q":"When surrounding air is cooler than the skin, the body's largest avenue of heat loss at rest is...","choices":["warming of inhaled air within the respiratory passages","evaporation of sweat driven by sympathetic cholinergic fibers","radiation of infrared heat waves to cooler nearby objects","conduction of heat directly into the solid objects being touched"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: at rest in cool surroundings, radiation of infrared waves is the dominant route of heat loss.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 6"}]},"metabolism-v3":{"title":"Metabolism (v3)","questions":[{"q":"The liver protects the body from many ingested and internally produced chemicals by...","choices":["converting toxins into oxygen for the tissues to use","metabolizing drugs and toxins into forms that can be excreted","secreting toxins unchanged directly into the bloodstream","storing all toxins permanently within its own cells in this scenario"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Hepatocytes carry out biotransformation, chemically modifying drugs, hormones, and toxins (often making them more water-soluble) so they can be excreted in bile or urine; this detoxifying role is a central hepatic function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 8-10"},{"q":"Failure of the liver to clear ammonia is dangerous because ammonia...","choices":["is the main metabolic fuel used by the beating cardiac muscle","is required in large amounts for red cell production","is harmless and simply excreted unchanged by the lungs","is toxic to the nervous system and can impair brain function"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Ammonia produced by amino-acid deamination and gut bacteria is neurotoxic; the liver normally converts it to urea for excretion. When hepatic function fails, ammonia accumulates and can cause hepatic encephalopathy — confusion, altered consciousness, and impaired brain function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 10; Ch 70, slide 16"},{"q":"The liver serves as a major storage site for...","choices":["oxygen bound to hemoglobin for release during exercise","digestive enzymes awaiting release into the duodenum","glycogen, iron, and several fat-soluble vitamins","mature lymphocytes ready to fight infection"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The liver stores glycogen (a glucose reserve), iron (as ferritin), and fat-soluble vitamins such as A and D, acting as a central metabolic warehouse the body can draw on between meals.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 2, 8"},{"q":"A hallmark synthetic function of the liver is production of...","choices":["plasma proteins such as albumin and most clotting factors","digestive amylase secreted into the small intestine","erythropoietin that stimulates red cell production","insulin and glucagon that closely regulate blood glucose"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The liver synthesizes the majority of plasma proteins, including albumin (the main determinant of colloid osmotic pressure) and most coagulation factors, which is why liver disease produces both edema and bleeding tendencies.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 2, 11"},{"q":"The brain relies heavily on a steady glucose supply because it...","choices":["normally uses glucose as its main fuel and stores very little of its own","stores large amounts of glycogen for its own use during this process in the tissues","produces its own glucose independently of the blood","can only use fatty acids delivered from adipose tissue"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Under normal conditions the brain depends on a continuous supply of blood glucose as its primary fuel and holds almost no energy reserve of its own, which is why hypoglycemia rapidly impairs brain function (though ketones can partly substitute during prolonged fasting).","cite":"Ch 68, slides 25-27; Ch 73, slide 12"},{"q":"Epinephrine and glucagon raise blood glucose partly through phosphorylation, which...","choices":["inactivates phosphorylase so stored glycogen is protected from breakdown","activates glycogen phosphorylase while inactivating glycogen synthase","activates both glycogen phosphorylase and glycogen synthase together","activates glycogen synthase to build glycogen from incoming glucose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: phosphorylation activates phosphorylase (breakdown) and inactivates synthase (storage), favoring glycogenolysis.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 11-12"},{"q":"Phosphorylating glucose to glucose-6-phosphate as it enters a cell serves to...","choices":["trap glucose inside the cell by preventing it from diffusing back out","release energy that the cell immediately uses for contraction","signal the pancreas to stop secreting insulin into the bloodstream right away","convert glucose into fat for long-term storage"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Adding a charged phosphate group keeps glucose from crossing the membrane back out, effectively trapping it inside so it is committed to intracellular metabolism (glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, or the pentose pathway).","cite":"Ch 68, slides 6-7"},{"q":"Between meals, the liver keeps blood glucose from falling by...","choices":["absorbing glucose taken from resting muscle in order to store it centrally","converting glucose into glycogen for storage","breaking down stored glycogen and releasing glucose (glycogenolysis)","halting all glucose release to conserve it"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. In the postabsorptive state the liver depolymerizes its glycogen (glycogenolysis) and, as that store runs low, makes new glucose (gluconeogenesis), releasing glucose into the blood to prevent hypoglycemia. This is its glucose-buffer function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9"},{"q":"Chylomicrons and VLDL both carry triglyceride, but they differ in that...","choices":["chylomicrons are made in the liver, while VLDL comes from the intestine under these conditions","both particles are made only within adipose tissue purely for local fat storage","chylomicrons carry cholesterol back to the liver, while VLDL carries dietary fat","chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the gut, while VLDL carries fat made by the liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Chylomicrons are assembled in the intestine to transport exogenous (dietary) fat, whereas VLDL is made by the liver to export endogenous triglyceride (much of it synthesized from carbohydrate); both deliver fatty acids to tissues via lipoprotein lipase.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 6; GI Physiology, slide 139"},{"q":"Very-low-density lipoprotein (VLDL) is produced by the liver mainly to...","choices":["deliver dissolved oxygen to the working tissues during periods of heavy exercise","export triglycerides, largely made from carbohydrate, to peripheral tissues","return excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver","carry dietary fat absorbed directly from the intestine"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The liver packages triglycerides (much of it synthesized from excess carbohydrate) into VLDL and exports them to peripheral tissues, where lipoprotein lipase releases fatty acids for use or storage.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 6"},{"q":"During prolonged fasting, the liver produces ketone bodies because...","choices":["high fatty-acid oxidation generates acetyl-CoA in excess of TCA cycle capacity","rising insulin stimulates the liver to store its excess fat as ketone bodies","abundant circulating glucose drives the conversion of pyruvate directly into ketones","amino acids are unavailable, forcing protein to be turned into ketones"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: heavy beta-oxidation floods the liver with acetyl-CoA beyond what the citric acid cycle can handle, so it is diverted to ketones.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 15-19"},{"q":"Cortisol influences protein metabolism by...","choices":["stimulating net protein synthesis in all tissues","preventing any amino acids at all from entering the blood during stress or fasting states","blocking the liver from making any new glucose during stress or fasting states","promoting breakdown of tissue protein to supply amino acids for gluconeogenesis"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cortisol (a glucocorticoid) drives catabolism of extrahepatic tissue protein, raising plasma amino acids that the liver uses for gluconeogenesis; this helps maintain blood glucose during stress and fasting.","cite":"Ch 70, slide 19; Ch 68, slide 30"},{"q":"Before an amino acid's carbon skeleton can be used for energy, its amino group is removed by...","choices":["the electron transport chain during ATP synthesis under these conditions","deamination or transamination, freeing the skeleton for metabolism","glycolysis, which strips the nitrogen as it makes ATP","beta-oxidation, which removes nitrogen two atoms at a time"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Removing the amino group by deamination (releasing ammonia) or transamination (transferring it to a keto acid) frees the carbon skeleton to enter energy pathways as a glucogenic or ketogenic intermediate, while the nitrogen is routed to urea.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Amino acids that are degraded to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are termed ketogenic because they...","choices":["can be converted into glucose through gluconeogenesis","release ammonia that is directly excreted by the lungs","give rise to ketone bodies rather than to new glucose","are used only to build new proteins, never for fuel"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Ketogenic amino acids feed into acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA, which can form ketone bodies but cannot be used to make net glucose (since acetyl-CoA cannot be converted back to pyruvate for gluconeogenesis).","cite":"Ch 70, slide 18"},{"q":"Which statement about amino-acid metabolism is correct?","choices":["Transamination permanently destroys the carbon skeleton of the amino acid","Transamination builds nonessential amino acids; deamination frees ammonia for urea","Both reactions occur only in muscle tissue and never take place within the liver","Deamination adds an amino group onto a carbon skeleton, a step needing vitamin B6"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: transamination (needing vitamin B6) forms nonessential amino acids, while deamination liberates ammonia that becomes urea.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 7-16"},{"q":"Leptin and ghrelin have opposing effects on appetite because...","choices":["leptin drives hunger during fasting, while ghrelin signals satiety after meals","both are released from adipose tissue but act on different brain regions","leptin from the stomach stimulates appetite, while ghrelin suppresses it","leptin from fat reduces appetite, while ghrelin from the stomach stimulates it"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: leptin from adipose tissue signals satiety and reduces intake, while ghrelin from the stomach stimulates hunger.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 11-14"},{"q":"During early starvation, before fat stores are heavily used, the body first relies on...","choices":["stored glycogen, which is exhausted within roughly a day","ketone bodies, which are the very first fuel mobilized","body protein, which is broken down before any glycogen","dietary intake, which continues to supply energy"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The body first draws on liver (and muscle) glycogen for glucose, but these stores are small and are largely depleted within about 24 hours; the body then shifts increasingly to fat oxidation and, later, ketone production and protein breakdown.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 17-19"},{"q":"Ghrelin, secreted largely by the stomach, influences feeding by...","choices":["digesting fats directly within the small intestine","suppressing hunger over the long term as fat stores grow","stimulating hunger and rising before meals to prompt eating","ending each meal by signaling fullness to the brain"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Ghrelin is often called the 'hunger hormone': its levels rise before meals and fall after eating, and it acts on the hypothalamus to stimulate appetite, in contrast to satiety signals like leptin and CCK that reduce intake.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 11-14"},{"q":"Per gram, the energy yields of the macronutrients are approximately...","choices":["9 kcal for carbohydrate, 9 for protein, and 4 for fat","4 kcal for carbohydrate, 4 for protein, and 9 for fat","4 kcal for fat, with carbohydrate and protein at 9 kcal","equal energy from all three, at about 4 kcal per gram"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Carbohydrate and protein each provide about 4 kcal per gram, while fat provides about 9 kcal per gram; fat's much higher energy density is why it is the body's most compact form of energy storage.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 4-5"},{"q":"Gram for gram, fat provides more than twice the energy of carbohydrate or protein because it...","choices":["requires no oxygen to release its stored chemical energy","is absorbed far more completely from the gut than either carbohydrate or protein","yields about 9 kcal/g versus roughly 4 kcal/g for carbohydrate and protein","is stored together with large amounts of water that add to its measured energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: fat provides ~9 kcal/g, over double the ~4 kcal/g of carbohydrate or protein.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 4"},{"q":"Thyroid hormone influences metabolic rate by...","choices":["lowering metabolic rate to conserve energy during fasting","raising the resting metabolic rate of most body tissues","acting only on skeletal muscle during exercise","having no measurable effect on basal metabolism"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Thyroid hormone increases the metabolic activity of nearly all tissues, raising basal metabolic rate and heat production; this is why thyroid status is a major determinant of BMR.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 9"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate represents...","choices":["the minimal energy needed to sustain the body while at rest and fasting","the energy used only for digesting and absorbing a meal","total daily energy output including all physical activity","the peak energy expenditure that is achievable during heavy physical exercise"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: basal metabolic rate is the minimal energy to maintain the body at rest, measured fasting and thermoneutral.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 8, 10"},{"q":"The thermic effect of food refers to...","choices":["the heat lost through sweating during a meal","the surplus calories that are stored away as fat after overeating","the energy used only during physical activity","the extra energy expended to digest, absorb, and process a meal"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The thermic effect of food is the rise in energy expenditure required to digest, absorb, and metabolize nutrients; it is modest for carbohydrate and fat but substantial for protein (which can raise metabolic rate up to about 30%).","cite":"Ch 73, slide 10"},{"q":"A respiratory quotient near 1.0 shortly after a carbohydrate meal reflects that...","choices":["protein breakdown dominates the fuel mix, fixing the ratio at exactly 0.8","carbohydrate oxidation produces CO2 and consumes O2 in roughly equal amounts","fat is the main fuel, releasing little CO2 relative to the O2 used","no gas exchange is occurring at all because metabolism has temporarily paused"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: burning carbohydrate gives an RQ near 1.0 because CO2 produced and O2 consumed are about equal.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 5-6"},{"q":"When a fever finally 'breaks,' the person often flushes and sweats because the hypothalamic set point has...","choices":["returned to normal, so the now-high body temperature is shed by sweating and vasodilation","risen further, causing the body to generate even more heat","been abolished, leaving temperature completely unregulated","dropped far below normal, triggering intense shivering during this particular process in the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. When pyrogen levels fall, the set point drops back to normal; the body temperature is now above the set point, so the hypothalamus activates heat-loss responses — vasodilation and sweating — to bring temperature down, producing the flush and sweat of the crisis.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 18-20"},{"q":"Sweating cools the body only when...","choices":["it is reabsorbed back into the sweat glands during this particular process","the surrounding air is already fully saturated with water","it remains as liquid droplets on the skin surface","the sweat actually evaporates, absorbing heat from the skin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cooling comes from the evaporation of sweat, which absorbs heat (the latent heat of vaporization) from the skin; sweat that merely drips off without evaporating removes little heat, which is why humid conditions blunt sweat's cooling effect.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6-9"},{"q":"Shivering raises body temperature by...","choices":["producing heat through rapid, involuntary muscle contractions","increasing evaporative water loss from the airways and skin","lowering the hypothalamic set point toward the cold","shunting warm blood from the core to the skin surface"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Shivering is driven by the hypothalamic motor center for shivering; rapid involuntary muscle contractions generate substantial metabolic heat (potentially several-fold above resting), warming the body in the cold.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 15"},{"q":"To conserve heat in the cold, sympathetic signals cause skin blood vessels to...","choices":["increase sweating to trap a warm surface layer","leak plasma into tissues to insulate the body","constrict, reducing heat transfer from the core to the surface","dilate widely, bringing much more warm blood to the skin surface"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Sympathetic activation produces cutaneous vasoconstriction, cutting blood flow to the skin so that less core heat is carried to the surface where it could be lost; the skin radiator is effectively turned down.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 11-14"},{"q":"The hypothalamus acts as the body's thermostat, with the responses to cold coordinated so that the body...","choices":["raises its set point to induce a protective fever","loses heat through vasodilation and sweating during this process in the tissues","conserves and generates heat through vasoconstriction and shivering","stops all metabolic heat production to save energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. When cold is sensed, the hypothalamus triggers heat-conserving and heat-generating responses: cutaneous vasoconstriction to reduce loss and shivering (plus increased metabolism) to produce heat, defending core temperature.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 4, 11-15"},{"q":"Sweat reaching the skin surface is normally hypotonic to plasma because...","choices":["potassium fully replaces sodium before the sweat reaches the surface","aldosterone actively adds salt to the sweat as it forms","the sweat glands secrete pure water that lacks any electrolytes","sodium and chloride are reabsorbed from the duct, especially at low flow"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: as primary secretion moves through the duct, Na+ and Cl- are reabsorbed, leaving hypotonic sweat, most markedly at low flow rates.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 8"}]},"pulmonary":{"title":"Pulmonary Physiology","questions":[{"q":"During quiet (resting) breathing, how is expiration accomplished?","choices":["By active contraction of the diaphragm","Passively, through elastic recoil of the lungs and chest wall","By contraction of the abdominal muscles","By contraction of the external intercostals"],"answer":1,"exp":"In quiet breathing the inspiratory muscles simply relax and the stretched lung recoils, expelling air passively — no active expiratory effort is needed. Diaphragm and external-intercostal contraction produce inspiration, and the abdominals are recruited only for forced expiration.","cite":"Slide 18"},{"q":"What happens to pleural (intrapleural) pressure during inspiration?","choices":["It becomes positive","It stays constant throughout the breath","It becomes more negative (about –5 to –8 cm H₂O)","It rises toward zero"],"answer":2,"exp":"As the chest expands, intrapleural pressure falls further below atmospheric (roughly –5 to –8 cm H₂O), pulling the lungs open. It does not turn positive or move toward zero during inspiration — those occur in expiration — and it clearly changes across the breath.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"How does forced expiration differ from quiet expiration?","choices":["It uses active muscle effort, and pleural pressure can become positive","It relies solely on relaxation of the diaphragm","It makes pleural pressure more negative","It requires surfactant to push air out"],"answer":0,"exp":"Forced expiration recruits expiratory muscles (e.g., abdominals), which can drive intrapleural pressure positive to expel air rapidly. Passive relaxation and a more-negative pleural pressure describe quiet breathing and inspiration, and surfactant lowers surface tension rather than expelling air.","cite":"Slide 18"},{"q":"Lung compliance is best defined as...","choices":["The pressure needed to overcome airway resistance","The tendency of the lung to recoil after stretch","The rate of airflow through the bronchioles","The change in lung volume per unit change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Compliance measures how much lung volume changes for a given change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP) — its distensibility. Recoil tendency is elasticity (the opposite idea), while airway resistance and airflow rate describe how easily air moves, not how easily the lung stretches.","cite":"Slide 14"},{"q":"Something described as “highly elastic,” like lung tissue, will...","choices":["Stretch easily and stay stretched","Resist being stretched and tend to recoil to its original shape","Have very high compliance","Lose its shape permanently after stretching"],"answer":1,"exp":"Elasticity is the tendency to return to the original shape after stretch, so a highly elastic structure resists deformation and recoils. Stretching easily or staying deformed describes low elasticity / high compliance — the opposite property.","cite":"Slide 19"},{"q":"Which TWO factors are chiefly responsible for the lung's elastic recoil?","choices":["Airway resistance and dead space","Blood flow and lymphatic drainage","Elastic tissue (collagen/elastin) and alveolar surface tension","Surfactant and mucus production"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lung's recoil comes from its elastic fibers (collagen and elastin) plus the surface tension of the alveolar lining fluid. Resistance, dead space, blood flow, and mucus are unrelated to recoil, and surfactant actually reduces the surface-tension component.","cite":"Slide 19"},{"q":"How does surface tension at the air–water interface affect the alveoli?","choices":["It draws alveolar walls together and favors collapse","It holds alveoli open by pushing their walls apart","It has no effect on alveolar stability","It increases lung compliance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Surface tension pulls the water-lined alveolar walls inward, tending to collapse the alveolus and lowering compliance. It does not push walls apart or leave stability unaffected — counteracting it is exactly why surfactant is needed.","cite":"Slide 19"},{"q":"Because airflow varies with r⁴, a small decrease in airway radius will...","choices":["Barely change resistance","Decrease resistance","Only matter in the alveoli, not the airways","Sharply increase resistance, since radius is raised to the fourth power"],"answer":3,"exp":"With resistance proportional to 1/r⁴, even slight narrowing greatly increases resistance to airflow. It does not decrease or barely change resistance, and the effect is greatest in the airways (the upper airways carry the major resistance), not the alveoli.","cite":"Slide 16"},{"q":"How does a decrease in lung volume affect airway resistance?","choices":["It increases resistance","It decreases resistance","It eliminates resistance","It has no effect on resistance"],"answer":0,"exp":"As lung volume falls, the airways are less stretched open and narrow, so airway resistance rises. Resistance is never eliminated, and it clearly depends on lung volume, so “no effect” is incorrect.","cite":"Slide 16"},{"q":"What is the difference between a lung “volume” and a lung “capacity”?","choices":["A capacity is always smaller than a single volume","They are two words for the same thing","A capacity is the sum of two or more lung volumes","A volume can only be measured during exercise"],"answer":2,"exp":"A lung capacity is defined as the sum of two or more lung volumes (e.g., vital capacity = IRV + TV + ERV). Capacities are therefore larger than individual volumes, are not synonymous with them, and are measured at rest.","cite":"Slide 27"},{"q":"Vital capacity is the sum of which volumes?","choices":["Tidal volume + residual volume","Inspiratory reserve + tidal volume + expiratory reserve","Expiratory reserve + residual volume","Inspiratory reserve + residual volume"],"answer":1,"exp":"Vital capacity — the maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration — equals IRV + TV + ERV. Any combination that includes residual volume is wrong, because residual volume cannot be exhaled and is not part of vital capacity.","cite":"Slide 29"},{"q":"Functional residual capacity (FRC) represents the...","choices":["Maximum air inspired after a normal expiration","Maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration","Air moved in one normal breath","Air remaining in the lungs after a normal (resting) expiration"],"answer":3,"exp":"FRC (= ERV + RV) is the volume left in the lungs after a normal, resting expiration. The maximum inspired after a normal expiration is inspiratory capacity, the maximum expired after maximal inspiration is vital capacity, and one normal breath is tidal volume.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Residual volume is the air that...","choices":["Enters the lungs during a normal breath","Can be forcibly inspired beyond a normal breath","Remains in the lungs even after a maximal expiration","Is exhaled during quiet breathing"],"answer":2,"exp":"Residual volume is the air that cannot be exhaled — it remains even after a maximal expiration, keeping alveoli from collapsing. Normal-breath air is tidal volume, extra inspired air is inspiratory reserve, and quiet-breathing exhaled air is tidal volume.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Which lung value CANNOT be measured directly by simple spirometry?","choices":["Tidal volume","Inspiratory reserve volume","Vital capacity","Residual volume"],"answer":3,"exp":"Spirometry measures only air that moves in and out, so it cannot capture residual volume (air that never leaves the lungs) — nor the capacities containing it (FRC, TLC). Tidal volume, inspiratory reserve, and vital capacity are all directly measurable.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Inspiratory capacity is the maximum air that can be inspired following...","choices":["A normal (resting) expiration","A maximal expiration","A maximal inspiration","A forced exhalation to residual volume"],"answer":0,"exp":"Inspiratory capacity (= TV + IRV) is the most air inhaled starting from the end of a normal, resting expiration. Starting from a maximal expiration or residual volume would approach total lung capacity, and you cannot inhale further after a maximal inspiration.","cite":"Slide 28"},{"q":"What is the primary function of pulmonary surfactant?","choices":["To increase surface tension so alveoli stay small","To reduce alveolar surface tension and prevent collapse","To thicken the respiratory membrane for protection","To trap inhaled particles like mucus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Surfactant lowers the surface tension of the alveolar lining fluid, preventing collapse and increasing compliance. It does not raise surface tension, thicken the membrane, or trap particles — those would impair breathing.","cite":"Slide 20"},{"q":"By Laplace's law (P = 2T/r), at equal surface tension a SMALLER alveolus...","choices":["Requires a smaller pressure to keep from collapsing","Is inherently more stable than a large one","Requires a larger pressure to keep from collapsing","Has no collapse tendency at all"],"answer":2,"exp":"With P = 2T/r, a smaller radius demands a higher pressure to stay open, so small alveoli are inherently less stable — which is why surfactant is essential. The other options reverse or ignore this radius relationship.","cite":"Slide 22"},{"q":"Without surfactant, what would happen to a small alveolus connected to a larger one?","choices":["The small alveolus would tend to collapse and empty into the larger one","The large alveolus would empty into the small one","Both would remain perfectly stable","Surface tension would disappear"],"answer":0,"exp":"Without surfactant, the higher collapse pressure of the small alveolus (Laplace) drives its air into the larger, lower-pressure alveolus — atelectasis. The reverse flow, perfect stability, and disappearance of surface tension are all incorrect.","cite":"Slide 23"},{"q":"How does surfactant help stabilize alveoli of different sizes?","choices":["By increasing surface tension in large alveoli","By enlarging all alveoli equally","By blocking airflow to small alveoli","By reducing surface tension, which lessens the collapse tendency of small alveoli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Surfactant lowers surface tension — most effectively in small alveoli — reducing their collapse tendency and equalizing stability across alveolar sizes. It does not raise tension, resize alveoli uniformly, or block airflow.","cite":"Slide 23"},{"q":"In what direction does a gas diffuse across the respiratory membrane?","choices":["From lower to higher partial pressure","Down its partial pressure gradient, from higher to lower","Always from blood to alveolus","Independent of any pressure gradient"],"answer":1,"exp":"A gas diffuses passively from higher to lower partial pressure. It cannot move up a gradient without energy, and its direction depends on that gradient (O₂ into blood, CO₂ out) — so “always blood to alveolus” and “independent of gradient” are wrong.","cite":"Slide 51"},{"q":"According to Fick's law, gas diffusion increases when...","choices":["The membrane is thicker","The surface area is smaller","The partial pressure gradient and surface area are larger","The solubility of the gas is lower"],"answer":2,"exp":"Fick's law makes diffusion proportional to the pressure gradient, surface area, and solubility, and inversely proportional to membrane thickness. So a bigger gradient and area speed diffusion, while a thicker membrane, smaller area, or lower solubility slow it.","cite":"Slide 62"},{"q":"Although CO₂ and O₂ have similar molecular weights, CO₂ diffuses much faster mainly because...","choices":["CO₂ is about 20 times more soluble than O₂","CO₂ has a much larger partial pressure gradient","CO₂ is a much smaller molecule","O₂ cannot cross the membrane at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"CO₂'s roughly 20-fold greater solubility lets it diffuse much faster despite a smaller partial pressure gradient. Its gradient is actually smaller, its molecular weight is similar (not smaller), and O₂ obviously does cross the membrane.","cite":"Slide 61"},{"q":"How does increasing alveolar ventilation affect alveolar PCO₂?","choices":["It raises alveolar PCO₂","It has no effect on alveolar PCO₂","It raises PCO₂ only during exercise","It lowers alveolar PCO₂"],"answer":3,"exp":"Greater alveolar ventilation washes out CO₂ faster than metabolism produces it, so alveolar (and arterial) PCO₂ falls. Ventilation and PCO₂ are inversely related, so raising PCO₂ or “no effect” is incorrect.","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Alveolar air is replaced only slowly (a fraction with each breath). What is the physiological benefit?","choices":["It lets CO₂ accumulate to high levels","It keeps alveolar gas concentrations stable, preventing sudden swings","It speeds oxygen loss from the blood","It prevents any gas exchange from occurring"],"answer":1,"exp":"Because only about one-seventh of alveolar air is exchanged per breath, alveolar O₂ and CO₂ stay relatively constant, buffering blood gases against breath-to-breath swings. It does not let CO₂ build up, speed O₂ loss, or halt exchange.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Why is the respiratory (alveolar) membrane extremely thin (~0.2 µm)?","choices":["To increase surface tension","To slow gas diffusion for regulation","To minimize diffusion distance and speed gas exchange","To store surfactant"],"answer":2,"exp":"At ~0.2 µm thick, the membrane keeps the diffusion distance tiny, allowing rapid gas exchange (Fick's law favors short distances). It is not there to raise surface tension, slow diffusion, or store surfactant.","cite":"Slide 60"},{"q":"The lungs contain roughly 300 million alveoli. How does this aid gas exchange?","choices":["It provides an enormous surface area for diffusion","It reduces the total surface area","It increases the diffusion distance","It decreases compliance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hundreds of millions of alveoli create a vast total surface area, which — per Fick's law — greatly increases gas exchange. This increases (not reduces) surface area and does not lengthen the diffusion distance or lower compliance.","cite":"Slide 57"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly lists layers a gas crosses in the respiratory membrane, from air to blood?","choices":["Capillary endothelium → alveolar epithelium → surfactant","Interstitial space → surfactant → capillary endothelium","Alveolar epithelium → surfactant → red blood cell","Surfactant/fluid → alveolar epithelium → basement membranes → capillary endothelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"Moving from air to blood, a gas crosses the surfactant/fluid layer, the alveolar epithelium, the fused basement membranes and interstitium, and finally the capillary endothelium. The other sequences scramble this air-to-blood order.","cite":"Slide 60"},{"q":"If the respiratory membrane becomes thickened, gas exchange is impaired because...","choices":["Surface area increases too much","The diffusion distance increases, slowing gas transfer","The partial pressure gradient reverses","The solubility of the gases changes"],"answer":1,"exp":"A thicker membrane lengthens the path a gas must diffuse, and by Fick's law greater distance slows transfer (e.g., in edema or fibrosis). Thickening does not add useful surface area, reverse the gradient, or change gas solubility.","cite":"Slide 62"},{"q":"Respiratory regulation is organized as which three-part system?","choices":["Sensors, a central controller, and effector muscles","Arteries, veins, and capillaries","Alveoli, bronchioles, and pleura","Surfactant, mucus, and cilia"],"answer":0,"exp":"Respiratory control is a feedback loop: sensors (chemoreceptors) gather data, the central controller (brainstem) integrates it, and effectors (respiratory muscles) act. The other trios list vascular, structural, or airway-lining parts, not the control loop.","cite":"Slide 88"},{"q":"The central chemoreceptors are located in the brainstem and respond mainly to...","choices":["Oxygen levels in arterial blood","Blood pressure changes","CO₂ and H⁺","Lung stretch"],"answer":2,"exp":"The central chemoreceptors sense CO₂ and H⁺ (via H⁺ generated in the CSF). Oxygen sensing is the job of the peripheral chemoreceptors, while blood pressure and lung stretch are detected by other receptors.","cite":"Slide 96"},{"q":"The peripheral chemoreceptors of the carotid and aortic bodies are especially important for sensing...","choices":["Lung compliance","Airway resistance","Pleural pressure","Low arterial oxygen (PO₂)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The carotid and aortic bodies are the main sensors of low arterial PO₂ (they also respond to CO₂/H⁺). Compliance, resistance, and pleural pressure are mechanical properties, not what these chemoreceptors detect.","cite":"Slide 97"},{"q":"Increased arterial PCO₂ stimulates the central chemoreceptors indirectly by...","choices":["Binding directly to oxygen sensors","Generating H⁺ after CO₂ crosses into the brain/CSF","Reducing blood flow to the medulla","Constricting the airways"],"answer":1,"exp":"CO₂ crosses into the brain/CSF, forms carbonic acid, and releases H⁺; the central chemoreceptors actually respond to that H⁺. They are not oxygen sensors, and CO₂ does not drive breathing by cutting medullary blood flow or narrowing airways.","cite":"Slide 91"},{"q":"Under normal resting conditions, the most important minute-to-minute stimulus driving ventilation is...","choices":["Arterial PCO₂ (and the resulting H⁺)","A small fall in arterial PO₂","Blood glucose level","Body temperature"],"answer":0,"exp":"Minute-to-minute ventilation is governed most tightly by arterial PCO₂ and the H⁺ it generates. Modest drops in PO₂ have little effect until PO₂ falls substantially, and glucose and temperature are not the primary respiratory stimulus.","cite":"Slide 92"},{"q":"When arterial PO₂ falls substantially (PCO₂ held constant), ventilation...","choices":["Decreases","Stays exactly the same","Increases, driven by the peripheral chemoreceptors","Stops entirely"],"answer":2,"exp":"A substantial fall in PO₂ stimulates the carotid and aortic bodies, increasing ventilation (the hypoxic drive). Ventilation does not fall, stay flat, or stop when oxygen drops.","cite":"Slide 99"},{"q":"About how much oxygen can each gram of hemoglobin bind?","choices":["0.3 ml O₂","20 ml O₂","100 ml O₂","1.34 ml O₂"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 ml of O₂. The 0.3 ml figure is dissolved O₂ per 100 ml of blood, and ~20 ml is the total O₂-carrying capacity per 100 ml — not the per-gram value.","cite":"Slide 77"},{"q":"Why does hemoglobin matter so much for oxygen transport?","choices":["Hemoglobin dissolves oxygen directly into plasma","Dissolved O₂ alone (~0.3 ml/100 ml) is far too little; Hb raises capacity to ~20 ml/100 ml","Dissolved oxygen carries most of the O₂ in blood","Hemoglobin only carries CO₂, not O₂"],"answer":1,"exp":"Physically dissolved O₂ is tiny (~0.3 ml/100 ml); binding to hemoglobin lifts capacity to about 20 ml/100 ml, so Hb carries the vast majority of oxygen. It does not dissolve O₂ into plasma, and it carries O₂ as well as some CO₂.","cite":"Slide 77"},{"q":"“Percent saturation” of hemoglobin refers to...","choices":["The absolute amount of O₂ in ml per 100 ml blood","The driving pressure for O₂ diffusion","The fraction of hemoglobin binding sites occupied by O₂","The number of red cells per microliter"],"answer":2,"exp":"Percent saturation is the proportion of hemoglobin binding sites carrying O₂ (a unitless fraction). The absolute amount is “content,” the driving pressure is partial pressure, and red-cell count is a separate measure.","cite":"Slide 76"},{"q":"The flat upper plateau of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve means that...","choices":["Hemoglobin stays highly saturated across a wide range of higher PO₂ values","Small drops in PO₂ at high levels cause large drops in saturation","Hemoglobin cannot bind oxygen in the lungs","Saturation and PO₂ are unrelated"],"answer":0,"exp":"On the flat plateau, hemoglobin stays nearly fully saturated even as PO₂ varies over a wide high range — protecting O₂ loading if alveolar PO₂ dips. That is the opposite of large saturation swings, and saturation clearly depends on PO₂.","cite":"Slide 80"},{"q":"Which change shifts the O₂-hemoglobin dissociation curve to the RIGHT, favoring O₂ unloading?","choices":["Decreased temperature","Increased pH (alkalosis)","Decreased 2,3-BPG","Increased CO₂ and H⁺ (lower pH)"],"answer":3,"exp":"A right shift (lower O₂ affinity, better unloading) results from increased CO₂, increased H⁺/lower pH, higher temperature, and increased 2,3-BPG — the conditions of active tissue. Lower temperature, higher pH, and less 2,3-BPG shift the curve left.","cite":"Slide 81"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide is dangerous to oxygen transport because it...","choices":["Increases the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood","Binds hemoglobin far more tightly than O₂, blocking O₂ binding","Cannot bind hemoglobin at all","Only affects dissolved oxygen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Carbon monoxide binds hemoglobin with far greater affinity than oxygen, occupying binding sites and preventing O₂ transport. It reduces (not increases) usable capacity, definitely binds hemoglobin, and acts on hemoglobin rather than dissolved O₂.","cite":"Slide 82"},{"q":"In what form is MOST CO₂ carried in the blood?","choices":["As dissolved CO₂","Bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin","As bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻)","As carbonic acid crystals"],"answer":2,"exp":"About 70% of CO₂ travels as bicarbonate formed in red cells by carbonic anhydrase. Roughly 23% rides on hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin and ~7% is dissolved; CO₂ is not carried as solid carbonic-acid crystals.","cite":"Slide 86"},{"q":"Which enzyme in red cells speeds the conversion of CO₂ and water to carbonic acid?","choices":["Carbonic anhydrase","Carboxypeptidase","Lactate dehydrogenase","ATP synthase"],"answer":0,"exp":"Carbonic anhydrase in red cells rapidly converts CO₂ + H₂O to carbonic acid, which dissociates to H⁺ and bicarbonate. The other enzymes act on peptides, lactate, and ATP production respectively, not on CO₂ hydration.","cite":"Slide 86"},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell in exchange for chloride entering, this exchange is called the...","choices":["Bohr shift","Haldane shift","Sodium shift","Chloride (Hamburger) shift"],"answer":3,"exp":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell, chloride moves in to preserve electrical neutrality — the chloride (Hamburger) shift. The Bohr and Haldane effects describe how pH/O₂ change gas affinities, and there is no “sodium shift” here.","cite":"Slide 86"},{"q":"About 23% of CO₂ is transported...","choices":["Dissolved in plasma","Bound to hemoglobin (carbaminohemoglobin)","As free carbonic acid","Inside white blood cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Roughly 23% of CO₂ is carried bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin. Only ~7% is dissolved, most is bicarbonate, and CO₂ is not stored as free carbonic acid or within white cells.","cite":"Slide 86"},{"q":"The Haldane effect describes how...","choices":["Low pH increases O₂ unloading","CO₂ increases hemoglobin's O₂ affinity","Binding of O₂ to hemoglobin in the lungs promotes CO₂ release","Chloride enters the red cell at the tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"The Haldane effect: when hemoglobin binds O₂ in the lungs, it releases CO₂ more readily, aiding CO₂ elimination. Low pH increasing O₂ unloading is the Bohr effect, and the other options misstate CO₂'s effect on O₂ affinity and the chloride shift.","cite":"Slide 85"},{"q":"How does rising blood CO₂ lower blood pH?","choices":["CO₂ combines with water to form carbonic acid, which releases H⁺","CO₂ directly binds and removes bicarbonate","CO₂ destroys hemoglobin's buffering ability","CO₂ has no relationship to pH"],"answer":0,"exp":"Dissolved CO₂ forms carbonic acid, which dissociates into H⁺ and bicarbonate, so rising CO₂ raises H⁺ and lowers pH. CO₂ does not remove bicarbonate directly or destroy hemoglobin buffering, and it is tightly linked to pH.","cite":"Slide 86"},{"q":"If a person hyperventilates and “blows off” CO₂, blood pH will...","choices":["Fall (become more acidic)","Stay exactly the same","Change only if oxygen also falls","Rise (become more alkaline)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Blowing off CO₂ shifts the CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ equilibrium to the left, lowering H⁺ and raising pH (respiratory alkalosis). Losing CO₂ cannot acidify the blood or leave pH unchanged, and the effect does not depend on oxygen.","cite":"Slide 92"},{"q":"The respiratory system helps regulate blood pH primarily by...","choices":["Producing bicarbonate in the alveoli","Adjusting how much CO₂ is exhaled","Filtering H⁺ out of the blood","Changing hemoglobin concentration"],"answer":1,"exp":"By changing ventilation, the lungs control how much CO₂ is exhaled, shifting the carbonic-acid equilibrium and adjusting pH within minutes. The alveoli don't make bicarbonate or filter H⁺ (a renal function), and hemoglobin level isn't the mechanism.","cite":"Slide 91"},{"q":"Tissue PO₂ is determined by the balance between...","choices":["Surfactant production and surface tension","Alveolar ventilation and dead space","The rate of blood flow (O₂ delivery) and the rate of O₂ consumption","Pleural pressure and compliance"],"answer":2,"exp":"Tissue PO₂ reflects the balance between O₂ delivered by blood flow and O₂ used by the cells — more flow raises it, more consumption lowers it. Surfactant, ventilation/dead space, and pleural mechanics govern the lung, not tissue PO₂.","cite":"Slide 72"},{"q":"During exercise, more oxygen is released to active muscle largely because...","choices":["Tissue PO₂ falls and local acidity/CO₂ promote O₂ unloading","Hemoglobin loses its ability to bind oxygen","Blood flow to muscle stops","Surfactant increases O₂ release"],"answer":0,"exp":"In exercising muscle, PO₂ drops and the higher CO₂/H⁺ and temperature right-shift the curve (Bohr effect), so hemoglobin releases far more O₂. Hemoglobin doesn't lose function, muscle blood flow rises rather than stops, and surfactant has no role in tissue O₂ release.","cite":"Slide 80"}]},"pulmonary-v2":{"title":"Pulmonary Physiology (v2)","questions":[{"q":"During heavy exercise, forced expiration becomes active and is driven largely by...","choices":["the release of surfactant that forces air out under these conditions","contraction of the diaphragm to push air outward","contraction of the abdominal and internal intercostal muscles","relaxation of the diaphragm alone, as in quiet breathing"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Whereas quiet expiration is passive, forced expiration recruits the abdominal muscles (which push the diaphragm upward) and the internal intercostals (which pull the ribs down), actively decreasing thoracic volume to expel air rapidly during exertion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"External respiration and internal respiration refer, respectively, to gas exchange...","choices":["only within the airways, and only within the bloodstream","between alveoli and blood, and between blood and the body's tissues","between the nose and the trachea, and within the alveoli","between blood and tissues, and between alveoli and blood as a general rule"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. External respiration is the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide between the alveoli and the pulmonary blood, while internal respiration is the exchange between the systemic blood and the metabolizing tissues; both rely on diffusion down partial-pressure gradients.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 3-6, 71-74"},{"q":"The principal muscle responsible for quiet inspiration is the...","choices":["diaphragm, whose contraction increases the vertical dimension of the thorax","sternocleidomastoid muscle, which is said to be the primary driver at rest","internal intercostal group, which actively pulls the ribs downward","abdominal wall, which pushes the diaphragm upward to draw in air"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. During quiet breathing the diaphragm does most of the work; its contraction flattens the dome and lengthens the thoracic cavity, lowering intrapleural and alveolar pressure so air flows in.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"If air enters the pleural space and abolishes the negative pressure, the lung tends to...","choices":["recoil and collapse because nothing opposes its elastic pull","remain unchanged since pleural pressure is irrelevant","stiffen noticeably and become nearly impossible to compress","expand further because recoil is now unopposed"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The lung's inherent elastic recoil pulls it inward; the negative pleural pressure normally counteracts this. If air enters the pleural space (pneumothorax) and abolishes that negative pressure, the recoil is unopposed and the lung collapses.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19, 50"},{"q":"Surface tension at the air-water interface lining the alveoli tends to...","choices":["increase lung compliance by making expansion easier","draw the alveolar walls together and favor collapse","have no measurable effect on alveolar stability at any size","hold the alveoli open by pushing their walls apart"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: surface tension pulls the liquid-lined walls inward, favoring alveolar collapse unless surfactant opposes it.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19-20"},{"q":"By the law of Laplace, without surfactant a small alveolus would tend to...","choices":["collapse and empty into a connected larger alveolus","become completely rigid and unable to change size","expand indefinitely at the expense of larger alveoli","generate less collapsing pressure than a large alveolus"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Laplace's law says that for a given surface tension, smaller alveoli generate higher collapsing pressure; without surfactant, a small alveolus would empty into a larger connected one. Surfactant lowers tension more in small alveoli, stabilizing them.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Pulmonary surfactant is produced by...","choices":["type I alveolar cells, forming the main gas-exchange surface","goblet cells lining the large conducting airways under these conditions","type II alveolar cells and lowers surface tension in the alveoli","alveolar macrophages that also clear inhaled debris"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Type II alveolar (pneumocyte) cells secrete surfactant, a phospholipid-rich material that lowers alveolar surface tension, stabilizes alveoli of different sizes, and reduces the work of breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Surfactant is chiefly composed of...","choices":["phospholipid, which interposes between water molecules to reduce surface tension","cartilage, which stiffens the alveolar wall for support","hemoglobin, which binds oxygen within the alveolus under most conditions in the body","mucus, which traps inhaled particles in the alveoli"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Surfactant is largely phospholipid (notably dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine); its molecules insert among the water molecules lining the alveoli, weakening their cohesive attraction and thereby lowering surface tension.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Alveolar ventilation is always less than total minute ventilation because...","choices":["the alveoli are able to exchange gas only during the expiratory phase","part of each breath fills conducting airways that do no gas exchange","oxygen is consumed before air can reach the alveoli","dead-space air is the only air that reaches the blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Each tidal breath must first fill the anatomic dead space (~150 mL of conducting airway), and that air never reaches the alveoli for exchange, so the ventilation available for gas exchange (alveolar ventilation) is less than the total minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"Residual volume cannot be measured by ordinary spirometry because it is the air that...","choices":["is exhaled with every ordinary quiet breath during this process","moves through the conducting airways each minute","can be forcibly inhaled beyond a normal breath","remains in the lungs and can never be voluntarily exhaled"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Residual volume is the air left in the lungs even after a maximal expiration; since it can never be exhaled, spirometry (which measures moved air) cannot capture it, and indirect methods such as gas dilution are required.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 30-31"},{"q":"Alveolar ventilation is a better measure of effective breathing than minute ventilation because it...","choices":["accounts for dead space, reflecting only air that reaches the alveoli","ignores the tidal volume entirely in its calculation as a general rule","measures only the residual volume left after expiration","counts all air moved, including that filling the airways"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Alveolar ventilation subtracts the dead-space volume (air in conducting airways that never reaches alveoli) from each breath, so it reflects only the air available for gas exchange; this is why slow, deep breathing can be more effective than rapid, shallow breathing at the same minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"Oxygen moves from alveolar air into pulmonary capillary blood because...","choices":["the blood actively pumps oxygen out of the alveolus as it is usually described here","carbon dioxide drags oxygen along with it into the blood","alveolar oxygen partial pressure is higher than that in the arriving blood","alveolar oxygen pressure is lower than that in the blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Gas exchange is driven by partial-pressure gradients: alveolar PO2 (~100 mmHg) exceeds the PO2 of the venous blood entering the pulmonary capillaries (~40 mmHg), so oxygen diffuses down its gradient into the blood until equilibration.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 61-66"},{"q":"In the upright lung, ventilation and perfusion are not perfectly matched; at the apex compared with the base there is...","choices":["exactly equal ventilation and perfusion throughout as a general rule","no ventilation and no perfusion reaching that region","relatively more perfusion than ventilation than the base","relatively more ventilation than perfusion (a higher V/Q ratio)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Gravity makes both ventilation and perfusion greater at the base, but perfusion increases more steeply, so the apex has a relatively higher ventilation-to-perfusion ratio, while the base has a relatively lower one. This regional variation is normal in the upright lung.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 64-66"},{"q":"The respiratory membrane is well suited to gas exchange because it is...","choices":["covered by thick mucus that traps the diffusing gases","extremely thin, so gases have only a very short distance to diffuse","quite thick, which slows diffusion but filters the air","lined with cartilage that supports rapid exchange in the body's tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The respiratory membrane is only about 0.2 to 0.6 micrometers thick, giving oxygen and carbon dioxide a very short diffusion path; combined with its enormous surface area, this thinness makes gas exchange rapid and efficient.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"The anatomic dead space refers to...","choices":["the alveoli that receive air but no blood flow","the total volume of air moved in one minute","the residual air that can never be exhaled during this process","the volume of conducting airways where no gas exchange occurs"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Anatomic dead space is the air filling the conducting zone — nose, trachea, and bronchi — which has no alveoli and therefore participates in no gas exchange; only the air reaching the alveoli contributes to gas exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"The peripheral chemoreceptors' oxygen response becomes an important drive to breathe mainly when...","choices":["blood pressure rises at the carotid sinus","carbon dioxide is the only gas that has changed","arterial oxygen falls to notably low levels","arterial oxygen is completely normal"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The carotid and aortic bodies respond to low arterial PO2, but this hypoxic drive becomes significant only when PO2 falls well below normal (roughly under 60 mmHg); under normal conditions, CO2 is the dominant stimulus and oxygen contributes little.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95, 99"},{"q":"The carotid and aortic bodies are especially important for detecting...","choices":["a rise in brain interstitial carbon dioxide concentration","a fall in the arterial partial pressure of oxygen","the pH of the cerebrospinal fluid around the medulla","stretch of the airway smooth muscle during inspiration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies are the main sensors of low arterial oxygen.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95, 97"},{"q":"The Hering-Breuer inflation reflex helps protect the lungs by...","choices":["inhibiting further inspiration when stretch receptors sense large inflation","forcing a deeper breath whenever the lungs are stretched","contracting the diaphragm independently of the brainstem","sensing arterial oxygen and driving ventilation during this particular process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Stretch receptors in the airway walls, when strongly stimulated by large lung inflation, send signals that inhibit the inspiratory center; this reflex helps prevent overinflation of the lungs, mainly during deep breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 89-90"},{"q":"The Bohr effect describes how increased CO2 and H+ in active tissue...","choices":["convert oxygen into bicarbonate for transport in the body under most conditions","prevent hemoglobin from binding any oxygen in the lungs","shift the curve leftward, making hemoglobin hold oxygen tightly","shift the curve rightward, helping hemoglobin release more oxygen"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The Bohr effect is the rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve caused by higher CO2, higher H+ (lower pH), and higher temperature in metabolically active tissue; the reduced affinity promotes oxygen unloading exactly where it is needed.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 81"},{"q":"The reason hemoglobin is essential for oxygen transport is that, without it,...","choices":["carbon dioxide would be unable to leave the tissues","the small amount of oxygen dissolved in plasma could not meet tissue demands","oxygen could not diffuse across the respiratory membrane","the lungs would be unable to ventilate at all during this process in the tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Oxygen is poorly soluble, so plasma alone carries only a tiny fraction of the body's needs; hemoglobin increases the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity many-fold by binding oxygen, which is why anemia (low hemoglobin) so seriously reduces oxygen delivery.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"The P50 of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve is the partial pressure at which hemoglobin is...","choices":["binding carbon dioxide rather than oxygen as it typically occurs here","fully saturated with the maximum amount of oxygen","50% saturated, serving as a measure of its affinity for oxygen","completely stripped of all of its bound oxygen"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. P50 is the PO2 at which hemoglobin is half saturated; a higher P50 means lower affinity (the curve is shifted right, favoring unloading), and a lower P50 means higher affinity (left shift), so P50 is a convenient index of oxygen affinity.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 78-81"},{"q":"During exercise, working muscle extracts more oxygen from each unit of blood because...","choices":["low tissue PO2 and a rightward curve shift favor greater unloading","hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen rises in active tissue","oxygen is actively pumped back out into the blood from the muscle","blood flow to the muscle stops during contraction under these conditions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Exercising muscle has a very low PO2 and generates heat, CO2, and acid that shift the oxygen-hemoglobin curve rightward; together these steepen the gradient and lower hemoglobin's affinity, so much more oxygen is unloaded per unit of blood than at rest.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-81"},{"q":"A rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve in exercising muscle...","choices":["occurs only in the lungs to speed the loading of oxygen","prevents any oxygen from being released to the surrounding tissues","increases hemoglobin's oxygen affinity so it holds oxygen more tightly","promotes oxygen unloading where tissue CO2, acid, and temperature are high"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: a rightward shift lowers affinity, enhancing oxygen release in active tissues with high CO2, low pH, and heat.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 81"},{"q":"Factors such as increased temperature, CO2, and acidity in metabolically active tissue tend to...","choices":["increase hemoglobin's affinity so it retains its oxygen","block hemoglobin from picking up any oxygen at all in the lungs","reduce oxygen unloading, sparing oxygen for later use","promote oxygen unloading from hemoglobin where it is most needed"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. These conditions mark actively metabolizing tissue and shift the oxygen-hemoglobin curve rightward, lowering affinity so hemoglobin releases more oxygen precisely at the tissues that are working hardest.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-81"},{"q":"Carbon dioxide is transported in blood in three forms; the largest fraction travels as...","choices":["dissolved CO2 gas in the plasma","carbaminohemoglobin bound to globin","bicarbonate ions dissolved in the plasma","carbonic acid contained within the red blood cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The majority of CO2 (about 70%) is carried as bicarbonate formed after carbonic anhydrase hydrates CO2 in red cells; smaller fractions travel bound to hemoglobin (carbamino, ~23%) or dissolved as free CO2 (~7%).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-86"},{"q":"Carbonic anhydrase speeds CO2 transport because it...","choices":["rapidly converts CO2 and water into carbonic acid inside red cells","binds the CO2 molecule directly onto the heme iron of hemoglobin","pumps bicarbonate out of the plasma into the lungs","destroys excess CO2 before it can be transported during this particular process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase in red cells greatly accelerates the hydration of CO2 to carbonic acid, which then dissociates to bicarbonate and H+; this lets the blood carry the large majority of its CO2 as bicarbonate and is central to CO2 transport and acid-base handling.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"A portion of CO2 is carried bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin; this binding occurs at...","choices":["the plasma proteins outside the red cell","the globin portion, not the heme iron where oxygen binds","the same heme iron site used by oxygen","the carbonic anhydrase enzyme molecule itself within the cell"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Carbamino CO2 attaches to amino groups on the globin chains of hemoglobin, a different site from the heme iron that binds oxygen; this is why hemoglobin can carry oxygen and some CO2 simultaneously.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-86"},{"q":"The bicarbonate buffer system links respiration to acid-base balance because...","choices":["the buffer works only in the kidney and not in the blood under most conditions in the body","hemoglobin converts bicarbonate into oxygen for transport","bicarbonate is exhaled directly by the lungs to remove acid","CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid, which dissociates to H+ and bicarbonate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. CO2 + H2O reversibly forms carbonic acid, which dissociates into H+ and bicarbonate. Because the lungs control CO2, changing ventilation shifts this equilibrium and thus blood pH — the mechanistic link between breathing and acid-base status.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"Acidosis and alkalosis are defined by blood pH such that acidosis is a...","choices":["shift toward a higher-than-normal pH (fewer hydrogen ions)","shift toward a lower-than-normal pH (more hydrogen ions)","state in which blood pH cannot change at all","condition affecting only oxygen levels, not pH"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Acidosis refers to a process lowering blood pH below the normal range (an increase in hydrogen ion concentration), while alkalosis refers to a process raising pH above normal; each can arise from respiratory (CO2) or metabolic causes.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"A disturbance is called a respiratory (rather than metabolic) acid-base problem when it originates from...","choices":["an accumulation of lactic acid during exercise","the loss of stomach acid through vomiting","a change in CO2 caused by altered ventilation","a change in bicarbonate produced by the kidneys"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Respiratory acid-base disturbances arise from changes in CO2 due to hypo- or hyperventilation (CO2 retention lowers pH; excess CO2 removal raises it), whereas metabolic disturbances arise from changes in bicarbonate or fixed acids independent of CO2.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"}]},"pulmonary-v3":{"title":"Pulmonary Physiology (v3)","questions":[{"q":"Throughout the normal breathing cycle, intrapleural pressure remains...","choices":["higher than alveolar pressure at all times under most conditions throughout the body","exactly equal to atmospheric pressure during inspiration","positive during quiet expiration to force air out","more negative than alveolar pressure, keeping the lung against the chest wall"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Intrapleural pressure stays below (more negative than) alveolar pressure across the cycle; this transpulmonary pressure difference holds the lung expanded against the chest wall and prevents it from collapsing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 16-19"},{"q":"The diaphragm receives its motor innervation from the...","choices":["phrenic nerve, arising from cervical spinal segments","sympathetic chain, acting through spinal ganglia","vagus nerve, which also controls the heart rate","intercostal nerves that supply only the rib muscles"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The diaphragm is driven by the phrenic nerve, which originates from cervical spinal segments (about C3–C5); this is why high cervical spinal cord injury can paralyze the diaphragm and abolish spontaneous breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-13"},{"q":"Airway radius has a powerful effect on airflow because resistance is...","choices":["independent of radius and set only by the air's viscosity","directly proportional to the radius of the airway","inversely proportional to the fourth power of the radius","proportional to the square of the airway's length"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: by Poiseuille's relationship, resistance varies with 1/r^4, so small radius changes greatly affect flow.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 16"},{"q":"Emphysema and pulmonary fibrosis affect compliance in opposite ways: emphysema tends to...","choices":["increase compliance by destroying elastic tissue, while fibrosis stiffens the lung","have no measurable effect on lung compliance at all as it is usually described here","stiffen the lung, while fibrosis makes it easier to inflate","make the lung easier to inflate and to recoil normally"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Emphysema destroys alveolar walls and elastic fibers, so the lung becomes floppy and easier to inflate (higher compliance) but recoils poorly; fibrosis lays down stiff tissue, lowering compliance so the lung is harder to inflate. They alter lung mechanics in opposite directions.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19-21"},{"q":"Intrapleural pressure is normally negative (sub-atmospheric), which...","choices":["has no effect on whether the lungs stay inflated","keeps the lungs expanded against their tendency to recoil inward","forces the lungs to collapse against the chest wall","actively pushes the air outward during quiet resting inspiration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The negative intrapleural pressure results from the lung's inward recoil opposing the chest wall's outward pull; this sub-atmospheric pressure holds the lungs expanded and coupled to the chest wall throughout the breathing cycle.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 14, 17-19"},{"q":"Insufficient surfactant, as in a premature newborn, leads to breathing difficulty because...","choices":["gas exchange speeds up beyond what the blood can handle","surface tension in the alveoli drops too low under most conditions throughout the body","alveoli tend to collapse, so much greater effort is needed to reinflate them","the alveoli become too easy to inflate and overexpand"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Without adequate surfactant, alveolar surface tension is high; alveoli collapse at the end of expiration, and reopening them requires large pressures, greatly increasing the work of breathing — the basis of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Surfactant stabilizes small alveoli by...","choices":["increasing the radius of every alveolus throughout the lung","lowering surface tension so small alveoli resist collapsing into larger ones","raising surface tension uniformly across the alveoli of every possible size","thickening the alveolar fluid lining so as to slow the diffusion of gases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: surfactant reduces surface tension more in small alveoli, preventing them from emptying into larger ones (Laplace).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"By lowering surface tension, surfactant...","choices":["raises the surface tension evenly across all of the alveoli regardless of size","reduces the effort needed to inflate the lungs and prevents alveolar collapse","thickens the fluid layer to slow gas exchange","increases the work of breathing to strengthen the lungs"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Surfactant lowers alveolar surface tension, which raises compliance (making the lungs easier to inflate) and stabilizes alveoli of different sizes so small ones do not empty into larger ones; without it, the work of breathing rises and alveoli collapse (as in neonatal respiratory distress).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Inspiratory reserve volume is the air that...","choices":["remains in the lungs after a maximal expiration","is exhaled during a single quiet resting breath","can still be exhaled beyond a normal quiet resting expiration","can still be inhaled beyond a normal quiet inspiration"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Inspiratory reserve volume is the additional air that can be forcibly inhaled after a normal tidal inspiration; it is the inspiratory 'reserve' available above the resting breath.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 27-29"},{"q":"Vital capacity is best described as...","choices":["the air still remaining in the lungs after a maximal forced expiration","the maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration (IRV + VT + ERV)","the air remaining after a normal quiet expiration","the volume of air that is moved during a single normal quiet resting breath"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: vital capacity is the greatest volume that can be expelled after a maximal inspiration, the sum of IRV, tidal volume, and ERV.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 29"},{"q":"Anatomic dead space reduces the efficiency of ventilation because...","choices":["it holds air that has already fully equilibrated with pulmonary blood","air in the conducting airways never reaches alveoli for gas exchange","it is the region where most oxygen uptake actually takes place","it represents alveoli that are ventilated but not perfused by blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: the ~150 mL in conducting airways does not participate in gas exchange, so alveolar ventilation is less than minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"In a healthy lung at rest, blood in the pulmonary capillary equilibrates with alveolar oxygen...","choices":["well before it leaves the capillary, giving a large safety margin","only at the very last instant before leaving the capillary","never fully, so arterial blood is always desaturated","only during vigorous exercise, and essentially never while at rest"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. At rest, oxygen equilibrates between alveolus and capillary blood in about a third of the transit time, so equilibration is complete long before the blood exits the capillary; this reserve is the safety factor that is eroded in disease or reduced with very fast transit during exercise.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 67-69"},{"q":"Ventilation-perfusion matching improves gas exchange by...","choices":["sending essentially all blood flow to the very apex of the upright lung","ensuring blood always flows to alveoli that receive no air during this particular process","keeping ventilation constant regardless of local blood flow","aligning airflow and blood flow so alveoli are neither wasted nor underused"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Efficient exchange requires that alveolar ventilation and capillary perfusion be matched; local mechanisms (such as hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction) direct blood toward well-ventilated alveoli, minimizing both wasted ventilation and wasted perfusion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 43, 64-65"},{"q":"Fluid accumulating in the interstitial space of the respiratory membrane would...","choices":["increase the diffusion distance and slow gas exchange","have no effect on the rate of gas diffusion","convert the membrane into an active transport surface","shorten the diffusion distance and speed exchange"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. By thickening the barrier that gases must cross, interstitial or alveolar fluid (as in pulmonary edema) lengthens the diffusion distance; per Fick's law, this reduces the rate of gas exchange and can impair oxygenation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 60-62"},{"q":"Gas exchange across the respiratory membrane is efficient largely because the total alveolar surface is...","choices":["very small but compensated by thickness","large but separated from blood by cartilage","thin but limited to a few large air sacs","very large while the membrane is extremely thin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The lungs contain hundreds of millions of alveoli providing an enormous total surface area, and the respiratory membrane is only about 0.2 micrometers thick; large area and short diffusion distance together maximize the rate of gas exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"Central chemoreceptors in the brainstem adjust ventilation mainly in response to...","choices":["changes in CO2 and H+ within the surrounding brain fluid","stretch signals arriving from receptors located in the lung","changes in arterial oxygen sensed directly within the medulla","blood pressure changes detected at the carotid sinus baroreceptors"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: central chemoreceptors respond primarily to CO2 and H+ in brain extracellular fluid, the strongest minute-to-minute drive.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91, 96"},{"q":"The pontine (pneumotaxic) center influences breathing mainly by...","choices":["contracting the diaphragm directly through the phrenic nerve","generating the fundamental breathing rhythm on its own","sensing arterial oxygen at the carotid bodies under most conditions in the body","limiting the duration of inspiration and helping set the breathing rate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The pneumotaxic center in the pons sends signals that switch off inspiration, thereby limiting inspiratory time; a stronger signal shortens inspiration and quickens the rate, so this center helps fine-tune the rhythm generated by the medulla.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 88-90"},{"q":"Peripheral chemoreceptors also respond to blood pH, so a fall in pH (acidosis) tends to...","choices":["have no effect on breathing, since only CO2 matters during this process","stimulate ventilation, helping to remove CO2 and correct the pH","cause the kidneys to immediately exhale the excess acid","suppress ventilation, allowing CO2 to accumulate further"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The carotid and aortic bodies sense a fall in pH and increase their signaling to the respiratory center; the resulting rise in ventilation blows off CO2, which lowers carbonic acid and helps raise the pH back toward normal — a respiratory compensation for acidosis.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95-99"},{"q":"Nearly all of the oxygen in blood is carried...","choices":["as bicarbonate formed from the reaction of oxygen and water","dissolved in the plasma, with hemoglobin contributing very little","chemically combined with plasma proteins other than hemoglobin","bound to hemoglobin, with only a small fraction dissolved in plasma"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the great majority of oxygen is carried on hemoglobin; only a small amount is physically dissolved.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide impairs oxygen delivery because it...","choices":["binds hemoglobin far more tightly than oxygen, blocking the O2 sites","destroys the heme iron so that hemoglobin can never re-form","dissolves oxygen out of the plasma into the expired air","stimulates excessive oxygen release before blood reaches the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: carbon monoxide binds hemoglobin with much greater affinity than oxygen, occupying binding sites and reducing O2 carriage.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 82"},{"q":"A leftward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve, indicating higher affinity, occurs with...","choices":["heavy exercise that raises the tissue temperature","decreased temperature, decreased CO2, and the presence of fetal hemoglobin","a rise in CO2 and hydrogen ion concentration as it is usually described here","increased temperature and increased acidity in the tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Lower temperature, lower CO2/acidity, decreased 2,3-BPG, fetal hemoglobin, and carbon monoxide all shift the curve leftward, raising oxygen affinity so hemoglobin binds oxygen more tightly and releases it less readily at the tissues.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-82"},{"q":"Which correctly describes CO2 movement?","choices":["CO2 is carried in the blood without ever actually leaving it at all","CO2 diffuses from blood into tissues at both sites","CO2 diffuses from tissues into blood, then from blood into alveoli","CO2 moves from alveoli into blood in the lungs"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metabolizing tissues have a high PCO2, so CO2 diffuses into the blood; in the lungs, alveolar PCO2 is lower than that of venous blood, so CO2 diffuses from blood into the alveoli to be exhaled. Each step follows the partial-pressure gradient.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 73-74, 86-87"},{"q":"Comparing alveolar gas with the systemic venous blood arriving at the lungs, the alveoli have...","choices":["a lower oxygen and a higher carbon dioxide partial pressure than that blood","no oxygen at all, so none can diffuse into the blood","a higher oxygen and a lower carbon dioxide partial pressure than that blood","identical oxygen and carbon dioxide pressures to that blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Alveolar air has higher PO2 and lower PCO2 than the venous blood entering the pulmonary capillaries; these opposing gradients drive oxygen into the blood and carbon dioxide out of it, so blood leaves the lungs oxygenated and CO2-depleted.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 63-66, 71-74"},{"q":"Oxygen moves from capillary blood into a metabolizing cell because...","choices":["the cell's PO2 is lower than that of the arriving blood","blood PO2 is always lower than the cell's PO2","the cell actively pumps oxygen across its membrane","carbon dioxide actively pushes the oxygen into the cell"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Actively metabolizing cells consume oxygen, keeping intracellular PO2 low; oxygen therefore diffuses down its partial-pressure gradient from the higher-PO2 capillary blood into the cell, with no active transport required.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 71-73"},{"q":"The Haldane effect describes how...","choices":["carbon monoxide competitively displaces carbon dioxide out of the plasma","bicarbonate physically prevents hemoglobin from carrying oxygen","oxygenating hemoglobin in the lungs promotes the release of carbon dioxide","high carbon dioxide levels force hemoglobin to bind still more oxygen molecules"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: the Haldane effect is that binding oxygen reduces hemoglobin's affinity for CO2, aiding CO2 release in the lungs.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 85"},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell in exchange for chloride (the chloride shift), the purpose is to...","choices":["prevent bicarbonate from ever entering the plasma","bind oxygen more tightly to the hemoglobin inside the red cell","generate ATP for the red cell's own energy needs","maintain electrical balance as CO2 is converted for transport"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase generates bicarbonate inside the red cell; as HCO3- diffuses out into plasma, chloride moves in to preserve electrical neutrality (the chloride shift), allowing large amounts of CO2 to be carried as plasma bicarbonate.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 86-87"},{"q":"The chloride shift accompanies bicarbonate handling because, as bicarbonate leaves the red cell,...","choices":["sodium leaves the cell to replace the lost charge","chloride enters the cell to keep it electrically balanced","the cell manufactures new hemoglobin to compensate","oxygen is forced out of the cell in exchange in most cases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase generates bicarbonate inside the red cell; as bicarbonate diffuses out into plasma, chloride moves in (the chloride, or Hamburger, shift) to preserve electrical neutrality, allowing large amounts of CO2 to be carried as plasma bicarbonate.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"The tight link between CO2 and pH means that increasing ventilation...","choices":["adds CO2 and thereby raises hydrogen ion concentration","has no relationship to blood acid-base status","removes CO2 and thereby reduces hydrogen ion concentration","changes oxygen levels but never affects pH"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Because CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid (and thus H+), increasing ventilation removes CO2, lowers carbonic acid, and reduces hydrogen ion concentration, raising pH; this is the respiratory system's rapid lever on acid-base balance.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92"},{"q":"Voluntary hyperventilation, by removing extra CO2, tends to...","choices":["raise blood pH, producing a respiratory alkalosis","leave blood pH completely unchanged","raise CO2 levels in the blood in the body under most conditions","lower blood pH, producing a respiratory acidosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Hyperventilation blows off CO2, lowering carbonic acid and hydrogen ion concentration, so blood pH rises — a respiratory alkalosis. This illustrates how ventilation directly influences acid-base balance through CO2.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"Central chemoreceptors respond to blood CO2 indirectly because CO2...","choices":["is sensed only after it has been converted into oxygen in the brain","cannot cross into the brain and must be sensed peripherally","crosses into brain fluid and forms H+, which the receptors detect","binds directly to the chemoreceptor without any change"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. CO2 readily crosses the blood-brain barrier into the brain extracellular fluid, where carbonic anhydrase converts it to carbonic acid and then H+; the central chemoreceptors actually sense that H+, giving CO2 its powerful (if indirect) effect on ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91, 96-98"}]},"physio-master":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam","questions":[{"q":"Lung compliance is best defined as...","choices":["The pressure needed to overcome airway resistance","The tendency of the lung to recoil after stretch","The change in lung volume per unit change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP)","The rate of airflow through the bronchioles"],"answer":2,"exp":"Compliance measures how much lung volume changes for a given change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP) — its distensibility. Recoil tendency is elasticity (the opposite idea), while airway resistance and airflow rate describe how easily air moves, not how easily the lung stretches.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 14"},{"q":"Peristalsis (the propulsive movement of the gut) fundamentally requires...","choices":["The sympathetic nervous system to initiate the contraction","The myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus, and can occur without the autonomic nervous system","The sphincter of Oddi to open first","Complete removal of the enteric nervous system"],"answer":1,"exp":"Peristalsis is coordinated by the enteric (myenteric) plexus and proceeds even without autonomic input, though the parasympathetics modulate it. It does not require the sympathetic system to start, the sphincter of Oddi, or removal of the ENS — destroying the ENS actually abolishes it.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 39"},{"q":"Glucose enters most cells of the body by...","choices":["Simple diffusion straight through the lipid bilayer","Primary active transport that directly uses ATP","Facilitated diffusion — a carrier is needed but energy is not","Receptor-mediated endocytosis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Glucose crosses most cell membranes by facilitated diffusion: a carrier protein (GLUT) moves it down its concentration gradient without using ATP. It is not pumped by primary active transport, does not dissolve through the bilayer, and is not taken up by endocytosis.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 4"},{"q":"White blood cells defend against infection through which two broad strategies?","choices":["Phagocytosis of invaders and forming antibodies/sensitized lymphocytes","Delivering oxygen and removing carbon dioxide","Clotting blood and repairing damaged vessels","Buffering pH and transporting hormones"],"answer":0,"exp":"WBCs both directly ingest invaders by phagocytosis and generate antibodies/sensitized lymphocytes that neutralize specific invaders. (B) and (D) describe red-cell and plasma roles, and (C) is the job of platelets and clotting factors, not the defensive strategies of WBCs.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 3"},{"q":"Aside from carrying oxygen, what is another major role of hemoglobin?","choices":["It acts as an excellent acid-base buffer","It is the main storage form of iron in plasma","It carries the majority of CO₂ as carbaminohemoglobin","It converts bilirubin into excretable bile pigments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hemoglobin is a very effective acid-base buffer in addition to transporting oxygen. (B) is wrong — iron is stored as ferritin/hemosiderin. (C) is wrong — most CO₂ travels as bicarbonate, not bound to hemoglobin. (D) is wrong — bilirubin is made by macrophages from the porphyrin ring, not by hemoglobin.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 3"},{"q":"How does a decrease in lung volume affect airway resistance?","choices":["It has no effect on resistance","It decreases resistance","It eliminates resistance","It increases resistance"],"answer":3,"exp":"As lung volume falls, the airways are less stretched open and narrow, so airway resistance rises. Resistance is never eliminated, and it clearly depends on lung volume, so “no effect” is incorrect.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 16"},{"q":"In GI smooth muscle, what is the role of “slow waves”?","choices":["They are rhythmic membrane oscillations that set the timing; contraction occurs only when they reach threshold and trigger spike potentials","They are action potentials that always produce contraction","They inhibit all smooth-muscle activity","They directly cause every contraction by themselves"],"answer":0,"exp":"Slow waves are subthreshold oscillations (the basic electrical rhythm); a contraction results only when a slow wave is driven to threshold and fires spike potentials. They do not by themselves cause every contraction, are not always action potentials, and are not purely inhibitory.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 35"},{"q":"The net product of glycolysis (per glucose) is...","choices":["2 lactate, 4 ATP, and 4 NADH","2 pyruvate, 2 ATP, and 2 NADH","2 acetyl-CoA and 6 ATP","1 pyruvate, 2 ATP, and no NADH"],"answer":1,"exp":"Glycolysis nets 2 pyruvate, 2 ATP (4 produced minus 2 invested), and 2 NADH per glucose. Lactate forms only when NAD⁺ must be regenerated, acetyl-CoA is a later product, and the other counts are wrong.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 14"},{"q":"What is chemotaxis, as it applies to neutrophils and macrophages?","choices":["Random drifting along with the bloodstream","Attachment of the cell to the vessel wall","Directed movement toward the source of a chemical signal","Ingestion of a foreign particle"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chemotaxis is directed movement toward (or away from) a chemical gradient — e.g., toward bacterial toxins or complement products. (A) is undirected, (B) describes margination, and (D) describes phagocytosis.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 14"},{"q":"The hematocrit ('packed cell volume') measures which of the following?","choices":["Grams of hemoglobin per 100 mL of blood","The number of red cells per cubic millimeter","The oxygen carried per gram of hemoglobin","The percentage of blood volume made up of packed red cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Hematocrit is the fraction of blood volume occupied by packed red cells (normally ~40–45%). (A) describes hemoglobin concentration, (B) the RBC count, and (C) oxygen-carrying capacity — all distinct measurements.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 6"},{"q":"What is the difference between a lung “volume” and a lung “capacity”?","choices":["A capacity is always smaller than a single volume","They are two words for the same thing","A capacity is the sum of two or more lung volumes","A volume can only be measured during exercise"],"answer":2,"exp":"A lung capacity is defined as the sum of two or more lung volumes (e.g., vital capacity = IRV + TV + ERV). Capacities are therefore larger than individual volumes, are not synonymous with them, and are measured at rest.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 27"},{"q":"The migrating motor complex (MMC) functions to...","choices":["Neutralize gastric acid","Mix chyme with enzymes right after a meal","Trigger mass movements in the colon","Sweep undigested residue toward the colon between meals, keeping upper-gut bacterial counts low"],"answer":3,"exp":"The MMC is the interdigestive “housekeeping” pattern that clears residue and bacteria from the upper gut between meals, mediated by motilin. It is not a postprandial mixing pattern, does not drive colonic mass movements, and has no role in neutralizing acid.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 55"},{"q":"In the electron transport chain, each NADH and each FADH₂ yield approximately...","choices":["3 ATP per NADH and 2 ATP per FADH₂","3 ATP from each","1 ATP from each","2 ATP per NADH and 3 ATP per FADH₂"],"answer":0,"exp":"NADH delivers electrons entering high in the chain (~3 ATP), while FADH₂ enters lower (~2 ATP). They do not yield equal amounts, and the last option reverses the two.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 22"},{"q":"How do lymph nodes help contain an infection?","choices":["They produce red blood cells to replace losses","Macrophages lining the sinuses phagocytize particles, preventing spread","They store neutrophils until an infection resolves","They filter oxygen out of the lymph"],"answer":1,"exp":"Macrophages lining the nodal sinuses phagocytize foreign particles carried in the lymph, keeping them from disseminating through the body. (A), (C), and (D) are not lymph-node functions.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 22"},{"q":"After hemoglobin is broken down, what happens to its porphyrin ring?","choices":["It is recycled directly into new hemoglobin","It is stored as hemosiderin in macrophages","It is converted, step by step, into bilirubin","It is excreted unchanged by the kidneys"],"answer":2,"exp":"Macrophages convert the porphyrin ring stepwise into bilirubin, which is released to the blood and secreted in bile. (A) and (B) apply to the iron portion (reused or stored); (D) is wrong — the ring is chemically processed first.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 28"},{"q":"Inspiratory capacity is the maximum air that can be inspired following...","choices":["A maximal expiration","A normal (resting) expiration","A maximal inspiration","A forced exhalation to residual volume"],"answer":1,"exp":"Inspiratory capacity (= TV + IRV) is the most air inhaled starting from the end of a normal, resting expiration. Starting from a maximal expiration or residual volume would approach total lung capacity, and you cannot inhale further after a maximal inspiration.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 28"},{"q":"Which gastric cell secretes both hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor?","choices":["Chief (peptic) cells","G-cells","Parietal (oxyntic) cells","Mucous neck cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parietal (oxyntic) cells secrete both HCl and intrinsic factor. Chief cells make pepsinogen, G-cells make gastrin, and mucous neck cells make mucus.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 79"},{"q":"Which condition favors gluconeogenesis?","choices":["Low cortisol levels","A high insulin-to-glucagon ratio","High blood glucose right after a meal","A high glucagon-to-insulin ratio (as in fasting)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Gluconeogenesis (mainly hepatic) is favored by a high glucagon:insulin ratio, high mitochondrial NADH and acetyl-CoA, and high cortisol — the fasting state. A high insulin ratio, post-meal hyperglycemia, and low cortisol all suppress it.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 30"},{"q":"During inflammation, neutrophils first stick to the vessel wall (margination). What mediates this sticking step?","choices":["Perforins binding to the endothelium","Adhesion molecules on the endothelium binding integrins on the neutrophil","Antibodies cross-linking the neutrophil","Complement lysing the endothelial cell"],"answer":1,"exp":"Inflammatory cytokines induce endothelial adhesion molecules (selectins, ICAM-1) that bind complementary integrins on neutrophils, causing margination before diapedesis. (A), (C), and (D) describe unrelated processes.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 28"},{"q":"What does it mean that hematopoietic stem cells are 'pluripotent'?","choices":["They can produce only red blood cells","They can give rise to several different cell types","They have already committed to a single lineage","They are mature cells already circulating in blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pluripotent means capable of giving rise to several different cell types — here, all blood cell lines. (A) and (C) describe committed/limited cells, and (D) is wrong — stem cells are not mature circulating cells.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 9"},{"q":"What is the primary function of pulmonary surfactant?","choices":["To reduce alveolar surface tension and prevent collapse","To increase surface tension so alveoli stay small","To thicken the respiratory membrane for protection","To trap inhaled particles like mucus"],"answer":0,"exp":"Surfactant lowers the surface tension of the alveolar lining fluid, preventing collapse and increasing compliance. It does not raise surface tension, thicken the membrane, or trap particles — those would impair breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 20"},{"q":"Why is intrinsic factor considered the only indispensable component of gastric juice?","choices":["It is required to activate pepsinogen","It is required for vitamin B12 absorption in the ileum","It neutralizes duodenal acid","It emulsifies dietary fat"],"answer":1,"exp":"Intrinsic factor binds vitamin B12 so the complex can be absorbed in the ileum, and its loss causes B12 deficiency — which is why it is the one indispensable gastric secretion. It does not activate pepsinogen, neutralize acid, or emulsify fat.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 87"},{"q":"Chylomicrons and VLDL differ in that...","choices":["both are made only in the liver","chylomicrons are made in the liver and VLDL in the gut","chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the intestine, while VLDL is made in the liver","neither particle carries triglyceride"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chylomicrons are assembled in intestinal mucosa to carry absorbed dietary fat, while VLDL is synthesized in the liver (its triglyceride made largely from carbohydrate). The other options misplace their origins or deny that they carry triglyceride.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 6"},{"q":"Which feature makes a particle MORE likely to be phagocytized?","choices":["A smooth surface","An intact protective protein coat","A negative charge that repels phagocytes","A rough surface"],"answer":3,"exp":"Rough surfaces favor phagocytosis, whereas the body's own smooth-surfaced, protein-coated structures resist it. So (A) and (B) describe features that resist phagocytosis, and (C) is not one of the three selective cues described.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 15"},{"q":"Why can reticulocytes still synthesize hemoglobin even though they are nearly mature?","choices":["They still contain a functional nucleus","They retain mitochondria and centrioles","They retain some endoplasmic reticulum and mRNA","They store erythropoietin internally"],"answer":2,"exp":"Reticulocytes keep a small amount of endoplasmic reticulum and mRNA, allowing continued hemoglobin synthesis. (A) is wrong — they have no nucleus; (B) and (D) name structures/substances not responsible for this synthesis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 18"},{"q":"How does surfactant help stabilize alveoli of different sizes?","choices":["By increasing surface tension in large alveoli","By enlarging all alveoli equally","By blocking airflow to small alveoli","By reducing surface tension, which lessens the collapse tendency of small alveoli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Surfactant lowers surface tension — most effectively in small alveoli — reducing their collapse tendency and equalizing stability across alveolar sizes. It does not raise tension, resize alveoli uniformly, or block airflow.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 23"},{"q":"When the antral pH becomes very low, gastrin release is inhibited largely because acid...","choices":["Stimulates somatostatin release, which suppresses gastrin (negative feedback)","Directly destroys the G-cells","Converts gastrin into secretin","Increases histamine release"],"answer":0,"exp":"A low antral pH stimulates somatostatin, which inhibits gastrin release — a negative-feedback brake on acid secretion. Acid does not destroy G-cells, convert gastrin to secretin, or raise histamine.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 94"},{"q":"Insulin promotes fat storage by...","choices":["stimulating hormone-sensitive lipase","stimulating lipoprotein lipase and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase","blocking glucose uptake into cells","promoting beta-oxidation of fat"],"answer":1,"exp":"Insulin stores fat by activating lipoprotein lipase (loading fatty acids into adipocytes) and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase (blocking breakdown of stored triglyceride). It promotes glucose uptake and opposes fat mobilization and beta-oxidation.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 22"},{"q":"What provides the FIRST line of cellular defense at a new site of infection?","choices":["Neutrophils migrating from the blood","Increased bone marrow production of white cells","Circulating antibodies","Tissue macrophages already present, which enlarge and mobilize"],"answer":3,"exp":"Resident tissue macrophages act first, enlarging and becoming mobile. Neutrophils are the second line (within ~1 hour), a second macrophage wave is third, and increased marrow output is fourth.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 27"},{"q":"What is the correct sequence of events in hemostasis?","choices":["Platelet plug → vascular constriction → blood clot → healing","Vascular constriction → platelet plug → blood clot → healing and recanalization","Blood clot → platelet plug → vascular constriction → healing","Vascular constriction → blood clot → platelet plug → healing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hemostasis proceeds as vascular constriction, then a platelet plug, then a blood clot, then healing/recanalization. The other orders misplace one or more steps — constriction comes first and the clot forms after the platelet plug.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 29"},{"q":"In what direction does a gas diffuse across the respiratory membrane?","choices":["From lower to higher partial pressure","Always from blood to alveolus","Down its partial pressure gradient, from higher to lower","Independent of any pressure gradient"],"answer":2,"exp":"A gas diffuses passively from higher to lower partial pressure. It cannot move up a gradient without energy, and its direction depends on that gradient (O₂ into blood, CO₂ out) — so “always blood to alveolus” and “independent of gradient” are wrong.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 51"},{"q":"Besides stimulating gastric acid secretion, gastrin has what other notable action?","choices":["Inhibiting all gastric secretion","Emptying the gallbladder","Stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion","A trophic effect promoting growth of the oxyntic (gastric) mucosa"],"answer":3,"exp":"Beyond stimulating acid, gastrin is trophic to the oxyntic mucosa, promoting its growth. Gallbladder emptying and pancreatic enzyme secretion are CCK's actions, and gastrin stimulates rather than inhibits gastric secretion.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 12"},{"q":"To synthesize a non-essential amino acid, a cell needs a carbon skeleton (α-keto acid), an amino group, and...","choices":["intrinsic factor","an aminotransferase enzyme (a vitamin B6 derivative)","bile salts","a fatty acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Making a non-essential amino acid requires a carbon skeleton (α-keto acid), an amino group (from glutamate/glutamine), and an aminotransferase, which is a vitamin B6–derived enzyme. Intrinsic factor, bile salts, and fatty acids play no role in transamination.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 7"},{"q":"Antibodies binding many bacteria together into a clump is an example of...","choices":["Agglutination","Neutralization","Lysis","Precipitation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Agglutination binds multiple particles bearing surface antigens into a clump. Neutralization masks toxic sites, lysis ruptures the target membrane, and precipitation drives a soluble antigen-antibody complex out of solution.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 52"},{"q":"Activated platelets secrete ADP and thromboxane A2. What do these substances accomplish?","choices":["They activate additional platelets through positive feedback","They dissolve the forming platelet plug","They convert fibrinogen into fibrin","They inhibit vascular constriction"],"answer":0,"exp":"ADP and thromboxane A2 recruit and activate more platelets, a positive-feedback loop that builds the plug. (B) is the opposite effect, (C) is thrombin's action, and (D) is wrong — these promote hemostasis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 34"},{"q":"Alveolar air is replaced only slowly (a fraction with each breath). What is the physiological benefit?","choices":["It lets CO₂ accumulate to high levels","It keeps alveolar gas concentrations stable, preventing sudden swings","It speeds oxygen loss from the blood","It prevents any gas exchange from occurring"],"answer":1,"exp":"Because only about one-seventh of alveolar air is exchanged per breath, alveolar O₂ and CO₂ stay relatively constant, buffering blood gases against breath-to-breath swings. It does not let CO₂ build up, speed O₂ loss, or halt exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 52"},{"q":"Which hormone is released cyclically during fasting to drive the migrating motor complexes?","choices":["Cholecystokinin","Secretin","Motilin","Gastrin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Motilin is released cyclically during fasting and drives the migrating motor complexes. CCK, secretin, and gastrin are released in response to a meal and serve digestive rather than interdigestive roles.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 18"},{"q":"Which hormone causes breakdown of tissue protein, providing amino acids for gluconeogenesis?","choices":["Insulin","Growth hormone","Testosterone","Cortisol (glucocorticoids)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cortisol promotes breakdown of extrahepatic tissue protein, raising plasma amino acids for gluconeogenesis. Insulin, growth hormone, and testosterone all promote protein synthesis instead.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 19"},{"q":"How do T-cells recognize antigen, unlike B-cells?","choices":["They recognize antigen fragments presented on MHC molecules","They bind intact free antigen directly","They detect antigen only after it is agglutinated","They require complement in order to bind antigen"],"answer":0,"exp":"T-cells respond only to processed antigen fragments displayed on MHC molecules of antigen-presenting cells, whereas B-cells (and antibodies) recognize intact antigen. (C) and (D) are not requirements for T-cell recognition.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 55"},{"q":"How does thrombin promote clot extension through positive feedback?","choices":["By inactivating factor V to slow the reaction","By acting on prothrombin and other factors to generate still more thrombin","By dissolving fibrin at the clot's edge","By blocking recruitment of additional platelets"],"answer":1,"exp":"Thrombin feeds back to produce more thrombin and more prothrombin activator, extending the clot. (A) is the opposite — thrombin activates factor V; (C) and (D) would limit the clot, not extend it.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 42"},{"q":"The lungs contain roughly 300 million alveoli. How does this aid gas exchange?","choices":["It provides an enormous surface area for diffusion","It reduces the total surface area","It increases the diffusion distance","It decreases compliance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hundreds of millions of alveoli create a vast total surface area, which — per Fick's law — greatly increases gas exchange. This increases (not reduces) surface area and does not lengthen the diffusion distance or lower compliance.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 57"},{"q":"After pancreatic amylase acts, where is carbohydrate digestion completed?","choices":["In the stomach by pepsin","At the brush border, by membrane-bound disaccharidases","In the colon by bacteria only","Inside the liver"],"answer":1,"exp":"Luminal amylase yields disaccharides and oligosaccharides, and final carbohydrate digestion is completed by brush-border disaccharidases (maltase, sucrase, lactase). It is not finished by gastric pepsin, in the liver, or solely by colonic bacteria.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 123"},{"q":"Regarding the liver's blood supply...","choices":["It is supplied almost entirely by the hepatic artery","It receives less than 5% of cardiac output","It receives about 30% of cardiac output, most of it from the portal vein","It has no venous inflow"],"answer":2,"exp":"About 30% of cardiac output flows through the liver, roughly 75% via the portal vein and 25% via the hepatic artery, at low pressure and resistance. It is not chiefly arterial, is far more than 5% of output, and has major portal venous inflow.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 3"},{"q":"Which statement best describes innate immunity?","choices":["It targets one specific antigen with tailored antibodies","It develops only after weeks of exposure to a pathogen","It relies on memory cells from a prior infection","It resists organisms and toxins using non-specific, general defenses"],"answer":3,"exp":"Innate immunity uses non-specific, ready-made defenses (skin, gastric acid, neutrophils/macrophages, complement, NK cells). (A), (B), and (C) all describe acquired immunity, which is specific, slower to develop, and memory-based.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 35"},{"q":"Where do the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways converge?","choices":["At the activation of factor X (the common pathway)","At the activation of factor XII","At the release of tissue factor","At the cross-linking of fibrin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Both pathways meet at the activation of factor X, entering the common pathway toward thrombin and fibrin. (B) and (C) are pathway-specific starting points, and (D) is a later step after thrombin has acted.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 47"},{"q":"Respiratory regulation is organized as which three-part system?","choices":["Surfactant, mucus, and cilia","Arteries, veins, and capillaries","Alveoli, bronchioles, and pleura","Sensors, a central controller, and effector muscles"],"answer":3,"exp":"Respiratory control is a feedback loop: sensors (chemoreceptors) gather data, the central controller (brainstem) integrates it, and effectors (respiratory muscles) act. The other trios list vascular, structural, or airway-lining parts, not the control loop.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 88"},{"q":"Where are bile salts reabsorbed to be recycled back to the liver?","choices":["In the ileum","In the duodenum","In the colon","In the stomach"],"answer":0,"exp":"Bile salts are actively reabsorbed in the ileum and returned to the liver (the enterohepatic circulation). They are not reclaimed in the stomach, duodenum, or colon.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 121"},{"q":"The liver requires which vitamin to manufacture prothrombin and several clotting factors?","choices":["Vitamin C","Vitamin K","Vitamin B12","Vitamin A"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver needs vitamin K to make prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X, so liver disease or vitamin K deficiency causes bleeding. Vitamins C, B12, and A serve other roles.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 11"},{"q":"What is an antigen, and which part of it does the immune system specifically recognize?","choices":["A carbohydrate on red cells; recognized by its charge","A protein or large polysaccharide; recognized at specific sites called epitopes","A small lipid; recognized by its solubility","A metal ion; recognized by complement"],"answer":1,"exp":"Antigens are typically proteins or large polysaccharides (MW > 8,000) with recurring surface groups; the specific sites recognized are epitopes. The other options misidentify both the molecule and the recognized region.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 38"},{"q":"How is a clot eventually broken down during healing?","choices":["Thrombin is converted to plasmin, which cross-links fibrin","Fibrinogen is converted to plasmin, which builds new clot","Plasminogen is activated to plasmin, which digests fibrin fibers","Antithrombin is converted to plasmin, which stores iron"],"answer":2,"exp":"Tissue plasminogen activator converts plasminogen (trapped in the clot) to plasmin, which digests fibrin and reopens the vessel. (A), (B), and (D) misidentify plasmin's precursor and function — plasmin comes from plasminogen and degrades, rather than builds, the clot.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 51"},{"q":"When arterial PO₂ falls substantially (PCO₂ held constant), ventilation...","choices":["Decreases","Stays exactly the same","Stops entirely","Increases, driven by the peripheral chemoreceptors"],"answer":3,"exp":"A substantial fall in PO₂ stimulates the carotid and aortic bodies, increasing ventilation (the hypoxic drive). Ventilation does not fall, stay flat, or stop when oxygen drops.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 99"},{"q":"The exocrine pancreas serves two key roles as chyme enters the small intestine:","choices":["Absorbing nutrients and storing bile","Producing intrinsic factor and gastrin","Supplying digestive enzymes for all nutrient types and bicarbonate to neutralize acid chyme","Emulsifying fat and reabsorbing bile salts"],"answer":2,"exp":"The exocrine pancreas secretes enzymes for carbohydrate, protein, and fat digestion plus bicarbonate to neutralize acidic chyme. It does not absorb nutrients or store bile, make intrinsic factor/gastrin, or emulsify fat (a bile-salt role).","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 99"},{"q":"In the enterohepatic circulation, about 95% of secreted bile salts are...","choices":["reabsorbed (mostly in the ileum) and returned to the liver for reuse","destroyed by pancreatic enzymes","converted to cholesterol in the gut","excreted in the feces"],"answer":0,"exp":"About 95% of secreted bile salts are reabsorbed, chiefly in the ileum, and returned via portal blood to the liver; only the small fraction lost in feces is replaced by new synthesis. They are not mostly excreted, digested, or turned back into cholesterol in the gut.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 25"},{"q":"What is the proposed role of suppressor (regulatory) T-cells?","choices":["To amplify the response to every antigen encountered","To secrete antibodies during humoral immunity","To present antigen on MHC molecules","To help maintain tolerance to self-antigens and limit autoimmunity"],"answer":3,"exp":"Suppressor/regulatory T-cells are thought to restrain helper and cytotoxic T-cells, maintaining self-tolerance and preventing autoimmunity. Amplifying every response is the opposite effect, secreting antibody is a plasma-cell function, and presenting antigen on MHC is an antigen-presenting-cell role.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 60"},{"q":"About how much oxygen can each gram of hemoglobin bind?","choices":["0.3 ml O₂","1.34 ml O₂","100 ml O₂","20 ml O₂"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 ml of O₂. The 0.3 ml figure is dissolved O₂ per 100 ml of blood, and ~20 ml is the total O₂-carrying capacity per 100 ml — not the per-gram value.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 77"},{"q":"Pancreatic enzyme secretion versus bicarbonate/fluid secretion are controlled mainly by:","choices":["Both entirely by gastrin","Enzyme output by acid; bicarbonate output by fat","Enzyme secretion by fat and protein (via CCK); bicarbonate/fluid secretion by acid (via secretin)","Both by intrinsic factor"],"answer":2,"exp":"Pancreatic enzyme secretion tracks duodenal fat and protein (through CCK), while bicarbonate/fluid secretion tracks duodenal acid (through secretin). Gastrin and intrinsic factor are not the main controllers, and the acid/fat pairing is reversed in the other option.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 107"},{"q":"Which macronutrient provides the most energy per gram?","choices":["Carbohydrate (~4 kcal/g)","All provide equal energy per gram","Protein (~4 kcal/g)","Fat (~9 kcal/g)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Fat yields about 9 kcal/g, more than double carbohydrate or protein (~4 kcal/g each). They are not equal per gram.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 4"},{"q":"Which statement about the complement system best captures how it bridges innate and acquired immunity?","choices":["It is part of innate immunity, yet its classical pathway can be activated by antibodies from the adaptive system","It is part of acquired immunity and produces memory cells","It is adaptable and changes over a person's lifetime","It presents antigen fragments to T-cells on MHC"],"answer":0,"exp":"Complement is a fixed, non-adaptive (innate) set of proteins, but antibodies from the adaptive system can trigger its cascade — linking the two arms. (B) and (C) wrongly call it adaptive/changeable, and (D) describes antigen presentation, not complement.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 53"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide is dangerous to oxygen transport because it...","choices":["Increases the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood","Binds hemoglobin far more tightly than O₂, blocking O₂ binding","Cannot bind hemoglobin at all","Only affects dissolved oxygen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Carbon monoxide binds hemoglobin with far greater affinity than oxygen, occupying binding sites and preventing O₂ transport. It reduces (not increases) usable capacity, definitely binds hemoglobin, and acts on hemoglobin rather than dissolved O₂.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 82"},{"q":"The villi and microvilli of the small intestine are important because they...","choices":["Vastly increase the surface area available for absorption","Secrete the pancreatic enzymes","Neutralize gastric acid","Store bile salts"],"answer":0,"exp":"Villi (~10-fold) and microvilli/brush border (~20-fold) hugely amplify the absorptive surface area of the small intestine. They do not secrete pancreatic enzymes, neutralize acid, or store bile salts.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 118"},{"q":"Which hypothalamic region serves as the satiety center, whose destruction causes overeating?","choices":["The lateral nuclei","The preoptic area","The ventromedial nuclei","The posterior hypothalamus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ventromedial nuclei form the satiety center; their destruction causes hyperphagia and obesity. The lateral nuclei are the feeding center (lesions cause inanition), and the preoptic/posterior areas handle temperature.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 9"},{"q":"In what form is MOST CO₂ carried in the blood?","choices":["As dissolved CO₂","Bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin","As carbonic acid crystals","As bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻)"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 70% of CO₂ travels as bicarbonate formed in red cells by carbonic anhydrase. Roughly 23% rides on hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin and ~7% is dissolved; CO₂ is not carried as solid carbonic-acid crystals.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"Which statement about protein absorption is correct?","choices":["Di- and tripeptides use a different carrier than free amino acids and are absorbed faster","Only free amino acids can be absorbed","Whole proteins are absorbed intact in adults","Peptides are absorbed only in the stomach"],"answer":0,"exp":"Small di- and tripeptides are taken up by a separate carrier (and hydrolyzed inside the cell), and are actually absorbed faster than free amino acids. Whole proteins are not absorbed intact in adults, and peptide absorption occurs in the small intestine, not the stomach.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 129"},{"q":"Which hormone, released mainly from the stomach, stimulates feeding?","choices":["Leptin","Ghrelin","CCK","Peptide YY"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ghrelin, released mainly from the stomach's oxyntic cells, stimulates feeding. Leptin, CCK, and peptide YY all inhibit feeding.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 11"},{"q":"The Haldane effect describes how...","choices":["Low pH increases O₂ unloading","CO₂ increases hemoglobin's O₂ affinity","Binding of O₂ to hemoglobin in the lungs promotes CO₂ release","Chloride enters the red cell at the tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"The Haldane effect: when hemoglobin binds O₂ in the lungs, it releases CO₂ more readily, aiding CO₂ elimination. Low pH increasing O₂ unloading is the Bohr effect, and the other options misstate CO₂'s effect on O₂ affinity and the chloride shift.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 85"},{"q":"Vitamin B12 (bound to intrinsic factor) is absorbed at which site?","choices":["The stomach","The duodenum","The colon","The ileum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The intrinsic-factor–B12 complex is absorbed in the ileum (as are bile salts). The stomach and colon absorb little B12, and the duodenum mainly absorbs other nutrients, iron, and calcium.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 121"},{"q":"Vitamin D is essential for...","choices":["calcium and phosphate balance","oxygen transport","amino acid transamination","collagen synthesis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Vitamin D (activated via skin UV, then the liver and kidney) is essential for calcium and phosphate balance; deficiency causes rickets. Collagen needs vitamin C, oxygen transport needs hemoglobin, and transamination needs vitamin B6.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 28"},{"q":"Phosphocreatine in muscle functions as...","choices":["the body's main long-term energy store","a rapid reserve to regenerate ATP during short bursts of activity","a direct source of glucose","a heat-producing hormone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Phosphocreatine acts as an immediate high-energy buffer, rephosphorylating ADP to ATP during brief, intense activity. It is not a long-term store, a glucose source, or a hormone.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 2"},{"q":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate by measuring...","choices":["body weight loss","urine volume","oxygen consumption","heart rate alone"],"answer":2,"exp":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate from oxygen consumption (~250 mL/min at rest), since about 95% of energy expenditure comes from reactions of oxygen with foods. Weight loss, urine volume, and heart rate alone are not used.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 7"},{"q":"Which is a mechanism of heat LOSS from the body?","choices":["Piloerection","Shivering","Vasoconstriction of skin vessels","Evaporation of sweat"],"answer":3,"exp":"Evaporation (of sweat and insensible water) loses heat, along with radiation and conduction/convection. Shivering and piloerection generate or conserve heat, and skin vasoconstriction reduces heat loss.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 6"}]},"physio-master-v2":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v2)","questions":[{"q":"According to the “law of the gut,” a bolus that distends the intestine causes...","choices":["Relaxation on both sides at the same time","Contraction on the orad (upstream) side and relaxation on the downstream (aboral) side","Contraction ahead of the bolus, pushing it backward","No coordinated response unless the sympathetic nerves fire"],"answer":1,"exp":"Distension makes the segment behind the bolus contract while the segment ahead relaxes, propelling contents aborally. Simultaneous relaxation, contraction ahead of the bolus, or dependence on sympathetic input all misdescribe this reflex.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 39"},{"q":"Which statement about insulin and cellular glucose uptake is correct?","choices":["Most glucose uptake uses insulin-independent carriers (e.g., GLUT-1); GLUT-4 in muscle and fat is insulin-dependent","All cellular glucose uptake requires insulin","No glucose transporter responds to insulin at all","Insulin is required for glucose uptake only in the liver"],"answer":0,"exp":"Most post-absorptive glucose uptake uses insulin-independent transporters like GLUT-1, while GLUT-4 in muscle and adipose is the insulin-dependent carrier. So not all uptake needs insulin, some transporters clearly respond to it, and the liver is not the special case.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 4"},{"q":"Platelets have no nucleus. What is the direct consequence of this?","choices":["They are unable to store calcium for clotting","They cannot adhere to exposed collagen","They cannot contract during clot retraction","They cannot reproduce"],"answer":3,"exp":"Without a nucleus, platelets cannot reproduce. (A) is wrong — platelets do store Ca²⁺. (B) is wrong — they adhere to collagen, aided by von Willebrand factor. (C) is wrong — they contract using actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 32"},{"q":"During quiet (resting) breathing, how is expiration accomplished?","choices":["By active contraction of the diaphragm","Passively, through elastic recoil of the lungs and chest wall","By contraction of the abdominal muscles","By contraction of the external intercostals"],"answer":1,"exp":"In quiet breathing the inspiratory muscles simply relax and the stretched lung recoils, expelling air passively — no active expiratory effort is needed. Diaphragm and external-intercostal contraction produce inspiration, and the abdominals are recruited only for forced expiration.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 18"},{"q":"Among the white blood cell types listed in the deck, which functions specifically to activate blood clotting?","choices":["Neutrophils","Eosinophils","Platelets","Lymphocytes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Platelets (from megakaryocytes) are grouped with the WBCs here and function specifically to trigger blood clotting. Neutrophils and eosinophils are phagocytic/effector granulocytes, and lymphocytes serve the immune system — none of these initiate clotting.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 4"},{"q":"How does autonomic input generally affect GI activity?","choices":["Parasympathetic input mainly stimulates, and sympathetic input mainly inhibits","Parasympathetic inhibits and sympathetic stimulates","Both divisions stimulate the gut equally","Neither division affects gut motility"],"answer":0,"exp":"Parasympathetic (vagal/pelvic, ACh) activity generally stimulates motility and secretion, while sympathetic (NE) activity generally inhibits. The other options reverse or deny these effects.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 25"},{"q":"The complete aerobic oxidation of one glucose molecule yields approximately how many ATP?","choices":["About 2 ATP","About 38 ATP","About 100 ATP","About 12 ATP"],"answer":1,"exp":"Full aerobic oxidation of one glucose yields roughly 38 ATP (glycolysis, pyruvate→acetyl-CoA, the TCA cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation). About 2 ATP is the anaerobic, glycolysis-only yield; 100 and 12 are incorrect.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 23"},{"q":"How many oxygen molecules can a single hemoglobin molecule carry, and why?","choices":["Two — one for each beta chain","Sixteen — four for each of the four chains","Four — one for each iron atom","Eight — one for each globin chain"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each hemoglobin has four heme groups, each with one iron atom that binds one O₂ molecule — four O₂ molecules (eight oxygen atoms) per hemoglobin. (D) confuses the four chains with eight molecules; (A) and (B) miscount the heme/iron units.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 21"},{"q":"How does forced expiration differ from quiet expiration?","choices":["It requires surfactant to push air out","It relies solely on relaxation of the diaphragm","It makes pleural pressure more negative","It uses active muscle effort, and pleural pressure can become positive"],"answer":3,"exp":"Forced expiration recruits expiratory muscles (e.g., abdominals), which can drive intrapleural pressure positive to expel air rapidly. Passive relaxation and a more-negative pleural pressure describe quiet breathing and inspiration, and surfactant lowers surface tension rather than expelling air.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 18"},{"q":"Compared with a neutrophil, an activated tissue macrophage can...","choices":["Ingest only a single bacterium before dying","No longer perform phagocytosis at all","Phagocytize far more particles — up to about 100 bacteria","Only ingest viruses, never bacteria"],"answer":2,"exp":"Activated macrophages are highly effective phagocytes, able to engulf up to ~100 bacteria and even large particles like damaged red cells. The other options — ingesting only one bacterium, no longer phagocytizing, or ingesting only viruses — all understate or misstate their capacity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 17"},{"q":"Pepsinogen is secreted primarily by which cells?","choices":["Chief (peptic) cells","Parietal cells","G-cells","ECL cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Chief (peptic) cells secrete pepsinogen. Parietal cells make acid and intrinsic factor, G-cells make gastrin, and ECL cells release histamine.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 79"},{"q":"The pentose phosphate (hexose monophosphate) shunt is important because it produces...","choices":["large amounts of ATP","NADPH and ribose-5-phosphate for biosynthesis and nucleic acids","ketone bodies for energy","lactate to send to the liver"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pentose phosphate shunt generates NADPH (for reductive biosynthesis) and ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleic acids), not ATP. It does not make lactate or ketone bodies.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 29"},{"q":"A low plasma transferrin level (poor iron transport) tends to produce which result?","choices":["Enlarged, macrocytic red cells","Iron overload deposited in tissues","Increased oxygen affinity of hemoglobin","Hypochromic red cells containing too little hemoglobin"],"answer":3,"exp":"With too little transferrin to deliver iron, red cells are made with less hemoglobin than normal — hypochromic anemia. (A) reflects B12/folate problems; (B) is the opposite of poor transport; (C) is unrelated.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 25"},{"q":"Something described as “highly elastic,” like lung tissue, will...","choices":["Resist being stretched and tend to recoil to its original shape","Stretch easily and stay stretched","Have very high compliance","Lose its shape permanently after stretching"],"answer":0,"exp":"Elasticity is the tendency to return to the original shape after stretch, so a highly elastic structure resists deformation and recoils. Stretching easily or staying deformed describes low elasticity / high compliance — the opposite property.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 19"},{"q":"What is the correct path of lymph through a lymph node?","choices":["Efferent lymphatics → sinuses → afferent lymphatics","Blood capillaries → node → arterial blood","Afferent lymphatics → nodal sinuses → hilus → efferent lymphatics","Hilus → afferent lymphatics → venous blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lymph enters through afferent lymphatics, flows through the medullary sinuses, and exits at the hilus via efferent lymphatics toward venous blood. (A) reverses the flow, and (B) and (D) misroute it.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 22"},{"q":"Gastrin and acetylcholine strongly stimulate acid secretion partly by triggering release of which paracrine agent from ECL cells?","choices":["Somatostatin","Secretin","Motilin","Histamine"],"answer":3,"exp":"Gastrin and ACh stimulate ECL cells to release histamine, which powerfully drives parietal-cell acid secretion. Somatostatin and secretin inhibit acid, and motilin governs interdigestive motility.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 91"},{"q":"Lipoprotein lipase, attached to capillary endothelium, functions to...","choices":["synthesize triglycerides inside adipocytes","hydrolyze triglycerides in chylomicrons and VLDL, releasing fatty acids to tissues","package cholesterol into HDL","make ketone bodies in the liver"],"answer":1,"exp":"Lipoprotein lipase hydrolyzes the triglycerides carried in chylomicrons and VLDL, freeing fatty acids for uptake by tissues (adipose, muscle, heart). It does not synthesize triglycerides, build HDL, or make ketones.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 13"},{"q":"Hematopoiesis is driven by which two general classes of signals?","choices":["Erythropoietin and thrombopoietin only","Oxygen and carbon dioxide gradients","Vitamin B12 and folate","Growth inducers and differentiation inducers"],"answer":3,"exp":"Hematopoiesis is driven by growth inducers (e.g., interleukin-3) and differentiation inducers. (A) names specific hormones, not the general categories; (B) and (C) are conditions/nutrients, not inducer classes.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 9"},{"q":"Because airflow varies with r⁴, a small decrease in airway radius will...","choices":["Sharply increase resistance, since radius is raised to the fourth power","Decrease resistance","Only matter in the alveoli, not the airways","Barely change resistance"],"answer":0,"exp":"With resistance proportional to 1/r⁴, even slight narrowing greatly increases resistance to airflow. It does not decrease or barely change resistance, and the effect is greatest in the airways (the upper airways carry the major resistance), not the alveoli.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 16"},{"q":"Compared with blood capillaries, lymph capillaries are...","choices":["Much less permeable to particles","Impermeable to all proteins","Highly permeable, allowing particles to enter the lymph","Identical in permeability"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lymph capillaries are highly permeable relative to blood capillaries, so particles readily enter the lymph (where nodal macrophages can screen them). (A), (B), and (D) misstate this permeability.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 21"},{"q":"Which luminal stimulus most strongly triggers CCK release from duodenal I-cells?","choices":["Intact triglycerides","Glucose alone","Water","Fatty acids and monoglycerides (products of fat digestion), plus peptides and amino acids"],"answer":3,"exp":"CCK release is triggered by fat-digestion products (fatty acids, monoglycerides) and by peptides/amino acids — not by intact triglycerides, glucose alone, or water.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 13"},{"q":"Ketone bodies are produced by the liver mainly...","choices":["from glucose during a carbohydrate-rich meal","from fatty acids, to serve as an energy source for other tissues","to store excess dietary protein","only during the well-fed state"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver makes ketone bodies from fatty acid–derived acetyl-CoA (especially when fat oxidation is high, as in fasting) and exports them as fuel for other tissues. They are not made from glucose in the fed state or used to store protein.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 15"},{"q":"Why are vitamin B12 and folate essential for red blood cell production?","choices":["They form the heme ring of hemoglobin","They carry iron into the mitochondria","They are required for DNA synthesis during rapid cell proliferation","They directly stimulate erythropoietin release"],"answer":2,"exp":"Both vitamins are needed to make thymidine triphosphate and therefore DNA, which rapidly dividing red-cell precursors require. (A) is wrong — heme synthesis is a separate pathway; (B) describes transferrin's role; (D) is wrong — they don't trigger EPO.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 17"},{"q":"Vital capacity is the sum of which volumes?","choices":["Tidal volume + residual volume","Inspiratory reserve + residual volume","Expiratory reserve + residual volume","Inspiratory reserve + tidal volume + expiratory reserve"],"answer":3,"exp":"Vital capacity — the maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration — equals IRV + TV + ERV. Any combination that includes residual volume is wrong, because residual volume cannot be exhaled and is not part of vital capacity.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 29"},{"q":"What does opsonization accomplish?","choices":["It marks a pathogen (with antibody and complement C3) for easier phagocytosis","It directly lyses the pathogen's membrane","It prevents antibodies from binding the pathogen","It neutralizes a toxin's active site"],"answer":0,"exp":"Opsonization tags a pathogen with antibody plus complement C3, attracting phagocytes and making ingestion far easier. (B) is complement-mediated lysis, (C) is the opposite of what happens, and (D) describes neutralization.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 15"},{"q":"Glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide (GIP) is notable because it...","choices":["Is the main stimulus for gallbladder contraction","Activates pancreatic proteolytic enzymes","Stimulates insulin release in response to oral nutrients (an incretin effect)","Is released only during fasting"],"answer":2,"exp":"GIP is an incretin: oral nutrients trigger it to enhance insulin release (and it inhibits gastric acid). Gallbladder contraction is CCK's role, zymogen activation is enterokinase/trypsin, and GIP is released after eating, not during fasting.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 17"},{"q":"How does increasing bile acid excretion (e.g., by fiber that traps bile salts) affect plasma cholesterol?","choices":["It lowers plasma cholesterol, because bile acids are made from cholesterol","It has no effect on plasma cholesterol","It converts cholesterol directly into glucose","It raises plasma cholesterol"],"answer":0,"exp":"Excreting bile acids forces the liver to consume cholesterol to make more, lowering plasma cholesterol; fecal loss is the only route of cholesterol removal. So it does not raise cholesterol, have no effect, or make glucose.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 36"},{"q":"Which mechanism is most important for constricting large blood vessels after injury?","choices":["Myogenic contraction from direct damage to the vessel wall","Thromboxane A2 released by platelets","Sympathetic nervous reflexes from pain fibers","Local autacoids from traumatized tissue"],"answer":0,"exp":"For large vessels, direct injury triggers myogenic contraction, the most important constriction mechanism. Thromboxane A2 (B) matters most for small vessels, while nervous reflexes (C) and autacoids (D) contribute but aren't dominant for large vessels.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 30"},{"q":"Which lung value CANNOT be measured directly by simple spirometry?","choices":["Tidal volume","Residual volume","Vital capacity","Inspiratory reserve volume"],"answer":1,"exp":"Spirometry measures only air that moves in and out, so it cannot capture residual volume (air that never leaves the lungs) — nor the capacities containing it (FRC, TLC). Tidal volume, inspiratory reserve, and vital capacity are all directly measurable.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 31"},{"q":"As a later line of defense, how does the bone marrow respond to a sustained infection?","choices":["It shuts down white-cell production to conserve resources","It increases granulocyte and monocyte production many-fold","It releases mature lymphocytes within minutes","It converts red cells into white cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The marrow can raise neutrophil and monocyte output 20–50-fold and sustain it for months, with the first new cells released in 3–4 days. (A) is the opposite, and (C) and (D) are physiologically wrong.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 31"},{"q":"Which enzyme in saliva begins the digestion of starch in the mouth?","choices":["Pepsin","Trypsin","α-amylase (ptyalin)","Lingual lipase"],"answer":2,"exp":"Salivary α-amylase (ptyalin) starts starch digestion in the mouth. Pepsin digests protein in the stomach, trypsin is a pancreatic protease, and lingual lipase acts on fat, not starch.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 72"},{"q":"Transamination is the process of...","choices":["removing a phosphate from glucose","oxidizing fatty acids to acetyl-CoA","breaking a peptide bond by adding water","transferring an amino group from one molecule (e.g., glutamate) to an α-keto acid"],"answer":3,"exp":"Transamination moves an amino group from a donor (often glutamate) onto an α-keto acid, forming a new amino acid — the core reaction for making non-essential amino acids. Dephosphorylation, peptide-bond hydrolysis, and beta-oxidation are unrelated.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 13"},{"q":"Which step is the rate-limiting step of blood coagulation?","choices":["Conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin","Cross-linking of fibrin by factor XIII","Activation of plasminogen to plasmin","Formation of prothrombin activator"],"answer":3,"exp":"Forming prothrombin activator is the rate-limiting step; once formed, it rapidly converts prothrombin to thrombin. (A) and (B) occur downstream, and (C) is part of clot breakdown, not formation.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 40"},{"q":"According to Fick's law, gas diffusion increases when...","choices":["The partial pressure gradient and surface area are larger","The surface area is smaller","The membrane is thicker","The solubility of the gas is lower"],"answer":0,"exp":"Fick's law makes diffusion proportional to the pressure gradient, surface area, and solubility, and inversely proportional to membrane thickness. So a bigger gradient and area speed diffusion, while a thicker membrane, smaller area, or lower solubility slow it.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 62"},{"q":"When an antibody covers the toxic site of a toxin so it can no longer act, this is called...","choices":["Agglutination","Precipitation","Neutralization","Opsonization"],"answer":2,"exp":"Neutralization is the antibody covering the harmful sites of an antigen/toxin. Agglutination clumps particles, precipitation makes a soluble complex insoluble, and opsonization tags a pathogen for phagocytosis.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 52"},{"q":"The final steps of protein digestion (di- and tripeptides to amino acids) occur...","choices":["Only in the stomach lumen","At the brush border and within the cytoplasm of the mucosal cells","Only in the mouth","In the colon"],"answer":1,"exp":"Protein digestion finishes at the brush border (oligopeptidases, dipeptidases) and in the enterocyte cytoplasm (di-/tripeptidases). It is not completed in the stomach, mouth, or colon.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 127"},{"q":"Amino acids that are broken down to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are called...","choices":["essential, because they cannot be made","glucogenic, because they form glucose","ketogenic, because they give rise to ketone bodies","non-essential, because they are synthesized"],"answer":2,"exp":"Amino acids degraded to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are ketogenic (they can form ketone bodies), whereas those forming glucose or TCA intermediates are glucogenic. 'Essential' vs 'non-essential' refers to whether the body can synthesize them — a different classification.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 18"},{"q":"Clot retraction depends on which cells, acting through what mechanism?","choices":["Platelets contracting via actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin","Red cells contracting by osmotic shrinkage","No cells — retraction is purely spontaneous","White cells engulfing and compacting fibrin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Platelets bound to fibrin contract using actin/myosin/thrombosthenin, tightening the clot; retraction will not occur without platelets. (B), (C), and (D) are incorrect — red cells, spontaneous action, and white cells do not drive retraction.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 43"},{"q":"How does increasing alveolar ventilation affect alveolar PCO₂?","choices":["It raises alveolar PCO₂","It has no effect on alveolar PCO₂","It raises PCO₂ only during exercise","It lowers alveolar PCO₂"],"answer":3,"exp":"Greater alveolar ventilation washes out CO₂ faster than metabolism produces it, so alveolar (and arterial) PCO₂ falls. Ventilation and PCO₂ are inversely related, so raising PCO₂ or “no effect” is incorrect.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 55"},{"q":"Why are helper T-cells described as central to the immune response?","choices":["They directly lyse infected cells with perforins","Their cytokines regulate B-cells, cytotoxic T-cells, and macrophages","They are the only cells that phagocytize bacteria","They form the antibodies of humoral immunity"],"answer":1,"exp":"Helper T-cells secrete cytokines/lymphokines that coordinate B-cells, cytotoxic T-cells, and macrophages — the immune system is nearly paralyzed without them. (A) is the cytotoxic T-cell's job, (C) is a phagocyte role, and (D) is the plasma cell's job.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 57"},{"q":"How do the products of fat digestion (monoglycerides and fatty acids) reach the enterocyte surface for absorption?","choices":["Packaged into micelles with bile salts, which ferry them to the brush border","Bound to intrinsic factor","Dissolved freely in water and diffusing on their own","Inside chylomicrons formed in the lumen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Because they are poorly water-soluble, monoglycerides and fatty acids are carried in micelles with bile salts to the enterocyte brush border. They do not simply diffuse, bind intrinsic factor, or ride in lumen-formed chylomicrons — chylomicrons form inside the enterocyte.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 133"},{"q":"The liver acts as a blood reservoir, normally holding about...","choices":["50% of total blood volume","10% of total blood volume (~450 mL), expandable in heart failure","less than 1% of blood volume","no blood between meals"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver normally holds about 10% of blood volume (~450 mL) and can expand by up to a liter in heart failure or release blood during hemorrhage/exercise. The other figures are far off.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 5"},{"q":"What triggers the intrinsic pathway of coagulation?","choices":["Release of tissue factor from injured tissue","Thrombin cleaving fibrinogen","Contact of blood and factor XII with collagen or a wettable surface","Binding of von Willebrand factor to platelets"],"answer":2,"exp":"The intrinsic pathway starts when blood/factor XII contacts collagen or a wettable surface (e.g., glass), activating factor XII. (A) initiates the extrinsic pathway, (B) is a common-pathway step, and (D) relates to platelet adhesion.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 46"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly lists layers a gas crosses in the respiratory membrane, from air to blood?","choices":["Capillary endothelium → alveolar epithelium → surfactant","Interstitial space → surfactant → capillary endothelium","Alveolar epithelium → surfactant → red blood cell","Surfactant/fluid → alveolar epithelium → basement membranes → capillary endothelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"Moving from air to blood, a gas crosses the surfactant/fluid layer, the alveolar epithelium, the fused basement membranes and interstitium, and finally the capillary endothelium. The other sequences scramble this air-to-blood order.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 60"},{"q":"A key contrast between acquired and innate immunity is that acquired immunity...","choices":["Is present and fully active from birth","Does not develop until the body is attacked and can take weeks to months","Provides no protection against toxins","Cannot distinguish one antigen from another"],"answer":1,"exp":"Acquired immunity develops only after exposure, requiring weeks to months to mount a specific response. (A) describes innate defenses, and (C) and (D) contradict acquired immunity's specificity and potency.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 35"},{"q":"Once formed, trypsin plays a central role in the intestine by...","choices":["Emulsifying fats","Neutralizing acid chyme","Activating chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and more trypsinogen","Absorbing peptides"],"answer":2,"exp":"Trypsin is the master activator: it converts chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and additional trypsinogen to their active forms. Neutralizing acid is bicarbonate's role, emulsifying fat is bile's, and absorption is the mucosa's.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 104"},{"q":"The liver's “glucose buffer” function means it...","choices":["stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose between meals","only stores glucose and never releases it","converts all absorbed glucose immediately to fat","prevents any glucose from entering the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"As a glucose buffer, the liver stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose (via glycogenolysis, then gluconeogenesis) between meals, stabilizing blood glucose. The other options describe one-way or nonexistent handling.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 9"},{"q":"What is vitamin K's essential role in coagulation?","choices":["It cross-links fibrin monomers into a stable clot","It converts plasminogen into plasmin","It directly activates platelets at the injury site","It is needed to carboxylate glutamic acid in prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X"],"answer":3,"exp":"Vitamin K is required to carboxylate glutamic acid residues on prothrombin and factors VII, IX, X (and protein C), making them functional. (A) is factor XIII's role, (B) is tPA's role, and (C) is unrelated to vitamin K.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 54"},{"q":"The central chemoreceptors are located in the brainstem and respond mainly to...","choices":["Oxygen levels in arterial blood","CO₂ and H⁺","Blood pressure changes","Lung stretch"],"answer":1,"exp":"The central chemoreceptors sense CO₂ and H⁺ (via H⁺ generated in the CSF). Oxygen sensing is the job of the peripheral chemoreceptors, while blood pressure and lung stretch are detected by other receptors.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 96"},{"q":"Where are future T-lymphocytes and B-lymphocytes 'preprocessed'?","choices":["T-cells in the thymus; B-cells in the bone marrow (and fetal liver)","Both in the thymus","Both in the spleen","T-cells in the marrow; B-cells in the thymus"],"answer":0,"exp":"T-cells are preprocessed in the thymus, while B-cells are preprocessed in the fetal liver and then the bone marrow. (B), (C), and (D) misassign one or both lineages.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 40"},{"q":"Which lipoprotein returns excess cholesterol from the tissues back to the liver?","choices":["LDL","VLDL","HDL","Chylomicrons"],"answer":2,"exp":"HDL performs reverse cholesterol transport, returning excess cholesterol from tissues to the liver. LDL delivers cholesterol to cells, VLDL carries liver-made triglyceride to tissues, and chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the gut.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 139"},{"q":"The amphipathic nature of bile salts allows them to...","choices":["absorb water in the colon","chemically digest triglycerides into fatty acids","neutralize stomach acid","emulsify fats and carry lipids to the intestinal wall in micelles"],"answer":3,"exp":"Being amphipathic, bile salts act as detergents that emulsify fat and ferry lipids to the mucosa in micelles. Chemical digestion of triglyceride is lipase's role, and bile salts neither neutralize acid nor absorb colonic water.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 20"},{"q":"Under normal resting conditions, the most important minute-to-minute stimulus driving ventilation is...","choices":["Arterial PCO₂ (and the resulting H⁺)","A small fall in arterial PO₂","Blood glucose level","Body temperature"],"answer":0,"exp":"Minute-to-minute ventilation is governed most tightly by arterial PCO₂ and the H⁺ it generates. Modest drops in PO₂ have little effect until PO₂ falls substantially, and glucose and temperature are not the primary respiratory stimulus.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 92"},{"q":"How does the body mainly avoid attacking its own tissues (immunologic tolerance)?","choices":["Self-reactive T- and B-cell clones are induced to undergo apoptosis and are deleted","Self-antigens are permanently hidden from all immune cells","Antibodies against self are neutralized by complement","Helper T-cells ignore every antigen they meet"],"answer":0,"exp":"Tolerance is achieved largely by clonal deletion: clones that bind self-antigens with high affinity are driven into apoptosis (T-cells in the thymus, B-cells in the marrow). (B), (C), and (D) are not the primary mechanism.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 61"},{"q":"Glucose and galactose are absorbed across the intestinal brush border by...","choices":["Simple diffusion down their concentration gradient","Secondary active transport coupled to sodium (SGLT-1)","Endocytosis","Facilitated diffusion that does not use sodium"],"answer":1,"exp":"Glucose and galactose share the Na⁺-coupled SGLT-1 carrier, using the sodium gradient (maintained by the Na⁺–K⁺ ATPase) for secondary active transport. They are not absorbed by simple diffusion, sodium-independent facilitated diffusion, or endocytosis.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 126"},{"q":"The body's largest energy reserve is stored as...","choices":["glucose in the blood","glycogen in the liver","triglyceride in adipose tissue","protein in muscle"],"answer":2,"exp":"Adipose triglyceride is by far the largest energy reserve (~120,000 kcal in a lean adult). Liver glycogen and blood glucose hold only small amounts, and although protein is abundant, little is used as an energy store.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 3"},{"q":"Why does hemoglobin matter so much for oxygen transport?","choices":["Hemoglobin dissolves oxygen directly into plasma","Hemoglobin only carries CO₂, not O₂","Dissolved oxygen carries most of the O₂ in blood","Dissolved O₂ alone (~0.3 ml/100 ml) is far too little; Hb raises capacity to ~20 ml/100 ml"],"answer":3,"exp":"Physically dissolved O₂ is tiny (~0.3 ml/100 ml); binding to hemoglobin lifts capacity to about 20 ml/100 ml, so Hb carries the vast majority of oxygen. It does not dissolve O₂ into plasma, and it carries O₂ as well as some CO₂.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 77"},{"q":"Why is a second exposure to the same antigen met with a stronger, faster response?","choices":["The first exposure eliminated all lymphocytes, so replacements react faster","Memory B- and T-cells from the first exposure persist and respond rapidly","Complement permanently coats the antigen after the first exposure","The antigen becomes weaker over time"],"answer":1,"exp":"Memory B- and T-cells generated during the first exposure remain and mount a rapid, amplified secondary response — the basis for booster immunizations. (A), (C), and (D) do not explain the secondary response.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 48"},{"q":"The final products of carbohydrate digestion that are actually absorbed are...","choices":["Monosaccharides, mostly glucose","Disaccharides such as maltose and lactose","Short glucose polymers","Starch fragments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Carbohydrates must be reduced to monosaccharides (about 80% glucose, plus fructose and galactose) before absorption. Disaccharides, oligosaccharides, and starch fragments must first be split at the brush border.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 125"},{"q":"Leptin, released from adipose tissue, acts on the hypothalamus to...","choices":["strongly stimulate hunger","reduce appetite and food intake","slow the heart rate","raise blood glucose directly"],"answer":1,"exp":"Leptin signals the hypothalamus to suppress appetite and raise energy expenditure as fat stores grow. It does not stimulate hunger (that is ghrelin), raise glucose, or slow the heart.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 13"},{"q":"Which change shifts the O₂-hemoglobin dissociation curve to the RIGHT, favoring O₂ unloading?","choices":["Decreased temperature","Increased pH (alkalosis)","Increased CO₂ and H⁺ (lower pH)","Decreased 2,3-BPG"],"answer":2,"exp":"A right shift (lower O₂ affinity, better unloading) results from increased CO₂, increased H⁺/lower pH, higher temperature, and increased 2,3-BPG — the conditions of active tissue. Lower temperature, higher pH, and less 2,3-BPG shift the curve left.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 81"},{"q":"Once inside the enterocyte, absorbed monoglycerides and fatty acids are...","choices":["Broken down further into glycerol and carbon dioxide","Returned to the lumen","Absorbed directly into the portal vein as free fat","Reassembled into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons"],"answer":3,"exp":"Inside the enterocyte, absorbed monoglycerides and fatty acids are re-esterified into triglycerides and packaged (with apoproteins) into chylomicrons. They are not oxidized to CO₂ there, sent into portal blood as free fat, or returned to the lumen.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 132"},{"q":"Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is essential for...","choices":["collagen formation and normal connective tissue","blood clotting factor synthesis","calcium absorption","visual pigment formation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Vitamin C is required for collagen synthesis, so its deficiency (scurvy) causes connective-tissue breakdown and poor wound healing. Clotting-factor synthesis needs vitamin K, calcium handling needs vitamin D, and visual pigments need vitamin A.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 27"},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell in exchange for chloride entering, this exchange is called the...","choices":["Bohr shift","Chloride (Hamburger) shift","Sodium shift","Haldane shift"],"answer":1,"exp":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell, chloride moves in to preserve electrical neutrality — the chloride (Hamburger) shift. The Bohr and Haldane effects describe how pH/O₂ change gas affinities, and there is no “sodium shift” here.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"For defecation to occur, the internal anal sphincter relaxes and then...","choices":["The internal sphincter must contract again","The pyloric sphincter must open","The external anal sphincter must be voluntarily relaxed","Mass movements must stop"],"answer":2,"exp":"The internal anal sphincter (smooth muscle) relaxes reflexively, but defecation proceeds only if the external anal sphincter (striated, voluntary) is consciously relaxed. Re-contracting the internal sphincter, opening the pylorus, or stopping mass movements would not allow it.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 66"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate (BMR) is measured under which conditions?","choices":["Immediately after exercise","During digestion of a large meal","In a cold environment while shivering","After a 12-hour fast, at rest, in a comfortable temperature, without excitement"],"answer":3,"exp":"BMR is measured under standardized resting conditions — a 12-hour fast, physical and mental rest, and a neutral temperature — so exercise, digestion, and shivering do not inflate it. The other conditions all raise metabolic rate.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 8"},{"q":"If a person hyperventilates and “blows off” CO₂, blood pH will...","choices":["Rise (become more alkaline)","Stay exactly the same","Change only if oxygen also falls","Fall (become more acidic)"],"answer":0,"exp":"Blowing off CO₂ shifts the CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ equilibrium to the left, lowering H⁺ and raising pH (respiratory alkalosis). Losing CO₂ cannot acidify the blood or leave pH unchanged, and the effect does not depend on oxygen.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 92"},{"q":"The “oxygen debt” repaid after strenuous exercise is used to...","choices":["digest the next meal","convert lactate back to glucose and restore ATP, phosphocreatine, and oxygen stores","produce more lactate","lower body temperature"],"answer":1,"exp":"The oxygen debt is the extra O₂ consumed afterward to reconvert lactate to glucose, rebuild ATP and phosphocreatine, and reload hemoglobin/myoglobin and lung oxygen. It is not for digestion, making lactate, or cooling.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 6"},{"q":"How do core and skin temperature differ?","choices":["Both vary widely with the environment","Skin temperature is the most tightly regulated value","Core temperature stays nearly constant, while skin temperature varies with the environment","Core temperature swings more than skin temperature"],"answer":2,"exp":"Deep (core) temperature is held nearly constant (varying <1°F normally), whereas skin temperature rises and falls with the surroundings. The other options misstate which is regulated.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 2"},{"q":"When the body is cold, which response increases heat production?","choices":["Cutaneous vasodilation","Sweating","Inhibition of the sympathetic nervous system","Shivering, which can raise heat production several-fold"],"answer":3,"exp":"In the cold, shivering (plus vasoconstriction, sympathetic excitation, and thyroxine) raises heat production up to 4–5-fold. Vasodilation, sweating, and sympathetic inhibition all promote heat loss, not gain.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 14"}]},"physio-master-v3":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v3)","questions":[{"q":"Why does phosphorylating glucose to glucose-6-phosphate “trap” it inside a cell?","choices":["The charged phosphate group prevents it from crossing the membrane back out","It binds the glucose to the cell's DNA","It makes the glucose molecule much smaller","It immediately converts the glucose into fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Adding a phosphate gives glucose-6-phosphate a charge that keeps it from recrossing the membrane, trapping it for use; tissues that export glucose need glucose-6-phosphatase to remove it. Phosphorylation does not shrink glucose, bind it to DNA, or turn it into fat.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 7"},{"q":"How does the number of white blood cells compare with red blood cells in the blood?","choices":["WBCs are roughly equal in number to RBCs","WBCs are about 700-fold fewer than RBCs","WBCs outnumber RBCs about 10-fold","WBCs are about 10-fold fewer than RBCs"],"answer":1,"exp":"With ~7,000 WBC/µL versus ~5,000,000 RBC/µL, WBCs are roughly 700-fold fewer than red cells. The other options misstate this large disparity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 5"},{"q":"Segmentation contractions serve mainly to...","choices":["Rapidly propel chyme toward the colon","Trigger the defecation reflex","Keep the sphincters tonically closed","Mix chyme with digestive secretions rather than propel it"],"answer":3,"exp":"Segmentation is a mixing movement that churns chyme with secretions and improves mucosal contact, with little net propulsion. Propulsion is peristalsis, tonic closure is a sphincter role, and the defecation reflex is a separate event.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 39"},{"q":"How does the biconcave disc shape of a red blood cell aid its function?","choices":["It maximizes mitochondrial packing for ATP production","It increases the number of heme groups the cell can hold","Its redundant membrane lets the cell deform to pass through capillaries","It stops the cell from ever being trapped and destroyed in the spleen"],"answer":2,"exp":"The biconcave shape provides excess ('redundant') membrane relative to volume, so the cell can bend and squeeze through capillaries narrower than itself. (A) is wrong — mature RBCs have no mitochondria. (B) is wrong — heme number tracks hemoglobin content, not shape. (D) is wrong — aged, stiffened cells are in fact removed in the spleen.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 4"},{"q":"Which TWO factors are chiefly responsible for the lung's elastic recoil?","choices":["Elastic tissue (collagen/elastin) and alveolar surface tension","Blood flow and lymphatic drainage","Airway resistance and dead space","Surfactant and mucus production"],"answer":0,"exp":"The lung's recoil comes from its elastic fibers (collagen and elastin) plus the surface tension of the alveolar lining fluid. Resistance, dead space, blood flow, and mucus are unrelated to recoil, and surfactant actually reduces the surface-tension component.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 19"},{"q":"During intense exercise, the main reason muscle converts pyruvate to lactate is to...","choices":["produce extra ATP directly from the lactate","regenerate NAD⁺ so glycolysis can continue producing ATP","store oxygen for later use","make new glucose from pyruvate in the muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"Converting pyruvate to lactate reoxidizes NADH to NAD⁺, which glycolysis needs to keep running when oxygen or mitochondrial capacity is limiting. Lactate formation makes no extra ATP itself, stores no oxygen, and gluconeogenesis happens later in the liver, not the muscle.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 25"},{"q":"How do neutrophils and monocytes differ in their readiness to fight infection?","choices":["Neutrophils are immature; monocytes act immediately","Both remain immature until activated in the marrow","Neither can act until it reaches a lymph node","Neutrophils are mature and act immediately; monocytes mature into macrophages in the tissues"],"answer":3,"exp":"Neutrophils are mature cells that respond at once, whereas monocytes are relatively immature and become effective only after maturing into tissue macrophages. (A) reverses this, and (B) and (C) are incorrect.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 13"},{"q":"GI smooth muscle behaves as a functional syncytium because...","choices":["Each cell is individually innervated by its own motor neuron","The cells physically fuse into one giant multinucleated fiber","Gap junctions electrically couple the cells, letting action potentials spread from cell to cell","It has no electrical connections between cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Gap junctions provide low-resistance electrical connections, so a signal spreads through the muscle as a unit. The cells are not each individually innervated, do not truly fuse into one fiber, and are certainly electrically connected.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 36"},{"q":"In which oxidation state must hemoglobin's iron remain to transport oxygen?","choices":["Ferrous (Fe²⁺); ferric iron cannot carry oxygen","Ferric (Fe³⁺); ferrous iron cannot carry oxygen","Either state carries oxygen equally well","Iron is not directly involved in oxygen binding"],"answer":0,"exp":"Oxygen is carried only when iron is ferrous (Fe²⁺); oxidation to ferric (Fe³⁺) yields methemoglobin, which cannot carry oxygen. (B) reverses the states, (C) is false, and (D) is wrong because iron is the oxygen-binding site.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 27"},{"q":"How does surface tension at the air–water interface affect the alveoli?","choices":["It increases lung compliance","It holds alveoli open by pushing their walls apart","It has no effect on alveolar stability","It draws alveolar walls together and favors collapse"],"answer":3,"exp":"Surface tension pulls the water-lined alveolar walls inward, tending to collapse the alveolus and lowering compliance. It does not push walls apart or leave stability unaffected — counteracting it is exactly why surfactant is needed.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 19"},{"q":"Beta-oxidation of fatty acids breaks them down into...","choices":["acetyl-CoA units that can enter the TCA cycle","amino acids","pyruvate directly","glucose molecules"],"answer":0,"exp":"Beta-oxidation sequentially cleaves fatty acids into acetyl-CoA units that feed the TCA cycle (and ketone-body synthesis). It does not yield glucose, amino acids, or pyruvate directly.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 17"},{"q":"Which trio of properties allows neutrophils and macrophages to reach a site of infection?","choices":["Diapedesis, ameboid motion, and chemotaxis","Agglutination, precipitation, and lysis","Opsonization, margination, and apoptosis","Phagocytosis, degranulation, and mitosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"These cells cross vessel walls (diapedesis), crawl through tissue (ameboid motion), and steer toward chemical signals (chemotaxis). (B) lists antibody actions, (C) mixes unrelated processes, and (D) lists effector/reproductive functions, not modes of locomotion.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 13"},{"q":"How is inactive pepsinogen converted to active pepsin?","choices":["Bile salts activate it in the duodenum","Gastric acid converts it to pepsin, which then activates more pepsinogen (autocatalysis)","It is secreted already active","Enterokinase cleaves it at the brush border"],"answer":1,"exp":"Acid converts pepsinogen to pepsin, and the pepsin formed activates still more pepsinogen — an autocatalytic loop. Bile salts and enterokinase act on other substances, and pepsinogen is secreted inactive.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 83"},{"q":"How is oxygen bound to hemoglobin's iron?","choices":["By an irreversible covalent bond to the globin chain","By a loose, reversible bond at a coordination site of iron","By an ionic bond, so it is carried as ionic oxygen","By binding to the porphyrin ring, independent of iron"],"answer":1,"exp":"Oxygen binds loosely and reversibly to one of iron's coordination bonds and is carried as molecular (not ionic) oxygen, allowing loading in the lungs and unloading in tissues. (A) is wrong — binding is reversible; (C) is wrong — oxygen stays molecular; (D) is wrong — iron is the binding site.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 23"},{"q":"Functional residual capacity (FRC) represents the...","choices":["Maximum air inspired after a normal expiration","Maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration","Air remaining in the lungs after a normal (resting) expiration","Air moved in one normal breath"],"answer":2,"exp":"FRC (= ERV + RV) is the volume left in the lungs after a normal, resting expiration. The maximum inspired after a normal expiration is inspiratory capacity, the maximum expired after maximal inspiration is vital capacity, and one normal breath is tidal volume.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 30"},{"q":"Which is a normal function of cholesterol?","choices":["Functioning as a digestive enzyme","Acting as the body's main energy currency","Carrying oxygen in the blood","Serving as a precursor for bile acids and steroid hormones"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cholesterol is a membrane component and the precursor for bile acids and steroid hormones. ATP is the energy currency, hemoglobin carries oxygen, and cholesterol is not an enzyme.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 2"},{"q":"What is the role of Kupffer cells in the liver sinusoids?","choices":["They synthesize clotting factors","They store iron released from red cells","They produce bile for digestion","They remove nearly all bacteria from portal blood in a single pass"],"answer":3,"exp":"Kupffer cells are fixed macrophages that clear ~99% of bacteria from portal blood on a single pass. (A) and (C) are hepatocyte functions, and (B) is not the Kupffer cell's defensive role.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 23"},{"q":"Which is a physiological function of gastric acid (HCl)?","choices":["Converting pepsinogen to pepsin and providing a bacteriostatic environment","Emulsifying fats for absorption","Directly absorbing amino acids","Neutralizing chyme entering the duodenum"],"answer":0,"exp":"Gastric acid activates pepsinogen to pepsin, begins protein digestion, and limits ingested microbes (bacteriostatic). It does not emulsify fat, absorb amino acids, or neutralize duodenal chyme — that is bicarbonate's role.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 82"},{"q":"Where is the largest share of the body's iron located?","choices":["Stored as ferritin in the liver","Within hemoglobin","Within myoglobin","Bound to circulating transferrin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Most body iron (~65%) is in hemoglobin. Liver ferritin stores, myoglobin, and transferrin-bound iron each hold much smaller fractions.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 24"},{"q":"Residual volume is the air that...","choices":["Enters the lungs during a normal breath","Can be forcibly inspired beyond a normal breath","Remains in the lungs even after a maximal expiration","Is exhaled during quiet breathing"],"answer":2,"exp":"Residual volume is the air that cannot be exhaled — it remains even after a maximal expiration, keeping alveoli from collapsing. Normal-breath air is tidal volume, extra inspired air is inspiratory reserve, and quiet-breathing exhaled air is tidal volume.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 31"},{"q":"Oxidative deamination of an amino acid removes the amino group, generating...","choices":["glucose","ammonia, which must be detoxified","a ketone body","a fatty acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Deamination strips the amino group off an amino acid, releasing ammonia (which the liver converts to urea). It does not directly yield glucose, a fatty acid, or a ketone body — those may come from the remaining carbon skeleton.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 16"},{"q":"Macrophages in the red pulp of the spleen are important for...","choices":["Producing erythropoietin","Storing lymph before it enters the blood","Removing invading organisms, debris, and aged blood cells","Presenting antigens exclusively to B-cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Splenic red-pulp macrophages are richly exposed to circulating blood and remove organisms, debris, and senescent cells and platelets. Producing erythropoietin, storing lymph, and presenting antigen only to B-cells all misattribute their role.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 24"},{"q":"A major action of CCK is to...","choices":["Neutralize acid by directly secreting bicarbonate","Stimulate gastric acid secretion","Relax the gallbladder so it stores more bile","Contract the gallbladder and relax the sphincter of Oddi, delivering bile to the intestine"],"answer":3,"exp":"CCK contracts the gallbladder and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi, sending bile and pancreatic enzymes into the duodenum. It does not stimulate acid, promote bile storage, or directly secrete bicarbonate.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 14"},{"q":"How does hematopoiesis shift in response to hypoxia versus infection?","choices":["Hypoxia drives white-cell output; infection drives red-cell output","Both conditions drive red-cell production equally","Hypoxia drives red-cell production; infection drives white-cell production","Neither condition changes hematopoiesis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hematopoiesis adapts: hypoxia stimulates erythropoiesis (more red cells for oxygen delivery), while infection/inflammation stimulates white-cell production. (A) reverses these; (B) and (D) ignore the selective response.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 9"},{"q":"By Laplace's law (P = 2T/r), at equal surface tension a SMALLER alveolus...","choices":["Requires a larger pressure to keep from collapsing","Is inherently more stable than a large one","Requires a smaller pressure to keep from collapsing","Has no collapse tendency at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"With P = 2T/r, a smaller radius demands a higher pressure to stay open, so small alveoli are inherently less stable — which is why surfactant is essential. The other options reverse or ignore this radius relationship.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 22"},{"q":"The urea cycle, which occurs essentially only in the liver, serves to...","choices":["synthesize new proteins","convert toxic ammonia into urea for excretion","produce ATP directly","store nitrogen as glycogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"The urea cycle (ornithine–citrulline–arginine) packages toxic ammonia into urea for renal excretion; excess ammonia is dangerous partly because it depletes α-ketoglutarate and stalls the TCA cycle. It does not build proteins, make ATP directly, or store nitrogen as glycogen.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 16"},{"q":"Why are the tonsils and adenoids positioned in the throat and pharynx?","choices":["To filter aged red cells from the blood","To intercept antigens entering from the upper respiratory tract","To store mature T-cells before release","To produce lymph fluid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Lymphoid tissue is placed strategically; tonsils and adenoids intercept antigens from the upper respiratory tract. (A), (C), and (D) are not their function.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 39"},{"q":"Secretin is called “nature's antacid” because, in response to duodenal acid, it...","choices":["Directly buffers acid within the stomach","Stimulates more gastrin release","Stimulates pancreatic and biliary bicarbonate secretion and inhibits gastric acid","Increases gastric emptying of acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Secretin, released by duodenal acid, drives bicarbonate secretion from pancreas and bile ducts and inhibits gastric acid and gastrin. It does not buffer acid directly in the stomach, raise gastrin, or speed acid emptying.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 16"},{"q":"Why do individuals without functioning kidneys typically become anemic?","choices":["The liver overproduces EPO and suppresses the marrow","Residual EPO (mostly hepatic) is too little for normal red-cell production","The bone marrow is destroyed without a renal signal","Iron can no longer be absorbed without a kidney hormone"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney makes ~90% of EPO; the ~10% residual (mainly liver) is insufficient, so hematocrit falls toward 23–25%. (A) is wrong — hepatic EPO is too low, not excessive; (C) is wrong — the marrow isn't destroyed; (D) misstates iron absorption.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 15"},{"q":"Without surfactant, what would happen to a small alveolus connected to a larger one?","choices":["Surface tension would disappear","The large alveolus would empty into the small one","Both would remain perfectly stable","The small alveolus would tend to collapse and empty into the larger one"],"answer":3,"exp":"Without surfactant, the higher collapse pressure of the small alveolus (Laplace) drives its air into the larger, lower-pressure alveolus — atelectasis. The reverse flow, perfect stability, and disappearance of surface tension are all incorrect.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 23"},{"q":"Kupffer cells in the liver sinusoids function to...","choices":["remove bacteria and particulate matter (about 99% of gut bacteria) from portal blood","synthesize bile salts","store vitamin B12","produce erythropoietin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Kupffer cells are sinusoidal macrophages that clear ~99% of bacteria arriving from the gut via the portal blood. Bile-salt synthesis is a hepatocyte function, B12 storage is separate, and erythropoietin is chiefly renal.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 7"},{"q":"How is an ingested microbe digested inside a phagocyte?","choices":["The phagosome fuses with a lysosome, exposing the microbe to digestive enzymes","The microbe is expelled and lysed outside the cell","Antibodies inside the cell dissolve the microbe","The nucleus engulfs and degrades the microbe"],"answer":0,"exp":"The phagosome fuses with a lysosome to form a phagolysosome, where proteolytic enzymes (and lipases in macrophages) digest the microbe. (B), (C), and (D) do not describe intracellular digestion.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 16"},{"q":"Pepsin works best under what conditions, and what happens as pH rises?","choices":["It works best at alkaline pH and is inactivated by acid","It is optimally active at acidic pH (~1.8–3.5) and is inactivated as pH rises toward neutral","It is equally active across all pH values","It requires bile salts to function"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pepsin is optimally active in the acidic stomach (pH ~1.8–3.5) and loses activity as pH climbs toward neutral (irreversibly above pH 7–8). It is not alkaline-optimal, pH-independent, or bile-dependent.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 83"},{"q":"Thromboxane A2 released from platelets is especially important for which action?","choices":["Dissolving the fibrin clot once healing begins","Directly activating the intrinsic pathway","Inhibiting platelet aggregation to limit the clot","Constricting smaller blood vessels"],"answer":3,"exp":"Thromboxane A2 from platelets is particularly important for constricting smaller vessels. (A) describes fibrinolysis, (B) is unrelated to TXA2, and (C) is the opposite — TXA2 promotes, not inhibits, platelet activation.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 30"},{"q":"Why is the respiratory (alveolar) membrane extremely thin (~0.2 µm)?","choices":["To increase surface tension","To slow gas diffusion for regulation","To minimize diffusion distance and speed gas exchange","To store surfactant"],"answer":2,"exp":"At ~0.2 µm thick, the membrane keeps the diffusion distance tiny, allowing rapid gas exchange (Fick's law favors short distances). It is not there to raise surface tension, slow diffusion, or store surfactant.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 60"},{"q":"In hepatic bilirubin handling, which step is rate-limiting?","choices":["Uptake of free bilirubin into the hepatocyte","Conjugation with glucuronic acid","Binding of bilirubin to albumin in the blood","Excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile"],"answer":3,"exp":"Of the hepatic steps — uptake, conjugation with glucuronic acid, and excretion — excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile is rate-limiting. Albumin binding happens in the blood before uptake, not within the hepatocyte.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 14"},{"q":"How does fibrinogen leaking from damaged capillaries help contain an infection?","choices":["It clots in the tissue, walling off the area and limiting bacterial spread","It directly kills bacteria by phagocytosis","It dissolves bacterial cell walls","It attracts red cells to the injury"],"answer":0,"exp":"Leaked fibrinogen clots in the interstitium, minimizing fluid exchange and 'walling off' the area so bacteria spread less. (B), (C), and (D) are not fibrinogen's role.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 26"},{"q":"What is the role of bile salts in fat digestion?","choices":["They chemically break triglycerides into fatty acids","They emulsify large fat droplets into smaller ones, increasing the surface area for lipase","They transport fat directly into the blood","They neutralize stomach acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Bile salts are emulsifiers: they disperse large fat globules into fine droplets, expanding the surface on which pancreatic lipase acts. The chemical breakdown of triglycerides is lipase's job, and bile salts neither carry fat into blood nor neutralize acid.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 137"},{"q":"What does prothrombin activator do?","choices":["It converts fibrinogen directly into fibrin","It converts prothrombin to thrombin in the presence of calcium","It cross-links adjacent fibrin fibers","It activates plasminogen to plasmin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Prothrombin activator, with Ca²⁺, converts prothrombin to thrombin. (A) is thrombin's downstream action, (C) is factor XIII's role, and (D) belongs to tissue plasminogen activator in fibrinolysis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 40"},{"q":"If the respiratory membrane becomes thickened, gas exchange is impaired because...","choices":["The diffusion distance increases, slowing gas transfer","Surface area increases too much","The partial pressure gradient reverses","The solubility of the gases changes"],"answer":0,"exp":"A thicker membrane lengthens the path a gas must diffuse, and by Fick's law greater distance slows transfer (e.g., in edema or fibrosis). Thickening does not add useful surface area, reverse the gradient, or change gas solubility.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 62"},{"q":"A respiratory quotient (RQ) of about 1.0 indicates the body is burning mainly...","choices":["fat","protein","carbohydrate","a mix favoring fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"An RQ (CO₂ produced ÷ O₂ consumed) near 1.0 indicates carbohydrate oxidation; pure fat gives ~0.7 and protein ~0.8, with a mixed diet averaging ~0.8.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 6"},{"q":"What is the main role of the complement system?","choices":["To produce antibodies specific to each antigen","To enhance antibody and phagocyte actions and attack pathogen membranes","To present antigens to helper T-cells","To generate memory cells for future exposures"],"answer":1,"exp":"Complement 'complements' antibodies and phagocytes — promoting clearance, driving inflammation, and attacking pathogen membranes. (A) is a B-cell role, (C) is antigen presentation, and (D) is a memory-cell function.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 53"},{"q":"The delivery of stored bile into the small intestine after a fatty meal is triggered mainly by...","choices":["Secretin, which contracts the gallbladder","Gastrin, which relaxes the sphincter of Oddi","Motilin, during fasting","CCK, which contracts the gallbladder"],"answer":3,"exp":"A fatty or protein-rich meal releases CCK, which contracts the gallbladder and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi to deliver bile. Secretin drives bicarbonate, gastrin governs acid, and motilin acts during fasting.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 15"},{"q":"What is the function of factor XIII (fibrin-stabilizing factor)?","choices":["It converts prothrombin to thrombin","It initiates the extrinsic pathway","It covalently cross-links fibrin, strengthening the clot","It dissolves the clot after healing"],"answer":2,"exp":"Factor XIII, activated by thrombin, covalently cross-links fibrin monomers and fibers, so the clot is weak without it. (A) is prothrombin activator's role, (B) is tissue factor's role, and (D) describes plasmin.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 40"},{"q":"The peripheral chemoreceptors of the carotid and aortic bodies are especially important for sensing...","choices":["Low arterial oxygen (PO₂)","Airway resistance","Pleural pressure","Lung compliance"],"answer":0,"exp":"The carotid and aortic bodies are the main sensors of low arterial PO₂ (they also respond to CO₂/H⁺). Compliance, resistance, and pleural pressure are mechanical properties, not what these chemoreceptors detect.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 97"},{"q":"Which vitamins are stored in the body to a significant extent?","choices":["Water-soluble vitamins such as C and the B group","Fat-soluble vitamins such as A and D","No vitamins are stored at all","Only vitamin C is stored"],"answer":1,"exp":"Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) can be stored, notably A and D in the liver, whereas water-soluble vitamins (C and most Bs) are not stored significantly and must be supplied regularly.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 17"},{"q":"How do cytotoxic (killer) T-cells destroy their targets?","choices":["By engulfing and digesting them through phagocytosis","By walling the cell off with fibrin","By producing large amounts of circulating antibody","By secreting perforins that punch holes and delivering cytotoxic substances"],"answer":3,"exp":"Killer T-cells bind a target bearing its antigen, secrete pore-forming perforins, and release cytotoxic substances directly into the cell. Engulfing/digesting is a phagocyte's method, walling off with fibrin is inflammation, and producing circulating antibody is humoral immunity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 59"},{"q":"In addition to acting on the pancreas, secretin stimulates the liver/biliary system to secrete...","choices":["Digestive enzymes","Intrinsic factor","Bicarbonate-rich fluid","Larger amounts of bile salts"],"answer":2,"exp":"Secretin stimulates the liver and bile ducts (and pancreas) to add bicarbonate-rich fluid that helps neutralize acid. It does not stimulate enzyme, intrinsic-factor, or bile-salt output.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 16"},{"q":"Why is the extrinsic pathway able to produce a clot faster than the intrinsic pathway?","choices":["It requires many more sequential steps","It does not require calcium","It has fewer steps and can clot in under about 15 seconds","It bypasses factor X entirely"],"answer":2,"exp":"The extrinsic pathway is 'explosive,' clotting in as little as ~15 seconds because it has fewer steps; the intrinsic pathway is slower (1–6 minutes). (A) is the opposite, (B) is false (Ca²⁺ is still needed), and (D) is wrong — both pathways activate factor X.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 47"},{"q":"Increased arterial PCO₂ stimulates the central chemoreceptors indirectly by...","choices":["Binding directly to oxygen sensors","Constricting the airways","Reducing blood flow to the medulla","Generating H⁺ after CO₂ crosses into the brain/CSF"],"answer":3,"exp":"CO₂ crosses into the brain/CSF, forms carbonic acid, and releases H⁺; the central chemoreceptors actually respond to that H⁺. They are not oxygen sensors, and CO₂ does not drive breathing by cutting medullary blood flow or narrowing airways.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 91"},{"q":"Which nutrient produces the greatest thermic effect (rise in metabolic rate during digestion)?","choices":["Protein (up to ~30%)","Fat (~4%)","Carbohydrate (~4%)","All are equal"],"answer":0,"exp":"Protein has by far the largest thermic effect of food, raising metabolic rate up to ~30%, versus about 4% for carbohydrate and fat.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 10"},{"q":"The two branches of acquired immunity are...","choices":["Humoral (B-cell/antibody) immunity and cell-mediated (T-cell) immunity","Phagocytosis and complement activation","Inflammation and fever","Skin barriers and gastric acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Acquired immunity comprises humoral immunity (circulating antibodies from B-cells) and cell-mediated immunity (activated T-cells). (B) and (D) are innate mechanisms, and (C) lists non-specific responses.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 37"},{"q":"Why are pancreatic proteolytic enzymes secreted as inactive precursors (zymogens)?","choices":["Because they are only active in the stomach","To prevent the pancreas from digesting itself","Because acid is required to synthesize them","To allow them to be absorbed before activation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Proteolytic enzymes are stored and secreted as inactive zymogens (with a trypsin inhibitor present) so they cannot digest the pancreas that makes them. They are not stomach-specific, do not require acid for synthesis, and are not absorbed.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 103"},{"q":"What is the role of antithrombin III in controlling coagulation?","choices":["It combines with and inactivates thrombin not bound to fibrin","It converts prothrombin into thrombin","It cross-links fibrin fibers","It activates the extrinsic pathway"],"answer":0,"exp":"Antithrombin III binds and inactivates the thrombin not already trapped on fibrin, limiting clot spread. (B), (C), and (D) describe pro-coagulant steps — the opposite of antithrombin III's inhibitory role.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 49"},{"q":"“Percent saturation” of hemoglobin refers to...","choices":["The absolute amount of O₂ in ml per 100 ml blood","The driving pressure for O₂ diffusion","The fraction of hemoglobin binding sites occupied by O₂","The number of red cells per microliter"],"answer":2,"exp":"Percent saturation is the proportion of hemoglobin binding sites carrying O₂ (a unitless fraction). The absolute amount is “content,” the driving pressure is partial pressure, and red-cell count is a separate measure.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 76"},{"q":"Which factor increases the metabolic rate?","choices":["Sleep","Decreased muscle mass","A warm, resting state after fasting","Increased thyroid hormone"],"answer":3,"exp":"Thyroid hormone — like exercise, greater lean mass, sympathetic activity, fever, and cold — raises metabolic rate. Sleep, less muscle, and a warm resting fasted state lower it.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 9"},{"q":"How can the body generate millions of distinct antibodies from only a few thousand relevant genes?","choices":["Each antibody is coded by its own dedicated gene","Antibodies mutate randomly after every infection","Complement rearranges the antibodies in plasma","Hundreds of gene 'cassettes' (segments) recombine in many permutations"],"answer":3,"exp":"Diversity arises because hundreds of gene segments (cassettes) combine in vast numbers of permutations, yielding millions of specificities. (A) contradicts the segment model, and (B) and (C) are not the mechanism described.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 44"},{"q":"Pancreatic acinar cells store a trypsin inhibitor in order to...","choices":["Block any trypsin that forms prematurely inside the acinar cells and ducts","Speed up enzyme activation within the pancreas","Neutralize bicarbonate","Activate chymotrypsin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Trypsin inhibitor neutralizes small amounts of trypsin that activate prematurely within acini and ducts, preventing autodigestion; overwhelming it contributes to pancreatitis. It does not accelerate activation, neutralize bicarbonate, or activate chymotrypsin.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 105"},{"q":"The flat upper plateau of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve means that...","choices":["Small drops in PO₂ at high levels cause large drops in saturation","Hemoglobin stays highly saturated across a wide range of higher PO₂ values","Hemoglobin cannot bind oxygen in the lungs","Saturation and PO₂ are unrelated"],"answer":1,"exp":"On the flat plateau, hemoglobin stays nearly fully saturated even as PO₂ varies over a wide high range — protecting O₂ loading if alveolar PO₂ dips. That is the opposite of large saturation swings, and saturation clearly depends on PO₂.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 80"},{"q":"The body's main temperature-control center is located in the...","choices":["cerebellum","medulla's respiratory center","hypothalamus (preoptic/anterior area)","spinal cord alone"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hypothalamus, especially the preoptic/anterior area with its heat- and cold-sensitive neurons, is the body's thermostat. The cerebellum, medullary respiratory center, and spinal cord are not the control center.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 5"},{"q":"How does passive immunity differ from active immunity?","choices":["It is generated by the person's own lymphocytes after infection","It produces lifelong protection through memory cells","It involves transferring preformed antibodies and is relatively short-lived","It relies on innate barriers such as skin and acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Passive immunity comes from infused preformed antibodies (or activated cells) from an immune individual and lasts only ~2–3 weeks. (A) and (B) describe active immunity, and (D) describes innate immunity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 63"},{"q":"Pancreatic bicarbonate secretion is important because it...","choices":["Activates trypsinogen directly","Emulsifies dietary fat","Stimulates gastric acid secretion","Neutralizes acidic chyme, creating the pH (~7–8) needed for pancreatic enzymes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Pancreatic bicarbonate neutralizes acid entering the duodenum, establishing the near-neutral pH at which pancreatic enzymes work best. It does not activate trypsinogen (enterokinase does), emulsify fat (bile does), or stimulate gastric acid.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 106"},{"q":"Which enzyme in red cells speeds the conversion of CO₂ and water to carbonic acid?","choices":["Carbonic anhydrase","Carboxypeptidase","Lactate dehydrogenase","ATP synthase"],"answer":0,"exp":"Carbonic anhydrase in red cells rapidly converts CO₂ + H₂O to carbonic acid, which dissociates to H⁺ and bicarbonate. The other enzymes act on peptides, lactate, and ATP production respectively, not on CO₂ hydration.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"Sweat glands are stimulated to secrete by...","choices":["parasympathetic fibers releasing norepinephrine","sympathetic cholinergic fibers releasing acetylcholine","the somatic motor system","circulating insulin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Sweating is driven by the anterior hypothalamus via sympathetic fibers that are cholinergic — they release acetylcholine even though they travel in sympathetic nerves. It is not parasympathetic, somatic, or insulin-mediated.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 8"},{"q":"After chylomicrons deliver most of their triglyceride to tissues, the remnants are...","choices":["Excreted in bile unchanged","Reabsorbed in the ileum","Taken up (cleared) by the liver","Converted back into bile salts in the gut"],"answer":2,"exp":"After lipoprotein lipase strips triglyceride from chylomicrons in the tissues, the cholesterol-rich remnants are cleared by the liver. They are not excreted intact in bile, reabsorbed in the ileum, or turned into bile salts in the gut.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 138"},{"q":"About 23% of CO₂ is transported...","choices":["Dissolved in plasma","Inside white blood cells","As free carbonic acid","Bound to hemoglobin (carbaminohemoglobin)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Roughly 23% of CO₂ is carried bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin. Only ~7% is dissolved, most is bicarbonate, and CO₂ is not stored as free carbonic acid or within white cells.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"How is fructose absorbed, in contrast to glucose?","choices":["By facilitated diffusion (GLUT-5), needing no energy or sodium","By primary active transport using ATP directly","By secondary active transport with sodium","By endocytosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Fructose crosses via GLUT-5 facilitated diffusion, moving down its gradient without energy or sodium coupling — unlike glucose and galactose. It is not actively transported or taken up by endocytosis.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 126"},{"q":"How does rising blood CO₂ lower blood pH?","choices":["CO₂ directly binds and removes bicarbonate","CO₂ combines with water to form carbonic acid, which releases H⁺","CO₂ destroys hemoglobin's buffering ability","CO₂ has no relationship to pH"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dissolved CO₂ forms carbonic acid, which dissociates into H⁺ and bicarbonate, so rising CO₂ raises H⁺ and lowers pH. CO₂ does not remove bicarbonate directly or destroy hemoglobin buffering, and it is tightly linked to pH.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"The intrinsic defecation reflex is initiated when...","choices":["The internal anal sphincter contracts","The stomach empties completely","Feces enter and distend the rectum, triggering myenteric-plexus signals","Bile enters the colon"],"answer":2,"exp":"Rectal distension by feces triggers the intrinsic (ENS-mediated) reflex, which contracts the colon/rectum and relaxes the internal anal sphincter. Gastric emptying, sphincter contraction, and bile entering the colon do not initiate it.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 66"},{"q":"Tissue PO₂ is determined by the balance between...","choices":["Surfactant production and surface tension","Alveolar ventilation and dead space","Pleural pressure and compliance","The rate of blood flow (O₂ delivery) and the rate of O₂ consumption"],"answer":3,"exp":"Tissue PO₂ reflects the balance between O₂ delivered by blood flow and O₂ used by the cells — more flow raises it, more consumption lowers it. Surfactant, ventilation/dead space, and pleural mechanics govern the lung, not tissue PO₂.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 72"}]},"physio-master-v4":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v4)","questions":[{"q":"Red blood cells are rich in carbonic anhydrase. Why is this enzyme important for gas transport?","choices":["It keeps hemoglobin's iron in the ferric state so it can bind oxygen","It lets most CO₂ be carried in the blood as bicarbonate","It allows the red cell to generate ATP without mitochondria","It buffers the plasma directly by producing lactic acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Carbonic anhydrase catalyzes CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃, which dissociates so most CO₂ travels as bicarbonate (also the body's major extracellular buffer). (A) is wrong — oxygen-binding iron must stay ferrous, and the enzyme doesn't set iron's state. (C) is wrong — RBC ATP comes from glycolytic enzymes. (D) is wrong — the enzyme handles CO₂/bicarbonate, not lactic acid.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 3"},{"q":"Where do granulocytes and monocytes primarily develop, and what happens to most of them before they are needed?","choices":["In lymph nodes; they circulate in blood immediately","In the thymus; they are stored in the spleen","In bone marrow; most are stored there until needed peripherally","In the liver; they mature within peripheral tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Granulocytes and monocytes develop in the bone marrow, where about three times as many are stored as circulate, ready for release. (A), (B), and (D) misplace both the developmental site and the storage pool.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 11"},{"q":"What gives platelets their contractile ability, used later in clot retraction?","choices":["Actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin","Osmotic swelling followed by collapse","Beating of surface cilia","ATP-powered flagellar movement"],"answer":0,"exp":"Platelets contain actin, myosin, and thrombosthenin (actomyosin), giving them true contractile capability. (B), (C), and (D) describe mechanisms platelets do not use — there is no ciliary, flagellar, or purely osmotic contraction.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 32"},{"q":"After entering the tissues, monocytes become macrophages that typically...","choices":["Die within a few hours","Can survive and function for months or longer","Return to the blood as neutrophils","Convert into lymphocytes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Tissue macrophages are long-lived, surviving months or longer. (A) understates their lifespan, and (C) and (D) describe conversions that do not occur — macrophages do not revert to neutrophils or become lymphocytes.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 12"},{"q":"What is the chain composition of the predominant adult hemoglobin (hemoglobin A)?","choices":["Four alpha chains","Two alpha and two gamma chains","Two alpha and two beta chains","Two beta and two delta chains"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hemoglobin A, the main adult form, has two alpha and two beta chains. (B) describes fetal-type pairing, and (A) and (D) are combinations not found in normal adult hemoglobin A.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 21"},{"q":"Where do most lymphocytes develop?","choices":["Peripheral lymphoid organs such as the thymus, spleen, and lymph nodes","Exclusively within the red bone marrow","In the liver sinusoids throughout adult life","Within the circulating blood plasma"],"answer":0,"exp":"Lymphocytes develop mostly in peripheral lymphoid organs (thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymph nodes, Peyer's patches). (B) describes granulocyte/monocyte development, and (C) and (D) are not sites of lymphocyte development.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 11"},{"q":"Platelets enter the circulation through which process?","choices":["Budding directly from vascular endothelial cells","Fragmentation of megakaryocytes","Division of circulating monocytes","Final maturation of reticulocytes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Platelets are cell fragments released by megakaryocytes in the bone marrow. (A), (C), and (D) name unrelated cells — endothelium, monocytes, and reticulocytes (which mature into red cells) do not produce platelets.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 31"},{"q":"Which specialized macrophages handle inhaled particles and microorganisms?","choices":["Kupffer cells","Histiocytes","Alveolar macrophages","Splenic macrophages"],"answer":2,"exp":"Alveolar macrophages digest or entrap particles and microbes reaching the lungs. Kupffer cells guard portal blood in the liver, histiocytes are skin/subcutaneous macrophages, and splenic macrophages screen circulating blood.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 21"},{"q":"Why is methemoglobin unable to support oxygen transport?","choices":["It binds oxygen so tightly it never releases it","Its iron is in the ferric state and cannot carry oxygen","It has lost the globin chains needed for cooperativity","It precipitates and ruptures the red cell membrane"],"answer":1,"exp":"Methemoglobin contains ferric (Fe³⁺) iron, which cannot bind and transport oxygen. (A) is wrong — the problem is failure to carry O₂, not to release it. (C) is wrong — globin chains are intact. (D) describes a different process.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 27"},{"q":"The monocyte-macrophage (reticuloendothelial) system mainly functions to...","choices":["Remove dead or abnormal cells, tissues, and foreign substances","Transport oxygen to peripheral tissues","Produce circulating antibodies","Generate clotting factors in the liver"],"answer":0,"exp":"This distributed system of macrophages clears dead/abnormal cells and foreign material throughout the body. (B) is a red-cell role, (C) is a B-cell/plasma-cell role, and (D) is a hepatocyte role.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 20"},{"q":"Why do differences among globin chain types matter functionally?","choices":["They change how many iron atoms each molecule contains","They determine the red cell's lifespan","They set the activity of carbonic anhydrase","They alter the oxygen-binding affinity of hemoglobin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Different globin chains give hemoglobin variants different oxygen-binding affinities. (A) is wrong — each chain still carries one heme/iron. (B) and (C) are unrelated to globin chain identity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 22"},{"q":"Which set of changes characterizes acute inflammation?","choices":["Vasoconstriction and decreased capillary permeability","Reduced blood flow and suppressed immunity","Vasodilation, increased capillary permeability, and leukocyte accumulation","Increased red-cell production and a fall in white-cell count"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inflammation features vasodilation with increased blood flow, greater capillary permeability, and accumulation of granulocytes and monocytes. Vasoconstriction with reduced permeability is the opposite, and the reduced-flow/suppression and raised-RBC options misdescribe the response.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 25"},{"q":"In what form is iron transported through the blood plasma?","choices":["Bound to transferrin","Enclosed within ferritin","As free ionic iron","Within hemosiderin granules"],"answer":0,"exp":"Plasma iron is carried loosely bound to transferrin, which can release it to any tissue cell. (B) and (D) are intracellular storage forms, and (C) is wrong — free ionic iron is not the normal transport form.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 25"},{"q":"A distinctive feature of lymphocytes, compared with granulocytes, is that they...","choices":["Live only a few hours in the circulation","Cannot leave the bloodstream","Are unable to enter lymph nodes","Continuously recirculate between blood and lymph and are long-lived"],"answer":3,"exp":"Lymphocytes continuously recirculate blood → lymph → nodes → blood and can live for weeks, months, or longer. (A) describes granulocytes, and (B) and (C) contradict lymphocyte recirculation.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 12"},{"q":"What is the main intracellular storage form of iron?","choices":["Transferrin","Ceruloplasmin","Ferritin, formed when iron combines with apoferritin","Apotransferrin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inside cells, iron combines with apoferritin to form ferritin, the principal storage form. (A) and (D) are transport-related proteins, and (B) is a copper-carrying protein, not an iron store.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 25"},{"q":"What triggers mast cells and basophils to degranulate?","choices":["Direct phagocytosis of a bacterium","Binding of complement C3 to the cell","Contact with a rough particle surface","Cross-linking of surface-bound IgE by its specific antigen"],"answer":3,"exp":"When antigen cross-links IgE already bound to their surface receptors, mast cells and basophils degranulate, releasing histamine, heparin, and other mediators. (A), (B), and (C) do not trigger this release.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 34"},{"q":"From the last month of gestation through adulthood, where does blood cell production mainly occur?","choices":["Bone marrow","The yolk sac","The liver and spleen","The lymph nodes"],"answer":0,"exp":"By late gestation and throughout adult life, the bone marrow is the primary site of hematopoiesis. The yolk sac (earliest weeks) and liver/spleen (mid-gestation) are earlier sites, and lymph nodes are not the main producers.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 7"},{"q":"Eosinophils are especially important in defense against...","choices":["Intracellular viruses","Encapsulated bacteria","Parasites such as helminths (worms)","Fungal spores circulating in the blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Eosinophils attach to parasites and release toxic substances (including major basic protein) that kill them. They are weak phagocytes, so (A), (B), and (D) are not their specialty.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 33"},{"q":"Where is the majority of erythropoietin produced?","choices":["The bone marrow","The liver","The spleen","The kidney"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 90% of erythropoietin is made in the kidney (roughly 10% in the liver). The bone marrow is EPO's target, not its main source, and the spleen is not a major producer.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 14"},{"q":"According to clonal selection, what happens when an antigen enters the body?","choices":["Every lymphocyte in the body responds to it equally","All lymphocytes change their receptors to match it","It activates the pre-existing clone whose receptors are complementary, which then proliferates","It suppresses lymphocyte division to conserve energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"An antigen selects the pre-existing clone bearing complementary receptors, which then multiplies and secretes matching antibodies. (A) and (B) contradict clonal specificity, and (D) is the opposite of what occurs.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 43"},{"q":"What is the primary physiological stimulus for erythropoietin release?","choices":["Hypoxia","A rise in blood pH","High iron stores","Increased blood viscosity"],"answer":0,"exp":"Low tissue oxygen (hypoxia) is the key trigger for EPO release. (B), (C), and (D) do not drive EPO; excessive viscosity is a consequence the system tries to avoid, not a stimulus.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 14"},{"q":"Which part of an antibody molecule binds to its specific antigen?","choices":["The constant portion of the heavy chains","The disulfide bonds linking the chains","The complement-binding region","The variable portion"],"answer":3,"exp":"The variable portion differs for each antibody and forms the antigen-binding site. The constant portion governs properties like diffusivity and complement binding, disulfide bonds hold the chains together, and the complement region is separate from antigen binding.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 49"},{"q":"Which molecule links low oxygen to increased erythropoietin gene transcription?","choices":["Thrombomodulin","Hypoxia-inducible factor-1 (HIF-1)","Carbonic anhydrase","Antithrombin III"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hypoxia raises HIF-1, which binds hypoxia-response elements in the EPO promoter to increase EPO transcription. (A) and (D) are coagulation regulators, and (C) is a CO₂-handling enzyme — none control EPO transcription.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 14"},{"q":"Which cells provide humoral immunity, and how?","choices":["Cytotoxic T-cells, by lysing infected cells","Macrophages, by phagocytizing antigens","Natural killer cells, by non-specific killing","B-lymphocytes, by forming antibodies"],"answer":3,"exp":"Humoral ('circulating') immunity comes from B-lymphocytes that produce antibodies, while T-cells provide cell-mediated immunity. (A) is cell-mediated, and (B) and (C) are effector mechanisms not classed as humoral immunity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 40"},{"q":"Why do platelets stick to injured vessel areas but not to normal, intact endothelium?","choices":["Intact endothelium constantly releases thromboxane A2","Platelets can bind only to nucleated cells","Their surface glycoproteins repel intact endothelium but adhere to exposed collagen","Intact endothelium lacks tissue factor"],"answer":2,"exp":"Platelet surface glycoproteins repel normal intact endothelium yet adhere to injured endothelium and exposed collagen. (A) and (D) misattribute the selectivity, and (B) is false — platelets bind collagen and matrix, not nucleated cells specifically.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 33"},{"q":"Active immunity is produced by...","choices":["Infusing preformed antibodies from an immune donor","Exposure to killed organisms, their products, or attenuated organisms","Blocking complement activation","Removing the thymus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Active immunity develops when the body is exposed to killed organisms/toxoids or attenuated organisms and mounts its own response. (A) describes passive immunity, and (C) and (D) would impair, not create, immunity.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 63"},{"q":"The relationship between tissue oxygenation, EPO, and red cell mass is an example of what kind of control?","choices":["A positive feedback loop","Feed-forward amplification","An open-loop system","A negative feedback loop"],"answer":3,"exp":"More red cells improve oxygenation, which then reduces the hypoxic drive for EPO — classic negative feedback. (A) would be self-amplifying (the opposite), and (B)/(C) do not describe this self-correcting system.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 13"},{"q":"As a later line of defense, how does the bone marrow respond to a sustained infection?","choices":["It shuts down white-cell production to conserve resources","It increases granulocyte and monocyte production many-fold","It releases mature lymphocytes within minutes","It converts red cells into white cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The marrow can raise neutrophil and monocyte output 20–50-fold and sustain it for months, with the first new cells released in 3–4 days. (A) is the opposite, and (C) and (D) are physiologically wrong.","cite":"Blood and Immunology, Slide 31"},{"q":"How does thrombin act on fibrinogen?","choices":["It cleaves small peptides from fibrinogen, forming fibrin monomers that polymerize","It directly cross-links fibrinogen into a stable mesh","It converts fibrinogen back into prothrombin","It degrades fibrinogen into soluble fragments"],"answer":0,"exp":"Thrombin removes small peptides from fibrinogen to create fibrin monomers, which polymerize into fibrin fibers. (B) is factor XIII's cross-linking step, (C) reverses the pathway, and (D) describes plasmin's degradative action.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 40"},{"q":"During exercise, more oxygen is released to active muscle largely because...","choices":["Blood flow to muscle stops","Hemoglobin loses its ability to bind oxygen","Tissue PO₂ falls and local acidity/CO₂ promote O₂ unloading","Surfactant increases O₂ release"],"answer":2,"exp":"In exercising muscle, PO₂ drops and the higher CO₂/H⁺ and temperature right-shift the curve (Bohr effect), so hemoglobin releases far more O₂. Hemoglobin doesn't lose function, muscle blood flow rises rather than stops, and surfactant has no role in tissue O₂ release.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 80"},{"q":"What is the role of von Willebrand factor in forming the platelet plug?","choices":["It converts prothrombin into thrombin","It helps platelets adhere to exposed collagen","It cross-links fibrin monomers into a mesh","It inhibits platelets to keep the plug small"],"answer":1,"exp":"Von Willebrand factor bridges platelets to collagen, facilitating adhesion. (A) is the job of prothrombin activator, (C) is factor XIII's role, and (D) is the opposite of vWF's pro-adhesive function.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 34"},{"q":"What happens to pleural (intrapleural) pressure during inspiration?","choices":["It becomes more negative (about –5 to –8 cm H₂O)","It stays constant throughout the breath","It becomes positive","It rises toward zero"],"answer":0,"exp":"As the chest expands, intrapleural pressure falls further below atmospheric (roughly –5 to –8 cm H₂O), pulling the lungs open. It does not turn positive or move toward zero during inspiration — those occur in expiration — and it clearly changes across the breath.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 14"},{"q":"What initiates the extrinsic pathway of coagulation?","choices":["Blood contacting collagen or a glass surface","Activation of factor XII","Thrombin cleaving fibrinogen","Release of tissue factor from traumatized tissue"],"answer":3,"exp":"The extrinsic pathway begins when injured tissue releases tissue factor (factor III). (A) and (B) start the intrinsic pathway, and (C) is a later, common-pathway event.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 45"},{"q":"Although CO₂ and O₂ have similar molecular weights, CO₂ diffuses much faster mainly because...","choices":["CO₂ is about 20 times more soluble than O₂","CO₂ has a much larger partial pressure gradient","CO₂ is a much smaller molecule","O₂ cannot cross the membrane at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"CO₂'s roughly 20-fold greater solubility lets it diffuse much faster despite a smaller partial pressure gradient. Its gradient is actually smaller, its molecular weight is similar (not smaller), and O₂ obviously does cross the membrane.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 61"},{"q":"In the extrinsic pathway, tissue factor forms a complex that activates which clotting factor?","choices":["Factor XII","Factor VII (converting it to VIIa)","Factor IX","Factor XIII"],"answer":1,"exp":"Tissue factor acts as a high-affinity receptor for factor VII, activating it to VIIa; the TF–VIIa complex then activates factor X. (A) and (C) belong to the intrinsic pathway, and (D) is the fibrin-stabilizing factor.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 45"},{"q":"The respiratory system helps regulate blood pH primarily by...","choices":["Adjusting how much CO₂ is exhaled","Producing bicarbonate in the alveoli","Filtering H⁺ out of the blood","Changing hemoglobin concentration"],"answer":0,"exp":"By changing ventilation, the lungs control how much CO₂ is exhaled, shifting the carbonic-acid equilibrium and adjusting pH within minutes. The alveoli don't make bicarbonate or filter H⁺ (a renal function), and hemoglobin level isn't the mechanism.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 91"},{"q":"How does thrombomodulin help limit clotting?","choices":["It directly digests fibrin fibers","It binds thrombin and activates protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa","It potentiates antithrombin III","It blocks the release of tissue factor"],"answer":1,"exp":"Thrombomodulin binds thrombin; the complex activates protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa, slowing coagulation. (A) describes plasmin, (C) describes heparin's mechanism, and (D) is not thrombomodulin's action.","cite":"Hemostasis & Blood Coagulation, Slide 48"},{"q":"Lung compliance is best defined as...","choices":["The pressure needed to overcome airway resistance","The tendency of the lung to recoil after stretch","The rate of airflow through the bronchioles","The change in lung volume per unit change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Compliance measures how much lung volume changes for a given change in pressure (ΔV/ΔP) — its distensibility. Recoil tendency is elasticity (the opposite idea), while airway resistance and airflow rate describe how easily air moves, not how easily the lung stretches.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 14"},{"q":"Enterokinase (enteropeptidase) on the intestinal brush border is essential because it...","choices":["Activates trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the other pancreatic zymogens","Directly digests triglycerides","Neutralizes gastric acid","Absorbs amino acids"],"answer":0,"exp":"Enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and more trypsinogen. It does not digest fat, neutralize acid, or absorb amino acids.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 104"},{"q":"What is the difference between a lung “volume” and a lung “capacity”?","choices":["A capacity is always smaller than a single volume","A capacity is the sum of two or more lung volumes","They are two words for the same thing","A volume can only be measured during exercise"],"answer":1,"exp":"A lung capacity is defined as the sum of two or more lung volumes (e.g., vital capacity = IRV + TV + ERV). Capacities are therefore larger than individual volumes, are not synonymous with them, and are measured at rest.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 27"},{"q":"After fats are reassembled into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons, they enter the...","choices":["Portal blood directly","Bile ducts","Lymphatic system (lacteals), because chylomicrons are too large for blood capillaries","Gastric veins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chylomicrons are too large to enter blood capillaries, so they pass into the lacteals and travel via lymph to the thoracic duct before reaching the blood. They do not enter portal blood, bile ducts, or gastric veins directly.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 135"},{"q":"How does a decrease in lung volume affect airway resistance?","choices":["It increases resistance","It decreases resistance","It eliminates resistance","It has no effect on resistance"],"answer":0,"exp":"As lung volume falls, the airways are less stretched open and narrow, so airway resistance rises. Resistance is never eliminated, and it clearly depends on lung volume, so “no effect” is incorrect.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 16"},{"q":"Bile, which is essential for fat emulsification, is produced by which organ?","choices":["The gallbladder","The liver","The pancreas","The duodenal mucosa"],"answer":1,"exp":"The liver produces bile continuously; the gallbladder only stores and concentrates it between meals. The pancreas and duodenal mucosa secrete other digestive fluids, not bile.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 113"},{"q":"Inspiratory capacity is the maximum air that can be inspired following...","choices":["A maximal inspiration","A maximal expiration","A normal (resting) expiration","A forced exhalation to residual volume"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inspiratory capacity (= TV + IRV) is the most air inhaled starting from the end of a normal, resting expiration. Starting from a maximal expiration or residual volume would approach total lung capacity, and you cannot inhale further after a maximal inspiration.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 28"},{"q":"How does the spinal-cord (parasympathetic) defecation reflex relate to the intrinsic reflex?","choices":["It replaces the intrinsic reflex entirely","It is qualitatively different and unrelated","It inhibits defecation","It greatly intensifies the intrinsic reflex via pelvic-nerve parasympathetic fibers"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spinal (parasympathetic, S2–S4) reflex reinforces — not replaces — the intrinsic reflex, greatly strengthening colonic and rectal contractions through pelvic-nerve fibers. It is not qualitatively different, unrelated, or inhibitory.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 67"},{"q":"When arterial PO₂ falls substantially (PCO₂ held constant), ventilation...","choices":["Increases, driven by the peripheral chemoreceptors","Stays exactly the same","Decreases","Stops entirely"],"answer":0,"exp":"A substantial fall in PO₂ stimulates the carotid and aortic bodies, increasing ventilation (the hypoxic drive). Ventilation does not fall, stay flat, or stop when oxygen drops.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 99"},{"q":"The migrating motor complex (MMC) functions to...","choices":["Mix chyme with enzymes right after a meal","Sweep undigested residue toward the colon between meals, keeping upper-gut bacterial counts low","Trigger mass movements in the colon","Neutralize gastric acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"The MMC is the interdigestive “housekeeping” pattern that clears residue and bacteria from the upper gut between meals, mediated by motilin. It is not a postprandial mixing pattern, does not drive colonic mass movements, and has no role in neutralizing acid.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 55"},{"q":"Respiratory regulation is organized as which three-part system?","choices":["Surfactant, mucus, and cilia","Arteries, veins, and capillaries","Alveoli, bronchioles, and pleura","Sensors, a central controller, and effector muscles"],"answer":3,"exp":"Respiratory control is a feedback loop: sensors (chemoreceptors) gather data, the central controller (brainstem) integrates it, and effectors (respiratory muscles) act. The other trios list vascular, structural, or airway-lining parts, not the control loop.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 88"},{"q":"Peristalsis (the propulsive movement of the gut) fundamentally requires...","choices":["The myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus, and can occur without the autonomic nervous system","The sphincter of Oddi to open first","The sympathetic nervous system to initiate the contraction","Complete removal of the enteric nervous system"],"answer":0,"exp":"Peristalsis is coordinated by the enteric (myenteric) plexus and proceeds even without autonomic input, though the parasympathetics modulate it. It does not require the sympathetic system to start, the sphincter of Oddi, or removal of the ENS — destroying the ENS actually abolishes it.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 39"},{"q":"About how much oxygen can each gram of hemoglobin bind?","choices":["0.3 ml O₂","1.34 ml O₂","100 ml O₂","20 ml O₂"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 ml of O₂. The 0.3 ml figure is dissolved O₂ per 100 ml of blood, and ~20 ml is the total O₂-carrying capacity per 100 ml — not the per-gram value.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 77"},{"q":"Which gastric cell secretes both hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor?","choices":["Chief (peptic) cells","G-cells","Parietal (oxyntic) cells","Mucous neck cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parietal (oxyntic) cells secrete both HCl and intrinsic factor. Chief cells make pepsinogen, G-cells make gastrin, and mucous neck cells make mucus.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 79"},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell in exchange for chloride entering, this exchange is called the...","choices":["Bohr shift","Haldane shift","Sodium shift","Chloride (Hamburger) shift"],"answer":3,"exp":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell, chloride moves in to preserve electrical neutrality — the chloride (Hamburger) shift. The Bohr and Haldane effects describe how pH/O₂ change gas affinities, and there is no “sodium shift” here.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 86"},{"q":"Besides stimulating gastric acid secretion, gastrin has what other notable action?","choices":["A trophic effect promoting growth of the oxyntic (gastric) mucosa","Emptying the gallbladder","Stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion","Inhibiting all gastric secretion"],"answer":0,"exp":"Beyond stimulating acid, gastrin is trophic to the oxyntic mucosa, promoting its growth. Gallbladder emptying and pancreatic enzyme secretion are CCK's actions, and gastrin stimulates rather than inhibits gastric secretion.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 12"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide is dangerous to oxygen transport because it...","choices":["Increases the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood","Cannot bind hemoglobin at all","Binds hemoglobin far more tightly than O₂, blocking O₂ binding","Only affects dissolved oxygen"],"answer":2,"exp":"Carbon monoxide binds hemoglobin with far greater affinity than oxygen, occupying binding sites and preventing O₂ transport. It reduces (not increases) usable capacity, definitely binds hemoglobin, and acts on hemoglobin rather than dissolved O₂.","cite":"Pulmonary Physiology I & II, Slide 82"},{"q":"When the antral pH becomes very low, gastrin release is inhibited largely because acid...","choices":["Directly destroys the G-cells","Increases histamine release","Converts gastrin into secretin","Stimulates somatostatin release, which suppresses gastrin (negative feedback)"],"answer":3,"exp":"A low antral pH stimulates somatostatin, which inhibits gastrin release — a negative-feedback brake on acid secretion. Acid does not destroy G-cells, convert gastrin to secretin, or raise histamine.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 94"},{"q":"Glucose enters most cells of the body by...","choices":["Primary active transport that directly uses ATP","Facilitated diffusion — a carrier is needed but energy is not","Simple diffusion straight through the lipid bilayer","Receptor-mediated endocytosis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Glucose crosses most cell membranes by facilitated diffusion: a carrier protein (GLUT) moves it down its concentration gradient without using ATP. It is not pumped by primary active transport, does not dissolve through the bilayer, and is not taken up by endocytosis.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 4"},{"q":"Once formed, trypsin plays a central role in the intestine by...","choices":["Emulsifying fats","Neutralizing acid chyme","Activating chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and more trypsinogen","Absorbing peptides"],"answer":2,"exp":"Trypsin is the master activator: it converts chymotrypsinogen, procarboxypeptidase, and additional trypsinogen to their active forms. Neutralizing acid is bicarbonate's role, emulsifying fat is bile's, and absorption is the mucosa's.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 104"},{"q":"Chylomicrons and VLDL differ in that...","choices":["both are made only in the liver","neither particle carries triglyceride","chylomicrons are made in the liver and VLDL in the gut","chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the intestine, while VLDL is made in the liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"Chylomicrons are assembled in intestinal mucosa to carry absorbed dietary fat, while VLDL is synthesized in the liver (its triglyceride made largely from carbohydrate). The other options misplace their origins or deny that they carry triglyceride.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 6"},{"q":"Which hormone is released cyclically during fasting to drive the migrating motor complexes?","choices":["Cholecystokinin","Motilin","Secretin","Gastrin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Motilin is released cyclically during fasting and drives the migrating motor complexes. CCK, secretin, and gastrin are released in response to a meal and serve digestive rather than interdigestive roles.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 18"},{"q":"Which condition favors gluconeogenesis?","choices":["High blood glucose right after a meal","A high insulin-to-glucagon ratio","A high glucagon-to-insulin ratio (as in fasting)","Low cortisol levels"],"answer":2,"exp":"Gluconeogenesis (mainly hepatic) is favored by a high glucagon:insulin ratio, high mitochondrial NADH and acetyl-CoA, and high cortisol — the fasting state. A high insulin ratio, post-meal hyperglycemia, and low cortisol all suppress it.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 68, Slide 30"},{"q":"The villi and microvilli of the small intestine are important because they...","choices":["Secrete the pancreatic enzymes","Store bile salts","Neutralize gastric acid","Vastly increase the surface area available for absorption"],"answer":3,"exp":"Villi (~10-fold) and microvilli/brush border (~20-fold) hugely amplify the absorptive surface area of the small intestine. They do not secrete pancreatic enzymes, neutralize acid, or store bile salts.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 118"},{"q":"Insulin promotes fat storage by...","choices":["stimulating lipoprotein lipase and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase","blocking glucose uptake into cells","stimulating hormone-sensitive lipase","promoting beta-oxidation of fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Insulin stores fat by activating lipoprotein lipase (loading fatty acids into adipocytes) and inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase (blocking breakdown of stored triglyceride). It promotes glucose uptake and opposes fat mobilization and beta-oxidation.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 69, Slide 22"},{"q":"Vitamin B12 (bound to intrinsic factor) is absorbed at which site?","choices":["The ileum","The duodenum","The colon","The stomach"],"answer":0,"exp":"The intrinsic-factor–B12 complex is absorbed in the ileum (as are bile salts). The stomach and colon absorb little B12, and the duodenum mainly absorbs other nutrients, iron, and calcium.","cite":"GI Physiology, Slide 121"},{"q":"Oxidative deamination of an amino acid removes the amino group, generating...","choices":["glucose","ammonia, which must be detoxified","a ketone body","a fatty acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Deamination strips the amino group off an amino acid, releasing ammonia (which the liver converts to urea). It does not directly yield glucose, a fatty acid, or a ketone body — those may come from the remaining carbon skeleton.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 70, Slide 16"},{"q":"Regarding the liver's blood supply...","choices":["It is supplied almost entirely by the hepatic artery","It receives less than 5% of cardiac output","It receives about 30% of cardiac output, most of it from the portal vein","It has no venous inflow"],"answer":2,"exp":"About 30% of cardiac output flows through the liver, roughly 75% via the portal vein and 25% via the hepatic artery, at low pressure and resistance. It is not chiefly arterial, is far more than 5% of output, and has major portal venous inflow.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 3"},{"q":"In the enterohepatic circulation, about 95% of secreted bile salts are...","choices":["excreted in the feces","destroyed by pancreatic enzymes","converted to cholesterol in the gut","reabsorbed (mostly in the ileum) and returned to the liver for reuse"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 95% of secreted bile salts are reabsorbed, chiefly in the ileum, and returned via portal blood to the liver; only the small fraction lost in feces is replaced by new synthesis. They are not mostly excreted, digested, or turned back into cholesterol in the gut.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 71, Slide 25"},{"q":"Which macronutrient provides the most energy per gram?","choices":["Fat (~9 kcal/g)","Carbohydrate (~4 kcal/g)","Protein (~4 kcal/g)","All provide equal energy per gram"],"answer":0,"exp":"Fat yields about 9 kcal/g, more than double carbohydrate or protein (~4 kcal/g each). They are not equal per gram.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 4"},{"q":"Vitamin D is essential for...","choices":["collagen synthesis","calcium and phosphate balance","amino acid transamination","oxygen transport"],"answer":1,"exp":"Vitamin D (activated via skin UV, then the liver and kidney) is essential for calcium and phosphate balance; deficiency causes rickets. Collagen needs vitamin C, oxygen transport needs hemoglobin, and transamination needs vitamin B6.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 72, Slide 28"},{"q":"Which nutrient produces the greatest thermic effect (rise in metabolic rate during digestion)?","choices":["Fat (~4%)","Carbohydrate (~4%)","Protein (up to ~30%)","All are equal"],"answer":2,"exp":"Protein has by far the largest thermic effect of food, raising metabolic rate up to ~30%, versus about 4% for carbohydrate and fat.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 73, Slide 10"},{"q":"Which is a mechanism of heat LOSS from the body?","choices":["Piloerection","Shivering","Vasoconstriction of skin vessels","Evaporation of sweat"],"answer":3,"exp":"Evaporation (of sweat and insensible water) loses heat, along with radiation and conduction/convection. Shivering and piloerection generate or conserve heat, and skin vasoconstriction reduces heat loss.","cite":"Metabolism, Nutrition & Thermoregulation — Ch. 74, Slide 6"}]},"physio-master-v5":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v5)","questions":[{"q":"Red blood cells contain abundant carbonic anhydrase. How does this enzyme support the blood's role in gas transport?","choices":["It speeds hydration of CO2 to carbonic acid, letting most CO2 travel as bicarbonate","It loads oxygen onto the heme groups so that each red cell carries more O2 per pass","It binds free iron and keeps hemoglobin locked in its oxygen-carrying ferrous state","It buffers lactic acid from the red cell's own anaerobic glucose metabolism"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: carbonic anhydrase catalyzes CO2 + H2O to H2CO3, so most CO2 is carried as HCO3-, the major extracellular buffer.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 3"},{"q":"A hematocrit of 42% tells you which of the following about a whole-blood sample?","choices":["Hemoglobin makes up roughly 42% of the mass of each individual red cell","Plasma proteins account for close to 42% of the blood's osmotic pressure","About 42% of circulating hemoglobin is currently saturated with oxygen","Red cells occupy about 42% of whole-blood volume, the remainder being plasma"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: hematocrit is the packed cell (mostly RBC) volume as a percent of whole blood, normally ~40-45%.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Each hemoglobin molecule can transport four O2 molecules. Which structural feature accounts for this?","choices":["Four heme groups, each with one iron atom that reversibly binds one O2","Four globin chains that each dissolve one O2 into the red-cell cytoplasm","Four carbonic anhydrase sites that each convert one O2 for transport","Four disulfide bonds that each trap a single dissolved oxygen molecule"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: adult hemoglobin has four globin chains, each with a heme/iron that reversibly binds one O2, so four O2 per molecule.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"Chronic hypoxia raises red-cell production largely through which mechanism?","choices":["Sympathetic signaling to the spleen that releases stored mature red cells","Direct hypoxic stimulation of the marrow stem cells acting independently of any hormone","Stabilized HIF-1 drives kidney erythropoietin output, boosting marrow erythropoiesis","Increased hepatic transferrin release that accelerates hemoglobin assembly"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: hypoxia stabilizes HIF-1, which increases renal erythropoietin, stimulating marrow production of red cells.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"Deficiency of vitamin B12 or folate produces abnormally large red cells because these vitamins are required for...","choices":["membrane repair, so cells round up and expand as they lose deformability","iron incorporation, so cells enlarge to compensate for low oxygen content","hemoglobin assembly, so cells swell to hold the excess unbound globin","DNA synthesis, so nuclear maturation lags while the cytoplasm keeps growing"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: without B12/folate, thymidine and thus DNA cannot be made, so the cell grows without dividing, forming large macrocytes.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"Von Willebrand factor contributes to primary hemostasis mainly by...","choices":["converting prothrombin to thrombin on the surface of activated platelets","bridging platelets to exposed collagen so they adhere at the injury site","cleaving fibrinogen into the fibrin strands that anchor the platelet mass","triggering vascular smooth muscle spasm to narrow the damaged vessel"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: von Willebrand factor binds platelets to exposed subendothelial collagen, promoting adhesion of the plug.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 34"},{"q":"Which event is considered the rate-limiting step of blood coagulation?","choices":["Cleavage of fibrinogen by thrombin into circulating fibrin monomers","Formation of prothrombin activator, which then converts prothrombin to thrombin","Aggregation of platelets into the initial soft plug that forms over the wounded vessel","Cross-linking of fibrin strands by activated fibrin-stabilizing factor"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: generating prothrombin activator is the rate-limiting step; it converts prothrombin to thrombin in the presence of calcium.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 40"},{"q":"The extrinsic pathway is triggered when tissue factor is exposed. The extrinsic and intrinsic pathways then converge by...","choices":["activating factor X, which assembles prothrombin activator","activating factor XII on contact with subendothelial collagen","cleaving fibrinogen directly without first forming thrombin","releasing thromboxane A2 to recruit additional nearby platelets"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: both pathways activate factor X, forming prothrombin activator in the common pathway.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"On healthy, intact endothelium, what normally limits inappropriate clot formation?","choices":["A smooth glycocalyx plus thrombomodulin that diverts thrombin toward protein C","Rapid platelet turnover that clears activated factors before they can act","Continuous low-level plasmin release that digests any fibrin as it forms","High local calcium that keeps the clotting factors in their inactive states"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: the smooth glycocalyx repels platelets/factors, and thrombomodulin binds thrombin to activate protein C, which inactivates factors Va and VIIIa.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 48"},{"q":"Vitamin K is required for the liver to make functional prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X because it...","choices":["transports the finished factors from hepatocytes into the circulating plasma","supplies the phospholipid surface where these clotting factors are assembled","enables carboxylation of glutamate residues needed for calcium binding","cleaves the inactive factor precursors into their active protease forms"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: vitamin K is the cofactor for carboxylating glutamate residues, allowing these factors to bind calcium and function.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 54"},{"q":"During acute infection, why do neutrophils dominate the earliest response while macrophages dominate later?","choices":["Neutrophils recirculate for weeks, so they reach tissue before slower monocytes","Macrophages act only after antibodies have coated the pathogen for ingestion","Macrophages must first divide within the tissue before they can phagocytize","Neutrophils are mature and arrive within an hour; macrophages take days to build up"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: mature neutrophils respond immediately, whereas monocytes must accumulate and mature into macrophages over days.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 28-30"},{"q":"Kupffer cells lining the liver sinusoids illustrate which principle of the monocyte-macrophage system?","choices":["Neutrophils mature in the liver before entering the general circulation","Lymphocytes convert into macrophages once they reach the portal vein","Circulating platelets become tissue phagocytes at sites of slow blood flow","Monocytes settle in tissue as fixed macrophages that filter passing blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: fixed tissue macrophages such as Kupffer cells strip bacteria from portal blood, filtering the circulation.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 20-23"},{"q":"Opsonization increases phagocytosis of a bacterium by...","choices":["attracting neutrophils along a chemical gradient toward the microbe","coating it with antibody and complement C3b that phagocytes recognize","digesting its protective capsule so the cell surface becomes rough","fusing lysosomes with the phagosome to form a digestive vesicle"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: opsonins such as antibody and C3b bind the microbe and mark it for recognition and ingestion by phagocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 15-16"},{"q":"The complement system enhances immunity primarily by...","choices":["producing the memory cells responsible for a faster secondary response","presenting antigen fragments to helper T-cells on MHC molecules","generating antigen-specific antibodies tailored to each pathogen","opsonizing microbes, driving inflammation, and lysing target membranes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: complement complements antibody and phagocyte action through opsonization, inflammation, and membrane lysis.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 53"},{"q":"Which describes a direct way antibodies neutralize a bacterial toxin?","choices":["Inserting pore-forming perforins directly into the toxin molecule","Binding and covering the toxic site so it cannot act on host cells","Secreting interleukins that suppress further toxin production","Phagocytizing the toxin and digesting it within a phagolysosome"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: neutralization occurs when antibodies cover the toxic/active site of the antigen so it cannot bind host tissue.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 52"},{"q":"Why can a cytotoxic T-cell not respond to free, intact antigen the way a B-cell can?","choices":["T-cells respond only to polysaccharide antigens, never to proteins","T-cells recognize only antigen fragments displayed on MHC molecules","T-cells lack surface receptors and rely entirely on secreted antibody","T-cells must first be opsonized by complement before they can bind antigen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: unlike B-cells, T-cells recognize processed antigen fragments presented by MHC, not free intact antigen.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 55"},{"q":"Which pairing correctly matches a defense with its immune category?","choices":["Memory B-cells — innate; natural killer cells — acquired immunity","Complement proteins — acquired; helper T-cell clones — innate immunity","Antigen-specific plasma cells — innate; lysozyme in tears — acquired","Gastric acid and intact skin — innate; circulating antibodies — acquired"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: skin and gastric acid are nonspecific innate barriers, while antigen-specific antibodies are acquired immunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 35-37"},{"q":"Humoral and cell-mediated immunity differ in that humoral immunity...","choices":["uses B-cell-derived antibodies, while cell-mediated uses activated T-cells","requires no prior antigen exposure, while cell-mediated must be triggered","provides no memory, while cell-mediated generates lasting protection","acts only inside infected cells, while cell-mediated acts in the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: humoral immunity works through B-cell antibodies; cell-mediated immunity works through activated T-lymphocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 37"},{"q":"Why is the secondary response to a repeated antigen faster and stronger than the first?","choices":["Complement proteins are consumed the first time and later regenerate larger","The innate system is permanently reprogrammed to recognize that antigen","Plasma cells from the first exposure never die and keep secreting antibody","Memory B- and T-cells from the first exposure persist and react quickly"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: memory lymphocytes generated on first exposure remain and mount a rapid, amplified secondary response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 48"},{"q":"In an immediate (type I) allergic reaction, symptoms arise when...","choices":["antibodies precipitate with soluble antigen and deposit in tissues","antigen cross-links IgE bound to mast cells, triggering histamine release","cytotoxic cells lyse host cells that display the offending antigen","T-cells slowly infiltrate the skin over one to two days after contact"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: in immediate hypersensitivity, antigen cross-links IgE on mast cells/basophils, causing degranulation and histamine release.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 64-65"},{"q":"The peristaltic reflex ('law of the gut') moves contents aborally by...","choices":["relying on sympathetic input to drive rhythmic forward propulsion","contracting the entire intestine at once to squeeze contents forward","alternating haustral pouches that slowly knead contents toward the anus","contracting the segment behind the bolus while relaxing the segment ahead"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: distension causes contraction orad (behind) with receptive relaxation downstream, propelling contents forward.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 39"},{"q":"Which hormone-action pairing is correct for the digestive response to a meal?","choices":["CCK — is the principal stimulus for gastric acid from parietal cells","Gastrin — relaxes the gallbladder and constricts the sphincter of Oddi","Secretin — stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate to neutralize duodenal acid","Motilin — is released after meals to speed nutrient absorption"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: secretin, released by duodenal acid, stimulates pancreatic and biliary bicarbonate, acting as 'nature's antacid'.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 14-16"},{"q":"How does gastrin most powerfully stimulate gastric acid secretion?","choices":["Largely by driving ECL cells to release histamine, which acts on parietal cells","By converting pepsinogen into active pepsin within the acidic gastric lumen itself","By stimulating duodenal S-cells to release secretin into the circulating bloodstream","By directly neutralizing somatostatin's inhibition of the chief cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: much of gastrin's potent acid effect is indirect, through histamine released from ECL cells acting on parietal cells.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 88-91"},{"q":"Late in a meal, as gastric contents become very acidic, acid secretion declines because...","choices":["histamine is depleted faster than ECL cells can regenerate it","secretin from the stomach directly stimulates further gastrin output","parietal cells run out of the carbonic anhydrase needed to make acid","low pH triggers somatostatin, which suppresses gastrin release"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: falling pH stimulates somatostatin and directly inhibits gastrin, providing negative feedback that reduces acid output.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 90, 94-95"},{"q":"The pancreas avoids digesting itself largely because...","choices":["pancreatic tissue simply lacks any receptors for its own digestive enzymes entirely","proteases are stored and secreted as inactive zymogens activated only in the gut","bicarbonate keeps the acinar pH too high for any enzyme to function","enzymes are secreted so slowly that ongoing tissue repair always manages to keep pace"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: enzymes like trypsinogen are stored inactive (with a trypsin inhibitor) and activated only in the intestine.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 103-105"},{"q":"Enterokinase (enteropeptidase) on the intestinal brush border initiates protein digestion by...","choices":["emulsifying protein aggregates so that pepsin can reach them","converting trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the other proteases","activating pancreatic amylase so that it can begin breaking down starch","cleaving dietary protein directly into individual absorbable free amino acids"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which autocatalytically activates chymotrypsinogen and procarboxypeptidase.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 104"},{"q":"Bile salts aid fat absorption because their amphipathic structure lets them...","choices":["convert dietary cholesterol into water-soluble bile pigments for excretion","chemically hydrolyze triglycerides into fatty acids and glycerol","emulsify fat and ferry lipid digestion products to the mucosa as micelles","actively pump fatty acids across the enterocyte membrane using ATP"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: being amphipathic, bile salts emulsify fat and form micelles that carry monoglycerides and fatty acids to the mucosa.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 20"},{"q":"Glucose and fructose are absorbed by the enterocyte through different routes because...","choices":["glucose enters by endocytosis while fructose is co-transported inward with sodium ions","glucose diffuses freely through the membrane while fructose requires ATP directly","glucose requires bile-salt micelles while fructose crosses as a free monosaccharide","glucose uses Na+-coupled secondary active transport; fructose uses facilitated diffusion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: glucose (and galactose) enter by Na+-dependent SGLT1, whereas fructose enters by facilitated diffusion via GLUT5.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 126"},{"q":"After fatty acids are reassembled into triglycerides inside the enterocyte, they...","choices":["bind intrinsic factor and are carried to the ileum for their later active uptake","are stored in the brush border until bile salts release them to plasma","are packaged into chylomicrons that enter lymph rather than blood capillaries","diffuse directly into portal blood for immediate transport to the liver"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: triglycerides are packaged into chylomicrons, which are too large for capillaries and enter lacteals/lymph, reaching blood via the thoracic duct.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 135-137"},{"q":"Rectal distension triggers defecation through which combined mechanism?","choices":["A hormonal signal from the colon that stimulates mass movements only","A sympathetic reflex that contracts the rectum and relaxes both sphincters","A purely voluntary process controlled entirely by the external sphincter","An intrinsic ENS reflex reinforced by a sacral parasympathetic cord reflex"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: an intrinsic myenteric reflex is strengthened by a sacral (parasympathetic) spinal cord reflex, with voluntary external sphincter control.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 65-67"},{"q":"The liver's role as a blood-glucose buffer means it...","choices":["stores glucose as glycogen after meals and releases glucose between meals","prevents any glucose from reaching the systemic circulation directly","converts all absorbed glucose immediately into triglyceride for storage","secretes insulin whenever plasma glucose rises above the normal range"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: the liver takes up and stores glucose as glycogen postprandially and releases glucose during fasting, buffering blood levels.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9"},{"q":"A key protective function of the liver in protein metabolism is to...","choices":["convert urea back into ammonia so nitrogen can be reused in synthesis","store surplus amino acids as intact protein until the body needs them","excrete surplus amino acids unchanged into the bile","convert ammonia from amino-acid deamination into urea for excretion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the liver converts toxic ammonia (from deamination) into urea via the urea cycle for renal excretion.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 10; Ch 70, slide 16"},{"q":"Under anaerobic conditions, converting pyruvate to lactate is useful mainly because it...","choices":["stores oxygen that the cell can later use inside the mitochondria","produces additional ATP directly from the lactate molecule itself","regenerates NAD+ so that glycolysis can continue producing ATP","removes hydrogen ions that would otherwise raise the cell's pH"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: lactate formation regenerates NAD+, which glycolysis needs to keep running when oxygen is limited.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 25-26"},{"q":"Epinephrine and glucagon raise blood glucose partly through phosphorylation, which...","choices":["activates glycogen phosphorylase while inactivating glycogen synthase","activates both glycogen phosphorylase and glycogen synthase together","activates glycogen synthase to build glycogen from incoming glucose","inactivates phosphorylase so stored glycogen is protected from breakdown"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: phosphorylation activates phosphorylase (breakdown) and inactivates synthase (storage), favoring glycogenolysis.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 11-12"},{"q":"Which conditions favor hepatic gluconeogenesis?","choices":["A high glucagon-to-insulin ratio with abundant acetyl-CoA from fat oxidation","Depleted acetyl-CoA that halts oxaloacetate formation from pyruvate","Low mitochondrial NADH levels signaling that cellular energy is already plentiful","A high circulating insulin level that drives glucose into muscle and fat cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: gluconeogenesis is favored by a high glucagon:insulin ratio and high mitochondrial acetyl-CoA/NADH from fat oxidation.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 30-31"},{"q":"Complete oxidation of one glucose yields far more ATP than glycolysis alone because...","choices":["oxygen is incorporated directly into ATP during the citric acid cycle","the citric acid cycle produces most ATP directly by substrate phosphorylation","NADH and FADH2 feed the electron transport chain to generate most of the ATP","glycolysis is simply repeated several times using the same glucose molecule"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: reduced carriers from glycolysis, pyruvate oxidation, and the citric acid cycle drive oxidative phosphorylation, the main ATP source.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Which lipoprotein-function pairing is correct?","choices":["VLDL returns excess cholesterol to the liver, while HDL carries the dietary fat","Chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the gut; LDL delivers cholesterol to cells","LDL transports gut triglyceride; chylomicrons deliver hepatic cholesterol","HDL carries dietary triglyceride, while VLDL returns cholesterol back to the gut"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: chylomicrons transport dietary lipid absorbed from the gut, and LDL delivers cholesterol to peripheral cells.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 6; GI Physiology, slide 139"},{"q":"During prolonged fasting, the liver produces ketone bodies because...","choices":["abundant circulating glucose drives the conversion of pyruvate directly into ketones","rising insulin stimulates the liver to store its excess fat as ketone bodies","high fatty-acid oxidation generates acetyl-CoA in excess of TCA cycle capacity","amino acids are unavailable, forcing protein to be turned into ketones"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: heavy beta-oxidation floods the liver with acetyl-CoA beyond what the citric acid cycle can handle, so it is diverted to ketones.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 15-19"},{"q":"Lipoprotein lipase on the capillary endothelium serves to...","choices":["hydrolyze triglycerides in chylomicrons and VLDL so tissues take up fatty acids","convert cholesterol into bile acids within the hepatocyte for later secretion","assemble chylomicrons from absorbed fatty acids while inside the enterocyte","transport intact triglycerides across the capillary wall into cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: lipoprotein lipase on endothelium hydrolyzes circulating triglyceride, releasing fatty acids for tissue uptake.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 13"},{"q":"Which statement about amino-acid metabolism is correct?","choices":["Both reactions occur only in muscle tissue and never take place within the liver","Deamination adds an amino group onto a carbon skeleton, a step needing vitamin B6","Transamination builds nonessential amino acids; deamination frees ammonia for urea","Transamination permanently destroys the carbon skeleton of the amino acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: transamination (needing vitamin B6) forms nonessential amino acids, while deamination liberates ammonia that becomes urea.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 7-16"},{"q":"Gram for gram, fat provides more than twice the energy of carbohydrate or protein because it...","choices":["requires no oxygen to release its stored chemical energy","yields about 9 kcal/g versus roughly 4 kcal/g for carbohydrate and protein","is absorbed far more completely from the gut than either carbohydrate or protein","is stored together with large amounts of water that add to its measured energy"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: fat provides ~9 kcal/g, over double the ~4 kcal/g of carbohydrate or protein.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 4"},{"q":"Leptin and ghrelin have opposing effects on appetite because...","choices":["leptin drives hunger during fasting, while ghrelin signals satiety after meals","leptin from the stomach stimulates appetite, while ghrelin suppresses it","leptin from fat reduces appetite, while ghrelin from the stomach stimulates it","both are released from adipose tissue but act on different brain regions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: leptin from adipose tissue signals satiety and reduces intake, while ghrelin from the stomach stimulates hunger.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 11-14"},{"q":"Damage to the ventromedial hypothalamic nuclei tends to cause overeating because these nuclei normally...","choices":["release ghrelin that signals the stomach to empty faster","serve as the feeding center that directly drives hunger","detect blood leptin and raise appetite whenever it falls","act as a satiety center that inhibits the feeding center"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the ventromedial nuclei are the satiety center; losing them removes inhibition of feeding, causing hyperphagia.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 9"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate represents...","choices":["the minimal energy needed to sustain the body while at rest and fasting","the energy used only for digesting and absorbing a meal","total daily energy output including all physical activity","the peak energy expenditure that is achievable during heavy physical exercise"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: basal metabolic rate is the minimal energy to maintain the body at rest, measured fasting and thermoneutral.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 8, 10"},{"q":"A respiratory quotient near 1.0 shortly after a carbohydrate meal reflects that...","choices":["no gas exchange is occurring at all because metabolism has temporarily paused","protein breakdown dominates the fuel mix, fixing the ratio at exactly 0.8","fat is the main fuel, releasing little CO2 relative to the O2 used","carbohydrate oxidation produces CO2 and consumes O2 in roughly equal amounts"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: burning carbohydrate gives an RQ near 1.0 because CO2 produced and O2 consumed are about equal.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 5-6"},{"q":"A protein-rich meal raises metabolic rate more than a fatty meal mainly due to...","choices":["the large thermic effect of processing protein, up to about a 30% rise","protein's higher energy content per gram compared with fat","protein suppressing thyroid hormone and thereby lowering heat loss","protein triggering shivering thermogenesis right after eating"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: protein has the highest thermic effect of food, raising metabolic rate up to ~30%, far more than fat or carbohydrate.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 10; Ch 72, slide 9"},{"q":"When surrounding air is cooler than the skin, the body's largest avenue of heat loss at rest is...","choices":["conduction of heat directly into the solid objects being touched","radiation of infrared heat waves to cooler nearby objects","warming of inhaled air within the respiratory passages","evaporation of sweat driven by sympathetic cholinergic fibers"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: at rest in cool surroundings, radiation of infrared waves is the dominant route of heat loss.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 6"},{"q":"The preoptic area of the anterior hypothalamus regulates temperature by...","choices":["controlling only behavioral responses such as adding or removing clothing","generating body heat directly through its own high metabolic activity","storing a fixed set point that never changes, even during a fever","sensing blood temperature and triggering heat-loss or heat-gain responses"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: the anterior hypothalamic preoptic area senses core temperature and drives appropriate heat-loss or heat-gain responses around a set point.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 5, 16"},{"q":"Sweat reaching the skin surface is normally hypotonic to plasma because...","choices":["the sweat glands secrete pure water that lacks any electrolytes","aldosterone actively adds salt to the sweat as it forms","potassium fully replaces sodium before the sweat reaches the surface","sodium and chloride are reabsorbed from the duct, especially at low flow"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: as primary secretion moves through the duct, Na+ and Cl- are reabsorbed, leaving hypotonic sweat, most markedly at low flow rates.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 8"},{"q":"On exposure to cold, the posterior hypothalamus conserves and generates heat by...","choices":["stimulating sweating and cutaneous vasodilation to trap and hold body warmth","driving cutaneous vasoconstriction and shivering to raise heat production","lowering the overall metabolic rate in order to reduce the body's oxygen demand","inhibiting thyroxine release to slow chemical thermogenesis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: cold responses include sympathetic cutaneous vasoconstriction and shivering, which conserve and generate heat.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 14-15"},{"q":"During quiet inspiration, air flows into the alveoli because...","choices":["expiratory muscles compress the chest wall and actively push the air inward","the diaphragm enlarges the thorax, making alveolar pressure sub-atmospheric","surfactant actively pulls air inward across the thin respiratory membrane","the diaphragm relaxes, raising alveolar pressure above atmospheric"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: diaphragmatic contraction expands the thorax, dropping alveolar pressure below atmospheric so air flows in.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"Airway radius has a powerful effect on airflow because resistance is...","choices":["directly proportional to the radius of the airway","proportional to the square of the airway's length","inversely proportional to the fourth power of the radius","independent of radius and set only by the air's viscosity"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: by Poiseuille's relationship, resistance varies with 1/r^4, so small radius changes greatly affect flow.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 16"},{"q":"Lung compliance describes...","choices":["the volume change produced per unit change in distending pressure","the resistance that the airways offer to the flow of moving air","the maximum air volume that the lungs can possibly hold","the tendency of stretched lung tissue to recoil to its resting shape"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: compliance is the change in lung volume per unit change in transmural (distending) pressure.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 14, 19"},{"q":"Surface tension at the air-water interface lining the alveoli tends to...","choices":["hold the alveoli open by pushing their walls apart","increase lung compliance by making expansion easier","draw the alveolar walls together and favor collapse","have no measurable effect on alveolar stability at any size"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: surface tension pulls the liquid-lined walls inward, favoring alveolar collapse unless surfactant opposes it.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19-20"},{"q":"Surfactant stabilizes small alveoli by...","choices":["thickening the alveolar fluid lining so as to slow the diffusion of gases","lowering surface tension so small alveoli resist collapsing into larger ones","increasing the radius of every alveolus throughout the lung","raising surface tension uniformly across the alveoli of every possible size"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: surfactant reduces surface tension more in small alveoli, preventing them from emptying into larger ones (Laplace).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Vital capacity is best described as...","choices":["the air still remaining in the lungs after a maximal forced expiration","the air remaining after a normal quiet expiration","the maximum air expired after a maximal inspiration (IRV + VT + ERV)","the volume of air that is moved during a single normal quiet resting breath"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: vital capacity is the greatest volume that can be expelled after a maximal inspiration, the sum of IRV, tidal volume, and ERV.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 29"},{"q":"Residual volume cannot be measured by simple spirometry because it...","choices":["is the air that remains in the lungs and cannot be exhaled","leaves the lungs completely during a maximal forced expiration","is identical to tidal volume and so needs no measurement","changes with every breath and therefore has no stable value"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: residual volume stays in the lungs even after maximal expiration, so a spirometer cannot capture it directly.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 27, 31"},{"q":"Anatomic dead space reduces the efficiency of ventilation because...","choices":["it is the region where most oxygen uptake actually takes place","air in the conducting airways never reaches alveoli for gas exchange","it holds air that has already fully equilibrated with pulmonary blood","it represents alveoli that are ventilated but not perfused by blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: the ~150 mL in conducting airways does not participate in gas exchange, so alveolar ventilation is less than minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"According to the principles of gas diffusion, transfer across the respiratory membrane increases when...","choices":["the membrane is considerably thicker and the available surface area is smaller","the partial-pressure gradient across the membrane is minimal","surface area and the partial-pressure gradient are large and the distance is small","the gas has a very high molecular weight together with a very low solubility"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: diffusion rises with greater area and pressure gradient and shorter diffusion distance, per Fick's principle.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 11, 62"},{"q":"The respiratory membrane is well suited for gas exchange largely because it is...","choices":["richly pigmented so that it can absorb oxygen directly out of the inspired air","thick and muscular so it can withstand high pulmonary pressures","extremely thin (about 0.2 micrometers) with a very large total surface area","lined with beating cilia that actively pump the inspired gases across its surface"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: the membrane is only ~0.2 um thick and spans a huge alveolar surface area, ideal for rapid diffusion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"Central chemoreceptors in the brainstem adjust ventilation mainly in response to...","choices":["changes in CO2 and H+ within the surrounding brain fluid","changes in arterial oxygen sensed directly within the medulla","blood pressure changes detected at the carotid sinus baroreceptors","stretch signals arriving from receptors located in the lung"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: central chemoreceptors respond primarily to CO2 and H+ in brain extracellular fluid, the strongest minute-to-minute drive.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91, 96"},{"q":"The carotid and aortic bodies are especially important for detecting...","choices":["the pH of the cerebrospinal fluid around the medulla","a rise in brain interstitial carbon dioxide concentration","stretch of the airway smooth muscle during inspiration","a fall in the arterial partial pressure of oxygen"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct: peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies are the main sensors of low arterial oxygen.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95, 97"},{"q":"Nearly all of the oxygen in blood is carried...","choices":["chemically combined with plasma proteins other than hemoglobin","dissolved in the plasma, with hemoglobin contributing very little","bound to hemoglobin, with only a small fraction dissolved in plasma","as bicarbonate formed from the reaction of oxygen and water"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: the great majority of oxygen is carried on hemoglobin; only a small amount is physically dissolved.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"The flat upper portion of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve means that...","choices":["hemoglobin stays highly saturated even when alveolar PO2 falls somewhat","small drops in PO2 cause large drops in saturation within the lungs","oxygen loading depends only on the amount dissolved in plasma","hemoglobin releases all its oxygen the instant PO2 begins to fall"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: on the plateau, saturation remains high despite moderate falls in PO2, providing a loading safety margin in the lungs.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 78-80"},{"q":"A rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve in exercising muscle...","choices":["increases hemoglobin's oxygen affinity so it holds oxygen more tightly","promotes oxygen unloading where tissue CO2, acid, and temperature are high","occurs only in the lungs to speed the loading of oxygen","prevents any oxygen from being released to the surrounding tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: a rightward shift lowers affinity, enhancing oxygen release in active tissues with high CO2, low pH, and heat.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 81"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide impairs oxygen delivery because it...","choices":["destroys the heme iron so that hemoglobin can never re-form","binds hemoglobin far more tightly than oxygen, blocking the O2 sites","dissolves oxygen out of the plasma into the expired air","stimulates excessive oxygen release before blood reaches the tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: carbon monoxide binds hemoglobin with much greater affinity than oxygen, occupying binding sites and reducing O2 carriage.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 82"},{"q":"Most carbon dioxide is transported from the tissues to the lungs...","choices":["bound directly to the heme iron of hemoglobin in place of oxygen molecules","as carbonic acid molecules that circulate freely throughout the plasma","as bicarbonate formed after carbonic anhydrase acts within red cells","dissolved unchanged in the plasma as free carbon dioxide gas"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct: the majority of CO2 travels as bicarbonate, generated when carbonic anhydrase in red cells hydrates CO2.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83, 86"},{"q":"The Haldane effect describes how...","choices":["carbon monoxide competitively displaces carbon dioxide out of the plasma","oxygenating hemoglobin in the lungs promotes the release of carbon dioxide","high carbon dioxide levels force hemoglobin to bind still more oxygen molecules","bicarbonate physically prevents hemoglobin from carrying oxygen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct: the Haldane effect is that binding oxygen reduces hemoglobin's affinity for CO2, aiding CO2 release in the lungs.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 85"},{"q":"A rise in arterial carbon dioxide increases ventilation, which in turn...","choices":["lowers CO2 and raises pH back toward the normal range","raises CO2 even further and drives the pH downward","raises pH by retaining additional carbonic acid in the blood","has no measurable effect on blood pH under any circumstance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: increased ventilation blows off CO2, reducing carbonic acid and returning pH toward normal.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"At the tissue level, gas exchange occurs because...","choices":["O2 diffuses from blood into cells while CO2 diffuses from cells into blood","both oxygen and carbon dioxide diffuse from the cells into the blood","oxygen moves from cells to blood while carbon dioxide moves from blood to cells","gases move only when they are actively pumped across the capillary wall"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct: tissue PO2 is low and PCO2 is high, so oxygen moves into cells and carbon dioxide moves into blood down their gradients.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 72-73"}]},"physio-master-v6":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v6)","questions":[{"q":"Which best describes a functional distinction between plasma proteins and the formed elements of blood?","choices":["Plasma proteins clot the blood on their own, while the formed elements neutralize all invading toxins","Plasma proteins such as albumin generate colloid osmotic pressure, while red cells transport oxygen","Plasma proteins carry oxygen, while the formed elements maintain colloid osmotic pressure","Plasma proteins buffer carbon dioxide, while the formed elements dissolve dietary lipids"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Albumin and the other plasma proteins are too large to cross the capillary wall freely, so they hold water in the vasculature and create colloid (oncotic) osmotic pressure; the formed element responsible for oxygen carriage is the red cell, via hemoglobin. The two therefore serve genuinely different roles.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"The biconcave disc shape of the red blood cell chiefly benefits its function by...","choices":["providing rigidity so the cell resists rupture in high-pressure arteries","maximizing surface area for gas exchange and allowing deformation through narrow capillaries","increasing its internal volume so that it can store a large amount of extra dissolved oxygen","creating a nucleus-rich center that supports rapid ongoing cell division"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The biconcave geometry gives a high surface-area-to-volume ratio (short diffusion distances for O2 and CO2) and lets the cell fold to squeeze through capillaries narrower than its own diameter, both of which optimize gas transport.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Each gram of hemoglobin binds about 1.34 mL of O2. Why does anemia lower oxygen delivery even when arterial PO2 is normal?","choices":["Less hemoglobin is available to bind oxygen, so the oxygen content per volume of blood falls","Anemia saturates the remaining hemoglobin so tightly that it cannot release oxygen","Low hemoglobin somehow raises arterial PO2 but then blocks oxygen from leaving the plasma","Fewer red cells increase plasma viscosity, which physically traps the oxygen under these conditions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Oxygen content depends on how much hemoglobin is present, not just on PO2. With fewer grams of hemoglobin, each unit of blood carries fewer milliliters of O2 even though PO2 (and therefore saturation) is normal, so delivery drops.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"A markedly elevated hematocrit (as in polycythemia) tends to...","choices":["raise blood viscosity, increasing the resistance the heart must pump against","have no effect on flow because viscosity depends only on the plasma","reduce oxygen-carrying capacity by crowding out the plasma proteins","lower blood viscosity markedly, easing the overall workload placed on the heart"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Viscosity rises steeply as hematocrit climbs; thicker blood increases vascular resistance, so the heart must generate more pressure to maintain flow. This is why very high hematocrits strain the circulation.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"Most of the erythropoietin that drives red cell production is released from the...","choices":["spleen, as it continually breaks down senescent red blood cells","liver, in direct response to a rising red blood cell count","bone marrow, whenever iron stores in the body run low","kidneys, in response to reduced oxygen delivery to renal tissue"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The kidneys are the principal source of erythropoietin; specialized cells sense reduced oxygen delivery and secrete EPO, which stimulates marrow erythropoiesis to restore oxygen-carrying capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"When senescent red cells are broken down, most of their iron is...","choices":["lost through the kidneys and must be fully replaced by diet each day","excreted unchanged in the bile as the body's main iron-removal route","converted into bilirubin so it can be stored in the liver","recycled by macrophages and returned to the marrow for new hemoglobin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages of the reticuloendothelial system phagocytize old red cells, salvage the iron, and return it (via transferrin) to the marrow, so the body reuses iron efficiently rather than relying on daily intake.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Immediately after a vessel is cut, the first hemostatic response is...","choices":["conversion of prothrombin to thrombin throughout the plasma","fibrin cross-linking that seals the wound within seconds","vascular spasm that constricts the vessel and limits blood loss","release of erythropoietin to replace the lost red cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The earliest response is immediate vascular spasm (myogenic, neural, and local factors), which narrows the vessel and reduces blood loss even before the platelet plug and coagulation cascade take over.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34-40"},{"q":"When platelets contact exposed collagen, they become activated and...","choices":["release ADP and thromboxane A2 that recruit and activate additional platelets","release plasmin that immediately begins dissolving the clot as it forms","secrete erythropoietin that stimulates the marrow to replace them","absorb calcium so it cannot participate in the clotting cascade during this particular process"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Activated platelets undergo the release reaction, secreting ADP and thromboxane A2; these recruit and activate more platelets, creating positive feedback that builds the platelet plug at the injury site.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 34"},{"q":"Thrombin is central to coagulation because it...","choices":["acts only on platelets and has no effect on plasma clotting proteins","directly digests fibrin strands to keep the growing clot from spreading","binds circulating vitamin K directly so that new clotting factors can then be manufactured","converts fibrinogen to fibrin and also activates factors that accelerate its own formation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Thrombin cleaves fibrinogen into fibrin and additionally activates factors (and platelets) upstream, creating positive feedback that accelerates further thrombin generation and rapidly amplifies the clot.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Days after a clot forms, it is dissolved when plasminogen is converted to...","choices":["plasmin, which digests the fibrin meshwork of the clot","thrombin, which reinforces the fibrin meshwork further","fibrinogen, which is redeposited to enlarge the clot","prothrombin activator, which restarts the clotting cascade"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Plasminogen incorporated into the clot is activated to plasmin, a protease that breaks down fibrin (fibrinolysis), clearing the clot once the vessel has healed.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-48"},{"q":"Neutrophils are the body's first cellular responders to bacterial infection because they...","choices":["secrete antibodies that specifically neutralize the invading bacteria","live for months in tissues, waiting to present antigen to lymphocytes","mature slowly in the tissue before they can begin any phagocytosis","are numerous, circulate ready to act, and rapidly phagocytize bacteria"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Neutrophils are the most abundant circulating white cell and are already mature, so they marginate, undergo diapedesis, and phagocytize bacteria within about an hour of infection, making them the earliest cellular defense.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 3-13, 28-30"},{"q":"Eosinophils are especially important in defending against...","choices":["fungal spores, which they engulf through receptor-mediated endocytosis","intracellular viruses, which they lyse using secreted perforins","parasitic worms, which they attack by releasing toxic granule proteins","extracellular bacteria, which they clear mainly by opsonization"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Eosinophils specialize against large parasites such as helminths; they attach to the worm and release toxic granule contents (including major basic protein) that damage it, since the parasite is too big to phagocytize.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 33"},{"q":"Lymph nodes contribute to immunity mainly by...","choices":["manufacturing red blood cells that carry antigen to the spleen","filtering lymph and exposing trapped antigens to resident lymphocytes","secreting digestive enzymes that break down circulating pathogens","storing mature neutrophils until an infection calls them out"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As lymph percolates through the node, macrophages lining the sinuses trap antigens and present them, while resident B- and T-lymphocytes are positioned to encounter and respond to those antigens, mounting an adaptive response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22, 39"},{"q":"One way the lymphatic system supports immune surveillance is by...","choices":["pumping freshly oxygenated blood directly to the sites of active infection in the tissues","producing antibodies within the lymphatic vessels themselves before lymph returns to blood","absorbing dietary glucose and delivering it straight to lymphocytes","returning interstitial fluid and any captured antigens through nodes before reaching the blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Lymphatics collect interstitial fluid (and antigens or microbes within it) and route it through lymph nodes for immune screening before returning it to the bloodstream, so pathogens are intercepted en route.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22, 39"},{"q":"Dendritic cells are considered the most potent antigen-presenting cells because they...","choices":["secrete the antibodies that tag pathogens throughout the body for destruction","specialize in capturing antigen and displaying it to activate naive T-cells","store iron recovered from red cells for later hemoglobin synthesis","form the pores that lyse virus-infected host cells directly"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Dendritic cells are distributed throughout tissues, and their principal job is to capture antigen and present it on MHC to naive T-cells, making them the most effective initiators of adaptive responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 55"},{"q":"Why does loss of helper T-cells (as in advanced HIV) cripple the whole immune response?","choices":["Helper T-cells release cytokines that coordinate both antibody and cytotoxic responses","Helper T-cells are the only cells able to directly phagocytize bacteria","Helper T-cells physically block viruses from entering any host cells in the body","Helper T-cells manufacture essentially all of the body's circulating complement proteins"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Helper (CD4) T-cells secrete cytokines/lymphokines that stimulate B-cell antibody production, cytotoxic T-cell activity, and macrophage function; without them, the coordinated adaptive response collapses, which is why CD4 loss is so devastating.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 57-58"},{"q":"Which statement about antibody isotypes is correct?","choices":["IgG appears first, while IgM is the antibody of allergic reactions","IgM appears first in a response, while IgG is the most abundant in plasma","IgA is produced only after IgG and functions inside infected cells","IgE is the most abundant plasma antibody and mainly drives agglutination"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. IgM is the earliest antibody produced in a primary response (and is a large pentamer with many binding sites), whereas IgG makes up roughly three-quarters of plasma immunoglobulin and dominates the later and secondary responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 51"},{"q":"Receiving preformed antibodies (for example, across the placenta) provides...","choices":["passive immunity that is immediate but temporary","permanent immunity through the recipient's own memory cells","innate immunity that never involves any antibodies","active immunity that is delayed but long-lasting"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Preformed antibodies protect right away because no immune response has to develop, but they are gradually degraded and no memory cells are formed, so the protection is short-lived (weeks).","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"The enormous variety of antibody specificities is generated by...","choices":["the antigen itself instructing the lymphocyte how to fold its antibody","random recombination of gene segments, producing many distinct lymphocyte clones","a single gene that mutates anew during each and every separate infection encountered","the thymus copying antibodies from previously infected individuals"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. A limited set of gene segments (cassettes) recombine in many permutations during lymphocyte development, so millions of clones each bearing a unique specificity arise from a modest number of genes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 44"},{"q":"Self-tolerance is maintained largely because lymphocyte clones that strongly react to self are...","choices":["converted into memory cells that ignore the self-antigen","coated with antibody so that they cannot reach any host tissue","stored in lymph nodes and activated only during infection","deleted by apoptosis during development in the thymus or marrow"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Developing T-cells in the thymus and B-cells in the marrow that bind self-antigens with high affinity are induced to undergo apoptosis (clonal deletion), removing most self-reactive clones and preventing autoimmunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 41, 61"},{"q":"Slow waves in gastrointestinal smooth muscle determine the...","choices":["rate at which the exocrine pancreas releases its digestive enzymes into the gut","absolute strength of every contraction regardless of neural input","maximum frequency and timing of contractions, though not every wave triggers one","the rate of gastric acid secretion coming from the stomach's parietal cells during a meal"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Slow waves are rhythmic oscillations in membrane potential set by the interstitial cells of Cajal; they set when contractions can occur, but an actual contraction happens only if the wave reaches threshold with spike potentials, so they pace but do not force every contraction.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 35-39"},{"q":"As a meal enters the stomach, receptive relaxation allows it to...","choices":["immediately propel all contents into the duodenum at once","absorb most nutrients before they reach the small intestine","secrete bile to begin the early emulsification of dietary fat","accommodate a large volume with little rise in internal pressure"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. A vagovagal reflex relaxes the orad stomach (mediated by NO and VIP) so it can expand to hold a meal without a large pressure increase, storing food for gradual processing and controlled emptying.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 44, 46"},{"q":"Cholecystokinin, released in response to fat and protein in the duodenum, acts to...","choices":["contract the gallbladder and stimulate pancreatic enzyme secretion","trigger mass movements that empty the distal colon in the body under most conditions","relax the gallbladder while inhibiting all pancreatic secretion","stimulate parietal cells to secrete their maximal load of acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. CCK from duodenal I-cells is the principal signal that contracts the gallbladder (and relaxes the sphincter of Oddi) while strongly stimulating pancreatic enzyme release, delivering bile and enzymes to digest fat and protein.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15"},{"q":"Final digestion of disaccharides such as lactose occurs...","choices":["within the pancreatic duct before the sugars reach the intestine","in the mouth, where salivary amylase completes their breakdown","at the brush border, where membrane-bound enzymes split them into monosaccharides","in the stomach, where gastric acid hydrolyzes them completely into free glucose units"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Disaccharidases such as lactase, sucrase, and maltase are fixed on the intestinal brush border; they perform the final step of carbohydrate digestion, splitting disaccharides into absorbable monosaccharides right at the absorptive surface.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 123-125"},{"q":"Enterohepatic circulation conserves bile salts by...","choices":["converting them into cholesterol for storage in the gallbladder","reabsorbing most of them in the ileum and returning them to the liver","secreting them into the urine for later reabsorption by the kidney","excreting nearly all of them in the feces after a single use"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. About 95% of secreted bile salts are actively reabsorbed in the terminal ileum, enter the portal blood, and are taken back up by hepatocytes for re-secretion, so the same pool is reused several times per meal and only a small fraction is lost in feces.","cite":"GI Physiology (bile), Ch 71 Liver, slide 25"},{"q":"The pancreatic bicarbonate response to a meal is driven mainly by...","choices":["gastrin, released as protein stretches the stomach wall","secretin, released when acidic chyme lowers the duodenal pH","insulin, released as blood glucose rises after eating","motilin, released cyclically during the fasting state"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. When acidic chyme enters the duodenum and pH falls below about 4.5, S-cells release secretin, which stimulates the pancreatic ducts to secrete a bicarbonate-rich fluid that neutralizes the acid and protects the mucosa.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 106-109"},{"q":"The liver prepares bilirubin for excretion by...","choices":["oxidizing it into iron that is then returned to the bone marrow","binding it tightly to intrinsic factor for its absorption in the ileum","conjugating it with glucuronic acid to make it water-soluble for bile","converting it into a bile salt that emulsifies dietary fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Hepatocytes conjugate lipid-soluble (unconjugated) bilirubin with glucuronic acid, converting it to a water-soluble (conjugated) form that can be excreted into bile; impaired conjugation or excretion causes jaundice.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-16"},{"q":"Which statement about protein absorption is correct?","choices":["Di- and tripeptides are absorbed by their own carrier, then split inside the cell","Only free amino acids can be absorbed, since peptides are never taken up at all","Peptides are absorbed intact into blood without any further breakdown","Protein absorption occurs mainly in the stomach alongside pepsin action"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. In addition to amino-acid transporters, the enterocyte has a distinct carrier for di- and tripeptides (which is actually faster); once inside, cytoplasmic peptidases hydrolyze these small peptides to free amino acids before they enter the blood.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 127-129"},{"q":"Micelles improve fat absorption by...","choices":["carrying absorbed fat directly into the portal blood as chylomicrons","ferrying poorly soluble fatty acids and monoglycerides to the enterocyte surface","actively transporting whole fat droplets across the cell membrane","chemically converting the triglycerides into small water-soluble sugars for uptake"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Bile-salt micelles solubilize the products of fat digestion (fatty acids, monoglycerides, cholesterol) and shuttle them across the unstirred water layer to the brush border, where they are released to diffuse into the enterocyte.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 132-133"},{"q":"By the time colonic contents approach the rectum, the large intestine has primarily...","choices":["added large volumes of bile to emulsify the residual dietary fat still present","secreted digestive enzymes to complete nutrient breakdown","absorbed most of the remaining water and electrolytes to form solid feces","absorbed the bulk of dietary glucose and amino acids"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The main function of the colon is to reabsorb water and electrolytes from the residual chyme, progressively concentrating it into formed feces before it reaches the rectum to trigger the defecation reflex.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"A hallmark synthetic function of the liver is production of...","choices":["insulin and glucagon that closely regulate blood glucose","plasma proteins such as albumin and most clotting factors","digestive amylase secreted into the small intestine","erythropoietin that stimulates red cell production"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The liver synthesizes the majority of plasma proteins, including albumin (the main determinant of colloid osmotic pressure) and most coagulation factors, which is why liver disease produces both edema and bleeding tendencies.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 2, 11"},{"q":"The liver serves as a major storage site for...","choices":["digestive enzymes awaiting release into the duodenum","glycogen, iron, and several fat-soluble vitamins","oxygen bound to hemoglobin for release during exercise","mature lymphocytes ready to fight infection"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The liver stores glycogen (a glucose reserve), iron (as ferritin), and fat-soluble vitamins such as A and D, acting as a central metabolic warehouse the body can draw on between meals.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 2, 8"},{"q":"Muscle and adipose tissue increase glucose uptake after a meal because insulin...","choices":["converts glucose directly into ATP inside the blood","opens voltage-gated channels that let glucose diffuse freely","stimulates the liver to release stored oxygen","recruits GLUT4 transporters to the cell membrane"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Insulin stimulates translocation of GLUT4 glucose transporters from intracellular vesicles to the plasma membrane of muscle and fat cells, greatly increasing their glucose uptake; this is why these tissues clear glucose after meals in an insulin-dependent way.","cite":"Ch 68, slide 4"},{"q":"Phosphorylating glucose to glucose-6-phosphate as it enters a cell serves to...","choices":["signal the pancreas to stop secreting insulin into the bloodstream right away","convert glucose into fat for long-term storage","release energy that the cell immediately uses for contraction","trap glucose inside the cell by preventing it from diffusing back out"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Adding a charged phosphate group keeps glucose from crossing the membrane back out, effectively trapping it inside so it is committed to intracellular metabolism (glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, or the pentose pathway).","cite":"Ch 68, slides 6-7"},{"q":"In the Cori cycle, lactate produced by exercising muscle is...","choices":["carried to the liver and converted back to glucose","stored in muscle indefinitely as a backup fuel","converted directly into fatty acids within the muscle","excreted by the kidney as the body's main disposal route"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Lactate generated by anaerobic muscle travels in the blood to the liver, where gluconeogenesis converts it back to glucose; that glucose can then return to the muscle, shifting the metabolic burden of lactate disposal to the liver.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 25-27; Ch 73, slide 4"},{"q":"Very-low-density lipoprotein (VLDL) is produced by the liver mainly to...","choices":["carry dietary fat absorbed directly from the intestine","return excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver","export triglycerides, largely made from carbohydrate, to peripheral tissues","deliver dissolved oxygen to the working tissues during periods of heavy exercise"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The liver packages triglycerides (much of it synthesized from excess carbohydrate) into VLDL and exports them to peripheral tissues, where lipoprotein lipase releases fatty acids for use or storage.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 6"},{"q":"The body's main route for eliminating cholesterol is...","choices":["exhalation of cholesterol breakdown products as carbon dioxide","storage of all excess cholesterol permanently in muscle","conversion to bile acids that are excreted in the feces","filtration of intact cholesterol by the kidneys into urine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The liver converts cholesterol into bile acids, and cholesterol/bile acids lost in feces represent the body's principal excretory route; this is why binding bile salts in the gut (as fiber does) can lower plasma cholesterol.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 36; Ch 71, slides 23, 25"},{"q":"Insulin promotes fat storage in part by...","choices":["inhibiting hormone-sensitive lipase so stored triglyceride is not broken down","blocking lipoprotein lipase so tissues cannot take up fat","activating hormone-sensitive lipase to release fatty acids","stimulating ketone body production from the mobilized fatty acids in the liver"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Insulin suppresses hormone-sensitive lipase in adipocytes, preventing breakdown of stored triglyceride, while it also stimulates lipoprotein lipase and fatty-acid synthesis, together favoring net fat storage in the fed state.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 22; Ch 73, slide 15"},{"q":"Nonessential amino acids differ from essential ones in that the body can...","choices":["synthesize them, often by transamination onto a carbon skeleton","store them long-term, unlike the essential amino acids","excrete them directly in the urine, bypassing the whole urea cycle","absorb them without any carrier, unlike essential ones"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Nonessential amino acids can be made in the body, typically by transferring an amino group (transamination, using a vitamin B6-derived cofactor) onto an appropriate carbon skeleton such as pyruvate or a TCA intermediate; essential amino acids cannot be synthesized and must come from the diet.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 7-11"},{"q":"Amino acids that are degraded to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA are termed ketogenic because they...","choices":["release ammonia that is directly excreted by the lungs","give rise to ketone bodies rather than to new glucose","are used only to build new proteins, never for fuel","can be converted into glucose through gluconeogenesis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Ketogenic amino acids feed into acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA, which can form ketone bodies but cannot be used to make net glucose (since acetyl-CoA cannot be converted back to pyruvate for gluconeogenesis).","cite":"Ch 70, slide 18"},{"q":"Sustained positive energy balance (intake exceeding output) leads to...","choices":["excretion of the extra calories unchanged in the urine","an immediate rise in basal metabolic rate that burns it off","storage of the surplus energy, primarily as body fat","conversion of the excess directly into muscle protein"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. When intake chronically exceeds expenditure, the extra energy is deposited, overwhelmingly as triglyceride in adipose tissue, which is the body's largest and most efficient energy store; this is the fundamental basis of weight gain.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 2-3"},{"q":"Short-term meal termination is promoted by signals such as...","choices":["ghrelin rising steadily throughout the meal","leptin secreted by fat cells over days to weeks","a steady fall in blood glucose occurring throughout the course of the meal","gastric distension and CCK release acting through vagal afferents"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. As the stomach fills, stretch is signaled by vagal afferents, and fat/protein in the duodenum releases CCK; together these short-term signals promote satiety and help end the meal, acting over minutes rather than days.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 11"},{"q":"Leptin is best described as a signal that...","choices":["triggers hunger within minutes of the stomach emptying","is released mainly by the stomach in order to help initiate each separate meal","reports the size of fat stores and reduces appetite over the long term","directly digests dietary fat within the lumen of the small intestine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Leptin is secreted by adipocytes in proportion to fat mass; higher stores mean more leptin, which acts on the hypothalamus to reduce appetite and increase expenditure, providing long-term regulation of body weight.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 13-15"},{"q":"Which statement about body temperature is correct?","choices":["Skin temperature stays constant while core temperature swings widely","Neither core nor skin temperature is regulated in any way by the hypothalamus at all","Both the core and the skin temperature change together and equally with the surroundings","Core temperature stays nearly constant while skin temperature varies with the environment"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The deep-body (core) temperature is tightly regulated and varies by less than about a degree under normal conditions, whereas skin (shell) temperature fluctuates widely as it exchanges heat with the surroundings.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 2-4"},{"q":"When ambient temperature exceeds skin temperature, the only effective route of heat loss becomes...","choices":["conduction of heat into the warmer surrounding air","radiation of infrared waves to the surroundings","evaporation of sweat from the skin surface","convection carrying heat away from the body"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Once the environment is warmer than the skin, radiation, conduction, and convection can no longer remove heat (they add it), so evaporation of sweat becomes the body's only effective avenue of heat loss.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6-9"},{"q":"Shivering raises body temperature by...","choices":["shunting warm blood from the core to the skin surface","increasing evaporative water loss from the airways and skin","producing heat through rapid, involuntary muscle contractions","lowering the hypothalamic set point toward the cold"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Shivering is driven by the hypothalamic motor center for shivering; rapid involuntary muscle contractions generate substantial metabolic heat (potentially several-fold above resting), warming the body in the cold.","cite":"Ch 74, slide 15"},{"q":"To conserve heat in the cold, sympathetic signals cause skin blood vessels to...","choices":["constrict, reducing heat transfer from the core to the surface","leak plasma into tissues to insulate the body","dilate widely, bringing much more warm blood to the skin surface","increase sweating to trap a warm surface layer"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Sympathetic activation produces cutaneous vasoconstriction, cutting blood flow to the skin so that less core heat is carried to the surface where it could be lost; the skin radiator is effectively turned down.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 11-14"},{"q":"Indirect calorimetry estimates metabolic rate by measuring...","choices":["the carbon dioxide dissolved in the arterial blood under these conditions","the heat radiated directly from the whole body surface over time","the total nitrogen excreted in the urine over a day","oxygen consumption, since most energy release depends on oxygen use"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Because about 95% of the body's energy release comes from reactions consuming oxygen, oxygen consumption is a reliable proxy for metabolic rate; indirect calorimetry measures O2 use rather than heat directly.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 7"},{"q":"Thyroid hormone influences metabolic rate by...","choices":["acting only on skeletal muscle during exercise","having no measurable effect on basal metabolism","raising the resting metabolic rate of most body tissues","lowering metabolic rate to conserve energy during fasting"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Thyroid hormone increases the metabolic activity of nearly all tissues, raising basal metabolic rate and heat production; this is why thyroid status is a major determinant of BMR.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 9"},{"q":"One reason men tend to have a higher basal metabolic rate than women is...","choices":["a somewhat lower body temperature that tends to speed up reactions","the absence of any thermic effect from their food","a higher ratio of metabolically active lean muscle to fat","a smaller total body surface area losing less heat"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Lean muscle is more metabolically active than fat, and men on average carry a higher muscle-to-fat ratio (linked to testosterone), which raises their resting energy expenditure relative to women.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 9, 11"},{"q":"The principal muscle responsible for quiet inspiration is the...","choices":["internal intercostal group, which actively pulls the ribs downward","diaphragm, whose contraction increases the vertical dimension of the thorax","abdominal wall, which pushes the diaphragm upward to draw in air","sternocleidomastoid muscle, which is said to be the primary driver at rest"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. During quiet breathing the diaphragm does most of the work; its contraction flattens the dome and lengthens the thoracic cavity, lowering intrapleural and alveolar pressure so air flows in.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"During quiet breathing, expiration is normally...","choices":["passive, driven by elastic recoil of the lungs and chest wall","active, requiring forceful contraction of the diaphragm","dependent on surfactant pushing air out of the alveoli","produced entirely by the external intercostal muscles alone"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. At rest, expiration requires no muscular effort: when the inspiratory muscles relax, the stored elastic recoil of the lungs and chest wall passively returns them to resting volume, pushing air out.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"The lung's tendency to recoil inward comes from...","choices":["the rigidity of the surrounding bony rib cage and vertebral column","active contraction of smooth muscle lining each alveolus","elastic fibers in lung tissue together with alveolar surface tension","positive pressure generated within the pleural space during this particular process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Two factors create recoil: the elastin and collagen of lung tissue, and the surface tension of the fluid lining the alveoli. Surface tension actually contributes the larger share of recoil, which is why surfactant (which reduces it) is so important.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19-20"},{"q":"A lung that is stiffer than normal (low compliance) requires...","choices":["less effort to inflate because it fills more readily","a greater change in pressure to achieve a given increase in volume","no change at all in the work of breathing under these conditions","a smaller pressure change to reach the same volume in the body under most conditions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Compliance is volume change per unit pressure change; a low-compliance (stiff) lung needs a larger pressure change to inflate by the same amount, which increases the work of breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 14, 19"},{"q":"Tidal volume refers to the amount of air...","choices":["moved into or out of the lungs during a single normal breath","remaining in the lungs after the most forceful expiration","in the lungs at the very end of a maximal inspiration","that can be inspired beyond a normal quiet inspiration"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Tidal volume is the volume inspired or expired with each ordinary quiet breath (about 500 mL at rest); the other volumes describe reserves beyond it or the air that cannot be exhaled.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 27-31"},{"q":"Functional residual capacity is the volume of air...","choices":["inspired maximally after a normal inspiration","expelled during a single normal resting breath","moved into and out per minute during ordinary breathing","remaining in the lungs after a normal, quiet expiration"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. FRC is the air left in the lungs at the end of a normal tidal expiration, equal to expiratory reserve volume plus residual volume; it represents the resting equilibrium volume where lung recoil and chest-wall recoil balance.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 30"},{"q":"Alveolar ventilation is always less than total minute ventilation because...","choices":["the alveoli are able to exchange gas only during the expiratory phase","part of each breath fills conducting airways that do no gas exchange","oxygen is consumed before air can reach the alveoli","dead-space air is the only air that reaches the blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Each tidal breath must first fill the anatomic dead space (~150 mL of conducting airway), and that air never reaches the alveoli for exchange, so the ventilation available for gas exchange (alveolar ventilation) is less than the total minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"Pulmonary surfactant is produced by...","choices":["alveolar macrophages that also clear inhaled debris","type I alveolar cells, forming the main gas-exchange surface","goblet cells lining the large conducting airways under these conditions","type II alveolar cells and lowers surface tension in the alveoli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Type II alveolar (pneumocyte) cells secrete surfactant, a phospholipid-rich material that lowers alveolar surface tension, stabilizes alveoli of different sizes, and reduces the work of breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Ventilation-perfusion matching improves gas exchange by...","choices":["aligning airflow and blood flow so alveoli are neither wasted nor underused","sending essentially all blood flow to the very apex of the upright lung","ensuring blood always flows to alveoli that receive no air during this particular process","keeping ventilation constant regardless of local blood flow"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Efficient exchange requires that alveolar ventilation and capillary perfusion be matched; local mechanisms (such as hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction) direct blood toward well-ventilated alveoli, minimizing both wasted ventilation and wasted perfusion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 43, 64-65"},{"q":"Which correctly lists a barrier that O2 crosses at the respiratory membrane?","choices":["several thick layers of contractile smooth muscle that surround each individual alveolus","a thick plate of cartilage that structurally supports each alveolar wall","a mucus-secreting ciliated epithelium lining the alveolus","the alveolar epithelium, a thin interstitial space, and the capillary endothelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Oxygen diffuses through the surfactant/fluid layer, the alveolar epithelium, a fused basement-membrane/interstitial space, and the capillary endothelium (then plasma and red-cell membrane). The whole barrier is only about 0.2 micrometers thick.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"The basic rhythm of quiet breathing is generated in the...","choices":["carotid bodies located at the carotid bifurcation","phrenic nerve endings within the diaphragm","medullary respiratory centers of the brainstem","cerebral cortex during all resting breaths"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The fundamental respiratory rhythm arises from networks in the medulla oblongata; these brainstem centers drive the cycle of inspiration and expiration, with modulation from the pons, chemoreceptors, and higher centers.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 88-90"},{"q":"Under normal conditions, the strongest minute-to-minute stimulus for breathing is...","choices":["stretch of the diaphragm occurring during each and every inspiration","a rise in arterial CO2, sensed largely by central chemoreceptors","a rise in arterial blood pressure at the aortic arch","a small fall in arterial oxygen sensed by the medulla"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Small increases in arterial CO2 (via the H+ they generate in brain fluid) powerfully stimulate central chemoreceptors, making CO2 the dominant normal drive to breathe; the oxygen drive becomes important only when PO2 falls substantially.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 96"},{"q":"The Bohr effect describes how increased CO2 and H+ in active tissue...","choices":["shift the curve rightward, helping hemoglobin release more oxygen","shift the curve leftward, making hemoglobin hold oxygen tightly","convert oxygen into bicarbonate for transport in the body under most conditions","prevent hemoglobin from binding any oxygen in the lungs"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The Bohr effect is the rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve caused by higher CO2, higher H+ (lower pH), and higher temperature in metabolically active tissue; the reduced affinity promotes oxygen unloading exactly where it is needed.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 81"},{"q":"Factors such as increased temperature, CO2, and acidity in metabolically active tissue tend to...","choices":["promote oxygen unloading from hemoglobin where it is most needed","reduce oxygen unloading, sparing oxygen for later use","block hemoglobin from picking up any oxygen at all in the lungs","increase hemoglobin's affinity so it retains its oxygen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. These conditions mark actively metabolizing tissue and shift the oxygen-hemoglobin curve rightward, lowering affinity so hemoglobin releases more oxygen precisely at the tissues that are working hardest.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-81"},{"q":"Two blood samples can have the same arterial PO2 but different oxygen content if they differ in...","choices":["the pH, which does not affect oxygen content","hemoglobin concentration, which sets how much oxygen the blood carries","the temperature of the surrounding plasma alone, independent of hemoglobin","the amount of dissolved carbon dioxide only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. PO2 determines saturation, but total oxygen content also depends on how much hemoglobin is present. An anemic sample and a normal sample at the same PO2 can be equally saturated yet carry very different amounts of oxygen because they differ in hemoglobin.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell in exchange for chloride (the chloride shift), the purpose is to...","choices":["maintain electrical balance as CO2 is converted for transport","generate ATP for the red cell's own energy needs","bind oxygen more tightly to the hemoglobin inside the red cell","prevent bicarbonate from ever entering the plasma"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase generates bicarbonate inside the red cell; as HCO3- diffuses out into plasma, chloride moves in to preserve electrical neutrality (the chloride shift), allowing large amounts of CO2 to be carried as plasma bicarbonate.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 86-87"},{"q":"Carbon dioxide is transported in blood in three forms; the largest fraction travels as...","choices":["carbonic acid contained within the red blood cells","bicarbonate ions dissolved in the plasma","dissolved CO2 gas in the plasma","carbaminohemoglobin bound to globin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The majority of CO2 (about 70%) is carried as bicarbonate formed after carbonic anhydrase hydrates CO2 in red cells; smaller fractions travel bound to hemoglobin (carbamino, ~23%) or dissolved as free CO2 (~7%).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-86"},{"q":"When metabolic acid accumulates in the blood, the respiratory system compensates by...","choices":["increasing bicarbonate excretion through the lungs","holding ventilation constant since breathing cannot affect pH","increasing ventilation to blow off CO2 and raise pH","decreasing ventilation to retain CO2 and lower pH"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Excess H+ stimulates ventilation; by exhaling more CO2, the body reduces carbonic acid, which raises pH back toward normal. This respiratory compensation partially offsets a metabolic acidosis.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"Central chemoreceptors respond to blood CO2 indirectly because CO2...","choices":["is sensed only after it has been converted into oxygen in the brain","cannot cross into the brain and must be sensed peripherally","binds directly to the chemoreceptor without any change","crosses into brain fluid and forms H+, which the receptors detect"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. CO2 readily crosses the blood-brain barrier into the brain extracellular fluid, where carbonic anhydrase converts it to carbonic acid and then H+; the central chemoreceptors actually sense that H+, giving CO2 its powerful (if indirect) effect on ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91, 96-98"},{"q":"Oxygen moves from capillary blood into a metabolizing cell because...","choices":["the cell actively pumps oxygen across its membrane","carbon dioxide actively pushes the oxygen into the cell","blood PO2 is always lower than the cell's PO2","the cell's PO2 is lower than that of the arriving blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Actively metabolizing cells consume oxygen, keeping intracellular PO2 low; oxygen therefore diffuses down its partial-pressure gradient from the higher-PO2 capillary blood into the cell, with no active transport required.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 71-73"}]},"physio-master-v7":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v7)","questions":[{"q":"Blood serves three broad roles — transport, regulation, and protection. Which pairing correctly matches a component to one of these roles?","choices":["Platelets transport dietary nutrients, while the red cells are what defend against infection","Red cells carry out transport of oxygen, while platelets and clotting proteins provide protection","White cells regulate body temperature, while plasma proteins carry oxygen","Plasma dissolves most oxygen for transport, while the red cells are what actually clot the blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Red cells (via hemoglobin) exemplify the transport role by carrying oxygen, while platelets and plasma clotting proteins serve the protective role by sealing damaged vessels; each component maps to a distinct one of blood's broad functions.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-6"},{"q":"Hemoglobin concentration is normally reported around 15 g/dL. This value reflects...","choices":["the fraction of hemoglobin currently bound to oxygen","the number of white cells circulating per microliter","the percentage of blood volume made up of red cells","the amount of oxygen-binding protein per volume of blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin concentration measures how much oxygen-carrying protein is present per unit volume of blood; since each gram binds about 1.34 mL of O2, this value largely determines the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"The sigmoid (S-shaped) oxygen-hemoglobin curve reflects that...","choices":["oxygen binding is entirely independent at each of the four sites","hemoglobin binds oxygen and carbon dioxide at the identical site","binding of one oxygen molecule increases hemoglobin's affinity for the next","each hemoglobin molecule can bind only a single oxygen at any given time"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin binds oxygen cooperatively: attachment of one O2 changes the molecule's conformation and raises its affinity for subsequent O2, producing the characteristic S-shaped curve that favors loading in the lungs and unloading at tissues.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 21"},{"q":"All blood cell lines ultimately arise from...","choices":["circulating monocytes that divide within the blood","pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow","endothelial cells lining the marrow sinusoids","mature lymphocytes that dedifferentiate in the spleen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Every blood cell lineage — red cells, all white cells, and platelets — derives from pluripotent hematopoietic stem cells in the marrow, which give rise to committed progenitors under the influence of specific growth factors.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-16"},{"q":"Adequate red cell production depends on vitamin B12, whose absorption in turn requires...","choices":["intrinsic factor secreted by the gastric parietal cells","pancreatic amylase acting in the duodenum","bile salts released from the gallbladder under these conditions","erythropoietin that is produced mainly by the kidneys"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vitamin B12 must bind intrinsic factor, made by gastric parietal cells, to be absorbed in the terminal ileum; loss of intrinsic factor (as in atrophic gastritis) causes B12 deficiency and the impaired red-cell maturation of pernicious anemia.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17; GI B12 slides"},{"q":"Calcium ions are required at multiple steps of coagulation because they...","choices":["are the enzyme that converts prothrombin to thrombin","dissolve the clot completely once the healing process is fully complete","are needed for clotting factors to assemble on phospholipid surfaces","directly cleave fibrinogen into fibrin strands"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Calcium (factor IV) bridges vitamin K-dependent clotting factors to the negatively charged phospholipid surfaces of platelets, allowing the reaction complexes to assemble; without calcium, the cascade cannot proceed, which is why calcium chelation prevents clotting in a blood tube.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"The intrinsic pathway of coagulation is initiated when blood contacts...","choices":["erythropoietin that is secreted by the injured kidney into the blood","a negatively charged surface such as exposed subendothelial collagen","bile salts entering the bloodstream from the gut","tissue factor released from damaged extravascular cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The intrinsic (contact) pathway is triggered when blood is exposed to negatively charged surfaces like subendothelial collagen, which activates factor XII and begins the cascade using components already present in the blood.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"Once fibrin strands form, factor XIII strengthens the clot by...","choices":["cross-linking adjacent fibrin strands into a stable meshwork","activating platelets to release more thromboxane","dissolving excess fibrin to limit the clot's size","converting still more fibrinogen into new fibrin strands"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Activated fibrin-stabilizing factor (factor XIII) forms covalent cross-links between fibrin strands, converting the initially loose fibrin into a strong, stable three-dimensional meshwork that resists breakdown.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-47"},{"q":"Antithrombin III limits clotting by...","choices":["stimulating the platelets to aggregate together much faster","inactivating thrombin and other activated clotting factors","cross-linking fibrin to strengthen the clot","supplying vitamin K for new factor synthesis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Antithrombin III is a natural anticoagulant that binds and neutralizes thrombin and several other activated serine-protease factors, restraining the cascade and helping confine clot formation to the site of injury (its action is greatly accelerated by heparin).","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 48"},{"q":"Place the phases of hemostasis in their correct order.","choices":["Platelet plug, then fibrinolysis, then vascular spasm during this particular process","Coagulation first, then vascular spasm, and finally the platelet plug","Clot retraction, then platelet plug, then vascular spasm","Vascular spasm, then platelet plug, then coagulation and clot formation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Hemostasis proceeds as immediate vascular spasm, followed by formation of the platelet plug (primary hemostasis), and then the coagulation cascade producing a fibrin clot (secondary hemostasis), which is later remodeled and dissolved.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34-48"},{"q":"Circulating monocytes contribute to defense by...","choices":["forming the fibrin meshwork that walls off infection","producing antibodies against specific bacterial antigens","entering tissues and maturing into long-lived phagocytic macrophages","carrying dissolved oxygen to the sites of active infection in the tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Monocytes circulate briefly, then migrate into tissues where they enlarge and mature into macrophages — powerful, long-lived phagocytes that can ingest many organisms, clear debris, and present antigen to lymphocytes.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 13, 17, 30"},{"q":"Basophils and mast cells release histamine and heparin, which contribute to...","choices":["the inflammatory and allergic response","the direct killing of virus-infected cells","the synthesis of new antibodies in lymph nodes","the transport of oxygen within the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Basophils and their tissue counterparts, mast cells, store histamine, heparin, and other mediators; when triggered (for example, by IgE cross-linking), they degranulate, driving the vasodilation, increased permeability, and other features of inflammation and immediate allergy.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 34, 64-65"},{"q":"The spleen supports immunity mainly by...","choices":["filtering blood and removing pathogens and worn-out cells","manufacturing intrinsic factor needed for B12 uptake","secreting digestive enzymes into the bloodstream","producing digestive bile that destroys the ingested bacteria"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The spleen filters the blood: macrophages in its red pulp and sinuses remove circulating microbes, debris, and senescent red cells and platelets, while its white pulp houses lymphocytes that mount adaptive responses to blood-borne antigens.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 24"},{"q":"Lymphocytes are unusual among leukocytes because they...","choices":["are unable to leave the bloodstream at any time","remain fixed in one tissue for their entire lifespan","survive only a few hours in the blood before being routinely replaced","recirculate continuously between blood, lymph, and lymphoid tissue"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Unlike short-lived neutrophils, lymphocytes are long-lived and recirculate endlessly — from blood into lymphoid tissue, into lymph, and back to blood — which maximizes their chance of encountering the specific antigen they recognize.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 12"},{"q":"The redness and warmth of acute inflammation result largely from...","choices":["antibody deposition occurring within the vessel walls","loss of all blood flow to the damaged region","vasoconstriction that traps blood in the tissue","vasodilation and increased blood flow to the injured area"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Inflammatory mediators such as histamine cause local vasodilation and increased blood flow, which produce the redness and warmth; increased capillary permeability then adds the swelling characteristic of inflammation.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 25"},{"q":"Cytotoxic (CD8) T-cells destroy virus-infected cells by...","choices":["coating the infected cell with antibody so it can be removed much later","engulfing the entire infected cell by phagocytosis","releasing perforins and enzymes that trigger the target cell's death","secreting histamine that lyses the infected cell"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Cytotoxic T-cells recognize antigen presented on MHC I of an infected cell, then release perforins that form pores and enzymes that enter and induce the target cell's death, eliminating the reservoir of viral replication.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 59"},{"q":"One direct action of the complement cascade is to...","choices":["form membrane pores that lyse the targeted microbe","generate memory cells for a faster second response","present antigen fragments to helper T-cells","synthesize antibodies specific to the pathogen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Beyond opsonizing microbes and promoting inflammation, the complement cascade assembles a membrane attack complex that punches pores in the target's membrane, causing lysis — a direct killing mechanism of this innate system.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 53"},{"q":"Compared with the primary response, the secondary antibody response is...","choices":["slower and weaker because memory cells have died off","limited to IgM with no IgG produced at all","faster, larger, and dominated by higher-affinity IgG","identical in speed and magnitude to the first"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Because memory B- and T-cells persist from the first exposure, a repeat encounter produces a response that is quicker, of greater magnitude, and dominated by high-affinity IgG rather than the IgM that led the primary response; this is the basis of booster immunizations.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 48"},{"q":"Vaccination with a killed or attenuated organism works by...","choices":["permanently deleting lymphocytes that react to the pathogen","exposing the immune system to antigen so memory cells form without disease","supplying preformed antibodies that act for a few weeks","boosting the nonspecific innate barriers such as the skin and gastric acid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. A vaccine presents the antigens of a pathogen (as killed or attenuated forms) so the adaptive system mounts a response and generates memory cells, conferring active immunity and rapid protection on later exposure — without causing the disease itself.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"Passive immunity, such as antibodies passed in breast milk, is limited because...","choices":["it works only against the recipient's own tissues rather than against pathogens","the recipient makes no memory cells, so protection fades as antibodies degrade","it triggers lifelong immunity through the recipient's own T-cells","it strengthens over time as the antibodies multiply"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. In passive immunity the recipient receives ready-made antibodies but mounts no response of their own, so no memory cells form; as the transferred antibodies are gradually degraded, protection wanes within weeks.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slide 63"},{"q":"The enteric nervous system is notable because it...","choices":["can coordinate motility and secretion largely on its own, independent of the CNS","operates solely through circulating hormones in the blood rather than through any neurons","requires constant input from the brain to function at all","controls only the secretion of gastric acid and nothing else along the gut wall"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The enteric nervous system, with its myenteric and submucosal plexuses, contains enough neurons to integrate reflexes and control motility and secretion by itself; the autonomic nervous system modulates it, but the gut can function even without central input.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 24-33"},{"q":"Vagal (parasympathetic) stimulation of the stomach generally...","choices":["shuts down all secretion during a meal","acts only on the pancreas, not the stomach","decreases motility while raising acid secretion","increases both gastric motility and acid secretion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Parasympathetic (vagal) input, acting largely through acetylcholine, stimulates gastric smooth muscle contraction and enhances secretion, including acid from parietal cells and gastrin release; this underlies the cephalic phase of gastric secretion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 88-90"},{"q":"The cephalic phase of gastric secretion is triggered by...","choices":["fat and protein reaching the small intestine","stretch of the stomach wall as food enters","the sight, smell, or thought of food acting through the vagus nerve","acidic chyme arriving in the duodenum after the stomach has emptied its load"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The cephalic phase begins before food reaches the stomach: sensory and cognitive cues (sight, smell, taste, thought of food) drive vagal output that stimulates gastric secretion in anticipation of the meal, accounting for roughly a third of the acid response.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 92-95"},{"q":"Pepsin works best in the stomach because it...","choices":["digests dietary carbohydrates rather than protein in the stomach","requires the alkaline environment created by bile","is a protease with an acidic optimal pH provided by gastric HCl","functions only after being neutralized in the duodenum"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Pepsin is a protein-digesting enzyme with an acidic pH optimum (roughly 1.8–3.5); gastric HCl both activates pepsinogen to pepsin and provides the low pH environment in which pepsin is most active, so it functions well in the stomach and is inactivated in the alkaline duodenum.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-85"},{"q":"Between meals, the gallbladder...","choices":["empties continuously to keep the duodenum supplied in the body under most conditions","stores and concentrates bile by absorbing water and electrolytes","manufactures new bile from cholesterol entirely on its own","actively secretes new bile salts into the duodenum"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. During fasting the sphincter of Oddi is closed and bile is diverted into the gallbladder, whose mucosa absorbs water and electrolytes to concentrate the bile several-fold; it is then released when a fatty meal triggers CCK.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 17"},{"q":"Pancreatic amylase continues carbohydrate digestion by...","choices":["splitting proteins into individual amino acids","converting absorbed glucose directly into stored glycogen in the gut wall","emulsifying dietary fat into small droplets","breaking starch down into disaccharides within the small intestine"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Pancreatic amylase, secreted into the duodenum, hydrolyzes starch and glycogen into disaccharides and short oligosaccharides; brush-border enzymes then complete the job by splitting these into absorbable monosaccharides. It is the main luminal enzyme for carbohydrate digestion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101, 123-124"},{"q":"Because portal blood passes through the liver before reaching the body, the liver can...","choices":["metabolize and detoxify many absorbed substances before they circulate","return undigested food directly to the stomach","add dissolved oxygen to the blood returning from the gut before it circulates","store the absorbed material permanently as bile"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Nutrients and other absorbed substances from the gut drain first through the portal vein into the liver, allowing it to process nutrients, store or release glucose, and detoxify drugs and toxins (first-pass metabolism) before the blood reaches the systemic circulation.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 3, 8"},{"q":"Glucose absorption against its gradient is powered indirectly by...","choices":["bile-salt micelles physically pulling the glucose into the cell","direct hydrolysis of ATP by the glucose carrier itself","the concentration gradient of fructose in the lumen","the sodium gradient maintained by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Glucose enters the enterocyte on the SGLT1 cotransporter, riding the inward sodium gradient; that gradient is set up by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase, so glucose uptake is secondary active transport ultimately powered by ATP used to pump sodium.","cite":"GI Physiology, slide 126"},{"q":"Absorbed dietary fat reaches the systemic circulation by...","choices":["binding tightly to hemoglobin so as to be carried for transport inside the red blood cells","traveling as chylomicrons through lymph and entering blood at the thoracic duct","diffusing straight into the portal vein like glucose","being stored within the liver for a time before any of it is finally released"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Reassembled triglycerides are packaged into chylomicrons, which are too large to enter blood capillaries; they enter the lacteals of the villi, travel through the lymphatic system, and join the bloodstream where the thoracic duct empties into the venous system.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 135-138"},{"q":"Defecation can be voluntarily postponed because...","choices":["the external anal sphincter is skeletal muscle under conscious control","the internal anal sphincter is under full voluntary command","individual mass movements can be consciously stopped anywhere in the colon","the rectum can absorb the feces if defecation is delayed"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Although rectal filling relaxes the internal anal sphincter reflexly, the external anal sphincter is striated (skeletal) muscle innervated by the somatic pudendal nerves and under voluntary control, so a person can consciously delay defecation.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 61-68"},{"q":"Failure of the liver to clear ammonia is dangerous because ammonia...","choices":["is harmless and simply excreted unchanged by the lungs","is the main metabolic fuel used by the beating cardiac muscle","is toxic to the nervous system and can impair brain function","is required in large amounts for red cell production"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Ammonia produced by amino-acid deamination and gut bacteria is neurotoxic; the liver normally converts it to urea for excretion. When hepatic function fails, ammonia accumulates and can cause hepatic encephalopathy — confusion, altered consciousness, and impaired brain function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 10; Ch 70, slide 16"},{"q":"During fasting, the liver supports other tissues by...","choices":["storing all fatty acids so they cannot be used","releasing oxygen bound to stored hemoglobin","converting circulating ketones back into stored dietary fat","producing ketone bodies from fatty acids for use as fuel"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. In fasting, the liver oxidizes fatty acids and converts the surplus acetyl-CoA into ketone bodies, which it exports as an alternative fuel for tissues such as the brain, sparing glucose during prolonged energy shortage.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 15-19; Ch 71, slide 12"},{"q":"The liver uses glucokinase (rather than only hexokinase) to phosphorylate glucose, which allows it to...","choices":["release glucose faster than any other tissue","convert the incoming glucose directly into new protein for the body's use","take up large amounts of glucose after a meal without being saturated","avoid trapping glucose inside its cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Glucokinase has a high capacity and is not readily inhibited by its product, so unlike hexokinase it keeps phosphorylating glucose even at high concentrations; this lets the liver absorb and store large glucose loads after a meal, buffering blood glucose.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 4-7"},{"q":"Between meals, the liver keeps blood glucose from falling by...","choices":["converting glucose into glycogen for storage","absorbing glucose taken from resting muscle in order to store it centrally","breaking down stored glycogen and releasing glucose (glycogenolysis)","halting all glucose release to conserve it"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. In the postabsorptive state the liver depolymerizes its glycogen (glycogenolysis) and, as that store runs low, makes new glucose (gluconeogenesis), releasing glucose into the blood to prevent hypoglycemia. This is its glucose-buffer function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9"},{"q":"The pentose phosphate pathway is important mainly because it produces...","choices":["urea, used to dispose of the body's excess nitrogen","NADPH for biosynthesis and ribose for nucleic acids","large amounts of ATP for muscle contraction","lactate to regenerate NAD+ during exercise"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The pentose phosphate (hexose monophosphate) shunt diverts glucose-6-phosphate to generate NADPH — the reducing power for fatty-acid and other biosynthesis and for antioxidant defense — and ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide and nucleic-acid synthesis, rather than making ATP.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 28-29"},{"q":"Chylomicrons and VLDL both carry triglyceride, but they differ in that...","choices":["chylomicrons carry dietary fat from the gut, while VLDL carries fat made by the liver","chylomicrons are made in the liver, while VLDL comes from the intestine under these conditions","both particles are made only within adipose tissue purely for local fat storage","chylomicrons carry cholesterol back to the liver, while VLDL carries dietary fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Chylomicrons are assembled in the intestine to transport exogenous (dietary) fat, whereas VLDL is made by the liver to export endogenous triglyceride (much of it synthesized from carbohydrate); both deliver fatty acids to tissues via lipoprotein lipase.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 6; GI Physiology, slide 139"},{"q":"Cells take up cholesterol-rich LDL particles by...","choices":["binding them to LDL receptors and internalizing them","converting LDL into HDL at the cell surface","digesting LDL with pancreatic lipase in the blood","allowing LDL to diffuse freely across the membrane"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Cells express LDL receptors that bind circulating LDL and bring it in by receptor-mediated endocytosis, delivering cholesterol for membrane and steroid synthesis; too few functional receptors leave LDL in the blood and raise plasma cholesterol.","cite":"Ch 69, slide 36"},{"q":"A person in positive nitrogen balance is...","choices":["excreting essentially all dietary nitrogen unchanged in the urine each day","building more body protein than is being broken down, as during growth","losing more nitrogen than is taken in, as during starvation","unable to synthesize any nonessential amino acids"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Positive nitrogen balance means nitrogen intake exceeds nitrogen loss, indicating net protein synthesis; it occurs during growth, pregnancy, and recovery/muscle-building, when the body is accumulating protein.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 7-8; Ch 70"},{"q":"The urea cycle disposes of nitrogen and is...","choices":["performed in every cell of the body equally","located mainly within the tubular cells of the kidney rather than the liver","independent of any other metabolic pathway","carried out essentially only in the liver and linked to the TCA cycle"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Urea synthesis occurs almost exclusively in the liver, where two ammonia molecules and CO2 are combined into urea; the cycle interlinks with the TCA cycle, and excess ammonia is toxic partly because it can deplete TCA intermediates.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 16-17"},{"q":"Cortisol influences protein metabolism by...","choices":["blocking the liver from making any new glucose during stress or fasting states","preventing any amino acids at all from entering the blood during stress or fasting states","promoting breakdown of tissue protein to supply amino acids for gluconeogenesis","stimulating net protein synthesis in all tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Cortisol (a glucocorticoid) drives catabolism of extrahepatic tissue protein, raising plasma amino acids that the liver uses for gluconeogenesis; this helps maintain blood glucose during stress and fasting.","cite":"Ch 70, slide 19; Ch 68, slide 30"},{"q":"In a sedentary person, the largest component of daily energy expenditure is...","choices":["the basal metabolic rate needed to sustain resting functions","shivering to maintain body temperature","the thermic effect of digesting food","the energy cost of occasional vigorous physical exercise sessions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. In most sedentary people the basal metabolic rate — the energy to run vital resting processes — accounts for the majority (roughly 50–70%) of daily expenditure, far exceeding the smaller contributions of activity and the thermic effect of food.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 2; Ch 73, slide 10"},{"q":"The body's largest energy reserve is stored as...","choices":["triglyceride in adipose tissue","glycogen in the liver","protein in circulating plasma","free glucose in the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. By far the largest energy store is triglyceride in adipose tissue, which packs about 9 kcal/g with little associated water; a lean adult may carry enough fat for weeks of energy, dwarfing the limited glycogen and glucose reserves.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 3; Ch 73, slide 12"},{"q":"Destruction of the lateral hypothalamic nuclei tends to cause...","choices":["excessive eating, since this is the satiety center","reduced eating and weight loss, since this is the feeding center","an inability to regulate body temperature only","essentially no change in appetite or feeding behavior whatsoever"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The lateral hypothalamus acts as the feeding (hunger) center; lesions here remove the drive to eat, producing reduced intake and weight loss (inanition). This complements the ventromedial nuclei, which serve as the satiety center.","cite":"Ch 72, slide 9"},{"q":"Which is a genuine mechanism of body heat loss?","choices":["Piloerection, the raising of the body hairs to shed heat to the surroundings","Shivering, the production of heat by muscle contraction","Radiation, the emission of infrared heat waves to cooler surroundings","Vasoconstriction, the narrowing of skin vessels"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Radiation transfers heat as infrared waves from the warm body to cooler surrounding objects and is a major route of heat loss at rest; the other options listed are heat-conserving or heat-generating responses, not means of losing heat.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6, 13-14"},{"q":"A fever occurs when the hypothalamic set point is...","choices":["raised, so the body activates heat-gaining responses until it reaches the new level","removed entirely by the pyrogen, leaving the body temperature completely uncontrolled now","lowered, so that the body promptly begins to sweat and cool itself back down again","unchanged, with the rise coming only from the environment"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Pyrogens raise the hypothalamic set point; the body then perceives itself as too cold and triggers heat-gaining responses (vasoconstriction, shivering, chills) until core temperature rises to the new, higher set point — producing fever.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 4, 18"},{"q":"Sweating cools the body only when...","choices":["it is reabsorbed back into the sweat glands during this particular process","it remains as liquid droplets on the skin surface","the surrounding air is already fully saturated with water","the sweat actually evaporates, absorbing heat from the skin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cooling comes from the evaporation of sweat, which absorbs heat (the latent heat of vaporization) from the skin; sweat that merely drips off without evaporating removes little heat, which is why humid conditions blunt sweat's cooling effect.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6-9"},{"q":"A respiratory quotient closer to 0.7 indicates that the body is primarily burning...","choices":["no fuel at all, because gas exchange has completely stopped","protein used exclusively, fixing the RQ at 1.0","fat, which yields relatively less CO2 per O2 consumed","carbohydrate, which yields an RQ of about 1.0"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Fat oxidation gives a respiratory quotient near 0.7 because oxidizing fatty acids consumes comparatively more oxygen relative to the CO2 produced; this is typical of the fasted state or fat-based metabolism.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 5-6"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate is measured under standardized conditions that include...","choices":["a rested, fasting state at a comfortable, constant temperature","measured during a period of exposure to fairly extreme environmental cold","immediately after vigorous exercise","right after a large protein-rich meal"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. BMR is measured after roughly a 12-hour fast, at rest, without excitement, and at a comfortable constant temperature, so that only the minimal maintenance energy is captured without the confounding effects of digestion, activity, or thermal stress.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 8"},{"q":"The thermic effect of food refers to...","choices":["the heat lost through sweating during a meal","the extra energy expended to digest, absorb, and process a meal","the energy used only during physical activity","the surplus calories that are stored away as fat after overeating"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The thermic effect of food is the rise in energy expenditure required to digest, absorb, and metabolize nutrients; it is modest for carbohydrate and fat but substantial for protein (which can raise metabolic rate up to about 30%).","cite":"Ch 73, slide 10"},{"q":"Sympathetic activation can raise metabolic rate in part by...","choices":["blocking thyroid hormone from acting on tissues","shutting down all cellular metabolism to save energy","stimulating heat production, including thermogenesis in brown fat","lowering the core body temperature in order to reduce metabolic demand"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Sympathetic activity increases cellular metabolism and can drive thermogenesis, notably in brown adipose tissue, raising heat production and metabolic rate; this contributes to the metabolic response to cold and stress.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 9"},{"q":"During forced (heavy) breathing, accessory muscles such as the sternocleidomastoid and abdominals...","choices":["are used exclusively during quiet resting breaths","assist the diaphragm to move larger volumes of air","act only to slow breathing back to rest","replace the diaphragm, which stops working during exercise"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. In quiet breathing the diaphragm suffices, but during forced or heavy breathing accessory muscles are recruited — the sternocleidomastoid and scalenes aid inspiration, and the abdominals and internal intercostals aid expiration — to move much larger volumes.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"Intrapleural pressure is normally negative (sub-atmospheric), which...","choices":["forces the lungs to collapse against the chest wall","has no effect on whether the lungs stay inflated","actively pushes the air outward during quiet resting inspiration","keeps the lungs expanded against their tendency to recoil inward"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The negative intrapleural pressure results from the lung's inward recoil opposing the chest wall's outward pull; this sub-atmospheric pressure holds the lungs expanded and coupled to the chest wall throughout the breathing cycle.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 14, 17-19"},{"q":"If air enters the pleural space and abolishes the negative pressure, the lung tends to...","choices":["stiffen noticeably and become nearly impossible to compress","recoil and collapse because nothing opposes its elastic pull","expand further because recoil is now unopposed","remain unchanged since pleural pressure is irrelevant"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The lung's inherent elastic recoil pulls it inward; the negative pleural pressure normally counteracts this. If air enters the pleural space (pneumothorax) and abolishes that negative pressure, the recoil is unopposed and the lung collapses.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19, 50"},{"q":"Inspiratory reserve volume is the air that...","choices":["can still be exhaled beyond a normal quiet resting expiration","is exhaled during a single quiet resting breath","remains in the lungs after a maximal expiration","can still be inhaled beyond a normal quiet inspiration"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Inspiratory reserve volume is the additional air that can be forcibly inhaled after a normal tidal inspiration; it is the inspiratory 'reserve' available above the resting breath.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 27-29"},{"q":"Total lung capacity equals...","choices":["tidal volume multiplied by the respiratory rate","the sum of all four lung volumes, including residual volume","the air exchanged in one minute of breathing in the body under most conditions","vital capacity alone, since residual volume is excluded"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Total lung capacity is the maximum air the lungs can hold, equal to the sum of tidal volume, inspiratory reserve, expiratory reserve, and residual volume; because it includes residual volume, it cannot be measured by spirometry alone.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 31"},{"q":"By lowering surface tension, surfactant...","choices":["increases the work of breathing to strengthen the lungs","thickens the fluid layer to slow gas exchange","raises the surface tension evenly across all of the alveoli regardless of size","reduces the effort needed to inflate the lungs and prevents alveolar collapse"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Surfactant lowers alveolar surface tension, which raises compliance (making the lungs easier to inflate) and stabilizes alveoli of different sizes so small ones do not empty into larger ones; without it, the work of breathing rises and alveoli collapse (as in neonatal respiratory distress).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Despite a smaller partial-pressure gradient, CO2 crosses the respiratory membrane readily because it is...","choices":["carried across bound to hemoglobin","much less soluble than oxygen, slowing its diffusion","actively pumped across by alveolar cells","far more soluble than oxygen, aiding its diffusion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Carbon dioxide is roughly 20 times more soluble than oxygen, so even though its partial-pressure gradient across the membrane is smaller, it diffuses about as readily; solubility is a key factor in Fick's law of diffusion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 11, 61-62"},{"q":"In a healthy lung at rest, blood in the pulmonary capillary equilibrates with alveolar oxygen...","choices":["never fully, so arterial blood is always desaturated","well before it leaves the capillary, giving a large safety margin","only at the very last instant before leaving the capillary","only during vigorous exercise, and essentially never while at rest"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. At rest, oxygen equilibrates between alveolus and capillary blood in about a third of the transit time, so equilibration is complete long before the blood exits the capillary; this reserve is the safety factor that is eroded in disease or reduced with very fast transit during exercise.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 67-69"},{"q":"Gas exchange across the respiratory membrane is efficient largely because the total alveolar surface is...","choices":["very small but compensated by thickness","large but separated from blood by cartilage","thin but limited to a few large air sacs","very large while the membrane is extremely thin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The lungs contain hundreds of millions of alveoli providing an enormous total surface area, and the respiratory membrane is only about 0.2 micrometers thick; large area and short diffusion distance together maximize the rate of gas exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"Fluid accumulating in the interstitial space of the respiratory membrane would...","choices":["increase the diffusion distance and slow gas exchange","convert the membrane into an active transport surface","have no effect on the rate of gas diffusion","shorten the diffusion distance and speed exchange"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. By thickening the barrier that gases must cross, interstitial or alveolar fluid (as in pulmonary edema) lengthens the diffusion distance; per Fick's law, this reduces the rate of gas exchange and can impair oxygenation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 60-62"},{"q":"Higher brainstem centers in the pons help shape breathing by...","choices":["generating the basic breathing rhythm entirely on their own","contracting the diaphragm without any nerve involvement","modifying the rhythm set by the medullary centers","sensing arterial oxygen directly like the carotid bodies"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The basic respiratory rhythm arises in the medulla, but pontine centers modulate and smooth it — fine-tuning the transition between inspiration and expiration — so breathing is regular rather than gasping.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 88-90"},{"q":"The peripheral chemoreceptors' oxygen response becomes an important drive to breathe mainly when...","choices":["arterial oxygen falls to notably low levels","blood pressure rises at the carotid sinus","carbon dioxide is the only gas that has changed","arterial oxygen is completely normal"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The carotid and aortic bodies respond to low arterial PO2, but this hypoxic drive becomes significant only when PO2 falls well below normal (roughly under 60 mmHg); under normal conditions, CO2 is the dominant stimulus and oxygen contributes little.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95, 99"},{"q":"At a normal arterial PO2 of about 100 mmHg, hemoglobin is...","choices":["only about half saturated with oxygen","almost fully saturated with oxygen","completely stripped of its oxygen","unable to bind oxygen until PO2 rises higher"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. On the flat upper plateau of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve, a normal arterial PO2 (~100 mmHg) leaves hemoglobin about 97–98% saturated; the plateau ensures saturation stays high even if PO2 dips somewhat, providing a loading safety margin.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 78-80"},{"q":"Carbon monoxide is dangerous partly because, in addition to blocking O2 sites, it...","choices":["makes hemoglobin hold its remaining oxygen more tightly, hindering release to tissues","actually increases the total oxygen-carrying content of the blood delivered to the tissues","causes hemoglobin to release its bound oxygen far too easily before reaching tissue","is readily displaced by the small amount of dissolved oxygen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Carbon monoxide not only occupies binding sites (it binds hemoglobin with far greater affinity than oxygen) but also shifts the dissociation curve so the remaining bound oxygen is released less readily at the tissues, compounding the impairment of oxygen delivery.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slide 82"},{"q":"During exercise, working muscle extracts more oxygen from each unit of blood because...","choices":["oxygen is actively pumped back out into the blood from the muscle","blood flow to the muscle stops during contraction under these conditions","low tissue PO2 and a rightward curve shift favor greater unloading","hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen rises in active tissue"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Exercising muscle has a very low PO2 and generates heat, CO2, and acid that shift the oxygen-hemoglobin curve rightward; together these steepen the gradient and lower hemoglobin's affinity, so much more oxygen is unloaded per unit of blood than at rest.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-81"},{"q":"Carbonic anhydrase speeds CO2 transport because it...","choices":["pumps bicarbonate out of the plasma into the lungs","destroys excess CO2 before it can be transported during this particular process","binds the CO2 molecule directly onto the heme iron of hemoglobin","rapidly converts CO2 and water into carbonic acid inside red cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase in red cells greatly accelerates the hydration of CO2 to carbonic acid, which then dissociates to bicarbonate and H+; this lets the blood carry the large majority of its CO2 as bicarbonate and is central to CO2 transport and acid-base handling.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"A portion of CO2 is carried bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin; this binding occurs at...","choices":["the plasma proteins outside the red cell","the carbonic anhydrase enzyme molecule itself within the cell","the globin portion, not the heme iron where oxygen binds","the same heme iron site used by oxygen"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Carbamino CO2 attaches to amino groups on the globin chains of hemoglobin, a different site from the heme iron that binds oxygen; this is why hemoglobin can carry oxygen and some CO2 simultaneously.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-86"},{"q":"Voluntary hyperventilation, by removing extra CO2, tends to...","choices":["raise CO2 levels in the blood in the body under most conditions","raise blood pH, producing a respiratory alkalosis","leave blood pH completely unchanged","lower blood pH, producing a respiratory acidosis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Hyperventilation blows off CO2, lowering carbonic acid and hydrogen ion concentration, so blood pH rises — a respiratory alkalosis. This illustrates how ventilation directly influences acid-base balance through CO2.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"The tight link between CO2 and pH means that increasing ventilation...","choices":["changes oxygen levels but never affects pH","has no relationship to blood acid-base status","adds CO2 and thereby raises hydrogen ion concentration","removes CO2 and thereby reduces hydrogen ion concentration"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Because CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid (and thus H+), increasing ventilation removes CO2, lowers carbonic acid, and reduces hydrogen ion concentration, raising pH; this is the respiratory system's rapid lever on acid-base balance.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92"},{"q":"Which correctly describes CO2 movement?","choices":["CO2 diffuses from tissues into blood, then from blood into alveoli","CO2 diffuses from blood into tissues at both sites","CO2 moves from alveoli into blood in the lungs","CO2 is carried in the blood without ever actually leaving it at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Metabolizing tissues have a high PCO2, so CO2 diffuses into the blood; in the lungs, alveolar PCO2 is lower than that of venous blood, so CO2 diffuses from blood into the alveoli to be exhaled. Each step follows the partial-pressure gradient.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 73-74, 86-87"}]},"physio-master-v8":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v8)","questions":[{"q":"Plasma differs from serum in that plasma still contains...","choices":["antibodies that are absent from serum as it typically occurs here","dissolved oxygen that serum cannot hold","far more red blood cells than serum does","the clotting proteins such as fibrinogen that serum has lost"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Plasma is the fluid obtained when clotting is prevented, so it retains fibrinogen and the other clotting factors; serum is the fluid left after blood has clotted, meaning those clotting proteins have been consumed and removed. That is the defining difference between the two.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-5"},{"q":"Platelets (thrombocytes) are best described as...","choices":["cell fragments pinched off from large megakaryocytes in the marrow","oxygen-carrying cells closely related to red blood cells in most cases","a specialized type of white blood cell that fights infection","mature nucleated cells that divide within the bloodstream"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Platelets are not whole cells but membrane-bound fragments shed from megakaryocytes in the bone marrow; despite lacking a nucleus, they carry granules and machinery essential for hemostasis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 6, 30-33"},{"q":"Anemia is fundamentally a state in which...","choices":["the blood carries too much oxygen for the tissues to use","arterial oxygen partial pressure is always markedly low","the white blood cell count falls below the normal range","the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity is reduced below normal"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Anemia means a deficiency of functional hemoglobin (from too few red cells or too little hemoglobin per cell), which lowers the amount of oxygen the blood can carry and deliver to tissues, regardless of the specific cause.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 20-21"},{"q":"In polycythemia the oxygen-carrying capacity rises, yet the condition can impair circulation because...","choices":["the plasma volume expands and dilutes the hemoglobin","the kidneys stop producing erythropoietin entirely","the extra red cells cannot bind any oxygen at all as it typically occurs here","the accompanying rise in blood viscosity increases resistance to flow"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Although more red cells raise oxygen-carrying capacity, the higher hematocrit sharply increases blood viscosity; the thicker blood resists flow and raises the load on the heart, which can offset or outweigh the benefit of extra oxygen capacity.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 6"},{"q":"The normal circulating lifespan of a red blood cell is about...","choices":["30 days, limited by the loss of their mitochondria","120 days, after which macrophages remove the aged cell","several years, being among the longest-lived cells","a few hours, similar to the lifespan of a neutrophil"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Red cells survive roughly 120 days; lacking a nucleus and organelles, they cannot repair themselves and become fragile, so macrophages (mainly in the spleen and liver) phagocytize the senescent cells and recycle their components.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Vitamin B12 and folate are needed for red cell production chiefly because they...","choices":["form the globin chains that make up the hemoglobin molecule","support DNA synthesis required for the rapid division of precursor cells","stimulate the kidney to release more erythropoietin under most normal conditions","provide the iron atom that sits at the center of each heme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Erythropoiesis involves rapid cell division, which demands DNA synthesis; B12 and folate are cofactors for that process. Their deficiency impairs nuclear maturation, producing large, poorly functional cells (megaloblastic anemia).","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"The extrinsic pathway of coagulation is triggered when...","choices":["plasmin begins to break down an existing fibrin clot during this process","blood contacts negatively charged collagen within the vessel","platelets release erythropoietin at the site of injury","tissue factor from damaged cells outside the vessel contacts the blood"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The extrinsic (tissue factor) pathway begins when trauma exposes blood to tissue factor released by damaged extravascular cells; this rapidly activates the cascade toward prothrombin activator, and it is the faster of the two initiating pathways.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-46"},{"q":"Vitamin K is essential for coagulation because it...","choices":["binds calcium so it cannot participate in the cascade","directly dissolves clots once a wound has healed during this particular process in the tissues","is the enzyme that converts fibrinogen into fibrin","is required by the liver to synthesize several clotting factors, including prothrombin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Vitamin K is a cofactor the liver uses to produce functional prothrombin and factors VII, IX, and X; without it, these factors are made in an inactive form, and clotting is impaired — the basis of warfarin's action.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 46-47"},{"q":"Von Willebrand factor contributes to hemostasis mainly by...","choices":["stimulating the marrow to produce more platelets under most normal conditions","converting prothrombin directly into active thrombin","helping platelets adhere to the exposed vessel wall at the injury site","dissolving the fibrin meshwork after the wound heals"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Von Willebrand factor bridges platelet surface receptors to exposed subendothelial collagen, anchoring platelets at the site of injury; it also stabilizes factor VIII in the circulation, so its deficiency causes a bleeding tendency.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 33-34"},{"q":"Intact, undamaged endothelium helps prevent unwanted clotting by...","choices":["actively cross-linking any fibrin that forms nearby during this process in the tissues","presenting a smooth, negatively charged surface that repels platelets and factors","absorbing all calcium out of the surrounding plasma","continuously releasing thrombin into the passing blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Healthy endothelium is smooth and carries a negative surface charge that repels platelets and clotting factors, and it secretes antithrombotic substances; this keeps blood fluid until injury exposes the underlying tissue and triggers hemostasis.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 34, 48"},{"q":"To reach an infected tissue, white blood cells first leave the capillary by...","choices":["squeezing between endothelial cells in a process called diapedesis","dissolving the entire capillary wall with digestive enzymes","converting into red blood cells that diffuse across the wall","being carried passively into the tissue by bulk fluid flow in the body"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Leukocytes exit the bloodstream by diapedesis — deforming and slipping between the endothelial cells of the capillary or venule wall — and then move toward the infection by chemotaxis, following chemical gradients released at the site.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-28"},{"q":"Compared with neutrophils, macrophages are able to...","choices":["carry oxygen to the site to support the inflammatory response","phagocytize many more particles and survive to keep functioning","divide rapidly within the blood to expand their numbers","produce specific antibodies against the ingested organism"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages are larger, longer-lived, and far more powerful phagocytes than neutrophils; they can engulf many organisms and large debris and continue functioning, whereas neutrophils typically ingest a limited number and then die.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 29-31"},{"q":"T-lymphocytes are so named because they mature in the...","choices":["thymus, where they are selected for function and self-tolerance","thyroid, under the direct control of thyroid hormone","tonsils, which serve as their primary maturation site","tibial marrow, a specialized region of long bones under these conditions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. T-cells complete their maturation in the thymus, where they undergo selection that keeps useful, self-tolerant clones and deletes strongly self-reactive ones; the 'T' reflects this thymic education.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 40-42"},{"q":"B-lymphocytes complete their maturation in the...","choices":["liver, throughout the whole of adult life in the body","spleen, which is their only site of origin","thymus, alongside developing T-lymphocytes","bone marrow, before circulating to lymphoid tissues"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. In mammals, B-cells mature in the bone marrow (the 'B' is often associated with the bursa in birds, but marrow in humans); once mature, they seed lymph nodes, spleen, and other lymphoid tissue where they can respond to antigen.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 40-44"},{"q":"Opsonization enhances phagocytosis by...","choices":["attracting white cells toward the infection along a gradient","coating a microbe with antibody or complement so phagocytes grip it more easily","dissolving the microbe's cell wall before it is engulfed","forming memory cells for a faster response next time during this process in the tissues"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Opsonization tags a pathogen with antibody or complement fragments that phagocyte receptors recognize; this greatly increases the efficiency with which neutrophils and macrophages attach to and engulf the organism.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 30, 53"},{"q":"Long-lasting immunity after an infection depends on...","choices":["a permanent rise in body temperature that deters the pathogen","antibodies from the first infection remaining in the blood forever","memory lymphocytes that persist and respond rapidly on re-exposure","neutrophils that stay elevated permanently after the infection"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. During a response, some activated B- and T-cells become long-lived memory cells; on later exposure to the same antigen they mount a faster, stronger secondary response, which is the basis of durable immunity and of vaccination.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 45-48"},{"q":"Antibodies help neutralize threats directly by...","choices":["binding and inactivating toxins or blocking a microbe's ability to attach","synthesizing new complement proteins at the infection site","engulfing and digesting bacteria the way phagocytes do","forming pores that lyse the host's own infected cells in the body's tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Beyond tagging pathogens for other defenses, antibodies can directly neutralize by binding toxins to render them harmless and by coating microbes to block the sites they use to attach to and enter host cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 50-53"},{"q":"Which is an example of an innate (nonspecific) defense?","choices":["memory B-cells produced after a specific vaccination during this process","intact skin and acidic gastric secretions that block or kill microbes","clonal selection of a lymphocyte matching one antigen","high-affinity IgG antibodies tailored to one pathogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Innate defenses are present from birth and act nonspecifically; physical and chemical barriers such as intact skin, mucus, cilia, and acidic stomach secretions prevent entry or destroy many microbes without needing prior exposure.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 18-20, 60"},{"q":"In an immediate allergic reaction, symptoms arise when an allergen...","choices":["cross-links IgE on mast cells, triggering release of histamine","stimulates the marrow to overproduce red blood cells","is engulfed by cytotoxic T-cells that then release perforin","neutralizes complement so inflammation cannot occur"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. In allergy, IgE bound to mast cells and basophils is cross-linked by the allergen, causing these cells to degranulate and release histamine and other mediators; the resulting vasodilation, increased permeability, and smooth-muscle effects produce allergic symptoms.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 64-65"},{"q":"Self versus non-self recognition by T-cells relies on...","choices":["histamine tags that mark self cells as friendly under these conditions","antibodies coating every one of the body's own cells","the color of the surface pigments on each host cell","MHC molecules that display cell peptides for T-cell inspection"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules on cell surfaces present peptide fragments; T-cells inspect these displays and react to foreign peptides while tolerating self, which is how the adaptive system distinguishes self from non-self.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 55-58"},{"q":"Peristalsis differs from segmentation in that peristalsis...","choices":["propels contents forward along the tract, while segmentation mainly mixes them","is a voluntary movement, while segmentation is involuntary","occurs only in the esophagus and nowhere else in the gut during this particular process","only mixes contents, while segmentation moves them forward"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Peristalsis is a progressive wave of contraction behind the bolus that moves contents onward, whereas segmentation is alternating localized contractions that chop and mix contents with digestive juices without net forward movement.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-46"},{"q":"Gastrin promotes digestion primarily by...","choices":["neutralizing stomach acid to protect the duodenum","inhibiting all secretion during the intestinal phase","contracting the gallbladder to release stored bile","stimulating gastric acid secretion and gastric motility"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Gastrin, released by antral G-cells in response to protein and stomach distension, stimulates parietal-cell acid secretion (largely via histamine release) and increases gastric motility, preparing the stomach to process a meal.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 96"},{"q":"Between meals, the migrating motor complex serves to...","choices":["trigger the release of bile in response to fat during this process","sweep residual contents and bacteria along the gut during fasting","mix a large meal thoroughly with digestive enzymes","absorb the bulk of dietary nutrients into the blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The migrating motor complex is a cyclic pattern of contractions during fasting (associated with motilin) that sweeps leftover food particles, secretions, and bacteria toward the colon — a 'housekeeping' function that keeps the small intestine clear between meals.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-46"},{"q":"Salivary amylase begins the digestion of...","choices":["starch, though its action is soon halted by stomach acid","nucleic acids, releasing their component nucleotides","fat, by emulsifying it into small droplets","protein, which it splits into individual amino acids"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Salivary amylase (ptyalin) starts breaking down starch in the mouth; when the bolus reaches the acidic stomach, the low pH inactivates the enzyme, and starch digestion resumes in the small intestine with pancreatic amylase.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 76-79, 123"},{"q":"Bile salts emulsify fat effectively because each molecule...","choices":["chemically digests the triglyceride into fatty acids itself","binds oxygen to help oxidize the fat for energy in the body's tissues","is entirely water-soluble and dissolves the fat outright","has both a water-soluble and a fat-soluble end (it is amphipathic)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Bile salts are amphipathic: one part associates with water and the other with lipid. This lets them coat fat droplets and break them into many tiny droplets, greatly increasing the surface area available for lipase to act on.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 130-133"},{"q":"Pancreatic proteases such as trypsin are secreted as inactive precursors that are then activated...","choices":["only after the food has entered the large intestine as it typically occurs here","within the pancreatic cells immediately after synthesis","by stomach acid before they reach the small intestine","in the intestinal lumen, so the pancreas is not digested by its own enzymes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Proteases are released as zymogens (e.g., trypsinogen) and activated only after reaching the small intestine — enterokinase converts trypsinogen to trypsin, which then activates the others. This delay protects the pancreas from self-digestion.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101-105"},{"q":"Kupffer cells within the liver contribute to defense by...","choices":["producing bile pigments for excretion into the intestine","secreting insulin to regulate the blood glucose level","phagocytizing bacteria and debris carried in from the gut via portal blood","storing iron recovered from the diet for later use under most normal conditions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Kupffer cells are resident macrophages lining the liver sinusoids; because portal blood from the intestine passes through the liver, they are positioned to engulf bacteria and debris before that blood enters the general circulation.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 6-8"},{"q":"Water is absorbed across the intestinal wall mainly by...","choices":["binding to bile salts that carry it into the enterocyte","digestion of water molecules by brush-border enzymes during this process","osmosis, following the absorption of solutes such as sodium and glucose","active transport pumps that move water directly against gradients"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Water absorption is passive: as sodium, glucose, amino acids, and other solutes are absorbed, they raise the osmotic pull on the blood side, and water follows by osmosis. This is why efficient solute uptake drives water uptake.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 140-143"},{"q":"Adequate absorption of the fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K depends on...","choices":["the presence of bile salts to incorporate them into micelles","conversion into water-soluble forms before uptake","a specialized active pump unique to each vitamin in this scenario","an acidic intestinal pH created by gastric secretions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fat-soluble vitamins are absorbed along with dietary fat; bile salts are needed to form the micelles that ferry them to the enterocyte surface. Impaired bile flow therefore reduces uptake of these vitamins.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 132-133, 144"},{"q":"The gastrocolic reflex helps explain why...","choices":["bile is released the moment food enters the mouth","nutrients are absorbed faster in the large intestine","the stomach empties immediately when the colon fills","eating a meal often stimulates the urge to defecate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The gastrocolic reflex links stomach filling to increased colonic motility: distension of the stomach triggers mass movements in the colon that propel contents toward the rectum, which is why a meal frequently prompts the urge to defecate.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"The liver protects the body from many ingested and internally produced chemicals by...","choices":["secreting toxins unchanged directly into the bloodstream","storing all toxins permanently within its own cells in this scenario","metabolizing drugs and toxins into forms that can be excreted","converting toxins into oxygen for the tissues to use"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Hepatocytes carry out biotransformation, chemically modifying drugs, hormones, and toxins (often making them more water-soluble) so they can be excreted in bile or urine; this detoxifying role is a central hepatic function.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 8-10"},{"q":"The liver disposes of the nitrogen from amino-acid breakdown by...","choices":["converting the ammonia into glucose for energy under these conditions","storing the ammonia in hepatocytes until it is needed","exhaling the ammonia directly through the lungs","converting toxic ammonia into urea for excretion by the kidneys"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Deamination of amino acids releases ammonia, which is highly toxic; the liver's urea cycle converts it into urea, a far less toxic compound that the kidneys excrete. Liver failure allows ammonia to accumulate.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 16-17; Ch 71, slide 10"},{"q":"Glycolysis in the cytoplasm yields, per glucose molecule, a net of...","choices":["36 ATP and carbon dioxide, requiring oxygen throughout","2 ATP and 2 pyruvate, even in the absence of oxygen","no ATP at all, serving only to store glucose as glycogen","2 ATP and lactate, which can occur only with oxygen present"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Glycolysis produces a net of 2 ATP (and 2 NADH) and 2 pyruvate molecules per glucose, and it proceeds without oxygen; this modest yield is why anaerobic tissues rely on it but generate far less ATP than aerobic metabolism.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 10-16"},{"q":"Most of the ATP from complete glucose oxidation is generated during...","choices":["fermentation of pyruvate to lactate in the cytoplasm","oxidative phosphorylation on the inner mitochondrial membrane","the initial phosphorylation of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate","glycolysis, which produces the bulk of the cell's ATP"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. While glycolysis and the citric acid cycle yield some ATP, the great majority is produced by oxidative phosphorylation, where electrons from NADH and FADH2 drive the electron transport chain and ATP synthase; this stage requires oxygen.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 16-22"},{"q":"Glucagon and insulin have opposing effects on blood glucose in that glucagon...","choices":["has no effect on blood glucose, unlike insulin","and insulin both raise blood glucose together","lowers blood glucose while insulin raises it","raises blood glucose while insulin lowers it"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Glucagon (from pancreatic alpha cells) raises blood glucose by promoting hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis, whereas insulin (from beta cells) lowers it by promoting cellular uptake and storage; together they keep glucose within a narrow range.","cite":"Ch 68, slides 4, 30; Ch 71, slide 9"},{"q":"Fatty acids are broken down for energy through beta-oxidation, which...","choices":["converts fatty acids directly into glucose for the brain","builds fatty acids up from acetyl-CoA for storage in the body's tissues","removes two-carbon units to form acetyl-CoA for the citric acid cycle","splits fatty acids into individual carbon atoms in the cytoplasm"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Beta-oxidation sequentially cleaves two-carbon acetyl-CoA units from fatty acids (in the mitochondria); the acetyl-CoA enters the citric acid cycle, and the process also yields NADH and FADH2, making fat a rich energy source.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 10-14"},{"q":"During prolonged fasting, the liver produces ketone bodies because...","choices":["ketones are the only fuel the heart can ever use during this particular process in the tissues","the body has an excess of glucose that must be stored","fatty acid breakdown outpaces the cycle's capacity, and ketones offer an alternative fuel","insulin levels are high and drive ketone formation"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. In fasting, abundant acetyl-CoA from fatty-acid oxidation exceeds what the citric acid cycle can process (partly because oxaloacetate is diverted to gluconeogenesis); the liver converts the surplus into ketone bodies, which tissues like the brain can use as fuel.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 15-19"},{"q":"High-density lipoprotein (HDL) is often called 'good' cholesterol because it...","choices":["prevents the liver from making any cholesterol at all in the body's tissues","delivers cholesterol from the liver to the artery walls","is the main particle that carries dietary fat from the gut","carries excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver for disposal"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. HDL performs reverse cholesterol transport, picking up excess cholesterol from peripheral tissues and returning it to the liver for excretion in bile; this helps clear cholesterol from vessel walls, in contrast to LDL, which delivers cholesterol to tissues.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 6, 36"},{"q":"Before an amino acid's carbon skeleton can be used for energy, its amino group is removed by...","choices":["beta-oxidation, which removes nitrogen two atoms at a time","glycolysis, which strips the nitrogen as it makes ATP","deamination or transamination, freeing the skeleton for metabolism","the electron transport chain during ATP synthesis under these conditions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Removing the amino group by deamination (releasing ammonia) or transamination (transferring it to a keto acid) frees the carbon skeleton to enter energy pathways as a glucogenic or ketogenic intermediate, while the nitrogen is routed to urea.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Body protein is used for energy only as a later resort because...","choices":["protein contains far more energy per gram than fat does under most conditions in the body","protein serves essential structural and functional roles the body preserves first","the body cannot break protein down under any conditions","protein is stored in large depots specifically for fuel"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Proteins are needed for enzymes, structure, transport, and immunity, so the body preferentially burns carbohydrate and fat and spares protein; only in prolonged starvation, once fat reserves are heavily depleted, does significant tissue-protein breakdown for fuel occur.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 3-6; Ch 72, slide 18"},{"q":"Per gram, the energy yields of the macronutrients are approximately...","choices":["equal energy from all three, at about 4 kcal per gram","9 kcal for carbohydrate, 9 for protein, and 4 for fat","4 kcal for carbohydrate, 4 for protein, and 9 for fat","4 kcal for fat, with carbohydrate and protein at 9 kcal"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Carbohydrate and protein each provide about 4 kcal per gram, while fat provides about 9 kcal per gram; fat's much higher energy density is why it is the body's most compact form of energy storage.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 4-5"},{"q":"Obesity develops when, over time,...","choices":["energy intake persistently exceeds energy expenditure","the body loses its ability to store any fat at all","dietary protein is completely eliminated from the diet","energy expenditure persistently exceeds energy intake"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Obesity is fundamentally a chronic positive energy balance: when caloric intake exceeds expenditure over an extended period, the surplus is stored as body fat. Genetic, hormonal, and behavioral factors influence intake and expenditure, but the balance principle underlies it.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 2-3, 16"},{"q":"During early starvation, before fat stores are heavily used, the body first relies on...","choices":["ketone bodies, which are the very first fuel mobilized","stored glycogen, which is exhausted within roughly a day","dietary intake, which continues to supply energy","body protein, which is broken down before any glycogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The body first draws on liver (and muscle) glycogen for glucose, but these stores are small and are largely depleted within about 24 hours; the body then shifts increasingly to fat oxidation and, later, ketone production and protein breakdown.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 17-19"},{"q":"The hypothalamus acts as the body's thermostat, with the responses to cold coordinated so that the body...","choices":["raises its set point to induce a protective fever","loses heat through vasodilation and sweating during this process in the tissues","stops all metabolic heat production to save energy","conserves and generates heat through vasoconstriction and shivering"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. When cold is sensed, the hypothalamus triggers heat-conserving and heat-generating responses: cutaneous vasoconstriction to reduce loss and shivering (plus increased metabolism) to produce heat, defending core temperature.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 4, 11-15"},{"q":"Heat loss by conduction and convection differ in that convection...","choices":["emits heat as infrared waves without any medium in this scenario","carries heat away by the movement of air or fluid over the skin","transfers heat only to objects touching the skin directly","requires evaporation of sweat to remove any heat"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Conduction transfers heat to objects or air in direct contact, while convection removes heat as moving air or water carries the warmed layer away and replaces it with cooler medium; a breeze increases convective loss.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 6-9"},{"q":"With repeated exposure to a hot environment, acclimatization improves heat tolerance largely by...","choices":["increasing the sweating rate and conserving salt in the sweat","shutting down cutaneous blood flow to the skin as a general rule","reducing the sweating rate to conserve body water","lowering the hypothalamic set point permanently"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Heat acclimatization enhances the capacity to sweat earlier and more profusely (improving evaporative cooling) and, via aldosterone, conserves sodium in the sweat, protecting the body's salt balance during heavy sweating.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 8-10"},{"q":"Larger individuals tend to have a higher total basal metabolic rate partly because...","choices":["surface area has no relationship to heat loss or metabolism","larger bodies have proportionally less active tissue during this process","a bigger body always has a much lower body temperature","a greater body mass and surface area require more energy to maintain"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Basal metabolic rate scales with body size: more metabolically active tissue and a larger surface area (over which heat is lost) mean more total energy is needed to maintain the resting body, which is why BMR is often expressed relative to body size.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 8-11"},{"q":"When a fever finally 'breaks,' the person often flushes and sweats because the hypothalamic set point has...","choices":["returned to normal, so the now-high body temperature is shed by sweating and vasodilation","risen further, causing the body to generate even more heat","been abolished, leaving temperature completely unregulated","dropped far below normal, triggering intense shivering during this particular process in the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. When pyrogen levels fall, the set point drops back to normal; the body temperature is now above the set point, so the hypothalamus activates heat-loss responses — vasodilation and sweating — to bring temperature down, producing the flush and sweat of the crisis.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 18-20"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate tends to decline with advancing age largely because of...","choices":["a steady rise in the amount of active muscle tissue","a permanent increase in body temperature over time","a gradual loss of lean, metabolically active muscle mass","a large increase in thyroid hormone secretion during this process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. With aging, lean muscle mass tends to decrease and is partly replaced by less active fat; since muscle is more metabolically active than fat, this shift lowers the basal metabolic rate over the years.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 9-11"},{"q":"The relatively large thermic effect of a protein-rich meal reflects the energy cost of...","choices":["digesting fiber that accompanies the protein","processing and metabolizing the amino acids after absorption","storing the protein directly as body fat under most normal conditions","cooling the body after the warm meal is eaten"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The specific dynamic action (thermic effect) of protein is high because the body expends considerable energy deaminating amino acids, forming urea, and processing the products; this can raise metabolic rate substantially more than carbohydrate or fat.","cite":"Ch 73, slide 10; Ch 72, slide 6"},{"q":"Air flows into the lungs during inspiration because, by Boyle's law, expanding the thorax...","choices":["compresses the lung to squeeze air inward","lowers alveolar pressure below atmospheric pressure","raises alveolar pressure above atmospheric pressure","has no effect on pressure, so air enters by active pumping"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As inspiratory muscles enlarge the thoracic cavity, lung volume increases and (by Boyle's law, pressure falling as volume rises) alveolar pressure drops just below atmospheric; air then flows down this pressure gradient into the lungs.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 14-18"},{"q":"Throughout the normal breathing cycle, intrapleural pressure remains...","choices":["higher than alveolar pressure at all times under most conditions throughout the body","positive during quiet expiration to force air out","more negative than alveolar pressure, keeping the lung against the chest wall","exactly equal to atmospheric pressure during inspiration"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Intrapleural pressure stays below (more negative than) alveolar pressure across the cycle; this transpulmonary pressure difference holds the lung expanded against the chest wall and prevents it from collapsing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 16-19"},{"q":"By the law of Laplace, without surfactant a small alveolus would tend to...","choices":["become completely rigid and unable to change size","generate less collapsing pressure than a large alveolus","collapse and empty into a connected larger alveolus","expand indefinitely at the expense of larger alveoli"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Laplace's law says that for a given surface tension, smaller alveoli generate higher collapsing pressure; without surfactant, a small alveolus would empty into a larger connected one. Surfactant lowers tension more in small alveoli, stabilizing them.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Vital capacity is defined as the maximum volume of air that can be...","choices":["expelled after the deepest possible inspiration","moved during a single quiet resting breath","held in the lungs at the end of a normal expiration","left in the lungs after a maximal forced expiration"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vital capacity is the greatest amount of air a person can exhale after taking the deepest possible breath; it equals the sum of tidal volume, inspiratory reserve, and expiratory reserve, and excludes the residual volume that cannot be exhaled.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 27-31"},{"q":"Residual volume cannot be measured by ordinary spirometry because it is the air that...","choices":["can be forcibly inhaled beyond a normal breath","is exhaled with every ordinary quiet breath during this process","remains in the lungs and can never be voluntarily exhaled","moves through the conducting airways each minute"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Residual volume is the air left in the lungs even after a maximal expiration; since it can never be exhaled, spirometry (which measures moved air) cannot capture it, and indirect methods such as gas dilution are required.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 30-31"},{"q":"Surfactant is chiefly composed of...","choices":["cartilage, which stiffens the alveolar wall for support","mucus, which traps inhaled particles in the alveoli","phospholipid, which interposes between water molecules to reduce surface tension","hemoglobin, which binds oxygen within the alveolus under most conditions in the body"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Surfactant is largely phospholipid (notably dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine); its molecules insert among the water molecules lining the alveoli, weakening their cohesive attraction and thereby lowering surface tension.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-23"},{"q":"Oxygen moves from alveolar air into pulmonary capillary blood because...","choices":["alveolar oxygen partial pressure is higher than that in the arriving blood","alveolar oxygen pressure is lower than that in the blood","carbon dioxide drags oxygen along with it into the blood","the blood actively pumps oxygen out of the alveolus as it is usually described here"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Gas exchange is driven by partial-pressure gradients: alveolar PO2 (~100 mmHg) exceeds the PO2 of the venous blood entering the pulmonary capillaries (~40 mmHg), so oxygen diffuses down its gradient into the blood until equilibration.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 61-66"},{"q":"According to the principles governing diffusion, the rate of gas transfer across the respiratory membrane increases with...","choices":["greater surface area and a thinner membrane","a smaller partial-pressure gradient across the membrane","lower solubility of the gas in the membrane","a thicker membrane and a smaller surface area"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Diffusion rate rises with a larger surface area, a shorter diffusion distance (thinner membrane), a steeper partial-pressure gradient, and higher gas solubility; the healthy lung maximizes area and minimizes thickness to favor exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-62"},{"q":"The anatomic dead space refers to...","choices":["the alveoli that receive air but no blood flow","the residual air that can never be exhaled during this process","the total volume of air moved in one minute","the volume of conducting airways where no gas exchange occurs"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Anatomic dead space is the air filling the conducting zone — nose, trachea, and bronchi — which has no alveoli and therefore participates in no gas exchange; only the air reaching the alveoli contributes to gas exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"The diaphragm receives its motor innervation from the...","choices":["phrenic nerve, arising from cervical spinal segments","sympathetic chain, acting through spinal ganglia","vagus nerve, which also controls the heart rate","intercostal nerves that supply only the rib muscles"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The diaphragm is driven by the phrenic nerve, which originates from cervical spinal segments (about C3–C5); this is why high cervical spinal cord injury can paralyze the diaphragm and abolish spontaneous breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-13"},{"q":"The Hering-Breuer inflation reflex helps protect the lungs by...","choices":["forcing a deeper breath whenever the lungs are stretched","contracting the diaphragm independently of the brainstem","inhibiting further inspiration when stretch receptors sense large inflation","sensing arterial oxygen and driving ventilation during this particular process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Stretch receptors in the airway walls, when strongly stimulated by large lung inflation, send signals that inhibit the inspiratory center; this reflex helps prevent overinflation of the lungs, mainly during deep breathing.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 89-90"},{"q":"The P50 of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve is the partial pressure at which hemoglobin is...","choices":["fully saturated with the maximum amount of oxygen","50% saturated, serving as a measure of its affinity for oxygen","completely stripped of all of its bound oxygen","binding carbon dioxide rather than oxygen as it typically occurs here"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. P50 is the PO2 at which hemoglobin is half saturated; a higher P50 means lower affinity (the curve is shifted right, favoring unloading), and a lower P50 means higher affinity (left shift), so P50 is a convenient index of oxygen affinity.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 78-81"},{"q":"Fetal hemoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen than adult hemoglobin, which helps the fetus by...","choices":["releasing oxygen more readily than adult hemoglobin does","carrying carbon dioxide instead of oxygen to the tissues","favoring transfer of oxygen from maternal blood across the placenta","preventing the fetus from taking up any maternal oxygen during this process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Because fetal hemoglobin binds oxygen more tightly (its curve is left-shifted), it can pull oxygen from the maternal circulation across the placenta even at the relatively low oxygen levels found there, ensuring adequate fetal oxygen supply.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 78-82"},{"q":"Of the total oxygen carried in arterial blood, the overwhelming majority is...","choices":["bound to hemoglobin, with only a small fraction dissolved in plasma","attached to plasma proteins such as albumin during this particular process","carried as bicarbonate within the red blood cells","dissolved in the plasma, with little bound to hemoglobin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. About 98–99% of the oxygen in blood is bound to hemoglobin; only a tiny fraction is physically dissolved in plasma. This is why hemoglobin concentration is such a critical determinant of oxygen delivery.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"The Haldane effect describes how, in the lungs, oxygenation of hemoglobin...","choices":["promotes the release of carbon dioxide from the blood","converts carbon dioxide directly into oxygen","has no effect on carbon dioxide transport at all","increases the blood's ability to hold carbon dioxide"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The Haldane effect is the reciprocal of the Bohr effect: as hemoglobin binds oxygen in the lungs, its ability to hold CO2 (as carbamino compounds and via H+ buffering) falls, promoting CO2 unloading for exhalation. In tissues, deoxygenation enhances CO2 uptake.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"Carbon dioxide diffuses across membranes more readily than oxygen despite a smaller gradient because CO2...","choices":["is actively transported across the membrane by pumps","is much more soluble, which offsets its smaller partial-pressure difference","binds hemoglobin at the same site oxygen uses as it is usually described here","has a much larger partial-pressure gradient than oxygen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Although the partial-pressure gradient for CO2 across the respiratory membrane is far smaller than that for oxygen, CO2's roughly 20-fold greater solubility allows it to diffuse about as fast, so CO2 exchange is rarely limiting.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 61-62, 86"},{"q":"The bicarbonate buffer system links respiration to acid-base balance because...","choices":["the buffer works only in the kidney and not in the blood under most conditions in the body","bicarbonate is exhaled directly by the lungs to remove acid","CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid, which dissociates to H+ and bicarbonate","hemoglobin converts bicarbonate into oxygen for transport"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. CO2 + H2O reversibly forms carbonic acid, which dissociates into H+ and bicarbonate. Because the lungs control CO2, changing ventilation shifts this equilibrium and thus blood pH — the mechanistic link between breathing and acid-base status.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"Compared with respiratory adjustment, the kidneys correct acid-base disturbances...","choices":["by exhaling excess acid as carbon dioxide gas during this particular process","more slowly, over hours to days, but with greater ultimate capacity","more quickly, within seconds, than the lungs can","without any effect on the blood's bicarbonate level"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The lungs adjust CO2 within minutes for rapid but limited compensation, whereas the kidneys act over hours to days by excreting acid and regulating bicarbonate; the renal response is slower to develop but can more completely restore balance.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"Central and peripheral chemoreceptors differ in that the central chemoreceptors...","choices":["directly measure the amount of oxygen bound to hemoglobin","lie in the medulla and respond mainly to CO2-driven changes in H+","lie in the carotid bodies and sense mainly low oxygen","sense arterial blood pressure at the aortic arch as a general rule"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Central chemoreceptors sit in the medulla and respond chiefly to H+ generated when CO2 crosses into brain fluid, whereas the peripheral chemoreceptors (carotid and aortic bodies) respond to low arterial oxygen as well as to CO2 and pH.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-99"},{"q":"Comparing alveolar gas with the systemic venous blood arriving at the lungs, the alveoli have...","choices":["a higher oxygen and a lower carbon dioxide partial pressure than that blood","identical oxygen and carbon dioxide pressures to that blood","a lower oxygen and a higher carbon dioxide partial pressure than that blood","no oxygen at all, so none can diffuse into the blood"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Alveolar air has higher PO2 and lower PCO2 than the venous blood entering the pulmonary capillaries; these opposing gradients drive oxygen into the blood and carbon dioxide out of it, so blood leaves the lungs oxygenated and CO2-depleted.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 63-66, 71-74"}]},"physio-master-v9":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v9)","questions":[{"q":"Albumin, the most abundant plasma protein, is important because it...","choices":["carries oxygen from the lungs to the peripheral tissues","acts as an antibody that neutralizes invading microbes","generates most of the plasma colloid osmotic pressure and transports many substances","forms the fibrin meshwork that seals a damaged vessel as it is usually described here"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Albumin is the chief contributor to plasma colloid (oncotic) osmotic pressure, keeping fluid within the vasculature, and it serves as a carrier for hormones, fatty acids, drugs, and other poorly soluble substances. Low albumin therefore causes edema.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 3-5"},{"q":"A reticulocyte count is useful clinically because reticulocytes are...","choices":["old red cells about to be removed by the spleen as it typically occurs here","a type of white cell that increases during infection","platelets that have just been released from megakaryocytes","immature red cells whose number reflects the marrow's production rate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Reticulocytes are newly released, not-yet-mature red cells; a rising count signals that the marrow is actively producing red cells (for example, in response to blood loss), while a low count suggests impaired production.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Each hemoglobin molecule can carry up to four oxygen molecules because it contains...","choices":["four globin chains but only a single oxygen-binding site","four copies of the iron-free protein globin without any heme","a single large heme unit that binds all four oxygens at once","four heme groups, each with an iron atom that binds one oxygen"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Hemoglobin is a tetramer with four polypeptide (globin) chains, each holding a heme group with a central iron (Fe2+) atom; each iron can reversibly bind one oxygen molecule, so one hemoglobin carries up to four.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 20-21"},{"q":"Erythropoietin secretion is governed by a negative feedback loop in which...","choices":["erythropoietin rises steadily regardless of oxygen levels under most normal conditions","low tissue oxygen raises erythropoietin, and restored oxygen delivery lowers it","the liver senses red cell count and sets erythropoietin directly","high tissue oxygen raises erythropoietin to make more red cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. When tissue oxygen delivery falls, the kidneys secrete more erythropoietin, stimulating red cell production; as the added red cells restore oxygen delivery, the stimulus subsides and erythropoietin falls, closing the loop and keeping red cell mass appropriate.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 14-17"},{"q":"Iron absorbed from the diet is carried in the blood bound to...","choices":["albumin, the general carrier for all trace metals","bile salts, which shuttle it back to the liver in the body's tissues","transferrin, which delivers it to the marrow and storage sites","hemoglobin, which ferries it through the plasma"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Absorbed iron is transported in plasma bound to transferrin, which delivers it to the bone marrow for hemoglobin synthesis and to the liver and other tissues for storage as ferritin; free iron is toxic, so it is kept protein-bound.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slide 17"},{"q":"The intrinsic and extrinsic pathways converge at a common pathway that begins with the activation of...","choices":["plasminogen, which initiates clot formation","tissue factor, which is unique to the intrinsic pathway","factor X, leading to prothrombin activator formation","fibrinogen, which is the first factor of the cascade"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Both initiating pathways lead to activation of factor X; activated factor X (with factor V, calcium, and phospholipid) forms prothrombin activator, which converts prothrombin to thrombin. This shared final sequence is the common pathway.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 44-47"},{"q":"After a clot forms, clot retraction occurs as platelets...","choices":["contract and pull the fibrin strands together, drawing wound edges closer","dissolve the fibrin to reopen the vessel immediately","convert fibrin back into soluble fibrinogen during this particular process","release erythropoietin to replace lost red cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Platelets trapped in the clot contract, pulling on the fibrin meshwork; this retracts the clot, squeezes out serum, and draws the edges of the damaged vessel closer together, aiding healing.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-43"},{"q":"Fibrinolysis is triggered when plasminogen activators such as tPA...","choices":["cross-link fibrin strands to strengthen the clot","convert plasmin back into inactive plasminogen","convert plasminogen trapped in the clot into active plasmin","stimulate platelets to build a larger clot during this process"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) and similar activators convert clot-bound plasminogen into plasmin, the enzyme that digests fibrin; this gradually dissolves the clot once the vessel has healed and restores normal flow.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 40-48"},{"q":"A very low platelet count tends to cause bleeding because platelets are needed to...","choices":["dissolve clots so blood can keep flowing freely","carry the oxygen required for wound healing during this particular process","produce the antibodies that fight wound infection","form the initial plug and support the reactions of the clotting cascade"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Platelets form the primary hemostatic plug at sites of injury and provide the phospholipid surface on which clotting reactions assemble; when their number is too low, both plug formation and clot generation are impaired, producing a bleeding tendency.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-34"},{"q":"A rise in the circulating white blood cell count (leukocytosis) commonly indicates...","choices":["an active infection or inflammatory process in the body","a fall in the number of red blood cells present as a rule","an excess of platelets circulating in the blood","a reduced ability of the body to fight infection"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Leukocytosis, an increase in circulating white cells, is a typical response to infection or inflammation, as the marrow releases and produces more leukocytes to meet the demand; the pattern of which cells rise can hint at the cause.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-30"},{"q":"Macrophages play a dual role in immunity because they both...","choices":["phagocytize pathogens and present their antigens to activate lymphocytes","secrete acid and also cross-link fibrin strands during this particular process","form blood clots and also filter lymph in the nodes","produce antibodies and also carry oxygen to tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Macrophages are powerful phagocytes that engulf and destroy pathogens, and they also display fragments of the ingested antigen on MHC to helper T-cells, bridging the innate and adaptive responses — a key dual function.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 29-31, 55"},{"q":"Because lymphatics return interstitial fluid to the blood, blockage of lymphatic drainage typically causes...","choices":["an immediate rise in the arterial blood pressure","a rapid fall in the volume of interstitial fluid","accumulation of fluid in the tissues, producing edema","complete loss of the body's ability to make antibodies"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The lymphatic system continuously returns filtered interstitial fluid (and protein) to the bloodstream; if drainage is blocked, that fluid accumulates in the tissue, causing swelling (edema). This links lymphatic function to fluid balance as well as immunity.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22-24"},{"q":"Primary lymphoid organs differ from secondary lymphoid organs in that primary organs are where lymphocytes...","choices":["are formed and mature, whereas secondary organs are where they meet antigen","encounter antigen, whereas secondary organs form them","produce antibodies, whereas secondary organs make red cells","are destroyed, whereas secondary organs store them as it is usually described here"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Primary lymphoid organs (bone marrow and thymus) are where lymphocytes originate and mature; secondary lymphoid organs (lymph nodes, spleen, tonsils) are where mature lymphocytes encounter antigen and mount responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 22-24, 40-44"},{"q":"When activated by their specific antigen, B-lymphocytes proliferate and differentiate into...","choices":["plasma cells that secrete large amounts of antibody","red blood cells that transport the antibody in plasma","cytotoxic cells that directly lyse infected host cells","phagocytes that engulf and digest the antigen"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Antigen-activated B-cells (with helper T-cell support) proliferate and differentiate into plasma cells, which are antibody factories secreting large quantities of the specific antibody, while some become memory B-cells for future responses.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 44-50"},{"q":"The complement system aids defense in several ways, including...","choices":["producing the specific antibodies against a pathogen","opsonizing microbes, attracting phagocytes, and lysing target cells","storing iron released from broken-down red cells","carrying oxygen to the site of an infection under most conditions in the body"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Complement enhances immunity in multiple ways: it opsonizes microbes to promote phagocytosis, its fragments attract phagocytes (chemotaxis) and drive inflammation, and its terminal components form a membrane attack complex that lyses target cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 52-53"},{"q":"Humoral immunity and cell-mediated immunity differ chiefly in that humoral immunity...","choices":["uses T-cells directly, while cell-mediated immunity uses antibodies","provides only immediate barriers such as skin and mucus during this particular process in the tissues","works through antibodies in body fluids, while cell-mediated immunity uses T-cells directly","is part of the innate system, while cell-mediated is acquired"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Humoral (antibody-mediated) immunity relies on antibodies secreted by plasma cells that circulate in body fluids to target extracellular threats, whereas cell-mediated immunity uses T-cells (especially cytotoxic T-cells) to act against intracellular pathogens and abnormal cells.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 44-59"},{"q":"Natural killer (NK) cells are considered part of innate immunity because they...","choices":["can only act after memory cells have formed during this process in the tissues","mature in the thymus and require MHC-matched antigen","produce highly specific antibodies after being primed","destroy virus-infected and abnormal cells without needing prior sensitization"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. NK cells recognize and kill virus-infected and tumor cells based on general 'danger' signals and altered surface markers, acting quickly without the antigen-specific priming that adaptive lymphocytes require — which places them in the innate arm.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 33, 59-60"},{"q":"In the sequence of an acute inflammatory response, which cells typically arrive first, followed by which?","choices":["macrophages arrive first, followed by neutrophils days later","neutrophils arrive first, followed later by monocytes that become macrophages","red blood cells arrive first to wall off the infection","lymphocytes arrive first, before any phagocytes appear under most normal conditions"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Neutrophils are the earliest cellular responders, arriving within about an hour; over the following hours to days, monocytes migrate in and mature into macrophages that continue phagocytosis and clean-up, giving the characteristic two-wave cellular response.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 26-31"},{"q":"During swallowing, the lower esophageal sphincter must relax to...","choices":["push stomach acid up into the mouth for buffering","allow the bolus to pass from the esophagus into the stomach","release bile into the esophagus to begin digestion","prevent any food from entering the stomach at all during this process"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As a peristaltic wave carries the bolus down the esophagus, the lower esophageal sphincter relaxes to let it enter the stomach, then closes again to help prevent reflux of acidic gastric contents back into the esophagus.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 40-45"},{"q":"When acidic, fatty chyme enters the duodenum, hormonal signals act to...","choices":["slow gastric emptying so the small intestine is not overwhelmed","stop all pancreatic secretion until the stomach empties in most cases","accelerate gastric emptying to clear the stomach quickly","trigger immediate defecation of the intestinal contents"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fat and acid in the duodenum trigger enterogastric signals (including CCK and secretin) that slow gastric emptying; this ensures the duodenum has time to neutralize acid and digest fat before receiving more chyme.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 13-15, 46"},{"q":"Within the gastric glands, the division of labor is such that...","choices":["chief cells secrete bile and parietal cells secrete enzymes","both cell types secrete only mucus to protect the lining during this particular process","parietal cells secrete pepsinogen while chief cells secrete acid","chief cells secrete pepsinogen while parietal cells secrete acid and intrinsic factor"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Chief cells release pepsinogen (activated to pepsin by acid), while parietal cells secrete hydrochloric acid (which also activates pepsinogen and kills microbes) and intrinsic factor needed for vitamin B12 absorption. Each cell type has a distinct secretory role.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-90"},{"q":"Bile contains both bile salts and bile pigments; the bile pigments (mainly bilirubin) are...","choices":["waste products of hemoglobin breakdown excreted in the bile","hormones that stimulate pancreatic secretion during this process","enzymes that digest carbohydrates in the duodenum","the active agents that emulsify fat in the intestine"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Bile pigments such as bilirubin are waste from the breakdown of heme (from old red cells); the liver conjugates and excretes them in bile. In contrast, bile salts are the functional emulsifiers derived from cholesterol.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-17"},{"q":"Secreting pancreatic proteases as inactive zymogens is important because it...","choices":["lets the pancreas store the enzymes for years at a time","allows the enzymes to digest carbohydrates instead of protein","makes the enzymes work better in the acidic stomach","prevents the enzymes from digesting the pancreas that makes them"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. If active proteases were produced within the pancreas, they would digest the organ's own tissue; secreting them as inactive zymogens (activated only in the intestine) protects the pancreas from self-digestion, a safeguard whose failure underlies pancreatitis.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 101-105"},{"q":"During fasting, the liver helps maintain blood glucose by gluconeogenesis, which is the...","choices":["absorption of glucose directly from the digested food","conversion of glucose into fat for long-term storage","synthesis of new glucose from noncarbohydrate sources such as amino acids and lactate","breakdown of stored glycogen into glucose molecules during this process in the tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Gluconeogenesis is the liver's production of glucose from noncarbohydrate precursors — amino acids (from protein), lactate, and glycerol — sustaining blood glucose once glycogen stores are exhausted during fasting, which is vital for glucose-dependent tissues like the brain.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slide 9; Ch 68, slides 25-27"},{"q":"The small intestine's absorptive surface is vastly increased by...","choices":["a single large chamber that holds food for a long time","circular folds, villi, and microvilli that multiply the surface area","thick muscular walls that grind the food finely under most normal conditions","a smooth, flat lining that speeds the passage of food"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Three levels of folding — the circular folds of the wall, the finger-like villi, and the microvilli of the brush border — together increase the absorptive surface area enormously, maximizing contact between nutrients and the absorptive cells.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 120-122, 140"},{"q":"Much of the absorption of nutrients like glucose and amino acids is coupled to...","choices":["the digestion of water into hydrogen and oxygen","the breakdown of the nutrients by stomach acid in most cases","the transport of sodium, whose gradient powers their uptake","the emulsifying action of bile salts on the nutrients"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Glucose and amino acids are absorbed by sodium-coupled cotransporters: the inward sodium gradient (maintained by the basolateral Na+/K+ ATPase) drives these nutrients into the enterocyte against their own gradients, an example of secondary active transport.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 126-129"},{"q":"The colon's pouch-like haustra are formed and their contractions serve to...","choices":["absorb the bulk of dietary fat and protein","mix and slowly move contents while water is absorbed","rapidly propel contents straight to the rectum","secrete digestive enzymes to finish breaking down food"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The haustra are sacculations produced by the colon's muscle arrangement; their slow, segmenting contractions (haustration) knead the contents and expose them to the mucosa for water and electrolyte absorption, gradually moving material along toward the rectum.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 59-66"},{"q":"The liver's contribution to fat digestion is its production of...","choices":["bile, which emulsifies fat to aid its digestion and absorption","hydrochloric acid, which breaks fat into fatty acids","insulin, which drives fat storage after a meal as a general rule","lipase, the main enzyme that digests dietary fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The liver continuously produces bile, whose bile salts emulsify dietary fat into small droplets; this greatly increases the surface area for pancreatic lipase to act and helps form the micelles that carry fat products to the absorptive surface.","cite":"Ch 71 Liver, slides 13-17"},{"q":"Glucagon raises blood glucose during fasting mainly by stimulating the liver to...","choices":["convert blood glucose directly into body protein","break down glycogen and produce new glucose for release","stop producing glucose so that levels can fall","take up glucose from the blood and store it as glycogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Glucagon, secreted when blood glucose is low, signals the liver to carry out glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis and to release glucose into the blood, counteracting hypoglycemia — the opposite of insulin's storage-promoting actions.","cite":"Ch 68, slide 30; Ch 71, slide 9"},{"q":"During a sudden fight-or-flight response, epinephrine helps supply energy by...","choices":["converting glucose into structural protein in the body's tissues","blocking the release of glucose into the blood","promoting glycogen storage to conserve glucose","stimulating rapid glycogen breakdown to raise blood glucose"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Epinephrine promotes glycogenolysis in the liver (and muscle), quickly liberating glucose to fuel a stress response; it also mobilizes fatty acids, providing a rapid surge of available energy substrates.","cite":"Ch 68, slide 30; Ch 71, slide 9"},{"q":"The brain relies heavily on a steady glucose supply because it...","choices":["produces its own glucose independently of the blood","stores large amounts of glycogen for its own use during this process in the tissues","normally uses glucose as its main fuel and stores very little of its own","can only use fatty acids delivered from adipose tissue"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Under normal conditions the brain depends on a continuous supply of blood glucose as its primary fuel and holds almost no energy reserve of its own, which is why hypoglycemia rapidly impairs brain function (though ketones can partly substitute during prolonged fasting).","cite":"Ch 68, slides 25-27; Ch 73, slide 12"},{"q":"When carbohydrate intake exceeds what can be stored as glycogen, the excess is...","choices":["excreted unchanged by the kidneys in the urine","stored indefinitely as additional glycogen without limit","turned directly into muscle protein for growth","converted to fat (lipogenesis) and stored in adipose tissue"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Once the limited glycogen stores are filled, surplus carbohydrate is converted through lipogenesis into fatty acids and triglyceride, which are stored in adipose tissue; this is a major route by which excess dietary carbohydrate contributes to body fat.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 20-23; Ch 68, slide 24"},{"q":"Certain fatty acids are called 'essential' because they...","choices":["cannot be synthesized by the body and must be obtained from the diet","can be produced from glucose whenever they are needed","are the only fatty acids the body can store as fat during this process","provide far more energy per gram than any other fat"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Essential fatty acids (such as linoleic and alpha-linolenic acid) cannot be made by the body and must come from food; they are needed for cell membranes and as precursors of signaling molecules, so their dietary intake is required.","cite":"Ch 69, slides 3-5; Ch 72, slides 20-22"},{"q":"Fat is the body's most efficient long-term energy store largely because it...","choices":["provides the least energy per gram of any fuel under most normal conditions","can be used only by the liver and not by other tissues","is stored with large amounts of water for quick access","yields more energy per gram and is stored with little associated water"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Fat provides about 9 kcal per gram (versus ~4 for carbohydrate or protein) and is stored in a nearly anhydrous form, so it packs far more energy per unit weight than glycogen, which is stored with substantial water — making fat the ideal compact reserve.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 4-5; Ch 73, slide 12"},{"q":"The body maintains an amino-acid pool that is best described as...","choices":["a reserve used only for energy and never for building protein","a set of amino acids that cannot be exchanged or replaced","a fixed, permanent store of protein that is never used under most conditions in the body","a dynamic supply drawn on for protein synthesis and replenished by turnover and diet"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Free amino acids form a pool that is continuously used to build new proteins and replenished by dietary intake and by the breakdown (turnover) of existing body proteins; this balance lets the body remodel and repair proteins constantly.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 3-6"},{"q":"The urea cycle is the body's solution to the problem that...","choices":["amino acids contain too little nitrogen to be useful","the body cannot break down amino acids at all during this particular process in the tissues","ammonia from amino-acid breakdown is toxic and must be converted for safe excretion","glucose must be converted into protein for storage"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Deamination of amino acids releases ammonia, which is toxic even at low levels; the liver's urea cycle converts ammonia into urea, a far safer compound that the kidneys excrete, allowing the body to dispose of nitrogen without ammonia toxicity.","cite":"Ch 70, slides 16-17"},{"q":"Growth hormone promotes a positive nitrogen balance by...","choices":["converting body protein directly into stored fat","accelerating the breakdown of tissue protein for fuel","stimulating amino-acid uptake and protein synthesis in tissues","blocking all amino acids from entering the cells in the body's tissues"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Growth hormone enhances the transport of amino acids into cells and stimulates protein synthesis while sparing protein from breakdown; the net anabolic effect builds tissue protein, producing a positive nitrogen balance during growth.","cite":"Ch 70, slide 19"},{"q":"Ghrelin, secreted largely by the stomach, influences feeding by...","choices":["ending each meal by signaling fullness to the brain","suppressing hunger over the long term as fat stores grow","digesting fats directly within the small intestine","stimulating hunger and rising before meals to prompt eating"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Ghrelin is often called the 'hunger hormone': its levels rise before meals and fall after eating, and it acts on the hypothalamus to stimulate appetite, in contrast to satiety signals like leptin and CCK that reduce intake.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 11-14"},{"q":"The glucostatic idea of appetite regulation proposes that...","choices":["a rise in blood glucose after a meal increases hunger","a fall in blood glucose availability increases hunger and prompts eating","blood glucose has no relationship to appetite at all under these conditions","only long-term fat stores, not glucose, affect appetite"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The glucostatic theory holds that hypothalamic centers monitor glucose availability: when the level or utilization of glucose falls, hunger increases and feeding is stimulated; when it rises after a meal, satiety centers are activated, helping regulate short-term intake.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 9-12"},{"q":"During prolonged starvation, ketone bodies become important because they...","choices":["are stored in large amounts before starvation begins","provide an alternative fuel for the brain, sparing body protein","prevent the body from using any fat for energy in the body's tissues","are the only fuel the body can produce from glucose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. As fasting continues, the brain adapts to use ketone bodies produced by the liver from fat; this reduces the brain's demand for glucose and therefore lessens the breakdown of body protein for gluconeogenesis, prolonging survival.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 17-19; Ch 69, slides 15-19"},{"q":"A stable body temperature is maintained when...","choices":["heat produced by metabolism is balanced by heat lost to the environment","heat loss always greatly exceeds heat production","the body stops producing any heat from metabolism","heat production always greatly exceeds heat loss under most normal conditions"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Body temperature stays constant when heat gain (chiefly from metabolism, plus any absorbed from the environment) equals heat loss (by radiation, conduction, convection, and evaporation); the hypothalamus adjusts these processes to keep the balance.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 2-6"},{"q":"Sweating is unusual among sympathetic responses because the sweat glands are activated by...","choices":["cholinergic sympathetic fibers, using acetylcholine rather than norepinephrine","local reflexes independent of any nervous input during this process in the tissues","parasympathetic fibers that override the sympathetic system","circulating thyroid hormone acting directly on the glands"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Although sweat glands are innervated by the sympathetic nervous system, their postganglionic fibers are cholinergic, releasing acetylcholine; this is an exception to the usual sympathetic transmitter norepinephrine, and it drives thermoregulatory sweating.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 8-14"},{"q":"Countercurrent heat exchange in the limbs helps conserve heat by...","choices":["evaporating water from the surface of the deep vessels","transferring heat from outgoing arterial blood to returning venous blood","preventing any blood from returning to the core as it is usually described here","carrying all the warm blood to the skin surface to radiate heat"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. In the limbs, deep veins run alongside arteries so that warm arterial blood heading outward gives up heat to cooler venous blood returning to the core; this countercurrent exchange retains heat centrally and reduces loss from the extremities in the cold.","cite":"Ch 74, slides 11-14"},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate and resting metabolic rate differ in that basal metabolic rate is measured under...","choices":["stricter standardized conditions of fasting and complete rest","a state immediately following a large meal","exposure to cold that triggers shivering","conditions of heavy physical exertion under most conditions in the body"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Basal metabolic rate is measured under rigorous conditions — after an overnight fast, fully rested, and at a comfortable temperature — whereas resting metabolic rate is measured under less strict resting conditions and is usually slightly higher; both estimate baseline energy needs.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 8-10"},{"q":"Physical activity raises total energy expenditure primarily because...","choices":["contracting muscles greatly increase their consumption of energy substrates","the basal metabolic rate itself falls during exercise","digestion of food stops so all energy goes to movement","body temperature drops, forcing more heat production during this process in the tissues"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Exercise is the most variable component of energy expenditure: working muscles sharply increase their use of glucose and fatty acids to fuel contraction, raising oxygen consumption and total metabolic rate well above the resting level.","cite":"Ch 73, slides 10-12"},{"q":"Many vitamins are required in the diet because they function as...","choices":["major sources of energy, like carbohydrates and fats","structural building blocks of muscle and bone tissue","coenzymes or their precursors, assisting enzymes in metabolic reactions","hormones produced by the body's endocrine glands as it typically occurs here"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Numerous vitamins (especially the B-complex) serve as coenzymes or coenzyme precursors that enzymes need to catalyze metabolic reactions; because the body cannot synthesize them in adequate amounts, they must be supplied by the diet, and deficiency impairs the linked pathways.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 20-24"},{"q":"Minerals such as calcium and iron are essential nutrients because, respectively, they...","choices":["act as the main digestive enzymes in the gut during this process in the tissues","support bone structure and nerve/muscle function, and form part of hemoglobin","provide most of the body's daily energy needs","are stored as fat for long-term energy reserves"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Calcium is needed for bone and teeth and for nerve conduction and muscle contraction, while iron is a key component of hemoglobin (and other proteins) for oxygen transport; both are required in the diet for these specific roles.","cite":"Ch 72, slides 24-26"},{"q":"External respiration and internal respiration refer, respectively, to gas exchange...","choices":["between blood and tissues, and between alveoli and blood as a general rule","only within the airways, and only within the bloodstream","between the nose and the trachea, and within the alveoli","between alveoli and blood, and between blood and the body's tissues"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. External respiration is the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide between the alveoli and the pulmonary blood, while internal respiration is the exchange between the systemic blood and the metabolizing tissues; both rely on diffusion down partial-pressure gradients.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 3-6, 71-74"},{"q":"Emphysema and pulmonary fibrosis affect compliance in opposite ways: emphysema tends to...","choices":["stiffen the lung, while fibrosis makes it easier to inflate","make the lung easier to inflate and to recoil normally","increase compliance by destroying elastic tissue, while fibrosis stiffens the lung","have no measurable effect on lung compliance at all as it is usually described here"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Emphysema destroys alveolar walls and elastic fibers, so the lung becomes floppy and easier to inflate (higher compliance) but recoils poorly; fibrosis lays down stiff tissue, lowering compliance so the lung is harder to inflate. They alter lung mechanics in opposite directions.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 19-21"},{"q":"Minute ventilation is calculated as...","choices":["the inspiratory reserve minus the expiratory reserve","the residual volume divided by the tidal volume","tidal volume multiplied by the respiratory rate","vital capacity multiplied by the residual volume"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Minute ventilation is the total volume of air moved per minute, equal to the tidal volume of each breath times the number of breaths per minute; it represents total airflow, though not all of it reaches the alveoli for exchange.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"Alveolar ventilation is a better measure of effective breathing than minute ventilation because it...","choices":["measures only the residual volume left after expiration","ignores the tidal volume entirely in its calculation as a general rule","counts all air moved, including that filling the airways","accounts for dead space, reflecting only air that reaches the alveoli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Alveolar ventilation subtracts the dead-space volume (air in conducting airways that never reaches alveoli) from each breath, so it reflects only the air available for gas exchange; this is why slow, deep breathing can be more effective than rapid, shallow breathing at the same minute ventilation.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 32-35"},{"q":"Insufficient surfactant, as in a premature newborn, leads to breathing difficulty because...","choices":["the alveoli become too easy to inflate and overexpand","alveoli tend to collapse, so much greater effort is needed to reinflate them","gas exchange speeds up beyond what the blood can handle","surface tension in the alveoli drops too low under most conditions throughout the body"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Without adequate surfactant, alveolar surface tension is high; alveoli collapse at the end of expiration, and reopening them requires large pressures, greatly increasing the work of breathing — the basis of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 22-24"},{"q":"In the upright lung, ventilation and perfusion are not perfectly matched; at the apex compared with the base there is...","choices":["relatively more ventilation than perfusion (a higher V/Q ratio)","exactly equal ventilation and perfusion throughout as a general rule","relatively more perfusion than ventilation than the base","no ventilation and no perfusion reaching that region"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Gravity makes both ventilation and perfusion greater at the base, but perfusion increases more steeply, so the apex has a relatively higher ventilation-to-perfusion ratio, while the base has a relatively lower one. This regional variation is normal in the upright lung.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 64-66"},{"q":"A ventilation-perfusion mismatch can take two forms: a shunt is best described as...","choices":["complete absence of both airflow and blood flow","blood passing alveoli that are perfused but not ventilated","air reaching alveoli that are ventilated but not perfused","equal ventilation and perfusion in every alveolus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. A shunt is perfusion without adequate ventilation — blood flows past alveoli that receive little or no air, so it is not oxygenated. Its counterpart, dead space, is ventilation without perfusion (alveoli receive air but no blood flow).","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 64-66"},{"q":"In a healthy lung, oxygen uptake is described as perfusion-limited, meaning that...","choices":["the membrane is too thick for oxygen to cross at all","blood becomes fully oxygenated so quickly that only increasing blood flow raises uptake","oxygen can never fully equilibrate with the blood during this particular process in the tissues","blood flow has no effect on how much oxygen is taken up"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Normally, oxygen equilibrates between alveolus and blood long before the blood leaves the capillary, so the amount taken up is limited by how much blood flows through (perfusion), not by diffusion; only in disease with a thickened membrane does diffusion become the limiting factor.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 67-69"},{"q":"During heavy exercise, forced expiration becomes active and is driven largely by...","choices":["contraction of the abdominal and internal intercostal muscles","relaxation of the diaphragm alone, as in quiet breathing","the release of surfactant that forces air out under these conditions","contraction of the diaphragm to push air outward"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Whereas quiet expiration is passive, forced expiration recruits the abdominal muscles (which push the diaphragm upward) and the internal intercostals (which pull the ribs down), actively decreasing thoracic volume to expel air rapidly during exertion.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 12-14"},{"q":"The respiratory membrane is well suited to gas exchange because it is...","choices":["lined with cartilage that supports rapid exchange in the body's tissues","extremely thin, so gases have only a very short distance to diffuse","quite thick, which slows diffusion but filters the air","covered by thick mucus that traps the diffusing gases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. The respiratory membrane is only about 0.2 to 0.6 micrometers thick, giving oxygen and carbon dioxide a very short diffusion path; combined with its enormous surface area, this thinness makes gas exchange rapid and efficient.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 57-60"},{"q":"The pontine (pneumotaxic) center influences breathing mainly by...","choices":["generating the fundamental breathing rhythm on its own","contracting the diaphragm directly through the phrenic nerve","sensing arterial oxygen at the carotid bodies under most conditions in the body","limiting the duration of inspiration and helping set the breathing rate"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The pneumotaxic center in the pons sends signals that switch off inspiration, thereby limiting inspiratory time; a stronger signal shortens inspiration and quickens the rate, so this center helps fine-tune the rhythm generated by the medulla.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 88-90"},{"q":"The reason hemoglobin is essential for oxygen transport is that, without it,...","choices":["the small amount of oxygen dissolved in plasma could not meet tissue demands","carbon dioxide would be unable to leave the tissues","the lungs would be unable to ventilate at all during this process in the tissues","oxygen could not diffuse across the respiratory membrane"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Oxygen is poorly soluble, so plasma alone carries only a tiny fraction of the body's needs; hemoglobin increases the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity many-fold by binding oxygen, which is why anemia (low hemoglobin) so seriously reduces oxygen delivery.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 76-77"},{"q":"A rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve is caused by conditions such as...","choices":["a complete absence of carbon dioxide in the tissues","the presence of carbon monoxide in the blood during this process","decreased CO2, increased pH, and lower temperature","increased CO2, increased acidity, and higher temperature"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Higher CO2, lower pH (more acid), higher temperature, and increased 2,3-BPG all shift the curve rightward, lowering hemoglobin's oxygen affinity and promoting oxygen release; these are exactly the conditions found in active, metabolizing tissue that needs more oxygen.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-81"},{"q":"A leftward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin curve, indicating higher affinity, occurs with...","choices":["decreased temperature, decreased CO2, and the presence of fetal hemoglobin","increased temperature and increased acidity in the tissues","a rise in CO2 and hydrogen ion concentration as it is usually described here","heavy exercise that raises the tissue temperature"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Lower temperature, lower CO2/acidity, decreased 2,3-BPG, fetal hemoglobin, and carbon monoxide all shift the curve leftward, raising oxygen affinity so hemoglobin binds oxygen more tightly and releases it less readily at the tissues.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 80-82"},{"q":"The chloride shift accompanies bicarbonate handling because, as bicarbonate leaves the red cell,...","choices":["oxygen is forced out of the cell in exchange in most cases","chloride enters the cell to keep it electrically balanced","the cell manufactures new hemoglobin to compensate","sodium leaves the cell to replace the lost charge"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Carbonic anhydrase generates bicarbonate inside the red cell; as bicarbonate diffuses out into plasma, chloride moves in (the chloride, or Hamburger, shift) to preserve electrical neutrality, allowing large amounts of CO2 to be carried as plasma bicarbonate.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"Compared with the oxygen curve, the carbon dioxide dissociation relationship is steeper and more linear, which means blood can...","choices":["exchange CO2 only in the tissues and never in the lungs","load and unload large amounts of CO2 with modest changes in its partial pressure","only transport CO2 that is bound directly to oxygen during this process in the tissues","carry no carbon dioxide unless its pressure is extremely high"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Because the CO2 dissociation curve is steeper and nearly linear over the physiologic range, relatively small changes in PCO2 produce large changes in CO2 content, so the blood can take up CO2 at the tissues and release it at the lungs efficiently with modest pressure differences.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 83-87"},{"q":"Acidosis and alkalosis are defined by blood pH such that acidosis is a...","choices":["shift toward a higher-than-normal pH (fewer hydrogen ions)","condition affecting only oxygen levels, not pH","shift toward a lower-than-normal pH (more hydrogen ions)","state in which blood pH cannot change at all"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Acidosis refers to a process lowering blood pH below the normal range (an increase in hydrogen ion concentration), while alkalosis refers to a process raising pH above normal; each can arise from respiratory (CO2) or metabolic causes.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"A disturbance is called a respiratory (rather than metabolic) acid-base problem when it originates from...","choices":["the loss of stomach acid through vomiting","an accumulation of lactic acid during exercise","a change in CO2 caused by altered ventilation","a change in bicarbonate produced by the kidneys"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Respiratory acid-base disturbances arise from changes in CO2 due to hypo- or hyperventilation (CO2 retention lowers pH; excess CO2 removal raises it), whereas metabolic disturbances arise from changes in bicarbonate or fixed acids independent of CO2.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 91-92, 100"},{"q":"At the tissues, carbon dioxide moves from the cells into the blood because...","choices":["the blood actively pumps carbon dioxide out of the cells","the PCO2 of metabolizing cells is higher than that of the arriving blood","cell PCO2 is always lower than that of the blood under most conditions in the body","oxygen forces the carbon dioxide out of the cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Metabolizing cells continuously produce CO2, keeping their PCO2 above that of the arterial blood entering the capillaries; CO2 therefore diffuses down its partial-pressure gradient from the cells into the blood to be carried to the lungs.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 71-74"},{"q":"Peripheral chemoreceptors also respond to blood pH, so a fall in pH (acidosis) tends to...","choices":["suppress ventilation, allowing CO2 to accumulate further","cause the kidneys to immediately exhale the excess acid","have no effect on breathing, since only CO2 matters during this process","stimulate ventilation, helping to remove CO2 and correct the pH"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The carotid and aortic bodies sense a fall in pH and increase their signaling to the respiratory center; the resulting rise in ventilation blows off CO2, which lowers carbonic acid and helps raise the pH back toward normal — a respiratory compensation for acidosis.","cite":"Pulmonary I & II, slides 95-99"},{"q":"Formation of the platelet plug follows the sequence of...","choices":["dissolution of the vessel wall to release clotting factors","aggregation first, then adhesion, and finally activation under these conditions","conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin before any platelets act","adhesion to the injured wall, activation, then aggregation into a plug"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Platelets first adhere to exposed collagen at the injury (aided by von Willebrand factor), then become activated and release mediators such as ADP and thromboxane A2, which recruit and cause more platelets to aggregate, building the primary hemostatic plug.","cite":"Hemostasis & Coagulation, slides 30-34"},{"q":"Interferons contribute to innate defense against viruses by...","choices":["signaling neighboring cells to resist viral replication","carrying oxygen to virus-infected tissues","forming the membrane attack complex that lyses cells","directly binding and neutralizing circulating antibodies"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Virus-infected cells release interferons, which act on nearby cells to induce an antiviral state — producing proteins that interfere with viral replication — thereby limiting the spread of the virus before the adaptive response is fully mobilized.","cite":"Blood & Immunology, slides 52-53, 60"},{"q":"The stomach lining is protected from its own acid and pepsin mainly by...","choices":["a continuous flow of bile that neutralizes the acid in the body","rapid peristalsis that keeps acid away from the lining","a layer of mucus and bicarbonate secreted over the epithelium","the complete absence of acid in contact with the wall"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Surface mucous cells secrete a thick, bicarbonate-rich mucus layer that coats the gastric epithelium; this barrier neutralizes acid at the cell surface and shields the lining from pepsin, so the stomach can hold strong acid without digesting itself.","cite":"GI Physiology, slides 82-90"}]},"physio-master-v10":{"title":"Physiology Master Exam (v10)","questions":[{"q":"Which best explains why plasma proteins such as albumin are essential to fluid balance?","choices":["They generate colloid osmotic pressure that pulls fluid back into capillaries","They carry the bulk of oxygen to the tissues","They directly trigger the vascular spasm that stops bleeding as a general rule","They set the freezing point of blood to regulate temperature"],"answer":0,"exp":"Albumin is the main plasma protein creating oncotic pressure, opposing filtration and holding fluid in vessels."},{"q":"How do serum and plasma differ?","choices":["Serum contains red cells while plasma does not","Plasma lacks electrolytes that serum keeps","Serum is the cellular portion and plasma the liquid in this setting","Serum is plasma after the clotting proteins have been used up"],"answer":3,"exp":"Serum is what remains once clotting occurs, so it lacks fibrinogen and other consumed clotting factors."},{"q":"Which pairing correctly matches a blood component to its main job?","choices":["Platelets — sealing a plug at sites of vessel injury","Red cells — presenting antigens to lymphocytes","Albumin — converting fibrinogen into fibrin","Neutrophils — carrying most of the body's oxygen here"],"answer":0,"exp":"Platelets adhere and aggregate to seal breaks in vessel walls."},{"q":"Two patients share the same hematocrit, yet one has much lower blood hemoglobin. What best explains this?","choices":["That patient must have extra plasma proteins","That patient has a much higher white-cell count in the healthy body","Each of that patient's red cells holds less hemoglobin than normal","It is impossible; the two always move together"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hematocrit reflects cell volume; if cells are underfilled with hemoglobin, the two values diverge."},{"q":"Why does hemoglobin's oxygen binding follow an S-shaped curve rather than a straight line?","choices":["Each hemoglobin can carry only a single oxygen molecule in this setting","Oxygen simply dissolves in plasma in direct proportion","Iron is permanently released each time oxygen binds","Binding is cooperative — each oxygen bound makes the next easier"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cooperativity among the four heme sites produces the sigmoid shape."},{"q":"Erythropoietin secretion rises in response to which stimulus?","choices":["A rise in blood calcium concentration","Reduced oxygen delivery sensed by the kidney","An increase in plasma fibrinogen","A fall in the circulating white-cell count here"],"answer":1,"exp":"Low tissue oxygen detected by the kidney drives erythropoietin and more red-cell production."},{"q":"Chronic vitamin B₁₂ deficiency produces anemia with abnormally large red cells. Why large rather than small?","choices":["B₁₂ deficiency floods the marrow with excess iron","B₁₂ is needed for DNA synthesis, so precursors keep growing but divide poorly","Lack of B₁₂ drives erythropoietin to oversized levels under normal conditions","B₁₂ deficiency makes hemoglobin crystallize and swell"],"answer":1,"exp":"Impaired DNA replication delays cell division, yielding fewer but larger cells."},{"q":"Tissue injury exposes tissue factor to blood. Which pathway does this start, and how fast?","choices":["The extrinsic pathway, which acts within seconds","The intrinsic pathway, over many minutes","Fibrinolysis, dissolving any clot at once","The common pathway, bypassing factor X entirely here"],"answer":0,"exp":"Tissue factor triggers the fast extrinsic route to clotting."},{"q":"Warfarin blocks vitamin K recycling. Why does this impair clotting?","choices":["Several clotting factors need vitamin K for the liver to build working versions","Vitamin K is the enzyme that converts fibrinogen to fibrin in the healthy body","Vitamin K physically forms the platelet plug","Vitamin K is the calcium source clotting requires"],"answer":0,"exp":"Vitamin K–dependent factors can't be properly synthesized, weakening the cascade."},{"q":"What is thrombin's central role in coagulation?","choices":["It permanently prevents any clot from forming under normal conditions","It carries oxygen within the forming clot","It converts fibrinogen to fibrin and drives more of its own formation","It dissolves fibrin once bleeding has stopped"],"answer":2,"exp":"Thrombin is the hinge enzyme, making fibrin and feeding back to generate more thrombin."},{"q":"Which white cell is usually the first and most numerous responder to a bacterial infection?","choices":["Eosinophil","Basophil","Lymphocyte","Neutrophil"],"answer":3,"exp":"Neutrophils arrive first in large numbers and phagocytize bacteria."},{"q":"How does a macrophage bridge innate and adaptive immunity?","choices":["It secretes antibodies after becoming a plasma cell in this setting","It carries oxygen to the inflamed tissue","It weaves the fibrin mesh of a blood clot","It engulfs invaders and then presents their antigens to lymphocytes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Antigen presentation links innate ingestion to activation of adaptive immunity."},{"q":"A limb's lymphatic drainage becomes blocked. What is the immediate result, and why?","choices":["Dehydration, because lymph is the body's main water store as a general rule","Swelling, because leaked capillary fluid can no longer return to the blood","Immediate clotting of the limb's veins","Loss of all red cells from the region"],"answer":1,"exp":"Lymphatics normally reclaim interstitial fluid, so a blockage backs it up as edema."},{"q":"Why are lymph nodes placed along the lymphatic vessels?","choices":["To pump lymph back to the heart with cardiac muscle in this setting","To manufacture red blood cells in adults","To store bile between meals","So antigens carried in lymph are filtered and shown to lymphocytes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Nodes act as checkpoints where immune cells sample the drainage."},{"q":"Which statement describes opsonization by complement?","choices":["Directly synthesizing antibodies against the microbe in this setting","Coating a microbe so phagocytes recognize and engulf it more readily","Raising the hypothalamic temperature set point","Storing a memory of the pathogen for decades"],"answer":1,"exp":"Opsonization tags a target to make phagocytosis more efficient."},{"q":"Antibodies generally do not kill pathogens directly. What do they mainly do?","choices":["Punch pores in every microbe on direct contact as a general rule","Neutralize, clump, and flag targets for phagocytes and complement","Replace red cells lost during the infection","Digest microbes with their own enzymes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Antibodies tag and immobilize; the killing is done by other effectors."},{"q":"Which cell directly kills the body's own virus-infected cells?","choices":["Antibody-secreting plasma cell","Oxygen-carrying red blood cell","Clot-forming platelet fragment","Cytotoxic T lymphocyte"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cytotoxic T-cells recognize and destroy infected host cells."},{"q":"What is the key advantage of acquired immunity over innate immunity on repeat exposure?","choices":["Memory makes the second response faster and larger","It reacts within seconds without any prior exposure","It treats every pathogen in exactly the same way","It functions with no lymphocytes involved"],"answer":0,"exp":"Immunological memory accelerates and amplifies later responses."},{"q":"A vaccine's second dose produces far more antibody than the first. Why?","choices":["The first dose erases all specificity, so the second starts fresh in this setting","Antibodies absorbed from food replace the response","Innate barriers strengthen permanently after one dose","Memory cells from the first dose allow a rapid, high-magnitude response"],"answer":3,"exp":"Earlier clonal expansion leaves primed memory cells for a bigger secondary response."},{"q":"In allergy, why does a second exposure to the allergen cause immediate symptoms?","choices":["The allergen directly dissolves cell membranes on contact","IgE from the first exposure coats mast cells, which degranulate when the allergen returns","The first exposure made cytotoxic T-cells that lyse the allergen during normal physiology","Complement forms a clot around the allergen"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pre-formed IgE primes mast cells for rapid histamine release."},{"q":"Which contraction pattern moves intestinal contents forward, versus mixing them?","choices":["Segmentation propels forward while peristalsis mixes as part of the process","Both patterns only mix and never propel","Both patterns only propel and never mix","Peristalsis propels contents forward while segmentation mixes them in place"],"answer":3,"exp":"Peristalsis is propulsive; segmentation is local mixing."},{"q":"Acidic chyme entering the duodenum stimulates which hormone, with what effect?","choices":["Secretin, which increases the stomach's acid output in this setting","Gastrin, which triggers pancreatic bicarbonate","Secretin, which prompts the pancreas to release bicarbonate","Cholecystokinin, which is released mainly by acid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Secretin responds to acid and triggers bicarbonate to neutralize it."},{"q":"Why is pepsin active in the stomach but not in the mouth?","choices":["Pepsin requires the acidic environment the stomach provides","Pepsin works only in the alkaline duodenum","The mouth secretes pepsin but supplies no substrate in this setting","Saliva chemically destroys all protein enzymes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Pepsin needs a low pH to work, and saliva's pH is too high."},{"q":"What makes bile salts effective at handling dietary fat?","choices":["They chemically digest fat into glycerol by themselves as part of the process","They neutralize stomach acid in place of bicarbonate","They convert dietary fat directly into glucose","They are amphipathic, emulsifying large fat globules into many small droplets"],"answer":3,"exp":"Water-liking and fat-liking ends let bile salts break fat into droplets for lipase."},{"q":"Which correctly describes the exocrine pancreas's two outputs and their triggers?","choices":["Bicarbonate on cholecystokinin's signal and enzymes on secretin's as a general rule","Bicarbonate on secretin's signal and digestive enzymes on cholecystokinin's signal","Insulin and glucagon delivered into the duodenum","Bile and intrinsic factor"],"answer":1,"exp":"Secretin drives bicarbonate release; cholecystokinin drives enzyme release."},{"q":"Why does the liver get 'first pass' at nutrients absorbed from the gut?","choices":["The liver sits inside the wall of the stomach","Gut venous blood drains through the portal vein into the liver before reaching the body","Nutrients are absorbed straight into the liver's bile ducts when the system is at rest in this setting","The liver receives all its blood from the pulmonary artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"Portal circulation routes absorbed material through the liver first."},{"q":"Which is a liver function in handling nitrogen waste?","choices":["Converting urea back into usable protein","Storing ammonia in bile for later use","Converting toxic ammonia into urea for excretion","Excreting ammonia unchanged through the skin here"],"answer":2,"exp":"The liver's urea cycle detoxifies ammonia from amino-acid breakdown."},{"q":"Glucose and amino acids are absorbed mainly by which mechanism, and where do they go first?","choices":["Packaging into chylomicrons that enter the lymph","Simple diffusion straight into lymphatic lacteals in this setting","Active transport into bile for recycling","Sodium-coupled transport, then into portal blood toward the liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"The sodium gradient drives uptake, and these water-soluble nutrients take the portal route."},{"q":"Why do absorbed fats enter the lymph before the blood?","choices":["Fats are water-soluble and dissolve straight into plasma in this setting","Blood capillaries actively reject all lipids","They are repackaged into chylomicrons too large for blood capillaries","Lymph digests the fat that blood cannot"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chylomicrons enter lymphatic lacteals before later joining the bloodstream."},{"q":"What allows voluntary control over the otherwise reflexive process of defecation?","choices":["The internal anal sphincter is skeletal and voluntary in this setting","The rectum contains no stretch receptors at all","Mass movements are entirely under conscious command","The external anal sphincter is skeletal muscle under conscious control"],"answer":3,"exp":"Voluntary skeletal control of the external sphincter allows defecation to be delayed."},{"q":"Which liver function keeps blood glucose steady between meals?","choices":["Breaking down stored glycogen and making new glucose to release","Storing dietary glucose permanently as bile in the healthy body","Converting glucose into urea for excretion","Absorbing glucose directly from the airways"],"answer":0,"exp":"The liver mobilizes glycogen and performs gluconeogenesis to sustain blood glucose."},{"q":"A patient with liver failure has low albumin and easy bleeding. Which liver role explains both?","choices":["The liver stores albumin and clotting factors made by the kidney in this setting","The liver makes the red cells that carry albumin","The liver absorbs whole albumin directly from food","The liver synthesizes plasma proteins, including albumin and clotting factors"],"answer":3,"exp":"Failing protein synthesis lowers albumin and clotting factors together."},{"q":"How much ATP does glycolysis yield, and does it need oxygen?","choices":["The majority of the cell's ATP, using oxygen in this setting","No ATP at all; it only consumes energy","A small net of two ATP, and it does not require oxygen","Two ATP, but only when oxygen is present"],"answer":2,"exp":"Glycolysis nets two ATP and proceeds without oxygen."},{"q":"Where is most ATP from glucose produced, and what does it require?","choices":["Oxidative phosphorylation, which requires oxygen","Glycolysis, which requires oxygen","The citric acid cycle alone, without any oxygen","Directly during glucose absorption in the gut"],"answer":0,"exp":"The electron-transport stage makes most of the ATP and depends on oxygen."},{"q":"Why is maintaining blood glucose critical even during a fast?","choices":["The brain depends almost entirely on glucose for fuel","Muscle can use no fuel other than glucose","Glucose is the only molecule that carries oxygen here","Red cells store glucose for the whole body"],"answer":0,"exp":"Neurons rely on glucose, so the body actively defends blood glucose."},{"q":"During prolonged fasting, the liver turns surplus acetyl-CoA into which alternative fuel?","choices":["Additional red blood cells","Bile salts for fat digestion in this setting","Ketone bodies, which the brain can use","Urea for the kidneys"],"answer":2,"exp":"Ketones spare glucose and fuel the brain during fasting."},{"q":"Which lipoprotein returns excess cholesterol from tissues back to the liver?","choices":["LDL","HDL","Chylomicrons","VLDL"],"answer":1,"exp":"HDL carries out reverse cholesterol transport toward the liver."},{"q":"Why must triglycerides travel inside lipoproteins in the blood?","choices":["They are too small to move without a carrier","Plasma enzymes would instantly turn them into glucose in this setting","They are not water-soluble and cannot dissolve in plasma alone","Lipoproteins are needed to freeze them for transport"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lipoproteins ferry insoluble fat through watery blood."},{"q":"To burn an amino acid for energy, what happens first, and what becomes of its nitrogen?","choices":["Its nitrogen is removed, then converted to urea for excretion","Its carbon skeleton is excreted while nitrogen is burned here","It is stored intact as glycogen","It is converted directly into bile"],"answer":0,"exp":"Nitrogen removal frees the carbon skeleton, and the liver turns the nitrogen into urea."},{"q":"Growth hormone and cortisol have opposite effects on body protein. Which is correct?","choices":["Growth hormone breaks down protein while cortisol builds it","Both hormones only build protein","Growth hormone builds protein while cortisol breaks it down","Both hormones only break down protein"],"answer":2,"exp":"Growth hormone is anabolic and cortisol is catabolic for protein."},{"q":"Why is fat the body's largest energy reserve compared with glycogen?","choices":["It provides fewer calories per gram but more volume in this setting","It stores more energy per gram and is kept nearly water-free","Glycogen holds no water and is denser than fat","Fat is the body's only usable fuel"],"answer":1,"exp":"About nine kilocalories per gram and minimal stored water make fat highly energy-dense."},{"q":"In early starvation, which fuel store is depleted first?","choices":["Body fat, before glycogen","Structural muscle protein, before any fat","Glycogen","Dietary fiber reserves"],"answer":2,"exp":"Glycogen is the small, quick-access store the body draws down first."},{"q":"Which hormone signals fullness and reflects the body's fat stores?","choices":["Ghrelin","Secretin","Erythropoietin","Leptin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Leptin rises with fat stores and promotes a sense of fullness."},{"q":"What is the hypothalamus's role in temperature regulation?","choices":["It acts as a thermostat, comparing body temperature to a set point and triggering responses","It only measures temperature but cannot trigger responses when the system is at rest in this setting","It sets body temperature by controlling bile flow","It cools the body only by speeding the heart"],"answer":0,"exp":"The hypothalamus defends a set-point temperature by initiating heat gain or loss."},{"q":"When the body is too hot, which response promotes heat loss?","choices":["Shivering together with vasoconstriction","Piloerection to trap a layer of air","Reduced blood flow to the skin surface","Skin vasodilation together with sweating"],"answer":3,"exp":"Dilating skin vessels and evaporating sweat shed heat."},{"q":"Sweating cools the body only under what condition?","choices":["When the sweat actually evaporates","Whenever sweat is produced, regardless of evaporation","Only when the sweat is reabsorbed by the skin","Only in a cold environment"],"answer":0,"exp":"Evaporation is the cooling step; sweat that merely drips off does not cool."},{"q":"During a fever, why do chills and shivering occur while temperature is rising?","choices":["The set point falls, so the body overheats","Pyrogens raise the set point, so the body feels cold until it reaches the new target","The hypothalamus stops working entirely","Sweating increases in order to raise temperature when the system is at rest in this setting"],"answer":1,"exp":"A higher set point makes current temperature feel too low, driving heat generation."},{"q":"Basal metabolic rate is measured at rest, fasting, in comfortable temperature. Why those conditions?","choices":["To push the measured rate as high as possible","Because metabolism stops unless the person is fasting when the system is at rest","To measure only the energy used by digestion","To exclude activity and digestion so only the baseline resting cost is captured"],"answer":3,"exp":"Controlling those variables isolates true basal energy expenditure."},{"q":"Which factor raises metabolic rate?","choices":["Advancing age with loss of muscle","Deep sleep","Falling sympathetic nervous activity","Increased thyroid hormone"],"answer":3,"exp":"Thyroid hormone increases the metabolic rate."},{"q":"A respiratory quotient near 0.7 indicates the body is mainly burning which fuel?","choices":["Carbohydrate","Fat","Pure protein only","No fuel is being burned at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Fat oxidation yields a respiratory quotient around 0.7."},{"q":"Which muscle does most of the work of quiet inspiration, and what nerve drives it?","choices":["The abdominal muscles, driven by the vagus","The diaphragm, driven by the phrenic nerve","The internal intercostals, driven by the phrenic nerve","The diaphragm, driven by the optic nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The diaphragm is the primary muscle of quiet inspiration, supplied by the phrenic nerve."},{"q":"By what principle does contracting the diaphragm draw air into the lungs?","choices":["Contraction pushes air out by raising the pressure","The lungs actively pump air the way the heart pumps blood in this setting","Enlarging the chest lowers internal pressure, so air flows inward","Warm air simply rises into the lungs on its own"],"answer":2,"exp":"Increasing volume drops pressure below outside air, and air flows in."},{"q":"Why do the lungs stay inflated rather than collapsing from their own elastic recoil?","choices":["A slightly negative intrapleural pressure holds them open","The lungs contain rigid cartilage that blocks collapse","Positive pressure from the stomach props them up","Surfactant makes the lungs completely non-elastic"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pleural vacuum counteracts the lung's inward elastic recoil."},{"q":"Which lung volume cannot be measured by ordinary spirometry, and why?","choices":["Tidal volume, because it is too small to detect","Inspiratory reserve, because it enters too fast","Residual volume, because it never leaves the lungs","Expiratory reserve, because it mixes with tidal air"],"answer":2,"exp":"Spirometry measures moved air, and residual air is never exhaled."},{"q":"What does vital capacity represent?","choices":["Every bit of air the lungs hold, including residual when the system is at rest in this setting","The most air a person can move — tidal plus inspiratory and expiratory reserves","Only the air in one normal quiet breath","The air that can never be exhaled"],"answer":1,"exp":"Vital capacity is all the movable air, excluding the residual volume."},{"q":"How does surfactant make breathing easier?","choices":["It raises surface tension to hold the alveoli open when the system is at rest in this setting","It thickens the respiratory membrane for strength","It lowers surface tension, raising compliance and keeping small alveoli from collapsing","It carries oxygen straight into the blood"],"answer":2,"exp":"Reducing surface tension stabilizes alveoli and eases inflation."},{"q":"At the lung, in what directions do oxygen and carbon dioxide move, and what drives it?","choices":["Oxygen into the blood and carbon dioxide out, each down its partial-pressure gradient","Both oxygen and carbon dioxide move into the blood","Movement requires active pumping by alveolar cells","Oxygen out and carbon dioxide in, against the gradients when the system is at rest in this setting"],"answer":0,"exp":"Gases diffuse passively along their own pressure gradients."},{"q":"Why does blood leaving the lung stay nearly fully oxygenated even if alveolar oxygen dips a little?","choices":["The blood bypasses the alveoli entirely","Exchange is fast and finishes with a safety margin before blood exits the capillary","Oxygen is pumped in by muscular capillaries","Hemoglobin releases oxygen at the lung to stay balanced when the system is at rest"],"answer":1,"exp":"A reserve in transit time keeps loading complete despite minor dips in alveolar oxygen."},{"q":"Which features of the respiratory membrane make gas exchange rapid?","choices":["A thick barrier with a small surface area","A muscular wall that squeezes gases across","A very thin barrier and a very large total surface area","An impermeable lining that blocks gas movement in this setting"],"answer":2,"exp":"Thinness and large surface area both speed diffusion."},{"q":"Fluid buildup in the lungs slows gas exchange mainly because it does what?","choices":["Increases the partial-pressure gradient for oxygen in this setting","Makes the membrane more permeable to gases","Thickens the diffusion barrier that the gases must cross","Shrinks the alveolar surface tension to zero"],"answer":2,"exp":"A thicker membrane slows diffusion of the gases."},{"q":"Which brain region generates the basic breathing rhythm?","choices":["The medulla","The cerebellum","The pituitary","The thalamus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The medulla sets the fundamental respiratory rhythm."},{"q":"What is the strongest minute-to-minute driver of ventilation, sensed centrally?","choices":["Falling oxygen, sensed centrally as the main driver in this setting","Rising blood glucose","Falling body temperature","Rising carbon dioxide, detected as increased hydrogen ion"],"answer":3,"exp":"Central chemoreceptors respond mainly to carbon dioxide sensed as acid."},{"q":"About what fraction of blood oxygen is carried on hemoglobin rather than dissolved?","choices":["About half of it","Almost none; most is dissolved in plasma","The large majority, roughly 98 percent","Exactly one quarter"],"answer":2,"exp":"Nearly all oxygen is bound to hemoglobin, with very little dissolved."},{"q":"During exercise, muscle produces heat, acid, and carbon dioxide. How does this aid oxygen delivery?","choices":["It shifts the oxygen–hemoglobin curve right, so more oxygen unloads","It shifts the curve left, so hemoglobin holds oxygen tighter in this setting","It stops hemoglobin from carrying oxygen at all","It raises oxygen solubility in plasma to bypass hemoglobin"],"answer":0,"exp":"A rightward shift lowers affinity and releases more oxygen where it's needed."},{"q":"Which conditions shift the oxygen–hemoglobin curve left, so hemoglobin holds oxygen tighter?","choices":["Heat, high carbon dioxide, and acid in this setting","Cold, low carbon dioxide, and fetal hemoglobin","Exercise with a rising temperature","High levels of BPG"],"answer":1,"exp":"These raise hemoglobin's affinity and shift the curve left."},{"q":"In what form is most carbon dioxide carried in the blood?","choices":["Bound to the iron of hemoglobin, like oxygen","As bicarbonate","Almost entirely dissolved in the plasma","As solid crystals inside the red cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The majority of carbon dioxide travels as bicarbonate."},{"q":"As bicarbonate leaves the red cell, chloride moves in. What is the purpose of this chloride shift?","choices":["To carry oxygen into the red cell","To generate ATP for the red cell","To keep the electrical charge balanced across the cell membrane","To digest carbon dioxide into glucose under normal conditions"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chloride entering offsets the negative bicarbonate leaving."},{"q":"A person hyperventilates and blows off large amounts of carbon dioxide. What happens to blood pH?","choices":["It falls toward acidosis because carbon dioxide is a base in this setting","It rises toward alkalosis as carbon dioxide and hydrogen ion fall","It stays exactly the same","It falls because bicarbonate rises sharply"],"answer":1,"exp":"Removing carbon dioxide pulls the reaction toward less hydrogen ion, raising pH."},{"q":"Compared with the lungs, how do the kidneys contribute to acid–base balance?","choices":["More slowly but thoroughly, by adjusting bicarbonate over hours to days","Faster than the lungs, within seconds","By directly exhaling carbon dioxide","They play no role in acid–base balance when the system is at rest in this setting"],"answer":0,"exp":"Renal compensation is slower but powerful, complementing the fast lung response."},{"q":"At an active tissue, which gradients drive gas exchange?","choices":["Low tissue oxygen pulls oxygen out of blood while high tissue carbon dioxide pushes it in","High tissue oxygen pushes oxygen back into the blood when the system is at rest in this setting","Low tissue carbon dioxide pulls it out of the tissue","Gases move by active transport, not by gradients"],"answer":0,"exp":"Gases diffuse down their gradients, opposite to the pattern at the lung."}]},"pharm-master":{"title":"Pharmacodynamics Master Exam","questions":[{"q":"A drug moves across the endothelial lining of blood vessels through aqueous pores, down its concentration gradient. This process is best described by which principle?","choices":["Endocytosis of impermeant solutes","Carrier-mediated active transport","Fick's law of aqueous diffusion","Michaelis-Menten capacity-limited kinetics"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Aqueous diffusion through the endothelial pores between blood and extravascular space is governed by Fick's law, driven by the concentration gradient.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 9-10"},{"q":"According to Fick's law, drug absorption is fastest across a membrane that is:","choices":["Large in surface area and thick","Large in surface area and thin","Small in surface area and thin","Small in surface area and thick"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Flux rises with area and falls with thickness, so large area + thin membrane (e.g., lungs) maximizes absorption.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 11"},{"q":"A weak acid drug is placed in an acidic environment. What is the consequence for its membrane permeability?","choices":["It becomes charged and water-soluble","It becomes deprotonated and lipid-insoluble","It becomes protonated, uncharged, and lipid-soluble","Its pKa shifts toward neutrality"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. In an acidic solution a weak acid is protonated (HA), uncharged, and therefore lipid-soluble — as with the protonated form of aspirin.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 18"},{"q":"P-glycoprotein (MDR1) is best characterized as a transporter that:","choices":["Passively moves lipophilic drugs down a gradient","Governs Fick's-law diffusion in the gut","Only functions in renal tubular reabsorption","Actively effluxes substrates and can be inhibited by grapefruit juice"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. MDR1/P-gp is a special efflux carrier in brain, testes, and GI tract; inhibiting it (e.g., grapefruit juice with statins) alters absorption of other drugs.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 21"},{"q":"Volume of distribution (Vd) is best defined as:","choices":["The literal fluid volume of the vascular compartment","The apparent volume needed to account for the measured plasma concentration","The volume of drug metabolized per hour","The plasma volume cleared of drug per minute"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vd is the apparent volume a drug would occupy to produce the measured serum concentration; it reflects tissue distribution.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 27"},{"q":"A 50 mg dose of a lipophilic drug yields a plasma concentration of 0.5 mg/L. What is its Vd?","choices":["5 L","100 L","25 L","250 L"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vd = D/C = 50 mg ÷ 0.5 mg/L = 100 L, consistent with extensive tissue distribution of a lipophilic drug.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 29"},{"q":"Which change would be expected to DECREASE a drug's volume of distribution?","choices":["Extensive plasma protein binding","Renal failure with fluid retention","Liver failure altering body fluid","High lipophilicity"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. High affinity for plasma proteins keeps more drug in plasma, reducing apparent Vd.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 32"},{"q":"The primary purpose of drug metabolism (biotransformation) is to:","choices":["Increase the drug's lipid solubility for storage","Always convert the drug into a more active form","Make the drug more polar so it can be renally excreted","Bind the drug to plasma proteins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metabolism generally makes substances more polar so they can be filtered by the glomerulus and excreted.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 34"},{"q":"Codeine converted to morphine is an example of:","choices":["A first-pass inactivation","A prodrug requiring metabolism for activity","A phase II conjugation product","Zero-order elimination"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Codeine is a prodrug metabolized to active morphine, like enalapril→enalaprilat.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 35"},{"q":"Which is a defining feature of a phase I metabolic reaction?","choices":["Conjugation via glucuronidation","Sulfation to increase solubility","Direct renal filtration of the parent drug","Introducing or uncovering a polar functional group"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Phase I (oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis) introduces or uncovers polar groups that provide sites for phase II.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 37"},{"q":"In the cytochrome P450 designation CYP2D6, the '2' refers to the:","choices":["Individual enzyme with a unique sequence","Subfamily (>55% homology)","Number of substrates it metabolizes","Family (>40% homology)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The first numeral denotes the family, defined by >40% amino acid homology.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 46"},{"q":"The first-pass effect refers to:","choices":["Rapid renal clearance on the first filtration","Saturation of plasma protein binding sites","Reduction of drug concentration by hepatic metabolism before reaching systemic circulation","The initial distribution phase after IV injection"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Drug absorbed from the intestine passes via the portal system to the liver, where metabolism reduces the amount reaching systemic circulation.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 43"},{"q":"Weak acids are excreted faster in alkaline urine because:","choices":["A greater fraction becomes charged, reducing tubular reabsorption","Alkaline pH keeps them uncharged and reabsorbed","Alkaline urine increases their lipid solubility","Alkalinization inhibits glomerular filtration"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. In alkaline urine a higher proportion of a weak acid is ionized/charged, so it is not reabsorbed and is excreted faster (basis for bicarbonate in aspirin overdose).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 56"},{"q":"Total body clearance is best represented by which relationship?","choices":["ClTotal = ClRenal + ClLiver + ClBiliary + ClOther","ClTotal = Vd × Ke only","ClTotal = Dose / half-life","ClTotal = C1 − C2 across the membrane"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Total clearance is the additive sum of clearance by each eliminating route.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 58"},{"q":"Renal clearance is clinically estimated using creatinine clearance because creatinine is:","choices":["Actively secreted and heavily reabsorbed","Produced at a constant rate by muscle and cleared by excretion","Bound extensively to plasma proteins","Metabolized primarily by CYP3A4"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Creatinine is a muscle-metabolism product generated at a constant rate and cleared by excretion, making it a useful marker of renal function.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 59"},{"q":"A drug eliminated by first-order kinetics has:","choices":["A constant amount removed per unit time","A constant percentage removed per unit time","Elimination independent of concentration","A fixed 20 mg/dL/hr elimination like ethanol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. First-order elimination removes a constant fraction/percentage per unit time and is proportional to concentration; most drugs follow this.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 63"},{"q":"Ethanol metabolism at roughly 20 mg/dL/hr regardless of blood level illustrates:","choices":["First-order kinetics","Flip-flop kinetics","Zero-order (capacity-limited) kinetics","Concentration-dependent clearance"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. A constant amount eliminated per time, independent of concentration, defines zero-order/capacity-limited kinetics — ethanol is the classic example.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 63"},{"q":"The elimination rate constant Ke is related to clearance and volume of distribution by:","choices":["Ke = Cl / Vd","Ke = Vd / Cl","Ke = Cl × Vd","Ke = 0.693 × Cl"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Ke = Cl/Vd; it is the fraction of drug eliminated per unit time.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 68"},{"q":"If a drug's plasma level falls from 20 mcg/mL to 10 mcg/mL over 4 hours, its half-life is:","choices":["2 hours","10 hours","8 hours","4 hours"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The concentration halved (20→10) over exactly 4 hours, so t½ = 4 hours.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 69"},{"q":"Given t½ = (0.693 × Vd)/Cl, a LARGER volume of distribution will:","choices":["Prolong the half-life","Shorten the half-life","Have no effect on half-life","Increase clearance proportionally"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A larger Vd increases the numerator, prolonging half-life.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 72-73"},{"q":"Steady state is defined as the point at which:","choices":["The rate of drug administration equals the rate of elimination","Plasma concentration first becomes measurable","The loading dose has been fully absorbed","Clearance falls to zero"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. At steady state, input rate equals elimination rate, so average plasma level plateaus.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 74"},{"q":"Approximately how many half-lives are required to reach steady state?","choices":["1-2 half-lives","It depends only on the loading dose","8-10 half-lives","4-5 half-lives"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Roughly 4-5 half-lives are needed to approach steady state.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 75"},{"q":"A loading dose is used primarily to:","choices":["Slow the approach to steady state","Rapidly achieve a desired (target) plasma concentration","Reduce total clearance","Prevent first-pass metabolism"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Loading dose = Vd × target concentration; it promptly raises plasma level to the desired steady-state target.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 80"},{"q":"Using Css = Dose/(Cl × dosing interval), increasing the dosing interval while holding dose constant will:","choices":["Decrease average steady-state concentration","Increase average steady-state concentration","Leave Css unchanged","Increase clearance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A larger dosing interval in the denominator decreases average steady-state concentration.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 75, 81"},{"q":"For a drug with 25% oral bioavailability, how much of a 160 mg dose reaches systemic circulation?","choices":["Approximately 4 mg","Approximately 40 mg","Approximately 120 mg","Approximately 160 mg"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. 160 mg × 0.25 = 40 mg reaches systemic circulation (propranolol example).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 88-89"},{"q":"Which fraction of a protein-bound drug is pharmacologically active?","choices":["The unbound (free) fraction","The bound fraction","Both equally","Only the metabolized fraction"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Only the unbound (free) fraction is pharmacologically active and available to act at the site of effect.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 90"},{"q":"Major classes of antimicrobials include cell wall inhibitors, protein synthesis inhibitors, and:","choices":["Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors","Beta-adrenergic blockers","Proton pump inhibitors","Inhibitors of nucleic acid function or synthesis"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. The nucleic acid inhibitor class (fluoroquinolones, metronidazole) is a major antimicrobial category alongside cell wall and protein synthesis inhibitors.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 27, 57"},{"q":"Beta-lactam antibiotics exert their bactericidal effect by:","choices":["Binding the 30S ribosomal subunit","Inhibiting DNA gyrase","Inactivating penicillin-binding proteins to block cell wall synthesis","Blocking folate synthesis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Beta-lactams inactivate PBPs, the enzymes that complete cell wall cross-linking.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 33"},{"q":"A concentration-dependent antibiotic with a prolonged post-antibiotic effect is best exemplified by:","choices":["Penicillin V","Vancomycin","A natural cephalosporin","A fluoroquinolone such as ciprofloxacin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones show concentration-dependent killing with a prolonged post-antibiotic effect.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 24, 59"},{"q":"The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) is determined by antibiotic sensitivity testing such as the:","choices":["Gram stain","Coagulase test","E-test","Antibiogram color chart"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. The E-test is used to determine the MIC of an antibiotic against an organism.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 13"}]},"pharm-master-v2":{"title":"Pharmacodynamics Master Exam (v2)","questions":[{"q":"Pharmacokinetics is best defined as:","choices":["The effect of the drug on the body","The effect of the body on the drug (ADME)","The study of drug-receptor binding affinity","The measurement of therapeutic index"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Pharmacokinetics is what the body does to the drug — absorption, distribution, metabolism, elimination (ADME).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 4"},{"q":"Carrier-mediated (special carrier) transport differs from passive diffusion in that it:","choices":["Always follows the concentration gradient","Is governed by Fick's law","Can be saturated and may move drug against a gradient","Requires no cellular energy"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Special carriers are capacity-limited (saturable), can move against a gradient, and require energy.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 8, 20"},{"q":"When the pH of a solution equals a drug's pKa, the drug is:","choices":["50% protonated and 50% unprotonated","Fully un-ionized","Fully ionized","Precipitated out of solution"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. At pH = pKa, the molecule is 50% protonated and 50% unprotonated by definition.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 14"},{"q":"A weak base in an acidic environment will predominantly be:","choices":["Protonated, charged, and lipid-insoluble","Unprotonated, uncharged, and lipid-soluble","Neutral and freely diffusible","Converted to a weak acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A weak base in acid gains a proton to become BH+ — charged and lipid-insoluble (e.g., protonated morphine is less lipid-soluble).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 18"},{"q":"Endocytosis is the appropriate absorption mechanism for a substance that is:","choices":["Small and lipophilic","Too large, lipid-insoluble, or impermeant","A weak acid at low pH","A gas exchanged in the lung"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Endocytosis engulfs substances too large, lipid-insoluble, or impermeant (e.g., B12 with intrinsic factor, iron with transferrin).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 23"},{"q":"A 70 kg man is given 100 mg of a drug with Vd = 0.6 L/kg IV. What is his estimated plasma concentration?","choices":["Approximately 2.4 mg/L","Approximately 1.4 mg/L","Approximately 0.6 mg/L","Approximately 6.0 mg/L"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vd = 70 × 0.6 = 42 L; C0 = 100 mg ÷ 42 L ≈ 2.38 mg/L.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 31"},{"q":"A drug with a very HIGH volume of distribution is most likely:","choices":["Hydrophilic and confined to plasma","Lipophilic and distributed widely into tissue","Highly protein-bound in the vasculature","Restricted by dehydration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. A high Vd usually indicates a lipophilic drug distributed extensively into tissues.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 28-29"},{"q":"Which enzyme is a principal PHASE I metabolizing enzyme?","choices":["UDP-glucuronosyltransferase","Sulfotransferase","Glutathione-S-transferase","Cytochrome P450"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cytochrome P450 is a principal phase I enzyme (along with monoamine oxidase, esterases, etc.).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 38"},{"q":"Phase II metabolic reactions primarily:","choices":["Uncover polar groups by oxidation","Reduce nitro groups","Hydrolyze ester bonds","Add or alter a molecule to increase water solubility via conjugation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Phase II adds/alters a moiety (glucuronidation, sulfation) to increase water solubility for excretion.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 39"},{"q":"Grapefruit juice is described in the lecture as an agent that:","choices":["Inhibits drug metabolism","Induces hepatic metabolism","Increases renal filtration","Enhances first-pass clearance"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Grapefruit juice is listed as an inhibitor of drug metabolism (contrast with charcoal-broiled foods, which induce).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 52"},{"q":"Which condition would MOST impair hepatic drug-metabolizing capacity?","choices":["Diabetic nephropathy","Acute renal failure","Renal artery stenosis","Alcoholic cirrhosis"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Alcoholic cirrhosis (a liver disease) impairs hepatic drug-metabolizing enzymes.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 50-51"},{"q":"In aspirin (a weak acid) overdose, alkalinizing the urine with sodium bicarbonate enhances elimination by:","choices":["Increasing tubular reabsorption of aspirin","Ion trapping — keeping aspirin charged so it is not reabsorbed","Inhibiting hepatic metabolism of aspirin","Reducing glomerular filtration of the drug"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Raising urine pH increases the charged fraction of the weak acid, trapping it in the tubule (ion trapping) and preventing reabsorption.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 57"},{"q":"For a first-order drug, the fraction eliminated per unit time is:","choices":["Constant regardless of concentration","A constant percentage, proportional to concentration","Fixed in absolute amount per hour","Zero until a threshold is reached"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. First-order elimination removes a constant percentage (e.g., 15%/hr), so the absolute amount tracks concentration.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 63, 66"},{"q":"The half-life equation t½ = (0.693 × Vd)/Cl predicts that decreasing clearance will:","choices":["Prolong the half-life","Shorten the half-life","Not change the half-life","Reduce the volume of distribution"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. A smaller Cl increases half-life because clearance is in the denominator.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 72-73"},{"q":"The maintenance dose can be calculated by rearranging Css = Dose/(Cl × interval) to:","choices":["Dose = Cl / (Css × interval)","Dose = Css / (Cl × interval)","Dose = Css × Cl × dosing interval","Dose = Css × Vd × Ke"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Rearranging gives Dose = Css × Cl × dosing interval.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 81"},{"q":"Highly lipid-soluble drugs filtered at the glomerulus tend to be:","choices":["Rapidly reabsorbed back into the circulation","Rapidly and completely excreted","Trapped as charged species in the tubule","Actively secreted without reabsorption"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Lipid-soluble drugs are freely filtered but rapidly reabsorbed; charged molecules are not readily reabsorbed.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 55"},{"q":"Compared with a bactericidal agent, a bacteriostatic antibiotic:","choices":["Directly causes bacterial cell death","Has no post-antibiotic effect by definition","Always requires lower doses","Inhibits a vital growth pathway without directly killing the organism"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Bacteriostatic agents (e.g., tetracyclines, sulfonamides) inhibit a vital growth pathway but do not directly kill.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 23"},{"q":"Which antibiotic is BACTERICIDAL?","choices":["Erythromycin","Vancomycin","Tetracycline","Trimethoprim"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is bactericidal (along with penicillins, cephalosporins, aminoglycosides, fluoroquinolones, metronidazole).","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 23"},{"q":"For a time-dependent antibiotic, the pharmacodynamic parameter that best predicts efficacy is:","choices":["Peak concentration well above the MIC","The post-antibiotic effect duration","A single high concentration-dependent spike","The time that drug concentration remains above the MIC (40-70% of the interval)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Time-dependent killing is optimized when concentration stays above MIC for 40-70% of the dosing interval; continuous/frequent infusions are best.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 24"},{"q":"As one advances from 1st to higher cephalosporin generations, the general trend is:","choices":["Increasing gram-negative activity with decreasing gram-positive activity","Increasing gram-positive and decreasing gram-negative activity","Loss of all bactericidal activity","Conversion to bacteriostatic mechanism"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Advancing generations gain gram-negative coverage while losing some gram-positive activity (4th gen recovers gram-positive without sacrificing gram-negative).","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 39-40"},{"q":"Vancomycin's mechanism of action is best described as:","choices":["A glycopeptide that blocks cell wall cross-linking","A beta-lactam that inactivates PBPs","A 30S ribosomal inhibitor","A DNA gyrase inhibitor"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is a glycopeptide that targets the cell wall by blocking cross-linking, making resistance more difficult to develop.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 43"},{"q":"Oral vancomycin is specifically indicated for:","choices":["MRSA bacteremia","Gram-negative UTIs","Community-acquired pneumonia","Severe C. difficile colitis (not systemically absorbed)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Oral vancomycin is limited to severe antibiotic-associated C. difficile colitis because it is not orally absorbed and acts locally in the gut.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 44"},{"q":"Tetracyclines inhibit bacterial protein synthesis by:","choices":["Binding the 50S subunit to block translocation","Inactivating penicillin-binding proteins","Binding the 30S subunit and preventing tRNA attachment","Inhibiting DNA-dependent RNA polymerase"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines bind the 30S subunit and prevent tRNA from binding the mRNA-ribosome complex.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 48-49"},{"q":"The most common mechanism of tetracycline resistance is:","choices":["Beta-lactamase production","An efflux pump that expels the drug","Altered penicillin-binding proteins","Ribosomal methylation of the 50S subunit"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Tetracycline resistance occurs primarily via an efflux pump that expels drug from the cell.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 49"},{"q":"Macrolides and clindamycin share which target?","choices":["The 30S ribosomal subunit","The bacterial cell wall","Bacterial DNA gyrase","The 50S ribosomal subunit (blocking translocation)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Macrolides and clindamycin inhibit translocation by binding the 50S subunit.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 52"},{"q":"Fluoroquinolones such as levofloxacin exert bactericidal activity by:","choices":["Blocking cell wall cross-linking","Binding the 50S ribosomal subunit","Inhibiting DNA gyrase and topoisomerase","Disrupting folate synthesis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones inhibit DNA gyrase and topoisomerase, halting DNA replication and transcription.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 59"},{"q":"Which fluoroquinolone is preferred for community-acquired pneumonia?","choices":["Ciprofloxacin","Levofloxacin","Nalidixic acid","Moxifloxacin for UTI"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Levofloxacin (with improved gram-positive and Pseudomonas coverage) is used for CAP; ciprofloxacin is not.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 60-61"},{"q":"Metronidazole's spectrum centers on:","choices":["Gram-positive aerobes only","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Anaerobes (gram-positive and gram-negative) and parasites","Atypical respiratory pathogens"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole covers gram-positive and gram-negative anaerobes plus parasites, with indications like C. difficile and BV/trichomoniasis.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 63-64"},{"q":"A disulfiram-like reaction with ethanol is a characteristic adverse effect of:","choices":["Cephalexin","Doxycycline","Metronidazole","Azithromycin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole causes a disulfiram-like reaction (flushing, nausea, vomiting, diaphoresis) with ethanol.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 65"},{"q":"Which is a recognized general adverse effect of antibiotic use?","choices":["Universal QT prolongation across all classes","Permanent loss of renal filtration","Disruption of normal flora with C. difficile overgrowth","Irreversible ribosomal damage in humans"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Disruption of normal flora leading to C. diff overgrowth, GI disturbance, and yeast infections is a general adverse effect.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 66"}]},"pharm-master-v3":{"title":"Pharmacodynamics Master Exam (v3)","questions":[{"q":"Which sequence correctly lists the ADME processes of pharmacokinetics?","choices":["Absorption, Diffusion, Metabolism, Equilibrium","Activation, Delivery, Metabolism, Excretion","Adsorption, Diffusion, Modification, Elimination","Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Elimination"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. ADME = Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Elimination — the body's actions on the drug.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 4"},{"q":"Permeation by passive diffusion is fundamentally driven by:","choices":["ATP hydrolysis","The concentration gradient from high to low","A specific membrane carrier","Vesicle formation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Passive diffusion is driven by the concentration gradient, moving drug from high to low concentration.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 7"},{"q":"In Fick's law, a LARGER concentration gradient (C1 − C2) results in:","choices":["Faster diffusion/absorption","Slower diffusion","No change in flux","Reversal of diffusion direction"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Flux is proportional to the concentration gradient, so a larger gradient means faster diffusion/absorption.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 10-11"},{"q":"The protonated (uncharged) form of aspirin, a weak acid, is described as:","choices":["More lipid-soluble","More water-soluble","Unable to cross any membrane","Charged at low pH"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. In acid, the protonated form of aspirin is uncharged and more lipid-soluble.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 18"},{"q":"The MRP1-MRP5 transporters play an important role in:","choices":["Passive lipid diffusion of steroids","Excretion of drugs/metabolites into urine and bile","Fick's-law diffusion across capillaries","Formation of intrinsic factor"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. MRP transporters help excrete drugs and metabolites into urine and bile and take up neurotransmitters at nerve endings.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 22"},{"q":"A drug with a Vd of 5 L (given 50 mg, plasma concentration 10 mg/L) is best characterized as:","choices":["Hydrophilic, remaining largely in central circulation","Lipophilic, distributed widely into tissue","Highly bound to peripheral tissue","Eliminated by zero-order kinetics"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vd = 50/10 = 5 L, a small volume indicating the hydrophilic drug stays mainly in central circulation.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 29"},{"q":"Which factor tends to INCREASE the volume of distribution?","choices":["Renal failure with fluid retention","Dehydration","Extensive plasma protein binding","Confinement to the vascular space"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Renal failure with fluid retention increases Vd (as does liver failure altering body fluid).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 32"},{"q":"Metabolic reactions are described as normally being:","choices":["Activating reactions that increase potency","Processes confined entirely to the kidney","Reactions that decrease water solubility","Deactivating, detoxifying reactions yielding less active products"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Metabolism is usually deactivating and detoxifying, producing less pharmacologically active products.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 34"},{"q":"An ACE inhibitor such as enalapril, which becomes enalaprilat, is an example of:","choices":["A zero-order drug","A prodrug","A phase II conjugate","A drug with no first-pass effect"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Enalapril is an inactive prodrug converted by metabolism to active enalaprilat.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 35"},{"q":"Besides the liver, drug metabolism can also occur in the:","choices":["Bone marrow and spleen","Central nervous system exclusively","Lungs, GI tract, skin, and kidney","Adipose tissue only"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Although primarily hepatic, metabolism also occurs in the lungs, GI tract, skin, and kidney.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 36"},{"q":"CYP450 isoenzymes are classified into families and subfamilies according to:","choices":["Their substrate specificity","The organ in which they are found","Amino acid sequence homology","Their molecular weight"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. P450 enzymes are grouped into families (>40% homology) and subfamilies (>55% homology) by amino acid sequence.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 45-46"},{"q":"Charcoal-broiled foods are described in the lecture as agents that:","choices":["Inhibit hepatic metabolism","Increase protein binding","Block renal excretion","Induce hepatic metabolism"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Charcoal-broiled foods are listed as inducers of metabolism (grapefruit juice is the inhibitor).","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 52"},{"q":"Which combination of routes contributes to total body clearance?","choices":["Only renal clearance","Only hepatic clearance","Renal, hepatic, biliary, and other routes summed","Clearance equals filtration minus reabsorption only"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. ClTotal = ClRenal + ClLiver + ClBiliary + ClOther.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 58"},{"q":"In first-order elimination, if 1000 units are present and 15% is eliminated in hour 1, the fraction eliminated in hour 2 is:","choices":["Approximately 30%","Still approximately 15%","Approximately 7.5%","0% until the next dose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. First-order elimination removes a constant percentage (~15%) each hour, though the absolute amount declines.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 66"},{"q":"Half-life can be calculated from the elimination constant Ke using:","choices":["t½ = Ke / 0.693","t½ = 0.693 / Ke","t½ = 0.693 × Ke","t½ = Ke × Vd"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. t½ = 0.693/Ke.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 72"},{"q":"A drug falls from 40 mcg/mL at 8 AM to 10 mcg/mL at 4 PM (8 hours). Its half-life is:","choices":["2 hours","6 hours","4 hours","8 hours"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. 40→20→10 is two halvings over 8 hours, so each half-life is 4 hours.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 69"},{"q":"At steady state, clearance functions as the proportionality constant that makes:","choices":["Vd equal to the plasma concentration","The loading dose equal to the maintenance dose","Half-life independent of Vd","Average steady-state plasma level equal to the rate of drug administration"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Clearance is the constant relating the average steady-state plasma level to the rate of drug administration.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 74"},{"q":"A loading dose is calculated as:","choices":["Cl × dosing interval","Vd × target concentration","Dose / half-life","Ke × Vd"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Loading dose = Vd × target (total) concentration to promptly reach the desired level.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 80"},{"q":"A drug with 90% plasma protein binding and 40 mg in circulation has how much active (unbound) drug?","choices":["36 mg","20 mg","4 mg","0.4 mg"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. 40 mg × 10% unbound = 4 mg is the pharmacologically active fraction.","cite":"PK I & II, Slide 90"},{"q":"Coagulase-positive staphylococcus, which may be MSSA or MRSA, is:","choices":["Staphylococcus aureus","Staphylococcus epidermidis","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Enterococcus faecalis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. S. aureus is the coagulase-positive staph that may be methicillin-sensitive (MSSA) or -resistant (MRSA).","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 5"},{"q":"A drug that inactivates penicillin-binding proteins to interfere with the final step of cell wall synthesis is a:","choices":["Beta-lactam","Protein synthesis inhibitor","Fluoroquinolone","Sulfonamide"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Beta-lactams inactivate PBPs, blocking the last step of cell wall synthesis.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 33"},{"q":"Which is a recognized mechanism of beta-lactam resistance?","choices":["Efflux pump specific to tetracyclines","Ribosomal methylation of the 50S subunit","Beta-lactamase enzymatic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring","Inhibition of DNA gyrase"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Beta-lactamases cleave the beta-lactam ring; other mechanisms include decreased permeability and altered PBPs.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 34"},{"q":"Adding a beta-lactamase inhibitor (e.g., clavulanic acid to amoxicillin) primarily:","choices":["Broadens coverage by protecting the beta-lactam from enzymatic degradation","Converts the drug to a bacteriostatic agent","Changes the target from PBPs to ribosomes","Provides gram-negative-only coverage"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The inhibitor protects the beta-lactam, adding anaerobe (bacteroides) and MSSA coverage for infections like diabetic foot ulcers and bites.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 42"},{"q":"Which class binds the 30S ribosomal subunit?","choices":["Macrolides","Aminoglycosides and tetracyclines","Clindamycin","Chloramphenicol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Aminoglycosides and tetracyclines bind the 30S subunit; macrolides, clindamycin, and chloramphenicol bind 50S.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 48"},{"q":"Vancomycin's antibacterial spectrum is best described as:","choices":["Gram-negative coverage only","Atypical pathogens only","Broad gram-positive and gram-negative coverage","Gram-positive coverage only"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin provides gram-positive coverage only, used for MRSA and (oral) C. difficile.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 44"},{"q":"Azithromycin is the preferred therapy among macrolides for:","choices":["C. difficile colitis","MRSA bacteremia","Pseudomonas pneumonia","Urethritis due to chlamydia"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Azithromycin is preferred for chlamydial urethritis and is more active against respiratory H. influenzae and M. catarrhalis.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 54"},{"q":"Clindamycin's coverage notably EXCLUDES:","choices":["Gram-positive aerobes","Gram-positive anaerobes","Gram-negative aerobes","Gram-negative anaerobes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Clindamycin has NO gram-negative aerobic coverage.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 55"},{"q":"Empiric antimicrobial therapy is best described as:","choices":["Therapy given to prevent an infection before it occurs","Therapy started before culture results, based on likely pathogens","Therapy targeting a confirmed organism from sensitivities","Therapy given only to non-infected surgical patients"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Empiric therapy is begun before definitive culture/sensitivity data, targeting the most likely organisms for the site.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 2 (obj f), 22"},{"q":"Which practice is most likely to MINIMIZE the emergence of antimicrobial resistance?","choices":["Routinely double-covering with broad-spectrum agents","Using broad-spectrum prophylaxis liberally","Prolonging therapy well beyond guideline durations","De-escalating and streamlining therapy based on cultures"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. De-escalating/streamlining therapy (guided by cultures) reduces selective pressure and minimizes resistance.","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 17"},{"q":"The post-antibiotic effect (PAE) is clinically significant because it:","choices":["Allows continued suppression of bacterial growth even after drug levels fall below the MIC","Requires continuous infusion to maintain killing","Only occurs with time-dependent agents lacking PAE","Eliminates the need to consider the MIC"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. PAE allows persistent growth suppression after concentrations drop below the MIC, permitting less frequent dosing (e.g., fluoroquinolones, aminoglycosides).","cite":"Antimicrobials, Slide 24, 59"}]},"antimicrobials-1":{"title":"Antimicrobials Quiz 1","questions":[{"q":"To which class does aztreonam belong?","choices":["Extended-spectrum penicillin","Carbapenem","Glycopeptide","Monobactam"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Aztreonam is the monobactam beta-lactam.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Beta-lactam antibiotics kill bacteria by:","choices":["Binding the 30S ribosomal subunit","Inhibiting DNA gyrase and topoisomerase","Inactivating penicillin-binding proteins to block the last step of cell wall synthesis","Blocking cell wall cross-linking as a glycopeptide"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Beta-lactams inactivate PBPs, the enzymes completing cell wall synthesis.","cite":"Slide 33"},{"q":"Vancomycin is:","choices":["Bacteriostatic","Only bacteriostatic when given orally","Bactericidal","Neither, it merely inhibits adhesion"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is bactericidal with time-dependent killing and moderate PAE.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Which agent is used for Rocky Mountain spotted fever and Lyme disease?","choices":["Azithromycin","Cephalexin","Doxycycline","Metronidazole"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Doxycycline (a tetracycline) is indicated for RMSF and Lyme disease.","cite":"Slide 50"},{"q":"The disulfiram-like reaction with ethanol (flushing, nausea, vomiting, diaphoresis) is characteristic of:","choices":["Metronidazole","Doxycycline","Cephalexin","Levofloxacin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole causes a disulfiram-like reaction with alcohol.","cite":"Slide 65"},{"q":"Which class binds the 30S ribosomal subunit?","choices":["Macrolides and clindamycin","Beta-lactams","Fluoroquinolones","Aminoglycosides and tetracyclines"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Aminoglycosides and tetracyclines bind the 30S subunit.","cite":"Slide 48"},{"q":"Vancomycin's antibacterial spectrum is:","choices":["Gram-negative only","Gram-positive only","Broad gram-positive and gram-negative","Anaerobes only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin covers gram-positives only.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Which fluoroquinolone is preferred for community-acquired pneumonia?","choices":["Ciprofloxacin","Nalidixic acid","Levofloxacin","Trovafloxacin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Levofloxacin, with improved gram-positive and Pseudomonas coverage, is used for CAP.","cite":"Slide 60-61"},{"q":"'Red man syndrome' (flushing from rapid infusion) is a distinctive adverse effect of:","choices":["Vancomycin","Amoxicillin","Doxycycline","Metronidazole"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Rapid vancomycin infusion causes red man syndrome/flushing.","cite":"Slide 45"},{"q":"Natural penicillin (penicillin V) is:","choices":["Bacteriostatic with no PAE","Bactericidal with time-dependent killing and no PAE","Bactericidal with concentration-dependent killing","Bacteriostatic with prolonged PAE"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Penicillin V is bactericidal, time-dependent, with no PAE.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"Which agent is a glycopeptide rather than a beta-lactam?","choices":["Vancomycin","Aztreonam","Cefepime","Piperacillin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is a glycopeptide, not a beta-lactam.","cite":"Slide 43"},{"q":"Metronidazole is:","choices":["Bactericidal","Bacteriostatic","Bacteriostatic against anaerobes only","Neither; it only inhibits toxin production"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole is bactericidal with concentration-dependent killing and prolonged PAE.","cite":"Slide 63"},{"q":"Tetracyclines inhibit protein synthesis by:","choices":["Binding the 50S subunit to block translocation","Inhibiting DNA gyrase","Binding the 30S subunit and preventing tRNA from binding the mRNA-ribosome complex","Inactivating PBPs"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines bind 30S and block tRNA attachment to the mRNA-ribosome complex.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"Oral vancomycin has a specific indication for:","choices":["MRSA bacteremia","Gram-negative UTIs","Community-acquired pneumonia","Severe C. difficile colitis (not orally absorbed)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Oral vancomycin is limited to severe C. difficile colitis because it acts locally in the gut.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Which class exerts concentration-dependent killing with a prolonged post-antibiotic effect?","choices":["Fluoroquinolones","Cephalosporins","Natural penicillins","Extended-spectrum penicillins"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones show concentration-dependent killing with a prolonged PAE.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"Metronidazole's spectrum centers on:","choices":["Gram-positive aerobes","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Anaerobes (gram-positive and gram-negative) and parasites","Atypical respiratory pathogens"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole covers gram-positive and gram-negative anaerobes plus parasites.","cite":"Slide 64"},{"q":"Clindamycin's coverage notably EXCLUDES:","choices":["Gram-positive aerobes","Gram-negative aerobes","Gram-negative anaerobes","Gram-positive anaerobes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Clindamycin has NO gram-negative aerobic coverage.","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Which cephalosporin generation offers maximal gram-negative activity without sacrificing gram-positive activity?","choices":["1st generation","2nd generation","3rd generation","4th generation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. 4th generation (cefepime) has maximal gram-negative and gram-positive activity.","cite":"Slide 39-40"},{"q":"Adding clavulanic acid to amoxicillin (Augmentin) primarily:","choices":["Protects the beta-lactam and adds anaerobe (bacteroides) and MSSA coverage","Changes the target to the ribosome","Converts it to a bacteriostatic drug","Restricts it to gram-negative organisms"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. The inhibitor protects the beta-lactam and adds anaerobe/MSSA coverage for skin, diabetic foot, bites, and intra-abdominal infections.","cite":"Slide 42"},{"q":"Which is the preferred macrolide therapy for urethritis due to chlamydia?","choices":["Erythromycin","Azithromycin","Clarithromycin","Clindamycin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Azithromycin is the preferred therapy for chlamydial urethritis.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"Tetracyclines are best classified as:","choices":["Bactericidal, concentration-dependent","Bacteriostatic, time-dependent with moderate PAE","Bactericidal, time-dependent with no PAE","Bacteriostatic with no PAE"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines are bacteriostatic, time-dependent, with moderate PAE and broad-spectrum coverage.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"A distinctive adverse effect of tetracyclines (e.g., doxycycline) is:","choices":["Tendon rupture","Tooth discoloration/deposition in bone and photosensitivity","Red man syndrome","Disulfiram-like reaction with alcohol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines deposit in bone/teeth (discoloration; avoid in children) and cause photosensitivity.","cite":"Slide 51"},{"q":"Which class inhibits bacterial DNA gyrase and topoisomerase?","choices":["Aminoglycosides","Macrolides","Cephalosporins","Fluoroquinolones"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones inhibit DNA gyrase and topoisomerase, halting DNA replication and transcription.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"Tendinitis and tendon rupture are distinctive adverse effects of:","choices":["Cephalosporins","Fluoroquinolones","Macrolides","Penicillins"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones carry a distinctive risk of tendinitis/tendon rupture (and cartilage concerns in children).","cite":"Slide 62"},{"q":"Which penicillin class covers Pseudomonas?","choices":["Anti-pseudomonal penicillins (piperacillin, ticarcillin)","Anti-staphylococcal penicillins","Natural penicillins","Extended-spectrum penicillins"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Anti-pseudomonal penicillins piperacillin and ticarcillin cover Pseudomonas.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Amoxicillin (an extended-spectrum penicillin) is specifically used prophylactically for:","choices":["Rocky Mountain spotted fever","Prevention of bacterial endocarditis in high-risk patients","C. difficile colitis","Trichomoniasis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Amoxicillin is used as prophylaxis to prevent bacterial endocarditis in high-risk patients.","cite":"Slide 36"},{"q":"Macrolides and clindamycin inhibit protein synthesis by targeting the:","choices":["30S subunit","Cell wall PBPs","DNA gyrase","50S subunit (blocking translocation)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Macrolides and clindamycin bind the 50S subunit and inhibit translocation.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Clindamycin is distinctively associated with which adverse effect?","choices":["Tendon rupture","Red man syndrome","C. difficile / pseudomembranous colitis","Tooth discoloration"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Clindamycin is strongly associated with C. difficile/pseudomembranous colitis.","cite":"Slide 56"},{"q":"Ciprofloxacin's spectrum is best described as:","choices":["Gram-positive only","Atypicals only","Anaerobes and parasites","Gram-negative and atypical coverage, with +/- Pseudomonas"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Ciprofloxacin provides gram-negative and atypical coverage with variable Pseudomonas activity.","cite":"Slide 61"},{"q":"Which agent is indicated for MRSA and is bactericidal against gram-positives?","choices":["Vancomycin","Aztreonam","Cephalexin","Nalidixic acid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is bactericidal against gram-positives and indicated for MRSA.","cite":"Slide 44"}]},"antimicrobials-2":{"title":"Antimicrobials Quiz 2","questions":[{"q":"Imipenem, meropenem, and ertapenem belong to which beta-lactam class?","choices":["Anti-staphylococcal penicillins","Monobactams","Cephalosporins","Carbapenems"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. These are the carbapenems.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Which agent is bactericidal AND exhibits concentration-dependent killing?","choices":["Tetracycline","Erythromycin","Levofloxacin","Clarithromycin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones like levofloxacin are bactericidal with concentration-dependent killing.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"The natural penicillin spectrum notably includes which spirochete?","choices":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Treponema pallidum (syphilis)","Bacteroides fragilis","Mycoplasma pneumoniae"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Penicillin V covers Treponema pallidum (syphilis).","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"Photosensitivity plus deposition in developing teeth and bone are hallmark adverse effects of:","choices":["Fluoroquinolones","Vancomycin","Tetracyclines","Cephalosporins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines cause photosensitivity and deposit in teeth/bone (avoid in children/pregnancy).","cite":"Slide 51"},{"q":"Which class targets the bacterial cell wall but is NOT a beta-lactam?","choices":["Macrolides","Tetracyclines","Fluoroquinolones","Glycopeptides (vancomycin)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is a glycopeptide that targets the cell wall without being a beta-lactam.","cite":"Slide 43"},{"q":"Clindamycin is described as:","choices":["Bacteriostatic","Bactericidal","Bacteriostatic only at high dose","Neither cidal nor static"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Clindamycin is bactericidal (macrolides are bacteriostatic, may be cidal at high doses).","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Which cephalosporin generation has the MOST gram-positive and LEAST gram-negative coverage?","choices":["1st generation (cephalexin)","3rd generation (cefdinir)","4th generation (cefepime)","5th generation (ceftaroline)"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. 1st generation (cephalexin) has the most gram-positive, least gram-negative coverage.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"Which agent is preferred for Clostridium difficile when given orally, alongside oral vancomycin?","choices":["Metronidazole","Ciprofloxacin","Amoxicillin","Doxycycline"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Oral metronidazole is indicated for C. difficile.","cite":"Slide 64"},{"q":"The mechanism of vancomycin is to:","choices":["Inactivate penicillin-binding proteins","Block cell wall cross-linking (glycopeptide)","Bind the 50S ribosomal subunit","Inhibit DNA gyrase"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin blocks cell wall cross-linking as a glycopeptide.","cite":"Slide 43"},{"q":"Which fluoroquinolone is specifically noted as NOT appropriate for UTI due to resistance concerns?","choices":["Ciprofloxacin","Levofloxacin","Moxifloxacin","Ofloxacin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Moxifloxacin is specifically noted as NOT for UTI.","cite":"Slide 60"},{"q":"Amoxicillin differs from penicillin V primarily by having:","choices":["MRSA coverage","Anaerobic coverage of Bacteroides","Anti-pseudomonal activity","More effective coverage against gram-negative bacilli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Amoxicillin shares penicillin V coverage but is more effective against gram-negative bacilli and widely used in respiratory infections.","cite":"Slide 36"},{"q":"Doxycycline is a recommended therapy for which STI-related or atypical scenario?","choices":["Pseudomonal pneumonia","Atypical pneumonia and STIs","C. difficile colitis","Bacterial vaginosis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Doxycycline is indicated for atypical pneumonia and STIs (as well as acne, RMSF, Lyme).","cite":"Slide 50"},{"q":"Fluoroquinolones are classified as:","choices":["Bactericidal, concentration-dependent, with prolonged PAE","Bacteriostatic, time-dependent","Bactericidal, time-dependent, no PAE","Bacteriostatic with moderate PAE"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones are bactericidal with concentration-dependent killing and a prolonged PAE.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"Which beta-lactam class is represented by dicloxacillin, nafcillin, and oxacillin?","choices":["Penicillins with beta-lactamase inhibitors","Natural penicillins","Anti-pseudomonal penicillins","Anti-staphylococcal penicillins"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. These are the anti-staphylococcal penicillins.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Erythromycin is clinically useful because its coverage is similar to penicillin, making it an option for patients who:","choices":["Have C. difficile","Have renal failure","Are pregnant","Have a penicillin allergy"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Erythromycin's coverage resembles penicillin G/V and may be used in penicillin-allergic patients.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"Nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity are adverse effects associated with:","choices":["Amoxicillin","Vancomycin","Metronidazole","Clindamycin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is associated with nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity in addition to red man syndrome.","cite":"Slide 45"},{"q":"Which class provides broad-spectrum coverage of both gram-positive and gram-negative organisms and is bacteriostatic?","choices":["Tetracyclines","Natural penicillins","Glycopeptides","Monobactams"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines are broad-spectrum (gram-positive and gram-negative) and bacteriostatic.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"Levofloxacin differs from ciprofloxacin by offering:","choices":["Loss of atypical coverage","Anaerobic coverage","Improved gram-positive coverage plus Pseudomonas, useful in CAP","MRSA coverage"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Levofloxacin adds improved gram-positive activity and Pseudomonas coverage, making it useful for CAP.","cite":"Slide 61"},{"q":"Which agent's oral formulation is NOT systemically absorbed, which is why it works locally for gut infection?","choices":["Vancomycin","Levofloxacin","Doxycycline","Cephalexin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Oral vancomycin is not absorbed, acting locally in the gut for C. difficile colitis.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Metronidazole is indicated for which set of infections?","choices":["C. difficile, intra-abdominal, and vaginal infections (BV, trichomoniasis)","Community-acquired pneumonia and sinusitis","MRSA skin infections","Streptococcal pharyngitis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole treats C. difficile, intra-abdominal infections, and vaginal infections including BV and trichomoniasis.","cite":"Slide 64"},{"q":"The 5th-generation cephalosporin listed is:","choices":["Cefepime (Maxipime)","Ceftaroline (Teflaro)","Ceftriaxone (Rocephin)","Cefazolin (Ancef)"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Ceftaroline (Teflaro) is the listed 5th-generation cephalosporin.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"Clindamycin's indications include all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["Gram-negative aerobic UTI","Osteomyelitis","Intra-abdominal infection","Skin/soft tissue infection"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. It has no gram-negative aerobic coverage, so a gram-negative aerobic UTI is not an indication.","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Penicillins with beta-lactamase inhibitors (e.g., Augmentin, Unasyn) are indicated for:","choices":["Atypical pneumonia only","Skin/soft tissue, diabetic foot ulcers, bites, and intra-abdominal infections","Trichomoniasis","MRSA bacteremia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. These combinations are used for skin/soft tissue, diabetic foot ulcers, bites, and intra-abdominal infections.","cite":"Slide 42"},{"q":"Which class is bactericidal and uses time-dependent killing with no post-antibiotic effect?","choices":["Metronidazole","Fluoroquinolones","Tetracyclines","Cephalosporins"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cephalosporins are bactericidal, time-dependent, with no PAE.","cite":"Slide 40"},{"q":"Cefepime is which generation of cephalosporin?","choices":["1st","2nd","3rd","4th"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Cefepime is a 4th-generation cephalosporin.","cite":"Slide 31, 40"},{"q":"Metronidazole's mechanism is to:","choices":["Bind the 30S ribosomal subunit","Inactivate penicillin-binding proteins","Bind bacterial and parasitic proteins and DNA, inhibiting nucleic acid synthesis","Block cell wall cross-linking"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole binds bacterial/parasitic proteins and DNA to inhibit nucleic acid synthesis and also has anti-protozoal/anti-parasitic effect.","cite":"Slide 63"},{"q":"Which agent is used for MRSA and multidrug-resistant organisms among the tetracyclines?","choices":["Aztreonam","Cefazolin","Doxycycline","Penicillin V"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Doxycycline is listed for MRSA and multidrug-resistant organisms.","cite":"Slide 50"},{"q":"A metallic taste and nausea/vomiting with abdominal cramps are adverse effects noted for:","choices":["Cephalexin","Vancomycin","Metronidazole","Levofloxacin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole causes metallic taste, nausea, vomiting, and abdominal cramps.","cite":"Slide 65"},{"q":"Which class is used for community-acquired pneumonia due to atypicals like Legionella and Mycoplasma?","choices":["Anti-staphylococcal penicillins","Macrolides","Monobactams","Glycopeptides"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Macrolides (e.g., clarithromycin, azithromycin) cover atypicals relevant to respiratory infections.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"Azithromycin, compared with other macrolides, is:","choices":["Far more active against respiratory infections due to H. influenzae and M. catarrhalis","More active against staphylococci","The preferred drug for Pseudomonas","Bactericidal against all gram-negatives"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Azithromycin is far more active against respiratory infections due to H. influenzae and M. catarrhalis.","cite":"Slide 54"}]},"antimicrobials-3":{"title":"Antimicrobials Quiz 3","questions":[{"q":"Which of the following is an anti-pseudomonal penicillin?","choices":["Penicillin G","Amoxicillin","Nafcillin","Piperacillin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Piperacillin (with ticarcillin) is an anti-pseudomonal penicillin.","cite":"Slide 30"},{"q":"Which describes the correct killing pattern for beta-lactams?","choices":["Concentration-dependent with prolonged PAE","Concentration-dependent with no PAE","Bacteriostatic with moderate PAE","Time-dependent with no PAE"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Beta-lactams are bactericidal with time-dependent killing and no PAE.","cite":"Slide 35-36"},{"q":"Which agent covers gram-positive anaerobes, gram-negative anaerobes, and parasites?","choices":["Vancomycin","Ciprofloxacin","Cephalexin","Metronidazole"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole covers gram-positive and gram-negative anaerobes plus parasites.","cite":"Slide 64"},{"q":"A patient develops flushing during a rapid IV infusion of an antibiotic. Which drug is most likely responsible?","choices":["Amoxicillin","Doxycycline","Vancomycin","Levofloxacin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin causes red man syndrome/flushing when infused rapidly.","cite":"Slide 45"},{"q":"Beta-lactams and vancomycin share which general target?","choices":["The bacterial ribosome","The bacterial cell wall","Bacterial DNA gyrase","Folate synthesis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Both target the cell wall, though by different mechanisms (PBP inactivation vs. blocking cross-linking).","cite":"Slide 33, 43"},{"q":"Which macrolide has additional activity against Haemophilus influenzae and is more effective against Legionella and H. pylori?","choices":["Clarithromycin","Erythromycin","Clindamycin","Penicillin V"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Clarithromycin adds activity against H. influenzae and is more effective against Legionella and H. pylori.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"Which agent is bacteriostatic?","choices":["Metronidazole","Vancomycin","Ciprofloxacin","Doxycycline"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines like doxycycline are bacteriostatic.","cite":"Slide 49"},{"q":"As one moves UP in cephalosporin generation, gram-positive activity generally:","choices":["Increases","Disappears entirely at 2nd generation","Stays exactly the same","Decreases (until 4th gen restores it)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Gram-positive activity decreases with advancing generation, while 4th generation restores it without sacrificing gram-negative coverage.","cite":"Slide 39"},{"q":"Which is a specific indication for oral vancomycin?","choices":["Rocky Mountain spotted fever","Severe antibiotic-associated C. difficile colitis","Bacterial vaginosis","Community-acquired pneumonia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Oral vancomycin is limited to severe antibiotic-associated C. difficile colitis.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Aztreonam (a monobactam) is bactericidal and its mechanism is to:","choices":["Inhibit DNA gyrase","Bind the 50S ribosomal subunit","Inactivate penicillin-binding proteins","Block cell wall cross-linking as a glycopeptide"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. As a beta-lactam, aztreonam inactivates PBPs to disrupt cell wall synthesis.","cite":"Slide 29, 33"},{"q":"Which agent is used for acne, atypical pneumonia, and animal-borne diseases such as RMSF and Lyme?","choices":["Aztreonam","Cefepime","Doxycycline","Vancomycin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Doxycycline is used for acne, atypical pneumonia, and animal-borne diseases including RMSF and Lyme.","cite":"Slide 50"},{"q":"Which class is bactericidal, time-dependent, with moderate PAE, and covers gram-positives only?","choices":["Glycopeptides (vancomycin)","Fluoroquinolones","Tetracyclines","Monobactams"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is bactericidal, time-dependent, with moderate PAE, gram-positive only.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Which fluoroquinolone should NOT be used for skin infections per the lecture?","choices":["Levofloxacin","Ciprofloxacin","Moxifloxacin","Ofloxacin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Ciprofloxacin is specifically noted as NOT for skin.","cite":"Slide 60"},{"q":"The natural penicillin spectrum includes which gram-negative cocci?","choices":["Neisseria species","Escherichia coli","Klebsiella species","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Penicillin V covers gram-negative cocci such as Neisseria gonorrhoeae and N. meningitidis.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"Which agent is bactericidal and covers gram-positives, gram-positive bacilli (e.g., Corynebacterium diphtheriae), and spirochetes?","choices":["Penicillin V","Ciprofloxacin","Doxycycline","Metronidazole"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Penicillin V is bactericidal and covers gram-positive cocci/bacilli and spirochetes.","cite":"Slide 35"},{"q":"Which distinctive adverse effect is linked to fluoroquinolones and warrants caution in children?","choices":["Cartilage/tendon damage","Tooth discoloration","Red man syndrome","Disulfiram-like reaction"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones are associated with cartilage/tendon damage, prompting caution in children.","cite":"Slide 62"},{"q":"Which class inhibits translocation steps of protein synthesis by binding the 50S subunit?","choices":["Aminoglycosides","Macrolides and clindamycin","Tetracyclines","Beta-lactams"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Macrolides and clindamycin inhibit translocation by binding the 50S subunit.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Which combination product increases anaerobe coverage (Bacteroides) and covers MSSA?","choices":["Aztreonam","Penicillin V","Cefdinir","Amoxicillin + clavulanic acid (Augmentin)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Augmentin (amoxicillin + clavulanic acid) increases anaerobe coverage and covers MSSA.","cite":"Slide 42"},{"q":"Which agent is preferred for CAP among the fluoroquinolones and adds Pseudomonas coverage?","choices":["Levofloxacin","Ciprofloxacin","Nalidixic acid","Ofloxacin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Levofloxacin is used for CAP with added Pseudomonas coverage and improved gram-positive activity.","cite":"Slide 61"},{"q":"Which is TRUE about macrolides' bactericidal/static classification?","choices":["Always bacteriostatic regardless of dose","Always bactericidal","Bacteriostatic, but may be bactericidal at higher doses","Neither; purely inhibits toxin release"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Macrolides are bacteriostatic but may be bactericidal at higher doses.","cite":"Slide 52"},{"q":"Cefazolin (Ancef) and cephalexin (Keflex) are examples of which generation?","choices":["1st generation","2nd generation","3rd generation","4th generation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Cefazolin and cephalexin are 1st-generation cephalosporins.","cite":"Slide 31"},{"q":"Which agent is indicated for vaginal infections such as bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis?","choices":["Doxycycline","Metronidazole","Cephalexin","Vancomycin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole treats BV and trichomoniasis.","cite":"Slide 64"},{"q":"Clindamycin's spectrum includes gram-positive aerobes, gram-positive anaerobes, and:","choices":["Atypicals","Gram-negative aerobes","Pseudomonas","Gram-negative anaerobes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Correct. Clindamycin covers gram-negative anaerobes (but not gram-negative aerobes).","cite":"Slide 55"},{"q":"Which agent is used for surgical prophylaxis in penicillin-allergic patients and for endocarditis and osteomyelitis?","choices":["Ciprofloxacin","Metronidazole","Vancomycin","Amoxicillin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Vancomycin is used for surgical prophylaxis (penicillin allergy), endocarditis, and osteomyelitis.","cite":"Slide 44"},{"q":"Which class is bactericidal and inhibits DNA replication and transcription?","choices":["Macrolides","Tetracyclines","Fluoroquinolones","Glycopeptides"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Fluoroquinolones are bactericidal and inhibit DNA replication/transcription via DNA gyrase and topoisomerase.","cite":"Slide 59"},{"q":"Which agent would you AVOID giving with dairy, antacids, or iron because of chelation?","choices":["Tetracyclines (doxycycline)","Vancomycin","Metronidazole","Aztreonam"],"answer":0,"exp":"Correct. Tetracyclines chelate cations, so dairy, antacids, and iron should be avoided.","cite":"Slide 51"},{"q":"Which agent is preferred (among macrolides) as it is less active against streptococci/staphylococci but far more active against respiratory H. influenzae and M. catarrhalis?","choices":["Erythromycin","Azithromycin","Clindamycin","Penicillin G"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Azithromycin is less active against strep/staph but far more active against respiratory H. influenzae and M. catarrhalis.","cite":"Slide 54"},{"q":"Which beta-lactam class is most resistant to certain beta-lactamases compared with penicillins?","choices":["Anti-staphylococcal penicillins","Natural penicillins","Cephalosporins","Extended-spectrum penicillins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Correct. Cephalosporins are more resistant to certain beta-lactamases than penicillins.","cite":"Slide 38"},{"q":"Which agent is bactericidal and has anti-protozoal/anti-parasitic effects in addition to antibacterial activity?","choices":["Doxycycline","Metronidazole","Cephalexin","Erythromycin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Metronidazole is bactericidal and has anti-protozoal/anti-parasitic effects.","cite":"Slide 63"},{"q":"Ceftriaxone (Rocephin) is which generation of cephalosporin?","choices":["1st generation","3rd generation","2nd generation","4th generation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Correct. Ceftriaxone is a 3rd-generation cephalosporin.","cite":"Slide 31"}]},"endocrine":{"title":"Endocrine System (Set 1)","questions":[{"q":"According to the lecture, which structure functions as an endocrine organ, contains autonomic nervous system centers, AND exerts control over the suprarenal medulla?","choices":["Hypothalamus","Pituitary gland","Pineal gland","Thymus gland"],"answer":0,"exp":"The hypothalamus fills all three roles: it acts as an endocrine organ (releasing ADH and oxytocin toward the pituitary), it contains autonomic nervous system centers, and it controls the suprarenal medulla.","cite":"Overview — 'The Hypothalamus and Endocrine Regulation'"},{"q":"The lecture lists several 'other endocrine tissues' beyond the main organs. Which of the following is named among them?","choices":["Spleen","Kidney","Liver","Gallbladder"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney is listed among other endocrine tissues (it produces erythropoietin and calcitriol per Figure 19.1).","cite":"Overview — 'Other endocrine tissues'; Figure 19.1"},{"q":"In Figure 19.1, which hormone is identified as the secretion of the pineal gland?","choices":["Calcitonin","Thymosins","Melatonin","Erythropoietin"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pineal gland is labeled with melatonin in Figure 19.1.","cite":"Figure 19.1 — The Endocrine System"},{"q":"Per Figure 19.1, the heart is shown as an endocrine tissue producing which of the following?","choices":["Leptin and resistin","Thyroxine and triiodothyronine","Insulin and glucagon","Atrial and brain natriuretic peptides"],"answer":3,"exp":"The heart is labeled as producing natriuretic peptides — atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP) and brain natriuretic peptide (BNP).","cite":"Figure 19.1 — Heart"},{"q":"According to Figure 19.1, adipose tissue is depicted as secreting which pair of hormones?","choices":["Leptin and resistin","Cortisol and aldosterone","Estrogens and progestins","EPO and calcitriol"],"answer":0,"exp":"Adipose tissue is labeled with leptin and resistin.","cite":"Figure 19.1 — Adipose Tissue"},{"q":"In Figure 19.2, the hypothalamus controls the suprarenal medulla by which of the three listed mechanisms?","choices":["Secreting regulatory hormones to the pars distalis","Controlling sympathetic output via preganglionic motor fibers","Producing ADH and oxytocin","Releasing melatonin into the portal system"],"answer":1,"exp":"Figure 19.2 shows mechanism 3: control of sympathetic output to the suprarenal medullae via preganglionic motor fibers, driving secretion of epinephrine and norepinephrine.","cite":"Figure 19.2 — Hypothalamic Control over Endocrine Organs"},{"q":"The pituitary gland sits within which bony fossa?","choices":["Jugular fossa","Pterygopalatine fossa","Hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica","Mandibular fossa"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pituitary (hypophysis) sits in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone.","cite":"'The Pituitary Gland' — location; 'Pituitary Gland (Hypophysis Cerebri)'"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is attached to the hypothalamus by which structure?","choices":["Diaphragma sellae","Dorsum sellae","Optic chiasma","Infundibulum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The infundibulum (pituitary stalk) attaches the pituitary to the hypothalamus, connecting the pars nervosa to the median eminence.","cite":"'The Pituitary Gland'; Figure 19.3a"},{"q":"The diaphragma sellae covering the pituitary is pierced centrally by the infundibulum and separates the gland from which structure?","choices":["Optic chiasma","Cavernous sinus","Sphenoid air sinus","Dorsum sellae"],"answer":0,"exp":"The diaphragma sellae of dura mater is pierced centrally by the infundibulum and separates the gland from the optic chiasma.","cite":"'Pituitary Gland (Hypophysis Cerebri)' — relations"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is related on either side to which structure?","choices":["Sphenoid air sinus","Cavernous sinus","Optic chiasma","Third ventricle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gland is related on either side to the cavernous sinus.","cite":"'Pituitary Gland (Hypophysis Cerebri)' — relations"},{"q":"Which subdivisions make up the anterior lobe (adenohypophysis) of the pituitary?","choices":["Pars nervosa, infundibulum, median eminence","Pars nervosa, pars distalis, pars tuberalis","Pars distalis, pars tuberalis, pars intermedia","Pars intermedia, pars nervosa, infundibular stalk"],"answer":2,"exp":"The adenohypophysis consists of the pars distalis, pars tuberalis, and pars intermedia.","cite":"'The pituitary gland consists of' — anterior lobe subdivisions"},{"q":"The posterior lobe (neurohypophysis) consists of the pars nervosa, which is connected by the infundibulum to which part of the hypothalamus?","choices":["Optic chiasm","Mammillary body","Paraventricular nucleus","Median eminence (tuber cinereum)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pars nervosa connects via the infundibulum (pituitary stalk) to the median eminence (tuber cinereum) of the hypothalamus.","cite":"'The pituitary gland consists of' — posterior lobe"},{"q":"Within the hypophyseal portal system, regulatory hormones leave the hypothalamus and pass through portal vessels to which target?","choices":["Adenohypophysis","Neurohypophysis","Suprarenal medulla","Pineal gland"],"answer":0,"exp":"Regulatory hormones travel through the fenestrated portal capillaries to the adenohypophysis (anterior pituitary).","cite":"'The Hypophyseal Portal System'; 'Note' slide"},{"q":"The lecture's 'Note' slide contrasts the blood supply of the two pituitary lobes. Which statement is correct?","choices":["Both lobes receive portal blood","The anterior pituitary receives portal blood; the posterior receives arterial blood","The anterior pituitary receives arterial blood; the posterior receives portal blood","Both lobes receive only arterial blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"The anterior pituitary receives portal blood, while the posterior pituitary receives arterial blood.","cite":"'Note' — anterior vs posterior pituitary blood supply"},{"q":"Somatotropes of the adenohypophysis release which hormone?","choices":["Prolactin (PRL)","Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)","Growth hormone (GH)","Luteinizing hormone (LH)"],"answer":2,"exp":"Somatotropes release growth hormone (GH, also called somatotropin).","cite":"'The Adenohypophysis' — five cell types"},{"q":"In the pars distalis, the acidophils (about 10% of cells, reddish cytoplasm) secrete which hormones?","choices":["TSH and ACTH","ADH and oxytocin","FSH and LH","Growth hormone and prolactin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Acidophils have reddish cytoplasm and secrete growth hormone (GH) and prolactin (lactogenic hormone).","cite":"'Pars distalis is formed of' — acidophils vs basophils"},{"q":"The pars nervosa contains bundles of nerve fibers, pituicytes, and homogenous intercellular material that on fixation precipitates to form what?","choices":["Herring's body","Colloid","Chromaffin granules","Zymogen granules"],"answer":0,"exp":"On fixation the homogenous intercellular substance of the pars nervosa precipitates to form Herring's bodies.","cite":"'Pars nervosa contains' — Herring's body"},{"q":"The thyroid gland lies in the lower neck spanning which vertebral levels?","choices":["C3 to C5","C5 to T1","T1 to T4","C1 to C3"],"answer":1,"exp":"The thyroid lies in the lower neck at the level of the 5th cervical (C5) to the 1st thoracic (T1) vertebrae.","cite":"'THE THYROID GLAND' — vertebral levels"},{"q":"The apex of each thyroid lobe reaches to which laryngeal landmark?","choices":["Cricoid cartilage","Hyoid bone","Oblique line of the thyroid cartilage","4th or 5th tracheal ring"],"answer":2,"exp":"The apex is at the level of the oblique line of the thyroid cartilage of the larynx.","cite":"'THE THYROID GLAND' — apex and base"},{"q":"The base of each thyroid lobe lies at the level of which structure?","choices":["Oblique line of thyroid cartilage","2nd and 3rd tracheal rings","1st tracheal ring","4th or 5th tracheal ring"],"answer":3,"exp":"The base of each lobe is at the level of the 4th or 5th tracheal ring.","cite":"'THE THYROID GLAND' — apex and base"},{"q":"The anterior border of the thyroid lobe is thin and related to which vessel?","choices":["Anterior branch of the superior thyroid artery","Inferior thyroid artery","Thyroidea ima artery","Middle thyroid vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The thin anterior border is related to the anterior branch of the superior thyroid artery and is continuous below with the upper border of the isthmus.","cite":"Thyroid borders — anterior border"},{"q":"The rounded posterior border of the thyroid is related below to the inferior thyroid artery and is the border to which the ______ glands are usually related.","choices":["Submandibular","Parathyroid","Thymus","Pineal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The parathyroid glands are usually related to the rounded posterior border of the thyroid.","cite":"Thyroid borders — posterior border"},{"q":"The medial surface of the thyroid is related to the larynx, pharynx, and which nerve, as well as the trachea, esophagus, and recurrent laryngeal nerve?","choices":["Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],"answer":2,"exp":"The medial surface is related to the larynx, pharynx, and external laryngeal nerve (and to the trachea, esophagus, and recurrent laryngeal nerve).","cite":"'The medial surface is related to'"},{"q":"The posterior surface of the thyroid is related to which structure overlapping the common carotid artery?","choices":["Sternomastoid muscle","Pretracheal fascia","Platysma","Carotid sheath"],"answer":3,"exp":"The posterior surface is related to the carotid sheath, which overlaps the common carotid artery.","cite":"'The posterior surface is related to' — carotid sheath"},{"q":"The thyroid gland moves up and down with deglutition because it is enclosed in which fascia, connected above to the thyroid cartilage?","choices":["Pretracheal fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Carotid sheath","Superficial fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The gland lies within the pretracheal fascia, which is connected above to the thyroid cartilage — the reason it moves with swallowing.","cite":"Thyroid surfaces — pretracheal fascia / deglutition"},{"q":"The thyroid isthmus lies opposite which tracheal rings?","choices":["1st and 2nd","2nd and 3rd","4th and 5th","3rd and 4th"],"answer":1,"exp":"The isthmus lies opposite the 2nd and 3rd tracheal rings and is covered by the sternohyoid and sternothyroid muscles.","cite":"'Thyroid isthmus'"},{"q":"The superior thyroid artery arises from which vessel?","choices":["Arch of the aorta","Thyrocervical trunk","External carotid artery","Internal carotid artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The superior thyroid artery arises from the external carotid artery and descends with the external laryngeal nerve to the gland.","cite":"'Blood supply of thyroid gland' — superior thyroid artery"},{"q":"The inferior thyroid artery arises from the thyrocervical trunk and becomes related to which nerve at the posterior surface of the gland?","choices":["External laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Vagus nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],"answer":3,"exp":"The inferior thyroid artery becomes related to the recurrent laryngeal nerve at the posterior surface of the gland.","cite":"'Blood supply of thyroid gland' — inferior thyroid artery"},{"q":"The thyroidea ima artery, an uncommon variant supplying the isthmus, arises from the arch of the aorta or which other vessel?","choices":["Brachiocephalic artery","Thyrocervical trunk","External carotid artery","Vertebral artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The thyroidea ima artery arises from the arch of the aorta or the brachiocephalic artery.","cite":"'Blood supply of thyroid gland' — thyroidea ima artery"},{"q":"Regarding venous drainage of the thyroid, the inferior thyroid vein ends in which vein?","choices":["Internal jugular vein","Brachiocephalic vein","External jugular vein","Subclavian vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"The inferior thyroid vein ends in the brachiocephalic vein, whereas the superior and middle thyroid veins usually end in the internal jugular vein.","cite":"'Venous drainage' — thyroid veins"},{"q":"The parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid sit near the follicular basement lamina, separated from the follicle lumen by follicular epithelium, and secrete which hormone?","choices":["Thyroxine","Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin","Thyroglobulin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parafollicular (C) cells secrete calcitonin; they are larger and lighter-staining than follicular cells.","cite":"'Para follicular or C cells' — calcitonin"},{"q":"The parathyroid glands are usually located in which position relative to the thyroid?","choices":["Anterior surface of the thyroid","Superior to the hyoid bone","Within the isthmus only","Posterior aspect of the thyroid"],"answer":3,"exp":"The parathyroid glands lie on the posterior aspect of the thyroid, between its posterior borders and capsule; sometimes tissue is embedded within the thyroid.","cite":"'Parathyroid Glands (Post. view of thyroid)'; 'PARATHYROID GLANDS'"},{"q":"How many parathyroid glands are usually present, and how are they arranged?","choices":["Four total, two on each side (one superior, one inferior)","Two total, one on each side","Six total, three on each side","Three total, all on the left"],"answer":0,"exp":"There are usually two on each side — one superior and one inferior — for four total.","cite":"'PARATHYROID GLANDS' — number and arrangement"},{"q":"Which parathyroid glands are more constant in location, usually lying midway along the posterior thyroid borders?","choices":["The inferior glands","The superior glands","The left-sided glands","The embedded glands"],"answer":1,"exp":"The superior parathyroid glands are more constant in location than the inferior and lie midway along the posterior thyroid borders.","cite":"'PARATHYROID GLANDS' — superior vs inferior constancy"},{"q":"The inferior pair of parathyroid glands may be found in which of the following positions?","choices":["Anterior to the sternohyoid muscle","Within the carotid sheath","Above or below the inferior thyroid arteries, or in the thyroid near its base","Deep to the trachea in the superior mediastinum only"],"answer":2,"exp":"The inferior pair may lie above or below the inferior thyroid arteries, or within the thyroid gland near its base.","cite":"'PARATHYROID GLANDS' — 'The inferior pair may be'"},{"q":"In parathyroid histology, which cells have slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm and produce parathyroid hormone (PTH)?","choices":["Oxyphil cells","Follicular cells","Chromaffin cells","Principal (chief) cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Principal (chief) cells have slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm and produce parathyroid hormone (PTH).","cite":"'Histology of parathyroid glands' — principal (chief) cells"},{"q":"The oxyphil cells of the parathyroid gland are described as:","choices":["Larger and very eosinophilic cells of unknown function","Small cells with no granules","Simple cuboidal cells surrounding colloid","Lipid-droplet-laden cells in radial columns"],"answer":0,"exp":"Oxyphil cells are larger and very eosinophilic; their function is unknown, though they may also secrete PTH.","cite":"'Histology of parathyroid glands' — oxyphil cells"},{"q":"The large rounded head of the pancreas fills the concavity of which structure?","choices":["Spleen","Duodenum","Stomach","Transverse colon"],"answer":1,"exp":"The head of the pancreas fills the concavity of the duodenum, while the pointed tail extends toward the spleen.","cite":"'The Pancreas and Other Endocrine Tissues'; 'Head fills concavity of duodenum'"},{"q":"The tail of the pancreas extends toward which organ?","choices":["Liver","Left kidney","Spleen","Gallbladder"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pointed tail of the pancreas extends toward the spleen (reaching the hilus of the spleen).","cite":"Pancreas gross anatomy — 'Tail reaches hilus of the spleen'"},{"q":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally at approximately which vertebral levels?","choices":["T6–T8","T9–T10","L4–L5","T12/L1 to L3"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally at approximately T12/L1 to L3.","cite":"Pancreas — 'Lies retroperitoneally at ~T-12/L-1 to L-3'"},{"q":"Within a pancreatic islet, which endocrine cell type produces insulin?","choices":["Beta (β) cells","Alpha (α) cells","Delta (δ) cells","F cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Beta (β) cells produce insulin.","cite":"Figure 19.10ab — endocrine cells of the pancreatic islet"},{"q":"Per the islet cell labeling, which cells produce glucagon?","choices":["Beta (β) cells","Alpha (α) cells","Delta (δ) cells","F cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Alpha (α) cells produce glucagon.","cite":"Figure 19.10ab — α cells (glucagon)"},{"q":"The main pancreatic duct (Duct of Wirsung) joins the common bile duct at which site?","choices":["Minor duodenal papilla","Pylorus","Ampulla of Vater","Neck of the pancreas"],"answer":2,"exp":"The Duct of Wirsung joins the CBD at the Ampulla of Vater (about 3–4\" below the pylorus).","cite":"'Pancreatic Duct System' — Duct of Wirsung"},{"q":"The accessory pancreatic duct (Duct of Santorini) drains into the duodenum at which site?","choices":["Major duodenal papilla","Duodenojejunal flexure","Ampulla of Vater","Minor duodenal papilla"],"answer":3,"exp":"The Duct of Santorini joins the duodenum at the minor papilla and represents part of the duct from the dorsal pancreas.","cite":"'Duct of Santorini' — accessory pancreatic duct"},{"q":"The suprarenal glands are located attached to which border of the kidneys?","choices":["Superior border","Inferior border","Medial border only","Lateral border only"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suprarenal (adrenal) glands are attached to the superior border of the kidneys.","cite":"'The Suprarenal Glands' — location"},{"q":"The suprarenal glands receive a highly vascular supply. Which of the following is one of the arteries named in the lecture?","choices":["Splenic artery","Middle suprarenal artery from the descending aorta","Gastroduodenal artery","Superior thyroid artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The middle suprarenal artery from the descending aorta supplies the gland, along with branches from the renal artery and the inferior phrenic artery.","cite":"'The Suprarenal Glands' — arterial supply"},{"q":"The three distinct zones of the suprarenal cortex, from outer to inner, are:","choices":["Zona reticularis, fasciculata, glomerulosa","Zona fasciculata, glomerulosa, reticularis","Zona glomerulosa, fasciculata, reticularis","Medulla, cortex, capsule"],"answer":2,"exp":"From outer to inner the cortex is zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis (deep to the capsule, superficial to the medulla).","cite":"'The Suprarenal Glands' — cortical zones; Figure (c/d)"},{"q":"The zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex secretes which class of hormone?","choices":["Catecholamines","Glucocorticoids (cortisol)","Androgens","Mineralocorticoids (aldosterone)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The zona glomerulosa secretes mineralocorticoids (aldosterone).","cite":"'HISTOLOGY OF ADRENAL GLANDS' — zona glomerulosa"},{"q":"The zona fasciculata, composed of lipid-droplet-laden cells in radial columns, secretes which hormone?","choices":["Glucocorticoids (cortisol)","Aldosterone","Androgens","Adrenaline"],"answer":0,"exp":"The zona fasciculata secretes glucocorticoids (cortisol).","cite":"'HISTOLOGY OF ADRENAL GLANDS' — zona fasciculata"},{"q":"The principal cells of the adrenal medulla, considered modified postganglionic sympathetic neurons lacking dendrites and axons, are called:","choices":["Chief cells","Chromaffin cells","Pituicytes","Oxyphil cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The chromaffin cells are the principal cells of the medulla; they secrete adrenaline and noradrenaline, and the medulla contains a large central vein.","cite":"'ADRENAL MEDULLA' — chromaffin cells"}]},"female-reproductive":{"title":"Female Reproductive System (Set 1)","questions":[{"q":"The internal female reproductive organs develop primarily from which paired embryonic ducts?","choices":["Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts","Mesonephric (Wolffian) ducts","Pronephric ducts","Metanephric ducts"],"answer":0,"exp":"The Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts develop into the major internal female reproductive organs in the absence of anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH).","cite":"Slide 16 — Müllerian ducts (paramesonephric ducts)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts develop into the female organs in the absence of which hormone?","choices":["Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)","Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH)","Progesterone","Estrogen"],"answer":1,"exp":"In the absence of anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH), the Müllerian ducts develop into the female reproductive organs; AMH causes their regression in males.","cite":"Slide 16–17 — regression in males occurs via AMH"},{"q":"The fused caudal portions of the Müllerian ducts (the uterovaginal primordium) give rise to which structures?","choices":["The fallopian (uterine) tubes","The ovaries","The uterus, cervix, and upper vagina","The labia majora"],"answer":2,"exp":"The fused caudal portions form the uterus, cervix, and the upper portion of the vagina.","cite":"Slide 16 — fused caudal portions → uterus and cervix; upper vagina"},{"q":"The unfused cranial portions of the Müllerian ducts differentiate into which structures?","choices":["Uterus and cervix","Clitoris","Lower vagina","Fallopian (uterine) tubes"],"answer":3,"exp":"The unfused cranial portions become the fallopian (uterine) tubes.","cite":"Slide 16 — unfused cranial portions → Fallopian tubes"},{"q":"According to the lecture, the lower portion of the vagina develops from which structure?","choices":["The urogenital sinus","The fused Müllerian ducts","The mesonephric ducts","The coelomic epithelium"],"answer":0,"exp":"The lower vagina develops from the urogenital sinus, while the upper portion develops from the fused Müllerian ducts.","cite":"Slide 16 — lower vagina develops from the urogenital sinus"},{"q":"The perineum is a diamond-shaped area circumscribed anteriorly by which structure?","choices":["Coccyx","Pubic symphysis","Ischial tuberosities","Sacrum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The perineum is circumscribed anteriorly by the pubic symphysis (laterally by the ischial tuberosities and posteriorly by the coccyx).","cite":"Slide 5 — Perineum boundaries"},{"q":"The perineum is divided into two triangles by an imaginary horizontal line extending between which landmarks?","choices":["The pubic tubercles","The anterior superior iliac spines","The ischial tuberosities","The greater trochanters"],"answer":2,"exp":"An imaginary horizontal line between the ischial tuberosities of the ossa coxae divides the perineum into anterior and posterior triangles.","cite":"Slide 5 — line between the ischial tuberosities"},{"q":"The anterior triangle of the perineum is also called the urogenital triangle. In females it contains which openings?","choices":["The anus","The internal and external os","The base of the penis and scrotum","The urethral and vaginal orifices"],"answer":3,"exp":"The anterior (urogenital) triangle contains the urethral and vaginal orifices in females.","cite":"Slide 5 — Anterior (urogenital) triangle"},{"q":"The posterior triangle of the perineum, containing the anus in both sexes, is also called the:","choices":["Anal triangle","Urogenital triangle","Femoral triangle","Cystic triangle"],"answer":0,"exp":"The posterior triangle is the anal triangle, the location of the anus in both sexes.","cite":"Slide 5 — Posterior (anal) triangle"},{"q":"The pelvic diaphragm is formed by which muscles?","choices":["Bulbospongiosus and ischiocavernosus muscles","Levator ani and coccygeus muscles","Rectus abdominis and pyramidalis muscles","Piriformis and obturator internus muscles"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm is formed by the levator ani and coccygeus muscles.","cite":"Slide 9 — Pelvic Diaphragm: levator ani and coccygeus"},{"q":"The levator ani muscle is made up of which three parts?","choices":["Internal, external, and mid sphincters","Superficial, middle, deep transverse perineal","Puborectalis, pubococcygeus, iliococcygeus","Ischiocavernosus, bulbospongiosus, coccygeus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The levator ani is made up of the puborectalis, pubococcygeus, and iliococcygeus.","cite":"Slide 9 — Levator ani: puborectalis, pubococcygeus, iliococcygeus"},{"q":"Which of the following is a function of the pelvic diaphragm described in the lecture?","choices":["Produces female gametes","Serves as the birth canal","Secretes reproductive hormones","Supports pelvic organs and seals the inferior opening of the bony pelvis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm supports the pelvic organs, seals the inferior opening of the bony pelvis, and lifts to help release feces during defecation.","cite":"Slide 9 — Pelvic Diaphragm functions"},{"q":"Which muscle related to the vagina is described as part of the levator ani?","choices":["Pubovaginalis muscle","Bulbospongiosus muscle","External urethral sphincter","Urethrovaginal sphincter"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pubovaginalis muscle is described as part of the levator ani.","cite":"Slide 62 — Muscles Related to the Vagina"},{"q":"The broad ligament is best described as which of the following?","choices":["A double fold of peritoneum attaching the ovary to the pelvic wall","A fold of peritoneum that drapes over the uterus","A cord extending through the inguinal canal","A thickening of subserous fascia and smooth muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The broad ligament is a fold of peritoneum that drapes over the uterus (and helps hold the ovaries and uterine tubes).","cite":"Slide 14 — Broad ligament: peritoneum, drapes over the uterus"},{"q":"The mesovarium is a double fold of peritoneum that attaches the ovary to which structure?","choices":["The pelvic wall","The uterus","The broad ligament","The labia majora"],"answer":2,"exp":"The mesovarium is a double fold of peritoneum attaching the ovaries to the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 14 — Mesovarium attaches ovaries to broad ligament"},{"q":"The ovarian ligament connects the ovary to which structure?","choices":["The pelvic wall","The labia majora","The broad ligament","The uterus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ovarian ligament runs from the ovary to the uterus (attaching to the superior margin of the uterus).","cite":"Slide 14, 18 — Ovarian ligament: ovary to uterus"},{"q":"The suspensory ligament of the ovary extends from the ovary/mesovarium to which structure?","choices":["The pelvic (body) wall","The uterus","The cervix","The labia minora"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suspensory ligament extends from the ovary (mesovarium) to the pelvic/body wall and transmits the ovarian vessels.","cite":"Slide 14, 18 — Suspensory ligament: ovary to pelvic wall / body wall"},{"q":"The round ligament of the uterus extends from the uterus through the inguinal canal to which structure?","choices":["The pelvic wall","The labia majora","The sacrum","The ovary"],"answer":1,"exp":"The round ligament extends from the uterus through the inguinal canal to the labia majora, helping maintain the anteverted position.","cite":"Slide 18, 36 — Round ligament to labia majora"},{"q":"The uterosacral ligaments extend from the inferior uterus to which structure?","choices":["The labia majora","The pubic symphysis","The sacrum","The lateral pelvic wall at the cervix"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterosacral ligaments extend from the inferior uterus to the sacrum.","cite":"Slide 36 — Uterosacral ligaments: inferior uterus to sacrum"},{"q":"What are the primary sex organs (gonads) of the female?","choices":["The uterine tubes","The mammary glands","The uterus","The ovaries"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ovaries are the primary sex organs of the female; the uterine tubes, uterus, vagina, clitoris, and mammary glands are accessory sex organs.","cite":"Slide 12 — Primary sex organs are the ovaries"},{"q":"The ovary lies posterior to which peritoneal structure?","choices":["The broad ligament (mesovarium)","The round ligament","The rectum","The urinary bladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ovary lies posterior to the broad ligament (mesovarium) and is anchored by the suspensory and ovarian ligaments.","cite":"Slide 24 — Ovary posterior to broad ligament (mesovarium)"},{"q":"The ovary receives its arterial blood supply from which vessel?","choices":["The uterine artery","The ovarian artery","The internal iliac artery","The vaginal artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ovary's blood supply is via the ovarian artery, which arises from the abdominal aorta and enters through the suspensory ligament.","cite":"Slide 24, 27 — Blood supply via ovarian artery"},{"q":"The venous drainage of the right ovary is to the inferior vena cava, while the left ovarian vein drains into which vessel?","choices":["The left internal iliac vein","The portal vein","The left renal vein","The azygos vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The right ovarian vein drains to the inferior vena cava and the left drains into the left renal vein.","cite":"Slide 24 — Venous drainage to IVC (right) and left renal vein"},{"q":"The lymphatics of the ovary follow the ovarian blood vessels to ascend to which nodes?","choices":["Superficial inguinal nodes","Axillary nodes","Internal iliac nodes","Lumbar (para-aortic) lymph nodes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Ovarian lymphatics follow the ovarian vessels to ascend to the lumbar lymph nodes.","cite":"Slide 27 — Lymphatics ascend to the lumbar lymph nodes"},{"q":"Afferent (sensory) fibers from the ovary enter the spinal cord through which nerve levels?","choices":["T10 and T11","L1 and L2","S2, S3, and S4","T6 and T7"],"answer":0,"exp":"Afferent fibers from the ovary enter the spinal cord through the T10 and T11 nerves.","cite":"Slide 27 — Afferent fibers enter spinal cord through T10 and T11"},{"q":"The uterus is located between which two organs?","choices":["The ovaries and the vagina","The urinary bladder and the rectum","The sacrum and the pubic symphysis","The ureters and the colon"],"answer":1,"exp":"The uterus lies between the urinary bladder (anteriorly) and the rectum (posteriorly).","cite":"Slide 32 — located between the urinary bladder and rectum"},{"q":"The normal position of the uterus is described as anteverted and anteflexed. Anteversion occurs at which junction?","choices":["The internal os","The junction of cervix and body","The junction of cervix and vagina","The fundus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterus is anteverted at the junction of the cervix and vagina (and anteflexed at the cervix and body).","cite":"Slide 31 — Anteverted at junction of cervix and vagina"},{"q":"Which is the rounded region of the uterus, superior and anterior to the entrance of the uterine tubes?","choices":["Body","Cervix","Isthmus","Fundus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The fundus is the rounded portion superior and anterior to the uterine tube entrance.","cite":"Slide 34 — Fundus"},{"q":"The constricted region of the uterus between the body and the cervix is the:","choices":["Isthmus","Fundus","Internal os","External os"],"answer":0,"exp":"The isthmus is the constricted region between the body and the cervix.","cite":"Slide 34 — Isthmus"},{"q":"In the cervix, the opening to the vagina is called the:","choices":["Internal os","External os","Fornix","Isthmus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The external os is the cervical opening to the vagina; the internal os opens to the isthmus.","cite":"Slide 34 — external os: opening to vagina"},{"q":"The three concentric tunics of the uterine wall, from outer to inner, are:","choices":["Endometrium, myometrium, perimetrium","Myometrium, perimetrium, endometrium","Perimetrium, myometrium, endometrium","Serosa, submucosa, mucosa"],"answer":2,"exp":"From outer to inner the uterine wall is the perimetrium, myometrium, and endometrium.","cite":"Slide 35, 39 — Uterine layers"},{"q":"Which uterine tunic is the thick middle layer of smooth muscle that becomes distended during pregnancy?","choices":["Perimetrium","Adventitia","Endometrium","Myometrium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The myometrium is the thick middle tunic of smooth muscle (three intertwining layers) that enlarges during pregnancy.","cite":"Slide 35, 39 — Myometrium: smooth muscle"},{"q":"In which region of the uterine tube does fertilization of the secondary oocyte usually occur (the long, wide portion)?","choices":["Ampulla","Infundibulum","Isthmus","Intramural (interstitial) portion"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ampulla is the long, wide portion of the uterine tube and the usual site of fertilization.","cite":"Slide 45, 51 — Ampulla: long, wide portion"},{"q":"The finger-like projections at the distal end of the uterine tube are the:","choices":["Villi","Fimbriae","Fornices","Cilia"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fimbriae are the finger-like projections at the distal (infundibular) end of the uterine tube.","cite":"Slide 51 — Fimbriae: finger-like projections at distal end"},{"q":"The mucosa of the uterine tube is lined by which epithelium?","choices":["Nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Simple ciliated columnar epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterine tube is lined by ciliated (and non-ciliated) simple columnar epithelium; ciliary movement helps move the ovum toward the uterus.","cite":"Slide 45, 53 — simple ciliated columnar epithelium"},{"q":"Which statement about the relationship of the uterine tube to the ovary is correct?","choices":["The tube is physically fused to the ovary","The tube is continuous with the ovarian cortex","The tube attaches to the ovary via the round ligament","The tube does not physically attach to the ovary"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterine (fallopian) tube receives the ovulated oocyte and attaches to the uterus, but does not physically attach to the ovary.","cite":"Slide 49–50 — Does not physically attach to the ovary"},{"q":"The uterine tube is supported by and located within which structure?","choices":["The broad ligament","The round ligament","The uterosacral ligament","The suspensory ligament of the ovary"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterine tube lies within and is supported by the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 47, 49 — Within broad ligament / supported by the broad ligament"},{"q":"According to the lecture, the nerve supply to the uterine tube is derived from which plexi?","choices":["The ovarian and uterine plexi","The pelvic splanchnic plexus only","The hypogastric and sacral plexi","The pampiniform plexus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterine tube receives its nerve supply from the ovarian and uterine plexi (its blood supply is via the ovarian and uterine arteries).","cite":"Slide 48 — Uterine Tube: Nerve supply from ovarian and uterine plexi"},{"q":"What is the positional relationship of the vagina to the urethra and rectum?","choices":["Anterior to the urethra and posterior to the rectum","Lateral to both","Posterior to the urethra and anterior to the rectum","Superior to both"],"answer":2,"exp":"The vagina lies posterior to the urethra and anterior to the rectum.","cite":"Slide 57 — Posterior to urethra, anterior to rectum"},{"q":"The recess or pocket surrounding the uterine cervix where it projects into the vagina is called the:","choices":["Infundibulum","Vestibule","Hymen","Fornix"],"answer":3,"exp":"The fornix is the pocket surrounding the uterine cervix (the junction with the cervix of the uterus).","cite":"Slide 59, 60 — Fornix: junction/pocket around cervix"},{"q":"The wall of the vagina consists of three tunics. What is its outer tunic?","choices":["Adventitia","Serosa","Perimetrium","Peritoneum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The vaginal wall consists of an inner mucosa, a middle muscularis, and an outer adventitia.","cite":"Slide 56 — inner mucosa, middle muscularis, outer adventitia"},{"q":"The external sex organs of the female are collectively called the:","choices":["Perineum","Vulva (pudendum)","Vestibule","Fornix"],"answer":1,"exp":"The external genitalia are collectively called the vulva (also called the pudendum).","cite":"Slide 66, 72 — external genitalia collectively called the vulva"},{"q":"The labia majora are homologous to which male structure?","choices":["The penis","The bulbourethral gland","The scrotum","The vas deferens"],"answer":2,"exp":"The labia majora are homologous to the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 69, 73 — Labia majora homologous to scrotum"},{"q":"The vestibule is the space enclosed by the labia that contains the openings of which structures?","choices":["The ureters and bladder","The anus and rectum","The cervix and fornix","The urethra, vagina, and vestibular glands"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vestibule contains the openings of the urethra, the vagina, and the vestibular glands.","cite":"Slide 70 — Vestibule contains openings: urethra, vagina, vestibular glands"},{"q":"The greater vestibular gland is homologous to which male gland and performs what function?","choices":["The bulbourethral gland; secretes mucus","The prostate; secretes enzymes","The seminal vesicle; stores sperm","The parotid gland; secretes saliva"],"answer":0,"exp":"The greater vestibular gland is homologous to the bulbourethral gland and secretes mucus, drained by a duct into the vestibule.","cite":"Slide 78 — Greater Vestibular Gland homologous to bulbourethral gland, secretes mucus"},{"q":"The breast lies between which ribs?","choices":["The 4th and 8th ribs","The 2nd and 6th ribs","The 1st and 4th ribs","The 6th and 10th ribs"],"answer":1,"exp":"The breast lies between the 2nd and 6th ribs, between the sternal edge and the midaxillary line.","cite":"Slide 79 — Lies between the 2nd and 6th rib"},{"q":"The breast is described as lying two-thirds superficial to which muscle?","choices":["Serratus anterior","Latissimus dorsi","Pectoral muscle","External oblique"],"answer":2,"exp":"About two-thirds of the breast lies superficial to the pectoral muscle, and one-third superficial to the serratus anterior.","cite":"Slide 79 — 2/3 superficial to pectoral muscle"},{"q":"The suspensory ligament of the breast that connects the skin to the breast fascia is also known as:","choices":["The cardinal ligament","The round ligament","The broad ligament","Cooper's ligament"],"answer":3,"exp":"The suspensory ligament of the breast is Cooper's ligament, which connects the skin to the breast fascia.","cite":"Slide 81 — suspensory ligament (Cooper's ligament)"},{"q":"Lymphatic drainage of the breast is primarily directed toward which region?","choices":["The axilla","The inguinal nodes","The popliteal nodes","The lumbar nodes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Breast lymphatic drainage is primarily toward the axilla (and also to the collateral side).","cite":"Slide 87 — Lymphatics: drainage towards axilla"},{"q":"The medial quadrant of the breast receives its blood supply in part from perforating branches of which artery?","choices":["The lateral thoracic artery","The internal thoracic artery","The thoracoacromial artery","The subscapular artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The medial quadrant is supplied by perforating branches (2, 3, 4) from the internal thoracic artery and by anterior intercostal branches.","cite":"Slide 85 — Medial quadrant: perforating branches from internal thoracic artery"}]},"male-reproductive":{"title":"Male Reproductive System (Set 1)","questions":[{"q":"During development, the testes first form in which location before descending?","choices":["Inside the abdominal cavity near the kidneys","Inside the scrotum","Within the inguinal canal","Within the pelvic cavity near the bladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The testes form inside the abdominal cavity near the kidneys during development, then descend toward the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 8 — Descent of the Testes"},{"q":"Which structure holds the testes in place and, by failing to elongate as the body grows, pulls them inferiorly toward the scrotum?","choices":["The spermatic cord","The gubernaculum testis","The tunica vaginalis","The cremaster muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gubernaculum testis holds the testes in place and, because it does not elongate with body growth, pulls the testes inferiorly toward the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 8 — Gubernaculum testis"},{"q":"As the testes descend, they reach the scrotum by passing through which structure?","choices":["The obturator foramen","The femoral canal","The inguinal canals","The urogenital diaphragm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The testes descend toward the scrotum by passing through the inguinal canals.","cite":"Slide 8 — pass through the inguinal canals"},{"q":"After descent, which structures remain bundled to the testes within the spermatic cords?","choices":["The ureter and urinary bladder","The corpora cavernosa and corpus spongiosum","The prostate and seminal glands","The ductus deferens, blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ductus deferens, blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves remain bundled to the testes in the spermatic cords.","cite":"Slide 8 — spermatic cords"},{"q":"According to the lecture, why do the testes develop within the abdominal cavity but sperm develop outside it in the scrotum?","choices":["Testicle development needs ~98.6°F while sperm development needs a cooler ~96.6°F","Sperm require a warmer temperature than the testes","The scrotum provides more space for the testes","Abdominal pressure is required for sperm formation"],"answer":0,"exp":"Testicle development requires about 98.6°F (hence within the abdomen), while sperm development requires a cooler ~96.6°F (hence outside the abdomen in the scrotum).","cite":"Slide 9 — temperature requirements for testicle vs sperm development"},{"q":"Powerful contractions of which two muscles push semen toward the external urethral orifice during ejaculation?","choices":["Dartos and cremaster","Ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus","Rectus abdominis and pyramidalis","Levator ani and coccygeus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ejaculation involves powerful contractions of the ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus muscles, which push semen toward the external urethral orifice.","cite":"Slide 66 — Ejaculation: contractions of ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus"},{"q":"The spongy urethra passes through which muscle at the base of the penis, as labeled in the reproductive system figure?","choices":["Cremaster muscle","Dartos muscle","Bulbospongiosus","Ischiocavernosus"],"answer":2,"exp":"In the figure, the spongy (penile) urethra and the bulb of the penis are associated with the bulbospongiosus muscle.","cite":"Slide 48/51 — Figure 27.1 (Bulbospongiosus)"},{"q":"Which superficial smooth muscle of the scrotum contracts to wrinkle the scrotal surface?","choices":["Cremaster muscle","Ischiocavernosus","Bulbospongiosus","Dartos muscle"],"answer":3,"exp":"The dartos muscle is a superficial smooth muscle whose contraction causes wrinkling of the scrotal surface.","cite":"Slide 17 — Dartos muscle"},{"q":"The internal pudendal arteries that help supply the scrotum are branches of which vessel?","choices":["The internal iliac artery","The femoral artery","The external iliac artery","The abdominal aorta"],"answer":0,"exp":"The internal pudendal arteries are branches of the internal iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 20 — Internal pudendal arteries from internal iliac"},{"q":"The external pudendal arteries supplying the scrotum arise from which vessel?","choices":["The internal iliac artery","The femoral artery","The external iliac artery","The testicular artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The external pudendal arteries are branches of the femoral artery.","cite":"Slide 20 — External pudendal arteries from femoral artery"},{"q":"The inferior epigastric arteries that help vascularize the scrotum branch from which vessel?","choices":["The femoral artery","The internal iliac artery","The external iliac artery","The internal pudendal artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The inferior epigastric arteries are branches of the external iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 20 — Inferior epigastric arteries from external iliac"},{"q":"Which two arteries are named as blood vessels running within the spermatic cord?","choices":["Superior and inferior vesical arteries","Internal and external pudendal arteries","Deep and dorsal arteries of the penis","Deferential and testicular arteries"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spermatic cord contains the deferential artery and the testicular artery (along with the pampiniform plexus of the testicular vein).","cite":"Slide 13 — Spermatic cord: deferential artery, testicular artery"},{"q":"The network of veins in the spermatic cord that drains the testis is called the:","choices":["Pampiniform plexus","Hypogastric plexus","Prostatic plexus","Dorsal venous plexus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus of the testicular vein is the venous network within the spermatic cord.","cite":"Slide 13 — Pampiniform plexus of the testicular vein"},{"q":"Which artery lies in the center of each corpus cavernosum of the penis?","choices":["The dorsal artery of the penis","The deep artery of the penis","The internal pudendal artery","The deferential artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The deep artery of the penis lies in the center of the corpus cavernosum.","cite":"Slide 61, 64 — Deep artery of the penis in the corpora cavernosa"},{"q":"Which two nerves are named as running within the spermatic cord?","choices":["Pudendal and obturator nerves","Femoral and sciatic nerves","Ilioinguinal and genitofemoral nerves","Hypogastric and vagus nerves"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ilioinguinal nerve and the genitofemoral nerve are the nerves named within the spermatic cord.","cite":"Slide 13 — Spermatic cord nerves: ilioinguinal, genitofemoral"},{"q":"According to the lecture, the scrotum is supplied with sensory and motor nerves from all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["The hypogastric plexus","The ilioinguinal nerves","The pudendal nerves","The vagus nerve"],"answer":3,"exp":"The scrotum is supplied by the hypogastric plexus and the ilioinguinal, genitofemoral, and pudendal nerves — the vagus nerve is not listed.","cite":"Slide 21 — Scrotal innervation"},{"q":"Erection of the penis is initiated by activation of which type of nerves?","choices":["Parasympathetic nerves","Sympathetic nerves","Somatic motor nerves only","The vagus nerve"],"answer":0,"exp":"Erection begins when parasympathetic nerves are activated, causing arterial smooth muscle to relax and the erectile tissue to engorge with blood.","cite":"Slide 65 — Erection: parasympathetic nerves activated"},{"q":"During semen release, which division of the autonomic nervous system controls emission?","choices":["Parasympathetic activity","Sympathetic activity","Enteric activity","Somatic reflex only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Emission is driven by sympathetic activity, mixing sperm with semen via peristaltic smooth-muscle action in the ductus deferens, seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands.","cite":"Slide 66 — Emission: sympathetic activity"},{"q":"The reproductive system is organized into gonads, a reproductive tract, accessory glands, and external genitalia. In the male, the gonads are the:","choices":["Epididymides","Seminal glands","Testes","Prostate"],"answer":2,"exp":"The gonads are the testes, which produce gametes (sperm) and hormones.","cite":"Slide 3 — Organization of the Reproductive System"},{"q":"The two scrotal chambers are separated by which structure, seen as thickened tissue extending from the anus across the scrotum?","choices":["The scrotal septum","The tunica albuginea","The dartos fascia","The raphe of the scrotum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The raphe of the scrotum separates the two scrotal cavities and appears as thickened tissue extending from the anus, across the scrotum, and along the anterior penis.","cite":"Slide 15 — Raphe of the scrotum"},{"q":"Which serous membrane lines each scrotal cavity and reduces friction between its opposing layers?","choices":["Tunica vaginalis","Tunica albuginea","Dartos fascia","Cremasteric fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The tunica vaginalis is a serous membrane that lines each scrotal cavity and reduces friction between the opposing serous layers.","cite":"Slide 15 — Tunica vaginalis lines each cavity"},{"q":"Contraction of the cremaster muscle produces which effect?","choices":["Wrinkles the scrotal skin","Tenses the scrotal sac and pulls it closer to the body","Relaxes the arterial walls of the penis","Propels sperm into the urethra"],"answer":1,"exp":"Cremaster contraction tenses the scrotal sac and pulls it closer to the body to help maintain the proper (cooler) temperature for sperm development.","cite":"Slide 18 — Cremaster muscle"},{"q":"The fibrous connective-tissue capsule of the testis that extends inward to form septa is the:","choices":["Tunica vaginalis","Mediastinum testis","Tunica albuginea","Rete testis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The tunica albuginea is the fibrous connective-tissue lining that extends deep into the testis and forms septa.","cite":"Slide 22 — Tunica albuginea forms septa"},{"q":"The septa of the testis converge toward which region, which supports the ducts moving material toward the epididymis?","choices":["The efferent ductule","The rete testis","The lobule","The mediastinum of the testis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The septa converge toward the mediastinum of the testis, which supports the ducts that move material toward the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 22 — Mediastinum of the testis"},{"q":"Each testicular lobule contains tightly coiled structures where sperm production begins. These are the:","choices":["Seminiferous tubules","Straight tubules","Efferent ductules","Rete testis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Each lobule contains tightly coiled seminiferous tubules (each ~80 cm long) where spermatogenesis begins.","cite":"Slide 24 — Seminiferous tubules"},{"q":"Place the following in the correct order of sperm flow within the testis: seminiferous tubules → ___ → rete testis → efferent ductules.","choices":["Ejaculatory duct","Straight tubules","Ductus deferens","Ampulla"],"answer":1,"exp":"Seminiferous tubules uncoil into straight tubules, which interconnect to form the rete testis, which connects to the efferent ductules leading to the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 24 — Straight tubules → rete testis → efferent ductules"},{"q":"The interstitial endocrine cells (Leydig cells) located between the seminiferous tubules produce which hormone?","choices":["Inhibin","Androgen-binding protein","Testosterone","Luteinizing hormone"],"answer":2,"exp":"The interstitial endocrine cells (Leydig cells) produce and release testosterone.","cite":"Slide 26 — Interstitial endocrine cells (Leydig cells) produce testosterone"},{"q":"Nurse cells (Sertoli cells) maintain the blood-testis barrier, which functions to:","choices":["Increase blood flow to the testis","Secrete testosterone","Store mature sperm","Isolate the seminiferous tubules from circulation to prevent autoimmune destruction of sperm"],"answer":3,"exp":"The blood-testis barrier isolates the seminiferous tubules from circulation to prevent autoimmune destruction of sperm cells.","cite":"Slide 35 — Nurse cells maintain the blood-testis barrier"},{"q":"Which two substances are secreted by the nurse (Sertoli) cells?","choices":["Inhibin and androgen-binding protein (ABP)","Testosterone and fructose","Prostaglandins and clotting factors","Seminalplasmin and mucus"],"answer":0,"exp":"Nurse cells secrete inhibin (which controls the rate of sperm formation) and androgen-binding protein (ABP), which keeps testosterone active within the seminiferous tubules.","cite":"Slide 35 — Nurse cells secrete inhibin and ABP"},{"q":"A sperm cell's head contains chromosomes and an acrosome. The acrosome enzyme necessary for fertilization of the egg is:","choices":["Seminalplasmin","Hyaluronidase","Fructose","Inhibin"],"answer":1,"exp":"The acrosome contains enzymes including hyaluronidase, which is necessary for fertilization of the egg.","cite":"Slide 37 — Acrosome enzyme hyaluronidase"},{"q":"The middle piece of a sperm cell contains which organelles that power its movement?","choices":["Ribosomes and lysosomes","Golgi apparatus and nucleus","Mitochondria and centrioles","Acrosome and chromosomes"],"answer":2,"exp":"The middle piece (with the neck) contains mitochondria and centrioles.","cite":"Slide 37 — Middle piece: mitochondria and centrioles"},{"q":"The epididymis is divided into three parts. In which part do the coiled tubes begin to uncoil to become the ductus deferens?","choices":["Head","Body","Ampulla","Tail"],"answer":3,"exp":"In the tail of the epididymis, the tubes begin to uncoil to become the single ductus deferens.","cite":"Slide 41 — Epididymis: head, body, tail"},{"q":"Which statement about the functions of the epididymis is correct?","choices":["It stores spermatozoa and serves as a recycling center for damaged sperm","It produces 60% of semen volume","It secretes testosterone","It is where fertilization occurs"],"answer":0,"exp":"The epididymis stores spermatozoa for further maturation and acts as a recycling center for damaged spermatozoa (sperm take ~2 weeks to pass through).","cite":"Slide 43 — Functions of the epididymis"},{"q":"The penis consists of three cylindrical columns of erectile tissue. These are:","choices":["Three corpora cavernosa","Two corpora cavernosa and one corpus spongiosum","Two corpora spongiosa and one corpus cavernosum","One corpus cavernosum and one corpus spongiosum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The penis has two posterior corpora cavernosa and one anterior corpus spongiosum.","cite":"Slide 60 — erectile tissue columns"},{"q":"The corpus spongiosum of the penis surrounds the spongy urethra and its thickened proximal end forms the:","choices":["Crus of the penis","Glans penis","Bulb of the penis","Prepuce"],"answer":2,"exp":"The corpus spongiosum surrounds the spongy urethra, and its thickened proximal end forms the bulb of the penis.","cite":"Slide 61 — corpus spongiosum forms the bulb of the penis"},{"q":"Spermatogenesis (sperm formation) begins in which layer of the seminiferous tubules?","choices":["The lumen","The rete testis","The mediastinum","The outer layer"],"answer":3,"exp":"Spermatogenesis begins in the outer layer of the seminiferous tubules, where spermatogonia (stem cells) reside.","cite":"Slide 29 — spermatogenesis begins in the outer layer"},{"q":"A single primary spermatocyte undergoing meiosis gives rise to how many sperm cells?","choices":["Four","Two","One","Twenty-three"],"answer":0,"exp":"A single primary spermatocyte gives rise to a total of four sperm cells (via meiosis I → two secondary spermatocytes, then meiosis II → four spermatids).","cite":"Slide 31 — one primary spermatocyte → four sperm cells"},{"q":"The physical maturation of spermatids into sperm cells, during which they are embedded in nurse cells, is called:","choices":["Spermatogenesis","Spermiogenesis","Capacitation","Emission"],"answer":1,"exp":"Spermiogenesis is the maturation of spermatids into physically mature sperm cells while embedded in nurse (Sertoli) cells.","cite":"Slide 34 — Spermiogenesis"},{"q":"After leaving the testis, sperm are physically but not functionally mature. Where are they stored and monitored for further maturation?","choices":["The seminal gland","The prostate","The epididymis","The ejaculatory duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The epididymis stores sperm for further maturation and monitors the fluid from the seminiferous tubules; sperm take ~2 weeks to pass through.","cite":"Slide 43 — epididymis stores spermatozoa"},{"q":"Before entering the prostate gland, the ductus deferens expands into a region called the:","choices":["Bulb","Rete testis","Efferent ductule","Ampulla"],"answer":3,"exp":"Before entering the prostate, the ductus deferens expands into the ampulla, which joins the excretory duct of the seminal gland to become the ejaculatory duct.","cite":"Slide 47 — ductus deferens expands into the ampulla"},{"q":"The ampulla of the ductus deferens joins the excretory duct of the seminal gland to form which structure?","choices":["The ejaculatory duct","The membranous urethra","The efferent ductule","The prostatic ductule"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ampulla joins the excretory duct of the seminal gland to become the ejaculatory duct, which empties into the prostatic urethra.","cite":"Slide 47 — ejaculatory duct formation"},{"q":"The ejaculatory duct empties into which part of the urethra?","choices":["The membranous urethra","The prostatic urethra","The spongy urethra","The external urethral orifice"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ejaculatory duct empties into the prostatic urethra.","cite":"Slide 47 — ejaculatory duct empties into the prostatic urethra"},{"q":"During emission, sperm are mixed with semen by peristaltic smooth-muscle action in all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["The ductus deferens","The seminal glands","The epididymis head only","The prostate and bulbo-urethral glands"],"answer":2,"exp":"Emission mixes sperm with semen by peristalsis in the ductus deferens, seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands — not by the epididymis head alone.","cite":"Slide 66 — Emission structures"},{"q":"Mature sperm cells become motile only after undergoing which process, which occurs outside the epididymis?","choices":["Spermiogenesis","Emission","Meiosis","Capacitation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Mature sperm are not motile until they undergo capacitation, which happens outside the epididymis (motility begins when mixed with seminal gland secretions).","cite":"Slide 43–44 — capacitation"},{"q":"Which accessory gland produces about 60 percent of the semen volume, with fluid rich in fructose, prostaglandins, and clotting factors?","choices":["The seminal glands","The prostate","The bulbo-urethral glands","The epididymis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The seminal glands (seminal vesicles) produce about 60% of the semen volume, with a high concentration of fructose, prostaglandins, and clotting factors.","cite":"Slide 54 — The Seminal Glands"},{"q":"The prostate secretes a weakly acidic fluid making up 20–30% of semen. It contains seminalplasmin, which functions as:","choices":["An energy source for sperm","An antibiotic believed to prevent UTIs in males","A clotting factor","A lubricant for the penis tip"],"answer":1,"exp":"Seminalplasmin is an antibiotic believed to prevent urinary tract infections in males; prostatic secretions also contain enzymes that prevent sperm coagulation in the vagina.","cite":"Slide 55 — The Prostate: seminalplasmin"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) glands produce ~5% of semen volume. Their thick, sticky, alkaline mucus empties into which structure and serves what purpose?","choices":["The prostatic urethra; to coagulate semen","The ejaculatory duct; to provide fructose","The spongy urethra; to neutralize residual urinary acids and lubricate the penis tip","The ampulla; to store sperm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty into the spongy urethra (just distal to the body wall); their alkaline mucus neutralizes residual urinary acids and lubricates the tip of the penis.","cite":"Slide 56 — The Bulbo-urethral Glands"},{"q":"The male urethra is divided into three regions. Which region extends from the urinary bladder through the prostate gland?","choices":["Ejaculatory urethra","Membranous urethra","Spongy (penile) urethra","Prostatic urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"The prostatic urethra extends from the urinary bladder through the prostate gland.","cite":"Slide 50 — Prostatic urethra"},{"q":"Which region of the urethra passes through the muscular wall of the pelvic cavity, between the prostatic and spongy portions?","choices":["Membranous urethra","Prostatic urethra","Spongy urethra","Cavernous urethra"],"answer":0,"exp":"The membranous urethra passes through the muscular wall of the pelvic cavity.","cite":"Slide 50 — Membranous urethra"},{"q":"The spongy urethra, sometimes called the penile urethra, passes through which structure?","choices":["The prostate gland","The penis","The pelvic diaphragm","The seminal gland"],"answer":1,"exp":"The spongy (penile) urethra passes through the penis, within the corpus spongiosum.","cite":"Slide 50 — Spongy (penile) urethra"}]},"anatomy-gi-i-ii":{"title":"Gastrointestinal Tract I & II (Set 1)","questions":[{"q":"The digestive organs that form the continuous tube from mouth to anus are collectively called the GI tract. Which of the following is an accessory digestive organ rather than part of that tube?","choices":["Liver","Stomach","Esophagus","Small intestine"],"answer":0,"exp":"The liver is an accessory digestive organ — it does not form the GI tube but connects to it (by ducts) and assists in digestion.","cite":"'General Structure and Functions of the GI Tract' — accessory organs (Teeth, Tongue, Salivary glands, Liver, Gallbladder, Pancreas)"},{"q":"From the lumen outward, the four tunics of the GI tract wall are arranged in which order?","choices":["Serosa, muscularis, submucosa, mucosa","Mucosa, submucosa, muscularis externa, serosa","Submucosa, mucosa, serosa, muscularis","Mucosa, muscularis, submucosa, serosa"],"answer":1,"exp":"From the lumen outward the layers are mucosa, submucosa, muscularis (externa), then serosa.","cite":"'GI tract tunics' diagram (pp. 10–11)"},{"q":"The muscularis externa of the GI tract consists of which two smooth-muscle layers?","choices":["Inner longitudinal and outer circular","Two circular layers","Inner circular and outer longitudinal","Two longitudinal layers"],"answer":2,"exp":"The muscularis externa has an inner circular layer and an outer longitudinal layer.","cite":"'GI tract tunics' — Muscularis externa (Longitudinal, Circular)"},{"q":"Unlike the rest of the GI tract, the esophagus is covered by which outer layer instead of a serosa?","choices":["Submucosa","Mesentery","Peritoneum","Adventitia"],"answer":3,"exp":"The esophagus is not covered by serosa; its outer layer is adventitia (noted directly on the tunics slide).","cite":"'GI tract tunics' handwritten note — 'esophagus not covered by serosa (adventitia)'"},{"q":"The intrinsic (enteric) innervation of the GI tract is distributed in two intramural plexuses. Which pair is named in the lecture?","choices":["Myenteric and submucosal plexuses","Celiac and mesenteric plexuses","Cardiac and pulmonary plexuses","Sympathetic and parasympathetic trunks"],"answer":0,"exp":"The two intrinsic plexuses are the myenteric nerve plexus and the submucosal nerve plexus.","cite":"'GI tract tunics' — Intrinsic nerve plexuses; 'Special Features' — enteric nervous system"},{"q":"The peritoneum is a serous membrane lining the abdomen and pelvis. Its two named potential spaces are the:","choices":["Pleural and pericardial sacs","Greater sac and lesser sac","Supracolic and infracolic sacs","Right and left subphrenic sacs"],"answer":1,"exp":"The peritoneal cavity contains the greater sac and the lesser sac.","cite":"'Peritoneum' — Greater sac, Lesser sac"},{"q":"The greater omentum extends from which structure and drapes over the transverse colon and small bowel?","choices":["Lesser curvature of the stomach","Porta hepatis","Greater curvature of the stomach","Root of the mesentery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The greater omentum extends from the greater curvature of the stomach and covers the transverse colon and small bowel.","cite":"'Greater Omentum' — extends from greater curvature of stomach"},{"q":"The lesser omentum extends from the porta hepatis to the lesser curvature of the stomach and comprises which two ligaments?","choices":["Falciform and coronary ligaments","Triangular and round ligaments","Splenorenal and gastrosplenic ligaments","Hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments"],"answer":3,"exp":"The lesser omentum is made of the hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments.","cite":"'Peritoneal Reflections' — Lesser Omentum"},{"q":"The mesentery proper suspends the jejunum and ileum. Its root runs from the duodenojejunal flexure to which landmark?","choices":["Right iliac fossa","Left iliac fossa","Porta hepatis","Splenic flexure"],"answer":0,"exp":"The root of the mesentery proper runs from the duodenojejunal flexure to the right iliac fossa.","cite":"'Mesentery' — Root from duodenojejunal flexure to right iliac fossa"},{"q":"The mesentery proper carries which structures between its two peritoneal layers?","choices":["Bile and pancreatic ducts","Blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves","Ureters and gonadal vessels","Cerebrospinal fluid"],"answer":1,"exp":"Blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves run between the layers of the mesentery proper.","cite":"'Mesentery' — Blood vessels, lymphatics, nerves between layers"},{"q":"Which peritoneal fold is described as extending from the greater curvature and hanging down 'like an apron' over the abdominal viscera?","choices":["Lesser omentum","Transverse mesocolon","Greater omentum","Falciform ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The greater omentum hangs like an apron from the greater curvature over the bowel.","cite":"'Omenta' cadaver slide — greater omentum 'hangs like apron'"},{"q":"The lateral walls of the oral cavity are formed by the cheeks, which contain which muscle?","choices":["Masseter","Mylohyoid","Orbicularis oris","Buccinator"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cheeks forming the lateral walls contain the buccinator muscles.","cite":"'Oral Cavity' — lateral walls formed by cheeks, contain buccinator muscles"},{"q":"The lips (labia) are covered by which type of epithelium and contain which muscle?","choices":["Keratinized stratified squamous ET; orbicularis oris","Nonkeratinized ET; buccinator","Simple columnar ET; mylohyoid","Pseudostratified ET; masseter"],"answer":0,"exp":"The lips contain the orbicularis oris muscle and are covered by keratinized stratified squamous epithelium.","cite":"'Oral Cavity' — Lips: orbicularis oris, keratinized stratified squamous ET"},{"q":"The floor (inferior surface) of the oral cavity is formed by the tongue and which muscle covered with mucosa?","choices":["Buccinator muscle","Mylohyoid muscle","Masseter muscle","Digastric muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The floor of the oral cavity is formed by the tongue and the mylohyoid muscle covered with mucosa.","cite":"'Oral Cavity (mouth)' — floor: tongue and mylohyoid muscle"},{"q":"The tongue is formed from skeletal muscle and manipulates food to form what during chewing?","choices":["Colloid","The chyme","The bolus","Feces"],"answer":2,"exp":"The tongue mixes ingested materials and forms the bolus, a globular mass of partially digested material.","cite":"'Tongue' — forms the bolus"},{"q":"Which pair of salivary glands is the largest and lies anterior and inferior to the ear, partially overlying the masseter?","choices":["Submandibular glands","Lingual glands","Sublingual glands","Parotid glands"],"answer":3,"exp":"The parotid glands are the largest salivary glands, located anterior/inferior to the ear and overlying the masseter, with a close relationship to the facial nerve.","cite":"'The Parotid Glands'"},{"q":"The parotid gland empties into the oral cavity by way of which duct?","choices":["Stensen's duct","Wharton's duct","Duct of Wirsung","Bartholin's duct"],"answer":0,"exp":"The parotid gland opens by way of the parotid (Stensen's) duct into the oral cavity.","cite":"'The Parotid Glands' — opens by way of Stensen's duct"},{"q":"The esophagus is described in the lecture as having which three portions along its course?","choices":["Cardiac, fundic, pyloric","Cervical, mediastinal, abdominal","Ascending, transverse, descending","Superior, descending, horizontal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The esophagus has cervical, mediastinal (thoracic), and abdominal portions.","cite":"'Esophagus' — Portions: Cervical, Mediastinal, Abdominal"},{"q":"The esophagus passes through the diaphragm at the esophageal hiatus at which vertebral level?","choices":["T8","T12","T10","L1"],"answer":2,"exp":"The esophagus passes through the diaphragm at the esophageal hiatus at the T10 level, terminating at about T11.","cite":"'Esophageal Relationships' (T10); 'Esophagus' — Diaphragm (T10), Termination (T11)"},{"q":"The esophageal mucosa is lined by which epithelium?","choices":["Simple columnar epithelium","Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The esophageal mucosa is lined by nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium.","cite":"'Esophagus' — Histology: Mucosa nonkeratinized stratified squamous ep."},{"q":"The superior esophageal sphincter, located where the pharynx and esophagus meet, is composed of which muscle type?","choices":["Skeletal muscle (cricopharyngeus)","Circular smooth muscle","Cardiac muscle","Elastic connective tissue"],"answer":0,"exp":"The superior esophageal sphincter is skeletal muscle — the cricopharyngeus — where the pharynx and esophagus meet.","cite":"'Esophagus' — Superior esophageal sphincter: skeletal muscle, cricopharyngeus"},{"q":"The inferior esophageal (cardiac) sphincter is described as circular smooth muscle whose function is assisted by which structure, since it is 'not a true sphincter'?","choices":["The liver","The diaphragm","The transverse colon","The greater omentum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The inferior/cardiac sphincter is circular smooth muscle that is not a true sphincter; its function is helped by the diaphragm.","cite":"'Esophagus' — Inferior esophageal sphincter, function helped by diaphragm"},{"q":"Which of the following is the most superior region of the stomach?","choices":["Cardia","Body","Fundus","Pyloric antrum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The fundus is the most superior region of the stomach.","cite":"'The Stomach' — Regions: Cardia, Fundus (most superior), Body, Pyloric"},{"q":"The pyloric region of the stomach is subdivided into which parts?","choices":["Greater and lesser curvatures","Fundus and body","Cardia and notch","Antrum and canal (with the pyloric sphincter)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pyloric region includes the antrum and the canal, ending at the pyloric sphincter.","cite":"'The Stomach' — Pyloric: Antrum, Canal, Sphincter"},{"q":"The two curvatures of the stomach are the:","choices":["Greater and lesser curvatures","Anterior and posterior curvatures","Superior and inferior curvatures","Medial and lateral curvatures"],"answer":0,"exp":"The stomach has a greater curvature and a lesser curvature.","cite":"'The Stomach' — Curvatures: Greater, Lesser"},{"q":"Which mucosal specialization of the stomach interior consists of longitudinal folds that allow the stomach to expand?","choices":["Plicae circulares","Rugae","Haustra","Villi"],"answer":1,"exp":"Rugae are the longitudinal mucosal folds of the stomach interior (along with the gastric canal, pits, and glands).","cite":"'Stomach Interior' — Mucosal specializations: Rugae, gastric canal, pits, glands"},{"q":"The greater omentum attaches along the greater curvature of the stomach. The lesser omentum attaches along which stomach border?","choices":["Greater curvature","Anterior surface","Lesser curvature","Pyloric antrum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser omentum attaches along the lesser curvature of the stomach (extending to the porta hepatis).","cite":"'Peritoneal Reflections' — lesser omentum to lesser curvature; 'The Stomach' — curvatures"},{"q":"The small intestine extends from the pylorus of the stomach to which structure of the large intestine?","choices":["Sigmoid colon","Splenic flexure","Rectum","Cecum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The small intestine extends from the pylorus of the stomach to the cecum of the large intestine.","cite":"'Small Intestine' — extends from pylorus to cecum"},{"q":"Which segment is the first part of the small intestine, is approximately 25 cm (10 inches) long, and contains the major duodenal papilla?","choices":["Duodenum","Jejunum","Ileum","Cecum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The duodenum is the first segment (~25 cm), originating at the pyloric sphincter and containing the major duodenal papilla.","cite":"'Small Intestine' — The duodenum"},{"q":"The small intestine terminates at the ileocecal valve, a sphincter located at the end of which segment?","choices":["Duodenum","Ileum","Jejunum","Pylorus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ileum is the last region of the small intestine and terminates at the ileocecal valve.","cite":"'Small Intestine' — The ileum terminates at the ileocecal valve"},{"q":"The plicae circulares of the small intestine are described as:","choices":["Temporary folds that flatten when the intestine fills","Longitudinal folds identical to gastric rugae","Permanent transverse folds that do not disappear when the intestine fills","Sacculations formed by muscle tone"],"answer":2,"exp":"Plicae circulares are permanent transverse folds that do not disappear when the small intestine fills.","cite":"'Plicae' — permanent, do not disappear when small intestine fills"},{"q":"Which portion of the duodenum is the shortest, retroperitoneal, and (for its first part / duodenal cap) intraperitoneal?","choices":["Ascending part","Descending part","Transverse (horizontal) part","Superior part"],"answer":3,"exp":"The superior part is the shortest and widest; its first portion, the duodenal cap (ampulla), is intraperitoneal, while the rest of the duodenum is retroperitoneal.","cite":"'Duodenum' — Superior part / Duodenal cap"},{"q":"Distinguishing features of the jejunum compared with the ileum include which of the following?","choices":["Larger diameter, thicker walls, and more prominent plicae circulares","Smaller diameter and thinner walls","Presence of numerous Peyer's patches","Location mainly in the right lower quadrant"],"answer":0,"exp":"The jejunum has a larger diameter, thicker walls, more plicae circulares, and is more vascular; it lies mostly in the left upper quadrant.","cite":"'Jejunum' — larger diameter, thicker walls, plicae circulares, more vascular"},{"q":"The large intestine is composed of which four segments?","choices":["Duodenum, jejunum, ileum, cecum","Cecum, colon, rectum, anal canal","Fundus, body, antrum, pylorus","Ascending, transverse, descending, sigmoid only"],"answer":1,"exp":"The large intestine is composed of the cecum, colon, rectum, and anal canal.","cite":"'Large Intestine' — cecum, colon, rectum, anal canal"},{"q":"Which three anatomic specializations are characteristic of the colon but absent in the rectum and appendix?","choices":["Villi, plicae, rugae","Peyer's patches, crypts, microvilli","Taeniae coli, haustra (sacculations), and omental appendices","Fundus, antrum, pylorus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The colon shows three taeniae coli, haustra (sacculations), and omental appendices — features absent in the rectum and appendix.","cite":"'Large Intestine' — Taeniae coli (3), sacculations (haustra), omental appendices"},{"q":"The appendix (vermiform appendix) is a slender hollow appendage anchored by which structure and dominated by which tissue?","choices":["Phrenicocolic ligament; villi","Transverse mesocolon; goblet cells","Falciform ligament; smooth muscle","Mesoappendix; lymphoid nodules"],"answer":3,"exp":"The appendix is fixed by the mesoappendix and is dominated by lymphoid nodules (a lymphoid organ).","cite":"'Cecum and Appendix'; 'The Appendix' — mesoappendix, lymphoid nodules"},{"q":"The ascending colon terminates at which flexure?","choices":["Right colic (hepatic) flexure","Left colic (splenic) flexure","Duodenojejunal flexure","Sigmoid flexure"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ascending colon terminates at the right colic (hepatic) flexure.","cite":"'Ascending Colon' — terminates at right colic (hepatic) flexure"},{"q":"Which segment of the colon is described as the most mobile and longest, is intraperitoneal, and is suspended by the transverse mesocolon?","choices":["Ascending colon","Transverse colon","Descending colon","Sigmoid colon"],"answer":1,"exp":"The transverse colon is the most mobile and longest portion, is intraperitoneal, and is suspended by the transverse mesocolon between the right and left colic flexures.","cite":"'Transverse Colon'"},{"q":"The liver is the largest visceral organ and largest gland. It is completely covered by which capsule?","choices":["Gerota's fascia","Bowman's capsule","Glisson's capsule","Tenon's capsule"],"answer":2,"exp":"The liver is completely covered by Glisson's capsule (with incomplete peritoneal covering).","cite":"'The Liver' — completely covered by Glisson's Capsule"},{"q":"The liver receives a triple blood supply. Which vessel delivers the inflow of blood needing metabolic processing?","choices":["Hepatic artery","Cystic artery","Hepatic veins","Portal vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The portal vein delivers inflow of blood needing metabolic processing to the liver.","cite":"'Liver triple blood supply' — Portal vein"},{"q":"The caudate lobe of the liver lies between the inferior vena cava and which structure?","choices":["Ligamentum venosum","Ligamentum teres","Gallbladder","Falciform ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The caudate lobe lies between the inferior vena cava and the ligamentum venosum.","cite":"'Lobes of the Liver' — Caudate: between IVC and ligamentum venosum"},{"q":"The quadrate lobe of the liver is located between which two structures?","choices":["The IVC and the ligamentum venosum","The gallbladder and the ligamentum teres","The falciform and coronary ligaments","The porta hepatis and the bare area"],"answer":1,"exp":"The quadrate lobe lies between the gallbladder and the ligamentum teres (round ligament).","cite":"'Lobes of the Liver' — Quadrate: between gall bladder and ligamentum teres"},{"q":"The portal triad — found at the corners of a liver lobule — consists of branches of which three structures?","choices":["Hepatic artery, cystic duct, and central vein","Central vein, hepatic vein, and lymphatic","Portal vein, hepatic artery, and bile duct","Portal vein, hepatic vein, and pancreatic duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The portal triad consists of a branch of the portal vein, hepatic artery, and bile duct.","cite":"'Histology of the liver' — Portal triad: portal vein, hepatic artery, bile duct"},{"q":"The pancreas is described as retroperitoneal with which regions?","choices":["Cardia, fundus, body, pylorus","Fundus, body, neck","Superior, descending, horizontal, ascending","Head, uncinate process, neck, body, and tail"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreas has a head, uncinate process, neck, body, and tail.","cite":"'The Pancreas' — Regions: Head, Uncinate process, Neck, body, tail"},{"q":"The main pancreatic duct is also known by which eponym?","choices":["Duct of Wirsung","Duct of Santorini","Duct of Wharton","Duct of Stensen"],"answer":0,"exp":"The principal (main) pancreatic duct is the duct of Wirsung; the accessory duct is the duct of Santorini.","cite":"'Pancreas' — Principal pancreatic duct (of Wirsung), accessory (of Santorini)"},{"q":"The pancreatic islets, the endocrine tissue of the pancreas, make up approximately what fraction of pancreatic cells?","choices":["About 25%","About 1%","About 50%","About 75%"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pancreatic islets are scattered endocrine tissue making up about 1% of pancreatic cells.","cite":"'Pancreatic Islets' — scattered (1% of pancreatic cells)"},{"q":"The celiac trunk arises from the aorta at the aortic hiatus and gives which three branches?","choices":["Right gastric, cystic, and gastroduodenal arteries","Superior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric, and renal arteries","Left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries","Splenic, superior mesenteric, and left colic arteries"],"answer":2,"exp":"The celiac trunk branches into the left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries.","cite":"'Arterial Supply of the Abdomen — The Celiac Trunk'"},{"q":"The common hepatic artery continues as the proper hepatic artery and also gives off which branch that descends toward the duodenum and pancreas?","choices":["Left gastric artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Splenic artery","Gastroduodenal artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"The common hepatic artery gives off the gastroduodenal artery (and the proper hepatic continues to the liver, giving right gastric and right/left hepatic branches).","cite":"'Common Hepatic Artery' — Proper hepatic, Right gastric, Gastroduodenal, Supraduodenal"},{"q":"Which artery supplying the esophagus is a branch of the celiac artery?","choices":["Left gastric branch of the celiac artery","Inferior thyroid branch of the thyrocervical trunk","Bronchial arteries","Internal thoracic artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The left gastric branch of the celiac artery supplies the (abdominal) esophagus.","cite":"'Esophagus' — arterial supply (left gastric branch of the celiac artery)"},{"q":"The hepatic veins that drain the liver empty directly into which vessel?","choices":["Portal vein","Inferior vena cava","Splenic vein","Superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"The hepatic veins drain into the inferior vena cava, carrying outflow toward the right atrium.","cite":"'Histology of the liver' — Hepatic veins drain into inferior vena cava; 'Liver triple blood supply'"}]},"renal-1":{"title":"Renal Physiology I","questions":[{"q":"The detrusor muscle is composed primarily of:","choices":["Skeletal muscle","Cardiac muscle","Smooth muscle","Elastic connective tissue"],"answer":2,"exp":"The detrusor is smooth muscle — it contracts involuntarily under parasympathetic (pelvic nerve) control to empty the bladder.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The primary function of the detrusor muscle is to:","choices":["Close the urethra","Contract the bladder during urination","Relax the bladder during filling","Produce urine"],"answer":1,"exp":"Detrusor contraction generates the pressure that expels urine during micturition.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The trigone is located:","choices":["At the dome of the bladder","Between the ureter openings and urethra","Inside the renal pelvis","Within the ureter"],"answer":1,"exp":"The trigone is the smooth triangular region bounded by the two ureteral orifices and the internal urethral opening.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which sphincter is under voluntary control?","choices":["Internal urethral sphincter","External urethral sphincter","Internal anal sphincter","Detrusor muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The external urethral sphincter is skeletal muscle controlled voluntarily via the somatic pudendal nerve.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Parasympathetic fibers supplying the bladder travel in the:","choices":["Pudendal nerve","Pelvic nerve","Hypogastric nerve","Vagus nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"Parasympathetic (S2–S4) fibers reach the bladder via the pelvic nerve to drive detrusor contraction and voiding.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The pelvic nerve originates from:","choices":["T5-T9","L1-L2","S2-S4","C5-C8"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pelvic splanchnic (parasympathetic) nerves arise from sacral segments S2–S4.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Sympathetic stimulation of the bladder primarily promotes:","choices":["Bladder emptying","Detrusor contraction","Urine storage","External sphincter relaxation"],"answer":2,"exp":"Sympathetic tone (hypogastric, T11–L2) relaxes the detrusor and contracts the internal sphincter — promoting storage.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which nerve controls the external urethral sphincter?","choices":["Pelvic","Vagus","Pudendal","Hypogastric"],"answer":2,"exp":"The somatic pudendal nerve provides voluntary control of the external (skeletal-muscle) sphincter.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The hypogastric nerve primarily:","choices":["Contracts the detrusor","Relaxes the detrusor","Detects stretch","Contracts skeletal muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The sympathetic hypogastric nerve relaxes the detrusor and closes the internal sphincter to favor filling/storage.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Loss of pudendal nerve function would MOST directly impair:","choices":["Glomerular filtration","Voluntary control of urination","Kidney blood flow","RAAS activation"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pudendal nerve controls the voluntary external sphincter; losing it impairs voluntary continence/voiding control.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Bladder stretch receptors send sensory information primarily through the:","choices":["Hypogastric nerve","Pelvic nerve","Pudendal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"Afferent stretch signals from the bladder wall travel centrally via the pelvic nerve, triggering the micturition reflex.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which pairing is CORRECT?","choices":["Pelvic = storage","Hypogastric = urination","Pudendal = voluntary control","Vagus = bladder contraction"],"answer":2,"exp":"Pudendal = voluntary control (external sphincter). Pelvic = voiding, hypogastric = storage; the vagus does not innervate the bladder.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The micturition reflex begins when:","choices":["Blood pressure rises","Stretch receptors in the bladder wall are activated","Plasma osmolarity falls","ADH is released"],"answer":1,"exp":"Bladder filling stretches wall receptors, whose afferent signals initiate the micturition reflex.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The micturition reflex is primarily a:","choices":["Cortical reflex","Brainstem reflex","Autonomic spinal reflex","Somatic reflex"],"answer":2,"exp":"It is fundamentally an autonomic spinal cord reflex (S2–S4), modulated by higher centers.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The spinal cord segments involved are:","choices":["C5-C8","T1-T4","L1-L2","S2-S4"],"answer":3,"exp":"The micturition reflex is centered on sacral segments S2–S4.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"During normal urination, the detrusor muscle:","choices":["Relaxes","Contracts","Does not change","Contracts only voluntarily"],"answer":1,"exp":"Detrusor contraction raises bladder pressure to expel urine during voiding.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The internal urethral sphincter:","choices":["Contracts during urination","Relaxes during urination","Is skeletal muscle","Is controlled by the pudendal nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The smooth-muscle internal sphincter relaxes during voiding to allow urine outflow.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The external urethral sphincter is relaxed by:","choices":["Pelvic nerves","Pudendal reflex inhibition","Hypogastric stimulation","RAAS activation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Voluntary voiding involves inhibition of pudendal (somatic) drive, relaxing the external sphincter.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which brain region normally inhibits the micturition reflex until an appropriate time?","choices":["Cerebral cortex","Cerebellum","Hypothalamus","Medulla only"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cerebral cortex exerts voluntary inhibitory control, holding the reflex in check until socially appropriate.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Normally, after complete urination, approximately how much urine remains?","choices":["0 mL","5-10 mL","100 mL","250 mL"],"answer":1,"exp":"Residual volume after normal voiding is minimal — roughly 5–10 mL.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Increasing abdominal pressure voluntarily helps initiate urination by:","choices":["Lowering bladder pressure","Stimulating stretch receptors","Closing the urethra","Activating sympathetic nerves"],"answer":1,"exp":"A Valsalva/abdominal squeeze raises bladder pressure and stretches wall receptors, reinforcing the reflex.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which event occurs FIRST?","choices":["External sphincter relaxes","Stretch receptors activate","Detrusor contracts","Urine exits urethra"],"answer":1,"exp":"Stretch receptor activation is the trigger — it precedes detrusor contraction and sphincter relaxation.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Failure of voluntary relaxation of the external sphincter would MOST likely result in:","choices":["Polyuria","Urinary retention","Increased GFR","Proteinuria"],"answer":1,"exp":"If the external sphincter cannot relax, outflow is obstructed and urine is retained.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The micturition reflex becomes stronger as:","choices":["Blood pressure rises","Bladder filling increases","Plasma sodium rises","Plasma glucose rises"],"answer":1,"exp":"Greater filling means more stretch-receptor firing, progressively strengthening the reflex.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Glomerular filtration is:","choices":["Reabsorption into blood","Secretion into tubules","Filtration of plasma into Bowman's capsule","Excretion of urine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Filtration moves a protein-free plasma ultrafiltrate from glomerular capillaries into Bowman's capsule.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Normal GFR is closest to:","choices":["25 mL/min","75 mL/min","125 mL/min","500 mL/min"],"answer":2,"exp":"Normal GFR is about 125 mL/min (~180 L/day).","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Approximately how much filtrate is produced each day?","choices":["2 L","20 L","180 L","500 L"],"answer":2,"exp":"~125 mL/min × 1440 min ≈ 180 L of filtrate per day, over 99% of which is reabsorbed.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which substance should normally NOT appear in glomerular filtrate?","choices":["Glucose","Sodium","Albumin","Water"],"answer":2,"exp":"Albumin is large and negatively charged, so it is normally excluded from the filtrate.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The glomerular filtration barrier consists of all EXCEPT:","choices":["Fenestrated endothelium","Basement membrane","Podocytes","Mesangial cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"The barrier = fenestrated endothelium + basement membrane + podocyte slits. Mesangial cells provide support, not a filtration layer.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Podocytes primarily function to:","choices":["Produce renin","Form filtration slits","Produce erythropoietin","Reabsorb glucose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Podocyte foot processes interdigitate to form filtration slits (with slit diaphragms), the final size barrier.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Albumin is minimally filtered because it is:","choices":["Too small","Positively charged","Negatively charged","Lipid soluble"],"answer":2,"exp":"Beyond size, albumin's negative charge is repelled by the negatively charged basement membrane.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Mesangial cells:","choices":["Form filtration slits","Are part of the filtration barrier","Provide structural support and contractile function","Produce urine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Mesangial cells support the glomerular tuft and contract to modulate surface area available for filtration.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which equation correctly describes GFR?","choices":["GFR = PG − PB","GFR = Kf × Net Filtration Pressure","GFR = BP × HR","GFR = RBF × FF"],"answer":1,"exp":"GFR = Kf × NFP, where Kf is the filtration coefficient and NFP is the net filtration pressure.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Kf represents:","choices":["Blood flow","Permeability × Surface Area","Pressure gradient","Oncotic pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Kf (filtration coefficient) = capillary permeability × available surface area.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which substance is considered the gold standard for measuring GFR?","choices":["Creatinine","Glucose","Inulin","Albumin"],"answer":2,"exp":"Inulin is freely filtered and neither reabsorbed nor secreted, making its clearance equal to GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Creatinine clearance slightly:","choices":["Underestimates GFR","Equals GFR exactly","Overestimates GFR","Has no relation to GFR"],"answer":2,"exp":"A small amount of creatinine is secreted by the tubules, so its clearance slightly overestimates true GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Filtration fraction equals:","choices":["GFR/RPF","RPF/GFR","GFR/RBF","RBF/GFR"],"answer":0,"exp":"Filtration fraction = GFR ÷ renal plasma flow (normally ~0.2).","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Normal filtration fraction is approximately:","choices":["5%","20%","50%","80%"],"answer":1,"exp":"About 20% of renal plasma flow is filtered at the glomerulus.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The clearance equation is:","choices":["U/P","UV/P","VP/U","PU/V"],"answer":1,"exp":"Clearance = (U × V) ÷ P, where U = urine concentration, V = urine flow rate, P = plasma concentration.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which pressure PROMOTES filtration?","choices":["Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure","Plasma oncotic pressure","Glomerular hydrostatic pressure","Capsular oncotic pressure"],"answer":2,"exp":"Glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure (PG) is the main force driving fluid out into Bowman's space.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which pressure OPPOSES filtration?","choices":["PG","PB","πB","Kf"],"answer":1,"exp":"Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure (PB) pushes back against filtration, along with plasma oncotic pressure.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Bowman's capsule oncotic pressure is normally:","choices":["High","Moderate","Approximately zero","Equal to plasma oncotic pressure"],"answer":2,"exp":"Because filtrate is normally protein-free, capsular oncotic pressure (πB) is ~0.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Increasing glomerular hydrostatic pressure causes:","choices":["Lower GFR","Higher GFR","No change","Lower RPF only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Raising PG increases the net filtration pressure, increasing GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Increasing Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure causes:","choices":["Increased GFR","Decreased GFR","Increased FF","Increased RPF"],"answer":1,"exp":"Higher PB opposes filtration, lowering net filtration pressure and GFR (e.g., in obstruction).","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Increasing plasma protein concentration will:","choices":["Increase GFR","Decrease GFR","Not affect GFR","Increase filtration fraction"],"answer":1,"exp":"Higher plasma oncotic pressure opposes filtration, reducing GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Constriction of the afferent arteriole causes:","choices":["Increased GFR","Decreased GFR","Increased PG","Increased FF"],"answer":1,"exp":"Afferent constriction reduces blood flow into the glomerulus, lowering PG and therefore GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Mild efferent constriction:","choices":["Usually increases GFR","Eliminates filtration","Lowers PG","Decreases FF"],"answer":0,"exp":"Mild efferent constriction backs up pressure in the glomerulus, raising PG and increasing GFR (and FF).","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Severe efferent constriction eventually:","choices":["Raises GFR indefinitely","Decreases GFR because oncotic pressure rises","Has no effect","Eliminates plasma proteins"],"answer":1,"exp":"With severe efferent constriction, blood flow slows so much that oncotic pressure rises along the capillary, opposing filtration and lowering GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which determinant of GFR is under the greatest physiological control?","choices":["Kf","PG","PB","πB"],"answer":1,"exp":"Glomerular hydrostatic pressure (PG) is most tightly regulated via afferent/efferent arteriolar tone.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The myogenic mechanism responds primarily to:","choices":["Plasma sodium","Increased arterial pressure","Plasma potassium","ADH"],"answer":1,"exp":"When arterial pressure rises, vascular smooth muscle stretches and reflexively contracts (myogenic response), stabilizing flow.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The macula densa senses:","choices":["Oxygen","Potassium","Sodium chloride","Glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"Macula densa cells in the early distal tubule sense NaCl delivery, the signal for tubuloglomerular feedback.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"High NaCl delivery to the macula densa causes:","choices":["Renin release","Afferent constriction","Efferent dilation","Increased GFR"],"answer":1,"exp":"High NaCl triggers ATP/adenosine release, constricting the afferent arteriole to lower GFR back toward normal.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Low NaCl at the macula densa stimulates:","choices":["ATP release","Renin release","ANP release","ADH release"],"answer":1,"exp":"Low NaCl delivery signals the JG cells to release renin, activating RAAS to restore perfusion.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The juxtaglomerular apparatus consists primarily of:","choices":["Podocytes and mesangial cells","Macula densa and juxtaglomerular cells","Bowman's capsule and glomerulus","Collecting duct and loop of Henle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The JGA = macula densa (distal tubule) + juxtaglomerular (granular/renin) cells of the afferent arteriole.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"RAAS primarily acts to:","choices":["Lower GFR","Maintain GFR during low perfusion","Increase urine production","Decrease blood pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"RAAS defends perfusion and GFR when pressure falls — via vasoconstriction, aldosterone, and efferent constriction.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"ANP generally:","choices":["Decreases filtration","Increases GFR","Increases sympathetic tone","Releases renin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Atrial natriuretic peptide dilates the afferent arteriole (and constricts efferent), raising GFR and promoting natriuresis.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Sympathetic stimulation of the kidney generally:","choices":["Raises GFR","Lowers GFR","Has no effect","Eliminates autoregulation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Strong renal sympathetic activity constricts afferent arterioles, reducing renal blood flow and GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Renal prostaglandins primarily:","choices":["Destroy nephrons","Protect renal blood flow","Block filtration","Increase albumin filtration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Prostaglandins vasodilate to preserve renal blood flow, especially during RAAS/sympathetic activation — why NSAIDs can harm the kidney.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The kidneys receive approximately what percentage of cardiac output?","choices":["5%","10%","22%","50%"],"answer":2,"exp":"The kidneys receive about 20–25% of cardiac output despite their small mass.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Renal blood flow is determined by:","choices":["Pressure gradient ÷ Resistance","Pressure × Resistance","GFR × FF","CO × BP"],"answer":0,"exp":"Flow = pressure gradient ÷ resistance (Ohm's law applied to the renal circulation).","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which arteriole enters the glomerulus?","choices":["Efferent","Afferent","Interlobar","Arcuate"],"answer":1,"exp":"The afferent arteriole carries blood into the glomerular capillary tuft.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"Which arteriole exits the glomerulus?","choices":["Afferent","Efferent","Segmental","Interlobular"],"answer":1,"exp":"The efferent arteriole drains the glomerulus and leads to the peritubular capillaries/vasa recta.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"The primary purpose of renal autoregulation is to maintain:","choices":["Constant urine color","Stable GFR despite changing blood pressure","Constant plasma glucose","Constant sodium intake"],"answer":1,"exp":"Autoregulation (myogenic + tubuloglomerular feedback) keeps GFR and RBF stable across a wide MAP range.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"A patient has nephrotic syndrome with damage to the filtration barrier. Which finding is MOST likely?","choices":["Albuminuria","Glycosuria only","RBC destruction","Increased renin production"],"answer":0,"exp":"A damaged barrier lets albumin through — the hallmark albuminuria/proteinuria of nephrotic syndrome.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"},{"q":"A patient has severe dehydration. Renal perfusion decreases, NaCl delivery to the macula densa decreases, and renin is released. Which physiological response helps preserve GFR?","choices":["Afferent dilation with no hormonal response","Increased Angiotensin II causing preferential efferent arteriolar constriction","Increased ANP release","Increased Bowman's capsule pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Angiotensin II preferentially constricts the EFFERENT arteriole, backing up glomerular pressure to preserve GFR when perfusion falls — the key integrative concept.","cite":"Renal Physiology I lecture"}]},"renal-2-comprehensive":{"title":"Renal II Comprehensive","questions":[{"q":"Which nephron segment is responsible for the majority of reabsorption of filtered water and sodium?","choices":["Thick ascending limb","Early distal tubule","Proximal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The PCT reabsorbs ~65% of filtered Na⁺ and water — the bulk workhorse of reabsorption.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Approximately what percentage of filtered sodium is reabsorbed by the proximal convoluted tubule?","choices":["10%","25%","40%","65%"],"answer":3,"exp":"About 65% of filtered sodium is reabsorbed in the PCT.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which substance is almost completely reabsorbed in the proximal convoluted tubule under normal physiological conditions?","choices":["Potassium","Glucose","Creatinine","Urea"],"answer":1,"exp":"Glucose is nearly 100% reabsorbed in the PCT (via SGLT2/SGLT1) up to the transport maximum.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The descending limb of the Loop of Henle is characterized by:","choices":["High NaCl permeability","High water permeability","Active sodium transport","Complete impermeability to water"],"answer":1,"exp":"The descending limb is highly water-permeable but nearly impermeable to solutes — water leaves, concentrating the fluid.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"As tubular fluid travels down the descending limb, it becomes:","choices":["More dilute","More concentrated","Isotonic to plasma throughout","Protein rich"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water exits into the hyperosmotic medulla, so the fluid becomes progressively more concentrated.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Why does water leave the descending limb?","choices":["Active transport pumps water outward","Sodium is actively transported out","The surrounding medulla is hyperosmotic","ADH directly pumps water outward"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hyperosmotic medullary interstitium osmotically draws water out of the water-permeable descending limb.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The thick ascending limb is unique because it:","choices":["Is highly permeable to water","Performs glomerular filtration","Actively transports Na⁺, K⁺, and Cl⁻","Secretes renin"],"answer":2,"exp":"The TAL actively reabsorbs Na⁺, K⁺, and Cl⁻ via NKCC2 while remaining impermeable to water.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The transporter primarily responsible for sodium, potassium, and chloride reabsorption in the thick ascending limb is:","choices":["ENaC","NKCC2","NCC","ROMK"],"answer":1,"exp":"NKCC2 (Na-K-2Cl cotransporter) drives salt reabsorption in the TAL — the target of loop diuretics.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Why is the thick ascending limb called the diluting segment?","choices":["It secretes water","Water leaves faster than sodium","Sodium leaves while water cannot follow","Glucose is reabsorbed"],"answer":2,"exp":"Salt is actively reabsorbed but the segment is water-impermeable, so tubular fluid becomes dilute (hypo-osmotic).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which nephron segment contains the macula densa?","choices":["Proximal tubule","Thin descending limb","Early distal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The macula densa sits in the early distal convoluted tubule, where the tubule contacts its own glomerulus.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The major sodium transporter found in the early distal convoluted tubule is:","choices":["NKCC2","ENaC","NCC","GLUT2"],"answer":2,"exp":"The NCC (Na-Cl cotransporter) reabsorbs sodium in the early DCT — the target of thiazide diuretics.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Parathyroid hormone primarily increases calcium reabsorption in the:","choices":["PCT","Thick ascending limb","Early distal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"PTH stimulates calcium reabsorption in the early DCT (via TRPV5 channels).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The collecting duct becomes permeable to water primarily in response to:","choices":["Aldosterone","ANP","ADH","Renin"],"answer":2,"exp":"ADH inserts aquaporin-2 channels into the collecting duct, making it water-permeable.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Without ADH, the collecting duct produces urine that is:","choices":["Highly concentrated","Small in volume","Dilute and high volume","Rich in protein"],"answer":2,"exp":"No ADH means no aquaporins, so water stays in the tubule — dilute, high-volume urine (as in diabetes insipidus).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which nephron segment makes the final adjustment in urine composition?","choices":["Glomerulus","PCT","Descending limb","Collecting duct"],"answer":3,"exp":"The collecting duct fine-tunes final water, sodium, potassium, and acid–base balance under hormonal control.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The primary function of the macula densa is to monitor:","choices":["Potassium","Plasma glucose","NaCl delivery","Plasma proteins"],"answer":2,"exp":"Macula densa cells sense NaCl delivery in the distal tubule, driving tubuloglomerular feedback and renin control.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Juxtaglomerular (granular) cells primarily release:","choices":["ADH","Aldosterone","Renin","ANP"],"answer":2,"exp":"JG (granular) cells of the afferent arteriole synthesize and release renin.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Low NaCl delivery to the macula densa results in:","choices":["Suppression of renin","Increased renin release","Increased ANP","Decreased sympathetic activity"],"answer":1,"exp":"Low NaCl signals low perfusion, so the macula densa promotes renin release to activate RAAS.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Extraglomerular mesangial cells primarily function in:","choices":["Glucose reabsorption","Communication between nephron structures","Urine concentration","Potassium secretion"],"answer":1,"exp":"Extraglomerular mesangial cells relay signals between the macula densa and the arterioles/JG cells.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The juxtaglomerular apparatus is primarily involved in regulating:","choices":["Acid secretion","Blood pressure and GFR","Protein synthesis","Erythropoiesis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The JGA regulates blood pressure and GFR through renin release and tubuloglomerular feedback.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient becomes severely dehydrated after running a marathon. Which hormone will increase FIRST to conserve water?","choices":["ANP","ADH","Insulin","Calcitonin"],"answer":1,"exp":"ADH responds rapidly to rising plasma osmolality, promoting immediate water reabsorption.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient has syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion (SIADH). Compared with normal, the urine would be expected to be:","choices":["Dilute with high volume","Concentrated with low volume","Protein rich","Glucose rich"],"answer":1,"exp":"Excess ADH drives maximal water reabsorption — concentrated, low-volume urine (with dilutional hyponatremia).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A mutation makes the thick ascending limb permeable to water. Which physiological process would be MOST impaired?","choices":["Glomerular filtration","Countercurrent multiplication","Renin release","Calcium secretion"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water leaking from the TAL would collapse the medullary gradient, crippling countercurrent multiplication.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient has damage to the proximal convoluted tubule. Which finding would be MOST likely?","choices":["Increased glucose loss in urine","Complete inability to secrete potassium","Failure of ADH release","Increased renin secretion"],"answer":0,"exp":"PCT damage impairs glucose reabsorption, so glucose spills into the urine (glycosuria).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient has a lesion that destroys the thick ascending limb. Which combination of findings is MOST likely?","choices":["Increased ability to concentrate urine and increased NKCC2 activity","Loss of medullary osmotic gradient and difficulty concentrating urine","Increased glucose reabsorption and increased GFR","Increased ADH secretion with highly concentrated urine despite loss of the loop"],"answer":1,"exp":"Without the TAL there is no salt pumping to build the medullary gradient, so the kidney cannot concentrate urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"ADH is synthesized primarily in the:","choices":["Anterior pituitary","Posterior pituitary","Hypothalamus","Kidney"],"answer":2,"exp":"ADH is synthesized in hypothalamic (supraoptic/paraventricular) neurons.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"ADH is released from the:","choices":["Adrenal cortex","Posterior pituitary","Hypothalamus","Juxtaglomerular cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"ADH is stored in and released from the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which stimulus is the MOST powerful for ADH secretion?","choices":["Decreased plasma osmolarity","Increased plasma osmolarity","Hypercalcemia","Increased GFR"],"answer":1,"exp":"Rising plasma osmolarity is the most potent trigger for ADH release, sensed by hypothalamic osmoreceptors.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"ADH acts primarily on:","choices":["Proximal tubule","Thin descending limb","Thick ascending limb","Late distal tubule and collecting duct"],"answer":3,"exp":"ADH acts on the late distal tubule and collecting duct to insert aquaporins.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The primary effect of ADH is to:","choices":["Increase sodium secretion","Increase potassium secretion","Increase water reabsorption","Increase bicarbonate secretion"],"answer":2,"exp":"ADH's core action is to increase water reabsorption via aquaporin-2 insertion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"ADH inserts which channels into the collecting duct?","choices":["ENaC","NKCC2","Aquaporin-2","ROMK"],"answer":2,"exp":"ADH signals (V2 receptor → cAMP) to insert aquaporin-2 water channels into the apical membrane.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient drinks six liters of water over two hours. Which response is MOST likely?","choices":["Increased ADH","Decreased ADH","Increased aldosterone","Increased renin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water loading lowers plasma osmolarity, suppressing ADH so dilute urine is excreted.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Without ADH, urine becomes:","choices":["Highly concentrated","Small in volume","Dilute with high volume","Rich in glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"No ADH → no aquaporins → water stays in tubule → dilute, high-volume urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which disease results from inadequate ADH secretion?","choices":["SIADH","Diabetes mellitus","Diabetes insipidus","Conn syndrome"],"answer":2,"exp":"Central diabetes insipidus results from inadequate ADH, causing large-volume dilute urine and thirst.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient with SIADH would MOST likely produce urine that is:","choices":["Dilute","Concentrated","Protein-rich","Glucose-rich"],"answer":1,"exp":"Excess ADH in SIADH drives water retention and concentrated urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Aldosterone is produced by the:","choices":["Adrenal medulla","Adrenal cortex (zona glomerulosa)","Posterior pituitary","Kidney"],"answer":1,"exp":"Aldosterone is made in the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Aldosterone primarily acts on:","choices":["Thick ascending limb","Proximal tubule","Principal cells","Podocytes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Aldosterone acts on principal cells of the late distal tubule/collecting duct.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Aldosterone increases reabsorption of:","choices":["Potassium","Sodium","Hydrogen ions","Calcium"],"answer":1,"exp":"Aldosterone increases sodium reabsorption (via ENaC and Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Aldosterone increases secretion of:","choices":["Sodium","Glucose","Potassium","Calcium"],"answer":2,"exp":"By driving sodium reabsorption, aldosterone increases potassium (and H⁺) secretion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Water follows sodium because:","choices":["Active transport pulls water","Osmosis","ATP pumps water","Aquaporins pump water"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water follows reabsorbed sodium passively by osmosis down its osmotic gradient.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which condition would stimulate aldosterone release?","choices":["Hypervolemia","Low blood pressure","High ANP","Hypernatremia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Low blood pressure (via RAAS and low volume) stimulates aldosterone; hyperkalemia does too.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient with primary hyperaldosteronism would MOST likely have:","choices":["Hyperkalemia","Hypokalemia","Hypercalcemia","Metabolic acidosis only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Excess aldosterone drives potassium wasting → hypokalemia (with hypertension and metabolic alkalosis).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Renin is released from:","choices":["Macula densa","Juxtaglomerular cells","Podocytes","Mesangial cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Renin is released from juxtaglomerular (granular) cells of the afferent arteriole.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Renin converts:","choices":["Angiotensin I → Angiotensin II","Angiotensinogen → Angiotensin I","ACE → Angiotensin II","Aldosterone → Renin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Renin cleaves angiotensinogen (from the liver) into angiotensin I.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"ACE is located primarily in the:","choices":["Liver","Kidney","Lung endothelium","Pancreas"],"answer":2,"exp":"Angiotensin-converting enzyme is concentrated on pulmonary (lung) capillary endothelium.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Angiotensin II causes:","choices":["Vasodilation","Vasoconstriction","Decreased thirst","Decreased aldosterone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Angiotensin II is a potent vasoconstrictor that also stimulates aldosterone, ADH, and thirst.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which arteriole does Angiotensin II preferentially constrict?","choices":["Afferent","Efferent","Both equally","Neither"],"answer":1,"exp":"Angiotensin II preferentially constricts the efferent arteriole, helping preserve GFR.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Why does Angiotensin II preferentially constrict the efferent arteriole?","choices":["To lower GFR","To maintain glomerular hydrostatic pressure","To increase Bowman's capsule pressure","To decrease renal blood flow completely"],"answer":1,"exp":"Efferent constriction backs up pressure in the glomerulus, maintaining hydrostatic pressure and GFR during low perfusion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which hormone works AGAINST RAAS?","choices":["ADH","ANP","Cortisol","Epinephrine"],"answer":1,"exp":"ANP opposes RAAS — promoting natriuresis, vasodilation, and reduced aldosterone/renin.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient has severe hemorrhage. Which sequence is MOST likely?","choices":["↑ ANP → ↓ Renin → ↓ Ang II","↑ Renin → ↑ Ang II → ↑ Aldosterone","↓ ADH → ↑ Urine Output","↓ Sympathetic Activity → ↓ Blood Pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hemorrhage lowers perfusion, activating RAAS: renin → angiotensin II → aldosterone, to restore volume/pressure.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The primary purpose of the countercurrent multiplier system is to:","choices":["Increase GFR","Create a hyperosmotic renal medulla","Increase renal blood flow","Filter proteins"],"answer":1,"exp":"The countercurrent multiplier builds the hyperosmotic medullary gradient needed to concentrate urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which nephron segment actively establishes the medullary osmotic gradient?","choices":["Proximal convoluted tubule","Descending limb","Thick ascending limb","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The TAL actively pumps NaCl into the interstitium (without water), establishing the gradient.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The descending limb of the Loop of Henle is highly permeable to:","choices":["Sodium","Potassium","Water","Glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"The descending limb is highly water-permeable but solute-impermeable.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The ascending limb is characterized by:","choices":["Water permeability","Active salt reabsorption","Glucose secretion","Protein filtration"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ascending limb actively reabsorbs salt while remaining impermeable to water.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The \"single effect\" of the countercurrent multiplier refers to:","choices":["Active pumping of NaCl from the ascending limb","Water movement through aquaporins","Glomerular filtration","ADH secretion"],"answer":0,"exp":"The single effect is the active NaCl pumping out of the ascending limb, repeated along the loop to multiply the gradient.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Fluid displacement refers to:","choices":["Movement of filtrate through the Loop of Henle","Protein filtration","Potassium secretion","Sodium filtration"],"answer":0,"exp":"Fluid displacement is the flow of tubular fluid through the loop, which multiplies the single effect over distance.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The corticomedullary osmotic gradient is essential because it allows:","choices":["Glucose filtration","ADH to reabsorb water effectively","Renin release","Protein secretion"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gradient provides the osmotic force that lets ADH-driven water reabsorption concentrate the urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Without the medullary osmotic gradient:","choices":["GFR increases dramatically","ADH cannot effectively concentrate urine","Potassium secretion stops","Albumin enters urine"],"answer":1,"exp":"No gradient means no osmotic pull, so even with ADH the kidney cannot concentrate urine.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which structure preserves the medullary osmotic gradient?","choices":["Afferent arteriole","Vasa recta","Bowman's capsule","Juxtaglomerular cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vasa recta act as countercurrent exchangers, removing water/solute without washing out the gradient.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The vasa recta functions primarily as:","choices":["The countercurrent multiplier","The countercurrent exchanger","The filtration barrier","The source of renin"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vasa recta is the countercurrent exchanger that preserves the medullary gradient.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"The four major renal processes include all EXCEPT:","choices":["Filtration","Reabsorption","Secretion","Digestion"],"answer":3,"exp":"The four renal processes are filtration, reabsorption, secretion, and excretion — not digestion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which equation correctly describes urinary excretion?","choices":["Filtration + Reabsorption − Secretion","Filtration − Reabsorption + Secretion","Reabsorption − Filtration","Secretion − Filtration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Excretion = Filtration − Reabsorption + Secretion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"If glucose is filtered and completely reabsorbed:","choices":["Glucose excretion equals filtration","Glucose excretion equals zero","Glucose secretion increases","Glucose appears in urine"],"answer":1,"exp":"Complete reabsorption with no secretion means net excretion is zero.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"If secretion of a substance increases while filtration remains unchanged:","choices":["Excretion decreases","Excretion increases","Reabsorption increases automatically","Filtration decreases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Adding secretion (with unchanged filtration/reabsorption) increases net excretion.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Principal cells are located primarily in the:","choices":["Proximal tubule","Thick ascending limb","Late distal tubule and collecting duct","Bowman's capsule"],"answer":2,"exp":"Principal cells reside in the late distal tubule and collecting duct.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Principal cells primarily regulate:","choices":["Calcium","Sodium and potassium","Glucose","Proteins"],"answer":1,"exp":"Principal cells handle sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion (aldosterone-responsive).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Aldosterone increases activity of:","choices":["Carbonic anhydrase","ENaC channels","NKCC2 transporters","GLUT2 transporters"],"answer":1,"exp":"Aldosterone upregulates ENaC (and Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase) in principal cells.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Activation of principal cells results in:","choices":["Increased Na⁺ reabsorption and K⁺ secretion","Increased K⁺ reabsorption","Increased glucose secretion","Increased bicarbonate secretion"],"answer":0,"exp":"Principal cell activation reabsorbs sodium and secretes potassium.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Intercalated cells primarily regulate:","choices":["Sodium","Water","Acid-base balance","Glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"Intercalated cells handle acid–base balance (H⁺ and bicarbonate handling).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Type A intercalated cells are activated primarily during:","choices":["Alkalosis","Acidosis","Hypernatremia","Hypokalemia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Type A intercalated cells secrete H⁺ during acidosis (and reabsorb bicarbonate).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Type A intercalated cells:","choices":["Secrete bicarbonate","Secrete hydrogen ions","Secrete sodium","Secrete glucose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Type A intercalated cells secrete hydrogen ions to correct acidosis.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Type B intercalated cells primarily:","choices":["Secrete hydrogen ions","Reabsorb potassium","Secrete bicarbonate","Reabsorb glucose"],"answer":2,"exp":"Type B intercalated cells secrete bicarbonate (and reabsorb H⁺) during alkalosis.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Approximately what percentage of filtered bicarbonate is reabsorbed in the proximal convoluted tubule?","choices":["20%","40%","60%","80–90%"],"answer":3,"exp":"The PCT reclaims roughly 80–90% of filtered bicarbonate (via carbonic anhydrase).","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"Which enzyme is essential for bicarbonate reabsorption?","choices":["Renin","ACE","Carbonic anhydrase","Aldosterone synthase"],"answer":2,"exp":"Carbonic anhydrase catalyzes the CO₂/bicarbonate conversions required for bicarbonate reabsorption.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"},{"q":"A patient develops severe metabolic acidosis after prolonged diarrhea. Which combination of renal responses would best compensate?","choices":["↓ H⁺ secretion, ↓ bicarbonate reabsorption","↑ H⁺ secretion, ↑ bicarbonate reabsorption, ↑ new bicarbonate generation","↑ sodium excretion only","↓ potassium secretion only"],"answer":1,"exp":"To compensate for acidosis the kidney increases H⁺ secretion, bicarbonate reabsorption, and generates new bicarbonate.","cite":"Renal Physiology II lecture"}]},"endocrine-2":{"title":"Endocrine System (Set 2)","questions":[{"q":"Which of the following is a PRIMARY (dedicated) endocrine organ rather than a tissue with a secondary endocrine role?","choices":["Heart","Thyroid gland","Kidney","Adipose tissue"],"answer":1,"exp":"Main endocrine organs include the pituitary, hypothalamus, thyroid, thymus, suprarenal, pineal, parathyroids, and pancreas; the heart, kidney, adipose, and digestive tract are 'other' endocrine tissues.","cite":"Slides 3–4 (Overview of the Endocrine System)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is attached to the hypothalamus by a stalk called the:","choices":["Isthmus","Infundibulum","Pedicle","Tentorium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The infundibulum connects the pituitary (hypophysis) to the hypothalamus; the gland sits in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica.","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The suprarenal (adrenal) gland is subdivided into which two parts?","choices":["Cortex and medulla","Anterior and posterior lobes","Follicular and parafollicular zones","Exocrine and endocrine acini"],"answer":0,"exp":"Each adrenal gland has an outer cortex and an inner medulla; the cortex has three zones and the medulla secretes catecholamines.","cite":"Slide 82 (The Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"Which pineal-gland hormone is listed in the endocrine overview?","choices":["Calcitonin","Melatonin","Aldosterone","Erythropoietin"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pineal gland secretes melatonin.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 overview)"},{"q":"The parathyroid glands are typically located on the:","choices":["Anterior surface of the trachea","Inferior surface of the liver","Superior pole of each kidney","Posterior surface of the thyroid gland"],"answer":3,"exp":"The parathyroid glands lie on the posterior aspect of the thyroid, sometimes embedded within thyroid tissue.","cite":"Slide 43 (Parathyroid Glands, posterior view)"},{"q":"Which natriuretic peptides are secreted by the heart as an endocrine function?","choices":["T3 and T4","ANP and BNP","FSH and LH","EPO and calcitriol"],"answer":1,"exp":"The heart secretes atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP) and brain natriuretic peptide (BNP).","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 overview)"},{"q":"The kidney contributes to endocrine function by producing erythropoietin (EPO) and:","choices":["Insulin","Calcitriol","Thyroxine","Oxytocin"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney produces EPO and calcitriol (active vitamin D).","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 overview)"},{"q":"The adenohypophysis (anterior lobe) releases how many peptide hormones, versus how many for the neurohypophysis?","choices":["Two anterior; nine posterior","Seven anterior; three posterior","Five anterior; five posterior","Nine anterior; two posterior"],"answer":3,"exp":"The adenohypophysis releases nine peptide hormones; the neurohypophysis releases two (oxytocin and ADH).","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"Which hormones are stored and released by the neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary)?","choices":["ACTH and TSH","FSH and LH","Growth hormone and prolactin","Oxytocin and antidiuretic hormone (ADH)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The posterior pituitary releases oxytocin and ADH, which are actually produced in hypothalamic nuclei.","cite":"Slides 5, 10 (posterior pituitary hormones)"},{"q":"The structural/functional unit of the thyroid gland is the thyroid follicle, whose wall is made of which epithelium surrounding a central colloid?","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium","Simple cuboidal (follicular) epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each thyroid follicle is lined by simple cuboidal follicular epithelium enclosing colloid; active follicles have taller epithelium.","cite":"Slide 30 (Histology of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"Calcitonin-secreting cells of the thyroid, located near the follicular basement membrane, are the:","choices":["Chief (principal) cells","Oxyphil cells","Parafollicular (C) cells","Chromaffin cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parafollicular (C) cells secrete calcitonin and lie near the follicular basement lamina, larger and lighter-staining than follicular cells.","cite":"Slide 31 (Parafollicular/C cells)"},{"q":"In the pars distalis, the cells that stain with granules and secrete active hormones are the:","choices":["Chromophils (acidophils and basophils)","Chromophobes","Pituicytes","Herring bodies"],"answer":0,"exp":"Chromophils have cytoplasmic granules: acidophils secrete GH and prolactin; basophils secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH. Chromophobes lack granules.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"Acidophils of the anterior pituitary secrete which hormones?","choices":["Growth hormone and prolactin","TSH and ACTH","FSH and LH","ADH and oxytocin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Acidophils (reddish cytoplasm) secrete growth hormone and prolactin; basophils secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis cell types)"},{"q":"The parathyroid hormone (PTH)–secreting cells of the parathyroid gland are the:","choices":["Oxyphil cells","Follicular cells","Principal (chief) cells","Zona glomerulosa cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chief (principal) cells produce PTH; oxyphil cells are larger, very eosinophilic, and of uncertain function (may also secrete PTH).","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"Which adrenal cortical zone secretes mineralocorticoids (aldosterone) and is composed of cells in ovoid clusters?","choices":["Zona reticularis","Zona fasciculata","Zona glomerulosa","Adrenal medulla"],"answer":2,"exp":"The zona glomerulosa (outer) secretes mineralocorticoids/aldosterone; fasciculata secretes glucocorticoids (cortisol); reticularis secretes androgens.","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of adrenal glands)"},{"q":"The zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex is composed of lipid-laden cells in radial columns and secretes:","choices":["Aldosterone","Glucocorticoids (cortisol)","Androgens","Epinephrine"],"answer":1,"exp":"The zona fasciculata secretes glucocorticoids such as cortisol.","cite":"Slide 87 (adrenal cortex zones)"},{"q":"The principal cells of the adrenal medulla, which secrete epinephrine and norepinephrine, are called:","choices":["Chief cells","Pituicytes","Chromaffin cells","Podocytes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chromaffin cells — modified postganglionic sympathetic neurons lacking axons/dendrites — secrete adrenaline and noradrenaline; the medulla contains a large central vein.","cite":"Slide 89 (Adrenal medulla)"},{"q":"The endocrine cells of the pancreatic islets that secrete insulin are the:","choices":["Alpha cells","Delta cells","F cells","Beta cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Beta cells secrete insulin; alpha cells secrete glucagon; delta cells secrete somatostatin; F cells secrete pancreatic polypeptide.","cite":"Slide 52 (Histology of pancreatic islets)"},{"q":"In the pars nervosa, the supportive glial-like cells are called:","choices":["Chromaffin cells","Podocytes","Pituicytes","Chief cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pars nervosa contains nerve-fiber bundles and pituicytes; Herring bodies represent accumulated neurosecretory material.","cite":"Slide 22 (Pars nervosa)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland sits within the hypophyseal fossa of which bone?","choices":["Sphenoid bone","Ethmoid bone","Occipital bone","Temporal bone"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pituitary lies in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone, covered superiorly by the diaphragma sellae.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary relationships)"},{"q":"On each side, the pituitary gland is related to which venous structure?","choices":["Sigmoid sinus","Superior sagittal sinus","Cavernous sinus","Straight sinus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pituitary is related laterally to the cavernous sinus on each side, and superiorly the diaphragma sellae separates it from the optic chiasma.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary relationships)"},{"q":"The anterior pituitary receives its blood supply mainly through which specialized vascular arrangement?","choices":["Direct arterial supply from the internal carotid","The hypophyseal portal system","The vertebral–basilar system","The cavernous venous plexus alone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Regulatory hormones travel from the hypothalamus to the adenohypophysis through the hypophyseal portal veins; the posterior pituitary receives arterial blood.","cite":"Slides 17, 19 (Hypophyseal portal system)"},{"q":"The superior thyroid artery, supplying the thyroid gland, arises from the:","choices":["External carotid artery","Thyrocervical trunk","Arch of the aorta","Subclavian artery directly"],"answer":0,"exp":"The superior thyroid artery arises from the external carotid; the inferior thyroid artery arises from the thyrocervical trunk of the subclavian.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The inferior thyroid artery arises from which vessel?","choices":["External carotid artery","Arch of the aorta","Thyrocervical trunk of the subclavian artery","Brachiocephalic artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The inferior thyroid artery arises from the thyrocervical trunk and becomes related to the recurrent laryngeal nerve at the posterior surface of the gland.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"On the medial surface of the thyroid, which nerve runs in the tracheoesophageal groove and is at risk during thyroid surgery?","choices":["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Vagus nerve trunk","Hypoglossal nerve"],"answer":0,"exp":"The recurrent laryngeal nerve lies near the trachea/esophagus on the medial surface; the external laryngeal nerve accompanies the superior thyroid artery.","cite":"Slide 27 (Thyroid medial surface relations)"},{"q":"The inferior thyroid vein drains into which vein?","choices":["Internal jugular vein","Brachiocephalic vein","Subclavian vein","External jugular vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"Superior and middle thyroid veins drain to the internal jugular; the inferior thyroid vein drains to the brachiocephalic vein.","cite":"Slide 33 (Venous drainage of thyroid)"},{"q":"The adrenal (suprarenal) glands receive arterial supply from three sources: the inferior phrenic artery, the renal artery, and the:","choices":["Gonadal artery","Splenic artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Middle suprarenal artery from the aorta"],"answer":3,"exp":"The superior suprarenal (from inferior phrenic), middle suprarenal (from aorta), and inferior suprarenal (from renal artery) supply the adrenal gland.","cite":"Slides 81, 86 (adrenal blood supply)"},{"q":"Venous drainage of the adrenal glands is asymmetric: the RIGHT suprarenal vein drains to the IVC, while the LEFT drains to the:","choices":["Portal vein","Azygos vein","Splenic vein","Left renal vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The right suprarenal vein drains directly to the IVC; the left suprarenal vein drains to the left renal vein.","cite":"Slide 86 (adrenal venous drainage)"},{"q":"The head of the pancreas — clinically important because ducts/vessels traverse it and carcinoma often arises there — fills the concavity of which structure?","choices":["The duodenum","The spleen","The stomach","The gallbladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pancreatic head fills the C of the duodenum; its blood supply comes from the pancreaticoduodenal arteries.","cite":"Slides 56, 65 (pancreas head relations)"},{"q":"The body and tail of the pancreas are supplied primarily by which artery?","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery","Splenic artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Left renal artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The splenic artery (a celiac branch) runs along the superior margin of the body and tail, supplying them; the head is supplied by pancreaticoduodenal arteries.","cite":"Slides 60, 70 (pancreas arterial supply)"},{"q":"The main pancreatic duct (duct of Wirsung) joins the common bile duct and empties at the:","choices":["Ampulla of Vater (major duodenal papilla)","Minor duodenal papilla","Pylorus","Duodenojejunal flexure"],"answer":0,"exp":"The duct of Wirsung joins the CBD at the ampulla of Vater; the accessory duct of Santorini opens at the minor papilla.","cite":"Slides 71, 74 (pancreatic duct system)"},{"q":"The right adrenal gland's anterior relations include the liver and which vessel?","choices":["Inferior vena cava","Aorta","Splenic vein","Portal vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The right (pyramidal) adrenal is related anteriorly to the liver and IVC; the left (semilunar) adrenal relates to the stomach and pancreas.","cite":"Slide 86 (adrenal relations table)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is related inferiorly and anteriorly to which air-filled space?","choices":["The frontal sinus","The mastoid air cells","The maxillary sinus","The sphenoid air sinus"],"answer":3,"exp":"Inferiorly and in front, the pituitary is related to the sphenoid air sinus; behind it lies the dorsum sellae.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary relationships)"},{"q":"The thyroid isthmus typically lies anterior to which tracheal rings?","choices":["2nd and 3rd tracheal rings","1st tracheal ring only","5th and 6th tracheal rings","Cricoid cartilage"],"answer":0,"exp":"The isthmus lies opposite the 2nd and 3rd tracheal rings, covered by the sternohyoid and sternothyroid muscles.","cite":"Slide 29 (Thyroid isthmus)"},{"q":"The parathyroid glands share their blood, lymphatic, and nerve supply with the:","choices":["Larynx","Thyroid gland","Trachea only","Esophagus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The parathyroids' blood, lymphatic, and nerve supply are the same as for the thyroid gland; they lie between the posteromedial thyroid lobes and the carotid sheath.","cite":"Slide 47 (Parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"The uncinate process of the pancreas lies posterior to which vessels?","choices":["The aorta and IVC","The portal vein and hepatic artery","The splenic artery and vein","The superior mesenteric artery and vein (SMA and SMV)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uncinate process lies posterior to the SMA and SMV and anterior to the aorta.","cite":"Slide 57 (pancreas uncinate relations)"},{"q":"Which hormone LOWERS blood calcium and is secreted by the parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid?","choices":["Parathyroid hormone (PTH)","Calcitriol","Calcitonin","Aldosterone"],"answer":2,"exp":"Calcitonin, from thyroid C cells, lowers blood calcium; it opposes PTH, which raises calcium.","cite":"Slides 5, 31 (calcitonin from C cells)"},{"q":"Which hormone RAISES blood calcium and is produced by the chief cells of the parathyroid glands?","choices":["Calcitonin","Parathyroid hormone (PTH)","Insulin","Thyroxine (T4)"],"answer":1,"exp":"PTH, secreted by parathyroid chief cells, raises blood calcium — the principal calcium-elevating hormone.","cite":"Slides 5, 46 (PTH from chief cells)"},{"q":"The active form of vitamin D that participates in calcium metabolism, produced by the kidney, is:","choices":["Calcitonin","Cortisol","Calcitriol","Erythropoietin"],"answer":2,"exp":"The kidney produces calcitriol (active vitamin D), which promotes intestinal calcium absorption and works with PTH in calcium homeostasis.","cite":"Slide 5 (kidney — calcitriol)"},{"q":"Calcitonin and PTH are described as having what relationship in calcium regulation?","choices":["They are antagonistic — PTH raises and calcitonin lowers blood calcium","They are synergistic, both raising calcium","Both lower blood calcium","Neither affects blood calcium"],"answer":0,"exp":"PTH (calcium-raising) and calcitonin (calcium-lowering) act antagonistically to regulate blood calcium levels.","cite":"Slides 5, 31, 46 (calcium regulation)"},{"q":"Because the parathyroid glands are the chief source of PTH, inadvertent removal during thyroid surgery would most directly impair:","choices":["Blood glucose regulation","Erythrocyte production","Sodium/water balance","Blood calcium regulation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Loss of PTH from the parathyroids would impair calcium regulation, since PTH is the primary calcium-elevating hormone.","cite":"Slides 43–46 (Parathyroid glands / PTH)"},{"q":"Which cells are the calcium-related hormone source located ON the posterior thyroid, distinct from the calcitonin-producing cells embedded WITHIN the thyroid follicular tissue?","choices":["Zona glomerulosa vs. zona fasciculata","Parathyroid chief cells (PTH) vs. thyroid C cells (calcitonin)","Alpha vs. beta islet cells","Acidophils vs. basophils"],"answer":1,"exp":"Parathyroid chief cells (on the posterior thyroid) secrete PTH, while parafollicular C cells (within the thyroid) secrete calcitonin — the two opposing calcium hormones.","cite":"Slides 31, 43, 46 (C cells vs. chief cells)"},{"q":"Which gland undergoes progressive atrophy during adulthood?","choices":["Thyroid gland","Pancreas","Pineal gland","Thymus gland"],"answer":3,"exp":"The thymus undergoes atrophy during adulthood, per the endocrine overview.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 overview)"},{"q":"The hypothalamus exerts endocrine control via three mechanisms, including releasing ADH and oxytocin to the pituitary and controlling which structure via sympathetic output?","choices":["The thyroid follicles","The pineal gland","The parathyroid glands","The suprarenal (adrenal) medulla"],"answer":3,"exp":"The hypothalamus acts as an endocrine organ, releases ADH/oxytocin to the pituitary, and controls the adrenal medulla via sympathetic (preganglionic) fibers.","cite":"Slide 9 (Hypothalamus and Endocrine Regulation)"},{"q":"Anatomically, the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) is subdivided into the pars distalis, pars tuberalis, and:","choices":["Pars intermedia","Pars nervosa","Median eminence","Infundibulum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The adenohypophysis comprises the pars distalis, pars tuberalis, and pars intermedia; the neurohypophysis is the pars nervosa.","cite":"Slide 14 (pituitary subdivisions)"},{"q":"The gonads function as endocrine organs: the testes secrete androgens and inhibin, while the ovaries secrete estrogens, progestins, and:","choices":["Calcitonin","Inhibin","Aldosterone","Erythropoietin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Both gonads secrete inhibin; testes add testosterone/androgens and ovaries add estrogens and progestins.","cite":"Slide 5 (gonads overview)"},{"q":"The colloid stored in the center of each thyroid follicle serves to:","choices":["Filter blood","Generate red blood cells","Produce calcitonin","Store thyroid hormone precursor (thyroglobulin)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Follicular colloid stores the thyroid-hormone-containing material; active follicles show tall epithelium as hormone is mobilized.","cite":"Slides 30, 40 (thyroid follicles/colloid)"},{"q":"Chromophobes make up roughly what fraction of pars distalis cells and characteristically LACK cytoplasmic granules?","choices":["About 10%","About 1%","About 90%","About 50%"],"answer":3,"exp":"Chromophobes are ~50% of pars distalis cells and have no granules; the other ~50% are chromophils (acidophils + basophils).","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"Basophils of the anterior pituitary secrete all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["TSH","ACTH","Growth hormone","FSH and LH"],"answer":2,"exp":"Basophils secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH; growth hormone is secreted by acidophils.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis cell types)"},{"q":"Oxyphil cells of the parathyroid gland are best described as:","choices":["Larger, very eosinophilic cells of uncertain function","Small, granule-free cells","Colloid-storing follicular cells","Catecholamine-secreting cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Oxyphil cells are larger and strongly eosinophilic with an unknown function (may secrete PTH); chief cells are the main PTH producers.","cite":"Slide 46 (parathyroid histology)"},{"q":"The parathyroid glands frequently contain increasing amounts of which tissue in older individuals?","choices":["Skeletal muscle","Cartilage","Adipose tissue","Colloid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Adipose tissue is frequently found in the parathyroid gland in older individuals.","cite":"Slide 46 (parathyroid histology)"},{"q":"The zona reticularis of the adrenal cortex is a loose meshwork of cells that secretes:","choices":["Aldosterone","Cortisol","Epinephrine","Androgens"],"answer":3,"exp":"The innermost zona reticularis secretes androgens; glomerulosa secretes aldosterone and fasciculata secretes cortisol.","cite":"Slide 87 (adrenal cortex zones)"},{"q":"The thyroid gland moves up and down with swallowing (deglutition) because it is enclosed within the:","choices":["Carotid sheath","Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia"],"answer":2,"exp":"The thyroid lies within the pretracheal fascia, which attaches above to the thyroid cartilage, so the gland ascends with swallowing.","cite":"Slide 28 (thyroid fascia)"},{"q":"The thyroidea ima artery, an uncommon variant supplying the thyroid isthmus, typically arises from the arch of the aorta or the:","choices":["External carotid artery","Vertebral artery","Brachiocephalic (innominate) artery","Facial artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The thyroidea ima is a small, uncommon artery supplying the isthmus, arising from the aortic arch or brachiocephalic artery.","cite":"Slide 32 (thyroid blood supply)"},{"q":"The carotid sheath, which delineates the lateral aspect of the thyroid, contains the internal jugular vein, the vagus nerve, and the:","choices":["Common and internal carotid arteries","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Thyrocervical trunk"],"answer":0,"exp":"The carotid sheath contains the internal jugular vein (lateral), the common/internal carotid arteries, and the vagus nerve.","cite":"Slide 38 (carotid sheath)"},{"q":"The splenic vein, which runs on the posterior surface of the pancreas, terminates in the:","choices":["Inferior vena cava","Portal vein","Left renal vein","Azygos vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"The splenic vein runs parallel to the splenic artery on the posterior pancreas and terminates in the portal vein.","cite":"Slide 62 (splenic vein)"},{"q":"The superior and inferior mesenteric veins pass deep to the pancreas and merge with the splenic vein to terminate in the:","choices":["Renal vein","Hepatic vein","Portal vein","Azygos vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The SMV and IMV pass deep to the pancreas, merge with the splenic vein, and terminate in the portal vein.","cite":"Slide 63 (mesenteric veins)"},{"q":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally in the epigastric and left hypochondriac regions at approximately which vertebral level?","choices":["T6–T8","S1–S2","L4–L5","T12/L1 to L3"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally at ~T12/L1 to L3.","cite":"Slide 56 (pancreas location)"},{"q":"The body of the pancreas is related posteriorly to the left crus of the diaphragm, the left adrenal, the left renal vein, and the:","choices":["Portal vein","Splenic vein","Superior mesenteric artery only","Gallbladder"],"answer":1,"exp":"The body of the pancreas relates posteriorly to the left crus, left adrenal, left renal vein, and splenic vein; the celiac trunk lies superior to the body.","cite":"Slide 59 (pancreas body relations)"},{"q":"The pancreatic head derives its blood supply from the superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries; the superior branches originate from the gastroduodenal artery (GDA) and the inferior from the:","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery (SMA)","Splenic artery","Left gastric artery","Inferior mesenteric artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"Anterior/posterior pancreaticoduodenal arcades form from GDA (superior) and SMA (inferior) branches, giving the head an extensive dual supply.","cite":"Slides 67–69 (pancreaticoduodenal arteries)"}]},"female-reproductive-2":{"title":"Female Reproductive System (Set 2)","questions":[{"q":"The paired embryonic ducts that develop into the major internal female reproductive organs are the:","choices":["Paramesonephric (Müllerian) ducts","Mesonephric (Wolffian) ducts","Pronephric ducts","Metanephric ducts"],"answer":0,"exp":"The Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts form the female internal organs in the absence of anti-Müllerian hormone.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"In the female embryo, the fused caudal portions of the Müllerian ducts form the uterus, cervix, and:","choices":["Lower vagina","Upper (upper one-third) vagina","Fallopian tubes","Ovaries"],"answer":1,"exp":"Fused caudal Müllerian portions form the uterus, cervix, and upper vagina; the lower vagina derives from the urogenital sinus.","cite":"Slide 16 (Müllerian ducts differentiation)"},{"q":"The unfused cranial portions of the Müllerian ducts differentiate into the:","choices":["Uterus and cervix","Fallopian (uterine) tubes","Lower vagina","Labia majora"],"answer":1,"exp":"The unfused cranial ends of the paramesonephric ducts become the fallopian tubes.","cite":"Slide 16 (Müllerian ducts differentiation)"},{"q":"In males, the Müllerian ducts regress due to the action of:","choices":["Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH)","Testosterone","Estrogen","Inhibin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) causes regression of the Müllerian ducts in males; in its absence, female structures develop.","cite":"Slides 16–17 (Müllerian system)"},{"q":"The lower portion of the vagina develops embryologically from the:","choices":["Fused Müllerian ducts","Gubernaculum","Mesonephric ducts","Urogenital sinus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The lower vagina develops from the urogenital sinus, while the upper vagina comes from the fused Müllerian ducts.","cite":"Slide 16 (Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts arise from the coelomic epithelium around which week of development?","choices":["2nd week","20th week","12th week","6th week"],"answer":3,"exp":"The paramesonephric ducts arise from coelomic epithelium on the lateral mesonephros around the 6th week; fusion forms the uterovaginal primordium (weeks 6–12).","cite":"Slides 16–17 (Müllerian development)"},{"q":"The perineum is a diamond-shaped area bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, posteriorly by the coccyx, and laterally by the:","choices":["Ischial tuberosities","Iliac crests","Greater trochanters","Sacral promontory"],"answer":0,"exp":"The perineum is circumscribed anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the ischial tuberosities, and posteriorly by the coccyx.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"An imaginary horizontal line between the ischial tuberosities divides the perineum into the anterior triangle and the:","choices":["Urogenital triangle","Lumbar triangle","Femoral triangle","Posterior (anal) triangle"],"answer":3,"exp":"The line between the ischial tuberosities separates the anterior (urogenital) triangle from the posterior (anal) triangle.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"In females, the anterior (urogenital) triangle contains the:","choices":["Urethral and vaginal orifices","Anus","Ovaries","Uterine tubes"],"answer":0,"exp":"The urogenital (anterior) triangle contains the urethral and vaginal orifices in females; the anal (posterior) triangle contains the anus.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The posterior (anal) triangle of the perineum contains which structure in both sexes?","choices":["The clitoris","The anus","The vaginal orifice","The urethra"],"answer":1,"exp":"The anal triangle contains the anus in both sexes.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The peritoneal fold that drapes over the uterus and holds the ovaries and uterine tubes is the:","choices":["Round ligament","Broad ligament","Ovarian ligament","Suspensory ligament"],"answer":1,"exp":"The broad ligament is a peritoneal fold that extends from the lateral uterus to the pelvic wall and holds the ovaries and uterine tubes.","cite":"Slides 14, 18 (Peritoneal Folds/Ligaments)"},{"q":"The double fold of peritoneum that attaches the ovaries to the broad ligament is the:","choices":["Mesovarium","Mesosalpinx","Mesometrium","Round ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mesovarium is a double peritoneal fold attaching each ovary to the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 14 (Peritoneal Folds/Ligaments)"},{"q":"Which ligament connects the ovary to the uterus?","choices":["Suspensory ligament","Round ligament","Ovarian ligament","Broad ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ovarian ligament attaches the ovary to the superior margin of the uterus; the suspensory ligament runs from the ovary to the pelvic wall.","cite":"Slides 14, 18 (ligaments)"},{"q":"The suspensory ligament of the ovary extends from the ovary/mesovarium to the:","choices":["Uterus","Sacrum","Labia majora","Pelvic (body) wall"],"answer":3,"exp":"The suspensory ligament extends from the mesovarium/ovary to the body (pelvic) wall and transmits the ovarian vessels.","cite":"Slides 14, 18 (ligaments)"},{"q":"The round ligament of the uterus travels from the uterus through the inguinal canal to end in the:","choices":["Labia majora","Sacrum","Pelvic wall","Ovary"],"answer":0,"exp":"The round ligament extends from the uterus through the inguinal canal to the labia majora and helps maintain the anteverted position.","cite":"Slides 18, 36 (round ligament)"},{"q":"Which paired ligaments — thickenings of subserous fascia and smooth muscle — support the cervix and vagina laterally to the pelvic wall?","choices":["Transverse cervical (cardinal) ligaments","Uterosacral ligaments","Round ligaments","Broad ligaments"],"answer":0,"exp":"The transverse cervical (cardinal) ligaments anchor the lateral cervix/vagina to the pelvic wall; uterosacral ligaments run from the inferior uterus to the sacrum.","cite":"Slides 31, 36 (uterine support)"},{"q":"The uterosacral ligaments extend from the inferior uterus to which structure?","choices":["The pubic symphysis","The lateral pelvic wall","The labia majora","The sacrum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterosacral ligaments connect the inferior uterus to the sacrum.","cite":"Slide 36 (uterine support)"},{"q":"The pelvic diaphragm is formed by the coccygeus muscle and the:","choices":["Ischiocavernosus","Bulbospongiosus","Levator ani","Obturator internus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm consists of the levator ani and coccygeus muscles, which support the pelvic organs and seal the inferior pelvic opening.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The levator ani muscle is composed of the puborectalis, iliococcygeus, and:","choices":["Pubococcygeus","Coccygeus","Bulbospongiosus","Piriformis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The levator ani is made up of the puborectalis, pubococcygeus, and iliococcygeus.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"A primary function of the pelvic diaphragm is to:","choices":["Produce ova","Secrete estrogen","Support the pelvic organs and seal the inferior opening of the bony pelvis","Transport sperm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm supports pelvic organs, seals the inferior pelvic outlet, and lifts to aid defecation.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"Which muscle, a part of the levator ani, is specifically related to the vagina?","choices":["Pubovaginalis","Coccygeus","Piriformis","Obturator internus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pubovaginalis (part of the levator ani) is among the muscles related to the vagina, along with the external urethral sphincter, urethrovaginal sphincter, and bulbospongiosus.","cite":"Slide 62 (Muscles Related to the Vagina)"},{"q":"The ovarian artery, supplying the ovary, arises directly from the:","choices":["Internal iliac artery","Abdominal aorta","Uterine artery","External iliac artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ovarian artery arises from the abdominal aorta (inferior to the renal arteries) and reaches the ovary via the suspensory ligament.","cite":"Slides 24, 27, 41 (ovarian vasculature)"},{"q":"The uterine artery, the main supply to the uterus, is a branch of the:","choices":["Abdominal aorta","Internal iliac artery","Ovarian artery","Femoral artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The uterine arteries arise from the internal iliac artery; the uterus is also supplied by vaginal and ovarian arteries.","cite":"Slides 35, 41 (uterine blood supply)"},{"q":"Venous drainage of the ovaries is asymmetric: the right ovarian vein drains to the IVC, while the left ovarian vein drains to the:","choices":["Left renal vein","Portal vein","Internal iliac vein","Azygos vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The right ovarian vein drains to the IVC; the left drains to the left renal vein — mirroring the gonadal drainage pattern.","cite":"Slide 24 (Ovary venous drainage)"},{"q":"The blood supply to the vagina is provided by the uterine, vaginal, and which additional arteries?","choices":["Femoral arteries","Ovarian arteries only","Pudendal arteries","Obturator arteries"],"answer":2,"exp":"The vagina is supplied by the uterine, vaginal, and pudendal arteries.","cite":"Slide 59 (Vagina blood supply)"},{"q":"The uterine tube (fallopian tube) receives its blood supply from the ovarian and which other arteries?","choices":["Inferior epigastric arteries","Pudendal arteries","Vaginal arteries","Uterine arteries"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterine tube is supplied by both the ovarian and uterine arteries.","cite":"Slide 48 (Uterine Tube blood supply)"},{"q":"The venous drainage of the ovary forms a network within the suspensory ligament called the:","choices":["Vesical plexus","Pampiniform plexus","Prostatic plexus","Vertebral plexus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ovarian veins drain via pampiniform plexi, analogous to the male testicular drainage.","cite":"Slide 27 (Vasculature of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The ovaries receive parasympathetic innervation from which nerves?","choices":["Pudendal nerve","Greater splanchnic nerves","Pelvic splanchnic nerves","Vagus nerve"],"answer":2,"exp":"Ovarian parasympathetic supply comes from the pelvic splanchnic nerves; afferent fibers enter the cord via T10–T11.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"Afferent (sensory) fibers from the ovary enter the spinal cord through which spinal nerve levels?","choices":["T5 and T6","T10 and T11","L1 and L2","S2 and S4"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ovarian afferent fibers enter the cord through the T10 and T11 nerves — relevant to referred ovarian pain.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The uterine tube receives its nerve supply from the ovarian and uterine:","choices":["Plexi","Splanchnic trunks","Pudendal branches","Sacral roots"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterine tube's nerve supply comes from the ovarian and uterine plexi.","cite":"Slide 48 (Uterine Tube nerve supply)"},{"q":"The external urethral sphincter and much of the perineum receive somatic innervation (voluntary control) from which nerve?","choices":["Obturator nerve","Pudendal nerve","Pelvic splanchnic nerve","Genitofemoral nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pudendal nerve provides somatic innervation to the perineum and external urethral sphincter (voluntary control).","cite":"Slides 62, 65 (perineal/vaginal innervation)"},{"q":"The uterus is located between which two organs?","choices":["The urinary bladder and the rectum","The ovaries and the sigmoid colon","The vagina and the cervix only","The kidneys and the bladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterus lies between the urinary bladder (anterior) and the rectum (posterior).","cite":"Slide 32 (Uterus)"},{"q":"Which sequence gives the regions of the uterus from superior to inferior?","choices":["Cervix → isthmus → body → fundus","Isthmus → fundus → body → cervix","Body → fundus → cervix → isthmus","Fundus → body → isthmus → cervix"],"answer":3,"exp":"From superior to inferior: fundus (above tube entry), body (main portion), isthmus (constriction), then cervix (joins the vagina).","cite":"Slides 33–34 (Regions of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The normal uterus is described as anteverted and anteflexed; anteflexion refers to the bend at the junction of the:","choices":["Cervix and vagina","Isthmus and fundus","Fundus and body","Cervix and body"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterus is anteverted at the cervix–vagina junction and anteflexed at the cervix–body junction.","cite":"Slide 31 (Uterus)"},{"q":"The cervix attaches to the vagina at approximately what angle, forming pockets called fornices?","choices":["45 degrees","180 degrees","90 degrees","30 degrees"],"answer":2,"exp":"The cervix attaches to the vagina at ~90°; the fornix is the recess surrounding the cervix (a site for surgical access and device placement).","cite":"Slide 60 (Cervix and Vagina)"},{"q":"The uterine tube's regions, from the ovary toward the uterus, are the infundibulum (with fimbriae), ampulla, isthmus, and:","choices":["Fundus","Intramural (interstitial/uterine) segment","Cervix","Fornix"],"answer":1,"exp":"The tube runs infundibulum → ampulla → isthmus → intramural/uterine segment (through the uterine wall).","cite":"Slides 45, 51 (Uterine Tube regions)"},{"q":"Fertilization of the secondary oocyte typically occurs in which part of the uterine tube?","choices":["Infundibulum","Intramural segment","Isthmus","Ampulla"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ampulla is the long, wide portion of the tube and the usual site of fertilization; it takes the pre-embryo about 5–6 days to reach the uterus.","cite":"Slides 45, 51 (Uterine Tubes)"},{"q":"The vagina is positioned posterior to the urethra and anterior to the:","choices":["Rectum","Bladder","Uterus","Sacrum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The vagina lies posterior to the urethra and anterior to the rectum, extending from the cervix to the exterior.","cite":"Slide 57 (Vagina)"},{"q":"The uterine (fallopian) tubes attach to the uterus but characteristically:","choices":["Physically attach to the ovary","Attach directly to the bladder","Do NOT physically attach to the ovary","Attach to the sacrum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The tubes receive the ovulated oocyte but do not physically attach to the ovary; they are supported by the broad ligament.","cite":"Slides 49–50 (Uterine Tubes)"},{"q":"The clitoris, located where the labia minora meet anteriorly, is homologous to which male structure?","choices":["The scrotum","The bulbo-urethral gland","The prostate","The penis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The clitoris contains erectile tissue and is homologous to the penis; the labia majora are homologous to the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 71 (External Genitalia)"},{"q":"The greater vestibular (Bartholin's) glands, which secrete mucus into the vestibule, are homologous to which male glands?","choices":["Prostate","Seminal glands","Bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) glands","Preputial glands"],"answer":2,"exp":"The greater vestibular glands are homologous to the male bulbourethral glands and secrete mucus into the vestibule.","cite":"Slide 78 (Greater Vestibular Gland)"},{"q":"The uterine (fallopian) tube is lined by which epithelium that helps move the oocyte toward the uterus?","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Ciliated (and non-ciliated) simple columnar epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"The tube is lined by ciliated and non-ciliated simple columnar epithelium; ciliary action plus peristalsis moves the ovum.","cite":"Slides 45, 53 (Uterine Tube histology)"},{"q":"The three tunics of the uterine wall, from outer to inner, are the perimetrium, myometrium, and:","choices":["Adventitia","Endometrium","Serosa","Mucosa propria"],"answer":1,"exp":"The uterine wall has the perimetrium (serosa), myometrium (smooth muscle), and endometrium (inner, hormone-sensitive lining).","cite":"Slides 35, 39 (Uterine Layers)"},{"q":"The myometrium of the uterus is composed primarily of:","choices":["Skeletal muscle","Smooth muscle","Cardiac muscle","Dense regular connective tissue"],"answer":1,"exp":"The myometrium is the thick middle tunic of intertwining smooth muscle that distends during pregnancy.","cite":"Slides 35, 39 (Uterine Wall)"},{"q":"The endometrium has two layers; which layer builds up and sheds each month in response to ovarian hormones?","choices":["Stratum basalis","Myometrium","Perimetrium","Stratum functionalis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The stratum functionalis builds up monthly and sloughs at menstruation; the stratum basalis regenerates it.","cite":"Slide 43 (Endometrium)"},{"q":"The vaginal wall consists of three tunics: an inner mucosa, a middle muscularis, and an outer:","choices":["Serosa","Perimetrium","Adventitia","Submucosa"],"answer":2,"exp":"The vagina's wall is an inner mucosa, middle muscularis, and outer adventitia.","cite":"Slide 56 (Vagina)"},{"q":"An ovarian follicle consists of an oocyte surrounded by:","choices":["Chromaffin cells","Podocytes","Follicular cells","Chief cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ovarian follicle is composed of an oocyte and surrounding follicular cells.","cite":"Slides 25–26 (Ovaries follicle structure)"},{"q":"At menstruation, the functional layer self-digests as the spiral arteries kink and constrict; just before flow, the spiral arteries open wide and:","choices":["Capillaries burst, sloughing the functional layer","The basalis is shed","The myometrium contracts permanently","The perimetrium thickens"],"answer":0,"exp":"Just before menses, spiral arteries dilate, capillaries burst, and the functional layer sloughs off.","cite":"Slide 43 (Endometrium)"},{"q":"Peritoneum folding around the pelvic organs creates the anterior vesicouterine pouch between the uterus and the:","choices":["Rectum","Sacrum","Urinary bladder","Sigmoid colon"],"answer":2,"exp":"The vesicouterine pouch is the anterior recess between the uterus and the urinary bladder.","cite":"Slide 12 (peritoneal pouches)"},{"q":"The posterior rectouterine pouch (of Douglas) forms the space between the uterus anteriorly and the:","choices":["Bladder","Vagina","Rectum","Ovary"],"answer":2,"exp":"The rectouterine pouch lies between the uterus (anterior) and the rectum (posterior).","cite":"Slide 12 (peritoneal pouches)"},{"q":"The outer serosal covering of most of the uterus, continuous with the broad ligament, is the:","choices":["Adventitia","Myometrium","Endometrium","Perimetrium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The perimetrium is the serosa (visceral peritoneum) covering most of the uterus and is continuous with the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 39 (Wall of the Uterus)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the uterus is best described as:","choices":["Intraperitoneal","Retroperitoneal","Subperitoneal only","Completely extraperitoneal"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterus is intraperitoneal, draped by the broad ligament (peritoneal fold).","cite":"Slide 31 (Uterus)"},{"q":"The ovary lies in which relationship to the broad ligament?","choices":["Anterior to the broad ligament","Inferior to the vagina","Within the myometrium","Posterior to the broad ligament (via the mesovarium)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ovary lies posterior to the broad ligament, attached by the mesovarium.","cite":"Slide 24 (Ovary)"},{"q":"The boundaries of the female perineum include the mons pubis, the medial aspects of the thighs, and the gluteal folds; the tip of which bone is palpable at the superior end of the intergluteal cleft?","choices":["Ischium","Coccyx","Pubis","Sacral promontory"],"answer":1,"exp":"The tip of the coccyx is palpable at the superior end of the intergluteal cleft, marking the posterior perineal boundary.","cite":"Slide 8 (Boundaries of Female Perineum)"},{"q":"The vestibule of the female external genitalia is the region enclosed by the labia minora that contains the openings of the urethra, the vagina, and the:","choices":["Anus","Ureters","Vestibular (Bartholin's) glands","Ejaculatory ducts"],"answer":2,"exp":"The vestibule contains the urethral orifice, vaginal orifice, and openings of the vestibular glands.","cite":"Slide 70 (External Genitalia)"},{"q":"During defecation, the levator ani of the pelvic diaphragm acts to:","choices":["Permanently close the anus","Lift to help release feces","Produce peristalsis in the colon","Secrete mucus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The levator ani lifts to help release feces during defecation, in addition to supporting the pelvic organs.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"Lymphatic drainage of the ovaries follows the ovarian blood vessels to ascend to which nodes?","choices":["Superficial inguinal nodes","Popliteal nodes","Internal iliac nodes only","Lumbar (para-aortic) lymph nodes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Ovarian lymphatics follow the ovarian vessels to the lumbar (para-aortic) nodes; the uterine tube also drains to lumbar nodes.","cite":"Slides 27, 48 (ovarian/tubal lymphatics)"},{"q":"The fimbriae are finger-like projections located at which part of the uterine tube?","choices":["The isthmus","The infundibulum","The intramural segment","The ampulla"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fimbriae are at the distal infundibulum, sweeping the ovulated oocyte into the tube.","cite":"Slide 51 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The perimetrium, the outer uterine tunic, is specifically a:","choices":["Mucosa","Muscularis","Serosa (peritoneum with thin connective tissue)","Submucosa"],"answer":2,"exp":"The perimetrium is a serosa — peritoneum plus thin connective tissue — continuous with the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 35 (Uterine Layers)"},{"q":"The broad ligament extends from the lateral uterine fold to which structure?","choices":["The sacrum","The bladder","The labia majora","The wall of the pelvis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The broad ligament extends from the lateral uterine fold to the wall of the pelvis and also holds the ovaries and uterine tubes.","cite":"Slide 18 (Supporting Ligaments)"}]},"anatomy-gi-i-ii-2":{"title":"Gastrointestinal Tract I & II (Set 2)","questions":[{"q":"The abdomen is commonly divided into four quadrants by which two intersecting planes?","choices":["A midsagittal (vertical) plane and a transumbilical (horizontal) plane","Two oblique subcostal planes","The transpyloric and intertubercular planes only","Two midclavicular vertical planes"],"answer":0,"exp":"The four-quadrant scheme uses a vertical median plane and a horizontal transumbilical plane intersecting at the umbilicus, producing RUQ, LUQ, RLQ, and LLQ.","cite":"Slide 4 (abdominal planes)"},{"q":"On the cadaver-abdomen key, the cecum and most of the ascending colon are found in which region?","choices":["Right lower / right side","Left upper quadrant","Epigastric region","Left lower quadrant"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cadaver key places the cecum and ascending colon on the right side of the abdomen (right lower to right flank), framing the small intestine.","cite":"Slide 6 (Key to Cadaver Abdomen)"},{"q":"Which viscus is identified on the cadaver key as lying in the left upper region alongside the stomach?","choices":["Appendix","Sigmoid colon","Cecum","Left lobe of the liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cadaver key lists the left lobe of the liver and stomach among the upper structures, with the falciform ligament separating the liver lobes.","cite":"Slide 6 (Key to Cadaver Abdomen)"},{"q":"The peritoneum is best classified as which type of membrane?","choices":["Mucous membrane","Synovial membrane","Cutaneous membrane","Serous membrane"],"answer":3,"exp":"The peritoneum is a serous membrane that lines the abdomen and pelvis, with parietal and visceral layers enclosing the peritoneal cavity.","cite":"Slide 13 (Peritoneum)"},{"q":"Which layer of peritoneum directly covers the surface of abdominal organs such as the stomach?","choices":["Visceral peritoneum","Parietal peritoneum","Transversalis fascia","Renal fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"Visceral peritoneum invests the organs themselves; parietal peritoneum lines the abdominal/pelvic walls.","cite":"Slide 13 (Peritoneum)"},{"q":"The greater omentum characteristically extends from which structure?","choices":["The lesser curvature of the stomach","The root of the mesentery","The porta hepatis","The greater curvature of the stomach"],"answer":3,"exp":"The greater omentum hangs from the greater curvature of the stomach, draping over the transverse colon and small bowel.","cite":"Slide 19 (Greater Omentum)"},{"q":"The lesser omentum extends from the porta hepatis to the lesser curvature and consists of which two ligaments?","choices":["Gastrosplenic and splenorenal ligaments","Falciform and coronary ligaments","Hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments","Phrenicocolic and triangular ligaments"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser omentum comprises the hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments running from the liver to the lesser curvature and duodenal bulb.","cite":"Slide 21 (Peritoneal Reflections)"},{"q":"The root of the mesentery proper runs from the duodenojejunal flexure to which landmark, suspending the jejunum and ileum?","choices":["The right iliac fossa","The left colic flexure","The porta hepatis","The pelvic brim at the pubis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mesentery proper's root extends from the duodenojejunal flexure to the right iliac fossa and carries vessels, lymphatics, and nerves between its layers.","cite":"Slide 22 (Mesentery)"},{"q":"A retroperitoneal organ is one that:","choices":["Lies behind the peritoneum with peritoneum covering only its anterior surface","Is completely surrounded by visceral peritoneum and suspended by a mesentery","Floats freely in the peritoneal cavity","Is enclosed in the lesser sac"],"answer":0,"exp":"Retroperitoneal organs (e.g., pancreas, ascending/descending colon, duodenum parts) lie posterior to the peritoneum, which covers only their anterior aspect.","cite":"Slides 66, 93, 96, 130 (retroperitoneal organs)"},{"q":"The GI tract is described as a continuous tube from mouth to anus with an approximate length of:","choices":["About 3 feet (1 meter)","About 30 feet (9–10 meters)","About 60 feet (18 meters)","About 10 feet (3 meters)"],"answer":1,"exp":"The alimentary canal runs about 30 feet (9–10 m) from mouth to anus, with smooth muscle in the wall responsible for motility.","cite":"Slide 8 (General Structure)"},{"q":"Which of the following is an ACCESSORY digestive organ rather than part of the GI tube itself?","choices":["Esophagus","Stomach","Liver","Large intestine"],"answer":2,"exp":"Accessory organs (teeth, tongue, salivary glands, liver, gallbladder, pancreas) do not form the tube but aid digestion; the esophagus, stomach, and intestines form the tube.","cite":"Slide 9 (Accessory digestive organs)"},{"q":"The enteric nervous system provides the intrinsic innervation of the gut and is distributed in how many intramuscular plexuses running the length of the gut?","choices":["One","Four","Three","Two"],"answer":3,"exp":"The enteric nervous system is distributed in two intramuscular plexuses that extend along the gut and coordinate smooth muscle activity; the tract is primarily parasympathetically innervated.","cite":"Slide 12 (Special Features)"},{"q":"Longitudinal folds in the stomach that disappear as the tract fills are called:","choices":["Plicae circulares","Villi","Haustra","Rugae"],"answer":3,"exp":"Rugae are temporary longitudinal folds that flatten as the stomach fills; plicae circulares are permanent transverse folds of the small intestine.","cite":"Slide 12 (Folding); Slide 63 (Plicae)"},{"q":"The mucosal lining of the esophagus is composed of which epithelium?","choices":["Simple columnar epithelium","Nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The esophageal mucosa is nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium, suited to abrasion from passing boluses.","cite":"Slide 42 (Esophagus histology)"},{"q":"Which sequence lists stomach regions correctly from the esophageal inlet toward the duodenum?","choices":["Pylorus → body → fundus → cardia","Body → cardia → fundus → pylorus","Fundus → cardia → pylorus → body","Cardia → fundus → body → pyloric region"],"answer":3,"exp":"Regions run cardia (inlet), fundus (most superior dome), body, then the pyloric region (antrum, canal, sphincter) toward the duodenum.","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"The most superior region of the stomach, which sits under the left dome of the diaphragm, is the:","choices":["Cardia","Antrum","Fundus","Pyloric canal"],"answer":2,"exp":"The fundus is the most superior region of the stomach.","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"Regarding its peritoneal relationship, the stomach is:","choices":["Retroperitoneal","Intraperitoneal","Secondarily retroperitoneal","Subperitoneal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The stomach is an intraperitoneal organ; the slide on the stomach interior explicitly notes 'Intraperitoneal.'","cite":"Slide 58 (Stomach Interior)"},{"q":"The two curvatures of the stomach are the:","choices":["Anterior and posterior curvatures","Greater and lesser curvatures","Superior and inferior curvatures","Medial and lateral curvatures"],"answer":1,"exp":"The stomach has a greater curvature (left/inferior, giving rise to the greater omentum) and a lesser curvature (right/superior, attached to the lesser omentum).","cite":"Slide 54 (Curvatures)"},{"q":"Mucosal specializations of the stomach interior include rugae, a gastric canal, and:","choices":["Villi and microvilli","Taeniae coli","Peyer's patches","Gastric pits leading into gastric glands"],"answer":3,"exp":"The stomach lining shows rugae, a gastric canal, and gastric pits that open into gastric glands; the stomach is intraperitoneal.","cite":"Slide 58 (Stomach Interior)"},{"q":"Which best describes the peritoneal status and rib relationship of the spleen?","choices":["Retroperitoneal, anterior to ribs 5–7","Intraperitoneal, anterior to ribs 1–3","Retroperitoneal, posterior to ribs 11–12","Intraperitoneal, anterior to ribs 9–11"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spleen is intraperitoneal and lies anterior to ribs 9–11 in the left hypochondrium.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"The spleen filters blood; its two functional pulps are:","choices":["Cortex (filtration) and medulla (storage)","White pulp (lymphatic) and red pulp (filters blood)","Alpha pulp and beta pulp","Cortical pulp and hilar pulp"],"answer":1,"exp":"White pulp is lymphatic/hematopoietic tissue; red pulp filters blood. The spleen is supplied by the splenic artery (a branch of the celiac trunk).","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"The arterial supply to the spleen is the splenic artery, which is a branch of the:","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery","Celiac trunk","Inferior mesenteric artery","Left renal artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The splenic artery is one of the three branches of the celiac trunk and courses along the superior margin of the pancreas to the splenic hilum.","cite":"Slides 137, 139 (Splenic Artery / Celiac Trunk)"},{"q":"Which lists the three parts of the small intestine in correct proximal-to-distal order?","choices":["Duodenum → jejunum → ileum","Jejunum → duodenum → ileum","Ileum → jejunum → duodenum","Duodenum → ileum → jejunum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The small intestine runs duodenum (first, ~25 cm), then jejunum, then ileum, ending at the ileocecal valve.","cite":"Slide 61 (Small Intestine)"},{"q":"The duodenum is described as the shortest and widest part and is largely:","choices":["Intraperitoneal","Suspended by a long mesentery","Retroperitoneal","Located in the pelvis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The duodenum is retroperitoneal (except the first part/duodenal cap), C-shaped around the pancreatic head, and ends at the duodenojejunal flexure.","cite":"Slide 66 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"Compared with the ileum, the jejunum characteristically has:","choices":["Larger diameter, thicker walls, more plicae circulares, and greater vascularity","Thinner walls, fewer plicae, and less vascularity","Prominent Peyer's patches and thin walls","No plicae circulares at all"],"answer":0,"exp":"The jejunum (proximal ~40%, mostly LUQ) has a larger diameter, thicker walls, more plicae circulares, and is more vascular; the ileum (distal 60%, RLQ) has thinner walls and prominent Peyer's patches.","cite":"Slides 75, 77 (Jejunum / Ileum)"},{"q":"The terminal ileum ends by joining the large intestine at the:","choices":["Duodenojejunal flexure","Ileocecal (ileocecolic) junction/valve","Hepatic flexure","Rectosigmoid junction"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ileum terminates at the ileocecal valve, which controls entry of material into the cecum and prevents reflux.","cite":"Slides 61, 77 (Ileum terminus)"},{"q":"Permanent transverse folds of the small-intestinal lining that do NOT flatten when the intestine fills are called:","choices":["Rugae","Haustra","Plicae circulares","Taeniae coli"],"answer":2,"exp":"Plicae circulares are permanent transverse folds that increase absorptive surface and persist regardless of filling.","cite":"Slide 63 (Plicae)"},{"q":"Which sequence gives the four segments of the large intestine correctly?","choices":["Cecum → rectum → colon → anal canal","Colon → cecum → anal canal → rectum","Rectum → colon → cecum → anal canal","Cecum → colon → rectum → anal canal"],"answer":3,"exp":"The large intestine comprises the cecum, colon, rectum, and anal canal, framing the small intestine.","cite":"Slide 81 (Large Intestine)"},{"q":"Which portions of the colon are RETROPERITONEAL?","choices":["Transverse and sigmoid colon","Cecum and appendix","Ascending and descending colon","Rectum and sigmoid colon"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ascending and descending colon are retroperitoneal, whereas the transverse and sigmoid colon are intraperitoneal (with mesenteries).","cite":"Slides 93, 96 vs 94, 98 (colon segments)"},{"q":"The three longitudinal muscle bands of the colon, absent in the rectum and appendix, are the:","choices":["Plicae circulares","Haustra","Taeniae coli","Omental appendices"],"answer":2,"exp":"Three taeniae coli run the colon's length; their tone forms the haustra (sacculations). They are absent in the rectum and appendix.","cite":"Slide 91 (Large Intestine specializations)"},{"q":"Which statement about the appendix is correct per the lecture?","choices":["It secretes most digestive enzymes","It is the widest part of the large intestine","It is retroperitoneal and lacks lymphoid tissue","It is a slender hollow appendage dominated by lymphoid nodules, fixed by the mesoappendix"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vermiform appendix is a narrow lymphoid organ attached to the cecum and anchored by the mesoappendix.","cite":"Slides 85, 87 (Cecum and Appendix)"},{"q":"The transverse colon differs from the ascending colon in that it is:","choices":["Retroperitoneal and fixed","Devoid of haustra","The narrowest colonic segment","The most mobile portion, intraperitoneal with a transverse mesocolon"],"answer":3,"exp":"The transverse colon is the most mobile, longest, intraperitoneal segment, suspended by the transverse mesocolon between the two colic flexures.","cite":"Slide 94 (Transverse Colon)"},{"q":"Which feature distinguishes the colonic mucosa from the small intestine?","choices":["Abundant villi and enzyme production","Lack of villi, abundant goblet cells, and no enzyme production","Presence of plicae circulares","Nonkeratinized squamous epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The colon lacks villi, is rich in goblet cells for lubrication, absorbs <10% of GI content, and produces no digestive enzymes.","cite":"Slide 88 (Characteristics of the Colon)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the pancreas is:","choices":["Intraperitoneal","Subperitoneal","Retroperitoneal","Suspended by the transverse mesocolon"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pancreas is a retroperitoneal organ lying at roughly T12–L3 level.","cite":"Slide 130 (The Pancreas)"},{"q":"Which lists the regions of the pancreas?","choices":["Fundus, body, antrum, pylorus","Head, uncinate process, neck, body, and tail","Superior pole, hilum, inferior pole","Cortex, medulla, and hilum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pancreas has a head (with uncinate process), neck, body, and tail, plus main and accessory pancreatic ducts.","cite":"Slide 130 (The Pancreas)"},{"q":"The tail of the pancreas is anatomically related to which structure?","choices":["The hilum of the spleen","The porta hepatis","The right kidney","The gallbladder fundus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The tail of the pancreas reaches the hilum of the spleen; the head fills the C of the duodenum and the body crosses the left kidney.","cite":"Slide 56 (Pancreas relationships)"},{"q":"The endocrine tissue of the pancreas is organized into scattered clusters called:","choices":["Pancreatic islets (islets of Langerhans)","Pancreatic acini","Brunner's glands","Peyer's patches"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pancreatic islets are the endocrine tissue (~1% of pancreatic cells) scattered among the exocrine acini.","cite":"Slide 132 (Pancreatic Islets)"},{"q":"Posterior to the pancreas, which large vessels lie behind the gland?","choices":["Portal vein and hepatic artery only","Aorta and IVC","Left and right renal arteries only","Superior and inferior mesenteric veins only"],"answer":1,"exp":"The aorta and IVC lie posterior to the pancreas; the uncinate process passes behind the SMA/SMV and anterior to the aorta.","cite":"Slide 57 (Pancreas posterior relations)"},{"q":"Which four lobes of the liver are named in the lecture?","choices":["Cranial, caudal, hilar, and marginal","Superior, inferior, medial, and lateral","Anterior, posterior, right, and left","Right, left, quadrate, and caudate"],"answer":3,"exp":"The liver has right (largest), left, quadrate, and caudate lobes.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The caudate lobe of the liver lies between which two structures?","choices":["The gallbladder and the ligamentum teres","The falciform ligament and the right lobe","The inferior vena cava and the ligamentum venosum","The porta hepatis and the fundus of the gallbladder"],"answer":2,"exp":"The caudate lobe sits between the IVC and the ligamentum venosum; the quadrate lobe lies between the gallbladder and the ligamentum teres.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The left lobe of the liver is separated from the right lobe on the diaphragmatic surface by the:","choices":["Coronary ligament","Falciform ligament","Round ligament of the ovary","Phrenicocolic ligament"],"answer":1,"exp":"The falciform ligament separates the left lobe from the right lobe and carries the ligamentum teres in its free edge.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The liver is completely covered by a fibrous capsule known as:","choices":["Gerota's fascia","Tunica albuginea","Glisson's capsule","Buck's fascia"],"answer":2,"exp":"Glisson's capsule completely covers the liver; peritoneum covers it incompletely (leaving the bare area).","cite":"Slide 104 (The Liver)"},{"q":"Within the hepatic portal triad, which structure carries nutrient-rich blood that requires metabolic processing?","choices":["The hepatic vein","The portal vein","The hepatic (biliary) artery","The bile duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The portal vein delivers blood needing metabolic processing; the hepatic artery supplies ~15% of hepatic flow, and hepatic veins drain to the IVC.","cite":"Slides 108, 121 (Liver blood supply / histology)"},{"q":"The splenic vein terminates by joining which vein to help form the hepatic portal vein?","choices":["The inferior vena cava directly","The azygos vein","The left renal vein","The superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The splenic vein runs on the posterior pancreas and joins the superior mesenteric vein to form the portal vein.","cite":"Slides 62, 135 (Splenic/pancreatic venous drainage)"},{"q":"After perfusing the hepatic sinusoids, blood ultimately leaves the liver via the hepatic veins, which drain into the:","choices":["Inferior vena cava","Portal vein","Splenic vein","Superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hepatic veins drain the processed blood into the inferior vena cava for return to the right atrium.","cite":"Slide 121 (Histology of the liver)"},{"q":"The three anatomical parts of the gallbladder are the:","choices":["Head, body, and tail","Root, shaft, and apex","Cardia, fundus, and antrum","Fundus, body, and neck"],"answer":3,"exp":"The gallbladder has a fundus, body, and neck; it lies between the right and quadrate lobes of the liver.","cite":"Slide 126 (The Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The gallbladder is positioned between which two lobes of the liver?","choices":["The caudate and left lobes","The right and quadrate lobes","The left and quadrate lobes","The caudate and right lobes"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gallbladder neck lies between the right and quadrate lobes of the liver.","cite":"Slide 126 (The Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The common bile duct passes behind the first part of the duodenum, through the pancreatic head, and terminates at the:","choices":["Duodenojejunal flexure","Ampulla of Vater (major duodenal papilla)","Minor papilla only","Pylorus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The common bile duct joins the main pancreatic duct at the ampulla of Vater, opening at the major duodenal papilla.","cite":"Slide 64 (Common Bile Duct)"},{"q":"The celiac trunk arises at the aortic hiatus and gives which three branches?","choices":["Left gastric, right gastric, and cystic arteries","Superior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric, and renal arteries","Left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries","Splenic, renal, and gonadal arteries"],"answer":2,"exp":"The celiac trunk branches into the left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries, supplying foregut derivatives.","cite":"Slide 139 (Arterial Supply of the Abdomen)"},{"q":"Which unpaired branch of the abdominal aorta supplies midgut structures including the jejunum, ileum, and proximal colon?","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery","Celiac trunk","Inferior mesenteric artery","Median sacral artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The superior mesenteric artery supplies midgut derivatives (small intestine and colon to the splenic-flexure region).","cite":"Slide 143 (Superior Mesenteric Artery)"},{"q":"The common hepatic artery gives off the gastroduodenal artery and continues as the proper hepatic artery, which supplies the:","choices":["Liver via right and left hepatic branches (with the cystic artery to the gallbladder)","Spleen and tail of the pancreas","Descending colon","Sigmoid colon and rectum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The proper hepatic artery divides into right and left hepatic arteries; the cystic artery (to the gallbladder) typically arises from the right hepatic. The right gastric and gastroduodenal also branch from this system.","cite":"Slide 142 (Common Hepatic Artery)"},{"q":"The left gastric artery, a direct celiac branch, supplies the lesser curvature and gives off which additional branches?","choices":["Cystic branches","Renal branches","Esophageal branches","Gonadal branches"],"answer":2,"exp":"The left gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach and gives esophageal branches.","cite":"Slide 139 (Celiac Trunk branches)"},{"q":"The inferior mesenteric artery supplies hindgut derivatives, which include the:","choices":["Descending colon, sigmoid colon, and rectum","Stomach and spleen","Duodenum and pancreatic head","Liver and gallbladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The IMA supplies the hindgut: distal transverse/descending colon, sigmoid colon, and upper rectum.","cite":"Slides 144–145 (Inferior Mesenteric Artery)"},{"q":"The inferior vena cava is formed by the union of the:","choices":["Two common iliac veins","Two renal veins","The splenic and superior mesenteric veins","The hepatic and azygos veins"],"answer":0,"exp":"The IVC begins at the confluence of the two common iliac veins and ascends to the right atrium.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Which of the following is a direct tributary of the inferior vena cava?","choices":["Left gastric vein","Splenic vein","Renal veins","Superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"Direct IVC tributaries include the renal, hepatic, right gonadal, right suprarenal, inferior phrenic, and lumbar/azygos-related veins. The splenic, SMV, and gastric veins drain via the portal system instead.","cite":"Slide 146 (IVC tributaries)"},{"q":"The RIGHT gonadal and right suprarenal veins typically drain directly into the IVC, whereas the LEFT gonadal and suprarenal veins drain into the:","choices":["Portal vein","Splenic vein","Azygos vein","Left renal vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"On the left, the gonadal and suprarenal veins drain into the left renal vein, which then joins the IVC; on the right they enter the IVC directly.","cite":"Slide 146 (IVC tributaries)"},{"q":"The hepatic veins are notable tributaries of the IVC because they:","choices":["Carry oxygenated blood from the hepatic artery only","Drain the spleen directly","Deliver the liver's processed (portal + arterial) blood to the IVC just below the diaphragm","Return blood to the portal vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hepatic veins deliver the liver's outflow to the IVC near the diaphragm, completing the portal-then-systemic return.","cite":"Slides 121, 146 (Hepatic veins / IVC)"},{"q":"Lymph from the abdominal viscera ultimately collects into a dilated sac at the origin of the thoracic duct called the:","choices":["Cysterna magna","Cisterna chyli","Ampulla of Vater","Pouch of Douglas"],"answer":1,"exp":"Abdominal lymphatic trunks converge on the cisterna chyli, the origin of the thoracic duct that carries lymph toward the venous system.","cite":"Slide 14 / IO14 (abdominal lymph drainage)"},{"q":"Abdominal lymphatic vessels characteristically travel alongside which structures?","choices":["The peripheral nerves only","The ureters","The major arteries (e.g., celiac, SMA, IMA nodal groups)","The bile ducts exclusively"],"answer":2,"exp":"Visceral lymph nodes are arranged around the major arterial branches (celiac, superior and inferior mesenteric), draining the organs those arteries supply toward the cisterna chyli.","cite":"Slide 14 (abdominal lymph drainage)"},{"q":"The esophagus, which drains partly into abdominal lymphatics, also has venous drainage into both the azygos vein and the:","choices":["Portal vein","Renal vein","Splenic vein directly","Gonadal vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"Esophageal venous drainage goes to both the portal vein (via left gastric) and the azygos system — a site of portosystemic anastomosis clinically relevant for varices.","cite":"Slide 41 (Esophagus venous drainage)"}]},"male-reproductive-2":{"title":"Male Reproductive System (Set 2)","questions":[{"q":"During development, the testes first form inside the abdominal cavity near which organs?","choices":["The kidneys","The liver","The spleen","The adrenal glands"],"answer":0,"exp":"The testes develop inside the abdominal cavity near the kidneys before descending toward the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which structure holds the testes in place and, by not elongating during body growth, pulls them inferiorly toward the scrotum?","choices":["The spermatic cord","The gubernaculum testis","The tunica albuginea","The pampiniform plexus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gubernaculum testis anchors the testes; as the body grows it fails to elongate, drawing the testes downward through the inguinal canals.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"As the testes descend, they pass through which passage that connects the scrotal chambers to the peritoneal cavity?","choices":["The inguinal canals","The obturator foramen","The greater sciatic foramen","The femoral canal"],"answer":0,"exp":"The testes descend through the inguinal canals; the ductus deferens, vessels, lymphatics, and nerves remain bundled with them in the spermatic cords.","cite":"Slides 9, 14 (Descent / Spermatic cords)"},{"q":"The requirement that sperm develop at ~2°F below core body temperature explains why:","choices":["The testes remain in the abdomen","The prostate enlarges with age","The testes descend to the external scrotum","Sperm mature within the seminal vesicles"],"answer":2,"exp":"Sperm development needs ~96.6°F (about 2°F cooler than body temperature), so the testes reside in the external scrotum.","cite":"Slide 10 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which superficial smooth muscle of the scrotum wrinkles the scrotal skin when it contracts?","choices":["Cremaster muscle","Bulbospongiosus","Dartos muscle","Ischiocavernosus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The dartos is a superficial smooth muscle whose contraction wrinkles the scrotal surface; the cremaster elevates the testes.","cite":"Slide 18 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"Contraction of the cremaster muscle produces which effect?","choices":["Tensing the scrotal sac and pulling the testes closer to the body","Wrinkling of the scrotal skin","Ejaculation of semen","Erection of the penis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cremaster tenses the scrotal sac and elevates the testes toward the body to maintain sperm-appropriate temperature.","cite":"Slide 19 (Cremaster muscle)"},{"q":"During ejaculation, forceful contractions of which two muscles push semen toward the external urethral orifice?","choices":["Dartos and cremaster","Ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus","Puborectalis and pubococcygeus","Rectus abdominis and transversus abdominis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ejaculation involves powerful contractions of the ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus muscles.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The scrotum is highly vascularized by the internal pudendal artery, the external pudendal artery, and the:","choices":["Middle rectal artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Obturator artery","Inferior epigastric artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"Scrotal supply comes from the internal pudendal (from internal iliac), external pudendal (from femoral), and inferior epigastric (from external iliac) arteries.","cite":"Slide 21 (Scrotum vascularization)"},{"q":"The internal pudendal artery supplying pelvic/reproductive structures is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["Femoral artery","Internal iliac artery","External iliac artery","Abdominal aorta directly"],"answer":1,"exp":"The internal pudendal artery arises from the internal iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 21 (Scrotum vascularization)"},{"q":"The external pudendal artery is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["Splenic artery","Internal iliac artery","Inferior mesenteric artery","Femoral artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"The external pudendal artery is a branch of the femoral artery.","cite":"Slide 21 (Scrotum vascularization)"},{"q":"Within the spermatic cord, the venous drainage of the testis forms a network called the:","choices":["Vesical venous plexus","Prostatic venous plexus","Pampiniform plexus","Vertebral venous plexus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus of the testicular vein is a component of the spermatic cord and aids in cooling arterial blood to the testis.","cite":"Slide 14 (The Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"The deep artery of the penis, responsible for engorging erectile tissue, lies in the center of which structure?","choices":["The corpus spongiosum","The bulb of the penis","Each corpus cavernosum","The glans penis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The deep artery of the penis runs in the center of each corpus cavernosum.","cite":"Slide 62 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The scrotum receives sensory and motor nerves from the hypogastric plexus, the pudendal nerves, the genitofemoral nerves, and the:","choices":["Femoral nerves","Phrenic nerves","Obturator nerves","Ilioinguinal nerves"],"answer":3,"exp":"Scrotal innervation includes the hypogastric plexus, ilioinguinal, genitofemoral, and pudendal nerves.","cite":"Slide 22 (Scrotum innervation)"},{"q":"Which two nerves are named as components running with the spermatic cord?","choices":["Vagus and phrenic nerves","Pudendal and obturator nerves","Femoral and sciatic nerves","Ilioinguinal and genitofemoral nerves"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spermatic cord contains the ilioinguinal and genitofemoral nerves along with the ductus deferens and vessels.","cite":"Slide 14 (The Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"Erection of the penis is mediated by which division of the autonomic nervous system?","choices":["Sympathetic nerves","Parasympathetic nerves","Somatic motor nerves only","The enteric nervous system"],"answer":1,"exp":"Parasympathetic activation relaxes arterial smooth muscle, dilating vessels and engorging erectile tissue to produce an erection ('point' = parasympathetic).","cite":"Slide 66 (Erection of the penis)"},{"q":"Emission and ejaculation of semen are primarily driven by which autonomic activity?","choices":["Parasympathetic activity","Purely voluntary control","Vagal activity","Sympathetic activity"],"answer":3,"exp":"Emission and ejaculation are driven by sympathetic activity ('shoot' = sympathetic), mixing sperm with glandular secretions and expelling semen.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"Which fibrous connective-tissue layer directly lines the testis and sends septa that converge at the mediastinum of the testis?","choices":["Tunica albuginea","Tunica vaginalis","Dartos fascia","Cremasteric fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The tunica albuginea lines the testis and forms septa converging toward the mediastinum, which supports the ducts leading to the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 23 (Structure of the Testes)"},{"q":"The serous membrane that surrounds the tunica albuginea and reduces friction within each scrotal cavity is the:","choices":["Glisson's capsule","Dartos muscle","Buck's fascia","Tunica vaginalis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The tunica vaginalis is a serous membrane lining each scrotal cavity, continuous with the epididymal covering, reducing friction.","cite":"Slides 16, 23 (Tunica vaginalis)"},{"q":"Within each testicular lobule, sperm are produced in tightly coiled tubules called:","choices":["Efferent ductules","Collecting ducts","Seminiferous tubules","Straight tubules"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each lobule contains coiled seminiferous tubules (~80 cm each) where spermatogenesis occurs.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly traces sperm through the intratesticular ducts?","choices":["Seminiferous tubules → straight tubules → rete testis → efferent ductules → epididymis","Rete testis → seminiferous tubules → epididymis → efferent ductules","Efferent ductules → rete testis → seminiferous tubules → epididymis","Epididymis → rete testis → straight tubules → seminiferous tubules"],"answer":0,"exp":"Sperm pass from seminiferous tubules to straight tubules, then the rete testis (in the mediastinum), then efferent ductules to the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"The interstitial endocrine cells (Leydig cells) located between the seminiferous tubules produce:","choices":["Testosterone","Inhibin","Androgen-binding protein","Fructose"],"answer":0,"exp":"Leydig (interstitial endocrine) cells produce and release testosterone.","cite":"Slide 27 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"The nurse cells (Sertoli cells) of the seminiferous tubules maintain the blood–testis barrier and secrete inhibin plus:","choices":["Testosterone","Prostaglandins","Fructose","Androgen-binding protein (ABP)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Sertoli (nurse) cells secrete inhibin (controls sperm formation rate) and androgen-binding protein, and maintain the blood–testis barrier to prevent autoimmune destruction of sperm.","cite":"Slide 36 (Nurse Cells)"},{"q":"The epididymis is divided into three parts; which part receives spermatozoa from the efferent ductules?","choices":["The tail","The body","The head","The isthmus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The head of the epididymis receives spermatozoa via the efferent ducts; the tail uncoils to become the ductus deferens.","cite":"Slide 42 (The Epididymis)"},{"q":"Which three glands are the accessory glands of the male reproductive system?","choices":["Parotid, submandibular, and sublingual glands","Seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands","Adrenal, thyroid, and parathyroid glands","Cowper's, Bartholin's, and Skene's glands"],"answer":1,"exp":"The accessory glands are the seminal glands (vesicles), the prostate, and the bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) glands.","cite":"Slide 53 (The Accessory Glands)"},{"q":"The seminal glands produce approximately what percentage of the semen volume, with fluid rich in fructose, prostaglandins, and clotting factors?","choices":["5 percent","20–30 percent","60 percent","95 percent"],"answer":2,"exp":"The seminal glands produce ~60% of semen volume; fructose provides energy for sperm motility.","cite":"Slide 55 (The Seminal Glands)"},{"q":"The prostate secretes a weakly acidic fluid comprising about 20–30% of semen volume that contains enzymes and an antibiotic substance called:","choices":["Seminalplasmin","Hyaluronidase","Inhibin","Androgen-binding protein"],"answer":0,"exp":"Prostatic fluid (20–30% of semen) is weakly acidic and contains seminalplasmin, an antibiotic thought to prevent UTIs in males.","cite":"Slide 56 (The Prostate)"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) glands secrete a thick alkaline mucus that neutralizes urinary acids and:","choices":["Provides energy via fructose","Triggers erection","Provides lubrication for the tip of the penis","Coagulates semen in the vagina"],"answer":2,"exp":"Bulbo-urethral secretions (~5% of semen) are alkaline mucus that neutralize residual urinary acid and lubricate the penile tip.","cite":"Slide 57 (Bulbo-urethral Glands)"},{"q":"The penis contains three columns of erectile tissue: two posterior corpora cavernosa and one anterior:","choices":["Corpus callosum","Corpus luteum","Corpus spongiosum","Glans column"],"answer":2,"exp":"The penis has two dorsal/posterior corpora cavernosa and one ventral/anterior corpus spongiosum surrounding the spongy urethra.","cite":"Slide 61 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The corpus spongiosum surrounds the spongy urethra and its thickened proximal end forms the:","choices":["Crus of the penis","Prepuce","Glans penis","Bulb of the penis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The corpus spongiosum's proximal enlargement forms the bulb of the penis; each corpus cavernosum extends posteriorly as a crus bound to the ischial ramus.","cite":"Slide 62 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The head of a spermatozoon contains chromosomes and an enzyme-filled cap essential for fertilization called the:","choices":["Acrosome","Flagellum","Centriole","Mitochondrial spiral"],"answer":0,"exp":"The sperm head contains the acrosome (with hyaluronidase) needed to penetrate the egg; the midpiece holds mitochondria and the tail is the flagellum.","cite":"Slide 38 (Anatomy of a Sperm)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly traces the pathway of sperm from production to the ejaculatory duct?","choices":["Ductus deferens → epididymis → seminiferous tubules → ejaculatory duct","Seminiferous tubules → epididymis → ductus deferens → ejaculatory duct","Epididymis → seminiferous tubules → ejaculatory duct → ductus deferens","Ejaculatory duct → ductus deferens → epididymis → seminiferous tubules"],"answer":1,"exp":"Sperm form in the seminiferous tubules, mature/store in the epididymis, travel up the ductus deferens, and enter the ejaculatory duct.","cite":"Slides 25, 42, 47–48 (sperm pathway)"},{"q":"Before entering the prostate, the ductus deferens expands into the ampulla, which joins the excretory duct of the seminal gland to form the:","choices":["Ejaculatory duct","Prostatic urethra","Membranous urethra","Efferent ductule"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ampulla of the ductus deferens joins the seminal gland's excretory duct to form the ejaculatory duct, which empties into the prostatic urethra.","cite":"Slide 48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"The ejaculatory duct empties into which part of the urethra?","choices":["External urethral orifice","Membranous urethra","Spongy urethra","Prostatic urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ejaculatory duct empties into the prostatic urethra within the prostate gland.","cite":"Slide 48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"Mature sperm stored in the epididymis are not yet able to fertilize an egg until they undergo which process outside the epididymis?","choices":["Spermiogenesis","Spermatogenesis","Meiosis I","Capacitation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Capacitation occurs outside the epididymis: sperm become motile when mixed with seminal-gland secretions and gain fertilizing ability in the female tract.","cite":"Slides 44–45 (The Epididymis)"},{"q":"The ductus deferens ascends from the tail of the epididymis into the abdomen through which passage?","choices":["The femoral canal","The inguinal canal","The obturator canal","The pudendal canal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ductus (vas) deferens ascends through the inguinal canal, then curves around the bladder and ureter toward the prostate.","cite":"Slides 47–48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"Approximately what percentage of semen volume comes from the prostate during ejaculation?","choices":["30 percent","5 percent","60 percent","90 percent"],"answer":0,"exp":"Semen composition is ~60% seminal vesicles, ~30% prostate, ~5% bulbo-urethral glands, and ~5% epididymis.","cite":"Slide 59 (Semen)"},{"q":"The male urethra is divided into three regions in which correct proximal-to-distal order?","choices":["Prostatic → membranous → spongy (penile)","Spongy → membranous → prostatic","Membranous → prostatic → spongy","Prostatic → spongy → membranous"],"answer":0,"exp":"From bladder to tip: prostatic urethra (through the prostate), membranous urethra (through the pelvic floor/UG diaphragm), then spongy/penile urethra.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The prostatic urethra is the portion of the urethra that:","choices":["Passes through the penis","Extends from the bladder through the prostate gland","Passes through the muscular wall of the pelvic cavity","Ends at the external urethral orifice"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prostatic urethra extends from the urinary bladder through the prostate gland.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The membranous urethra is characterized by:","choices":["Passing through the prostate","Passing through the muscular wall of the pelvic cavity (pelvic floor)","Passing through the penile shaft","Being the terminal segment at the glans"],"answer":1,"exp":"The membranous urethra passes through the muscular wall/floor of the pelvic cavity between the prostatic and spongy portions.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The spongy (penile) urethra runs within which erectile column and ends at the external urethral orifice?","choices":["Corpus cavernosum","Tunica albuginea","Bulb of the penis crus","Corpus spongiosum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spongy urethra passes through the corpus spongiosum along the length of the penis to the external urethral orifice on the glans.","cite":"Slides 51, 62 (spongy urethra / corpus spongiosum)"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty their secretions into which part of the urethra, just distal to the membranous urethra?","choices":["Prostatic urethra","Directly into the bladder","Spongy urethra","The ejaculatory duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"Bulbo-urethral gland contents empty into the spongy urethra immediately distal to the body wall (end of the membranous urethra).","cite":"Slide 57 (Bulbo-urethral Glands)"},{"q":"The spermatic cords, which remain bundled with the descended testes, contain the ductus deferens, nerves, lymphatics, and:","choices":["The prostate gland","Blood vessels (deferential and testicular arteries, pampiniform plexus)","The seminal vesicles","The ejaculatory duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The spermatic cord contains the ductus deferens, deferential and testicular arteries, pampiniform plexus, lymphatics, and nerves.","cite":"Slide 14 (The Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"Testicle development itself requires a temperature of approximately:","choices":["96.6°F","98.6°F","94.0°F","101.0°F"],"answer":1,"exp":"Testicle development requires ~98.6°F (hence initial abdominal development), whereas sperm development requires the cooler ~96.6°F of the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 10 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Spermatogonia, the stem cells that give rise to sperm, are formed during embryonic development but remain dormant until:","choices":["Birth","The male climacteric","Middle age","Puberty"],"answer":3,"exp":"Spermatogonia form during embryonic development but stay dormant until puberty, when they begin continuous division.","cite":"Slide 30 (Spermatogenesis and Meiosis)"},{"q":"The raphe of the scrotum, which separates the two scrotal cavities, appears as thickened tissue extending from the anus across the scrotum to the:","choices":["Perineal body only","Inguinal ligament","Pubic symphysis","Anterior surface of the penis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The scrotal raphe marks the midline septum and extends from the anus across the scrotum onto the anterior surface of the penis.","cite":"Slide 16 (Scrotum and Position of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which paired muscles contract during ejaculation to help expel semen — the same muscles associated with the penile bulb and crura?","choices":["Bulbospongiosus and ischiocavernosus","Dartos and cremaster","Levator ani and coccygeus","Rectus abdominis and pyramidalis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Bulbospongiosus (over the bulb/corpus spongiosum) and ischiocavernosus (over the crura) contract forcefully during ejaculation.","cite":"Slide 67 (ejaculation muscles)"},{"q":"The inferior epigastric artery, contributing to scrotal supply, is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["Internal iliac artery","External iliac artery","Femoral artery","Abdominal aorta"],"answer":1,"exp":"The inferior epigastric artery is a branch of the external iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 21 (Scrotum vascularization)"},{"q":"The pampiniform plexus surrounding the testicular artery functions primarily to:","choices":["Increase testicular temperature","Produce testosterone","Store mature sperm","Cool arterial blood entering the testis via a countercurrent mechanism"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus wraps the testicular artery, cooling incoming arterial blood to help maintain the lower temperature sperm require.","cite":"Slides 14–15 (Spermatic cord / pampiniform plexus)"},{"q":"Which artery specifically accompanies the ductus deferens within the spermatic cord?","choices":["Deferential artery","Internal pudendal artery","Obturator artery","Inferior vesical artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The deferential artery runs with the ductus deferens in the spermatic cord alongside the testicular artery.","cite":"Slides 14–15 (Spermatic cord vessels)"},{"q":"The genitofemoral nerve, which supplies the scrotum and cremaster, is identified as a component of which structure?","choices":["The pudendal canal","The spermatic cord","The obturator canal","The femoral sheath"],"answer":1,"exp":"The genitofemoral nerve travels with the spermatic cord and contributes motor/sensory supply to the scrotum and cremaster.","cite":"Slides 14–15, 22 (spermatic cord / scrotal innervation)"},{"q":"During emission, sperm are mixed with glandular secretions by peristaltic contraction of smooth muscle in the ductus deferens, seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands under which control?","choices":["Parasympathetic control","Somatic voluntary control","Sympathetic control","Vagal control"],"answer":2,"exp":"Emission is a sympathetic event; peristalsis of the ducts and glands moves sperm and secretions into the urethra prior to ejaculation.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"A single primary spermatocyte undergoing meiosis ultimately gives rise to how many sperm cells?","choices":["Two","One","Four","Eight"],"answer":2,"exp":"A primary spermatocyte yields two secondary spermatocytes (meiosis I), each producing two spermatids (meiosis II), for a total of four haploid sperm.","cite":"Slide 32 (Spermatogenesis and Meiosis)"},{"q":"The physical maturation of spermatids into sperm cells, occurring while embedded in Sertoli (nurse) cells, is called:","choices":["Spermatogenesis","Spermiogenesis","Capacitation","Meiosis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Spermiogenesis is the maturation of spermatids into sperm; capacitation (fertilizing ability) occurs later, outside the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 35 (Spermiogenesis)"},{"q":"The middle piece (with the neck) of a spermatozoon contains mitochondria and:","choices":["The acrosome","Chromosomes","Centrioles","The flagellum tip"],"answer":2,"exp":"The midpiece/neck contains mitochondria (energy) and centrioles; the head holds chromosomes and the acrosome, and the tail is the flagellum.","cite":"Slide 38 (Anatomy of a Sperm)"},{"q":"The blood–testis barrier, maintained by nurse (Sertoli) cells, functions to:","choices":["Produce testosterone","Store mature sperm","Isolate developing sperm from the circulation to prevent autoimmune destruction","Secrete prostatic fluid"],"answer":2,"exp":"Nurse cells form the blood–testis barrier, isolating seminiferous tubules from the circulation so the immune system does not attack developing sperm.","cite":"Slide 36 (Nurse Cells)"},{"q":"The prepuce (foreskin) attaches to the neck of the glans; preputial glands secrete a waxy material called:","choices":["Smegma","Colloid","Seminalplasmin","Meconium"],"answer":0,"exp":"Preputial glands secrete waxy smegma, which can encourage bacterial growth; circumcision removes the prepuce to avoid this.","cite":"Slide 63 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The efferent ductules connect which two structures?","choices":["The epididymis and the prostatic urethra","The seminiferous tubules and the rete testis","The ductus deferens and the ejaculatory duct","The rete testis and the epididymis"],"answer":3,"exp":"Efferent ductules lead from the rete testis (in the mediastinum) to the head of the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"After the tail of the epididymis, the duct that transports sperm toward the abdomen is called the:","choices":["Efferent ductule","Ejaculatory duct","Ductus (vas) deferens","Straight tubule"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ductus deferens (vas deferens) begins at the tail of the epididymis and ascends through the inguinal canal.","cite":"Slide 47 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"Approximately how much semen is released per ejaculation, per the lecture?","choices":["2 to 5 mL","0.5 to 1 mL","10 to 15 mL","20 to 30 mL"],"answer":0,"exp":"Each ejaculation releases about 2–5 mL of semen, with a normal sperm count of 20–100 million per mL.","cite":"Slide 59 (Semen)"},{"q":"The male reproductive tract, involved in maturation, storage, and transport of sperm, consists of the epididymis, the ductus deferens, and the:","choices":["Seminal gland","Urethra","Prostate","Bulbo-urethral gland"],"answer":1,"exp":"The male reproductive tract proper is the epididymis, ductus deferens, and urethra; the seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands are accessory glands.","cite":"Slide 41 (The Male Reproductive Tract)"}]},"nephrology-urinary":{"title":"Nephrology / Urinary System","questions":[{"q":"Which four organs make up the urinary system?","choices":["Kidneys, ureters, prostate, and urethra","Kidneys, adrenal glands, ureters, and bladder","Kidneys, ureters, urinary bladder, and urethra","Nephrons, ureters, bladder, and rectum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The urinary system consists of the kidneys, ureters, urinary bladder, and urethra.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"The primary organs of the urinary system that filter waste and form urine are the:","choices":["Ureters","Urethra","Bladder","Kidneys"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidneys are the primary organs; they filter waste from the bloodstream and convert filtrate into urine.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"The medical term for urination is:","choices":["Micturition","Defecation","Deglutition","Mastication"],"answer":0,"exp":"Micturition is the medical term for urination; the ureters, bladder, and urethra transport urine out of the body.","cite":"Slide 4 (Systems Involved)"},{"q":"The ureters, bladder, and urethra together form the:","choices":["Urinary tract (for transport of urine)","Nephron","Renal corpuscle","Juxtaglomerular apparatus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The urinary tract (ureters, bladder, urethra) transports urine out of the body after the kidneys produce it.","cite":"Slide 4 (Systems Involved)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the kidneys are:","choices":["Intraperitoneal","Suspended by a mesentery","Subperitoneal","Retroperitoneal"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs; the right sits about T12–L3 and the left about T10/11–L2.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The concave medial border of the kidney, where vessels and nerves enter, is the:","choices":["Hilum","Renal sinus","Renal papilla","Renal pelvis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The hilum is the concave medial border through which the nerves, arteries, and veins (NAVs) enter and the renal pelvis exits.","cite":"Slides 6, 10 (Kidney anatomy)"},{"q":"Listing from deep (nearest kidney) to superficial, the tissue layers surrounding the kidney are:","choices":["Renal fascia → fibrous capsule → perinephric fat → paranephric fat","Paranephric fat → renal fascia → perinephric fat → fibrous capsule","Fibrous capsule → perinephric fat → renal fascia → paranephric fat","Perinephric fat → fibrous capsule → paranephric fat → renal fascia"],"answer":2,"exp":"From deep to superficial: fibrous (renal) capsule, perinephric (adipose) fat, renal fascia, then paranephric fat, then peritoneum.","cite":"Slides 11, 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The renal medulla is divided into cone-shaped structures whose apices (renal papillae) point toward the renal sinus; these are the:","choices":["Renal columns","Renal pyramids","Renal calyces","Renal corpuscles"],"answer":1,"exp":"The medulla is divided into 8–15 renal pyramids per kidney; the base abuts the cortex and the apex is the renal papilla.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The cortical tissue that dips between the renal pyramids is called the:","choices":["Renal papilla","Minor calyx","Renal sinus","Renal columns"],"answer":3,"exp":"Renal columns are extensions of cortex between the pyramids.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The internal space of the kidney that houses the vessels, renal pelvis, and calyces (plus fat) is the:","choices":["Renal cortex","Renal sinus","Renal papilla","Bowman's capsule"],"answer":1,"exp":"The renal sinus is the internal space housing blood/lymphatic vessels, nerves, renal pelvis, and calyces, embedded in fat.","cite":"Slide 10 (Gross and Sectional Anatomy)"},{"q":"The dense irregular connective tissue layer that directly covers the outer surface (cortex) of the kidney is the:","choices":["Fibrous (renal) capsule","Renal fascia","Paranephric fat","Peritoneum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The fibrous (renal) capsule is dense irregular connective tissue covering the cortex; the renal fascia anchors the kidney to the posterior wall.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly traces arterial blood from the aorta to the glomerulus?","choices":["Renal artery → afferent arteriole → arcuate → interlobar → glomerulus","Renal artery → arcuate → interlobar → segmental → afferent arteriole → glomerulus","Renal artery → interlobular → arcuate → interlobar → efferent arteriole → glomerulus","Renal artery → segmental → interlobar → arcuate → interlobular → afferent arteriole → glomerulus"],"answer":3,"exp":"Aorta → renal → segmental → lobar → interlobar → arcuate → interlobular → afferent arteriole → glomerulus.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Blood leaves the glomerulus via the efferent arteriole, which then branches into peritubular capillaries or the:","choices":["Interlobar vein","Arcuate artery","Segmental artery","Vasa recta"],"answer":3,"exp":"Efferent arterioles form peritubular capillaries (juxtaposed to the nephron) or the vasa recta, where solute exchange occurs.","cite":"Slide 18 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"The renal vein drains into which large vessel?","choices":["Portal vein","Azygos vein","Inferior vena cava","Superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The renal vein drains to the inferior vena cava; on the left it also receives the gonadal vein.","cite":"Slides 6, 18 (renal venous drainage)"},{"q":"Which sequence traces venous blood correctly from the vasa recta back toward the IVC?","choices":["Vasa recta → arcuate vein → interlobular vein → segmental vein → IVC","Vasa recta → renal vein → arcuate vein → interlobar vein → IVC","Vasa recta → interlobular vein → arcuate vein → interlobar vein → renal vein → IVC","Vasa recta → interlobar vein → interlobular vein → renal vein → IVC"],"answer":2,"exp":"Vasa recta → interlobular vein → arcuate vein → interlobar vein → renal vein → inferior vena cava.","cite":"Slide 18 (Blood Supply, venous)"},{"q":"Blood plasma is filtered across which structure into the glomerular (capsular) space?","choices":["The efferent arteriole","The collecting duct","The vasa recta","The glomerulus"],"answer":3,"exp":"Plasma is filtered across the glomerulus into the glomerular space of Bowman's capsule.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"On the left side, the renal vein additionally receives which vein before draining to the IVC?","choices":["The left gonadal vein","The right gonadal vein","The azygos vein","The splenic vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The left renal vein receives the left gonadal (and left suprarenal) vein before entering the IVC.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The renal corpuscle is composed of the glomerulus and the:","choices":["Proximal convoluted tubule","Loop of Henle","Glomerular (Bowman's) capsule","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The renal corpuscle = glomerulus + glomerular (Bowman's) capsule; it is the filtering unit of the nephron.","cite":"Slide 29 (Nephron Structures)"},{"q":"Which segment of the renal tubule begins at the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle and is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium?","choices":["Distal convoluted tubule","Proximal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct","Ascending limb of Henle"],"answer":1,"exp":"The proximal convoluted tubule begins at the corpuscle's tubular pole and is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium.","cite":"Slide 38 (Proximal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"Which type of nephron has long loops of Henle that extend deep into the medulla and possess vasa recta to concentrate urine?","choices":["Cortical nephrons","Juxtamedullary (medullary) nephrons","Aglomerular nephrons","Superficial nephrons"],"answer":1,"exp":"Juxtamedullary nephrons (~15%) have long loops and vasa recta to recover water/Na+/Cl- and concentrate urine; cortical nephrons (~85%) have short loops and peritubular capillaries.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"Approximately what percentage of nephrons are cortical (short-looped) nephrons producing 'standard' urine?","choices":["85%","50%","15%","5%"],"answer":0,"exp":"About 85% of nephrons are cortical type; ~15% are juxtamedullary.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly traces filtrate through the nephron tubules?","choices":["Collecting duct → DCT → loop of Henle → PCT → glomerulus","DCT → PCT → loop of Henle → collecting duct → papillary duct","PCT → descending limb → loop of Henle → ascending limb → DCT → collecting duct","PCT → DCT → descending limb → ascending limb → collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"Filtrate flows: Bowman's → PCT → descending limb → loop of Henle → ascending limb → DCT → collecting duct → papillary duct.","cite":"Slides 22, 42 (Flow of Urine)"},{"q":"The distal convoluted tubule begins at the end of the thick ascending limb and lies adjacent to the afferent arteriole, forming part of the:","choices":["Renal corpuscle","Juxtaglomerular apparatus","Renal sinus","Vasa recta"],"answer":1,"exp":"The DCT lies next to the afferent arteriole, contributing to the juxtaglomerular apparatus.","cite":"Slide 40 (Distal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The loop of Henle has two limbs; the descending limb runs from the cortex/PCT toward the medulla, and the ascending limb:","choices":["Returns to the renal cortex and leads into the DCT","Continues deeper into the medulla","Empties directly into the minor calyx","Becomes the collecting duct"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ascending limb (thin then thick) returns toward the cortex and leads into the distal convoluted tubule.","cite":"Slide 39 (Loop of Henle)"},{"q":"Once filtrate enters the collecting ducts, it:","choices":["Can no longer be modified and officially becomes urine","Undergoes further extensive modification","Returns to the glomerulus","Is reabsorbed into the vasa recta entirely"],"answer":0,"exp":"No further modification occurs once filtrate is in the collecting ducts; it is now officially urine. Multiple collecting ducts converge at a renal papilla.","cite":"Slide 41 (Collecting Tubule & Ducts)"},{"q":"The ureters are retroperitoneal fibromuscular tubes about how long, conducting urine from the renal pelvis to the bladder?","choices":["About 5 cm","About 50 cm","About 25 cm","About 3 cm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ureters average ~25 cm, are retroperitoneal, originate at the renal pelvis, and enter the posterolateral bladder base.","cite":"Slide 44 (Ureters)"},{"q":"In the 'water under the bridge' relationship, the ureter passes deep/inferior to which vessels bilaterally?","choices":["The renal artery and vein","The common iliac artery only","The testicular or ovarian (gonadal) artery and vein","The inferior vena cava"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ureter travels deep (inferior) to the gonadal (testicular/ovarian) vessels — 'water (ureter) under the bridge (gonadal vessels)'.","cite":"Slide 48 ('Water under the bridge')"},{"q":"The urinary bladder lies immediately superior and posterior to which structure?","choices":["The kidneys","The sacrum","The umbilicus","The pubic symphysis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The bladder lies immediately superior and posterior to the pubic symphysis.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The bladder is a non-peritoneal organ EXCEPT for which wall, which is covered by peritoneum?","choices":["The inferior wall","The anterior wall","The superior wall","The posterior wall"],"answer":2,"exp":"Only the superior wall of the bladder is peritoneal; this affects where bladder pain is sensed.","cite":"Slides 49, 53 (Bladder)"},{"q":"In females, the organ located posterosuperior to the bladder is the:","choices":["Rectum","Prostate","Uterus","Sigmoid colon"],"answer":2,"exp":"In females, the uterus is posterosuperior and the vagina posteroinferior to the bladder; in males the rectum is posterosuperior and the prostate inferior.","cite":"Slide 51 (Urinary Bladder relationships)"},{"q":"The median umbilical ligament, related to the bladder, is a remnant of which fetal structure?","choices":["The gubernaculum","The urachus","The mesonephric duct","The ductus venosus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The median umbilical ligament is the remnant of the urachus, the fetal tube that returned urine to the mother via the umbilical cord.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The blood supply to the bladder runs: aorta → common iliac → internal iliac → anterior division → superior and:","choices":["Inferior mesenteric artery","Inferior vesical arteries","Gonadal arteries","Middle rectal arteries only"],"answer":1,"exp":"The bladder is supplied by the superior and inferior vesical arteries from the anterior division of the internal iliac; venous drainage is via the vesical venous plexus to the internal iliac veins.","cite":"Slide 56 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Approximate urethral length differs by sex: the female urethra is about 3–4 cm, whereas the male urethra is about:","choices":["8–10 cm","2 cm","25 cm","18–20 cm"],"answer":3,"exp":"The female urethra is ~3–4 cm; the male urethra is ~18–20 cm and has prostatic, membranous, and penile (spongy) regions.","cite":"Slides 58–59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"Common sites where kidney stones lodge in the ureter include the ureteropelvic junction, where the ureters cross the common iliac artery, and the:","choices":["Renal papilla","Urethral meatus","Ureterovesical junction","Renal sinus"],"answer":2,"exp":"Stones commonly lodge at the UPJ, at the common iliac crossing, and at the ureterovesical junction — the three natural constrictions.","cite":"Slide 47 (Zones Related to the Ureters)"},{"q":"The membranous portion of the male urethra is distinguished anatomically because it pierces the:","choices":["Urogenital diaphragm","Prostate gland","Corpus spongiosum","Renal fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The membranous urethra runs from the prostatic urethra to the penile urethra and pierces the urogenital diaphragm.","cite":"Slide 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The lining of the ureters, which gives them stretch, is composed of which epithelium?","choices":["Transitional epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ureteral mucosa is transitional epithelium, allowing distension; the muscularis has inner longitudinal and outer circular smooth muscle (plus an external longitudinal layer distally).","cite":"Slide 45 (Ureter Walls)"},{"q":"The inner lining of the urinary bladder is which stretchy epithelium?","choices":["Simple columnar epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The bladder's inner lining is transitional (stretchy) epithelium; it can expand ~15× its empty volume to hold ~500 mL.","cite":"Slide 53 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The parietal layer of Bowman's capsule is composed of which epithelium?","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Podocytes","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":0,"exp":"The parietal (outer) layer of Bowman's capsule is simple squamous epithelium; the visceral layer is made of podocytes.","cite":"Slide 35 (Renal Corpuscle)"},{"q":"The visceral layer of the glomerular capsule is formed by specialized cells with foot processes (pedicles) called:","choices":["Chromaffin cells","Mesangial cells","Chief cells","Podocytes"],"answer":3,"exp":"Podocytes form the visceral layer; their pedicles create filtration slits and are coated in negatively charged glycocalyx.","cite":"Slides 33–35 (Glomerulus / Renal Corpuscle)"},{"q":"The glomerular capillary endothelium is described as ______, allowing high permeability during filtration.","choices":["Continuous","Sinusoidal only","Fenestrated","Stratified"],"answer":2,"exp":"The glomerular endothelium is fenestrated (large pores), making it highly permeable; a negatively charged basement membrane and podocyte slits restrict large anions/proteins.","cite":"Slides 33–34 (Filtration Membranes)"},{"q":"The detrusor muscle of the bladder wall is composed of which muscle type arranged in three layers?","choices":["Skeletal muscle","Smooth muscle","Cardiac muscle","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The detrusor is smooth muscle (inner and outer longitudinal around a middle circular layer), forming the muscular middle layer of the bladder.","cite":"Slide 53 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The macula densa, a sensor of tubular NaCl concentration within the juxtaglomerular apparatus, is a cluster of specialized cells located in the:","choices":["Distal convoluted tubule","Proximal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct","Loop of Henle descending limb"],"answer":0,"exp":"The macula densa is in the distal (convoluted) tubule and senses NaCl to help regulate GFR and renin release.","cite":"Slides 36, 40 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus / DCT)"},{"q":"The juxtaglomerular (granular) cells, modified smooth muscle cells of the afferent arteriole, synthesize, store, and secrete:","choices":["Erythropoietin","Renin","Calcitriol","Aldosterone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Juxtaglomerular (granular) cells secrete renin in response to decreased blood pressure or macula densa signals; EPO-producing/oxygen-sensing (REPOS) cells secrete erythropoietin.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"},{"q":"The kidneys perform all of the following functions EXCEPT:","choices":["Filtering waste from the blood","Forming urine","Regulating fluid and electrolyte balance","Producing digestive enzymes"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidneys filter waste, form urine, and regulate fluids/electrolytes; producing digestive enzymes is a function of the pancreas and GI tract, not the urinary system.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"After the kidneys produce urine, which structure conducts it from each kidney to the bladder?","choices":["Urethra","Renal pelvis","Collecting duct","Ureter"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each ureter carries urine from the renal pelvis of the kidney to the bladder; the urethra then carries urine from the bladder out of the body.","cite":"Slide 4 (Systems Involved)"},{"q":"Which kidney typically sits slightly lower than the other because of the liver?","choices":["The left kidney","The right kidney","Both sit at exactly the same level","Neither — position varies randomly"],"answer":1,"exp":"The right kidney (about T12–L3) sits slightly lower than the left (about T10/11–L2) because the liver occupies space superiorly on the right.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The funnel-shaped structure formed by the convergence of the major calyces, which collects urine before the ureter, is the:","choices":["Renal sinus","Renal papilla","Renal pelvis","Renal column"],"answer":2,"exp":"Minor calyces merge into major calyces, which merge into the renal pelvis; the pelvis funnels urine into the ureter.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"About what fraction of resting cardiac output do the kidneys receive?","choices":["About 5%","About 75%","About 50%","About 20–25%"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidneys receive roughly 20–25% of resting cardiac output, reflecting their high filtration workload.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Sympathetic stimulation constricts BOTH the afferent and efferent arterioles, which has what effect on urine production?","choices":["Increases blood flow to the glomerulus and increases urine production","Has no effect on glomerular blood flow","Decreases blood flow to the glomerulus and decreases urine production","Increases GFR while decreasing urine output"],"answer":2,"exp":"Vasoconstriction of both afferent and efferent arterioles decreases blood flow to the glomerulus, thus decreasing urine production; filtration increases when sympathetic tone falls.","cite":"Slides 27–28 (autonomic control)"},{"q":"Which is the correct order of nephron structures that filtrate passes through after the renal corpuscle?","choices":["PCT → DCT → loop of Henle → collecting duct","DCT → loop of Henle → PCT → collecting duct","Loop of Henle → PCT → DCT → collecting duct","PCT → loop of Henle → DCT → collecting duct"],"answer":3,"exp":"After the renal corpuscle, filtrate flows: proximal convoluted tubule → loop of Henle (descending then ascending) → distal convoluted tubule → collecting duct.","cite":"Slides 29, 42 (Nephron Structures / Flow of Urine)"},{"q":"Juxtamedullary nephrons, which make up ~15% of nephrons, are specialized for what function?","choices":["Producing 'standard' urine","Concentrating urine via long loops of Henle and vasa recta","Secreting erythropoietin","Filtering large proteins"],"answer":1,"exp":"Juxtamedullary nephrons (~15%) have long loops of Henle extending into the medulla and vasa recta, enabling recovery of water/Na+/Cl- and concentration of urine.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"Cortical nephrons, which make up about 85% of nephrons, are characterized by:","choices":["Short loops of Henle and peritubular capillaries","Long loops of Henle and vasa recta","No glomerulus","Location entirely within the medulla"],"answer":0,"exp":"Cortical nephrons (~85%) sit near the peripheral cortex, have short loops of Henle and peritubular capillaries, and produce 'standard' urine.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"The proximal convoluted tubule begins at the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle and ends where which structure begins?","choices":["The distal convoluted tubule","The collecting duct","The thick descending limb of the loop of Henle","The papillary duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The PCT begins at the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle and ends where the thick descending limb of the loop of Henle begins.","cite":"Slide 38 (Proximal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The distal convoluted tubule begins at the end of the thick ascending limb and lies adjacent to which structure, forming the juxtaglomerular apparatus?","choices":["The efferent arteriole","The afferent arteriole","The vasa recta","The collecting duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The DCT begins at the end of the thick ascending limb and lies adjacent to the afferent arteriole, forming the juxtaglomerular apparatus.","cite":"Slide 40 (Distal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"Once filtrate enters the collecting ducts, what happens to its composition?","choices":["No further modifications can be made — it is officially urine","It undergoes major reabsorption of glucose","It is returned to the glomerulus","It is filtered a second time"],"answer":0,"exp":"Once in the collecting ducts the filtrate officially becomes urine; no further modifications are made. Multiple collecting ducts converge to form a renal papilla.","cite":"Slide 41 (Collecting Tubule & Ducts)"},{"q":"The kidneys are capped superiorly by which endocrine glands, which share the perinephric fat and renal fascia?","choices":["The thyroid glands","The gonads","The parathyroid glands","The adrenal (suprarenal) glands"],"answer":3,"exp":"The adrenal (suprarenal) glands sit atop each kidney, enclosed within the renal fascia and perinephric fat.","cite":"Slides 6, 11 (Kidney location and coverings)"},{"q":"Which posterior abdominal muscles form part of the bed on which the kidneys rest?","choices":["Rectus abdominis and external oblique","Psoas major, quadratus lumborum, and transversus abdominis","Diaphragm only","Iliacus and sartorius"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidneys rest against the psoas major, quadratus lumborum, and transversus abdominis of the posterior abdominal wall (with the diaphragm superiorly).","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The epithelium lining the proximal convoluted tubule, specialized for reabsorption with a prominent brush border, is:","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The PCT is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium (with microvilli/brush border) suited to its heavy reabsorptive role.","cite":"Slide 38 (Proximal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The negatively charged coating on podocytes that helps repel anions and proteins during filtration is called:","choices":["Glycocalyx","Surfactant","Mucin","Keratin"],"answer":0,"exp":"Podocytes are coated in a negatively charged substance called glycocalyx, which (with the negatively charged basement membrane) helps prevent filtration of large anions and proteins such as albumin.","cite":"Slides 33–34 (Filtration Membranes)"},{"q":"The EPO-producing, oxygen-sensing (REPOS) cells of the kidney secrete which hormone in response to low oxygenation?","choices":["Renin","Erythropoietin","Aldosterone","Calcitonin"],"answer":1,"exp":"REPOS cells sense oxygenation levels and secrete erythropoietin, stimulating red blood cell production; juxtaglomerular (granular) cells instead secrete renin.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"}]},"endocrine-3":{"title":"Endocrine System (Set 3)","questions":[{"q":"Which of the following is considered a PRIMARY endocrine organ rather than a tissue with a secondary endocrine role?","choices":["Adipose tissue","Heart","Pineal gland","Digestive tract"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pineal gland is a dedicated endocrine organ; the heart, adipose tissue, and digestive tract are tissues with secondary endocrine roles.","cite":"Slides 3–4 (Overview of the Endocrine System)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is attached to the hypothalamus by which stalk?","choices":["Infundibulum","Isthmus","Median raphe","Pedicle"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pituitary (hypophysis) attaches to the hypothalamus via the infundibulum and sits in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica.","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The anterior lobe of the pituitary gland is also called the:","choices":["Pars nervosa","Neurohypophysis","Adenohypophysis","Median eminence"],"answer":2,"exp":"The adenohypophysis is the anterior lobe (glandular); the neurohypophysis is the posterior lobe (neural).","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The thyroid gland consists of two lobes connected by a bridge of tissue called the:","choices":["Isthmus","Infundibulum","Pyramidal lobe","Colloid"],"answer":0,"exp":"The thyroid is formed of two lobes connected by an isthmus, which lies opposite the 2nd and 3rd tracheal rings.","cite":"Slides 25, 29 (The Thyroid Gland)"},{"q":"How many parathyroid glands are usually present, and where are they located?","choices":["Two, within the pituitary fossa","Four, on the posterior aspect of the thyroid","Six, along the trachea","Two, on the adrenal glands"],"answer":1,"exp":"There are usually four parathyroid glands (one superior and one inferior on each side) on the posterior aspect of the thyroid.","cite":"Slides 43–44 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"Each suprarenal (adrenal) gland is subdivided into an outer cortex and an inner:","choices":["Capsule","Isthmus","Follicle","Medulla"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each adrenal gland has an outer cortex (three zones) and an inner medulla (chromaffin cells).","cite":"Slide 82 (The Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The endocrine portion of the pancreas is organized into clusters of cells called the:","choices":["Pancreatic acini","Pancreatic islets (of Langerhans)","Follicles","Chief cell cords"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pancreatic islets (islets of Langerhans) are the endocrine cells; the acini are the exocrine cells.","cite":"Slide 52 (Anatomy of the Pancreas)"},{"q":"The hypothalamus releases which two hormones to the posterior pituitary?","choices":["Insulin and glucagon","TSH and ACTH","Antidiuretic hormone and oxytocin","Cortisol and aldosterone"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hypothalamus produces ADH and oxytocin, which are stored/released by the neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary).","cite":"Slide 9 (Hypothalamus and Endocrine Regulation)"},{"q":"The structural unit of the thyroid gland is the thyroid follicle, whose wall is composed of which epithelium?","choices":["Pseudostratified columnar epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each thyroid follicle consists of simple cuboidal follicular epithelium surrounding a central mass of colloid.","cite":"Slide 30 (Histology of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid secrete which hormone?","choices":["Cortisol","Thyroxine (T4)","Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin"],"answer":3,"exp":"Parafollicular (C) cells sit near the follicular basement lamina and secrete calcitonin; they are larger and lighter-staining than follicular cells.","cite":"Slide 31 (Parafollicular / C cells)"},{"q":"Within the parathyroid gland, which cells produce parathyroid hormone?","choices":["Principal (chief) cells","Oxyphil cells","Follicular cells","Chromaffin cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Principal (chief) cells, with slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm, produce PTH; oxyphil cells are larger and their function is uncertain.","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"In the pars distalis, the acidophils (reddish cytoplasm) secrete which hormones?","choices":["TSH and ACTH","Growth hormone and prolactin","FSH and LH","ADH and oxytocin"],"answer":1,"exp":"Acidophils (~10% of pars distalis cells) secrete growth hormone and prolactin; basophils secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"The zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex secretes which class of hormones?","choices":["Androgens","Glucocorticoids (cortisol)","Mineralocorticoids (aldosterone)","Catecholamines"],"answer":2,"exp":"The zona glomerulosa secretes mineralocorticoids (aldosterone); fasciculata secretes glucocorticoids; reticularis secretes androgens.","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of Adrenal Glands)"},{"q":"The principal cells of the adrenal medulla, which secrete epinephrine and norepinephrine, are the:","choices":["Podocytes","Chief cells","Follicular cells","Chromaffin cells"],"answer":3,"exp":"Chromaffin cells are modified postganglionic sympathetic neurons (lacking dendrites/axons) that secrete adrenaline and noradrenaline.","cite":"Slide 89 (Adrenal Medulla)"},{"q":"The pars nervosa of the posterior pituitary contains supporting glial-like cells called:","choices":["Pituicytes","Chromophobes","Acidophils","Oxyphils"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pars nervosa contains pituicytes plus bundles of nerve fibers of the hypothalamo-hypophyseal tract and Herring bodies.","cite":"Slide 22 (Pars nervosa)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland sits in the hypophyseal fossa of which bone?","choices":["Temporal bone","Ethmoid bone","Occipital bone","Sphenoid bone"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pituitary lies in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone, covered by the diaphragma sellae.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The superior thyroid artery, which supplies the thyroid gland, is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["Thyrocervical trunk","External carotid artery","Arch of the aorta","Internal carotid artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The superior thyroid artery arises from the external carotid artery; the inferior thyroid artery arises from the thyrocervical trunk.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The recurrent laryngeal nerve is closely related to which artery at the posterior surface of the thyroid gland?","choices":["Inferior thyroid artery","Superior thyroid artery","Thyroidea ima artery","Facial artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The inferior thyroid artery becomes related to the recurrent laryngeal nerve at the posterior surface of the thyroid — a key surgical relationship.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The tail of the pancreas extends toward which organ?","choices":["The gallbladder","The liver","The spleen","The stomach fundus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The rounded head connects to the duodenum and the pointed tail extends toward the hilum of the spleen.","cite":"Slides 50, 56 (The Pancreas)"},{"q":"The suprarenal (adrenal) glands are located attached to which border of the kidneys?","choices":["The inferior border","The superior border","The lateral border","The hilum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The adrenal glands sit on the superior border of the kidneys, enclosed in renal fascia but separated by fibrous tissue.","cite":"Slides 81, 86 (The Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The right suprarenal vein drains into the IVC, whereas the left suprarenal vein drains into the:","choices":["Portal vein","Left renal vein","Azygos vein","Splenic vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"Venous drainage is asymmetric: the right suprarenal vein → IVC; the left suprarenal vein → left renal vein.","cite":"Slide 86 (The Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The thyroid gland moves up and down with swallowing because it is enclosed within which fascia, attached to the larynx?","choices":["Renal fascia","Carotid sheath","Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia"],"answer":3,"exp":"The thyroid lies within the pretracheal fascia, connected above to the thyroid cartilage, so it elevates during deglutition.","cite":"Slide 28 (Thyroid relationships)"},{"q":"Parathyroid hormone (PTH), which raises blood calcium, is produced by which gland?","choices":["Adrenal cortex","Thyroid follicular cells","Parathyroid glands","Pineal gland"],"answer":2,"exp":"PTH is produced by the parathyroid chief cells and raises blood calcium, opposing calcitonin.","cite":"Slides 44, 46 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"Calcitonin, which tends to lower blood calcium, is secreted by which thyroid cells?","choices":["Parafollicular (C) cells","Follicular cells","Chief cells","Oxyphil cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Calcitonin is secreted by the thyroid's parafollicular (C) cells and acts to lower blood calcium, opposing PTH.","cite":"Slide 31 (Parafollicular / C cells)"},{"q":"Calcitriol, the active form of vitamin D involved in calcium regulation, is produced by which organ?","choices":["The thyroid gland","The kidney","The parathyroid glands","The adrenal medulla"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney produces calcitriol (and erythropoietin); calcitriol increases intestinal calcium absorption.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Kidney)"},{"q":"The three hormones most directly involved in calcium metabolism are:","choices":["Aldosterone, ADH, and ANP","Insulin, glucagon, and cortisol","T3, T4, and TSH","PTH, calcitonin, and calcitriol"],"answer":3,"exp":"Calcium balance is governed chiefly by PTH (raises Ca2+), calcitonin (lowers Ca2+), and calcitriol (active vitamin D).","cite":"Slides 5, 31, 44 (calcium-regulating hormones)"},{"q":"The oxyphil cells of the parathyroid gland are notable because they:","choices":["Are chromaffin cells","Secrete calcitonin","Form the follicular colloid","Are larger and very eosinophilic, possibly also secreting PTH"],"answer":3,"exp":"Oxyphil cells are larger and very eosinophilic; their function is uncertain but they may also secrete PTH.","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"The oxyphil cells of the parathyroid gland are larger and very eosinophilic; their function is:","choices":["To store colloid","To secrete calcitonin","Unknown, though they may also secrete PTH","To produce catecholamines"],"answer":2,"exp":"Oxyphil cells are larger and very eosinophilic; their function is unknown but they may also secrete PTH.","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"Active thyroid follicles generally exhibit which change in their follicular epithelium?","choices":["Conversion to stratified epithelium","Flattened squamous epithelium","Loss of the basement membrane","Taller ('high') epithelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"Active follicles generally have 'high' (taller) follicular epithelium, reflecting increased secretory activity.","cite":"Slide 30 (Histology of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The adrenal medulla contains which prominent vascular structure?","choices":["A large central vein","A fenestrated glomerulus","A portal venous plexus","A lymphatic sinus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The adrenal medulla contains a large central vein into which medullary blood drains.","cite":"Slide 89 (Adrenal Medulla)"}]},"endocrine-4":{"title":"Endocrine System (Set 4)","questions":[{"q":"Which endocrine gland undergoes atrophy during adulthood?","choices":["Adrenal","Thyroid","Pancreas","Thymus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The thymus (source of thymosins) undergoes atrophy during adulthood, unlike the other endocrine organs.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Thymus)"},{"q":"The posterior lobe of the pituitary gland is also known as the:","choices":["Pars distalis","Adenohypophysis","Neurohypophysis","Pars tuberalis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The neurohypophysis is the posterior lobe, releasing oxytocin and ADH; the adenohypophysis is the anterior lobe.","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The adenohypophysis releases how many peptide hormones?","choices":["Five","Two","Nine","Twelve"],"answer":2,"exp":"The anterior lobe (adenohypophysis) releases nine peptide hormones; the posterior lobe releases two (ADH and oxytocin).","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"Which of the following is NOT one of the main (primary) endocrine organs?","choices":["Pituitary gland","Adipose tissue","Thyroid gland","Adrenal glands"],"answer":1,"exp":"Adipose tissue is a secondary endocrine tissue (leptin, resistin); the pituitary, thyroid, and adrenal glands are primary endocrine organs.","cite":"Slides 3–4 (Overview)"},{"q":"The suprarenal cortex is subdivided into how many distinct zones?","choices":["Five","Two","Four","Three"],"answer":3,"exp":"The adrenal cortex has three zones: glomerulosa, fasciculata, and reticularis.","cite":"Slide 82 (The Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"Which endocrine structure is located on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland?","choices":["Pineal gland","Parathyroid glands","Pituitary gland","Thymus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The parathyroid glands lie on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland; sometimes parathyroid tissue is embedded within the thyroid.","cite":"Slide 43 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"The reproductive glands (gonads) function as endocrine organs by secreting:","choices":["Insulin and glucagon","Sex steroids and inhibin","Calcitonin and PTH","Epinephrine and cortisol"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gonads secrete sex steroids (androgens or estrogens/progestins) and inhibin, functioning as endocrine organs.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Gonads)"},{"q":"Which endocrine tissue of the heart secretes natriuretic peptides (ANP, BNP)?","choices":["Cardiac tissue (a secondary endocrine tissue)","The pericardium","The pituitary","The adrenal cortex"],"answer":0,"exp":"The heart is a secondary endocrine tissue that secretes atrial and brain natriuretic peptides (ANP and BNP).","cite":"Slides 4–5 (Overview / Figure 19.1)"},{"q":"Within the pars distalis, chromophobes are distinguished from chromophils in that chromophobes:","choices":["Have no granules in their cytoplasm","Have reddish cytoplasm","Secrete PTH","Form colloid"],"answer":0,"exp":"Chromophobes (~50% of pars distalis cells) lack cytoplasmic granules; chromophils (acidophils and basophils) contain granules.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"The central mass of material stored within a thyroid follicle is called the:","choices":["Chromaffin granule","Herring body","Zymogen granule","Colloid"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each thyroid follicle surrounds a central mass of colloid, which stores thyroid hormone precursor.","cite":"Slides 30, 40 (Thyroid Follicles showing Colloid)"},{"q":"The zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex is composed of lipid-laden cells arranged in radial columns and secretes:","choices":["Glucocorticoids (cortisol)","Mineralocorticoids (aldosterone)","Androgens","Catecholamines"],"answer":0,"exp":"The zona fasciculata secretes glucocorticoids (cortisol); its cells are lipid-droplet-laden and arranged in radial columns.","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of Adrenal Glands)"},{"q":"The zona reticularis of the adrenal cortex secretes which class of hormones?","choices":["Mineralocorticoids","Androgens","Glucocorticoids","Catecholamines"],"answer":1,"exp":"The zona reticularis, arranged in a loose meshwork, secretes androgens.","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of Adrenal Glands)"},{"q":"In the pars distalis, basophils (bluish cytoplasm) secrete all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["TSH","Growth hormone","ACTH","FSH"],"answer":1,"exp":"Basophils secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH; growth hormone (and prolactin) are secreted by acidophils.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"The chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla are best described as:","choices":["Modified postganglionic sympathetic neurons","Modified follicular epithelial cells","Modified podocytes","Modified chief cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Chromaffin cells are modified postganglionic sympathetic neurons that lack dendrites and axons and secrete catecholamines.","cite":"Slide 89 (Adrenal Medulla)"},{"q":"On fixation, the homogeneous intercellular substance of the pars nervosa precipitates to form:","choices":["Colloid","Herring bodies","Zymogen granules","Reticular fibers"],"answer":1,"exp":"In the pars nervosa, the homogeneous intercellular substance precipitates on fixation to form Herring bodies.","cite":"Slide 22 (Pars nervosa)"},{"q":"The medial surface of the thyroid gland is related to the larynx, pharynx, and which nerve?","choices":["External laryngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Phrenic nerve","Accessory nerve"],"answer":0,"exp":"The medial surface relates to the larynx, pharynx, and external laryngeal nerve, plus the trachea, esophagus, and recurrent laryngeal nerve.","cite":"Slide 27 (Thyroid medial surface)"},{"q":"The neck of the pancreas lies anterior to which vessel, with the pylorus just above it?","choices":["The aorta","The inferior vena cava","The superior mesenteric vein (SMV)","The splenic artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pancreatic neck lies anterior to the SMV, with the pylorus just above; the SMV outlines the medial head-to-neck region.","cite":"Slides 57, 76 (Pancreas relationships)"},{"q":"The body of the pancreas is related posteriorly to the left kidney, left adrenal, left renal vein, and which vessel?","choices":["Common bile duct","Portal vein","Superior mesenteric artery","Splenic vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreatic body relates posteriorly to the left crus, left adrenal, left renal vein, and splenic vein; the celiac trunk lies superior.","cite":"Slide 59 (Pancreas body relations)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is related on either side to which venous structure?","choices":["The internal jugular vein","The cavernous sinus","The sigmoid sinus","The great cerebral vein"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pituitary is related on either side to the cavernous sinus, and behind to the dorsum sellae.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The diaphragma sellae, a fold of dura over the pituitary, is pierced centrally by the infundibulum and separates the gland from the:","choices":["Sphenoid sinus","Cavernous sinus","Optic chiasma","Dorsum sellae"],"answer":2,"exp":"The diaphragma sellae is pierced by the infundibulum and separates the pituitary from the optic chiasma above.","cite":"Slide 13 (Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The head of the pancreas is clinically important in part because carcinoma is usually located there and because:","choices":["It filters blood","It is intraperitoneal and mobile","It secretes calcitonin","Numerous ducts and vessels traverse it"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreatic head is clinically important because numerous ducts and vessels traverse it and carcinoma is usually located there.","cite":"Slide 65 (Head of Pancreas)"},{"q":"The thyroid gland lies in the lower neck spanning approximately which vertebral levels?","choices":["T4 to T6","C1 to C3","C5 to T1","C7 to T4"],"answer":2,"exp":"The thyroid lies at the level of the 5th cervical to the 1st thoracic vertebrae.","cite":"Slide 25 (The Thyroid Gland)"},{"q":"Parathyroid hormone and calcitonin have what relationship in calcium regulation?","choices":["They are unrelated to calcium","They both raise blood calcium","They both lower blood calcium","They are antagonists — PTH raises and calcitonin lowers blood calcium"],"answer":3,"exp":"PTH raises blood calcium and calcitonin lowers it, making them functional antagonists in calcium homeostasis.","cite":"Slides 31, 44 (calcium regulation)"},{"q":"The kidney contributes to calcium metabolism by producing which hormone?","choices":["Calcitriol","Calcitonin","Parathyroid hormone","Aldosterone"],"answer":0,"exp":"The kidney produces calcitriol (active vitamin D), which raises calcium by increasing intestinal absorption.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Kidney)"},{"q":"Which cells would be MOST directly implicated if blood calcium became abnormally low and needed to be raised?","choices":["Thyroid parafollicular C cells","Parathyroid chief cells (secreting PTH)","Adrenal chromaffin cells","Pancreatic beta cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Low blood calcium stimulates parathyroid chief cells to secrete PTH, which raises blood calcium.","cite":"Slides 44, 46 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"Parafollicular C cells are separated from the follicular lumen by which structure?","choices":["The follicular epithelium","The colloid","The capsule","The basement membrane of a capillary"],"answer":0,"exp":"C cells lie near the follicular basement lamina but are separated from the follicle lumen by the follicular epithelium.","cite":"Slide 31 (Parafollicular / C cells)"},{"q":"Adipose tissue is frequently found within which calcium-regulating gland, especially in older individuals?","choices":["Adrenal medulla","Thyroid gland","Parathyroid gland","Pineal gland"],"answer":2,"exp":"Adipose tissue is frequently found within the parathyroid gland in older individuals.","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"Compared with the acidophils, the basophils of the pars distalis generally:","choices":["Form the colloid","Are smaller and lack granules","Secrete growth hormone","Are larger and stain deeper"],"answer":3,"exp":"Basophils are generally larger and stain deeper than acidophils, and secrete TSH, ACTH, FSH, and LH.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"The thyroid isthmus lies opposite which tracheal rings?","choices":["The 2nd and 3rd tracheal rings","The 4th and 5th tracheal rings","The 1st tracheal ring only","The 6th and 7th tracheal rings"],"answer":0,"exp":"The thyroid isthmus lies opposite the 2nd and 3rd tracheal rings, covered by the sternohyoid and sternothyroid muscles.","cite":"Slide 29 (Thyroid isthmus)"},{"q":"The pointed tail of the pancreas extends toward which organ?","choices":["The stomach","The liver","The spleen","The right kidney"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pancreatic tail extends toward the hilum of the spleen; the rounded head connects to the duodenum.","cite":"Slide 50 (The Pancreas)"}]},"female-reproductive-3":{"title":"Female Reproductive System (Set 3)","questions":[{"q":"The paired embryonic ducts that give rise to the major internal female reproductive organs (in the absence of AMH) are the:","choices":["Mesonephric (Wolffian) ducts","Paramesonephric (Müllerian) ducts","Pronephric ducts","Metanephric ducts"],"answer":1,"exp":"The paramesonephric (Müllerian) ducts develop into the female internal organs when anti-Müllerian hormone is absent.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The fused caudal portions of the Müllerian ducts form the uterovaginal primordium, which gives rise to the uterus, cervix, and:","choices":["Upper one-third of the vagina","Entire vagina","Fallopian tubes","Ovaries"],"answer":0,"exp":"The fused caudal Müllerian ducts form the uterus, cervix, and upper third of the vagina; the lower vagina arises from the urogenital sinus.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The unfused cranial portions of the paramesonephric ducts differentiate into the:","choices":["Ovaries","Fallopian (uterine) tubes","Cervix","Labia majora"],"answer":1,"exp":"The unfused cranial portions of the Müllerian ducts become the fallopian (uterine) tubes.","cite":"Slides 16–17 (Müllerian system)"},{"q":"The perineum is a diamond-shaped area bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the ischial tuberosities, and posteriorly by the:","choices":["Coccyx","Sacral promontory","Iliac crest","Pubic tubercle"],"answer":0,"exp":"The perineum is circumscribed anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the ischial tuberosities, and posteriorly by the coccyx.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The anterior (urogenital) triangle of the female perineum contains which structures?","choices":["The ischial spines","The anus","The coccyx","The urethral and vaginal orifices"],"answer":3,"exp":"The anterior (urogenital) triangle contains the urethral and vaginal orifices in females; the posterior (anal) triangle contains the anus.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The imaginary line dividing the perineum into its anterior and posterior triangles runs between the:","choices":["Ischial tuberosities","Pubic tubercles","Anterior superior iliac spines","Sacroiliac joints"],"answer":0,"exp":"A horizontal line between the ischial tuberosities forms the shared base of the two perineal triangles.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The double fold of peritoneum that attaches the ovary to the broad ligament is the:","choices":["Cardinal ligament","Round ligament","Suspensory ligament","Mesovarium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The mesovarium is a double peritoneal fold attaching the ovary to the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 14 (Peritoneal Folds / Ligaments)"},{"q":"The suspensory ligament of the ovary connects the ovary to the:","choices":["Pelvic (lateral body) wall","Uterus","Labia majora","Sacrum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suspensory ligament runs from the ovary/mesovarium to the pelvic (lateral body) wall and carries the ovarian vessels; the ovarian ligament connects ovary to uterus.","cite":"Slides 14, 18 (Ligaments)"},{"q":"The round ligament of the uterus travels from the uterus through which structure to reach the labia majora?","choices":["The greater sciatic foramen","The obturator foramen","The inguinal canal","The femoral canal"],"answer":2,"exp":"The round ligament extends from the uterus through the inguinal canal to the labia majora and helps maintain uterine anteversion.","cite":"Slides 18, 36 (Round ligament)"},{"q":"Which fold of peritoneum drapes over the uterus and also holds the ovaries and uterine tubes?","choices":["Round ligament","Ovarian ligament","Broad ligament","Uterosacral ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The broad ligament is a peritoneal fold draping over the uterus and extending to hold the ovaries and uterine tubes.","cite":"Slides 14, 18 (Broad ligament)"},{"q":"The pelvic diaphragm is composed of the coccygeus and which other muscle group?","choices":["Obturator externus","Rectus abdominis","Bulbospongiosus","Levator ani"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm comprises the levator ani and coccygeus muscles, which support the pelvic organs and seal the pelvic outlet.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The levator ani muscle is made up of the puborectalis, iliococcygeus, and:","choices":["Bulbospongiosus","Coccygeus","Pubococcygeus","Ischiocavernosus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The levator ani consists of the puborectalis, pubococcygeus, and iliococcygeus.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"A key function of the pelvic diaphragm is to:","choices":["Form the birth canal lining","Produce oocytes","Secrete cervical mucus","Support pelvic organs and seal the inferior opening of the bony pelvis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm supports the pelvic organs, seals the inferior pelvic opening, and lifts to help release feces during defecation.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The ovarian artery, which supplies the ovary, arises from which vessel?","choices":["The internal iliac artery","The abdominal aorta","The uterine artery","The internal pudendal artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ovarian artery arises from the abdominal aorta (inferior to the renal arteries) and reaches the ovary via the suspensory ligament.","cite":"Slides 24, 27, 41 (Vasculature of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The uterine artery, a major supply to the uterus, is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["External iliac artery","Abdominal aorta","Internal iliac artery","Ovarian artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterine arteries arise from the internal iliac arteries; the ovarian arteries come from the aorta.","cite":"Slide 41 (The Uterine Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Venous drainage of the ovaries is asymmetric: the right ovarian vein drains into the IVC, while the left drains into the:","choices":["Azygos vein","Portal vein","Splenic vein","Left renal vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The right ovarian vein drains to the IVC; the left ovarian vein drains to the left renal vein.","cite":"Slide 24 (Ovary)"},{"q":"Parasympathetic innervation to the ovaries is carried by which nerves?","choices":["Vagus nerve","Pelvic splanchnic nerves","Phrenic nerve","Greater splanchnic nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ovaries receive parasympathetic supply from the pelvic splanchnic nerves; visceral afferents enter the cord at T10–T11.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"Visceral afferent (pain) fibers from the ovary enter the spinal cord at which levels?","choices":["T10 and T11","L4 and L5","S2, S3, S4","C6 and C7"],"answer":0,"exp":"Afferent fibers from the ovary enter the spinal cord through the T10 and T11 nerves — explaining periumbilical referred pain.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"Nerve supply to the uterine tube is derived from which plexi?","choices":["Celiac and mesenteric plexi","Cardiac and pulmonary plexi","Ovarian and uterine plexi","Cervical and brachial plexi"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterine tube receives nerve supply from the ovarian and uterine plexi.","cite":"Slide 48 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"Which sequence lists the regions of the uterus from superior to the vaginal end?","choices":["Fundus → body → isthmus → cervix","Cervix → isthmus → body → fundus","Body → fundus → cervix → isthmus","Isthmus → fundus → body → cervix"],"answer":0,"exp":"From superior to inferior: fundus, body, isthmus (constricted region), then cervix, which joins the vagina.","cite":"Slides 33–34 (Regions of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The uterus normally sits in which position relative to the urinary bladder and rectum?","choices":["Posterior to both","Between the urinary bladder (anterior) and rectum (posterior)","Anterior to both","Superior to the kidneys"],"answer":1,"exp":"The uterus lies between the urinary bladder anteriorly and the rectum posteriorly.","cite":"Slide 32 (Uterus)"},{"q":"The uterine tube region into which the fimbriae open, receiving the ovulated oocyte, is the:","choices":["Interstitial (intramural) segment","Isthmus","Infundibulum","Ampulla"],"answer":2,"exp":"The infundibulum is the flared, fimbriated distal end of the uterine tube that receives the ovulated oocyte.","cite":"Slides 45, 51 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The vagina in an adult female measures approximately how long?","choices":["About 25 cm","About 10 cm","About 3 cm","About 18 cm"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vagina is a thick-walled fibromuscular tube about 10 cm long, forming the inferior-most region of the tract.","cite":"Slide 56 (Vagina)"},{"q":"The uterine tubes are lined by which epithelium, whose cilia help move the oocyte toward the uterus?","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Simple ciliated columnar epithelium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterine tube mucosa is simple ciliated (and non-ciliated) columnar epithelium; ciliary action and peristalsis move the ovum.","cite":"Slides 45, 53 (Uterine Tube Histology)"},{"q":"The middle tunic of the uterine wall, composed of three intertwining layers of smooth muscle, is the:","choices":["Endometrium","Perimetrium","Myometrium","Adventitia"],"answer":2,"exp":"The myometrium is the thick middle tunic of smooth muscle; it enlarges greatly in pregnancy.","cite":"Slides 35, 39 (Uterine Layers)"},{"q":"The functional unit of the ovary, a sac-like structure containing an oocyte surrounded by follicular cells, is the:","choices":["Ovarian follicle","Corpus luteum only","Uterine gland","Fornix"],"answer":0,"exp":"Ovaries are composed of ovarian follicles, each containing an oocyte and its surrounding follicular cells.","cite":"Slides 25–26 (Ovaries)"},{"q":"The anterior peritoneal recess between the uterus and the urinary bladder is the:","choices":["Mesovarium","Rectouterine pouch","Broad ligament","Vesicouterine pouch"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vesicouterine pouch is the anterior dead-end recess between the uterus and bladder.","cite":"Slide 12 (Anatomy of the Female Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The outer serosal tunic of the uterus, continuous with the broad ligament, is the:","choices":["Mucosa","Myometrium","Endometrium","Perimetrium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The perimetrium is the outer serosa of the uterus and is continuous with the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 39 (Wall of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The greater vestibular gland, which secretes mucus into the vestibule, is homologous to which male structure?","choices":["The prostate","The bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) gland","The seminal gland","The epididymis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The greater vestibular gland lies behind the bulb of the vestibule and is homologous to the male bulbo-urethral gland.","cite":"Slide 78 (Greater Vestibular Gland)"},{"q":"The clitoris, located where the labia minora meet anteriorly, contains erectile tissue and is homologous to which male organ?","choices":["The testis","The scrotum","The penis","The prostate"],"answer":2,"exp":"The clitoris contains erectile tissue (two corpora cavernosa and two crura) and is homologous to the penis.","cite":"Slides 71, 76 (Clitoris)"}]},"female-reproductive-4":{"title":"Female Reproductive System (Set 4)","questions":[{"q":"The Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts arise from the coelomic epithelium on the lateral aspect of the mesonephros at about which week of development?","choices":["6th week","2nd week","12th week","20th week"],"answer":0,"exp":"The paramesonephric ducts arise from coelomic epithelium on the lateral mesonephros around the 6th week.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The lower portion of the vagina develops from which embryonic structure rather than the Müllerian ducts?","choices":["The allantois","The mesonephric duct","The gubernaculum","The urogenital sinus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The upper vagina derives from the fused Müllerian ducts, but the lower vagina develops from the urogenital sinus.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"In male embryos, the Müllerian ducts regress due to the action of which hormone?","choices":["Testosterone","Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH)","Estrogen","Progesterone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) causes regression of the Müllerian ducts in males; without it, they develop into female organs.","cite":"Slides 16–17 (Müllerian system)"},{"q":"The posterior triangle of the perineum, containing the anus in both sexes, is also called the:","choices":["Femoral triangle","Urogenital triangle","Anal triangle","Cystohepatic triangle"],"answer":2,"exp":"The posterior (anal) triangle contains the anus; the anterior triangle is the urogenital triangle.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The mons pubis, a boundary landmark of the female perineum, lies immediately anterior to which structure?","choices":["The coccyx","The pubic symphysis","The sacrum","The anus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The mons pubis is an expanse of skin and subcutaneous tissue immediately anterior to the pubic symphysis.","cite":"Slides 8, 66 (Boundaries / External Genitalia)"},{"q":"The urogenital triangle in the female is distinguished from the male's in that it contains the:","choices":["Anus","Base of the penis and scrotum","Urethral and vaginal orifices","Prostate"],"answer":2,"exp":"In females the urogenital (anterior) triangle contains the urethral and vaginal orifices; in males it contains the base of the penis and scrotum.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The ovarian ligament attaches the ovary to which structure?","choices":["The labia majora","The pelvic side wall","The superior margin of the uterus","The sacrum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ovarian ligament attaches the ovary to the superior margin (lateral fundus) of the uterus.","cite":"Slide 18 (Supporting Ligaments)"},{"q":"The cardinal (transverse cervical) and uterosacral ligaments are described as thickenings of:","choices":["Hyaline cartilage","Skeletal muscle","Peritoneum only","Subserous fascia and smooth muscle"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cardinal and uterosacral ligaments are thickenings of subserous fascia and smooth muscle that help support the uterus.","cite":"Slide 31 (Uterus support)"},{"q":"The uterosacral ligaments run from the inferior uterus to which structure?","choices":["The ischial tuberosity","The pubic symphysis","The labia majora","The sacrum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterosacral ligaments extend from the inferior uterus to the sacrum.","cite":"Slide 36 (Support of the Uterus)"},{"q":"Which muscle group listed is part of the levator ani rather than a separate perineal muscle?","choices":["Puborectalis","Ischiocavernosus","Bulbospongiosus","Dartos"],"answer":0,"exp":"The puborectalis (with pubococcygeus and iliococcygeus) forms the levator ani; ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus are separate perineal muscles.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The pubovaginalis, a muscle related to the vagina, is a part of which larger muscle?","choices":["Coccygeus","Levator ani","Rectus abdominis","Obturator internus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pubovaginalis is a component of the levator ani and is one of the muscles related to the vagina.","cite":"Slide 62 (Muscles Related to the Vagina)"},{"q":"Besides the pelvic diaphragm, the uterus is supported inferiorly by which additional muscular structure?","choices":["The urogenital diaphragm","The diaphragm (thoracic)","The transversus abdominis","The psoas major"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterus is supported by the pelvic floor muscles including the pelvic diaphragm and the urogenital diaphragm.","cite":"Slide 36 (Support of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The blood supply to the uterus is provided by the uterine, ovarian, and which additional arteries?","choices":["Vaginal arteries","Renal arteries","Femoral arteries","Inferior epigastric arteries"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterus is supplied by the uterine, vaginal, and ovarian arteries.","cite":"Slide 35 (Uterine Layers — blood supply)"},{"q":"The vagina receives its blood supply from the uterine, vaginal, and which additional arteries?","choices":["Renal arteries","Pudendal arteries","Gonadal arteries only","Splenic arteries"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vagina is supplied by the uterine, vaginal, and pudendal arteries.","cite":"Slide 59 (Vagina — blood supply)"},{"q":"The ovarian artery reaches the ovary by traveling within which ligament?","choices":["The ovarian ligament","The round ligament","The suspensory ligament","The uterosacral ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ovarian artery enters the suspensory ligament and sends branches through the mesovarium to the ovary.","cite":"Slide 27 (Vasculature of Ovaries)"},{"q":"Superior lymphatic drainage of the vagina is to which nodes?","choices":["Popliteal nodes","Axillary nodes","Internal and external iliac nodes","Submandibular nodes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Superior vaginal lymph drains to internal and external iliac nodes; the inferior vagina drains partly to superficial inguinal nodes.","cite":"Slide 64 (Lymphatic Drainage of Vagina)"},{"q":"Lymphatic drainage of the ovaries follows the ovarian vessels to ascend to which nodes?","choices":["Lumbar (para-aortic) lymph nodes","Superficial inguinal nodes","Axillary nodes","Popliteal nodes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Ovarian lymphatics follow the ovarian blood vessels to ascend to the lumbar (para-aortic) lymph nodes.","cite":"Slide 27 (Lymphatics of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The uterine tube's lymphatic drainage is to which nodes?","choices":["Superficial inguinal nodes","Lumbar lymph nodes","Popliteal nodes","Submental nodes"],"answer":1,"exp":"The uterine tube drains to the lumbar lymph nodes, following its ovarian/uterine vasculature.","cite":"Slide 48 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The narrow, constricted region of the uterus located between the body and the cervix is the:","choices":["Infundibulum","Fundus","Fornix","Isthmus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The isthmus is the constricted region between the uterine body and the cervix.","cite":"Slide 34 (Anatomic Regions)"},{"q":"The cervix communicates with the uterine body through the internal os and with the vagina through the:","choices":["External os","Infundibulum","Fornix","Hymen"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cervical canal opens to the isthmus via the internal os and to the vagina via the external os.","cite":"Slides 33–34 (Regions of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The recess surrounding the vaginal portion of the cervix, used for surgical access and device placement, is the:","choices":["Infundibulum","Vestibule","Fornix","Ampulla"],"answer":2,"exp":"The fornix is the pocket surrounding the uterine cervix where it projects into the vagina.","cite":"Slides 59–60 (Cervix and Vagina)"},{"q":"The long, wide portion of the uterine tube where fertilization typically occurs is the:","choices":["Intramural portion","Isthmus","Infundibulum","Ampulla"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ampulla is the long, wide portion of the uterine tube and the usual site of fertilization.","cite":"Slide 51 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The hormone-sensitive inner lining of the uterus that cycles between puberty and menopause is the:","choices":["Serosa","Myometrium","Perimetrium","Endometrium"],"answer":3,"exp":"The endometrium is the hormone-sensitive inner lining with cyclic growth; it has stratum basalis and stratum functionalis layers.","cite":"Slides 35, 43 (Endometrium)"},{"q":"Which endometrial layer builds up each month in response to ovarian hormones and sloughs off at menstruation?","choices":["Stratum basalis","Stratum functionalis","Myometrium","Perimetrium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The stratum functionalis builds up monthly and sloughs at menstruation; the stratum basalis regenerates it.","cite":"Slide 43 (Endometrium)"},{"q":"The wall of the vagina consists of three tunics: an inner mucosa, a middle muscularis, and an outer:","choices":["Endometrium","Serosa","Perimetrium","Adventitia"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vaginal wall has an inner mucosa, middle muscularis, and outer adventitia.","cite":"Slide 56 (Vagina)"},{"q":"The labia minora are characterized histologically by a core of:","choices":["Hyaline cartilage","Adipose tissue with hair follicles","Skeletal muscle","Spongy connective tissue with erectile tissue and many small vessels"],"answer":3,"exp":"The labia minora have no hair or fat but contain a core of spongy connective tissue with erectile tissue and many small blood vessels.","cite":"Slide 74 (Labia Minora)"},{"q":"The posterior peritoneal recess between the uterus and the rectum is the:","choices":["Mesovarium","Vesicouterine pouch","Rectouterine pouch","Broad ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The rectouterine pouch (of Douglas) is the posterior dead-end recess between the uterus and rectum.","cite":"Slide 12 (Anatomy of the Female Reproductive System)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the uterus is classified as:","choices":["Subperitoneal","Retroperitoneal","Intraperitoneal","Extraperitoneal"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterus is an intraperitoneal organ, draped by the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 31 (Uterus)"},{"q":"The broad ligament is best classified as which type of structure?","choices":["A dense fibrous cord","A fold of peritoneum","A smooth muscle band","A serous gland"],"answer":1,"exp":"The broad ligament is a fold of peritoneum that drapes over the reproductive organs and is continuous with the perimetrium.","cite":"Slides 28, 39 (Broad ligament / perimetrium)"},{"q":"The labia majora are derived from the same embryonic structures as which male structure?","choices":["The scrotum","The penis","The prostate","The glans"],"answer":0,"exp":"The labia majora are homologous to (derived from the same embryonic structures as) the scrotum.","cite":"Slides 69, 73 (Labia Majora)"}]},"anatomy-gi-i-ii-3":{"title":"Gastrointestinal Tract I & II (Set 3)","questions":[{"q":"The GI tract forms a continuous tube from mouth to anus measuring approximately:","choices":["3 meters (about 10 feet)","9–10 meters (about 30 feet)","15 meters (about 45 feet)","1 meter (about 3 feet)"],"answer":1,"exp":"The GI tract is a continuous muscular tube roughly 9–10 meters (about 30 feet) long from mouth to anus.","cite":"Slide 8 (General Structure)"},{"q":"The accessory digestive organs assist the GI tract but develop as outgrowths connected to it, sometimes by ducts. Which group lists only accessory organs?","choices":["Duodenum, jejunum, ileum, colon","Esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine","Pharynx, esophagus, cecum, rectum","Teeth, tongue, salivary glands, liver, gallbladder, pancreas"],"answer":3,"exp":"Accessory organs — teeth, tongue, salivary glands, liver, gallbladder, and pancreas — assist digestion but do not form the GI tube itself.","cite":"Slide 9 (Accessory digestive organs)"},{"q":"The peritoneal cavity is divided into two spaces known as the:","choices":["Pleural and pericardial sacs","Supracolic and infracolic compartments only","Greater sac and lesser sac","Right and left paracolic gutters"],"answer":2,"exp":"The peritoneal cavity consists of the greater sac and the lesser sac (omental bursa).","cite":"Slide 13 (Peritoneum)"},{"q":"The greater omentum extends from which structure and drapes over the transverse colon and small bowel?","choices":["The lesser curvature of the stomach","The root of the mesentery","The porta hepatis","The greater curvature of the stomach"],"answer":3,"exp":"The greater omentum extends from the greater curvature of the stomach, covering the transverse colon and small bowel.","cite":"Slide 19 (Greater Omentum)"},{"q":"The enteric nervous system controls coordinated gut smooth-muscle activity via how many intramuscular plexuses extending along the gut?","choices":["Two","One","Three","Four"],"answer":0,"exp":"The enteric nervous system is distributed in two intramuscular plexuses running the length of the gut.","cite":"Slide 12 (Special Features)"},{"q":"The GI tract is innervated primarily by which division of the autonomic nervous system?","choices":["Sympathetic","None — it is avascular and aneural","Somatic motor","Parasympathetic"],"answer":3,"exp":"The GI tract is innervated primarily by the parasympathetic division, along with its intrinsic enteric nervous system.","cite":"Slide 12 (Innervation)"},{"q":"Which sequence lists stomach regions from superior to the pyloric end?","choices":["Cardia → fundus → body → pyloric region","Fundus → cardia → pyloric → body","Body → fundus → cardia → pylorus","Pylorus → body → fundus → cardia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The stomach regions are the cardia, fundus (most superior), body, and pyloric region (antrum, canal, sphincter).","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the stomach is:","choices":["Retroperitoneal","Intraperitoneal","Subperitoneal","Extraperitoneal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The stomach is an intraperitoneal organ; its interior shows rugae, a gastric canal, pits, and glands.","cite":"Slide 58 (Stomach Interior)"},{"q":"The spleen is located intraperitoneally and lies anterior to which ribs?","choices":["Ribs 4–6","Ribs 1–3","Ribs 9–11","Ribs 11–12 only"],"answer":2,"exp":"The spleen lies intraperitoneally, anterior to ribs 9–11.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"Within the spleen, the component responsible for filtering blood is the:","choices":["Red pulp","White pulp","Portal triad","Splenic hilum"],"answer":0,"exp":"Red pulp filters blood and supports hematopoiesis; white pulp is lymphatic tissue.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"Which segment of the small intestine is the primary site of chemical digestion and nutrient absorption and makes up ~two-fifths of its length?","choices":["Jejunum","Duodenum","Ileum","Cecum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The jejunum is the middle region (~2.5 m), the primary site of chemical digestion and nutrient absorption.","cite":"Slide 61 (Small Intestine)"},{"q":"The permanent transverse folds of the small-intestinal lining that do NOT disappear when it fills are called:","choices":["Rugae","Haustra","Plicae circulares","Taeniae coli"],"answer":2,"exp":"Plicae circulares are permanent transverse folds; unlike gastric rugae, they persist when the intestine fills.","cite":"Slide 63 (Plicae)"},{"q":"The three longitudinal bands of smooth muscle characteristic of the colon are the:","choices":["Omental appendices","Haustra","Taeniae coli","Plicae circulares"],"answer":2,"exp":"Taeniae coli are three longitudinal muscle bands; their tone forms haustra. They are absent in the rectum and appendix.","cite":"Slide 91 (Anatomic specializations)"},{"q":"Which portion of the colon is the most mobile and is suspended by the transverse mesocolon?","choices":["Ascending colon","Rectum","Descending colon","Transverse colon"],"answer":3,"exp":"The transverse colon is the most mobile, intraperitoneal, and longest segment, suspended by the transverse mesocolon.","cite":"Slide 94 (Transverse Colon)"},{"q":"The pancreatic head is cradled by the C-shaped curve of which adjacent organ?","choices":["The stomach","The spleen","The duodenum","The transverse colon"],"answer":2,"exp":"The retroperitoneal pancreatic head (with its uncinate process) nestles within the C-loop of the duodenum.","cite":"Slides 66, 130 (Duodenum / Pancreas)"},{"q":"The endocrine tissue of the pancreas, comprising only about 1% of pancreatic cells, is the:","choices":["Acinar cells","Uncinate process","Main pancreatic duct","Pancreatic islets"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pancreatic islets are the scattered endocrine tissue, about 1% of pancreatic cells.","cite":"Slide 132 (Pancreatic Islets)"},{"q":"The quadrate lobe of the liver is bounded by the gallbladder and which structure?","choices":["The ligamentum teres","The ligamentum venosum","The inferior vena cava","The falciform ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The quadrate lobe lies between the gallbladder and the ligamentum teres; the caudate lobe lies between the IVC and ligamentum venosum.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The liver is completely covered by a connective-tissue capsule known as:","choices":["Gerota's fascia","Bowman's capsule","Glisson's capsule","The tunica albuginea"],"answer":2,"exp":"The liver is completely covered by Glisson's capsule and only incompletely covered by peritoneum (leaving a bare area).","cite":"Slide 104 (The Liver)"},{"q":"Within the hepatic portal triad, which three structures travel together?","choices":["Portal vein, central vein, and hepatic vein","Portal vein, hepatic artery, and bile duct","Hepatic artery, cystic duct, and IVC","Splenic vein, SMA, and common bile duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The portal triad consists of the portal vein, hepatic artery, and bile duct.","cite":"Slide 121 (Histology of the liver)"},{"q":"Of the liver's triple blood supply, the portal vein delivers:","choices":["Blood needing metabolic processing","Oxygenated blood for tissue metabolism","Outflow to the right atrium","Bile from the gallbladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The portal vein provides inflow of blood needing metabolic processing; hepatic veins carry outflow; the hepatic artery supplies ~15% of flow.","cite":"Slide 108 (Liver triple blood supply)"},{"q":"The neck of the gallbladder is continuous with which duct that carries bile toward the common bile duct?","choices":["Main pancreatic duct","Cystic duct","Hepatic portal duct","Accessory duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gallbladder's neck continues as the cystic duct, which joins the common hepatic duct to form the common bile duct.","cite":"Slide 126 (The Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The gallbladder sits between which two lobes of the liver?","choices":["Left and caudate lobes","Right and quadrate lobes","Caudate and quadrate lobes","Right and left lobes"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gallbladder lies between the right and quadrate lobes of the liver.","cite":"Slide 126 (The Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The celiac trunk arises at the aortic hiatus and gives off all of the following branches EXCEPT the:","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery","Splenic artery","Common hepatic artery","Left gastric artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The celiac trunk's three branches are the left gastric, splenic, and common hepatic arteries; the SMA is a separate aortic branch.","cite":"Slide 139 (Arterial Supply of the Abdomen)"},{"q":"The gastroduodenal and right gastric arteries are branches of which vessel?","choices":["Splenic artery","Left gastric artery","Inferior mesenteric artery","Common/proper hepatic artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"The common hepatic artery gives the proper hepatic and gastroduodenal branches; the right gastric also arises from this system.","cite":"Slide 142 (Common Hepatic Artery)"},{"q":"The inferior vena cava is formed inferiorly by the union of the:","choices":["Renal veins","Common iliac veins","Hepatic veins","Gonadal veins"],"answer":1,"exp":"The IVC begins with the union of the common iliac veins and ascends receiving renal, hepatic, and other tributaries.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Which of the following drains directly into the inferior vena cava?","choices":["Splenic vein","Superior mesenteric vein","Hepatic veins","Left gastric vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hepatic veins drain directly into the IVC; the splenic, SMV, and left gastric are part of the portal system.","cite":"Slides 121, 146 (hepatic veins → IVC)"},{"q":"The esophagus has a dual venous drainage that makes it a site of portosystemic anastomosis; it drains into the azygos vein and the:","choices":["Renal vein","Inferior phrenic vein","Gonadal vein","Portal vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"Esophageal venous drainage goes to both the azygos system and the portal vein (via the left gastric), a clinically important portosystemic anastomosis.","cite":"Slide 41 (Esophagus)"},{"q":"Abdominal visceral lymph nodes are characteristically arranged around which structures?","choices":["The ureters","The major arteries (celiac, SMA, IMA)","The peripheral nerves","The bile ducts only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Visceral lymph nodes cluster around the major arterial branches (celiac, superior and inferior mesenteric), draining toward the cisterna chyli.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"The submandibular glands produce approximately what share of total saliva, the largest of the three pairs' contributions?","choices":["About 60–70%","About 25–30%","About 3–5%","About 90%"],"answer":0,"exp":"The submandibular glands produce most saliva (~60–70%); the parotids give ~25–30% and sublinguals only ~3–5%.","cite":"Slides 30–33 (Salivary Glands)"},{"q":"The internal anal sphincter differs from the external anal sphincter in that it is composed of:","choices":["Elastic cartilage","Skeletal muscle, under voluntary control","Cardiac muscle","Smooth muscle, not under voluntary control"],"answer":3,"exp":"The internal anal sphincter is involuntary smooth muscle; the external anal sphincter is voluntary skeletal muscle.","cite":"Slide 102 (Anal Sphincters)"}]},"anatomy-gi-i-ii-4":{"title":"Gastrointestinal Tract I & II (Set 4)","questions":[{"q":"Digestive organs are divided into two categories: the GI (alimentary) tract organs and the:","choices":["Lymphatic organs","Retroperitoneal organs","Endocrine organs","Accessory digestive organs"],"answer":3,"exp":"The digestive system comprises the GI-tract organs and the accessory digestive organs (e.g., liver, gallbladder, pancreas).","cite":"Slide 7 (General Structure)"},{"q":"Motility that pushes material along the GI tract is generated by which tissue in the wall?","choices":["Skeletal muscle throughout","Elastic cartilage","Cardiac muscle","Smooth muscle"],"answer":3,"exp":"Smooth muscle in the GI wall is responsible for motility, pushing materials from one end to the other.","cite":"Slide 8 (General Structure)"},{"q":"The lesser omentum extends from the porta hepatis to the lesser curvature of the stomach and comprises the hepatogastric and which other ligament?","choices":["Hepatoduodenal ligament","Falciform ligament","Coronary ligament","Splenorenal ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The lesser omentum consists of the hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments, running from the porta hepatis to the lesser curvature and duodenal bulb.","cite":"Slide 21 (Peritoneal Reflections)"},{"q":"The root of the mesentery proper runs from the duodenojejunal flexure to which location?","choices":["The pelvic brim","The left colic flexure","The right iliac fossa","The porta hepatis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The mesentery proper's root runs from the duodenojejunal flexure to the right iliac fossa, suspending the jejunum and ileum.","cite":"Slide 22 (Mesentery)"},{"q":"The lips (labia) are covered externally by which epithelium?","choices":["Simple columnar epithelium","Keratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The lips are covered by keratinized stratified squamous epithelium; the gingivae have nonkeratinized epithelium over dense regular CT.","cite":"Slide 26 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The mucosa of the esophagus is lined by which epithelium?","choices":["Simple cuboidal epithelium","Nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Pseudostratified columnar epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The esophageal mucosa is nonkeratinized stratified squamous epithelium, suited to the passage of a bolus.","cite":"Slide 42 (Esophagus histology)"},{"q":"The lesser omentum attaches to the stomach along which curvature?","choices":["The anterior surface","The greater curvature","The lesser curvature","The pyloric antrum only"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser omentum attaches along the lesser curvature; the greater omentum hangs from the greater curvature.","cite":"Slides 21, 54 (Lesser Omentum / Stomach)"},{"q":"The pyloric region of the stomach includes the antrum, the canal, and the:","choices":["Cardia","Fundus","Sphincter","Rugae"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pyloric region comprises the antrum, pyloric canal, and pyloric sphincter, which controls gastric emptying.","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"The splenic artery, which supplies the spleen, is a branch of which larger vessel?","choices":["Celiac trunk","Superior mesenteric artery","Inferior mesenteric artery","Renal artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The splenic artery is one of the three branches of the celiac trunk and also gives pancreatic branches.","cite":"Slides 137, 139 (Splenic Artery / Celiac Trunk)"},{"q":"The white pulp of the spleen is functionally classified as which kind of tissue?","choices":["Hematopoietic filtering","Endocrine","Lymphatic","Adipose"],"answer":2,"exp":"White pulp is lymphatic tissue; red pulp performs hematopoietic and blood-filtering functions.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"The first segment of the small intestine, which begins at the pyloric sphincter and is largely retroperitoneal, is the:","choices":["Duodenum","Jejunum","Ileum","Cecum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The duodenum (~25 cm) is the shortest, widest, and mostly retroperitoneal first segment, beginning at the pyloric sphincter.","cite":"Slides 61, 66 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"The ileum terminates at which structure, which controls entry into the large intestine?","choices":["The pyloric sphincter","The major duodenal papilla","The duodenojejunal flexure","The ileocecal valve"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ileum terminates at the ileocecal valve, a sphincter controlling entry of material into the cecum.","cite":"Slide 61 (Small Intestine)"},{"q":"Which segments of the colon are retroperitoneal?","choices":["Sigmoid colon and rectum","Transverse and sigmoid colon","Cecum and appendix","Ascending and descending colon"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ascending and descending colon are retroperitoneal, whereas the transverse and sigmoid colon are intraperitoneal.","cite":"Slides 93, 96 (Ascending / Descending Colon)"},{"q":"The blind pouch located posterior to the ileocecal valve that helps prevent reflux into the ileum is the:","choices":["Cecum","Rectum","Sigmoid colon","Appendix"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cecum is an intraperitoneal blind pouch posterior to the ileocecal valve; the appendix hangs from it.","cite":"Slide 85 (Cecum and Appendix)"},{"q":"Which region of the pancreas is a hook-shaped extension projecting from the head?","choices":["Body","Tail","Neck","Uncinate process"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uncinate process is an extension of the pancreatic head; the pancreas also has a neck, body, and tail.","cite":"Slide 130 (The Pancreas)"},{"q":"The pancreas has how many ducts conveying its exocrine secretions?","choices":["A main and an accessory duct","Only a single main duct","Three ducts","None — secretions enter directly"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pancreas has a main pancreatic duct and an accessory duct.","cite":"Slide 130 (Pancreatic ducts)"},{"q":"Which lobe of the liver is the largest?","choices":["Left lobe","Right lobe","Quadrate lobe","Caudate lobe"],"answer":1,"exp":"The right lobe is the largest; the left lobe is separated from it by the falciform ligament.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The peritoneal ligaments that reflect onto the liver from the diaphragm and surround the bare area include the falciform, coronary, triangular, and:","choices":["Ligamentum teres","Splenorenal ligament","Phrenicocolic ligament","Broad ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The liver's peritoneal reflections include the falciform, ligamentum teres, coronary, and triangular ligaments, surrounding the bare area.","cite":"Slide 113 (Anatomy of the Liver)"},{"q":"After passing through hepatic sinusoids, blood collects into the central vein of each lobule and ultimately drains into the:","choices":["Portal vein → SMA","Hepatic veins → inferior vena cava","Bile duct → duodenum","Splenic vein → celiac trunk"],"answer":1,"exp":"Blood flows from the portal triad through sinusoids to the central vein, then to hepatic veins, which drain into the IVC.","cite":"Slide 121 (Histology of the liver)"},{"q":"The hepatic artery supplies approximately what percentage of blood flow to liver tissue?","choices":["About 95%","About 50%","About 75%","About 15%"],"answer":3,"exp":"The hepatic artery gives about 15% of flow to liver tissue and chiefly supplies the bile ducts; the portal vein provides the majority.","cite":"Slide 108 (Liver triple blood supply)"},{"q":"Bile ultimately reaches the duodenum through an opening on the descending part of the duodenum called the:","choices":["Duodenojejunal flexure","Pyloric sphincter","Major duodenal papilla","Ileocecal valve"],"answer":2,"exp":"The descending duodenum contains the major (and lesser) duodenal papilla, where bile and pancreatic secretions enter.","cite":"Slides 61, 66 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"The gallbladder's primary role in the biliary system is to:","choices":["Produce bile","Store and concentrate bile","Produce digestive enzymes","Filter blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gallbladder stores and concentrates bile produced by the liver; the liver secretes the bile itself.","cite":"Slides 104, 126 (Liver / Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The superior mesenteric artery and inferior mesenteric artery are unpaired branches of which vessel?","choices":["The common hepatic artery","The celiac trunk","The abdominal aorta","The splenic artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The SMA and IMA are unpaired midline branches of the abdominal aorta supplying the midgut and hindgut respectively.","cite":"Slides 143–145 (SMA / IMA)"},{"q":"The left gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature and also gives off which branches?","choices":["Renal branches","Esophageal branches","Gonadal branches","Phrenic branches only"],"answer":1,"exp":"The left gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature and gives esophageal branches.","cite":"Slide 139 (Arterial Supply)"},{"q":"Unlike the portal system, the inferior vena cava carries blood directly to which chamber of the heart?","choices":["Right ventricle","Left atrium","Right atrium","Left ventricle"],"answer":2,"exp":"The IVC returns blood directly to the right atrium; portal blood must first pass through the liver.","cite":"Slides 108, 146 (hepatic veins / IVC)"},{"q":"The right gonadal and right suprarenal veins typically drain directly into the IVC, whereas on the left they usually drain into the:","choices":["Left renal vein","Portal vein","Azygos vein","Splenic vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"On the right the gonadal/suprarenal veins enter the IVC directly; on the left they usually drain into the left renal vein.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"The lymphatic drainage of the abdominal viscera ultimately converges toward which dilated lymphatic structure?","choices":["The splenic hilum","The thoracic inlet","The portal vein","The cisterna chyli"],"answer":3,"exp":"Abdominal visceral lymph drains along the arterial nodal groups toward the cisterna chyli, the origin of the thoracic duct.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"Which arterial nodal groups organize the lymphatic drainage of the GI organs?","choices":["Iliac groups only","Renal and gonadal groups","Celiac, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric groups","Phrenic and lumbar groups only"],"answer":2,"exp":"Lymph nodes are grouped around the celiac, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric arteries, matching each artery's territory.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"Aggregated lymphoid nodules (Peyer's patches) are a distinguishing histological feature of which small-intestinal segment?","choices":["Duodenum","Ileum","Jejunum","Pylorus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Peyer's patches (aggregated lymphoid nodules) are characteristic of the ileum, the distal 60% of the small intestine.","cite":"Slide 77 (Ileum)"},{"q":"The appendix is fixed to the cecum by a small mesentery called the:","choices":["Mesentery proper","Transverse mesocolon","Sigmoid mesocolon","Mesoappendix"],"answer":3,"exp":"The appendix, a lymphoid organ, is fixed by the mesoappendix and hangs from the cecum.","cite":"Slide 85 (Cecum and Appendix)"}]},"male-reproductive-3":{"title":"Male Reproductive System (Set 3)","questions":[{"q":"During descent, the testes are guided toward the scrotum by which fibrous cord that fails to elongate as the body grows?","choices":["Gubernaculum testis","Spermatic cord","Ligamentum teres","Round ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The gubernaculum testis holds the testes in place; because it does not elongate with body growth, it pulls the testes inferiorly toward the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"As the testes descend, they pass through which structures connecting the scrotal chambers to the peritoneal cavity?","choices":["The inguinal canals","The obturator foramina","The femoral canals","The ureters"],"answer":0,"exp":"The testes descend through the inguinal canals, which connect the scrotal chambers to the peritoneal cavity.","cite":"Slides 9, 14 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Testicle development within the abdominal cavity is favored by a temperature of about 98.6°F, whereas sperm development requires a temperature about:","choices":["10°F warmer than body temperature","2°F cooler than body temperature","Equal to body temperature","5°F cooler, at 90°F"],"answer":1,"exp":"Sperm development requires ~96.6°F, roughly 2°F cooler than body temperature — the reason the testes reside outside the abdomen.","cite":"Slides 10, 19 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which superficial smooth muscle wrinkles the scrotal surface when it contracts?","choices":["Bulbospongiosus","Cremaster muscle","Dartos muscle","Ischiocavernosus"],"answer":2,"exp":"The dartos is a superficial smooth muscle whose contraction wrinkles the scrotal skin.","cite":"Slide 18 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"When the external temperature is cold, contraction of the cremaster muscle serves to:","choices":["Trigger ejaculation","Wrinkle only the scrotal skin","Draw the testes closer to the abdomen to keep them warm","Relax the scrotal sac fully"],"answer":2,"exp":"In cold conditions the cremaster contracts to pull the testes toward the abdomen, maintaining the temperature needed for sperm development.","cite":"Slide 19 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"During ejaculation, powerful contractions of which paired perineal muscles help push semen toward the external urethral orifice?","choices":["Levator ani and coccygeus only","Dartos and cremaster","Rectus abdominis and pyramidalis","Ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus"],"answer":3,"exp":"Ejaculation involves powerful contractions of the ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus muscles, propelling semen distally.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The internal pudendal artery, which helps supply the scrotum and perineum, is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["Internal iliac artery","Femoral artery","External iliac artery","Abdominal aorta directly"],"answer":0,"exp":"The internal pudendal artery branches from the internal iliac artery; the external pudendal comes off the femoral, and the inferior epigastric off the external iliac.","cite":"Slide 21 (scrotal blood supply)"},{"q":"The testicular veins form a network within the spermatic cord known as the:","choices":["Prostatic plexus","Hypogastric plexus","Vesical plexus","Pampiniform plexus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus is the venous network of the testicular vein within the spermatic cord, aiding countercurrent heat exchange.","cite":"Slide 14 (The Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"The deep artery of the penis, which engorges erectile tissue, runs in the center of which structure?","choices":["The corpus spongiosum","The corpora cavernosa","The spongy urethra","The glans penis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The deep artery of the penis runs in the center of each corpus cavernosum, filling it with blood during erection.","cite":"Slides 62, 65 (The Penis)"},{"q":"Erection of the penis is mediated by activation of which type of nerves?","choices":["Somatic motor nerves only","Sympathetic nerves only","Parasympathetic nerves","Enteric nerves"],"answer":2,"exp":"Parasympathetic activity relaxes arterial smooth muscle, dilating vessels and engorging erectile tissue to produce erection.","cite":"Slide 66 (Erection of the penis)"},{"q":"Semen emission and ejaculation are driven primarily by which division of the autonomic nervous system?","choices":["Parasympathetic","Sympathetic","Somatic afferent","Enteric"],"answer":1,"exp":"Emission and ejaculation are driven by sympathetic activity (with somatic contraction of perineal muscles for ejaculation).","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"Which of the following nerves is listed as supplying the scrotum?","choices":["Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Genitofemoral nerve"],"answer":3,"exp":"The scrotum receives sensory/motor supply from the hypogastric plexus, ilioinguinal, genitofemoral, and pudendal nerves.","cite":"Slide 22 (scrotal nerve supply)"},{"q":"Approximately what are the typical dimensions of an adult testis?","choices":["About 5 cm long, 3 cm wide, 2.5 cm thick","About 12 cm long","About 1 cm long","About 20 cm long"],"answer":0,"exp":"An adult testis is roughly 5 cm long, 3 cm wide, and 2.5 cm thick, weighing 10–15 g.","cite":"Slide 7 (The Testes)"},{"q":"The fibrous connective-tissue capsule of the testis that sends septa inward toward the mediastinum is the:","choices":["Tunica albuginea","Tunica vaginalis","Dartos fascia","Cremasteric fascia"],"answer":0,"exp":"The tunica albuginea is the fibrous lining that forms septa converging on the mediastinum of the testis; the tunica vaginalis is the outer serous layer.","cite":"Slide 23 (Structure of the Testes)"},{"q":"Testosterone, which drives spermatogenesis and secondary sex characteristics, is produced by which testicular cells?","choices":["Spermatogonia","Nurse (Sertoli) cells","Interstitial endocrine (Leydig) cells","Follicular cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"Interstitial endocrine (Leydig) cells, in the spaces between seminiferous tubules, produce and release testosterone.","cite":"Slides 27, 29 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"The nurse cells (Sertoli cells) of the seminiferous tubules secrete inhibin and which protein that keeps testosterone concentrated in the tubules?","choices":["Fibrinogen","Hyaluronidase","Seminalplasmin","Androgen-binding protein (ABP)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Nurse (Sertoli) cells secrete inhibin (controls sperm-formation rate) and androgen-binding protein, which binds testosterone within the tubules.","cite":"Slide 36 (Nurse Cells)"},{"q":"The seminal glands (seminal vesicles) contribute approximately what percentage of semen volume?","choices":["About 5 percent","About 20 percent","About 60 percent","About 90 percent"],"answer":2,"exp":"The seminal glands produce about 60% of semen volume, rich in fructose, prostaglandins, and clotting factors.","cite":"Slide 55 (The Seminal Glands)"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral (Cowper's) glands secrete a thick alkaline mucus that primarily serves to:","choices":["Produce testosterone","Provide fructose for sperm energy","Trigger capacitation","Neutralize residual urinary acids in the urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"Bulbo-urethral glands secrete alkaline mucus that neutralizes urinary acids in the urethra and lubricates the penis tip; ~5% of semen volume.","cite":"Slide 57 (The Bulbo-urethral Glands)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly traces sperm from formation to the epididymis inside the testis?","choices":["Efferent ductules → rete testis → straight tubules → seminiferous tubules","Rete testis → seminiferous tubules → epididymis → efferent ductules","Seminiferous tubules → straight tubules → rete testis → efferent ductules → epididymis","Epididymis → rete testis → seminiferous tubules"],"answer":2,"exp":"Sperm pass from seminiferous tubules → straight tubules → rete testis (in the mediastinum) → efferent ductules → epididymis.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"Before entering the prostate, the ductus deferens expands into a dilated region called the:","choices":["Rete testis","Ampulla","Bulb","Crus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ductus deferens expands into the ampulla, which joins the seminal gland's excretory duct to form the ejaculatory duct.","cite":"Slide 48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"The ejaculatory duct, formed by the union of the ampulla and the seminal gland duct, empties into the:","choices":["Membranous urethra","Prostatic urethra","Spongy urethra","Epididymis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ejaculatory duct empties into the prostatic urethra.","cite":"Slide 48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"Sperm become fully capable of fertilizing an egg only after capacitation, which is completed:","choices":["In the female reproductive tract","Within the epididymis","In the seminiferous tubules","In the prostate"],"answer":0,"exp":"Capacitation occurs outside the epididymis: sperm become motile when mixed with seminal secretions and gain fertilizing capability in the female tract.","cite":"Slide 45 (capacitation)"},{"q":"Which region of the male urethra passes through the prostate gland?","choices":["Spongy urethra","Membranous urethra","Prostatic urethra","Penile urethra"],"answer":2,"exp":"The prostatic urethra extends from the urinary bladder through the prostate gland.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The membranous urethra is distinguished anatomically because it passes through the:","choices":["Prostate gland","Muscular wall of the pelvic cavity (urogenital diaphragm)","Corpus spongiosum","Epididymis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The membranous urethra passes through the muscular wall of the pelvic cavity (the urogenital diaphragm), between the prostatic and spongy portions.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The spongy (penile) urethra is enclosed within which erectile column?","choices":["Crus of the penis","Corpus cavernosum","Corpus spongiosum","Tunica albuginea"],"answer":2,"exp":"The spongy urethra runs within the corpus spongiosum, which surrounds it along the length of the penis.","cite":"Slides 51, 62 (Urethra / Penis)"},{"q":"The three regions of the male urethra, in order from the bladder outward, are:","choices":["Prostatic, spongy, membranous","Spongy, membranous, prostatic","Membranous, prostatic, spongy","Prostatic, membranous, spongy"],"answer":3,"exp":"From the bladder outward the male urethra is prostatic, then membranous, then spongy (penile).","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The head of a spermatozoon contains the chromosomes and an enzyme-filled cap called the:","choices":["Centriole","Acrosome","Flagellum","Mitochondrial spiral"],"answer":1,"exp":"The sperm head contains the chromosomes and the acrosome, which holds enzymes (e.g., hyaluronidase) needed to fertilize the egg.","cite":"Slide 38 (Anatomy of a Sperm)"},{"q":"The middle piece of a spermatozoon is packed with which organelles to power the tail?","choices":["Golgi stacks","Ribosomes","Lysosomes","Mitochondria"],"answer":3,"exp":"The middle piece (with the neck) contains mitochondria and centrioles; the tail is the only flagellum in the human body.","cite":"Slide 38 (Anatomy of a Sperm)"},{"q":"The blood vessels, ductus deferens, and nerves bundled to each descended testis constitute the:","choices":["Spermatic cord","Ejaculatory duct","Pampiniform plexus","Rete testis"],"answer":0,"exp":"These structures bundled to the testis form the spermatic cord, which passes through the inguinal canal.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which portion of the male urethra is the shortest, passing through the urogenital diaphragm?","choices":["Penile urethra","Prostatic urethra","Spongy urethra","Membranous urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"The membranous urethra is the short segment passing through the muscular pelvic floor (urogenital diaphragm), between prostatic and spongy portions.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"}]},"male-reproductive-4":{"title":"Male Reproductive System (Set 4)","questions":[{"q":"The mesonephric duct and diaphragmatic ligament appear in early diagrams of testicular descent alongside the developing gonads near which organs?","choices":["The liver and spleen","The developing lungs","The developing kidneys","The urinary bladder only"],"answer":2,"exp":"Early descent diagrams show the gonads, mesonephric duct, and diaphragmatic ligament adjacent to the developing kidneys before descent.","cite":"Slide 12 (The Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"As the testes descend, which structures remain bundled with them within the spermatic cords?","choices":["The bulbo-urethral glands","Only the ureter","The prostate and seminal glands","Ductus deferens, blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ductus deferens, blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves remain bundled to the testes as the spermatic cords.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"The serous membrane that comes to line each scrotal cavity as the testis descends is the:","choices":["Dartos fascia","Tunica albuginea","Tunica vaginalis","Peritoneum proper"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each scrotal cavity is lined by the tunica vaginalis, a serous membrane that reduces friction around the testis.","cite":"Slides 13, 16 (tunica vaginalis)"},{"q":"The two chambers of the scrotum are separated externally by a ridge of tissue called the:","choices":["Inguinal ligament","Linea alba","Median umbilical ligament","Raphe of the scrotum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The raphe of the scrotum marks the separation of the two scrotal cavities and extends from the anus across the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 16 (Scrotum)"},{"q":"The bulbospongiosus muscle is associated with which structure at the base of the penis?","choices":["The prostate gland","The corpora cavernosa only","The bulb of the penis / spongy urethra","The epididymis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The bulbospongiosus overlies the bulb of the penis and, with the ischiocavernosus, contracts during ejaculation.","cite":"Slides 49, 67 (Bulbospongiosus / ejaculation)"},{"q":"The scrotal septum internally corresponds to which external landmark?","choices":["The perineal body","The pubic symphysis","The inguinal ligament","The raphe of the scrotum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The internal scrotal septum divides the scrotum into two cavities and corresponds externally to the raphe.","cite":"Slides 15, 16 (Scrotal septum / raphe)"},{"q":"The external pudendal artery, contributing to scrotal supply, arises from which vessel?","choices":["External iliac artery","Internal iliac artery","Femoral artery","Abdominal aorta"],"answer":2,"exp":"The external pudendal artery is a branch of the femoral artery; the internal pudendal comes from the internal iliac.","cite":"Slide 21 (scrotal blood supply)"},{"q":"The inferior epigastric artery, which contributes to scrotal vascularity, branches from the:","choices":["External iliac artery","Femoral artery","Internal iliac artery","Renal artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The inferior epigastric artery arises from the external iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 21 (scrotal blood supply)"},{"q":"The spermatic cord contains which two arteries supplying the testis and ductus deferens?","choices":["Testicular artery and deferential artery","Renal artery and gonadal vein","Internal pudendal and femoral arteries","Inferior epigastric and obturator arteries"],"answer":0,"exp":"Within the spermatic cord run the testicular artery and the deferential artery, along with the pampiniform plexus and nerves.","cite":"Slides 14–15 (The Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"The scrotum receives sensory and motor supply from all of the following EXCEPT the:","choices":["Pudendal nerve","Ilioinguinal nerve","Genitofemoral nerve","Vagus nerve"],"answer":3,"exp":"Scrotal innervation comes from the hypogastric plexus, ilioinguinal, genitofemoral, and pudendal nerves — not the vagus.","cite":"Slide 22 (scrotal nerve supply)"},{"q":"During erection, the smooth muscle in the penile arterial walls does what in response to parasympathetic activity?","choices":["Relaxes, dilating the arteries","Contracts, constricting the arteries","Remains unchanged","Undergoes fibrosis"],"answer":0,"exp":"Parasympathetic activity relaxes arterial smooth muscle, dilating the vessels so erectile tissue engorges with blood.","cite":"Slide 66 (Erection of the penis)"},{"q":"The genitofemoral nerve, which supplies the scrotum, is also a named component of which structure?","choices":["The pampiniform plexus","The spermatic cord","The ejaculatory duct","The prostatic plexus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The genitofemoral nerve is listed among the nerves of the spermatic cord and also supplies the scrotum.","cite":"Slides 14–15, 22 (spermatic cord / scrotal nerves)"},{"q":"Which accessory gland produces a weakly acidic secretion containing seminalplasmin, an antibiotic thought to help prevent UTIs?","choices":["Prostate","Seminal gland","Bulbo-urethral gland","Epididymis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The prostate secretes a weakly acidic fluid (20–30% of semen) containing enzymes and seminalplasmin, an antibiotic.","cite":"Slide 56 (The Prostate)"},{"q":"Each seminiferous tubule is approximately how long?","choices":["About 8 mm","About 8 cm","About 80 cm","About 8 meters"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each tightly coiled seminiferous tubule is approximately 80 cm long.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"The head of the epididymis receives spermatozoa via which structures?","choices":["The ejaculatory duct","The efferent ductules","The straight tubules directly","The ampulla"],"answer":1,"exp":"The head of the epididymis receives spermatozoa via the efferent ductules; the tail becomes the ductus deferens.","cite":"Slide 42 (The Epididymis)"},{"q":"The blood-testis barrier, maintained by nurse cells, functions primarily to:","choices":["Trigger ejaculation","Concentrate calcium in the tubules","Produce testosterone","Isolate seminiferous tubules from circulation to prevent autoimmune destruction of sperm"],"answer":3,"exp":"The blood-testis barrier isolates the seminiferous tubules from circulation, preventing autoimmune destruction of developing sperm.","cite":"Slide 36 (Nurse Cells)"},{"q":"The three cylindrical erectile columns of the penis are:","choices":["Two corpora spongiosa and one bulb","Three corpora cavernosa","One corpus cavernosum and two corpora spongiosa","Two corpora cavernosa and one corpus spongiosum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The penis contains two posterior corpora cavernosa and one anterior corpus spongiosum, which surrounds the spongy urethra.","cite":"Slide 61 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The root of the penis attaches its base to which bony structures?","choices":["The sacrum","The pubic symphysis only","The rami of the ischia","The iliac crests"],"answer":2,"exp":"The root of the penis attaches the base to the rami of the ischia; each corpus cavernosum forms a crus bound to the ischial ramus.","cite":"Slides 60, 62 (The Penis)"},{"q":"After leaving the tail of the epididymis, the ductus deferens ascends into the abdomen through which passage?","choices":["The inguinal canal","The femoral canal","The obturator canal","The ureteric orifice"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ductus deferens begins at the tail of the epididymis and ascends into the abdominal cavity through the inguinal canal.","cite":"Slide 47 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"Which is the correct order of accessory-gland/duct contributions as semen is assembled toward ejaculation?","choices":["Ejaculatory duct → ampulla → spongy urethra → prostatic urethra","Spongy urethra → prostatic urethra → ejaculatory duct → ampulla","Prostatic urethra → ampulla → ejaculatory duct → spongy urethra","Ductus deferens/ampulla → ejaculatory duct → prostatic urethra → spongy urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"Semen travels: ductus deferens/ampulla → ejaculatory duct → prostatic urethra → membranous → spongy urethra → external orifice.","cite":"Slides 48, 51 (Ductus Deferens / Urethra)"},{"q":"Roughly what volume of semen is released in a typical ejaculation?","choices":["20 to 50 mL","2 to 5 mL","0.1 to 0.5 mL","10 to 15 mL"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each ejaculation releases about 2 to 5 mL of semen, containing 20–100 million sperm per mL.","cite":"Slide 59 (Semen)"},{"q":"During emission, sperm are mixed with glandular secretions by peristaltic contractions of smooth muscle in the ductus deferens, seminal glands, prostate, and:","choices":["Corpora cavernosa","Epididymal head only","Bulbo-urethral glands","Rete testis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Emission mixes sperm with secretions via peristalsis of the ductus deferens, seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The spongy urethra is also known by which name?","choices":["Prostatic urethra","Penile urethra","Membranous urethra","Cavernous canal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The spongy urethra passes through the penis and is sometimes called the penile urethra.","cite":"Slide 51 (The Urethra)"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty their secretions into which portion of the urethra, just distal to the body wall?","choices":["The internal urethral orifice","The prostatic urethra","The membranous urethra","The spongy urethra"],"answer":3,"exp":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty into the spongy urethra immediately distal to the body wall (end of the membranous urethra).","cite":"Slide 57 (The Bulbo-urethral Glands)"},{"q":"The external urethral orifice is surrounded by which expanded distal region of the penis?","choices":["The crus of the penis","The bulb of the penis","The glans penis","The neck of the glans"],"answer":2,"exp":"The glans penis is the expanded distal end of the penis and surrounds the external urethral orifice.","cite":"Slide 60 (The Penis)"},{"q":"The internal urethral orifice marks the junction between the urinary bladder and which urethral segment?","choices":["The membranous urethra","The prostatic urethra","The spongy urethra","The ejaculatory duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The internal urethral orifice lies at the bladder, opening into the prostatic urethra, which runs through the prostate.","cite":"Slides 49, 51 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The prepuce (foreskin) attaches to which part of the penis?","choices":["The bulb of the penis","The neck of the glans","The crus of the penis","The root of the penis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prepuce (foreskin) surrounds the tip of the penis and attaches to the neck of the glans; preputial glands there secrete smegma.","cite":"Slide 63 (The Penis)"},{"q":"Spermatozoa typically take about how long to pass through the epididymis?","choices":["About 2 weeks","About 2 days","About 2 months","About 2 hours"],"answer":0,"exp":"Spermatozoa take about 2 weeks to pass through the epididymis, where they are stored and further matured.","cite":"Slide 44 (The Epididymis)"},{"q":"The dartos muscle differs from the cremaster in that the dartos is:","choices":["A skeletal muscle that elevates the testes","A superficial smooth muscle that wrinkles the scrotal skin","A perineal muscle used in ejaculation","A sphincter of the urethra"],"answer":1,"exp":"The dartos is a superficial smooth muscle that wrinkles the scrotal surface, whereas the cremaster elevates the testes.","cite":"Slides 18–19 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"The pampiniform plexus is thought to aid testicular function by:","choices":["Cooling arterial blood via countercurrent heat exchange","Producing testosterone","Storing mature sperm","Secreting seminal fluid"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus surrounds the testicular artery and provides countercurrent heat exchange, cooling incoming arterial blood.","cite":"Slides 14–15 (The Spermatic Cords)"}]},"nephrology-urinary-2":{"title":"Nephrology / Urinary System (Set 2)","questions":[{"q":"Which organ of the urinary system is considered the primary organ, performing filtration?","choices":["The ureter","The kidney","The bladder","The urethra"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidneys are the primary urinary organs, filtering waste and converting filtrate to urine; the ureters, bladder, and urethra transport and store it.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"The collective ureters, bladder, and urethra (the urinary tract) function primarily to:","choices":["Filter blood plasma","Transport urine out of the body","Produce erythropoietin","Concentrate the filtrate"],"answer":1,"exp":"The urinary tract (ureters, bladder, urethra) transports urine out of the body; micturition is the term for urination.","cite":"Slide 4 (Systems Involved)"},{"q":"The primary functional role of the kidneys is to:","choices":["Produce reproductive hormones","Store urine until micturition","Transport urine to the exterior","Filter waste products from the bloodstream and convert filtrate into urine"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidneys filter waste from the bloodstream and convert the filtrate into urine; the rest of the tract transports and stores it.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"Which sequence lists the tissues surrounding the kidney from deep (nearest the kidney) to superficial?","choices":["Perinephric fat → fibrous capsule → peritoneum → renal fascia","Peritoneum → renal fascia → perinephric fat → fibrous capsule","Renal fascia → fibrous capsule → paranephric fat → perinephric fat","Fibrous capsule → perinephric fat → renal fascia → paranephric fat → peritoneum"],"answer":3,"exp":"From deep to superficial: fibrous (renal) capsule, perinephric (adipose) fat, renal fascia, paranephric fat, then peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 11 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The concave medial border of the kidney where vessels and the renal pelvis enter/exit is the:","choices":["Renal column","Renal papilla","Hilum","Major calyx"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hilum is the concave medial border; it leads to the renal sinus, which houses vessels, nerves, and the renal pelvis/calyces.","cite":"Slide 10 (Gross and Sectional Anatomy)"},{"q":"The renal medulla is divided into cone-shaped structures called renal pyramids, whose apex is known as the:","choices":["Renal arch","Renal column","Renal papilla","Renal sinus"],"answer":2,"exp":"Each renal pyramid has its base against the cortex and its apex, the renal papilla, projecting toward a minor calyx.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The base of each renal pyramid is oriented toward which region of the kidney?","choices":["The cortex","The renal sinus","The hilum","The minor calyx"],"answer":0,"exp":"Each renal pyramid has its base against the cortex and its apex (renal papilla) pointing toward a minor calyx.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The renal capsule (fibrous capsule) is composed of which tissue?","choices":["Simple squamous epithelium","Dense irregular connective tissue","Smooth muscle","Adipose tissue"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fibrous (renal) capsule is dense irregular connective tissue covering the outer cortex; the renal fascia is also dense irregular CT.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"Immediately after the renal artery, blood enters which set of arteries as it progresses toward the cortex?","choices":["Segmental → lobar → interlobar arteries","Arcuate → interlobular → afferent arterioles","Interlobular → segmental → arcuate arteries","Efferent → peritubular → vasa recta"],"answer":0,"exp":"After the renal artery, blood flows through segmental → lobar → interlobar arteries, then arcuate → interlobular → afferent arteriole → glomerulus.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Blood exits the glomerulus through which vessel (rather than a vein)?","choices":["The efferent arteriole","The interlobular vein","The arcuate vein","The renal vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"Uniquely, blood leaves the glomerulus via the efferent arteriole, which then forms peritubular capillaries or vasa recta.","cite":"Slides 16, 18 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"The efferent arteriole branches into two capillary types responsible for solute exchange: the peritubular capillaries and the:","choices":["Portal capillaries","Glomerular capillaries","Fenestrated cortical sinusoids","Vasa recta"],"answer":3,"exp":"Efferent arterioles form peritubular capillaries (juxtaposed to the nephron) and the vasa recta, which perform solute/molecule exchange.","cite":"Slide 18 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Which sequence traces venous return from the vasa recta to the IVC?","choices":["Arcuate → interlobular → segmental → renal vein → IVC","Interlobular → arcuate → interlobar → renal vein → IVC","Interlobar → interlobular → arcuate → renal vein → IVC","Renal vein → arcuate → interlobar → IVC"],"answer":1,"exp":"Venous return: vasa recta → interlobular vein → arcuate vein → interlobar vein → renal vein → inferior vena cava.","cite":"Slide 18 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"The two components of the renal corpuscle are the glomerulus and the:","choices":["Proximal convoluted tubule","Glomerular (Bowman's) capsule","Loop of Henle","Collecting duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The renal corpuscle consists of the glomerulus and the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule.","cite":"Slide 29 (Nephron Structures)"},{"q":"Which sequence correctly orders filtrate flow through the nephron tubules?","choices":["PCT → DCT → loop of Henle → ascending limb → collecting duct","DCT → PCT → loop of Henle → collecting duct","PCT → descending limb → loop of Henle → ascending limb → DCT → collecting duct","Loop of Henle → PCT → DCT → collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"Filtrate flows: Bowman's capsule → PCT → descending limb → loop of Henle → ascending limb → DCT → collecting duct.","cite":"Slide 22 (Urinary/Filtrate Flow)"},{"q":"Juxtamedullary (medullary) nephrons, comprising ~15% of nephrons, are distinguished by:","choices":["Location only at the cortical edge","Short loops with peritubular capillaries","Absence of a glomerulus","Long nephron loops extending into the medulla, with vasa recta"],"answer":3,"exp":"Juxtamedullary nephrons (~15%) have long loops extending into the medulla and vasa recta, concentrating urine.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"Which nephron type produces 'standard' urine and sits near the peripheral edge of the cortex?","choices":["Papillary nephrons","Juxtamedullary nephrons","Medullary nephrons","Cortical nephrons"],"answer":3,"exp":"Cortical nephrons (~85%) lie near the peripheral cortex with short loops and peritubular capillaries, producing 'standard' urine.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"The proximal convoluted tubule begins at which structure?","choices":["The tubular pole of the renal corpuscle","The end of the loop of Henle","The collecting duct","The minor calyx"],"answer":0,"exp":"The PCT begins at the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle and ends where the thick descending limb of the loop of Henle begins.","cite":"Slide 38 (Proximal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The distal convoluted tubule begins at the end of the thick ascending limb and lies adjacent to which structure?","choices":["The minor calyx","The afferent arteriole (juxtaglomerular apparatus)","The renal papilla","The collecting duct only"],"answer":1,"exp":"The DCT begins at the end of the thick ascending limb and lies adjacent to the afferent arteriole, forming part of the juxtaglomerular apparatus.","cite":"Slide 40 (Distal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The kidneys are classified as which type of organ with respect to the peritoneum?","choices":["Retroperitoneal","Intraperitoneal","Subperitoneal","Suspended by mesentery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs anchored to the posterior body wall.","cite":"Slides 6, 13 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The right kidney typically spans which vertebral levels?","choices":["T6 to T9","T8 to T10","L3 to L5","T12 to L3"],"answer":3,"exp":"The right kidney spans about T12–L3; the left is slightly higher (T10/11–L2) because the liver displaces the right kidney inferiorly.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The left renal vein is distinctive because it receives which additional vein?","choices":["The azygos vein","The right suprarenal vein","The left gonadal vein","The portal vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The left renal vein receives the left gonadal vein; the renal veins drain to the IVC.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The ureters are described as passing 'water under the bridge,' meaning the ureter travels deep (inferior) to which vessels?","choices":["The inferior mesenteric artery","The renal artery and vein","The common iliac artery only","The testicular or ovarian artery and vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ureter passes deep (inferior) to the gonadal (testicular/ovarian) vessels bilaterally — the 'water under the bridge' relationship.","cite":"Slide 48 ('Water under the bridge')"},{"q":"The parietal layer of the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule is lined by which epithelium?","choices":["Simple cuboidal epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Podocytes"],"answer":1,"exp":"The parietal layer of Bowman's capsule is simple squamous epithelium; the visceral layer consists of podocytes.","cite":"Slide 35 (Renal Corpuscle)"},{"q":"The specialized visceral epithelial cells that wrap the glomerular capillaries with foot processes (pedicels) are the:","choices":["Podocytes","Macula densa cells","Juxtaglomerular cells","Mesangial cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"Podocytes form the visceral layer of Bowman's capsule; their pedicels create filtration slits around the glomerular capillaries.","cite":"Slides 34–35 (Filtration Membranes / Renal Corpuscle)"},{"q":"The proximal convoluted tubule is lined by which epithelium?","choices":["Transitional epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium","Simple cuboidal epithelium","Stratified columnar epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"The PCT is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium.","cite":"Slide 38 (Proximal Convoluted Tubule)"},{"q":"The ureters and bladder are lined by which epithelium, which allows them to stretch?","choices":["Simple cuboidal epithelium","Simple squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Stratified squamous epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"Transitional epithelium lines the ureters and bladder, allowing distension as urine volume changes.","cite":"Slides 45, 53 (Ureter Walls / Bladder)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the urinary bladder is best described as:","choices":["Suspended by a mesentery","Fully intraperitoneal","Fully retroperitoneal like the kidney","Non-peritoneal except for its superior wall"],"answer":3,"exp":"The bladder is a non-peritoneal organ except for its superior wall, which is covered by peritoneum — affecting where pain is sensed.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The distal convoluted tubule contains a cluster of cells that sense tubular NaCl; these cells are the:","choices":["Juxtaglomerular (granular) cells","Podocytes","Macula densa","Parietal squamous cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"The macula densa is a cluster of cells in the DCT that senses NaCl concentration as part of the juxtaglomerular apparatus.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"},{"q":"The juxtaglomerular (granular) cells, modified smooth muscle of the afferent arteriole, synthesize and secrete which substance?","choices":["Renin","Erythropoietin","Calcitriol","Aldosterone"],"answer":0,"exp":"Juxtaglomerular (granular) cells secrete renin in response to decreased BP or macula densa stimulation.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"},{"q":"The kidney averages approximately what length?","choices":["20 cm","4 cm","11 cm","30 cm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The average kidney is about 11 cm in length.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"}]},"nephrology-urinary-3":{"title":"Nephrology / Urinary System (Set 3)","questions":[{"q":"The tubes that transport urine from the kidneys to the urinary bladder are the:","choices":["Collecting ducts","Urethra","Ureters","Renal pelvises"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ureters conduct urine from the kidneys to the bladder; the urethra drains urine from the bladder to the exterior.","cite":"Slides 3–4 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"The last part of the urethra, where urine exits the body, is called the:","choices":["Internal urethral orifice","Renal papilla","External urethral meatus (orifice)","Ureterovesical junction"],"answer":2,"exp":"The external urethral meatus (orifice) is the last portion of the urethra where urine leaves the body.","cite":"Slide 58 (Urethra)"},{"q":"Which organ serves as the expandable reservoir for urine prior to micturition?","choices":["Urethra","Ureter","Renal pelvis","Urinary bladder"],"answer":3,"exp":"The urinary bladder is an expandable muscular organ that stores urine; its muscle is the detrusor.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The perinephric (perirenal) fat is best described as:","choices":["Dense irregular connective tissue anchoring the kidney","A layer between the renal fascia and peritoneum","An adipose layer that completely surrounds the kidney for cushioning and insulation","The internal space housing the renal pelvis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Perinephric (perirenal) fat completely surrounds the kidney, providing cushioning and insulation; paranephric fat lies between renal fascia and peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The renal sinus, the internal space of the kidney, houses all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":["The renal calyces","The renal pelvis","The renal pyramids","Blood vessels and fat"],"answer":2,"exp":"The renal sinus houses the renal pelvis, calyces, vessels, nerves, and fat; the renal pyramids are part of the medulla, not the sinus.","cite":"Slide 10 (Gross and Sectional Anatomy)"},{"q":"Approximately how many renal pyramids are typically found in each kidney?","choices":["1 to 3","8 to 15","20 to 30","40 to 50"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each kidney typically contains 8 to 15 renal pyramids in the medulla.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The renal fascia functions to:","choices":["Anchor the kidney to the posterior wall and peritoneum","Filter blood plasma","Store urine","Produce erythropoietin"],"answer":0,"exp":"The renal fascia is dense irregular connective tissue that anchors the kidney to the posterior body wall and peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The afferent arteriole delivers blood directly to which structure?","choices":["The arcuate vein","The peritubular capillaries","The vasa recta","The glomerulus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The afferent arteriole delivers blood to the glomerulus, where plasma is filtered into the glomerular (capsular) space.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"The arcuate arteries are positioned where within the kidney?","choices":["Along the ureter","Within the renal papillae","In the renal pelvis","Arching over the bases of the renal pyramids (corticomedullary junction)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Arcuate arteries arch along the corticomedullary junction (over the pyramid bases), giving rise to interlobular arteries.","cite":"Slides 16–17 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Plasma filtered across the glomerulus enters which space first?","choices":["The collecting duct","The proximal convoluted tubule directly","The glomerular (capsular) space of Bowman's capsule","The minor calyx"],"answer":2,"exp":"Filtered plasma crosses the glomerulus into the glomerular (capsular) space of Bowman's capsule before entering the PCT.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Which capillary network is specifically associated with juxtamedullary nephrons for concentrating urine?","choices":["Fenestrated sinusoids","Peritubular capillaries","Glomerular capillaries","Vasa recta"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vasa recta accompany the long loops of juxtamedullary nephrons and help concentrate urine.","cite":"Slides 18, 30 (Blood Supply / Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"The loop of Henle originates at the end of which tubule?","choices":["The distal convoluted tubule","The proximal convoluted tubule","The collecting duct","Bowman's capsule"],"answer":1,"exp":"The loop of Henle originates at the end of the PCT and projects toward/into the medulla, then returns to the cortex to become the DCT.","cite":"Slide 39 (Loop of Henle)"},{"q":"Once filtrate reaches the collecting ducts, what happens to its composition?","choices":["It is reabsorbed entirely","It is filtered again at a second glomerulus","It re-enters the PCT","No further modifications occur — it is now officially urine"],"answer":3,"exp":"In the collecting ducts no further modifications occur; the filtrate is now officially urine, draining via papillary ducts to the minor calyces.","cite":"Slide 41 (Collecting Tubule & Ducts)"},{"q":"The primary purpose of the long loops of juxtamedullary nephrons is the recovery of:","choices":["Proteins and albumin","Glucose and amino acids only","Water, Na+, and Cl-","Bicarbonate exclusively"],"answer":2,"exp":"Juxtamedullary nephrons' long loops primarily recover water, Na+, and Cl-, helping concentrate the urine.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"Multiple collecting ducts converge to form a structure that drains urine into a minor calyx; this structure is the:","choices":["Renal column","Renal papilla","Renal hilum","Glomerulus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Multiple collecting ducts come together at a renal papilla, which drains urine into a minor calyx.","cite":"Slide 41 (Collecting Tubule & Ducts)"},{"q":"Each limb of the loop of Henle has a characteristic wall thickness pattern. The descending limb is:","choices":["Thick then thin, projecting toward the medulla","Thin then thick, returning to the cortex","Uniformly thick throughout","Uniformly thin throughout"],"answer":0,"exp":"The descending limb runs thick then thin toward the medulla; the ascending limb runs thin then thick back toward the cortex.","cite":"Slide 39 (Loop of Henle)"},{"q":"In females, which organ lies posterosuperior to the urinary bladder?","choices":["The uterus","The rectum","The prostate","The sigmoid colon"],"answer":0,"exp":"In females the uterus lies posterosuperior to the bladder and the vagina lies posteroinferior; in males the rectum is posterosuperior.","cite":"Slide 51 (Urinary Bladder)"},{"q":"In males, which gland lies immediately inferior to the urinary bladder?","choices":["The adrenal gland","The seminal gland","The bulbo-urethral gland","The prostate gland"],"answer":3,"exp":"In males the prostate gland lies inferior to the bladder, and the rectum lies posterosuperior.","cite":"Slide 51 (Urinary Bladder)"},{"q":"The urinary bladder lies immediately superior and posterior to which bony landmark?","choices":["The pubic symphysis","The sacral promontory","The ischial tuberosity","The iliac crest"],"answer":0,"exp":"The bladder lies immediately superior and posterior to the pubic symphysis.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The median umbilical ligament, related to the bladder apex, is a remnant of the:","choices":["Ureteric bud","Ductus deferens","Round ligament","Urachus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The median umbilical ligament is the remnant of the urachus, the fetal tube that returned urine via the umbilical cord.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The ureters average approximately what length as they run retroperitoneally from the renal pelvis to the bladder?","choices":["10 cm","25 cm","50 cm","5 cm"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ureters are long fibromuscular tubes averaging about 25 cm in length, running retroperitoneally.","cite":"Slide 44 (Ureters)"},{"q":"The detrusor muscle of the bladder wall is composed of which tissue arranged in three layers?","choices":["Smooth muscle","Skeletal muscle","Cardiac muscle","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":0,"exp":"The detrusor is smooth muscle arranged as inner and outer longitudinal fibers around a middle circular layer (three layers).","cite":"Slide 53 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The muscularis of the ureter consists of smooth muscle whose peristaltic action moves urine. Its basic arrangement is:","choices":["Inner longitudinal and outer circular","Inner circular and outer longitudinal only","A single circular layer","Skeletal muscle bundles"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ureter's muscularis is inner longitudinal and outer circular smooth muscle (with an external longitudinal layer in the distal third), producing peristalsis.","cite":"Slide 45 (Ureter Walls)"},{"q":"The fenestrated endothelium of the glomerular capillaries is significant because the fenestrae make the capillaries:","choices":["Impermeable to water","Highly permeable for filtration","Contractile","Rich in cilia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Large fenestrae (pores) make the glomerular endothelium highly permeable, facilitating filtration of plasma.","cite":"Slide 33 (Filtration Membranes)"},{"q":"Filtration slits, which help prevent large anions and proteins from being filtered, are formed by the pedicels of which cells?","choices":["Macula densa cells","Podocytes","Juxtaglomerular cells","Simple squamous parietal cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Podocyte pedicels (foot processes) form the negatively charged filtration slits that restrict passage of large anions and proteins.","cite":"Slide 34 (Filtration Membranes)"},{"q":"The macula densa, part of the juxtaglomerular apparatus, functions as a sensor for:","choices":["Sodium (NaCl) concentration and tubular flow","Oxygen tension only","Blood pH only","Glucose concentration"],"answer":0,"exp":"The macula densa senses NaCl concentration and tubular flow; juxtaglomerular (granular) cells secrete renin in response.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"},{"q":"On average, the fully distended adult bladder can hold approximately how much urine?","choices":["About 2 liters","About 100 mL","About 500 mL","About 50 mL"],"answer":2,"exp":"The bladder can expand to about 15 times its empty volume, holding roughly 500 mL of urine in an average adult.","cite":"Slide 53 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The male urethra differs from the female urethra in length, measuring approximately:","choices":["3–4 cm (vs 18–20 cm in females)","18–20 cm (vs 3–4 cm in females)","25 cm (vs 10 cm in females)","1 cm (vs 5 cm in females)"],"answer":1,"exp":"The male urethra is about 18–20 cm long and has three regions; the female urethra is about 3–4 cm long.","cite":"Slides 58–59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"Excitation of the renal sympathetic nerves affects the glomerulus by:","choices":["Dilating the afferent arteriole to increase filtration","Vasoconstricting both afferent and efferent arterioles, decreasing urine production","Directly secreting renin","Relaxing the detrusor muscle"],"answer":1,"exp":"Sympathetic activity vasoconstricts both the afferent and efferent arterioles, decreasing glomerular blood flow and urine production.","cite":"Slide 26 (Innervation)"},{"q":"The apex of a renal pyramid, which projects toward a minor calyx, is the:","choices":["Renal hilum","Renal column","Renal papilla","Renal arch"],"answer":2,"exp":"The apex of each renal pyramid is the renal papilla, which drains urine into a minor calyx.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"}]},"anatomy-master-a":{"title":"Anatomy Exam 3 Comprehensive Master Exam — Form A","questions":[{"q":"The alimentary canal is another name for the:","choices":["Peritoneal cavity","Gastrointestinal (digestive) tract","Portal venous system","Biliary tree"],"answer":1,"exp":"The GI tract is also called the digestive tract or alimentary canal — a continuous tube from mouth to anus.","cite":"Slide 7 (General Structure)"},{"q":"Which organ is the FIRST segment of the GI tract, serving as its entrance?","choices":["Esophagus","Oral cavity","Pharynx","Stomach"],"answer":1,"exp":"The oral cavity is the entrance to the GI tract and the initial site of mechanical and chemical digestion.","cite":"Slide 24 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The peritoneum is what type of membrane?","choices":["Serous membrane","Mucous membrane","Synovial membrane","Fibrous membrane"],"answer":0,"exp":"The peritoneum is a serous membrane lining the abdomen and pelvis, with parietal and visceral layers.","cite":"Slide 13 (Peritoneum)"},{"q":"The gingivae (gums) are covered by which epithelium?","choices":["Nonkeratinized epithelium over dense regular CT","Keratinized stratified squamous epithelium","Simple columnar epithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":0,"exp":"The gingivae have nonkeratinized epithelium over dense regular connective tissue; the lips are keratinized.","cite":"Slide 26 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The most superior region of the stomach, positioned above the cardia, is the:","choices":["Body","Antrum","Pyloric canal","Fundus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The fundus is the most superior region of the stomach; the cardia surrounds the esophageal opening.","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"The spleen develops from and functions primarily as part of which system?","choices":["Digestive system","Lymphatic system","Endocrine system","Urinary system"],"answer":1,"exp":"The spleen is a lymphatic organ with white pulp (lymphatic) and red pulp (blood filtering/hematopoietic).","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"The retroperitoneal, shortest and widest segment of the small intestine is the:","choices":["Ileum","Jejunum","Duodenum","Cecum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The duodenum is the shortest, widest, and mostly retroperitoneal first segment of the small intestine.","cite":"Slide 66 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"The pouches formed along the colon by muscle tone of the taeniae coli are the:","choices":["Villi","Plicae circulares","Rugae","Haustra"],"answer":3,"exp":"Haustra are the sacculations of the colon created by the tone of the taeniae coli, permitting expansion.","cite":"Slides 89, 91 (The Colon)"},{"q":"The main pancreatic duct is also called the:","choices":["Common bile duct","Duct of Santorini","Duct of Wirsung","Cystic duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The main pancreatic duct is the duct of Wirsung; the accessory duct is the duct of Santorini.","cite":"Slides 71–72 (Pancreatic Duct System)"},{"q":"The left lobe of the liver is separated from the right lobe by which structure on the anterior surface?","choices":["The porta hepatis","The ligamentum venosum","The falciform ligament","The coronary ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The falciform ligament separates the right and left lobes of the liver anteriorly.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The hepatic portal vein is formed by the union of the splenic vein and which other vein?","choices":["Renal vein","Inferior vena cava","Hepatic vein","Superior mesenteric vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"The hepatic portal vein forms from the union of the splenic and superior mesenteric veins.","cite":"Slides 121, 135 (Portal supply / Pancreas Veins)"},{"q":"The rounded, blind end of the gallbladder that projects beyond the liver margin is the:","choices":["Neck","Fundus","Body","Cystic duct"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gallbladder's fundus is the rounded blind end; the body and neck continue toward the cystic duct.","cite":"Slide 126 (The Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The celiac trunk emerges from the aorta at which location?","choices":["Within the inguinal canal","At the bifurcation into common iliacs","Behind the left renal vein","The aortic hiatus between the diaphragmatic crura"],"answer":3,"exp":"The celiac trunk arises at the aortic hiatus between the crura of the diaphragm.","cite":"Slide 139 (Arterial Supply of the Abdomen)"},{"q":"The inferior vena cava carries blood to which chamber of the heart?","choices":["Right ventricle","Left atrium","Right atrium","Left ventricle"],"answer":2,"exp":"The IVC returns systemic venous blood directly to the right atrium.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Lymph from the abdominal GI viscera ultimately collects into which structure at the start of the thoracic duct?","choices":["The portal vein","The azygos vein","The cisterna chyli","The hepatic duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"Abdominal lymph drains toward the cisterna chyli, the dilated origin of the thoracic duct.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"The hypothalamus exerts direct control over which part of the adrenal gland via preganglionic sympathetic fibers?","choices":["The zona glomerulosa","The suprarenal medulla","The zona fasciculata","The adrenal capsule"],"answer":1,"exp":"The hypothalamus controls sympathetic output to the suprarenal (adrenal) medulla, driving epinephrine/norepinephrine release.","cite":"Slides 9, 11 (Hypothalamic Control)"},{"q":"The pineal gland secretes which hormone?","choices":["Cortisol","Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin","Melatonin"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pineal gland secretes melatonin.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1)"},{"q":"The thyroid follicle is the structural unit of the thyroid gland and stores hormone precursor in the form of:","choices":["Glycocalyx","Zymogen granules","Herring bodies","Colloid"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each thyroid follicle surrounds a central mass of colloid, the storage form of thyroid hormone precursor.","cite":"Slide 30 (Histology of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"Chromophobes of the pars distalis are distinguished by:","choices":["Secreting calcitonin","Reddish granulated cytoplasm","Lacking cytoplasmic granules","Forming follicles"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chromophobes (~50% of pars distalis cells) lack granules; chromophils (acidophils/basophils) contain granules.","cite":"Slide 21 (Pars distalis)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland occupies the hypophyseal fossa within which bony feature?","choices":["The foramen magnum","The cribriform plate of the ethmoid","The petrous temporal bone","The sella turcica of the sphenoid"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pituitary sits in the hypophyseal fossa of the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone.","cite":"Slides 13, 15 (Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"The regulatory hormones of the hypothalamus reach the adenohypophysis via which vascular route?","choices":["The internal carotid artery directly","The hypophyseal portal system","The cavernous sinus","The hepatic portal system"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hypothalamic regulatory hormones travel through the hypophyseal portal veins to the adenohypophysis.","cite":"Slides 17–18 (Hypophyseal Portal System)"},{"q":"A rise in blood calcium would be expected to stimulate the secretion of which hormone?","choices":["Parathyroid hormone","Calcitonin","Calcitriol","Aldosterone"],"answer":1,"exp":"High blood calcium stimulates calcitonin (from thyroid C cells), which lowers blood calcium.","cite":"Slide 31 (Parafollicular / C cells)"},{"q":"The male gamete produced by the reproductive system is called:","choices":["A spermatogonium only","An oocyte","A zygote","Sperm"],"answer":3,"exp":"The male produces gametes called sperm; the female produces oocytes.","cite":"Slide 3 (Introduction)"},{"q":"The joining of a sperm and an oocyte, which forms a zygote, is called:","choices":["Capacitation","Fertilization","Spermiogenesis","Meiosis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Fertilization is the joining of sperm and oocyte, resulting in a zygote.","cite":"Slide 3 (Introduction)"},{"q":"The muscle that overlies the bulb of the penis and contracts during ejaculation is the:","choices":["Dartos","Bulbospongiosus","Cremaster","Iliococcygeus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The bulbospongiosus overlies the bulb of the penis and, with the ischiocavernosus, aids ejaculation.","cite":"Slides 49, 67 (Bulbospongiosus / ejaculation)"},{"q":"The ischiocavernosus muscle, active in ejaculation, is associated with which structure?","choices":["The crus of the penis","The bulb of the penis","The glans","The prostate"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ischiocavernosus overlies the crura of the penis and contracts during ejaculation.","cite":"Slides 62, 67 (Penis / ejaculation)"},{"q":"The internal pudendal artery arises from which vessel?","choices":["External iliac artery","Femoral artery","Internal iliac artery","Abdominal aorta"],"answer":2,"exp":"The internal pudendal artery is a branch of the internal iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 21 (scrotal blood supply)"},{"q":"Erection is primarily mediated by which autonomic division?","choices":["Enteric","Sympathetic","Somatic only","Parasympathetic"],"answer":3,"exp":"Parasympathetic activity dilates penile arteries, engorging the erectile tissue to produce erection.","cite":"Slide 66 (Erection of the penis)"},{"q":"The mediastinum of the testis supports ducts that move material toward the:","choices":["Epididymis","Prostate","Bladder","Seminal gland"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mediastinum of the testis supports the rete testis and ducts leading toward the epididymis.","cite":"Slide 23 (Structure of the Testes)"},{"q":"Within the testis, sperm move from the seminiferous tubules into which structure next?","choices":["The rete testis directly","The efferent ductules","The epididymis","The straight tubules"],"answer":3,"exp":"Sperm pass from seminiferous tubules into straight tubules, then the rete testis, then efferent ductules.","cite":"Slide 25 (Histology of the Testes)"},{"q":"The prostatic urethra receives the openings of the:","choices":["Bulbo-urethral ducts only","Ejaculatory ducts and prostatic ducts","Efferent ductules","Ureters"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prostatic urethra receives the ejaculatory ducts and multiple small prostatic ducts.","cite":"Slides 50, 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts are also known as the:","choices":["Pronephric ducts","Mesonephric ducts","Wolffian ducts","Paramesonephric ducts"],"answer":3,"exp":"The Müllerian ducts are the paramesonephric ducts, which form the female internal organs.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The Wolffian ducts are another name for the:","choices":["Mesonephric ducts","Paramesonephric ducts","Müllerian ducts","Metanephric ducts"],"answer":0,"exp":"The Wolffian (mesonephric) ducts run alongside the Müllerian ducts during development.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The perineum is described as which shape?","choices":["Circular","Triangular","Diamond-shaped","Rectangular"],"answer":2,"exp":"The perineum is a diamond-shaped area between the thighs.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The perineum is bounded anteriorly by which structure?","choices":["The pubic symphysis","The coccyx","The ischial tuberosities","The sacrum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The perineum is bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the ischial tuberosities, and posteriorly by the coccyx.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The broad ligament attaches from the lateral uterine fold to which structure?","choices":["The labia majora","The sacrum","The wall of the pelvis","The ovary directly"],"answer":2,"exp":"The broad ligament extends from the lateral uterine fold to the pelvic wall, holding the ovaries and uterine tubes.","cite":"Slide 18 (Supporting Ligaments)"},{"q":"The two muscle groups composing the pelvic diaphragm are the coccygeus and the:","choices":["Levator ani","Bulbospongiosus","Ischiocavernosus","Obturator internus"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm is formed by the levator ani and coccygeus muscles.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The ovarian artery arises from the abdominal aorta at a level just inferior to which arteries?","choices":["The renal arteries","The celiac trunk","The common iliac arteries","The inferior mesenteric artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ovarian arteries arise from the abdominal aorta inferior to the renal arteries.","cite":"Slide 41 (The Uterine Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Parasympathetic innervation to the ovary is provided by the:","choices":["Vagus nerve","Pelvic splanchnic nerves","Greater splanchnic nerve","Phrenic nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ovary receives parasympathetic supply from the pelvic splanchnic nerves.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The main portion of the uterus, whose cavity is triangular, is the:","choices":["Cervix","Fundus","Isthmus","Body"],"answer":3,"exp":"The body is the main portion of the uterus with a triangular cavity; the fundus is superior and the cervix inferior.","cite":"Slide 34 (Anatomic Regions)"},{"q":"The uterine tube epithelium moves the ovum toward the uterus by ciliary action, taking approximately:","choices":["3–4 days","30 minutes","2 weeks","6 hours"],"answer":0,"exp":"Cilia move the oocyte toward the uterus over roughly 3–4 days.","cite":"Slide 52 (Histology)"},{"q":"The rectouterine pouch forms the space between the uterus and the:","choices":["Vagina","Urinary bladder","Rectum","Sacrum"],"answer":2,"exp":"The rectouterine pouch is the posterior recess between the uterus and rectum.","cite":"Slide 12 (Anatomy of the Female Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The kidneys convert filtered plasma into which product?","choices":["Urine","Bile","Lymph","Chyme"],"answer":0,"exp":"The kidneys filter waste from the blood and convert the filtrate into urine.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"Which structure conducts urine from the bladder to the exterior?","choices":["Renal pelvis","Ureter","Urethra","Collecting duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The urethra drains urine from the bladder to outside the body.","cite":"Slides 3, 58 (Organs Involved / Urethra)"},{"q":"The functional filtering tissue of the kidney is organized into an outer cortex and an inner:","choices":["Sinus","Medulla","Pelvis","Capsule"],"answer":1,"exp":"The kidney has an outer renal cortex and an inner renal medulla (divided into pyramids).","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The renal pelvis exits the kidney at which structure?","choices":["The hilum","The renal papilla","The cortex","The fibrous capsule"],"answer":0,"exp":"The renal pelvis exits at the hilum, the concave medial border where vessels and nerves also enter.","cite":"Slides 6, 10 (Kidney Location / Gross Anatomy)"},{"q":"The arcuate arteries give rise to which vessels that ascend into the cortex?","choices":["Afferent arterioles directly","Interlobar arteries","Segmental arteries","Interlobular arteries"],"answer":3,"exp":"Arcuate arteries give rise to interlobular arteries, which then supply afferent arterioles.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"The renal corpuscle is composed of the glomerular capsule and the:","choices":["Glomerulus","Proximal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct","Loop of Henle"],"answer":0,"exp":"The renal corpuscle consists of the glomerulus and the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule.","cite":"Slide 29 (Nephron Structures)"},{"q":"The left kidney typically sits at which vertebral levels?","choices":["L3 to L5","T12 to L3","T10/11 to L2","T6 to T9"],"answer":2,"exp":"The left kidney is slightly higher (T10/11–L2); the right is T12–L3 because the liver displaces it inferiorly.","cite":"Slide 6 (Kidney Location)"},{"q":"The visceral layer of Bowman's capsule is formed by which specialized cells?","choices":["Podocytes","Simple squamous parietal cells","Macula densa cells","Chief cells"],"answer":0,"exp":"The visceral layer of Bowman's capsule consists of podocytes with foot processes (pedicels).","cite":"Slide 35 (Renal Corpuscle)"}]},"anatomy-master-b":{"title":"Anatomy Exam 3 Comprehensive Master Exam — Form B","questions":[{"q":"Which of the following organs is part of the continuous GI tube rather than an accessory organ?","choices":["Pharynx","Liver","Pancreas","Gallbladder"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pharynx is part of the GI tube (oral cavity, pharynx, esophagus, stomach, intestines); the liver, gallbladder, and pancreas are accessory organs.","cite":"Slide 8 (General Structure)"},{"q":"The teeth, tongue, and salivary glands assist digestion but are classified as:","choices":["GI tract organs","Accessory digestive organs","Retroperitoneal viscera","Peritoneal folds"],"answer":1,"exp":"Teeth, tongue, and salivary glands are accessory digestive organs connected to but not forming the GI tube.","cite":"Slide 9 (Accessory digestive organs)"},{"q":"The lesser sac of the peritoneal cavity is also known as the:","choices":["Rectouterine pouch","Greater sac","Omental bursa","Paracolic gutter"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser sac (omental bursa) is one of the two peritoneal cavity spaces, the other being the greater sac.","cite":"Slide 13 (Peritoneum)"},{"q":"The tongue is composed of which muscle type, covered by lightly keratinized epithelium?","choices":["Elastic cartilage","Smooth muscle","Cardiac muscle","Skeletal muscle"],"answer":3,"exp":"The tongue is formed from skeletal muscle covered with lightly keratinized stratified squamous epithelium.","cite":"Slide 35 (Tongue)"},{"q":"The region of the stomach immediately surrounding the esophageal opening is the:","choices":["Cardia","Fundus","Pylorus","Body"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cardia is the stomach region surrounding the gastroesophageal junction.","cite":"Slide 54 (The Stomach)"},{"q":"The splenic vein, draining the spleen, ultimately contributes to which venous system?","choices":["The azygos system","The portal venous system","The renal venous system","The pulmonary veins"],"answer":1,"exp":"The splenic vein joins the superior mesenteric vein to form the hepatic portal vein.","cite":"Slide 138 (Splenic Vein)"},{"q":"The duodenojejunal flexure is anchored by which structure?","choices":["The mesoappendix","The ligamentum teres","The falciform ligament","The ligament of Treitz"],"answer":3,"exp":"The suspensory ligament of the duodenum (ligament of Treitz) marks the duodenojejunal flexure.","cite":"Slide 68 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"The ascending colon terminates at which flexure?","choices":["The sigmoid flexure","The left colic (splenic) flexure","The duodenojejunal flexure","The right colic (hepatic) flexure"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ascending colon begins at the ileocecal valve and ends at the right colic (hepatic) flexure.","cite":"Slide 93 (Ascending Colon)"},{"q":"The main pancreatic duct typically joins the common bile duct at the:","choices":["Ampulla of Vater","Pyloric sphincter","Ileocecal valve","Duodenal cap"],"answer":0,"exp":"The main pancreatic duct joins the common bile duct at the hepatopancreatic ampulla (of Vater) in the descending duodenum.","cite":"Slide 71 (Pancreatic Duct System)"},{"q":"The liver performs which of the following functions?","choices":["Filtration of urine","Production of insulin","Production of blood clotting proteins","Storage of bile only, with no synthesis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Liver functions include bile secretion, detoxification, clotting-protein production, glycogen/vitamin/mineral storage, and immune support.","cite":"Slide 104 (The Liver)"},{"q":"Blood in the hepatic portal vein is characterized as:","choices":["Fully oxygenated arterial blood","Nutrient-rich blood needing metabolic processing","Deoxygenated blood returning to the heart","Filtered lymph"],"answer":1,"exp":"The portal vein carries nutrient-rich blood from the GI tract that requires hepatic metabolic processing.","cite":"Slide 108 (Liver triple blood supply)"},{"q":"The common bile duct is formed by the union of the cystic duct and the:","choices":["Accessory pancreatic duct","Main pancreatic duct","Right hepatic duct only","Common hepatic duct"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cystic duct joins the common hepatic duct to form the common bile duct.","cite":"Slides 121, 126 (biliary tree)"},{"q":"The proper hepatic artery is a continuation of which vessel?","choices":["The left gastric artery","The splenic artery","The common hepatic artery","The superior mesenteric artery"],"answer":2,"exp":"The common hepatic artery gives the gastroduodenal artery and continues as the proper hepatic artery.","cite":"Slide 142 (Common Hepatic Artery)"},{"q":"Which of the following is a direct tributary of the IVC?","choices":["Superior mesenteric vein","Splenic vein","Hepatic veins","Left gastric vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The hepatic veins drain directly into the IVC; the splenic, SMV, and left gastric are portal tributaries.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Visceral abdominal lymph nodes are typically clustered around which structures?","choices":["The bile ducts only","The ureters","The peripheral nerves","The major arterial branches of the aorta"],"answer":3,"exp":"Visceral nodes cluster around the celiac, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric arteries.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"Which pancreatic islet hormones are highlighted as products of the endocrine pancreas?","choices":["T3 and T4","Cortisol and aldosterone","Insulin and glucagon","ADH and oxytocin"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pancreatic islets secrete insulin and glucagon (plus somatostatin and pancreatic polypeptide).","cite":"Slides 5, 52 (Pancreatic Islets)"},{"q":"The kidney contributes to the endocrine system by producing erythropoietin and:","choices":["Melatonin","Calcitonin","Insulin","Calcitriol"],"answer":3,"exp":"The kidney produces erythropoietin (EPO) and calcitriol (active vitamin D).","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Kidney)"},{"q":"The bundles of nerve fibers in the pars nervosa arise in the hypothalamus and form which tract?","choices":["The tuberoinfundibular tract","The corticospinal tract","The spinothalamic tract","The hypothalamo-hypophyseal tract"],"answer":3,"exp":"The pars nervosa contains fibers of the hypothalamo-hypophyseal tract descending from the hypothalamus.","cite":"Slide 22 (Pars nervosa)"},{"q":"Principal (chief) cells of the parathyroid gland are characterized by:","choices":["Colloid storage","Very eosinophilic cytoplasm of unknown function","Slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm and PTH production","Catecholamine secretion"],"answer":2,"exp":"Chief cells have slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm and produce PTH; oxyphils are larger and more eosinophilic.","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"Unlike the anterior pituitary, the posterior pituitary receives predominantly:","choices":["Portal venous blood","Arterial blood","Lymphatic drainage only","No blood supply"],"answer":1,"exp":"The anterior pituitary receives portal blood; the posterior pituitary receives arterial blood.","cite":"Slide 19 (Note)"},{"q":"The superior thyroid artery descends toward the gland accompanied by which nerve?","choices":["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve"],"answer":1,"exp":"The superior thyroid artery is accompanied by the external laryngeal nerve, from which it separates at the gland's apex.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"Parathyroid hormone is secreted in response to which stimulus?","choices":["A fall in blood glucose","A rise in blood calcium","A fall in blood calcium","A rise in blood pressure"],"answer":2,"exp":"Low blood calcium stimulates parathyroid chief cells to release PTH, which raises blood calcium.","cite":"Slides 44, 46 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"During descent, why do the testes ultimately reside outside the abdominal cavity?","choices":["Sperm development requires a cooler temperature","Testosterone is produced only in the scrotum","The abdominal cavity lacks blood supply","Descent prevents torsion"],"answer":0,"exp":"Sperm development requires ~96.6°F, cooler than core body temperature, so the testes descend to the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 10 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"Which structures pass through the inguinal canal along with the descending testis?","choices":["The prostate","The ureter","The bulbo-urethral glands","The spermatic cord contents"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spermatic cord (ductus deferens, vessels, nerves, lymphatics) passes through the inguinal canal with the testis.","cite":"Slides 9, 14 (Descent / Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"The dartos muscle is best classified as which muscle type?","choices":["Striated voluntary muscle","Skeletal muscle","Cardiac muscle","Smooth muscle"],"answer":3,"exp":"The dartos is a superficial smooth muscle that wrinkles the scrotal skin.","cite":"Slide 18 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"The cremaster muscle is found within which structure?","choices":["The cremasteric fascia of the spermatic cord","The tunica albuginea","The corpus spongiosum","The prostate capsule"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cremaster lies within the cremasteric fascia, part of the spermatic cord/scrotal coverings.","cite":"Slide 15 (Layers of the Scrotum)"},{"q":"The deep artery of the penis is responsible for:","choices":["Engorging the corpora cavernosa during erection","Draining venous blood from the glans","Supplying the scrotal skin","Supplying the epididymis"],"answer":0,"exp":"The deep artery of the penis runs centrally in each corpus cavernosum and engorges the erectile tissue.","cite":"Slides 62, 65 (Penis)"},{"q":"Emission and ejaculation are primarily under which autonomic control?","choices":["Parasympathetic","Sympathetic","Somatic sensory","Enteric"],"answer":1,"exp":"Emission and ejaculation are driven by sympathetic activity, with somatic contraction of perineal muscles.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The prostate gland contributes approximately what percentage of semen volume?","choices":["60 percent","20–30 percent","5 percent","90 percent"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prostate produces 20–30% of semen volume; the seminal glands produce ~60%.","cite":"Slide 56 (The Prostate)"},{"q":"The ejaculatory duct is formed by the union of the ampulla of the ductus deferens and the:","choices":["Excretory duct of the seminal gland","Cystic duct","Prostatic urethra","Efferent ductule"],"answer":0,"exp":"The ampulla joins the seminal gland's excretory duct to form the ejaculatory duct.","cite":"Slide 48 (The Ductus Deferens)"},{"q":"The membranous urethra is the segment that pierces the:","choices":["Bladder wall","Prostate gland","Corpus spongiosum","Urogenital diaphragm"],"answer":3,"exp":"The membranous urethra pierces the urogenital diaphragm (muscular pelvic floor).","cite":"Slides 51, 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The uterovaginal primordium is formed by the fusion of which structures?","choices":["The urogenital sinus and allantois","The two mesonephric ducts","The caudal portions of the paired Müllerian ducts","The gubernaculum and round ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The caudal portions of the paired Müllerian ducts fuse in the midline to form the uterovaginal primordium.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts develop into female organs during approximately which developmental window?","choices":["Weeks 6–12","Weeks 1–3","Weeks 20–24","Weeks 30–36"],"answer":0,"exp":"The paramesonephric ducts develop into female organs during weeks 6–12.","cite":"Slide 17 (Müllerian System)"},{"q":"The anal triangle contains which structure in both sexes?","choices":["The urethral orifice","The anus","The vaginal orifice","The clitoris"],"answer":1,"exp":"The posterior (anal) triangle contains the anus in both sexes.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The urogenital triangle is another name for the perineum's:","choices":["Anterior triangle","Posterior triangle","Lateral triangle","Deep triangle"],"answer":0,"exp":"The anterior triangle is the urogenital triangle; the posterior is the anal triangle.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The round ligament of the uterus terminates in which structure?","choices":["The pelvic wall","The sacrum","The labia majora","The ovary"],"answer":2,"exp":"The round ligament passes through the inguinal canal to end in the labia majora.","cite":"Slide 18 (Supporting Ligaments)"},{"q":"The iliococcygeus is a component of which muscle?","choices":["Bulbospongiosus","Coccygeus","Levator ani","Rectus abdominis"],"answer":2,"exp":"The levator ani comprises the puborectalis, pubococcygeus, and iliococcygeus.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The uterine artery is a branch of which vessel?","choices":["The internal iliac artery","The abdominal aorta","The external iliac artery","The ovarian artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterine artery arises from the internal iliac artery.","cite":"Slide 41 (The Uterine Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Ovarian visceral afferent (pain) fibers enter the spinal cord at:","choices":["T10–T11","L4–L5","S2–S4","C6–C7"],"answer":0,"exp":"Ovarian afferent fibers enter the cord at T10 and T11.","cite":"Slide 27 (Innervation of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The rounded portion of the uterus superior and anterior to the entrance of the uterine tubes is the:","choices":["Body","Fundus","Isthmus","Cervix"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fundus is the rounded portion superior and anterior to the uterine tube entrances.","cite":"Slide 34 (Anatomic Regions)"},{"q":"The perimetrium of the uterus is composed of:","choices":["Hormone-sensitive glandular epithelium","Three layers of smooth muscle","Peritoneum and thin connective tissue","Transitional epithelium"],"answer":2,"exp":"The perimetrium is peritoneum plus thin connective tissue — the outer serosa of the uterus.","cite":"Slide 35 (Uterine Layers)"},{"q":"The vesicouterine pouch forms the space between the uterus and the:","choices":["Rectum","Urinary bladder","Vagina","Ovary"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vesicouterine pouch is the anterior recess between the uterus and the bladder.","cite":"Slide 12 (Anatomy of the Female Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The ureters, bladder, and urethra together are referred to as the:","choices":["Renal sinus","Renal corpuscle","Nephron","Urinary tract"],"answer":3,"exp":"The urinary tract (ureters, bladder, urethra) transports urine out of the body.","cite":"Slide 4 (Systems Involved)"},{"q":"The female urethra is approximately how long?","choices":["3–4 cm","18–20 cm","10 cm","25 cm"],"answer":0,"exp":"The female urethra is about 3–4 cm long; the male urethra is about 18–20 cm.","cite":"Slide 58 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The paranephric (pararenal) fat is located where?","choices":["Within the renal sinus","Directly on the cortex","Between the renal fascia and the peritoneum","Inside the renal pelvis"],"answer":2,"exp":"Paranephric (pararenal) fat lies between the renal fascia and the peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The renal papilla drains urine into which structure?","choices":["The renal pelvis directly","A major calyx","A minor calyx","The ureter directly"],"answer":2,"exp":"The renal papilla (apex of a pyramid) drains urine into a minor calyx.","cite":"Slides 14, 41 (Coronal Sections / Collecting Ducts)"},{"q":"Which vessel carries blood INTO the glomerulus?","choices":["Efferent arteriole","Afferent arteriole","Interlobular vein","Peritubular capillary"],"answer":1,"exp":"The afferent arteriole delivers blood to the glomerulus; the efferent arteriole carries it away.","cite":"Slide 16 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Filtrate leaving the distal convoluted tubule next enters the:","choices":["Bowman's capsule","Proximal convoluted tubule","Loop of Henle","Collecting tubule/duct"],"answer":3,"exp":"After the DCT, filtrate enters the collecting tubule and then the collecting duct.","cite":"Slides 22, 42 (Flow of Urine)"},{"q":"The urachus, whose remnant is the median umbilical ligament, originally functioned to:","choices":["Supply blood to the bladder","Return fetal urine to the mother via the umbilical cord","Anchor the kidneys","Drain the ureters"],"answer":1,"exp":"The urachus returned fetal urine to the mother via the umbilical cord; its remnant is the median umbilical ligament.","cite":"Slide 49 (Bladder)"},{"q":"The juxtaglomerular (granular) cells are modified smooth muscle cells of which structure?","choices":["The renal capsule","The distal convoluted tubule","The collecting duct","The afferent arteriole"],"answer":3,"exp":"Juxtaglomerular (granular) cells are modified smooth muscle of the afferent arteriole; they secrete renin.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"}]},"anatomy-master-c":{"title":"Anatomy Exam 3 Comprehensive Master Exam — Form C","questions":[{"q":"Peristaltic movement of material through the GI tract is a function of which wall property?","choices":["Passive gravity flow","Ciliary beating","Skeletal muscle only","Smooth muscle contraction"],"answer":3,"exp":"Smooth muscle in the GI wall produces motility, pushing material along the tract.","cite":"Slide 8 (General Structure)"},{"q":"The intrinsic innervation of the GI tract that coordinates smooth-muscle activity is the:","choices":["Phrenic nerve","Sympathetic chain","Somatic motor system","Enteric nervous system"],"answer":3,"exp":"The enteric nervous system, distributed in two intramuscular plexuses, provides intrinsic innervation of the gut.","cite":"Slide 12 (Special Features)"},{"q":"The mesentery proper suspends which parts of the bowel?","choices":["The jejunum and ileum","The ascending and descending colon","The duodenum and pancreas","The rectum and anal canal"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mesentery proper suspends the jejunum and ileum and carries their vessels, lymphatics, and nerves.","cite":"Slide 22 (Mesentery)"},{"q":"The muscularis of the esophagus is unusual in that it contains:","choices":["Only cardiac muscle","Only skeletal muscle","Both skeletal and smooth muscle","Only elastic tissue"],"answer":2,"exp":"The esophageal muscularis has inner circular and outer longitudinal layers of both skeletal and smooth muscle.","cite":"Slide 42 (Esophagus)"},{"q":"The longitudinal folds of the stomach lining that disappear as it fills are the:","choices":["Haustra","Plicae circulares","Rugae","Taeniae coli"],"answer":2,"exp":"Rugae are longitudinal gastric folds that flatten as the stomach fills; plicae circulares are permanent small-intestinal folds.","cite":"Slides 12, 58 (Stomach Interior)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the spleen is:","choices":["Intraperitoneal","Retroperitoneal","Subperitoneal","Extraperitoneal"],"answer":0,"exp":"The spleen is intraperitoneal, lying anterior to ribs 9–11.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"Compared with the ileum, the jejunum is characterized by:","choices":["A retroperitoneal position","Thinner walls and Peyer's patches","Larger diameter, thicker walls, and more vascularity","Absence of plicae circulares"],"answer":2,"exp":"The jejunum has a larger diameter, thicker walls, prominent plicae circulares, and richer vascularity than the ileum.","cite":"Slide 75 (Jejunum)"},{"q":"The narrowest-diameter, retroperitoneal segment continuous with the sigmoid colon is the:","choices":["Descending colon","Ascending colon","Transverse colon","Cecum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The descending colon is retroperitoneal, the narrowest in diameter, and continuous with the sigmoid colon.","cite":"Slide 96 (Descending Colon)"},{"q":"The accessory pancreatic duct (of Santorini) drains into the duodenum at the:","choices":["Ampulla of Vater","Major papilla","Pyloric canal","Minor papilla"],"answer":3,"exp":"The accessory duct of Santorini joins the duodenum at the minor papilla.","cite":"Slide 74 (Duct of Santorini)"},{"q":"The bare area of the liver is significant because it is:","choices":["Covered by two layers of omentum","Where the gallbladder attaches","The site of the portal triad","Not covered by peritoneum"],"answer":3,"exp":"The liver is completely covered by Glisson's capsule but only incompletely by peritoneum, leaving a bare area surrounded by peritoneal ligaments.","cite":"Slides 104, 113 (Liver)"},{"q":"Within a liver lobule, blood ultimately collects into which vessel at the center?","choices":["The portal vein","The central vein","The bile duct","The hepatic artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"Blood flows from the portal triad through sinusoids to the central vein of each lobule.","cite":"Slide 121 (Histology of the liver)"},{"q":"The common bile duct passes behind the first part of the duodenum and then through which structure before reaching the ampulla?","choices":["The transverse colon","The spleen","The left lobe of the liver","The head of the pancreas"],"answer":3,"exp":"The common bile duct passes behind the first part of the duodenum, then through the pancreatic head, terminating at the ampulla of Vater.","cite":"Slide 64 (Common Bile Duct)"},{"q":"The superior mesenteric artery primarily supplies which region of the gut?","choices":["The hindgut","The foregut","The midgut","The pelvic viscera"],"answer":2,"exp":"The SMA supplies midgut derivatives (distal duodenum through the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon).","cite":"Slide 143 (Superior Mesenteric Artery)"},{"q":"The IVC begins at approximately which vertebral level from the union of the common iliac veins?","choices":["T8","L5","T12","S1"],"answer":1,"exp":"The IVC begins around L5 where the common iliac veins unite, ascending to pierce the diaphragm at T8.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"The esophagus is clinically important for portosystemic anastomosis because it drains into the portal vein and the:","choices":["Splenic vein","Renal vein","Gonadal vein","Azygos vein"],"answer":3,"exp":"Esophageal venous drainage reaches both the portal vein (via left gastric) and the azygos system, a key portosystemic anastomosis.","cite":"Slide 41 (Esophagus)"},{"q":"The pituitary gland is also known by which name?","choices":["The infundibulum","The epiphysis","The hypophysis","The sella turcica"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pituitary gland is the hypophysis, attached to the hypothalamus by the infundibulum.","cite":"Slide 10 (The Pituitary Gland)"},{"q":"Which gland is subdivided into a cortex and a medulla that have entirely different embryonic origins and secretions?","choices":["Thyroid gland","Suprarenal (adrenal) gland","Parathyroid gland","Pineal gland"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each suprarenal gland has an outer cortex (steroid hormones) and inner medulla (catecholamines).","cite":"Slides 5, 82 (Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex is composed of cells arranged in which pattern?","choices":["Ovoid clusters","Radial columns","Loose meshwork","Follicles"],"answer":0,"exp":"The zona glomerulosa has cells in ovoid clusters and secretes mineralocorticoids (aldosterone).","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of Adrenal Glands)"},{"q":"The zona reticularis is histologically arranged as a:","choices":["Simple cuboidal follicle","Radial column","Loose meshwork","Stratified sheet"],"answer":2,"exp":"The zona reticularis is arranged as a loose meshwork and secretes androgens.","cite":"Slide 87 (Histology of Adrenal Glands)"},{"q":"The thyroidea ima artery, an uncommon variant supplying the isthmus, arises from the arch of the aorta or the:","choices":["Internal carotid artery","Brachiocephalic artery","Subclavian artery","Facial artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The thyroidea ima is a variant artery to the isthmus arising from the aortic arch or brachiocephalic artery.","cite":"Slide 32 (Blood supply of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The superior and middle thyroid veins usually drain into which vessel?","choices":["Internal jugular vein","Brachiocephalic vein","Subclavian vein","External jugular vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The superior and middle thyroid veins drain into the internal jugular vein; the inferior thyroid vein drains to the brachiocephalic vein.","cite":"Slide 33 (Venous drainage)"},{"q":"Calcitriol raises blood calcium primarily by:","choices":["Stimulating calcitonin release","Increasing intestinal calcium absorption","Inhibiting the parathyroid glands","Filtering calcium in the kidney"],"answer":1,"exp":"Calcitriol (active vitamin D) increases intestinal calcium absorption, raising blood calcium.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Kidney)"},{"q":"The gubernaculum testis contributes to descent because it:","choices":["Forms the tunica albuginea","Actively contracts to push the testis","Secretes testosterone","Fails to elongate as the body grows, pulling the testis down"],"answer":3,"exp":"The gubernaculum does not elongate with body growth, so it draws the testes inferiorly toward the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 9 (Descent of the Testes)"},{"q":"The reproductive tract (ducts) functions to:","choices":["Produce gametes and hormones","Receive, store, and transport gametes","Secrete only alkaline mucus","Filter blood"],"answer":1,"exp":"The reproductive tract consists of ducts that receive, store, and transport gametes.","cite":"Slide 4 (Organization of the Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The raphe of the scrotum is best described as:","choices":["A muscle that elevates the testes","A thickened tissue ridge marking the scrotal septum","A serous membrane","An arterial plexus"],"answer":1,"exp":"The raphe is a thickened tissue ridge (corresponding to the internal septum) extending from the anus across the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 16 (Scrotum)"},{"q":"Contraction of the dartos muscle produces which visible effect?","choices":["Erection of the penis","Elevation of the testes toward the abdomen","Wrinkling of the scrotal surface","Ejaculation"],"answer":2,"exp":"Dartos contraction wrinkles the scrotal surface; cremaster contraction elevates the testes.","cite":"Slide 18 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"The pampiniform plexus drains blood from which structure?","choices":["The bladder","The prostate","The testis","The bulbo-urethral gland"],"answer":2,"exp":"The pampiniform plexus is the venous network draining the testis within the spermatic cord.","cite":"Slide 14 (Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"The pudendal nerve is listed among the nerves supplying which structure?","choices":["The kidney","The scrotum","The liver","The spleen"],"answer":1,"exp":"The scrotum receives supply from the hypogastric plexus, ilioinguinal, genitofemoral, and pudendal nerves.","cite":"Slide 22 (scrotal nerve supply)"},{"q":"The seminal fluid from the seminal glands is rich in fructose, prostaglandins, and:","choices":["Clotting factors","Hyaluronidase","Seminalplasmin","Bicarbonate mucus"],"answer":0,"exp":"Seminal gland fluid contains fructose, prostaglandins, and clotting factors.","cite":"Slide 55 (The Seminal Glands)"},{"q":"During emission, sperm are mixed with glandular secretions by peristalsis of the ductus deferens and which glands?","choices":["Adrenal glands","Salivary glands","Seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands","Thyroid gland"],"answer":2,"exp":"Emission mixes sperm with secretions from the seminal glands, prostate, and bulbo-urethral glands.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The spongy urethra ends at which structure?","choices":["The prostatic urethra","The internal urethral orifice","The ejaculatory duct","The external urethral orifice"],"answer":3,"exp":"The spongy (penile) urethra runs through the penis and ends at the external urethral orifice.","cite":"Slides 51, 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"In the absence of anti-Müllerian hormone, the Müllerian ducts develop into the:","choices":["Major internal female reproductive organs","Male reproductive tract","Urinary bladder","External genitalia only"],"answer":0,"exp":"Without AMH, the Müllerian ducts develop into the major internal female reproductive organs.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts initially appear in:","choices":["Female embryos only","Both male and female embryos","Male embryos only","Neither until puberty"],"answer":1,"exp":"The Müllerian ducts are initially present in both male and female embryos.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The two perineal triangles share a base formed by a line between the:","choices":["Anterior superior iliac spines","Pubic tubercles","Ischial tuberosities","Ischial spines"],"answer":2,"exp":"An imaginary line between the ischial tuberosities forms the shared base of the two triangles.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The mons pubis is composed of skin and subcutaneous connective tissue overlying the:","choices":["Pubic symphysis","Coccyx","Ischial tuberosity","Sacral promontory"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mons pubis is an expanse of skin and subcutaneous tissue anterior to the pubic symphysis.","cite":"Slides 8, 66 (Boundaries / External Genitalia)"},{"q":"The suspensory ligament extends from the mesovarium to the:","choices":["Cervix","Uterine fundus","Labia minora","Body (pelvic/lateral) wall"],"answer":3,"exp":"The suspensory ligament extends from the mesovarium to the body wall and carries the ovarian vessels.","cite":"Slide 18 (Supporting Ligaments)"},{"q":"The pelvic diaphragm lifts to assist which function?","choices":["Release of feces during defecation","Filtration of urine","Secretion of cervical mucus","Ovulation"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm supports pelvic organs and lifts to help release feces during defecation.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"Venous drainage of the ovaries occurs via a network termed the:","choices":["Prostatic plexus","Vesical venous plexus","Hypogastric plexus","Pampiniform plexus"],"answer":3,"exp":"Ovarian veins drain via pampiniform plexi (an ovarian venous network).","cite":"Slide 27 (Vasculature of Ovaries)"},{"q":"The uterine tube receives its nerve supply from which plexi?","choices":["Celiac plexus only","Cardiac and pulmonary plexi","Ovarian and uterine plexi","Sacral plexus only"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterine tube's nerve supply is from the ovarian and uterine plexi.","cite":"Slide 48 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The uterine tube region that passes through the uterine wall is the:","choices":["Infundibulum","Ampulla","Intramural (interstitial) portion","Fimbriae"],"answer":2,"exp":"The intramural (interstitial) portion of the uterine tube passes through the uterine wall.","cite":"Slide 51 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The uterine glands of the endometrium secrete glycoproteins that serve as:","choices":["Nutrients for a potential zygote","Digestive enzymes","Clotting factors","Cervical mucus plug"],"answer":0,"exp":"Endometrial uterine glands secrete glycoproteins that nourish a potential zygote.","cite":"Slide 43 (Endometrium)"},{"q":"With respect to the peritoneum, the uterus is:","choices":["Extraperitoneal","Retroperitoneal","Subperitoneal","Intraperitoneal"],"answer":3,"exp":"The uterus is intraperitoneal, draped by the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 31 (Uterus)"},{"q":"The male urethra's first region, passing through the prostate, is the:","choices":["Prostatic urethra","Membranous urethra","Penile urethra","Spongy urethra"],"answer":0,"exp":"The prostatic urethra is the portion of the male urethra passing through the prostate.","cite":"Slide 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The penile (spongy) urethra ends at the:","choices":["External urethral orifice","Internal urethral orifice","Membranous urethra","Prostatic urethra"],"answer":0,"exp":"The penile (spongy) urethra passes within the penile shaft and ends at the external urethral orifice.","cite":"Slide 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The internal space of the kidney that houses the renal pelvis, calyces, vessels, and fat is the:","choices":["Renal cortex","Renal column","Renal papilla","Renal sinus"],"answer":3,"exp":"The renal sinus is the internal space housing the pelvis, calyces, vessels, nerves, and fat.","cite":"Slide 10 (Gross and Sectional Anatomy)"},{"q":"The fibrous capsule of the kidney directly covers which surface?","choices":["The medulla","The outer cortex","The renal pelvis","The minor calyces"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fibrous (renal) capsule of dense irregular connective tissue covers the outer cortex.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The peritubular capillaries are described as being:","choices":["Located only in the renal pelvis","Juxtaposed to the nephron for solute exchange","Part of the filtration membrane","Draining directly into the aorta"],"answer":1,"exp":"Peritubular capillaries are juxtaposed to the nephron and, with the vasa recta, perform solute exchange.","cite":"Slide 18 (Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Juxtamedullary nephrons are essential for which function?","choices":["Concentrating urine via long loops and vasa recta","Producing renin only","Storing urine","Providing voluntary bladder control"],"answer":0,"exp":"Juxtamedullary nephrons (long loops, vasa recta) concentrate the urine by recovering water and salts.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"The ureter is clinically noted to travel deep (inferior) to which vessels bilaterally?","choices":["The inferior mesenteric artery","The renal vessels","The common iliac artery only","The gonadal (testicular/ovarian) vessels"],"answer":3,"exp":"The 'water under the bridge' relationship: the ureter passes deep to the gonadal vessels bilaterally.","cite":"Slide 48 ('Water under the bridge')"},{"q":"The ureter mucosa is lined by transitional epithelium, which provides:","choices":["Enzyme secretion","Stretch (distensibility)","Ciliary motion","Filtration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Transitional epithelium lines the ureters, allowing them to stretch as urine passes.","cite":"Slide 45 (Ureter Walls)"}]},"anatomy-master-d":{"title":"Anatomy Exam 3 Comprehensive Master Exam — Form D","questions":[{"q":"The oral cavity's superior boundary is formed by the:","choices":["Tongue and mylohyoid","Hard and soft palates","Teeth and lips","Oropharynx"],"answer":1,"exp":"The oral cavity is bounded superiorly by the hard and soft palates, anteriorly by teeth/lips, posteriorly by the oropharynx.","cite":"Slide 24 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The space between the cheeks or lips and the gums is the:","choices":["Oral cavity proper","Vestibule","Vermilion border","Fauces"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vestibule is the space between the cheeks/lips and the gums; the oral cavity proper lies within the teeth.","cite":"Slide 26 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The greater omentum performs which notable function in the abdomen?","choices":["Forms the inguinal canal","Suspends the liver from the diaphragm","Anchors the kidneys","Covers the transverse colon and small bowel"],"answer":3,"exp":"The greater omentum hangs from the greater curvature of the stomach, covering the transverse colon and small bowel.","cite":"Slide 19 (Greater Omentum)"},{"q":"The outermost layer of the esophagus is the:","choices":["Adventitia","Serosa","Mucosa","Submucosa"],"answer":0,"exp":"The esophagus has mucosa, submucosa, muscularis, and an outer adventitia (not a serosa along most of its course).","cite":"Slides 42–43 (Histology of the Esophagus)"},{"q":"The inferior esophageal (cardiac) sphincter is described as:","choices":["Skeletal muscle under voluntary control","Circular smooth muscle that is not a true sphincter","A cartilaginous ring","Absent in humans"],"answer":1,"exp":"The inferior (cardiac) esophageal sphincter is circular smooth muscle, not a true anatomical sphincter; the diaphragm aids its function.","cite":"Slide 46 (Esophagus)"},{"q":"Which component of the spleen supports hematopoietic function and blood filtration?","choices":["Hilum","White pulp","Splenic capsule","Red pulp"],"answer":3,"exp":"Red pulp filters blood and has hematopoietic capacity; white pulp is lymphatic tissue.","cite":"Slide 136 (The Spleen)"},{"q":"The jejunum occupies mostly which region of the abdomen?","choices":["Pelvis","Right lower quadrant","Right upper quadrant","Left upper quadrant"],"answer":3,"exp":"The proximal ~40% (jejunum) lies mostly in the left upper quadrant; the ileum occupies the right lower quadrant.","cite":"Slides 75, 77 (Jejunum / Ileum)"},{"q":"The rectum forms approximately the last how much of the digestive tract?","choices":["15 cm","5 cm","30 cm","50 cm"],"answer":0,"exp":"The rectum forms the last 15 cm of the digestive tract and stores feces before defecation.","cite":"Slide 101 (The Rectum)"},{"q":"The body of the pancreas is separated from the stomach by which peritoneal space?","choices":["The paracolic gutter","The greater sac only","The rectouterine pouch","The lesser sac (omental bursa)"],"answer":3,"exp":"The anterior surface of the pancreatic body is deep to the stomach, separated from it by the lesser sac of peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 70 (Body & Tail of Pancreas)"},{"q":"Which liver lobe is bounded by the inferior vena cava and the ligamentum venosum?","choices":["Right lobe","Quadrate lobe","Caudate lobe","Left lobe"],"answer":2,"exp":"The caudate lobe lies between the IVC and the ligamentum venosum.","cite":"Slide 115 (Lobes of the Liver)"},{"q":"The inferior mesenteric vein typically drains into which vessel of the portal system?","choices":["The splenic vein","The inferior vena cava","The hepatic vein","The renal vein"],"answer":0,"exp":"The inferior mesenteric vein usually drains into the splenic vein, part of the portal system.","cite":"Slide 135 (Pancreas Veins / portal system)"},{"q":"The cystic artery, which supplies the gallbladder, most commonly arises from the:","choices":["Superior mesenteric artery","Left gastric artery","Splenic artery","Right hepatic artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cystic artery typically branches from the right hepatic artery (from the proper hepatic).","cite":"Slide 142 (Common Hepatic Artery)"},{"q":"The inferior mesenteric artery supplies which region of the gut?","choices":["The midgut","The foregut","The hindgut","The stomach and spleen"],"answer":2,"exp":"The IMA supplies hindgut derivatives (distal transverse colon through the upper rectum).","cite":"Slides 144–145 (Inferior Mesenteric Artery)"},{"q":"Which paired veins drain directly into the IVC?","choices":["Left gastric veins","Splenic veins","Superior mesenteric veins","Renal veins"],"answer":3,"exp":"The renal veins are paired direct tributaries of the IVC, along with hepatic, gonadal, suprarenal, phrenic, and lumbar veins.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Lymphatic drainage grouped around the celiac artery would primarily drain which organs?","choices":["The lower limbs","The rectum and anal canal","The kidneys","Foregut organs (stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas)"],"answer":3,"exp":"Celiac nodal groups drain foregut derivatives — stomach, liver, spleen, and pancreas — matching the celiac artery's territory.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"Adipose tissue functions as a secondary endocrine tissue by secreting leptin and:","choices":["Calcitonin","Insulin","Resistin","Aldosterone"],"answer":2,"exp":"Adipose tissue secretes leptin and resistin.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Adipose Tissue)"},{"q":"The main endocrine organs include the thyroid, parathyroid, pituitary, pineal, and:","choices":["Sebaceous glands","Salivary glands","Sweat glands","Suprarenal glands"],"answer":3,"exp":"The main endocrine organs include the pituitary, hypothalamus, thyroid, thymus, suprarenal, pineal, parathyroid, pancreas, and reproductive glands.","cite":"Slide 3 (Overview)"},{"q":"The pancreatic islets are also known as the:","choices":["Islets of Langerhans","Acini","Follicles of Wirsung","Islets of Santorini"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pancreatic islets are the islets of Langerhans, the endocrine portion of the pancreas.","cite":"Slide 52 (Pancreas histology)"},{"q":"The parathyroid gland is described histologically as being formed of:","choices":["Radial columns of lipid-laden cells","Follicles filled with colloid","Solid cell cords, well vascularized, with a capsule","Chromaffin cell nests"],"answer":2,"exp":"The parathyroid has a capsule, is well vascularized, and consists of solid cell cords (chief and oxyphil cells).","cite":"Slide 46 (Histology of parathyroid glands)"},{"q":"The right suprarenal gland's anterior relations include the liver and which vessel?","choices":["Portal vein","Aorta","Inferior vena cava","Splenic vein"],"answer":2,"exp":"The right adrenal gland is related anteriorly to the liver and IVC; the left relates to the stomach and pancreas.","cite":"Slide 86 (Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The adrenal glands receive arterial supply from the inferior phrenic artery, the renal artery, and the:","choices":["Middle suprarenal artery from the aorta","Splenic artery","Superior mesenteric artery","Gonadal artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"Adrenal supply is from superior (phrenic), middle (aorta), and inferior (renal) suprarenal arteries.","cite":"Slides 81, 86 (Suprarenal Glands)"},{"q":"The gland whose chief cells are the principal PTH source lies in which location?","choices":["On the posterior surface of the thyroid","Within the sella turcica","On the superior kidney","In the mediastinum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The parathyroid glands (chief cells produce PTH) lie on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland.","cite":"Slides 43–44 (Parathyroid Glands)"},{"q":"The gonads of the reproductive system are defined as the organs that:","choices":["Store mature sperm","Produce gametes and hormones","Secrete seminal fluid","Form the external genitalia"],"answer":1,"exp":"The gonads (testes/ovaries) produce gametes and hormones.","cite":"Slide 4 (Organization of the Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The tunica vaginalis, which lines the scrotal cavity, is derived embryologically from the:","choices":["Peritoneum","Tunica albuginea","Dartos fascia","Mesonephric duct"],"answer":0,"exp":"The tunica vaginalis is a peritoneal-derived serous membrane carried down with the descending testis.","cite":"Slides 13, 16 (tunica vaginalis)"},{"q":"The muscular contractions that expel semen during ejaculation are described as:","choices":["Contraction of the detrusor","Peristalsis of the ureter","Powerful contractions of ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus","Relaxation of the external urethral sphincter"],"answer":2,"exp":"Ejaculation results from powerful contractions of the ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus muscles.","cite":"Slide 67 (Semen release and ejaculation)"},{"q":"The scrotal septum divides the scrotum into how many chambers?","choices":["Three","One","Two","Four"],"answer":2,"exp":"The scrotal septum divides the scrotum into two chambers (scrotal cavities).","cite":"Slide 16 (Scrotum)"},{"q":"The two arteries traveling within the spermatic cord are the testicular artery and the:","choices":["Deferential artery","Internal pudendal artery","External pudendal artery","Inferior epigastric artery"],"answer":0,"exp":"The spermatic cord carries the testicular artery and the deferential artery.","cite":"Slides 14–15 (Spermatic Cords)"},{"q":"During erection, arterial smooth muscle responds to parasympathetic signals by:","choices":["Contracting to constrict the vessels","Relaxing to dilate the vessels","Undergoing fibrosis","Secreting testosterone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Parasympathetic signals relax arterial smooth muscle, dilating vessels so erectile tissue engorges.","cite":"Slide 66 (Erection of the penis)"},{"q":"The acrosome of a sperm head contains which fertilization-critical enzyme?","choices":["Hyaluronidase","Renin","Amylase","Trypsin"],"answer":0,"exp":"The acrosome contains enzymes including hyaluronidase, necessary for penetrating and fertilizing the egg.","cite":"Slide 38 (Anatomy of a Sperm)"},{"q":"Capacitation, which renders sperm capable of fertilization, is completed:","choices":["In the epididymis","In the female reproductive tract","In the seminiferous tubules","In the prostate"],"answer":1,"exp":"Sperm become motile with seminal secretions and gain fertilizing capacity in the female reproductive tract.","cite":"Slide 45 (capacitation)"},{"q":"The male urethra is approximately how long overall?","choices":["8–10 cm","3–4 cm","18–20 cm","25 cm"],"answer":2,"exp":"The male urethra is about 18–20 cm long with three regions; the female urethra is only ~3–4 cm.","cite":"Slide 58 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The cervix, along with the uterus, is derived from which embryonic source?","choices":["The urogenital sinus","The fused caudal Müllerian ducts","The mesonephric ducts","The gubernaculum"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fused caudal Müllerian ducts form the uterus and cervix (and the upper vagina).","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"The Müllerian ducts arise from the coelomic epithelium on the lateral aspect of the:","choices":["Pronephros","Metanephros","Mesonephros","Allantois"],"answer":2,"exp":"The paramesonephric (Müllerian) ducts arise from coelomic epithelium on the lateral aspect of the mesonephros.","cite":"Slide 16 (The Müllerian ducts)"},{"q":"Which boundary landmark of the female perineum is located posteriorly, palpable at the superior end of the intergluteal cleft?","choices":["The pubic symphysis","The tip of the coccyx","The mons pubis","The ischial tuberosity"],"answer":1,"exp":"The tip of the coccyx is palpable at the superior end of the intergluteal cleft, a posterior perineal landmark.","cite":"Slide 8 (Boundaries of Female Perineum)"},{"q":"In the female, the anterior (urogenital) triangle contains the vaginal orifice and the:","choices":["Rectum","Anus","External os of the cervix","Urethral orifice"],"answer":3,"exp":"In females, the urogenital triangle contains the urethral and vaginal orifices.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The cardinal (transverse cervical) ligaments run from the lateral cervix and vagina to the:","choices":["Sacrum","Pelvic wall","Labia majora","Pubic symphysis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The transverse cervical (cardinal) ligaments run from the lateral cervix and vagina to the pelvic wall.","cite":"Slide 36 (Support of the Uterus)"},{"q":"The urethrovaginal sphincter is one of the muscles related to the vagina, alongside the external urethral sphincter and the:","choices":["Coccygeus","Pubovaginalis (part of levator ani)","Iliococcygeus only","Obturator externus"],"answer":1,"exp":"Muscles related to the vagina include the pubovaginalis (levator ani), external urethral sphincter, urethrovaginal sphincter, and bulbospongiosus.","cite":"Slide 62 (Muscles Related to the Vagina)"},{"q":"The endometrium's blood supply is derived from the uterine, vaginal, and which arteries?","choices":["Ovarian arteries","Renal arteries","Femoral arteries","Pudendal arteries only"],"answer":0,"exp":"The uterine layers are supplied by the uterine, vaginal, and ovarian arteries.","cite":"Slide 35 (Uterine Layers)"},{"q":"Superior lymphatic drainage of the vagina goes to the internal and which other iliac nodes?","choices":["Superficial inguinal nodes","Common iliac nodes only","External iliac nodes","Para-aortic nodes"],"answer":2,"exp":"Superior vaginal lymph drains to internal and external iliac nodes.","cite":"Slide 64 (Lymphatic Drainage of Vagina)"},{"q":"The finger-like projections at the distal end of the uterine tube are the:","choices":["Fornices","Fimbriae","Rugae","Papillae"],"answer":1,"exp":"The fimbriae are finger-like projections at the infundibulum of the uterine tube.","cite":"Slide 51 (Uterine Tube)"},{"q":"The ovarian follicle consists of an oocyte surrounded by which cells?","choices":["Chief cells","Podocytes","Follicular cells","Chromaffin cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"An ovarian follicle is composed of an oocyte and its surrounding follicular cells.","cite":"Slide 25 (Ovaries)"},{"q":"The broad ligament is continuous with which layer of the uterine wall?","choices":["The myometrium","The perimetrium","The endometrium","The mucosa"],"answer":1,"exp":"The perimetrium (outer serosa) is continuous with the broad ligament.","cite":"Slide 39 (Wall of the Uterus)"},{"q":"In the female, the external urethral orifice is located:","choices":["Anterior to the vaginal opening, posterior to the clitoris","Within the vaginal canal","Posterior to the anus","At the tip of the clitoris"],"answer":0,"exp":"In females, the external urethral orifice lies anterior to the vaginal opening and posterior to the clitoris.","cite":"Slide 63 (Innervation / orifice)"},{"q":"The membranous urethra in the male is the segment that:","choices":["Extends from the prostatic urethra to the penile urethra, piercing the urogenital diaphragm","Passes through the prostate","Runs the length of the penis","Lies within the bladder wall"],"answer":0,"exp":"The membranous urethra runs from the end of the prostatic urethra to the penile urethra and pierces the urogenital diaphragm.","cite":"Slide 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"Minor calyces converge to form which larger structure?","choices":["Renal papillae","Major calyces","Renal columns","Collecting ducts"],"answer":1,"exp":"Minor calyces receive urine from the papillae and converge into major calyces, then the renal pelvis.","cite":"Slides 22, 42 (Urinary Flow)"},{"q":"The perinephric fat serves primarily which function?","choices":["Hormone production","Filtration","Urine storage","Cushioning and insulation"],"answer":3,"exp":"Perinephric (perirenal) fat completely surrounds the kidney, providing cushioning and insulation.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"Sympathetic stimulation of the kidney affects urine production by:","choices":["Increasing glomerular filtration","Dilating the afferent arteriole to increase output","Vasoconstricting the afferent and efferent arterioles, decreasing output","Relaxing the detrusor muscle"],"answer":2,"exp":"Sympathetic tone vasoconstricts both arterioles, reducing glomerular blood flow and urine production.","cite":"Slide 26 (Innervation)"},{"q":"The thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle leads directly into the:","choices":["Renal papilla","Proximal convoluted tubule","Collecting duct","Distal convoluted tubule"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ascending limb returns to the cortex and leads into the distal convoluted tubule.","cite":"Slide 39 (Loop of Henle)"},{"q":"In males, which structure lies posterosuperior to the urinary bladder?","choices":["The uterus","The prostate","The rectum","The vagina"],"answer":2,"exp":"In males the rectum lies posterosuperior to the bladder and the prostate lies inferior.","cite":"Slide 51 (Urinary Bladder)"},{"q":"The EPO-producing, oxygen-sensing cells of the juxtaglomerular apparatus secrete:","choices":["Aldosterone","Renin","Calcitonin","Erythropoietin"],"answer":3,"exp":"The oxygen-sensing (REPOS) cells sense oxygenation and secrete erythropoietin.","cite":"Slide 36 (Juxtaglomerular Apparatus)"}]},"anatomy-master-e":{"title":"Anatomy Exam 3 Comprehensive Master Exam — Form E","questions":[{"q":"Approximately how long is the small intestine, occupying much of the abdominal cavity?","choices":["About 1.5 meters (5 feet)","About 6 meters (20 feet)","About 12 meters (40 feet)","About 0.5 meters"],"answer":1,"exp":"The small intestine is a thin-walled coiled tube about 6 meters (20 feet) long.","cite":"Slide 60 (Small Intestine)"},{"q":"The lateral walls of the oral cavity proper are formed by the cheeks, which contain which muscle?","choices":["Buccinator","Masseter","Orbicularis oris","Mylohyoid"],"answer":0,"exp":"The cheeks contain the buccinator muscles; the lips contain orbicularis oris.","cite":"Slide 26 (Oral Cavity)"},{"q":"The hepatoduodenal and hepatogastric ligaments together form which peritoneal structure?","choices":["The falciform ligament","The greater omentum","The lesser omentum","The mesentery proper"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser omentum comprises the hepatogastric and hepatoduodenal ligaments, running from the porta hepatis to the lesser curvature.","cite":"Slide 21 (Peritoneal Reflections)"},{"q":"The colon lining is notable for an abundance of which cells that provide lubrication?","choices":["Chief cells","Parietal cells","Goblet cells","Paneth cells"],"answer":2,"exp":"The colon has abundant goblet cells for mucus/lubrication, lacks villi, and does not produce enzymes.","cite":"Slide 88 (Characteristics of the Colon)"},{"q":"The pyloric sphincter controls gastric emptying into which structure?","choices":["The duodenum","The jejunum","The esophagus","The cecum"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pyloric sphincter regulates emptying of stomach contents into the duodenum.","cite":"Slides 54, 61 (Stomach / Small Intestine)"},{"q":"The splenic artery characteristically follows which course relative to the pancreas?","choices":["Within the mesentery proper","Through the head and uncinate process","Posterior to the aorta","Along the superior margin of the body and tail"],"answer":3,"exp":"The splenic artery, a celiac branch, runs along the upper margin of the pancreatic body and tail toward the spleen.","cite":"Slides 60, 137 (Splenic Artery)"},{"q":"The duodenum receives bile and pancreatic secretions at which structure on its descending part?","choices":["The ileocecal valve","The pyloric sphincter","The greater and lesser papillae","The duodenal cap"],"answer":2,"exp":"The descending duodenum bears the greater and lesser papillae, where the bile and pancreatic ducts open.","cite":"Slide 66 (Duodenum)"},{"q":"The appendix is dominated by which tissue, making it a lymphoid organ?","choices":["Adipose tissue","Goblet cells","Smooth muscle","Lymphoid nodules"],"answer":3,"exp":"The vermiform appendix is dominated by lymphoid nodules and is fixed to the cecum by the mesoappendix.","cite":"Slides 85, 87 (The Appendix)"},{"q":"The head of the pancreas is bounded inferiorly by which structure?","choices":["The common bile duct","The splenic artery","The left colic flexure","The ligament of Treitz"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pancreatic head is delineated superiorly by the gastroduodenal artery and inferiorly by the common bile duct.","cite":"Slide 76 (Head of pancreas)"},{"q":"The lesser omentum attaches to the liver at which region?","choices":["The falciform ligament","The bare area","The porta hepatis","The right triangular ligament"],"answer":2,"exp":"The lesser omentum's attachment surrounds the porta hepatis and extends to the caudate and left lobes.","cite":"Slides 117–118 (Lesser Omentum)"},{"q":"The superior mesenteric vein passes in which relationship to the pancreas before joining the portal vein?","choices":["Through the liver parenchyma","Anterior to the stomach","Within the falciform ligament","Deep (posterior) to the neck of the pancreas"],"answer":3,"exp":"The SMV passes deep to the pancreas and merges with the splenic vein (behind the neck) to form the portal vein.","cite":"Slides 63, 135 (Mesenteric Veins)"},{"q":"The gallbladder concentrates bile, which is produced by which organ?","choices":["The duodenum","The pancreas","The spleen","The liver"],"answer":3,"exp":"Bile is produced by the liver and stored/concentrated in the gallbladder.","cite":"Slides 104, 126 (Liver / Gall Bladder)"},{"q":"The left gastric artery is a direct branch of which vessel?","choices":["The superior mesenteric artery","The celiac trunk","The common hepatic artery","The splenic artery"],"answer":1,"exp":"The left gastric artery is one of the three direct branches of the celiac trunk.","cite":"Slide 139 (Arterial Supply)"},{"q":"The IVC receives the azygos communication and pierces the diaphragm at which level?","choices":["T8 (caval hiatus)","T10 (esophageal hiatus)","T12 (aortic hiatus)","L1"],"answer":0,"exp":"The IVC passes through the caval hiatus of the diaphragm at T8.","cite":"Slide 146 (Inferior Vena Cava)"},{"q":"Which nodal group would drain hindgut structures such as the descending and sigmoid colon?","choices":["Inferior mesenteric nodes","Celiac nodes","Superior mesenteric nodes","Hepatic nodes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Inferior mesenteric nodes drain hindgut derivatives, following the IMA's supply.","cite":"Slide 52 (lymphatic drainage)"},{"q":"The thymus, an endocrine organ that atrophies in adulthood, secretes which hormones?","choices":["Mineralocorticoids","Thyroxines","Catecholamines","Thymosins"],"answer":3,"exp":"The thymus secretes thymosins and undergoes atrophy during adulthood.","cite":"Slide 5 (Figure 19.1 — Thymus)"},{"q":"The anterior pituitary hormones such as ACTH and TSH function primarily to:","choices":["Filter blood","Control the activity of other endocrine organs","Store calcium","Produce bile"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hormones from the pars distalis (e.g., ACTH, TSH) control other endocrine organs.","cite":"Slides 5, 11 (Pituitary hormones)"},{"q":"The exocrine (acinar) cells of the pancreas are distinct from the islet cells in that they:","choices":["Secrete insulin","Secrete digestive enzymes rather than hormones","Store colloid","Are chromaffin cells"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pancreatic acini are exocrine cells secreting digestive enzymes; the islets are the endocrine cells.","cite":"Slide 52 (Anatomy of the Pancreas)"},{"q":"The follicular epithelium of an actively secreting thyroid follicle tends to be:","choices":["Stratified","Flattened and squamous","Taller (columnar-like) rather than flat","Pseudostratified ciliated"],"answer":2,"exp":"Active thyroid follicles have taller ('high') epithelium; inactive follicles are flatter.","cite":"Slide 30 (Histology of thyroid gland)"},{"q":"The tail of the pancreas, an endocrine-containing organ, reaches which structure?","choices":["The porta hepatis","The hilum of the spleen","The right kidney","The gallbladder fossa"],"answer":1,"exp":"The pancreatic tail reaches the hilus of the spleen.","cite":"Slide 56 (Pancreas relationships)"},{"q":"The lateral surface of the thyroid gland is related to the sternomastoid and which muscle group?","choices":["Infrahyoid (strap) muscles","Suprahyoid muscles","Scalene muscles","Pharyngeal constrictors"],"answer":0,"exp":"The lateral thyroid surface relates to the sternomastoid and the infrahyoid (strap) muscles (except thyrohyoid).","cite":"Slide 28 (Thyroid lateral surface)"},{"q":"Calcitonin and PTH exemplify which type of hormonal control over blood calcium?","choices":["Synergistic control","Antagonistic (opposing) control","Permissive control","Feedforward control"],"answer":1,"exp":"PTH (raises Ca2+) and calcitonin (lowers Ca2+) are antagonists that together regulate blood calcium.","cite":"Slides 31, 44 (calcium regulation)"},{"q":"The accessory glands of the reproductive system are defined by their role in:","choices":["Secreting fluids","Producing gametes","Forming the perineum","Housing the testes"],"answer":0,"exp":"Accessory glands secrete fluids that support the gametes.","cite":"Slide 4 (Organization of the Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The external genitalia of the reproductive system are described as:","choices":["Gamete-producing organs","Perineal structures","Ducts for gamete storage","Fluid-secreting glands"],"answer":1,"exp":"The external genitalia are perineal structures.","cite":"Slide 4 (Organization of the Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The cremaster's role in thermoregulation is to:","choices":["Produce testosterone","Wrinkle the scrotal skin only","Cool the testes when warm by sweating","Elevate the testes toward the body when cold"],"answer":3,"exp":"The cremaster contracts to draw the testes toward the warm body in cold conditions.","cite":"Slide 19 (Muscles of the scrotum)"},{"q":"Both the ischiocavernosus and bulbospongiosus are what type of muscle?","choices":["Cardiac muscle","Smooth muscle","Skeletal muscle","Involuntary smooth muscle"],"answer":2,"exp":"These perineal muscles are skeletal muscle, producing the forceful contractions of ejaculation.","cite":"Slide 67 (ejaculation)"},{"q":"The scrotum receives contributions from the external pudendal artery, a branch of the:","choices":["Aorta","Internal iliac artery","External iliac artery","Femoral artery"],"answer":3,"exp":"The external pudendal artery arises from the femoral artery to help supply the scrotum.","cite":"Slide 21 (scrotal blood supply)"},{"q":"The ilioinguinal and genitofemoral nerves are notable because they:","choices":["Control the detrusor muscle","Innervate the diaphragm","Supply the kidney","Supply the scrotum and travel with the spermatic cord"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ilioinguinal and genitofemoral nerves supply the scrotum; the genitofemoral is part of the spermatic cord.","cite":"Slides 14, 22 (spermatic cord / scrotal nerves)"},{"q":"Which portion of the epididymis becomes the ductus deferens?","choices":["The tail","The head","The body","The efferent ductules"],"answer":0,"exp":"At the tail of the epididymis the tubes uncoil to become the single ductus deferens.","cite":"Slide 42 (The Epididymis)"},{"q":"After the ejaculatory duct, semen next enters which portion of the urethra?","choices":["The spongy urethra","The membranous urethra","The prostatic urethra","The external urethral orifice"],"answer":2,"exp":"The ejaculatory duct empties into the prostatic urethra, the first urethral segment.","cite":"Slides 48, 51 (Ductus Deferens / Urethra)"},{"q":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty their secretions into which urethral segment?","choices":["The membranous urethra","The prostatic urethra","The spongy urethra","The ejaculatory duct"],"answer":2,"exp":"The bulbo-urethral glands empty into the spongy urethra, just distal to the membranous urethra.","cite":"Slide 57 (Bulbo-urethral Glands)"},{"q":"The ovary is homologous to which male structure?","choices":["The scrotum","The prostate","The penis","The testis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ovaries are homologous to the testes.","cite":"Slide 26 (Ovaries)"},{"q":"The uterine (fallopian) tubes are homologous to which male structure?","choices":["The scrotum","The prostate","The vas (ductus) deferens","The glans"],"answer":2,"exp":"The uterine tubes are homologous to the vas deferens.","cite":"Slide 50 (Uterine Tubes)"},{"q":"The lateral boundaries of the perineum are formed by the:","choices":["Ischial tuberosities","Pubic tubercles","Sacroiliac joints","Femoral heads"],"answer":0,"exp":"The perineum is bounded laterally by the ischial tuberosities of the ossa coxae.","cite":"Slide 5 (Perineum)"},{"q":"The medial aspects of the thighs and the gluteal folds serve as which type of perineal reference?","choices":["Vascular landmarks","Deep muscular boundaries","Surface boundaries of the female perineum","Lymphatic landmarks"],"answer":2,"exp":"The medial thighs and gluteal folds are surface boundaries of the female perineum.","cite":"Slide 8 (Boundaries of Female Perineum)"},{"q":"The mesovarium is a subdivision of which larger peritoneal structure?","choices":["The broad ligament","The round ligament","The suspensory ligament","The uterosacral ligament"],"answer":0,"exp":"The mesovarium is a double fold of the broad ligament peritoneum attaching the ovary.","cite":"Slides 14, 28 (Peritoneal Folds)"},{"q":"The pelvic diaphragm functions to seal which opening?","choices":["The inferior opening of the bony pelvis","The pelvic inlet","The obturator foramen","The greater sciatic foramen"],"answer":0,"exp":"The pelvic diaphragm seals the inferior opening of the bony pelvis and supports the pelvic organs.","cite":"Slide 9 (Pelvic Diaphragm)"},{"q":"The ovarian artery reaches the ovary after entering which ligament?","choices":["The cardinal ligament","The round ligament","The uterosacral ligament","The suspensory ligament"],"answer":3,"exp":"The ovarian artery enters the suspensory ligament and branches through the mesovarium.","cite":"Slide 27 (Vasculature of Ovaries)"},{"q":"Inferior lymphatic drainage of the vagina includes which superficial node group?","choices":["Axillary nodes","Superficial inguinal nodes","Popliteal nodes","Submental nodes"],"answer":1,"exp":"The inferior vagina drains partly to the superficial inguinal nodes (also sacral and common iliac).","cite":"Slide 64 (Lymphatic Drainage of Vagina)"},{"q":"The vagina lies posterior to which organ and anterior to the rectum?","choices":["The uterus","The urethra","The bladder fundus","The ovary"],"answer":1,"exp":"The vagina lies posterior to the urethra and anterior to the rectum.","cite":"Slide 57 (Vagina)"},{"q":"The labia majora bear which features distinguishing them histologically from the labia minora?","choices":["Hair, sweat, and sebaceous glands","A core of erectile tissue only","Simple ciliated columnar epithelium","Colloid-filled follicles"],"answer":0,"exp":"The labia majora have pigmented outer skin with hair, sweat, and sebaceous glands; the labia minora lack hair and fat.","cite":"Slides 73–74 (Labia)"},{"q":"Peritoneum folding around the pelvic organs creates two dead-end recesses called:","choices":["The greater and lesser sacs","The vesicouterine and rectouterine pouches","The paracolic gutters","The mesovarium and mesosalpinx"],"answer":1,"exp":"Peritoneum forms the anterior vesicouterine and posterior rectouterine pouches around the uterus.","cite":"Slide 12 (Anatomy of the Female Reproductive System)"},{"q":"The kidneys are considered the primary organs of the urinary system because they:","choices":["Transport urine","Store urine","Filter waste and form urine","Provide voluntary control of urination"],"answer":2,"exp":"The kidneys are the primary organs, filtering waste and forming urine; the rest of the system transports and stores it.","cite":"Slide 3 (Organs Involved)"},{"q":"Multiple small prostatic ducts enter which urethral region during sexual stimulation?","choices":["The penile urethra","The membranous urethra","The prostatic urethra","The external urethral orifice"],"answer":2,"exp":"Multiple small prostatic ducts open into the prostatic urethra.","cite":"Slide 59 (Urethra)"},{"q":"The base of each renal pyramid abuts which region, while the apex points inward?","choices":["The renal pelvis","The cortex","The hilum","The minor calyx"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each renal pyramid has its base against the cortex and its apex (papilla) pointing toward a minor calyx.","cite":"Slide 14 (Coronal Plane Sections)"},{"q":"The layer that anchors the kidney to the posterior body wall is the:","choices":["Paranephric fat","Fibrous capsule","Perinephric fat","Renal fascia"],"answer":3,"exp":"The renal fascia (dense irregular connective tissue) anchors the kidney to the posterior wall and peritoneum.","cite":"Slide 13 (Surrounding Tissues)"},{"q":"The renal vein ultimately drains into which vessel?","choices":["Azygos vein","Abdominal aorta","Portal vein","Inferior vena cava"],"answer":3,"exp":"Venous return proceeds through the renal vein to the inferior vena cava.","cite":"Slides 6, 18 (Kidney Location / Blood Supply)"},{"q":"Approximately what fraction of nephrons are the cortical type?","choices":["15%","85%","50%","25%"],"answer":1,"exp":"About 85% of nephrons are cortical (short loops, peritubular capillaries); ~15% are juxtamedullary.","cite":"Slide 30 (Types of Nephrons)"},{"q":"A common site for kidney stones to lodge is the ureteropelvic junction because of:","choices":["The gonadal artery crossing","A sphincter at that point","The presence of transitional epithelium","The transition in ductal lumen size from the renal pelvis"],"answer":3,"exp":"The UPJ is a common obstruction site due to the change in lumen size from the wider renal pelvis to the narrower ureter.","cite":"Slide 47 (Zones Related to the Ureters)"},{"q":"The basement membrane of the glomerulus restricts filtration of albumin because it contains:","choices":["A negatively charged proteoglycan gel","Ciliated columnar cells","Chromaffin granules","Colloid"],"answer":0,"exp":"The glomerular basement membrane has a negatively charged proteoglycan gel that blocks large/charged molecules like albumin.","cite":"Slide 34 (Filtration Membranes)"}]}};
